A1401 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANDIVX-SFCHRON-BANDI     08-13 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANDIVX-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATEST VIDEO WAR ERUPTS  
 BY DAN FOST 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - BAN DIVX   c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Not since a Scottish scientist cloned a sheep named Dolly has a new
technology sparked such divisions as the war between DVD and Divx,
two new formats for watching movies at home.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Texas videophile has launched a ``Ban Divx'' Web site. A video
industry coalition erected a billboard in San Francisco that
cryptically opposes Divx. Stores that carry Divx titles receive
angry letters and e-mails touting DVD's superiority.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy centers on Divx's pay-per-view scheme, in which
consumers rent video titles that ``self-destruct'' in two days via
digital scrambling.
</P>
<P>
   Digital Video Express, the Circuit City-backed company that
rents and sells Divx titles, touts this as a big selling point
because it eliminates the hassle of returning movies to the video
store. But the downside is a move to metered entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``How would you feel if every time you pop a disc in your
compact disc player, you had to pay for it?'' asks John Giberson,
47, a real estate agent from Flower Mound, Texas, who runs
 &LR; www.bandivx.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``How long before, when Divx gains popularity, you're going to
have pay-per-listen CDs, and pay-per-use CD-ROMs, and
pay-per-everything?''
</P>
<P>
   Divx is a DVD variant that hit the marketplace as an experiment
in the Bay Area and Richmond, Va., in June, and is rolling out
nationally next month.
</P>
<P>
   It comes at the very moment the long-awaited DVD revolution
appears poised to catch on. DVD players are in about 500,000 U.S.
households, with the number expected to grow to 1 million by the
end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; DVD, which stands for digital video disc or digital versatile
disc, eclipses video cassettes in movie quality. It offers crisper
picture and better sound, plus features such as freeze frames and
instant rewind.
</P>
<P>
   Divx discs look just like DVDs (and compact discs), &UR;  &LR; but they
only work in special Divx players. They don't offer all the
features of DVD, and they expire 48 hours after they're first used
_ although customers can pay more money for extra viewings or
permanent ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Foes of Divx contend that it represents a step toward Big
Brother, because Digital Video Express can tell what movies each
customer watched, and when. The company says video privacy laws
prevent it from using that information.
</P>
<P>
   Divx opponents also say it's environmentally unsound, because
people can throw out the plastic discs. But Virginia-based Digital
Video Express says it encourages people to keep the discs for
future paid use, &UR;  &LR; recycle them at the rental store, or pass them on
to friends who can pay the smaller renewal fee.
</P>
<P>
   Arlene Baisa, 52, of Grass Valley, was looking for a new CD
player and wound up with a Divx machine. She loves the sound, the
picture clarity and the freedom from video store hassles. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``It keeps you from having to go back to the store and return it
and do all that necessary garbage, which I hate to do,'' said
Baisa, an administrative assistant.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Divx has riled the video industry, which sees a
major threat to its way of life. Only Circuit City and Good Guys
carry Divx titles; other giant companies like Tower, Blockbuster
and Hollywood Video don't plan to offer Divx.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``Divx is a direct attack on the VHS rental retailer,'' said
John Powers, vice president of DVD market development worldwide for
Burbank-based Warner Home Video.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Video stores like DVD, because they can still rent movies on
disc just as they do on videocassette. But store owners say Digital
Video Express hurts them with its no-return appeal.
</P>
<P>
   A store would make money when it sold a Divx disc, but wouldn't
get any extra money when the viewer renewed a movie or bought it
outright, said John Thrasher, vice president of video sales for
Tower Records/Video/Books in West Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   ``The studio and the Divx company share that money and the
retailers are shut out,'' he said. ``The amount of money we make on
it is negligible.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tower isn't completely opposed to Divx. ``If Divx became the
format of choice, we'd be there,'' said Rick Timmermans, video
regional manager for Tower in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Tower is one of several companies, including Suncoast, Sam
Goody, Hollywood Video and Frye's Electronics, that have lent their
names to Warner Home Video's billboard along Highway 101 near the
Seventh Street exit in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The billboard proclaims, ``Only Open DVD Delivers.''
</P>
<P>
   Only the most dedicated videophiles know that it means DVD is an
open standard _ so the discs can be played on numerous platforms _
while it takes a veiled swipe at Divx, a ``closed'' standard, where
you can only use one kind of machine.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say Divx and DVD aren't in a clear format war, the way
VHS fought and beat Betamax at the dawn of the VCR age. Many
analysts also shy away from bashing Divx, saying it has an
appealing business model that could catch on in time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like anything that completely attempts to change the business
model of the industry, it's a hugely risky undertaking,'' said Tom
Adams, president of Adams Media Research in Carmel Valley. ``On the
other hand, it attempts to address the very real issues the video
industry faces.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams said a video industry survey showed that the thing 38
percent of customers hated the most _ almost four times as much as
any other _ was the hassle of returning videos.
</P>
<P>
   Divx's main answer to the complaints is to let those who like
DVD buy DVD, and others can buy Divx.
</P>
<P>
   Will one emerge as a clear winner? ``Any summary judgments on
the market, on whether one platform will win or lose, are
premature,'' said Jae Kim, an analyst with Paul Kagan Associates in
Carmel.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
