<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITALBAY-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGITAL BAY/TOM ABATE  
 LAWYERS WHO'VE DEPOSED BILL GATES AND LIVED TO TELL ABOUT IT 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - DIGITAL BAY   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Not many lawyers have deposed Bill Gates across a conference table.
<TEXT>
<P>
   I asked two members of this tiny club whether they would have
wanted the press and public watching their every move.
</P>
<P>
   Their split decision may help you decide whether allowing the
public to eavesdrop on the antitrust case against Microsoft will
advance the cause of justice or turn the whole affair into a
carnival.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco attorney Sam Miller, who spent two days
questioning Gates in the Justice Department's 1995 antitrust
investigation, said the presence of a peanut gallery would break
the magic spell that an interrogator seeks to cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way this works is that you literally sit across the table
from the witness and look them in the eye,'' Miller said. ``You
want to develop a rapport that gets them to answer your
questions,'' even if that means disregarding the defense attorney
who sits beside witnesses, whispering into their ear.
</P>
<P>
   Of course witnesses like Gates aren't stupid. Interrogators
rarely elicit damaging admissions. But the more people in the room,
says Miller, the harder it is to weave that spell between subject
and interrogator that gets at the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Chu, a managing partner at the Los Angeles law firm of
Irell &AMP; Manella, couldn't disagree more. Chu whipped Microsoft in
1994 _ and won a $120 million judgment _ when he convinced a jury
that Microsoft ripped off a patented process for doubling the
density of hard drives from Stac Electronics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't have mattered one whit whether or not there were
press present,'' said Chu, who deposed Gates privately before
questioning him on the stand.
</P>
<P>
   But Chu said his Gates deposition was so dull, he's sure
reporters won't get a whiff of drama _ until and unless the current
antitrust case goes to trial. That's when the trivial questions get
edited out, and Microsoft's powerful chairman will have to face the
issues that matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``How was Gates on the stand?'' Chu said, posing then answering
the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is without question very smart, but there were some in the
courtroom who felt he came across as arrogant.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is appealing the order to let the media hear the
depositions. Los Angeles media attorney Karen Frederiksen said
federal case law on the issue is so complex, Microsoft may yet keep
the Fourth Estate out of the room.
</P>
<P>
   I'd love to know what the government attorney who will depose
Gates thinks about the press being there. My sources say that will
probably be Phillip Malone, who works in the antitrust division's
San Francisco office.
</P>
<P>
   But Malone and his San Francisco colleagues _ proteges all of
Marin antitrust lawyer Gary Spratling _ never leak, an ethical
standard that don't seem to inhibit the loose lips on special
prosecutor Kenneth Starr's staff.
</P>
<P>
   So the only clue as to Malone's thinking comes from the fact
that the government did not oppose the motion by various media
organizations to let the public hear the depositions.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, the ex-Justice leaguer now with Folger Levin &AMP; Kahn in
San Francisco, guessed that the government antitrust team may see a
tactical advantage in having the press around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defending lawyers typically do what they can to be disruptive,
and Microsoft's attorneys tend to be very aggressive,'' Miller
said. ``It might reduce the table-pounding if the newspapers were
in the room.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Tough guy: &LR;  I visited Lycos CEO Bob Davis in Mountain View
yesterday, where he was taking possession of his newest
acquisition, the WhoWhere Web site run by former Apple executive
Dale Fuller.
</P>
<P>
   In his very Boston accent, Davis argued that the $133 million
WhoWhere deal would propel his East Coast search engine past its
West Coast competitors like Yahoo, Excite, Infoseek and Inktomi.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may sound arrogant but you can use it anyway,'' Davis
said. ``Excite and Infoseek just don't matter to me. I see
ourselves as overtaking Yahoo in a year or so.''
</P>
<P>
   He said WhoWhere would fuel that drive, because Fuller's
Mountain View outfit had signed up 1.3 million users to develop
personal Web pages. Davis thinks personal Web page publishing is
the next killer app on the Web. And Lycos owns not just WhoWhere
but Tripod, the other 800-pound gorilla of personal publishing.
</P>
<P>
   Of course you get a different view from the local search
engines, who say Fuller shopped his property around and couldn't
get anybody to bid over $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   Fuller joined us in WhoWhere's soundproof black conference room
to extol the virtues of the deal. In the process, he revealed how
the ambitions of former-DMG investment banker Frank Quattrone
indirectly led him to merge into Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   Fuller said WhoWhere had been queued up for an IPO _ which would
have been handled by Quattrone's factotum, Bill Brady _ when the
DMG gang decided the investment-banking grass was greener over at
Credit Suisse First Boston side.
</P>
<P>
   Their abrupt defection delayed the IPO, and gave Fuller and
Davis a chance to renew some on-again, off-again talks that
resulted in the deal Fuller happily announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by phone
(650-961-2689), fax (650-961-5023) or e-mail ( &LR; abate &LR; sfgate.com &LR; ).
</P>
