<SLUG> BC-UFW-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 23 YEARS, FARM WORKERS DEMAND DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - UFW.   By Ilana DeBare  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Some Salinas farm workers who have been waiting for a union
contract for 23 years took their case yesterday to San Francisco's
North Beach, where scores of Italian restaurants and groceries sell
the dark green broccoli rabe that they pick.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A dozen workers on strike from D'Arrigo Bros. Co. in Salinas
joined about 35 local supporters to protest their long wait for a
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Workers at D'Arrigo _ which grows 95 percent of the country's
broccoli rabe, a pungent, leafy vegetable also known as rape and
often used in Italian cooking _ voted for representation by the
United Farm Workers in 1975. The two sides have held years of
contract talks since then, but they remain far apart on issues such
as whether the company should provide a pension plan.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, about 700 of D'Arrigo's 900 field workers held a
one-day walkout to demand a contract, according to the UFW. A
smaller number _ somewhere between 100 and 400, depending on
whether the union or company is counting _ remain on strike this
week.
</P>
<P>
   The strikers accused the company of intentionally stalling the
contract talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been on the negotiating committee myself for 12 years.
There have been generations of us trying to negotiate with the
company,'' said Efrain Lara, who has worked at D'Arrigo for a total
of 17 years. ``We are anxious and desperate to get a contract.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Arrigo officials insisted yesterday that they have bargained
in good faith, and that the delay is the fault of the UFW.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been waiting for a contract proposal from them for
five years, and we just received it in June,'' said marketing
director Nick Pasculli. ``Now, they're expecting us to turn it
around in a couple of weeks. This is an attempt to pressure us to
accept the UFW proposal without time to prepare an adequate
counterresponse.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Arrigo is a 75-year-old, family owned firm that grows, ships
and processes vegetables that include not just broccoli rabe, but
regular broccoli and lettuce. It farms 24,000 acres of land in the
Salinas Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The company pays its field workers a base wage of $6.50 an hour.
It says that with piece-rate pay added in, its broccoli rabe
workers averaged $11.03 per hour during the past six months.
</P>
<P>
   However, the current dispute centers less on pay than on
benefits and working conditions. The workers are asking the company
for a joint union/management-run health plan that would be more
generous than the company's current plan. They also have asked for
a pension and a grievance-arbitration procedure, neither of which
D'Arrigo currently provides.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
