<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-JACKSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGGIE JACKSON TALKS OF SPLIT WITH YANKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The tempestuous 22-year relationship between Reggie
Jackson and George Steinbrenner soured once again last month in a
spat over name-calling, or terms of employment, or perhaps both
issues.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter what happens, Jackson said Wednesday in the New
York Yankees' clubhouse, he and Steinbrenner will always be joined
together as part of the club's tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though I don't think it'll be easy to work things,'' Jackson
said, ``I think it could be, because I'm a Yankee.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was at Yankee Stadium to participate in the filming of a
movie in which he plays himself. The movie is set at the time when
Jackson was with the Yankees, and in the scene shot Wednesday,
Jackson stood in right field wearing his retired No. 44, waving to
a crowd of extras who stood and cheered him.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was a special assistant for the Yankees before sending a
letter of resignation to Steinbrenner last month, shortly after
Jackson was quoted in a magazine referring to the Yankees' owner
with a vulgarity.
</P>
<P>
   Others in the organization say Steinbrenner was furious about
the reference and pushed to sever the team's relationship with
Jackson, but Jackson said he was already frustrated with his job,
which afforded him almost no decision-making responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just didn't work out the way I wanted it to,'' he said. ``I
wished I could've done more. I was frustrated because I couldn't
make a larger contribution.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson says he intends to visit Steinbrenner and try to smooth
over their differences _ a recurring theme in their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner first courted Jackson as a free agent before the
1977 season, disparaging Jackson when he struggled and lauding him
at those many moments when he generated big hits.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson subsequently left the club as a free agent, and
Steinbrenner has repeatedly said he wished he had kept Jackson.
Ultimately, Jackson was hired as a special assistant, and on his
Hall of Fame plaque he wears a Yankee cap.
</P>
<P>
   That he is no longer with the organization ``is sad,'' Jackson
said. ``I mentioned that to George. He said, `You should stay with
the Yankees.'''
</P>
<P>
   There will be further chapters, no doubt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
