<SLUG> BC-INSIDER-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOTECH GURU HIT WITH FINE  
 BY PETER SINTON 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - INSIDER   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Alejandro Zaffaroni, one of the leaders of the biotechnology
industry in the Bay Area, has agreed with five of his friends and
family members to pay a total of $1.85 million to settle insider
trading charges, the Securities and Exchange Commission said
yesterday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Zaffaroni agreed to pay a civil penalty of $552,021 for
passing &UR;  &LR; inside information about the January 1995 acquisition of
Palo Alto's Affymax by Glaxo PLC before the deal was publicly
announced. Zaffaroni founded Affymax and was its CEO at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Zaffaroni _ who also founded Alza, Affymetrix and DNAX and
headed pharmaceutical giant Syntex _ was not accused of
intentionally violating U.S. securities laws or personally
benefiting from the news leaks.
</P>
<P>
   Three of Zaffaroni's friends and two family members who received
the information about the merger have agreed to pay back insider
trading profits and interest totaling $746,411 and $552,021 in
penalties.
</P>
<P>
   They include Eugene Farber of Portola Valley, who agreed to pay
$230,510; Nicholas Vida of San Mateo, $83,501; Alba Rose Arzate of
Mexico City, $165,809; and relatives Pedro Zaffaroni and Ines
Romero of Montevideo, Uruguay, will pay $746,973 and $71,639,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC alleges that following meetings and phone calls with
Zaffaroni, his friends purchased large blocks of Affymax stock in
the two weeks preceding the Glaxo takeover announcement. (After the
deal was announced, Affymax shot from $18 to $29.50 per share.)
</P>
<P>
   Zaffaroni also told his sister in Uruguay that he could not
attend her 80th birthday because of the pending deal, and she
passed this information on to other relatives who acted on it.
</P>
<P>
   Zaffaroni, who is 75 and lives in Atherton, could not be reached
for comment. But his attorney, Michael Shepard of Heller Ehrman
White &AMP; McAuliffe, said, ``Dr. Zaffaroni made no trades, received
no benefit from any trading by others and did not intentionally tip
anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trading in Uruguay was conducted by distant relatives of
Dr. Zaffaroni who took advantage of a social call,'' Shepard added.
He said Zaffaroni settled the case ``to devote his time to science
and charity rather than litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The SEC brings 30 to 40 insider trading actions a year. ``If
anyone would be aware of insider trading laws, it should be
Zaffaroni,'' said SEC attorney Peter Bresnan. ``This is not one
isolated incident that could be described as a slip of the tongue,
but four separate instances of communicating that a company is
being taken over.''
</P>
<P>
   In previous legal actions against Affymax resulting from tips to
friends and family by a legal assistant to the company's general
counsel, the SEC recovered nearly $300,000 in insider trading
profits and penalties.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
