<HEADER>
A1414 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-PGA-HNS &LR;      08-13 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
O'Meara stays 
humble, focused
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JAYNE CUSTRED &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ It's funny, actually, when Mark O'Meara takes
the time to really think about it. It was only a few months ago
when O'Meara wore the mantle of best player never to win a major.
Now, he's the unquestioned authority on what it takes to be
successful in the big tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a vicious circle, the circle that goes around here,''
O'Meara said. ``First, the fact that I hadn't won a major was the
talk. Then, I win a major and it's, `How do you win the first
major?' And then I win the second major, and it's like, `OK, can he
win the third major?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, if I don't play good for the rest of my life, it will be,
`How come you can't play good anymore?'''
</P>
<P>
   Not that O'Meara was concerned about the prospect. In fact, he
had bigger things on his mind this week at the 1998 PGA
Championship at Sahalee Country Club. Things like becoming the
first man since Ben Hogan in 1953 to win three major championships
in one season.
</P>
<P>
   When the first round gets under way today, bringing professional
golf to the Northwest for the first time, O'Meara will be among the
favorites. A footnote when the season began, O'Meara has climbed to
the top of the PGA Tour ranks and has become something of a major
guru, a big-brother type who can counsel the young guys and still
beat the pants off them.
</P>
<P>
   And despite having two major titles, O'Meara hasn't lost any
enthusiasm for winning more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for me to come here and try to play well,''
O'Meara said. ``There will be plenty of pressure on me. I'll be
nervous when I'm out there playing, like I am in any championship.
If I get in contention and have a chance on Sunday, then I'll give
it a shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I'm going to try to go for it. There's no reason why
not to. People remember the people who win. You don't remember who
finishes second, third, fourth or fifth. They remember who wins the
golf tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his accomplishments, O'Meara insists he's not one of the
great players in the game. That's a title he reserves for the
legends like Jack Nicklaus, Byron Nelson and Hogan. Point out that
O'Meara is trying to tie his name with Hogan's forever by taking
three majors in one year, and O'Meara gets almost embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just to even have the opportunity or even be tossed around in
that same light as a Mr. Hogan is a tremendous honor,'' O'Meara
said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara also is one of the lucky ones who had the opportunity to
know Hogan. When O'Meara turned pro in 1980, he did so in Fort
Worth at Hogan's office. And O'Meara maintained a relationship with
Hogan and the Hogan company for his first seven years as a
professional.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were several occasions where he took me aside or I
watched him hit golf balls or he'd watch me hit golf balls,''
O'Meara said. ``A couple of times, I would be struggling with my
game and I'd sit down and write him a handwritten letter asking for
some help or advice. And he'd pick up the phone and call me and
tell me he wasn't a teacher. Didn't want to teach me anything
because he didn't want me to ruin my game.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he gave me good advice. At times, he treated me like a
grandson. And at other times, he was very distant. So I think I got
to know him as well as most young players of our era. And it was a
lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   But while O'Meara is reluctant to link his name with Hogan's in
the great-player department, others aren't so shy. Fred Couples
couldn't say enough about the 41-year-old O'Meara.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a great player,'' Couples said. ``He talks a lot about
`semi.' But he's a good player. Winning two majors is incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Defending PGA champion Davis Love III agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark's coming in with a lot of confidence,'' Love said. ``Mark
is a very patient, scrambling, hard-working golfer. He's just
getting his due right now. (Winning a major) just kind of confirmed
what the players have always known, that Mark O'Meara is one of the
great players of all time.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I hope that he continues on, because he is not only a
great player, he's one of the great gentlemen of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, all the praise in the world isn't going to help
O'Meara win golf tournaments, specifically the 1998 PGA, and he
knows it. That will be up to his game and mental attitude. O'Meara
said Wednesday that long irons will be at a premium this week,
which is good for him, and while the fairways are narrow, he called
the course very fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've picked a course that is going to require a lot of
thought, and it's going to require a lot of shot-making, not only
on the tee but also coming into the greens,'' O'Meara said. ``If I
put the ball in the fairway off the tee, and keep it in the fairway
most of the week, then there's no reason why I shouldn't have a
good week and play well. I really like the greens. The surface and
the texture are probably the best greens that we've putted on all
year.''
</P>
<P>
   The last man with a chance to win three majors in one year was
Nick Faldo, who won the 1990 Masters and British Open. He finished
tied for 19th at the PGA Championship that year, ending any hopes
of tying Hogan. Only Bobby Jones has won four majors in one season.
But O'Meara is poised on the edge of golf history, just waiting for
his ball to drop in for his third major victory of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think anything's possible,'' O'Meara said. ``If you had told
me at the beginning of the year that I would have the opportunity
to win two of them, I would have jumped and prayed for the chance
to have that happen, let alone coming here and know that Ben Hogan
was the last player to win three major championships in one year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the odds are a little stacked against me. But that
doesn't stop me from going out there and trying to give it my best.
And if I have a chance come Sunday afternoon, hopefully I can dwell
on what I've learned from the Masters and the British Open and use
that to my advantage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
