A1415 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SENATE-DEMS-DEBATE     08-13 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-DEMS-DEBATE-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREEN AND SCHUMER CLASH IN DEBATE AS FERRARO LOOKS ON 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ New York City Public Advocate Mark Green and Rep.
Charles Schumer clashed Wednesday night over the tone of the
Democratic Senate primary as Green repeatedly assailed Schumer's
positions on Social Security and health insurance abuses, and
Schumer warned that such intraparty attacks could insure the
re-election of the Republican incumbent, Sen. Alfonse D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   The third major Democratic candidate in the race, former Rep.
Geraldine Ferraro, sat by silently in their second debate as Green,
almost from the moment his microphone was switched on, attacked
Schumer by seeking to raise concerns about his Democratic
credentials in a forum sponsored by a labor federation.
</P>
<P>
   Green pointed to positions that Schumer had taken during 18
years in Congress to support his contention that he would not
protect Social Security or block insurance company abuses.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the evening, Schumer ignored Green, sitting with his
arms folded tightly in front of him. But finally, as the forum drew
to a close, Schumer reached under his chair and produced a blown-up
headline from a 1992 issue of the New York Post _ ``Dem Debaters
Dish Dirt Again'' _ reminding his rivals and audience of the
Democratic infighting that occurred the last time the party tried
to come up with a candidate to unseat D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be focusing our fire on Al D'Amato,'' Schumer said.
``Otherwise, we're going to repeat what happened in the 1992
primary. Democrats will bash one another and Al D'Amato will be
your senator.''
</P>
<P>
   Green, who had had no success until then in provoking an
exchange with Schumer, looked out at the audience and grinned. ``If
the congressman wants to run on his record, he's going to have to
defend it,'' he said. ``I know the difference between slander and
substance and I'm sure you do as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The exchange between Green and Schumer was the most memorable
moment in the candidates' last scheduled joint appearance until the
weekend before the Sept. 15 primary.
</P>
<P>
   More than that, though, the session suggested a change in the
tenor of the campaign, with Schumer and Green emerging as the main
contestants at the expense of Ms. Ferraro, who was once considered
the front-runner because of her political history. She is a former
member of Congress from Queens who was the Democratic vice
presidential nominee in 1984.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The three candidates were warmly received; indeed, the only
person who received a bad reception was one of the moderators, Dave
Hepp, a host of ``Inside Albany,'' a weekly public television show,
who tried to ask the three candidates for their opinions about
President Clinton's legal difficulties. The first mention of the
name ``Lewinsky,'' though, brought a chorus of boos and hisses, and
shouts of ``No, no, no.'' ``You're wasting our time!'' one man
shouted.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've just gotten the response,'' Schumer told Hepp, a
respected fixture in Albany news reporting. ``Next question.''
</P>
<P>
   The forum was sponsored by the New York State Public Employees
Federation, which is to announce its endorsement Thursday. The
remarks by the candidates were clearly intended, to some extent, to
court the union's support.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Green's attempts to draw differences between himself,
Ms. Ferraro and Schumer, the hour-long debate showed that their
views were similar on many issues of interest to labor. All three
candidates, for example, said they would oppose a flat tax and a
national sales tax, as well as oppose proposals that governments
hire private companies to do public work. Ms. Ferraro, Green and
Schumer also said they opposed any effort to turn over either
Social Security or Medicare to private concerns, an issue that is
more likely to arise in the general election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The privatization issue is a real bad idea _ all you have to
do is look at the stock market over the last month,'' Ms. Ferraro
said. The candidates also opposed efforts to require income-level
testing for recipients of Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, the candidates were vague on what they would do to
protect the long-term viability of the Social Security system. Ms.
Ferraro said she had asked Clinton to appoint her to a commission
to recommend ways of protecting the system's solvency. Green said
he would oppose increasing Social Security taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer avoided a question about whether he might eventually
support raising either the retirement age or Social Security taxes.
Instead, he argued that the projected federal budget surpluses
would be enough to insure the system's viability.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ferraro's position on the sidelines might have reflected a
political decision: Polls still show her in the lead, and it is
arguably in her interest not to do anything to upset the balance.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Ms. Ferraro, in her conclusion, argued that one of the
reasons the labor union should support her is that she is the
candidate with the best chance of defeating D'Amato, who is seeking
a fourth term.
</P>
<P>
   ``When push comes to shove, take a look at the polls,'' she
said. ``I'm the only one who can beat him. None of them do.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer and Green sought to make similar claims. As Schumer put
it: ``I'd say this to Al D'Amato: `You have never been up against a
Chuck Schumer in your life. You don't know what you're in for.'''
</P>
<P>
   Green, who was the Democratic Senate nominee in 1986 and lost to
D'Amato, offered the same argument, if for different reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I have made the case against Al D'Amato over 12 years, I
think I have the best experience to finally privatize him in
1998,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
