u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-NOTEBOOK-NYT     08-13 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNDLEY WORKS EXTRA FROM THE RIGHT SIDE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Todd Hundley said he would be at Busch Stadium
``early, early, early,'' on Wednesday. And there Hundley was, four
hours before game time, taking right-handed swings off a Mets coach
one day after he had struck out three times batting right-handed
against St. Louis left-hander Kent Mercker.
</P>
<P>
   By session's end, Hundley was driving the ball with authority
off the left-handed coach, Randy Niemann. True, it was only batting
practice. But for someone who is 1 for 12 with 11 strikeouts and 1
walk from the right side of the plate since his midseason comeback,
any positive sign had to be embraced.
</P>
<P>
   After, Hundley said he felt he had figured some things out as he
tried to find a good, fluid motion to his stroke. Niemann said the
same. And Manager Bobby Valentine, who watched the session, seemed
optimistic that something positive had been accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he and Tom clicked on a little something,''
Valentine said, referring to the hitting coach, Tom Robson. ``At
the end, he hit the ball much better. He should be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   The question, of course, is how long can the Mets, who are in
the middle of a wild-card race, afford to wait for Hundley to show
anything as a right-handed hitter?
</P>
<P>
   Butch Huskey (left hamstring strain) is eligible to come off the
disabled list Tuesday. And even though Valentine said he might want
the right-handed-hitting Huskey to take a minor league
rehabilitation assignment before he comes back, it is possible that
Hundley and Huskey might end up platooning in the outfield _
Hundley playing against righties, and Huskey against lefties.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, however, Valentine doesn't seem all that worried
about Hundley's complete ineffectiveness from the right side (he
was only hitting .205 over all going into last night's game).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one of those things,'' Valentine said. ``Todd
sometimes gets hot right-handed, but it's never been his strongest
side.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Valentine pointed out, he prefers to have Hundley's bat
in place in the lineup, because the other team will often bring in
a right-handed reliever. That was the case here Tuesday night, and
Hundley delivered a key run batted in off the St. Louis
right-hander Mark Petkovsek.
</P>
<P>
   As for pinch-hitting for Hundley against a left-hander in a key
situation, Valentine said, ``Right now, probably not. I don't think
I'd send up Jermaine Allensworth to pinch-hit for Todd Hundley.''
</P>
<P>
   Rest Comes First
</P>
<P>
   It had taken the Mets more than two months to retake the
National League wild-card lead from Chicago on Tuesday night. And
the Cubs had already won in San Francisco on Wednesday afternoon to
pull into a tie with the Mets. But that didn't seem to faze Bobby
Valentine, who manages the way he sees fit. That explains why his
two most important hitters, John Olerud and Mike Piazza, were out
of the Mets' starting lineup Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine is intent on keeping his players rested. He knew that
the Mets' have an off day on Thursday, followed by a three-game
series in Arizona this weekend (including a Sunday night game), a
red-eye flight back to New York, followed by a game Monday night
against Colorado at Shea Stadium. Then come two more games against
the Rockies and back-to-back doubleheaders against the Cardinals.
Then there is a home weekend series against the Diamondbacks
followed by a nine-day West Coast swing. And then, finally, the
team gets another day off on Sept. 3.
</P>
<P>
   That was why Valentine said he might give Edgardo Alfonzo and
Brian McRae the day off on Friday, in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike, at the end of the game last night, looked like he was in
need,'' Valentine said of Piazza. ``And I thought at the end of the
game, John looked like he was right at that point. They'll probably
rest again, too. Rest is one of those things I believe in. You
don't want to run out of gas. When you run out of gas, it hurts the
engine. You want to get in the gas station before you run out of
gas.''
</P>
<P>
   A First for Fabregas
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Fabregas made his first start behind the plate for the
Mets Wednesday night since being acquired from the Arizona
Diamondbacks on July 31, in the Bernard Gilkey trade.
</P>
<P>
   Fabregas admitted he has been hampered all season by a severe
right ankle sprain and a pulled muscle in his abdomen, which might
explain his .192 batting average. As a Met, Fabregas was 0 for 5 in
six games before tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza said that one of the reasons Manager Bobby Valentine
told him he was giving him the day off was because he wanted to get
Fabregas a start before the upcoming back-to-back doubleheaders.
And Piazza added he did not have any problem with Valentine's
decision to rest him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to flip him to the Arizona side of the off day,''
Valentine said. ``But there was no way I could space it any longer
with Fabregas, I didn't think.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
