<SLUG> BC-NY-SHOPKEEPER-SLAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENWICH VILLAGE SHOPKEEPER KILLED; GUNMAN AT LARGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CHARLIE LeDUFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A shopkeeper was fatally shot in the face Wednesday
night in his West Greenwich Village novelty shop, apparently during
an attempted robbery, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The victim, Ki Lim, 34, was pronounced dead around 8:40 p.m.,
his body slumped in a chair in his shop, Village Wear Design, at 87
Christopher St., said Capt. Charles Hanley of the Manhattan South
Detective Squad.
</P>
<P>
   According to Hanley, a man entered the shop, which is on the
busy Christopher Street strip between Bleecker Street and Seventh
Avenue, and forced Lim into the back of the store behind a display
case, ``a place where customers are not normally invited to go.''
It was there that Lim was shot in the face, police said. It was
8:30 p.m. and Lim was still open for business, selling T-shirts,
buttons, sunglasses and sundry items.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a noise coming from the cash register that we think
indicates that someone tried to break into it,'' Hanley said. No
money was stolen, he said, and the shop did not appear to have been
ransacked. He said investigators believe the gunman left
empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect fled on foot, investigators said, and as of
Wednesday night police had no suspects and few leads. The only clue
was a single bullet casing near the body, suggesting the weapon was
a semi-automatic pistol, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   Police were questioning neighbors Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seemed like a decent, hard-working guy,'' said Andy Fair,
who lives above the shop. ``It's pretty shocking. This kind of
thing doesn't happen in the stores around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Lim opened the store about three years ago. John Park, a local
merchant and a friend of Lim's, said he was a Korean immigrant who
consistently worked 12-hour days in the shop, seven days a week.
</P>
<P>
   Lim emigrated from Seoul a decade ago, was married and had a
7-year-old girl and a 3-year-old boy, Park said. ``They're here by
themselves,'' Park said. ``They have no relatives here. We'll try
to help them.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with the explosion of bars and foot traffic in the West
Village in recent years, violent crime _ particularly murder _ is
relatively uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   Located within the 6th Precinct, the West Village has
historically been one of the city's safest districts. Until
Wednesday night, there had only been one reported murder this year,
that of an aspiring actress, Naomi Maki, 23. On May 7, she was
fatally shot by her ex-boyfriend, not far from her apartment on
Morton Street. So far this year, there have been six reported
rapes, according to police records.
</P>
<P>
   There were no reported murders in 1997 or 1996, and three in
1995. In August 1994, Greenwich Village jeweler Alfonoso Albrizio
was fatally stabbed by a man with a long arrest record after the
two quarreled in Albrizio's store. That store, C'est Magnifique,
had catered to a celebrity clientele that included Madonna and
Bruce Springsteen, embodying a special brand of West Village
eclecticism.
</P>
<P>
   But New York being New York, a murder is a curio and moments
after police arrived people with pizza slices and bottled beer were
peeking through windows, trying to steal a glimpse inside.
</P>
<P>
   It is people like that who make neighbors suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   ``This street has had a particularly uneasy feeling to it,
especially at night,'' said Teimoc Johnston, 41. ``It's not so much
the people who live here, but the people who hang out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
