<SLUG> BC-RAC-SARATOGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KELLY KIP SHOWS DAZZLING SPEED AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ In racing, speed is dangerous,
especially at short distances. And no horse demonstrates it more
relentlessly than Kelly Kip, who flashed his speed again at
Saratoga on Wednesdy, winning the A Phenomenon Handicap by three
lengths and streaking to his third straight victory.
</P>
<P>
   He did not set a track record, as he had already done at Belmont
Park, Aqueduct and Finger Lakes. But he did race six furlongs in
1:09 3/5, which is faster than anybody else has run it during this
meeting. And he outran any horse who came close, especially the
accomplished Richter Scale, who dueled him into the homestretch
before conceding. In the True North at Belmont Park two months ago,
Richter Scale and Trafalgar withstood the speed of Kelly Kip, but
not this time.
</P>
<P>
   After leading all the way, pursued closely by Richter Scale,
Kelly Kip poured it on as they shot down the stretch and finished
three lengths in front of Trafalgar, who had 2{ lengths on Receiver
in a well-scattered field of seven. And Richter Scale by then had
faded to sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not good, he's remarkable,'' said Allen Jerkens, who
trains Kelly Kip for the Hobeau Farm. ``What's remarkable is he can
be vanned for four or five hours and be ready to run. He's got
God-given speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Luc Samyn, the regular rider on Kelly Kip, praised his star
in these words: ``He's been getting better and better. He's got to
be sprint-champion material. He has carried more weight each time,
and he's doing what we are asking him to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Kip carried high weight of 122 pounds and was the solid
favorite, returning $4.10 for a $2 bet to win. He was shadowed for
five furlongs by Richter Scale, who carried 120 pounds and was the
second favorite. But the duel ended in the homestretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really felt confident going around the turn,'' said Jerry
Bailey, who rode Richter Scale, ``and I figured that it was just
going to be us and Kelly Kip. At one point, we were on even terms,
and I thought we were going to be able to outrun him. But once
Kelly Kip started to open up, my horse just vanished underneath
me.''
</P>
<P>
   D. Wayne Lukas, who trains Trafalgar, gave the ultimate salute
to the speed of the winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kelly Kip is proving that he's a quality horse,'' Lukas said,
``and, with that, when we saw a first quarter in 23 seconds, that
just gave us too much to make up.
</P>
<P>
   ``With an average horse, you can possibly run them down, but not
one like Kelly Kip.''
</P>
<P>
   FINISH LINES
</P>
<P>
   _ The trustees of the New York Racing Association approved a
schedule of dates for next year's Saratoga meeting that mirrors
this year's. It will consist of 36 racing dates from Wednesday,
July 28, through Labor Day, Monday, Sept. 6.
</P>
<P>
   _ The booming market in horse sales continued on the opening
night of Saratoga's auction of selected yearlings. The 58 yearlings
sold fetched $13 million, an increase of 44 percent over last
year's opening session. The average price was $226,000, a gain of
29 percent. And the show stopper was a chestnut filly by Storm Cat
who brought $1.7 million, the fourth-highest price for a yearling
filly in the history of the Fasig-Tipton auction house. RICHARD
MULHALL, the agent for Prince AHMED SALMAN, the buyer, said:
``She's a big, good-looking filly and very hard to fault. Of all
the horses in the sale, she's the top pick.'' The sale closes
Thursday night. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
