<SLUG> BC-RANGERS-INDIANS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS FALTER WITH RUNNERS IN SCORING POSITION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Texas Rangers manager Johnny Oates rarely criticizes
his players.
</P>
<P>
   Oates' No. 1 complaint during his four-year tenure with the
organization involves his players sometimes trying too hard.
</P>
<P>
   The manager witnessed that in a 6-3 loss to the Indians on
Wednesday night at Jacobs Field. The Rangers squeezed too tightly
and let victory slip between their fingers by pressing at the plate
with runners aboard.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers _ who stranded 12 runners, including seven at either
second or third base _ went 0-for-7 with runners in scoring
position in the final seven innings. Thus, the second-place Angels,
who Wednesday night beat the Tigers, 3-2, crept within a half-game
of the Rangers in the American League West.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt in my mind that we take different swings in
run-producing situations,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Mark McLemore, left fielder Rusty Greer and
catcher Ivan Rodriguez went down on strikes with a runner at third
and less than two outs during the course of the evening.
</P>
<P>
   The manager would prefer at-bats like the one delivered by third
baseman Todd Zeile in the seventh inning against Indians
right-hander Steve Reed, who dodged a bullet after retiring
Rodriguez on strikes with one out and runners at first and third.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile then strode to the plate and lined a pitch into left
field. The ball, though, carried directly into the glove of left
fielder Brian Giles.
</P>
<P>
   ``He worked and got a good pitch to hit and smoked it right at
Giles,'' Oates said. ``Those are the type of at-bats we need. We
gave away some outs tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, who entered the game leading the league in hitting
with runners in scoring position (.308), indeed squandered their
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   None proved more frustrating than the fourth inning against
All-Star right-hander Bartolo Colon (12-6).
</P>
<P>
   Right fielder Roberto Kelly drew a leadoff walk and advanced to
second on a single by shortstop Royce Clayton. Center fielder Tom
Goodwin advanced the runners with a sacrifice bunt, but Colon
retired McLemore and Greer on strikes to terminate the threat.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers also rejected the Indians' generosity in the sixth
inning. Kelly reached on the second of two errors by usually
sure-handed shortstop Omar Vizquel and advanced on a sacrifice bunt
by Clayton.
</P>
<P>
   However, Colon stranded another runner in scoring position by
inducing consecutive ground balls from Goodwin and McLemore.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers also failed to convert two defensive plays that
allowed two of the Indians' runs. Vizquel's deep fly ball to right
field during the fourth inning resulted in a double after it
glanced off Kelly's glove, and Clayton's seventh-inning throw to
the plate sailed over the head of Rodriguez and allowed Indians
first baseman Richie Sexson to score on a double by second baseman
David Bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this,'' Oates said, ``could be described as a game of
near misses for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates saw this as a ball game the Rangers could have won, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the manager saw his players press and try too hard in
their attempt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
