<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ MAKING PROGRESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ramon Martinez, the Dodgers' top pitcher until
undergoing season-ending surgery on his right shoulder in late
June, is ahead of schedule on his rehabilitation and could begin
throwing lightly in October.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who had rotator cuff and cartilage damage repaired,
returned to Los Angeles on Tuesday from his native Dominican
Republic, where he spent the past month working out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spoke to (Martinez's surgeon) Dr. (Frank) Jobe and he told
me Ramon is two months ahead of schedule,'' said Dodgers vice
president Ralph Avila, who has become the top confidant of general
manager Tom Lasorda. ``If anyone can come back from this, it is
Ramon.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, 30, acknowledged the weeks after his season ended were
difficult emotionally. He had worked diligently from a similar
injury during the winter after electing to pass on surgery. He
opened the season 7-3 with a 2.83 ERA before breaking down and was
told he probably would not pick up a ball until Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard not to get frustrated, thinking that all I did was
not good enough,'' Martinez said. ``It took a few weeks to get
through that. But then I realized if I was going to come back again
I had to put that aside and concentrate on my rehab.''
</P>
<P>
   Jobe, who said after the surgery that Martinez could be back on
a major-league mound next June, examined the pitcher Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``His strength and range of motion are excellent,'' Jobe said.
``It's too soon to say if that means he'll be back any sooner, but
we are very encouraged.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez is in the final season of a multi-year contract, but
there is a club option for 1999 at $5.6 million. The Dodgers are
expected to offer Martinez a $500,000 buyout and re-sign him at a
lower figure.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez had hinted to friends he might like to rejoin his
brother Pedro with the Boston Red Sox, but Pedro has said he
doesn't think that is a good idea because of the unforgiving fans
in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too soon to say how that is going to go,'' Avila said.
</P>
<P>
   Florida's Orie: One of the most interesting players to watch for
the Florida Marlins the final six weeks of the season is third
baseman Kevin Orie, who was acquired at the trade deadline from the
Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Orie was a promising rookie for the Cubs last year after jumping
two minor-league levels to have eight homers and 44 RBI. But he
fell out of favor after a slow start this year. He was the Cubs'
Opening Day third baseman but batted just .181 in 64 games and also
spent a month in the minors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still trying to figure out what happened,'' said Orie, who
was traded with two minor leaguers for left-hander Felix Heredia
and and minor-league pitcher Steve Hoff. ``They said I was part of
the future, but I guess the future changed. This is a good place to
be. They'll give me the chance to play. That's all I ask.''
</P>
<P>
   Orie, who did not start Wednesday, said he lost some confidence
after having several potential home runs cut down by the stiff
Wrigley Field wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must have lost six or eight homers the first month and
started to press,'' Orie said. ``It just kind of snowballed from
there. Hopefully everything will come together here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
