<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ACURA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELES GLAD TO BE BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE STEVENS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANHATTAN BEACH _ Welcome back.
</P>
<P>
   That was the appropriate phrase to say to Monica Seles when she
returned to the Acura Classic, which she won last year. The phrase
was especially apropos to welcome her (begin ital)back(end ital).
</P>
<P>
   Seles considered withdrawing from the tournament because of
chronic stiffness in her back. Last week at the Toshiba Classic in
La Costa, Seles' back bothered her so much at times she could not
swing a racket. But after physical-therapy treatments, she felt
better Wednesday. Seles, showing no effects, needed just 49 minutes
to beat Barbara Paulus 6-1, 6-2 in the Acura Classic's second
round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing better, but it's not 100 percent,'' Seles said.
``There were no aches, no pains today.''
</P>
<P>
   Paulus, ranked 37th on the Corel WTA tour, did not present a
serious threat to the tournament's defending champ. Seles, seeded
fourth and ranked sixth in the world, is 4-0 in her career against
her. The most games Paulus ever won in a set against Seles is two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I had to be careful,'' said Seles about taking a win
for granted against Paulus. ``Nobody plays a topspin game like she
does.''
</P>
<P>
   But that nonstop topspin did not trip up Seles.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd greeted Seles with earsplitting applause and more of
the same as she left the stadium. The Yugoslavia native and
resident of Sarasota, Fla., is a crowd favorite in Los Angeles,
winning three of the four times she has played here and making it
to the finals the other time.
</P>
<P>
   She also is a favorite because of her past and the empathy she
receives because of it. On April 30, 1993, Seles' life changed
during a changeover in a match in Hamburg, Germany. Ranked first in
the world then, Seles was stabbed below her left shoulder blade.
The incident knocked her out of tennis for nearly 2{ years. She
never has regained a top ranking alone.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Seles' life changed again when her father and coach,
Karolj, died on May 14 after losing a battle with stomach cancer.
In the first tournament after his death, she beat top-ranked
Martina Hingis in the French Open's semifinals and appeared ready
to make a serious run at reclaiming the top ranking.
</P>
<P>
   Seles said she has not played as well as when she beat Hingis.
She considers herself a longshot in this week's tournament. ``I
think it's going to be between Martina and Lindsay Davenport,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Seles is a different player now than she was when she owned the
top ranking. Her foot speed is slower, and her swing may not be as
powerful. Parts of her game have improved, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing I'm doing better than I used to do is my serve
in terms of strength, but not consistency,'' she said. ``Before, I
could go through the French Open and maybe serve one single
double-fault in the entire tournament. Now, I have a hard time
doing that in one match.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the French Open, Seles has yet to take another step toward
No.1, but the environment in Los Angeles could give her a boost,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The three tournaments in California are a tour favorite for
everybody, just because they are so convenient,'' Seles said. ``For
me, this is one of my most favorite tournaments _ that's for
sure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
