<HEADLINE>
SANCHEZ VICARIO WORKS OVERTIME 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE STEVENS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANHATTAN BEACH _ Arantxa Sanchez Vicario had to weather a
grueling, 2-hour, 27-minute match against Ai Sugiyama to advance to
the Acura Classic's quarterfinals at Manhattan Country Club.
Sanchez Vicario edged Sugiyama 4-6, 6-4, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   The match between third-seeded Sanchez Vicario and Sugiyama was
the tournament's closest so far, which Sanchez Vicario expected.
After all, this was her first match in six weeks. During the
layoff, however, Sanchez Vicario didn't exactly sit on her couch
and eat chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have as much of a holiday as I wish I could have,''
said Sanchez Vicario, who spent a lot of her time working on her
game.
</P>
<P>
   The close match had more to do with the emergence of Sugiyama,
ranked 16th.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis advances easily: Top-ranked and top-seeded Martina Hingis
did not have many problems when she eliminated Iva Majoli 6-3, 6-3.
Majoli, ranked 20th, could not pull the upset on her 21st birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we both played well,'' Hingis said. ``It's hard to
play somebody on her birthday, but once you get on the court, you
always want to be the best player.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucky loser wins: Before her first-round match on Wednesday,
Mary Pierce withdrew from the tournament because of a strained
right groin. So the lucky loser, Elena Tatarkova, ranked 79th,
earned a spot in the tournament and beat Yayuk Basuki 4-6, 6-3,
6-3. The lucky loser is the highest-ranked player who lost in one
of the four qualifying-round finals.
</P>
</TEXT>
