<HEADLINE>
HEART SURGERY TO BE PERFORMED ON THE INTERNET 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RUTH SoRELLE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The network that broadcast a live Internet birth June
16 plans to put open heart surgery from the Texas Heart Institute
on the Internet next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The patient who will undergo the procedure has not yet been
named, institute spokeswoman Jennifer Snyder said Wednesday in
Houston. Nor has it been revealed exactly what kind of open-heart
procedure will be performed.
</P>
<P>
   But the procedure will be live on the America's Health Network
Web site at www.ahn.com and on its cable television channel.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder said she could not confirm that Dr. Denton Cooley _ THI's
surgeon-in-chief _ will perform the operation, although he probably
will be in the surgical suite while it was going on.
</P>
<P>
   The birth to Elizabeth Ann and Gilberto Oliver attracted
worldwide attention and more than a million hits on the site, said
the network's officials.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands who tried to view the birth were unable to see it
because of the great demand.
</P>
<P>
   Cooley, in a statement, said: ``We elected to take part in this
Internet/cable broadcast because it offers an unprecedented
opportunity to teach the public the importance of heart disease
prevention, and to inform them about the new technologies and
treatment that helped many patients live longer and more satisfying
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The surgery will be part of a full day of programming on the
network dedicated to increasing heart health awareness.
</P>
<P>
   Network executives said they had increased the capacity of their
network so that more viewers could log on to the Website during the
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   According to The Associated Press, the Web site supplied about
5,000 simultaneous video streams during the birth but at least
45,000 other users were trying to log on during that time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
