<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO CAN, CAN'T WIN AT PGA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ The shame of the PGA Championship at Sahalee is
that it arrived in the Northwest too late for the competitive
careers of Jack Nicklaus, Arnold Palmer, Gary Player, Lee Trevino
and other big names from the childhoods of all the aging yuppies
whose split levels do their ungainly squats upon the Sammamish
plateau.
</P>
<P>
   Even Greg Norman, a potential successor to the legacy of the
ancients, skipped this one because of injury.
</P>
<P>
   What we have teeing off Thursday morning, for those who don't
consider themselves dimpleheads (the golf equivalent of baseball
seamheads), is Tiger Woods, local hero Fred Couples and everybody
else. The prospect has all the panache of the Sahalee clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   While it's true that having 86 of the world's 100 top-rated
golfers makes this the toughest field in the history of majors (at
least in the history since some corporation bought rights to invent
rankings), the course is not overflowing with charismatic figures
who transcend the game.
</P>
<P>
   Mark O'Meara, winner of the Masters and British Open, is as fine
a gentleman and golfer as the sport has produced, but he's a late
bloomer and a bit of a beige wall.
</P>
<P>
   John Daly can certainly light up a gallery, but his shots lately
are spending too much time in the gallery. Besides, a broken putter
is not the sort of thing the PGA likes to put on the cover of its
media guide.
</P>
<P>
   Two-time PGA winner Nick Price is another good man who's a
household name in Zimbabwe and among the golf mags, but won't snap
many heads on the Monorail.
</P>
<P>
   None of this precludes the novice tourney follower from having a
good time this week _ as long as you stick with the winner. If
you're not in this for love (Davis or golf), and if you're not a
trendoid who must be in either the Woods or Couples camp, here's a
useful, if highly inaccurate, P-I guide for the great unwashed.
</P>
<P>
   WHO CAN'T WIN
</P>
<P>
   Any European. No player from the Incontinent has won the PGA
since the Depression, which also coincides with the rise of
international soccer as well as the rock group ABBA. Clearly the
answer to the decay of European society lies here.
</P>
<P>
   Unconventional fashion statement-makers. Sorry, David Duval
(sunglasses), Payne Stewart (knickers), Jesper Parnevik (turned-up
hat). PGA policy is to never allow its tournament to be won by a
player more than a single wingtip removed from the dead middle of
fashion mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   Owners of Microsoft stock. In case you've missed page one, also
in Redmond this week is the Justice Department, which is holding
Bill Gates upside down by the ankles, trying to shake the truth out
of him. If it works, the value of Microsoft stock could drop
dramatically, and all these rich golfers will spend the weekend
screaming into their cell phones at their brokers.
</P>
<P>
   Woods. One big stock more vulnerable than Microsoft is Nike,
which has buried itself so deeply into Woods' soul that when he
sneezes, swooshes fill his handkerchief. Now that Nike is in
free-fall, it will insist that Woods win the PGA. The pressure will
be so great that he will fail.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who talks to his ball. If you see anyone on the course
screaming after his shot, ``Get left!'' or ``Bite!'', realize he's
a muni hack just like you, performing the silliest, most hackneyed
cliche in golf. Besides, in big tournaments, galleries are much
closer to the end of shots than the golfers. The ball can hear them
better.
</P>
<P>
   Retief Goosen and Scott Gump. No one named Goosen or Gump can
win a major.
</P>
<P>
   WHO COULD WIN
</P>
<P>
   An Australian. After the Yanks, the Aussies have won more PGA
titles than any other nationality (Jim Ferrier, 1947; David Graham,
1979; Wayne Grady, 1990; Steve Elkington, 1995). There are seven
here: Elkington, Robert Allenby, Stuart Appleby, Greg Chalmers,
Stephen Leaney, Peter Lonard and Craig Parry. You have to like the
idea Sunday afternoon at the clubhouse of more shrimp for the
barbie and more ice for the Fosters.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has his club manufacturer's name and logo on his bag
in type the size of radar stations. This would be everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Couples. The guy is sandbagging. He's poormouthed his recent
game in order to take some pressure off having to carry the clubs
for all of Northwest golf. But lurking inside is the beast of
Jefferson Park, whose furor was fueled by rubber mats, muddy greens
and greasy clubhouse fries. It's something that no rival PGA golfer
wants to see unleashed upon him.
</P>
<P>
   Duffy Waldorf. Somebody named Duffy MUST win a major sometime.
</P>
<P>
   WHO WILL WIN
</P>
<P>
   Billy Mayfair. After O'Meara's triumphs at the Masters and
British Open, it is clear this is the year of roundness. Mayfair is
a round guy, about 5-foot-8 and 180-190 pounds, with a wild shock
of platinum hair and enough rumples to make a good sportswriter.
All these long, lean powerhouses like Woods and Ernie Els are good
for TV, but as with normal women and supermodels, nobody can
relate.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Mayfair beat Woods in a playoff to win the Los Angeles
Open. Last week, he won the Buick Open in Michigan. He's also the
perfect semi-obscure but solid guy (prize winnings of more than $4
million) who tends to make his career with a PGA win, like Grady,
Mark Brooks, Jeff Sluman and Bob Tway.
</P>
<P>
   For the demographic-minded, in the 79 previous PGAs, guys
between ages 30 and 34 have won the most times (35). Mayfair is 32.
That fact is as relevant to forecasting Sunday's winner as any
other speculation you will hear this week.
</P>
<P>
   I have no idea if Mayfair's game is made for Sahalee. Mainly
because nobody's game is made for Sahalee unless he's a beaver or a
termite.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
