<SLUG> BC-BKL-ABLCUTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABL TO REDUCE EMPLOYEE SALARIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American Basketball League will begin administering
temporary salary cuts to all its employees, except for contracted
players and coaches, effective when pay checks are released later
in August.
</P>
<P>
   Front office employees were informed last week that that will
receive 10 percent reductions and as many as nine league personnel
will have cuts ranging from 15 to 100 percent in an ongoing effort
to increase profitability in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is we'll have it restored in three to five months,''
said Jim Weyermann, who was promoted from league vice president for
team operations to chief operating officer on Monday. ``We want to
use the savings to channel them into revenue generating initiatives
that increase our profitability. Part of that is marketing, part of
that's broadcasts, part of that's P.R., whatever those initiatives
are we want them to ... have a significant return on that
investment.''
</P>
<P>
   The league's financial demands have increased since expanding
from nine to 10 teams for the upcoming third season, slated to
begin in November. Plus it recently signed a television agreement
with CBS in which the league will have to locate advertisers for
the two playoff games the network will broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   Although coaches are excluded, they will be asked to volunteer
10 percent of their salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is we would like coaches to participate on the part
of the organization across the board, but we understand that
individual choice and circumstances will differ. I don't think that
we're in position to say that they've all agreed to it. I think the
majority on the phone at that point thought that that was something
they would be able to do,'' said Weyermann.
</P>
<P>
   So far, negative reaction from employees regarding the cuts have
been minimum, he said.
</P>
<P>
   `` Does everybody want to do it, no, but there wasn't a massive
outbreak.''
</P>
<P>
   Weyerman talked to all 10 general managers who reported that
employees ``understood the choice, they understood the decision,
and they understood it was part of the league needing to get more
profitable. The bottom line is we have to manage for the long
term.''
</P>
<P>
   The cuts effect six employees in the Long Beach StingRay
franchise, including general manager Bill McGillis. McGillis, who
declined to comment specifically about the cuts and the effect on
his staff, said he was optimistic about the future of the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I can say is that the league is looking for an important
financial model that would insure the ABL's long term health. This
is part of that,'' McGillis said.
</P>
<P>
   Weyermann said that employees who were expected to receive pay
increases in August will have their reductions made against the
projected raises. The raises will be activated when the cuts are no
longer necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are trends and there are things that we have to get
ourselves through and being fiscally responsible is one of the tops
things on our list along with providing the best product we can on
the basketball court,'' Weyermann said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 0111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
