<SLUG> BC-BKC-COTTON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COTTON TO PLAY AT LONG BEACH CITY COLLEGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LOUIS JOHNSON  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former St. John Bosco High star Schea Cotton has finally found a
place to play basketball. And this time, he didn't have to travel
across the country to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Cotton, who was one of the most celebrated high school players
in the history of Southern California, enrolled at Long Beach City
College on Monday morning, according to sports information director
Dean Hopkins, and plans to suit up for coach Gary Anderson's team
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Cotton's decision to attend LBCC is the latest chapter in an
odyssey that has seen the 6-foot-6 swingman sign three different
letters of intent with three different universities; gain his
collegiate eligibility only to have it revoked by the NCAA;
consider entering the NBA draft even though he hadn't played a high
school basketball game since his junior year; and finally deciding
to attend St. Thomas More Academy, a prep school in Oakdale, Conn.,
this past season while his family appealed the NCAA's decision.
</P>
<P>
   The Cotton family's battles with the NCAA have played the
biggest part in his becoming a Viking. They started after Schea was
released from the first letter of intent he signed with Long Beach
State in April of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few weeks after gaining his release from the 49ers,
Cotton signed a letter of intent with UCLA and seemed on the verge
of joining a standout recruiting class that included current Bruin
point guard Baron Davis.
</P>
<P>
   But Cotton and Davis spent most of last summer embroiled in a
NCAA probe that looked into the 1997 Ford Explorers both players
were driving. Also at question was the relationship between the
players and well-known traveling league coach Pat Barrett.
</P>
<P>
   Both players were eventually cleared of any wrongdoing, but
Cotton learned a week before he was to enroll in classes at UCLA
last fall that his college entrance examination score was being
invalidated by the NCAA Eligibility Clearinghouse because he had
received special accommodations a test with bigger print and no
time limit while taking the exam. The Cotton family contended that
Schea has a learning disability called test anxiety, but the NCAA
said it did not receive proper documentation regarding Cotton's
disability.
</P>
<P>
   While he appealed the NCAA's decision, Cotton attended St.
Thomas More, where he averaged 23 points and 11 rebounds per game
last season. When UCLA signed All-American shooting guard Ray Young
of Alameda St. Joseph in November, Cotton opted to take his
considerable talents elsewhere and immediately put together a short
list that included North Carolina State, Syracuse and UConn.
</P>
<P>
   N.C. State won the battle for Cotton's services and he signed a
letter of intent with the Wolfpack on April 13, becoming the
centerpiece of a highly regarded class.
</P>
<P>
   But the NCAA denied Cotton's final appeal on June 5, and earlier
this month, N.C. State coach Herb Sendek confirmed that Cotton
would not be a part of his program. With no plans to retake the SAT
and with the NBA no longer a viable option, Cotton was left with
few alternatives, of which going to a junior college emerged as the
most attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Cotton will join a Vikings squad that finished a disappointing
</P>
<P>
   14-16 under interim coach Tony Lipold last season. But four key
players return from the group, led by all-conference forward
Darnell Williams, frontcourt mate Kevin Blunt and guards Isamu
Nichols and Richard Trevino.
</P>
<P>
   Cotton began his high school career at St. John Bosco, where he
played in a handful of games before transferring to Mater Dei just
a few weeks into his freshman season. The muscular lefty guided the
Monarchs to the Division I state title as a sophomore in 1995, but
transferred back to St. John Bosco prior to his junior year.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries and academic difficulties limited his play as a junior,
and a shoulder injury suffered during a summer game completely
wiped out his senior season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 0114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
