<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1456 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-WILCOX-COLUMN-LAD     08-13 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-WILCOX-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PGA IS STEPCHILD AMONG MAJORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG WILCOX  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The season's final major is the last chance for
the world's best golfers to make some noise.
</P>
<P>
   The (begin ital)really big shows(end ital) _ the Masters, U.S.
Open, British Open and even the Players Championship _ generally
suck all of the interest out of golf by the time the PGA arrives,
unless a Ryder Cup match follows.
</P>
<P>
   It's the fourth jewel in the game's grand slam; more a ruby than
a diamond. With no disrespect, the PGA is the smallest of the big
four, even though it's got a tougher field than the Masters, which
lets past champions keep playing again and again and again.
</P>
<P>
   It's a minor major, albeit a lucrative one.
</P>
<P>
   This year's winner pockets $540,000. That's the second biggest
major payday behind the Masters, which paid Mark O'Meara $576,000.
He also collected $492,000 for his British Open victory.
</P>
<P>
   But Justin Leonard took home the biggest check of all, $720,000
for his win at the Players Championship, which is the tournament
that might eventually knock the PGA off its major pedestal.
</P>
<P>
   It's doubtful any pro starts the year focused on winning the
PGA, unless one of the other major titles already resides on his
resume. The exception, of course, might be defending champion Davis
Love III, whose late father was a noted teacher and respected
member of the PGA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always felt like in the majors the most important one was
the one that you were preparing for,'' Love said in a press
conference Wednesday. ``This tournament right now is the biggest
tournament in the world. And it's got the best field that we'll see
until the Players Championship next year.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Love never wins another major, he's proud that his named
is engraved on the PGA trophy.
</P>
<P>
   This tournament makes the John Dalys of the world famous. It's a
first-timer's paradise.
</P>
<P>
   Nine of the last 10 winners used the tournament to excise the
phrase ``best player not to win a major'' from their names.
</P>
<P>
   Colin Montgomerie, the best player in the world not to win a
major, should tee off today as the favorite.
</P>
<P>
   And this week they are playing in Seattle, which is famous for
several things, just not golf. It's the soggiest place on earth,
has lots of great coffee shops, a really big mountain, an even
bigger software company, a world famous rich guy, and Ken Griffey
Jr., who is not the rich guy but, even better, is a fishing buddy
of Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   The PGA is Golf's off-Broadway show, routinely going where the
regular tour dares not. Courses with names like Valhalla and
Crooked Stick, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   In a noble gesture, the PGA _ not the group that puts on the
professional tournaments each week but the one that staffs courses
around the country _ likes to spread its venues around so more fans
get to see a major championship. They are a lot like the U.S. Golf
Association in this respect.
</P>
<P>
   The product is not, though.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995 Steve Elkington claimed the Rodman Wanamaker Trophy,
named for a department store magnate, when the championship came to
Riviera Country Club. Almost no one noticed. The tournament fell
far short of selling out, a rarity for a major. Grandstand seats
were empty on championship Sunday and spectators walking the course
had no trouble getting a good view of the action.
</P>
<P>
   There is some historical precedent in the tournament not getting
the same kind of respect as the other three. No one has ever scored
a gland slam, winning all four majors in the same year.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1953, the late Ben Hogan won the Masters and the U.S. and
British Opens. The PGA was played two weeks after the British and
Hogan, who owns a lot of history, took a pass on making more.
</P>
<P>
   He had been horribly injured in a 1949 car wreck and thought
playing two majors in such short a time would be too demanding.
Hogan never took a shot at the slam.
</P>
<P>
   This year history might just jump up and tell us exactly where
the PGA falls in the major scheme of things if Lee Janzen wins.
</P>
<P>
   Right now O'Meara, winner of two of the four majors, is the
favorite for player of the year.
</P>
<P>
   If Janzen, who won the U.S. Open on Father's Day, emerges on
Sunday from the towering pines lining Sahalee Country Club
clutching the Wanamaker trophy, he too will have two major titles
this year.
</P>
<P>
   So the question is, does a Masters and British Open add up to
more than a U.S. Open and PGA Championship? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 0115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
