<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1459 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLF-PGA-WATSON-SPI &LR;      08-13 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-PGA-WATSON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PGA: WATSON'S UNFINISHED QUEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ For 26 years, Tom Watson has pursued this
title. A PGA Championship would further distinguish an already
fabulous career, one that ranks him with the best in history.
</P>
<P>
   He has won eight major titles, including five British Opens, two
U.S. Opens and one Masters. The fourth leg of the Grand Slam has
been as elusive as his putting stroke. For Watson, it is time to
stop talking and start stalking.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is significant to me,'' Watson said Wednesday after his
practice round at Sahalee. ``This is the one I most want to win.''
</P>
<P>
   If one of golf's enduring players is to prevail Sunday, he would
join Gene Sarazen, Ben Hogan, Gary Player and Jack Nicklaus as the
only men to capture all four majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can pull it off,'' Watson said.
</P>
<P>
   With another 48-year-old, the confidence would sound as if it
came from an aging prizefighter whose punches aren't landing any
more.
</P>
<P>
   But now that he has rediscovered his touch on the greens, Watson
is connecting again. There were signs early this year when he
finished second in Phoenix and Hawaii. In between, he played at
Pebble Beach and is tied for first with Tim Herron with one more
round to go in the rain-delayed tourney Monday, the day after the
PGA concludes.
</P>
<P>
   There is statistical evidence supporting the revival of his
putter. He ranks 20th on tour with 28.55 putts per round. Watson is
first in sand saves, getting up and down 71 percent of the time,
proving he can once again convert the short ones.
</P>
<P>
   The solution was supposedly simple, perhaps complex. Watson
attributed his improved putting to acceleration through the ball
and proper use of his shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   In what was a coincidence or a correlation, Watson also began to
make putts after he stopped drinking in November. He admitted that
the two developments might have been linked.
</P>
<P>
   Watson worked on his lag putting Wednesday, realizing the
importance of two-putts at Sahalee.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't really challenge the pin positions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Watson thinks long-iron play will be critical, an encouraging
possibility given the solid shots he was cracking from the fairways
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But he has not played well in the major championships this year,
missing the cut at all of them, even at the British, where he
expected to play well. He said his swing is ``out of kilter'' but
manageable. It won't cloud his outlook.
</P>
<P>
   ``Byron Nelson said he never wanted to go into a tournament
feeling 100 percent,'' Watson said. ``It was better to be a little
tentative. It made him concentrate more.''
</P>
<P>
   As game faces go, Watson wears one of the best. Nicklaus likened
him to a horse with blinders, so intent is his focus. Criticism
bothers him; distractions do not. Watson's wife of 25 years filed
for divorce in December, and then he went out and played some of
his best golf ever in a three-week stretch spanning January and
February.
</P>
<P>
   He is a man of conviction and contradiction. One of his best
friends, Ben Crenshaw, called him ``a no-nonsense person,'' using
adjectives like resolute and honest.
</P>
<P>
   Another friend, Tom Kite, says Watson is a ``good guy with a
great sense of humor.''
</P>
<P>
   But if you try to pry the lid off, you will find that Tom Watson
is a public figure and a private man. He will put his golf on
display but nothing else. Watson will listen to Rush Limbaugh and
then tell you something that conveys a liberal-minded thought. Put
this in your pipe and smoke it: The supposed conservative from the
nation's heartland supports the legalization of recreational drugs.
</P>
<P>
   In any attempts to analyze the Mission Hills, Kan., resident,
you could end up as the subject. Watson majored in psychology at
Stanford. Watson hopes that all of his peers will think he was ``a
pretty good golfer,'' underplaying the actual thought. In 26 years
on tour, he has 34 championships. Arnold Palmer won seven majors,
but was shut out at the PGA.
</P>
<P>
   Winning at Sahalee will only enhance the legacy and diminish the
memories of nine long years between victories when he couldn't putt
it into a garbage can. It has been 15 years since Watson won his
last major at the British Open. In '83, he was still putting
aggressively, knocking the ball past the hole. At the Colonial,
Watson kept making the comebacks, and he is in the middle of
another one now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit quality shots,'' Watson said, evaluating his
ball-striking Wednesday. ``Not too bad for a guy who is almost 49
years old.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, he will try to smack one into the generation gap.
Watson is paired with David Duval and Justin Leonard, the
26-year-old wonderboys who could be his sons. Duval and Leonard
might be the ones trying to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm expecting him to play well,'' Kite said. ``I'm more
surprised when he doesn't play well. He's hitting it better than he
used to.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, Watson was denied his best chance at a PGA
championship. Trailing by seven shots after the third round, John
Mahaffey caught Watson and then beat him and Jerry Pate in a
playoff.
</P>
<P>
   This morning, Watson will be among the Douglas firs, dwarfed by
his surroundings, standing out regardless of any perceived past
failures in PGA Championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like playing in a tunnel,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And the light at the end is Watson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
