<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1463 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      08-13 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Astros
<TEXT>
<P>
   Johnson puts &QL; 
the K-bosh &QL; 
on Brewers
</P>
<P>
   Shutout comes with 13 strikeouts
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
The Milwaukee Brewers became the newest tenants of the National
League Central this season, supposedly getting away from Randy
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Well, look who showed up in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson pitched his second consecutive shutout Wednesday night,
striking out 13 batters as the Astros dumped the Brewers 3-0 before
a crowd of 40,217 at the Astrodome. The Astros maintained an
8{-game hold on the NL Central in winning their sixth straight
game.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Biggio provided all the offense the Astros needed with a
bases-empty home run in the third and a run-scoring single in the
fourth. Johnson notched the first RBI of his career in the sixth
inning with a broken-bat single up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain in the Johnson era: Whether in the American
League or National, he owns the Brewers. In his last 12 games
against Milwaukee, the 6-10 lefthander is 10-0 with a 2.53 earned
run average.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday was no different as Johnson pitched a five-hitter and
ran his scoreless-innings streak to 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he pitches like that, he's going to really like the
National League,'' said Milwaukee third baseman Jeff Cirillo, who
was ejected along with manager Phil Garner in the ninth inning for
arguing balls and strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Since being acquired by the Astros in a trade with the Seattle
Mariners on July 31, Johnson is 3-0 with a 0.72 ERA. He has allowed
only two runs in 25 innings while striking out 33.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's 13 strikeouts Wednesday were the most by an Astros
pitcher this season (he held the previous high of 12 in his debut
Aug. 2) and marked the 97th time in his career he has recorded 10
or more strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson moved into second place on the all-time list for
double-digit strikeout performances, tying Sandy Koufax. The
all-time leader at 215 is Nolan Ryan, who watched Wednesday's game
from behind home plate.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his career-long dominance of Milwaukee, Johnson said
there was nothing easy about his latest victory. He never fully got
comfortable on the mound and said he tired during the game after
running the bases and throwing 135 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson could have fooled the Brewers. Milwaukee's starting
lineup Wednesday night is batting a combined .176 (18-for-102) with
34 strikeouts lifetime against him. First baseman John Jaha has had
the least success against Johnson, going 2-for-25 with 10
strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know me so well, they give me fits,'' Johnson said of the
Brewers, who have beaten him four times in 20 career meetings.
``They are a very disciplined, well-managed team. I shut down a
very good team.''
</P>
<P>
   What impressed Astros manager Larry Dierker was that Johnson's
performance came on a night when he never quite reached a comfort
zone on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, Randy came in and said the mound was a little
steeper (than the bullpen mound), and he didn't feel he had the
ball riding the way he likes to,'' Dierker said. ``Honestly, he
didn't feel at his best. What I found to be special about him is
his control. Even when he's not at his best, he still has better
stuff than the average guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten of Johnson's strikeouts came after the fourth inning,
including a string of seven in 10 batters from the fifth inning
through the seventh. The Brewers' only real scoring chance came in
the eighth when they loaded the bases with a pair of singles and a
walk. Johnson escaped the jam by getting Mark Loretta to pop out to
center field.
</P>
<P>
   Biggio, who went 3-for-5, put the Astros ahead 1-0 in the third
with his 13th home run of the season, a solo shot to left field off
Brad Woodall (5-7). In the fourth, Biggio drove in Brad Ausmus, who
was hit by a pitch, with a single up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson added his first major-league RBI with a single off
Milwaukee reliever Eric Plunk.
</P>
<P>
   On most nights, three runs might not have been enough. But they
were a plateful for Johnson, who became the first Astros pitcher
since Mike Scott in 1988 to toss back-to-back shutouts. The shutout
was Johnson's fourth of the season and 21st of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that easy to score three runs and win,'' said
Dierker, whose club improved to 6-0 on its current 10-game
homestand. ``I have a feeling with him starting the game it's a lot
more likely.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's taking some getting used to. So what is the biggest
difference for Johnson in the NL?
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't felt real comfortable out here,'' he said. ``The
mounds and ballparks are different in the NL. I'm pretty tired and
realize now that NL pitchers have to be in great shape to do all
the extra running. Maybe I need to get on a treadmill.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 0124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
