<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 01:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1469 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-DISTANCE-NYT &LR;      08-13 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-DISTANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: IN GOLF, IT'S WHERE YOU HIT IT, NOT HOW FAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl) 
By AL BARKOW   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When legendary British golf champion Harry Vardon made an
exhibition swing through the United States in 1900 to promote what
was then the new game in town, he soon perceived an American
predilection for power.
</P>
<P>
   Best known for his exceptionally accurate approach shots, Vardon
wrote in his memoir: ``At that period, the Americans were not
sufficiently advanced to appreciate some of the finer points of the
game. They did, however, appear to thoroughly enjoy the type of
ball I drove. I hit it high for carry, which resembled a home
run.''
</P>
<P>
   The times have not changed much. Hitting the golf ball farther,
and farther, and farther, continues to be the mesmeric mantra of
American golf. Every golf club or ball advertised has promised to
produce longer shots; accuracy is thrown in at the end.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, equipment manufacturers have been living up to this
sacred oath. In fact, they have wrought a serious conflict with the
United States Golf Association, which administers the rules of golf
and the legality of the equipment used: the USGA feels that the
titanium drivers so popular of late are allowing golfers to hit the
ball too far.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's hard to argue with power. The best or quickest
way for a tournament golfer to reach the heart of the American golf
fan is to be a long-knocker. Arnold Palmer became a folk hero not
simply because he won tournaments, but also because he won them by
force with his shirttail flying, his club gyrating wildly in the
follow-through and the ball soaring. The gallery regularly forgives
John Daly his past excesses of drink, tobacco, gambling and give-up
nonperformances when he rears back and sends a drive soaring into
the stratosphere. Tiger Woods' moments of youthful petulance are
forgotten the moment he swings his driver and sends the ball
outlandish distances.
</P>
<P>
   That is why the USGA loves the story of Paul Runyan's victory in
the 1938 PGA Championship. With this week's PGA being played in
Redmond, Wash., we celebrate the 60th anniversary of one of the
most astounding performances in the event, if not in all golf
history. Sixty years ago, at the Shawnee Country Club, in
Shawnee-on-the-Delaware, Pa., the tiny Runyan, though outhit by an
average of 75 yards a hole, defeated Sam Snead. And it wasn't a
squeaker; Runyan drowned Snead, 8 and 7, in the scheduled 36-hole
final of what was then a match-play event.
</P>
<P>
   Runyan proved the point: in golf, length is not everything. And
more specifically, super long hitters have a low percentage of
victories in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1946, 212 major championships have been played, and 35 of
them have been won by golfers with reputations for being
exceptionally long hitters. Jack Nicklaus won 17 of the 35, and
here we enter a conditional stipulation: throughout his illustrious
career, Nicklaus more often than not kept his driver in his bag and
played anything from a 3-wood to a 2-iron from the tees, on even
the longest holes, to make certain he kept the ball in play.
Granted, Nicklaus was so long that he did not give up all that much
yardage to the rest of the field, but he did level it. And won.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. and British Opens, and the PGA Championship, are the
best measures of what we can call the pinpoint principle. Unlike
the Masters, where there is no rough (and which has had the most
long-knocker winners, 12 of 53), the narrow fairways and heavy
rough in the three other majors make accuracy off the tee essential
to success. Only five U.S. Opens in modern times have been won by
super sluggers, and four of them were won by Nicklaus. The other
was Palmer, and it is interesting that this was Palmer's only
victory in the most prized of the majors.
</P>
<P>
   After Woods' victory at the Masters, in 1997, seasoned golf
observers took a wait-and-see stance to those who were declaiming
the youngster unconquerable. How would he do in the Opens, and the
PGA, with that long ball of his? Would he be able to keep the ball
in the short grass? The answer was no. And it turned out that even
with shorter clubs off the tee, and from the fairway, he was unable
to throttle back his swing.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Woods' U.S. Open performances have been ordinary. In this
year's British Open, however, his third-place finish, only one
stroke short of the playoff between Mark O'Meara and Brian Watts,
indicated he was beginning to learn how to play golf. His swing was
more controlled, and so were his shots.
</P>
<P>
   Many young blasters have come along who could hit the ball out
of sight. But the ones who have the most long-term success are
those who have lightened their foot on the pedal, reined in the
macho pride of long-ball hitters and learned how to hit it where
they could see it.
</P>
<P>
   At the PGA, beginning Thursday, we may see the further maturing
of Woods into the complete champion. In the meantime, look for the
control freaks to dominate center stage, like Justin Leonard, or
O'Meara, the current Masters and British Open champion.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the USGA ought to throttle back itself, in its
concern over the effects of titanium. Let's assume that Americans
are now sufficiently advanced to appreciate the finer points of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 0153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1472 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-lopez-HNS &LR;      08-13 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-lopez-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   Star attraction &QL; 
keeps his cool
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THEY came to see Randy Johnson's heat, which is, after all, why he
is such a perfect match for Houston.
</P>
<P>
   We revel in the heat. We soak it in and drink it up _ 100-degree
temperatures, 100-mph fastballs. Give it to us. Let it pour down on
us and drench us in sweat from the sizzling temperatures and
exhilaration from the scalding fastballs.
</P>
<P>
   J.R. Richard did this to us. So did Nolan Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   They came to the Astrodome on Wednesday night, 40,217 of them,
not so much to see Johnson throw sizzling strikes but to hear him
do it. After all, who really sees the baseball blast out of
Johnson's hand and split the strike zone?
</P>
<P>
   Not the batters. Not you. Not me. And on several occasions
Wednesday night, certainly not home-plate umpire Jerry Meals, whose
strike zone more closely resembled the name of Johnson's favorite
grunge band _ Bush.
</P>
<P>
   A sight to see
</P>
<P>
   Dusty Hill, of the rock band ZZ Top, came. Hill might even be
the perfect poster boy for National League batters who face
Johnson's fastball. After all, have you ever seen the way Hill's
knees wobble when he plays the guitar?
</P>
<P>
   That's what they came to see Johnson do to these guys called
Brewers, whose knees first quivered, then wobbled, then buckled in
what would be a 3-0 Astros win that Johnson even best described
when he walked to his locker stall afterward and said, ``Wow.''
</P>
<P>
   They chanted Johnson's name. They stood and cheered. They begged
for the heat and got what looked like a Houston summer _ 13
strikeouts and fastballs in the mid-90s.
</P>
<P>
   Our patron saint for heat, Ryan, even came, sitting behind home
plate with one arm slung over the seat next to him and, like all of
us, looking so contented and happy in the midst of the heat.
</P>
<P>
   But what Ryan and a few others knew about Johnson before
Wednesday night, Johnson showed loud and clear to the raucous crowd
and his Astros teammates.
</P>
<P>
   This guy is cool.
</P>
<P>
   The box score and highlight reel no doubt will make this look
like just another dominating fastball night for Johnson. The 13
strikeouts were an Astros season high and tied Johnson with Dodgers
great Sandy Koufax for second overall in the major-league record
book for double-digit strikeout games at 97.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only a hundred and something to go,'' Johnson said, in
reverence of Ryan, who tutored a young Johnson years ago and holds
the double-digit record with 215.
</P>
<P>
   But looking at the way Johnson worked in and out, here and
there, on Wednesday, it was Johnson's polish that had to make
everyone feel that putting Johnson in an Astros uniform shouldn't
just be a rental agreement for the remainder of 1998. This should
be lease-purchase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming out, he didn't really feel that he had the ball working
like he likes to,'' Astros skipper Larry Dierker said. ``He didn't
seem to be at his best.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough, through two innings it was Brewers starter Brad
Woodall, whose ERA entering the game (4.52) would have been
excellent if it were a grade-point average, who had twice as many
strikeouts as Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Until the fifth inning, when Johnson finally seemed to loosen
the arm and struck out the side, Woodall still had more strikeouts.
Johnson walked a batter in the first and gave up a hard leadoff
single in the second and another smash in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel like I had a whole lot on the fastball,''
Johnson said. ``I feel like I lost three or four mph on my fastball
somewhere between Seattle (and here).''
</P>
<P>
   Heat not all there is
</P>
<P>
   The scoreboard radar-gun reading backed up Johnson's contention
as much as his teammates backed him up defensively through the
early going.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night in his home debut when Johnson had eight
strikeouts, he was hitting 97 and 98 mph on the gun. On this night,
he mostly hovered in the 92-to-95-mph range, which still might be
fast for most big-league fans, but this is Houston. That's like
autumn.
</P>
<P>
   But why was everyone standing and cheering wildly when Johnson
ended with a complete game? Because it was just that _ a complete
pitching performance.
</P>
<P>
   A sharp-breaking slider got Fernando Via to end the sixth. A
little corner-nibbling got Jeff Cirillo and Darrin Jackson swinging
at air in the seventh. Another slider capped off the eighth. He had
Brewers chasing everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's special,'' Dierker said. ``In all of his games, he's had
total command of both sides of the plate. When you watch him pitch
by pitch, he's making those pitches all the time. What it tells me
is this guy has a lot of charisma about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's performance told us the same thing Wednesday night.
It's not just the heat. It's the cool. And the scariest thing of
all, as Dierker bluntly put it afterward: ``There are going to be
games where he'll throw harder.''
</P>
<P>
   And we'll be there. We love the heat. The cool will do, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 0156EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 01:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1473 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-LOPEZ-HNS &LR;      08-13 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   Star attraction &QL; 
keeps his cool
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THEY came to see Randy Johnson's heat, which is, after all, why he
is such a perfect match for Houston.
</P>
<P>
   We revel in the heat. We soak it in and drink it up _ 100-degree
temperatures, 100-mph fastballs. Give it to us. Let it pour down on
us and drench us in sweat from the sizzling temperatures and
exhilaration from the scalding fastballs.
</P>
<P>
   J.R. Richard did this to us. So did Nolan Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   They came to the Astrodome on Wednesday night, 40,217 of them,
not so much to see Johnson throw sizzling strikes but to hear him
do it. After all, who really sees the baseball blast out of
Johnson's hand and split the strike zone?
</P>
<P>
   Not the batters. Not you. Not me. And on several occasions
Wednesday night, certainly not home-plate umpire Jerry Meals, whose
strike zone more closely resembled the name of Johnson's favorite
grunge band _ Bush.
</P>
<P>
   A sight to see
</P>
<P>
   Dusty Hill, of the rock band ZZ Top, came. Hill might even be
the perfect poster boy for National League batters who face
Johnson's fastball. After all, have you ever seen the way Hill's
knees wobble when he plays the guitar?
</P>
<P>
   That's what they came to see Johnson do to these guys called
Brewers, whose knees first quivered, then wobbled, then buckled in
what would be a 3-0 Astros win that Johnson even best described
when he walked to his locker stall afterward and said, ``Wow.''
</P>
<P>
   They chanted Johnson's name. They stood and cheered. They begged
for the heat and got what looked like a Houston summer _ 13
strikeouts and fastballs in the mid-90s.
</P>
<P>
   Our patron saint for heat, Ryan, even came, sitting behind home
plate with one arm slung over the seat next to him and, like all of
us, looking so contented and happy in the midst of the heat.
</P>
<P>
   But what Ryan and a few others knew about Johnson before
Wednesday night, Johnson showed loud and clear to the raucous crowd
and his Astros teammates.
</P>
<P>
   This guy is cool.
</P>
<P>
   The box score and highlight reel no doubt will make this look
like just another dominating fastball night for Johnson. The 13
strikeouts were an Astros season high and tied Johnson with Dodgers
great Sandy Koufax for second overall in the major-league record
book for double-digit strikeout games at 97.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only a hundred and something to go,'' Johnson said, in
reverence of Ryan, who tutored a young Johnson years ago and holds
the double-digit record with 215.
</P>
<P>
   But looking at the way Johnson worked in and out, here and
there, on Wednesday, it was Johnson's polish that had to make
everyone feel that putting Johnson in an Astros uniform shouldn't
just be a rental agreement for the remainder of 1998. This should
be lease-purchase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming out, he didn't really feel that he had the ball working
like he likes to,'' Astros skipper Larry Dierker said. ``He didn't
seem to be at his best.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough, through two innings it was Brewers starter Brad
Woodall, whose ERA entering the game (4.52) would have been
excellent if it were a grade-point average, who had twice as many
strikeouts as Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Until the fifth inning, when Johnson finally seemed to loosen
the arm and struck out the side, Woodall still had more strikeouts.
Johnson walked a batter in the first and gave up a hard leadoff
single in the second and another smash in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel like I had a whole lot on the fastball,''
Johnson said. ``I feel like I lost three or four mph on my fastball
somewhere between Seattle (and here).''
</P>
<P>
   Heat not all there is
</P>
<P>
   The scoreboard radar-gun reading backed up Johnson's contention
as much as his teammates backed him up defensively through the
early going.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night in his home debut when Johnson had eight
strikeouts, he was hitting 97 and 98 mph on the gun. On this night,
he mostly hovered in the 92-to-95-mph range, which still might be
fast for most big-league fans, but this is Houston. That's like
autumn.
</P>
<P>
   But why was everyone standing and cheering wildly when Johnson
ended with a complete game? Because it was just that _ a complete
pitching performance.
</P>
<P>
   A sharp-breaking slider got Fernando Via to end the sixth. A
little corner-nibbling got Jeff Cirillo and Darrin Jackson swinging
at air in the seventh. Another slider capped off the eighth. He had
Brewers chasing everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's special,'' Dierker said. ``In all of his games, he's had
total command of both sides of the plate. When you watch him pitch
by pitch, he's making those pitches all the time. What it tells me
is this guy has a lot of charisma about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's performance told us the same thing Wednesday night.
It's not just the heat. It's the cool. And the scariest thing of
all, as Dierker bluntly put it afterward: ``There are going to be
games where he'll throw harder.''
</P>
<P>
   And we'll be there. We love the heat. The cool will do, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
