<SLUG> BC-GOLF-PGA-LOVE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOVE KNOWS PAIN OF FAMILY TRAGEDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Defending PGA Champion Davis Love III knows the
pain and suffering that Stuart Appleby is feeling after the tragic
death of his wife, Renay, last month when she was hit by a London
taxicab.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Love lost his father, noted PGA teaching pro Davis Love
Jr., in a plane crash. The tragedy nearly destroyed him until he
returned to what his father always wanted him to do: play
professional golf.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Love III seemed haunted by the death. He would still
win now and then, but the one major victory that he sought always
seemed to elude him.
</P>
<P>
   That was until last year at Winged Foot Golf Club in New York,
when Love, invoking the memory of his father, blew away the field
and claimed the 79th PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   His advice to Appleby: Be prepared for the pain to linger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until he goes all the way through the whole tour and he speaks
to every one of his friends and every one of the tournament
directors and every marshal at every tournament, it's not going to
be over for him,'' Love said Wednesday. ``And that was the hardest
thing for me.''
</P>
<P>
   But Love also knows the best way of dealing with the tragedy is
to play through it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy that he's back out because he needs to start that
process and try to enjoy himself out here playing golf,'' Love
said.
</P>
<P>
   For Love, the past year has been particularly joyful because of
the win at Winged Foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as what it's meant to me, it will mean a lot to me the
rest of my life,'' he said of the PGA title. ``This year has been
great, and it still kind of gives you a little shock when you get
on the first tee and they introduce you as the 1997 PGA champion.''
</P>
<P>
   Love would love to be introduced next year as the 1998 PGA
champion, but knows that history is not on his side. The last time
there was a repeat champion of the PGA was in 1937 when Denny Shute
won back-to-back events when the tournament was match play.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've reminded me of that a couple of times in the last
couple of days,'' Love said when told how difficult it is to repeat
at the PGA. ``You're just beating it into my head, I think. ... But
it would be a thrill to have a chance on Sunday and I'd like to
break that long-standing record.''
</P>
<P>
   Love likes what he's seen of Sahalee Country Club during the
past two days of practice rounds, but doesn't believe he has the
type of game that is well-suited to the course. Unless, of course,
he can stick to the straight and narrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Straight works, and that is the main thing,'' Love said. ``You
just have to hit a lot of fairways. Obviously, we're used to that.
In most of the majors, your accuracy off the tee is a premium. But
I think this one is going to be different.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because the players are in a quandary over what clubs to
use off of the tees. Some will hit fairway woods, others 1- or
2-irons. Some might even hit 5- or 6-irons on some par-4s just to
get the ball in play and in good position.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes it very hard,'' Love said. ``You have to hit two
really good iron shots in a row to get on the greens.''
</P>
<P>
   Love, however, does have something on his side: the confidence
of a defending champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I've been there before,'' he said. ``You're still
nervous. You still want to win. You're still excited. You still
have to prepare. But you have that little bit of a more comfortable
feeling going in that I know what it takes and what it's going to
take on Sunday to win here.''
</P>
<P>
   In winning last year, Love also shed what he said was a
``negative mantel'' as one of the best players to have never won
one of golf's four major events. Now, the same thing is being said
about players such as Colin Montgomerie and Jim Furyk.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, Love said he chose to use that as a positive
inspiration for the quality of his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed the challenge of getting past that (first win at a
major) and I think a bigger challenge now is trying to get more,''
he said. ``I always took it as a compliment that people and other
players said that I should win (a major) and that when I did they
said, `It was about time.' ... Hopefully, we can build on that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
