<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-ROYALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLPEN LETS RED SOX DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Mist and rain and gloom hung over Fenway Park when
Wednesday night's game against the Royals began. By game's end,
after a Royal 8-4 thrashing of the Red Sox, the gloom was worse.
</P>
<P>
   In between the early gloom and late doom, though, there were
seven innings of clean, crisp, tight baseball. ``It's
frustrating,'' said Boston starter Bret Saberhagen, ``these games
you're supposed to win but don't win, a close game throughout
except for the ninth inning. I feel we're a better ball club than
what they have.''
</P>
<P>
   A night after Boston rallied against Kansas City closer Jeff
Montgomery for a 7-4, 10-inning win, the Sox bullpen wasted
Saberhagen's gutsy six innings of one-run ball, allowing seven runs
in the final three innings as its ERA jumped from 3.78 to 3.93. And
the ERA of Carlos Reyes, who tried to pitch the ninth, jumped from
1.45 to 3.66 as the Royals batted around and scored five runs
against him.
</P>
<P>
   Until that horrible finish, the game was a sight to enjoy.
Royals starter Jose Rosado (1 run, 2 hits in 5 innings) toyed with
the Boston batters. ``Rosado always pitches us tough,'' said Sox
manager Jimy Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Saberhagen allowed only one run on six hits, striking
out the unfortunate Dean Palmer _ who left 10 runners on base _
with men on second and third in the third and the bases loaded in
the fifth. Each time Palmer whiffed, there was only one out.
</P>
<P>
   The score was 1-1 into the seventh, and as is the custom with
1-1 games, there was spectacular defense.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City right fielder Jermaine Dye made one of the Fenway
catches of the season, charging into the wall and reaching into the
seats at Pesky's Pole in the fifth to take a home run away from
Jason Varitek. It's a rarity at Fenway because right fielders
seldom can get to Pesky's Pole in time to even attempt a catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised he was even playing me that far over (toward
the pole),'' said the switch-hitting Varitek, who was batting
righthanded against lefty Rosado. ``I think that's the first ball
I've even hit to that side of second base all year. I thought when
I hit it, there wasn't a chance he'd catch it.''
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox shortstop Nomar Garciaparra made a spectacular play in
the fifth after Saberhagen struck out Palmer for the second out.
Terry Pendleton hit a dart between Garciaparra and the bag, but the
shortstop dived, snagged the ball, righted himself, and fired to
first to nail Pendleton on a very close play, saving two runs.
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen made his usual departure after throwing 100 pitches.
``I felt good, but that's what they want to do, look out for the
high pitch count,'' he said. ``They don't want to wear me out.''
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the seventh, Greg Swindell ambled to the mound
in relief. Plate umpire Larry Young was calling some balls strikes
and some strikes balls all night for both teams, and Swindell was
not a beneficiary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all threw some pitches that should have been strikes,''
said Saberhagen. ``Especially when I came up here to watch the
seventh (on TV) and Greg threw a 3-2 pitch that I thought was a
strike and they called it ball four and that guy ended up
scoring.''
</P>
<P>
   That 3-2 pitch came when Johnny Damon was at the plate with one
out and none on. After Damon walked, Hal Morris _ who was 5 for 6 _
drilled a double to left, moving Damon to third. Swindell then
walked Jose Offerman intentionally, loading the bases, before
Williams summoned Jim Corsi to face Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   Corsi was ahead in the count, 1-2, and Palmer seemed destined to
strand his sixth, seventh, and eighth runners in three at-bats. But
on that 1-2 count with the bases loaded in a 1-1 game, Corsi threw
a breaking ball that skipped in the dirt and eluded Varitek,
rolling about 25 feet behind the catcher and allowing Damon to
score the go-ahead run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a slider in the dirt,'' said Varitek. ``I was in front
of it, but it got under me.''
</P>
<P>
   Each team added a run in the eighth, and it was 3-2 when Reyes
hitched his ERA to a balloon and watched it soar. Kansas City sent
10 batters to the plate _ including Palmer, who struck out with two
on _ and added five runs on six hits. Of course, Morris had one of
them _ an RBI double after Luis Rivera's RBI single and Damon's
two-run single.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like tonight was like any other night out there, but
when you get a couple of hits, you seem to find more and more holes
out there,'' said Morris, who was 6 for 9 in the two-game series.
``I was just up there swinging and hoping something would fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, it was not the Boston ERA that fell on this night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
