<SLUG> BC-COPDEATH-SUSPECT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT HELD IN OFFICER'S DEATH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LISA VAN PROYEN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Information from the public led to the arrest of a
20-year-old man suspected of killing police officer Filbert Henry
Cuesta Jr., officials announced Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Police Chief Bernard C. Parks identified the suspect as Catarino
Gonzalez Jr. of Los Angeles, who turned himself in Tuesday ``after
becoming aware that he had been identified and was wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears the motive was he had an intent to kill a police
officer,'' Parks said. ``I would say it was not accidental. That's
why we call it murder.''
</P>
<P>
   Parks said that ``it was very important the public came forth
with information leading to the suspect. ... When his family became
aware of our interest in him as a suspect, they chose to bring him
to the station.''
</P>
<P>
   When he made the announcement, Park said that Gonzalez had been
arrested a number of times in the past. Lt. Anthony Alba said those
arrests were in connection with narcotics, but had no more details.
</P>
<P>
   Police said a witness told them that Gonzalez was with gang
members crashing a wedding party in the Crenshaw district of Los
Angeles early Sunday morning when he fired at Cuesta who was
outside in a police car.
</P>
<P>
   Cuesta, 26, was shot at 12:35 a.m. while he waited in the car
for backup officers to deal with the boisterous gathering.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are continuing our investigation,'' Parks said. ``Every
investigative lead will be covered ... in hopes of having the most
severe penalty possible at the conclusion of the trial.''
</P>
<P>
   The chief said a vigil for Cuesta is scheduled for 8 p.m. today
at the Los Angeles Police Department's Southwest Division where
Cuesta worked.
</P>
<P>
   Funeral services for are scheduled for 10 a.m. Friday at Calvary
Chapel in Diamond Bar, with burial to follow at Rose Hills Memorial
Park and Mortuary in Whittier.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the suspect turned himself in Tuesday and was
booked on suspicion of murder Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen police officers stood by with a photograph of
Cuesta as Parks announced the arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Police officers at the LAPD's Southwest Division expressed
relief when they learned that a suspect was in custody.
</P>
<P>
   Cuesta's killing was a blow to many Los Angeles residents, some
of whom brought flowers to police stations and expressed their
sorrow in other ways.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Jim McDonnell at the Southwest Division said that even
motorists being ticketed by LAPD officers were anxious to offer
their condolences.
</P>
<P>
   There were more than 20 detectives from the LAPD's
Robbery-Homicide and Southwest divisions hunting for the killer.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles County supervisors offered a $15,000 reward Tuesday
for information leading to the arrest and conviction of the killer.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who was in Los Angeles on Tuesday, telephoned
Cuesta's wife, Sylvia, and spoke to her about violence in America
and about how dangerous it is to be a police officer.
</P>
<P>
   Cuesta had served in the LAPD for four years and was assigned to
the Southwest Division, where he worked in an anti-gang detail.
</P>
<P>
   When he was shot, he had been back at work for only three days
after taking a month off for the birth of his second daughter,
Sierra Rose.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
