<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUE JAYS' RALLY SPOILS A-ROD MILESTONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Alex Rodriguez made it onto a short list in the record
books Wednesday at SkyDome. The Mariners just wished they could
find seventh heaven.
</P>
<P>
   For the second time in less than 24 hours, the Toronto Blue Jays
erupted with a big seventh inning to erase a Mariner lead. Tuesday
night, the rally was six runs; Wednesday it was seven. But the
result was the same. Wednesday's 11-5 loss left the Mariners
limping back across the border with an 0-2 record in the brief
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we said we didn't want to see another six-spot,''
manager Lou Piniella said Wednesday, referring to Tuesday night's
series opener.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariner bullpen, which has been pitching magnificently
recently, took it on the chin again, squandering the two-run lead
Rodriguez provided in the top of the inning with his 36th homer of
the season and the 100th of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we had a great opportunity to win the game after
hitting that home run,'' the 23-year-old Rodriguez said, ``but that
wasn't the case. (The home run) is secondary to winning.''
</P>
<P>
   In matching his career high for homers in a season, he became
the fourth-youngest player in big-league history to hit 100 homers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of the accomplishment, no doubt about it,''
Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Only Mel Ott, Tony Conigliaro and Eddie Mathews hit their 100th
homers at a younger age. Ott and Mathews are in the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``A-Rod has had a marvelous year, and he's a marvelous player,''
Piniella said. ``He can do just about anything he wants to do on a
baseball field. The young man can play, period.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, in losing their second straight game after beginning
the nine-game road trip with a four-game sweep against the Detroit
Tigers, the Mariners further damaged their vanishing hopes of
climbing back into the American League West pennant race.
</P>
<P>
   Blame the bullpen for this loss. Specifically Bobby Ayala and
Greg McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   Starter Jamie Moyer, who retired the first nine batters he faced
and led 3-0 going into the fifth inning, wobbled a little in the
fifth when Toronto scored two runs. Moyer exited in the seventh
after Mark Dalesandro doubled and scored on Craig Grebeck's one-out
single.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Ayala.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander faced two batters and retired neither,
prompting Piniella to summon McCarthy, a left-hander, to face
left-handed hitter Shawn Green.
</P>
<P>
   A good pitch on a 2-and-2 count put Toronto in front for good as
Green fought off a pitch on his hands and blooped a two-run double
over third baseman Russ Davis' head.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could jump higher or was about two inches taller, I would
have had it,'' said Davis, who stationed himself closer to home
plate to cut down the go-ahead run at the plate. ``I had to play in
in that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy, who has been brilliant since replacing Tony Fossas in
the bullpen, holding left-handers to one hit in 19 at-bats, said he
thought both of the preceding pitches to Green on two-strike counts
were strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably should have thrown him a fastball (on 2-and-2)
instead of a slider,'' said McCarthy, who then walked Jose Canseco
and served up a grand slam to Carlos Delgado.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bullpen had stabilized before we came in here,'' Piniella
said, ``but didn't do the job the past two days. Let's hope
starting (Friday night in Chicago) it starts doing the job again.''
</P>
<P>
   After Rodriguez's clutch home run off winning Blue Jay reliever
Nerio Rodriguez, with Rob Ducey aboard on a leadoff walk, Piniella
hoped to get through the seventh and then turn the game over to
closer Mike Timlin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going to pitch him two innings because he hadn't
pitched in three days,'' Piniella said. ``But we didn't get to
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Joey Cora opened the game with a walk and eventually scored on
Edgar Martinez's two-out single. The M's made it a 3-0 game in the
third off Toronto starter Kelvim Escobar when both Cora and
Rodriguez, who had singled, scored on a wild throw to third base by
catcher Darrin Fletcher on a double steal.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez and Davis each had two hits for the M's, but Ken
Griffey Jr. and David Segui continued to struggle. Both went
hitless.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Griffey) had more snap on the bat and he'll come out of it,''
Piniella said of his center fielder, who is 8-for-41 in August.
``No one is immune to going into a hitting funk. We need Junior to
start swinging the bat the way he's capable of, and he will.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Griffey: ``Wow, I'm human! Maybe that's it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
