<HEADER>
A1506 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-HUSKIES-SPI &LR;      08-13 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HUSKIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOTBALL FRESHMAN GETS HIS ACT TOGETHER TO HIT WASHINGTON STAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The biggest yelp from anyone around the Washington
football program this summer had nothing to do with the Huskies
being ranked
</P>
<P>
   No. 17, or Jim Lambright, the head coach, boating another king
salmon off the Alaskan coast.
</P>
<P>
   It came from Scott Pelluer, the defensive assistant coach, when
he got the news that one of his prime recruits had a qualifying
score on the American College Test and would indeed be eligible
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Hakim Akbar, a 6-foot-1, 195-pound free safety, sat there
Wednesday at the Huskies' annual freshman luncheon, and he said it
more than once: ``I'm just happy to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Happy? He ought to hear the Huskies' side of it.
</P>
<P>
   Word is already out that when Akbar arrived 10 days ago,
quarterback Brock Huard took fast notice of how Akbar can shadow a
wide receiver. ``A three-year (college) player,'' said another
veteran Husky defender, seeing the NFL in Akbar's future.
</P>
<P>
   Those things happen when you arrive with a healthy 325-pound
bench press, a 38-inch vertical jump and football smarts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks really good,'' Lambright said after the Huskies'
first freshman drills Wednesday morning. ``Fundamentally, he does a
lot of things right. His athletic ability allows you to think good
things about him being able to play right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Happy to be here. The phrase has come to mean little, but in
Akbar's case, it carries some weight.
</P>
<P>
   Reared in Atlanta, he and his brother, Mikal, now 19, were sent
west by their mom to live with their dad in Riverside, Calif., six
years ago. That worked until a major misstep by the father.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad's a good person,'' Akbar said. ``He helped me be where
I am today. He was strict. He just did the wrong thing. He got
caught up ... he did it for us.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Akbar's father was convicted of bank robbery in
Riverside. His younger son says he is serving time until 2002 in
San Luis Obispo, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers bounced around, from the home of an uncle to family
friends, failure waiting to happen. They wouldn't let it.
</P>
<P>
   Akbar spent his senior year living with only his brother, who is
now a wide receiver at San Bernardino Valley College. It's not the
prescribed way to overcome an academic hurdle, but he accomplished
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I didn't want to go to school, I didn't have to,'' Akbar
said, referring to the absence of parents. ``I had to really push
myself. I had to think about how bad I wanted to get up here. If I
wanted to be a little dud or something, I could have done it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ended up making the honor roll.''
</P>
<P>
   The test score came harder. Foiled three times on the Scholastic
Assessment Test, he survived the ACT. When he got his score late in
June, the first thing he did was fall to his knees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thanked God,'' Akbar said. ``I couldn't have done it without
him. I assumed I was done, and I'd have to go to a JC.''
</P>
<P>
   Akbar's family is close. He wrote to his father the other day,
lamenting that for now, he has no telephone to take a collect call.
But he and Mikal talk almost daily, dreaming of a time when they
might meet on the football field.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother, he stays on me pretty hard,'' Akbar said. ``If I'm
doing something wrong, he lets me know I'm doing it. I love him to
death. It's kind of hard being away from him. He's a real good
influence.''
</P>
<P>
   Akbar visited Arkansas, Arizona State, Cal and Washington.
Tennessee went hard after him, but a change in assistant coaches
swayed him against the Vols. He got eight of 10 votes on the Long
Beach Press-Telegram's Best in the West voting, but was considered
iffy at best when the Huskies signed him because of the
freshman-qualifying questions.
</P>
<P>
   SuperPrep Magazine was impressed, writing, ``Anyone who saw tape
of Akbar projects him as an all-conference player within two
years.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll likely get his chance. Akbar comes into a position
considered one of the Huskies' most vulnerable, especially against
the considerable legacy of free safeties like Lawyer Milloy and
Tony Parrish.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Brendan Jones is the likely starter, pursued by redshirt
freshman Omare Lowe and Walla Walla JC product Renard Edwards, who
is not at the UW yet because he is trying to finish his two-year
degree.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the opening, Akbar is unassuming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going to work hard,'' he said. ``There's a lot of
good guys there. I'm just going to try to earn my way, work hard
and see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   SPEED FREAKS: In a morning testing session of the new players,
running back Jelani Harrison and outside linebacker Jafar Williams
topped all classmates by running 40 yards in 4.55 seconds in
football shoes. That puts in perspective the 4.29 of wide receiver
Ja'Warren Hooker last year in the same circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Lambright said he thought some players' times were slowed by
nervousness, but nevertheless called it ``the best running group of
freshmen we've ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   IFS, ANDS, MUTTS: Two who weren't on hand were LB Anthony Kelley
and DE Roger Faagata. Kelley, one of the marquee recruits of the
class, is awaiting results of his attempt to get a waiver from the
NCAA Clearinghouse on a core-class issue, and Faagata, one of three
junior-college recruits, is completing work on his JC degree in
Long Beach ... Wideout Will Hooks of Anchorage is apparently
healthy after sustaining a torn Achilles tendon since last season.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most pleased to be here is QB Jerramy Stevens of
River Ridge, freed by a Thurston County judge's ruling to attend
camp after a summer during which Stevens was on electronic home
monitoring for an assault charge, then jailed for three weeks for a
subsequent failed drug test. ``I'm just happy to be at the UW
playing football,'' Stevens said. Lambright, saying Stevens had a
3.5 grade-point average and 1,000 SAT score, observed, ``He made a
mistake. It'll go through the process of trial and we'll let it
take its course. We don't give up on a player because he makes one
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Freshmen continue workouts Thursday, with the rest of the squad
reporting Friday. The initial full workout is Saturday afternoon,
preceded by annual picture-day festivities at Husky Stadium from
1-3 p.m. Admission, soft drinks and hot dogs are free.
</P>
<P>
   DT T.J. Jackson, projected as a backup, has left the program, as
has FS Curtis Williams.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
