<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOON SETTLES FOR LESS, ENDING 25-DAY HOLDOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHENEY _ In the end, Warren Moon decided it wasn't worth trying
to win at any cost.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks starting quarterback ended his 25-day holdout that
was all about money Wednesday by agreeing to a two-year, $4.97
million package that includes a $2.25 million signing bonus and
base salaries of $220,000 this season and $2.5 million next year.
Moon could earn another $1.2 million this season in team-oriented
incentives.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't as much money as Moon was seeking, or feels he
deserved. It could end up being less money than he could have
gotten by accepting the club's one-year, $2 million deal that had
been on the table for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``A holdout is not a positive thing at all,'' Moon said. ``At
some point, you have to make a decision: Is money more important
than being with the players and doing the things you love most?
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to basically come to the realization that I'd much
rather be out here playing football and with my teammates than
sitting out there a little longer for a few extra dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   What finally got a deal done was the Seahawks agreeing to the
signing bonus; Moon and his agent, Leigh Steinberg, accepting the
low base salary that frees up $500,000 under the team's snug salary
cap; and Moon realizing he needed to report to training camp now to
have enough time to prepare himself to be the starter in the Sept.
6 regular-season opener.
</P>
<P>
   Moon is not expected to sign his contract until later this week
because it is the first in NFL history to include guarantees that a
player will repay money to the club in the second year if he
retires or is cut and must be approved by the league. If Moon
retires, he will repay as much as 75 percent of the $1.125 million
that is the prorated signing bonus for the second year. If he is
cut, Moon will repay 25 percent of that amount.
</P>
<P>
   So he could end up with as little as $1.626 million, and Moon
owes the team $125,000 in fines from his holdout and lost another
$68,000 in game checks for missing the first two preseason outings.
</P>
<P>
   But none of this seemed to matter Wednesday. Not to Moon, who
was relieved to have the first holdout in his 21-year professional
career behind him. Not to the large crowd of fans, who trumpeted
Moon's late arrival to the afternoon practice with a chorus of
shrieks and a round of applause. Not to Moon's teammates, who
greeted his return with hugs, handshakes and a little good-natured
ribbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's excited,'' running back Ricky Watters said.
``Everybody knows what he does and what he brings to a team.
There's no way we're going to sit here and try to downplay that
situation. He's a Hall of Fame quarterback. I'm just happy I'm
going to get a chance to play with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Moon will not play in Saturday night's game against the San
Francisco 49ers in Vancouver, B.C., coach Dennis Erickson said. Jon
Kitna will start and play most of the first half before giving way
to John Friesz. Moon will take over the No. 1 offense Monday after
the team returns to its training complex in Kirkland and start next
week's game at Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The official word on whether the 41-year-old Moon starts the
regular-season opener depends on how well he progresses in practice
and the last two preseason games. The expectations are that it's a
given.
</P>
<P>
   Moon remained after practice Wednesday and threw passes for 15
minutes. Each was on target. Each had that Moon touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to have Warren in camp. We hoped it would come down
to this. Obviously we hoped it would be sooner than this,''
Erickson said. ``But we think there's plenty of time to get
ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Moon agrees, especially since he participated in each of the
team's four minicamps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'll be ready for the season,'' he said. ``It's just a
matter of getting out here and doing a little extra work every
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Moon admitted that as late as Tuesday night he wasn't sure if he
would be flying to training camp or his offseason home in Houston
Wednesday. But after he and Steinberg finalized the deal in Seattle
with club president Bob Whitsitt at 12:30 p.m., Moon hopped a plane
to Spokane, was driven to training camp and made his late-practice
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   It was a long day that ended right where Moon wanted it to _
standing in the middle of the post-practice huddle addressing his
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I basically talked to them about the reasons why I wanted to
come back,'' he said. ``I had to draw a line on what was most
important. ... I just wanted to let them know why I held out and
hopefully they'll understand and accept me back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
