r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU     08-13 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS LOSE AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Dodgers can talk all they want before the
game. They're still stuttering on the field.
</P>
<P>
   An impassioned half-hour meeting Wednesday was designed to turn
the season around, but in the end they lost 3-2 to the lowly
Florida Marlins in front of 36,452 at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Leadoff hitter Eric Young, a keynote speaker at the meeting,
also stepped up during the game with four hits and two two-out RBI
hits. But No.2 hitter Mark Grudzielanek really spoke for the team,
going 0 for 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good teams battle through these things,'' Grudzielanek said.
``We'll see if we're a good team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers aren't right now, going 2-6 during a stretch of
games against sub-.500 teams that is leading up to a weekend series
against the mighty Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta?'' manager Glenn Hoffman said. ``We're fighting just
to get to tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Marlins first baseman Derrick Lee hit a game-winning home run
with one out in the eighth off Dodgers reliever Antonio Osuna, who
had just entered the game in place of starter Carlos Perez.
</P>
<P>
   For Lee, it was his 14th homer and it gave the Marlins their
first three-game winning streak of the season. For Osuna, it was
his first loss in eight decisions. For the Dodgers, it was their
third consecutive loss.
</P>
<P>
   But with the beauty, or the perversity, of the wild card, they
remain just 5{ games back with 42 to play. The top of the wild-card
picture changed hands Wednesday when the New York Mets lost in 14
innings to St. Louis and the Chicago Cubs beat San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are close, but they are hardly playing like
champions. They had the tying run on base in the eighth and ninth
but couldn't get it done.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' sixth and Marlins' seventh innings were good
examples of the lack of intensity on the home team.
</P>
<P>
   With the game tied 1-1 in the bottom of the sixth, Raul Mondesi
appeared to get something started when he legged out an infield
single to short. But with slumping Gary Sheffield at the plate,
Mondesi was picked off first.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield, who entered the game just 2 for 11 on the homestand,
flied out. Eric Karros blooped a single off the glove of Marlins
second baseman Luis Castillo in shallow right but was thrown out
trying to stretch the play into double.
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins' seventh was worse.
</P>
<P>
   Castillo grounded wide of first base and beat Karros' throw to
Perez at the bag. One out later, John Cangelosi grounded a playable
ball to third, but it bounced off Adrian Beltre's glove and rolled
away from Dodgers fielders. By the time it stopped, Castillo scored
all the way from first and Florida led 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers had taken a 1-0 lead in the fifth against
left-hander Kirt Ojala, the second of three Marlins rookie starters
they will face in this series.
</P>
<P>
   Ojala walked Charles Johnson with one out but appeared to get
out of trouble when he struck out Perez for the second out. Young
had other ideas. He doubled to the gap in right-center and Johnson
scored from first base.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers tied it in the seventh and again it was Young
playing the catalyst. Rob Stanifer (1-3), who turned out to be the
winning pitcher, took over for Ojala to open the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Bonilla, who was booed for the second consecutive game,
drew cheers when he led off with a ground single to right. Roger
Cedeno pinch ran and moved to second on a sacrifice by Beltre.
Johnson struck out, but pinch-hitter Jim Eisenreich kept the inning
alive with a walk.
</P>
<P>
   Young, who came in just 3 for 14 on the homestand, slapped his
third hit of the game over second base and Cedeno scored.
</P>
<P>
   After batting practice, the entire team, minus coaches and
manager Hoffman, retreated to a players' lounge to discuss how to
turn around their season.
</P>
<P>
   It was no longer a matter of catching the San Diego Padres, who
have run away with the National League West.
</P>
<P>
   The problem has been intensity and the fans are noticing. In
Tuesday's 8-6 loss to the Marlins, they loudly booed every Dodgers
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to start playing like this is our last game,'' Mondesi
said after the meeting. ``Believe me, we are trying hard, but it
isn't enough. There is time, but have get this thing going. We have
to feel like every game is big. I don't want to go back to the
Dominican and watch other teams in those playoffs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
