r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUAKE-BAYAREA-SFCHRON     08-13 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAKE-BAYAREA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
S.F. BAY AREA SHAKEN UP BY 5.4 TEMBLOR 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAROLYNE ZINKO,  
 STACY FINZ  
 and DAVID PERLMAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    SAN FRANCISCO _ A moderate 5.4 earthquake and two minor
temblors rolled through the Bay Area and Central California early
Wednesday, sending bottles crashing to floors, setting off alarms,
opening up a handful of cracks on Highway 101 and sending seniors
at an early-morning bingo game in Gilroy running for cover.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But the main quake, which jolted residents from Rohnert Park to
Big Sur and rocked San Francisco highrises, left San Juan
Bautista's oldest living male resident unmoved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a little shake,'' said 93-year-old Spot Wood, who
lives a short distance from the epicenter of the quake. ``You get
more shake in a rocking chair.''
</P>
<P>
   The 5.4-magnitude earthquake was centered seven miles
south-southeast of San Juan Bautista on the edge of the San Andreas
Fault system. No serious damage or injuries were reported, and most
residents in San Benito County took the 7:10 a.m. quake in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're kind of used to it, considering the San Andreas Fault is
a few blocks away,'' said Robert Barnett, assistant manager of the
Lucky supermarket in Hollister, which suffered $700 in damage from
broken bottles of cooking oil and liquor. ``This is the second or
third good one this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The only reported quake-related injury occurred near Santa Cruz
when an 18-year-old man climbing out of a bunk bed in the loft of
his home on Lionsfield Drive slipped off a ladder when the ground
shook and he struck his head on a wall.
</P>
<P>
   Paramedics took the man to Dominican Hospital in Santa Cruz,
where he was treated for minor injuries and released, a nursing
supervisor said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; A minor quake, registering 3.1, preceded the main temblor at
7:02 a.m. More than 40 small aftershocks followed within four
hours, the largest being a 3.0 that hit at 8:56 a.m., according to
seismologists at the U.S. Geological Survey in Menlo Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were not unexpected for the region,'' said seismologist
Frederick W. Lester, who monitors earthquakes day and night
throughout Northern California with the geological survey's
computer-linked network of seismographs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very seismically active area,'' said Susan Garcia, a
spokeswoman for the agency, saying this was the strongest quake
since 1990, when there was a 5.4 temblor in the same area. There
was a 5.7 quake in the area in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason to believe this is the precursor for
something bigger,'' she said. ``It's just a reminder from Mother
Nature that these happen, and we need to be prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Humberto Arredondo, manager of the Windmill Market in downtown
San Juan Bautista, said his store sustained about $5,000 in damage
when bottles of liquor and hot sauce tumbled from shelves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was here counting money,'' Arredondo said. ``We heard a big
noise and felt a hard shaking _ a very hard shaking. The lights
went off, and we had customers running out the door screaming and
yelling. All the aisles were full of broken glass and other
merchandise, especially wine and liquor.''
</P>
<P>
   Clerks working at the Garlic Festival Store in downtown Gilroy
could not seem to rid the place of the pungent smell of gourmet
oils and vinegars Wednesday. About $2,000 worth of the stuff
clattered to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just mopped over and over and over,'' said Kim Ashford, a
salesclerk.
</P>
<P>
   The Wal-Mart Store in Gilroy closed for an hour so employees
could clean up broken picture frames and gallons of paint that
splashed on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The quake also disrupted a weekly bingo game there. Thirty to 40
seniors had gathered at the McDonald's inside the Wal-Mart for
their regular game. But as the ground started to rumble, they ran
for cover with doughnuts and coffee in hand. ``They were a little
scared, but not too disappointed,'' said Robin Pilger, a department
manager.
</P>
<P>
   California Department of Transportation crews were dispatched to
Highway 101, just north of Highway 129, to repair three spidery
cracks that had opened up in the southbound lanes. The cracks did
not disrupt traffic, but ``if left untreated, the traffic would
start beating the raw edges and make it worse,'' said Don Webster,
an area superintendent for Caltrans.
</P>
<P>
   The 201-year-old San Juan Bautista mission, a popular tourist
spot, sustained minor damage when a patch of plaster fell from an
interior wall, said Rosie Murray, an office manager. But otherwise
the historic site was undamaged.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Kemp, manager of the Mission Farm R.V. Park in San Juan
Bautista, a community of 1,650 people about 90 miles south of San
Francisco, said other than having to chase two loose goats _ freed
when the quake knocked down the gate to their pen _ he had no
damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say sometimes that the best place to be is on top of the
fault line _ the impact spreads out,'' mused resident Jim Morrison,
while chatting with another resident at the park.
</P>
<P>
   After analyzing the three quakes and the smaller aftershocks
that followed, seismologists at the geological survey said there is
a small probability that a ``strong and possibly damaging
aftershock'' with a magnitude of 5.0 or larger could hit the region
within the next seven days.
</P>
<P>
   They stressed, however, that the probability of such an event is
only 20 percent and that their calculation is ``not an exact
prediction, but only a rough guide to expected aftershock
activity.'' Other very small aftershocks that might be felt locally
are expected in the same seven-day period, the quake experts said.
</P>
<P>
   The foreshock that preceded Wednesday's main event by barely a
minute and half was typical of many California earthquakes.
Foreshocks occur in about 10 to 20 percent of all temblors that hit
the state, according to geophysicist David P. Hill at the
geological survey.
</P>
<P>
   The small temblors can vary from a single event to a series of
frequent ones, and any of them can precede a main quake by minutes
to hours or even days, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Earth scientists who study the phenomena have long hoped that
understanding the relationship of foreshocks to larger quakes might
some day lead to early warnings of dangerous events to come, Hill
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are certainly symptomatic that something is happening
inside a fault, but there's still a lot we need to learn about
them,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
