r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HACKER-THEFT-SFCHRON &LR;      08-13 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HACKER-THEFT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HACKER STOLE THOUSANDS OF PASSWORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   By HENRY K. LEE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When a University of California at Berkeley
graduate student logged onto his computer, he made a startling
discovery: someone had cracked his password and was using his
account to run a program to get even more passwords.
</P>
<P>
   Using a program called ``John the Ripper'' that can be
downloaded from the Internet, the high-tech intruder had broken
into computer accounts not only at UC Berkeley but at universities
and companies around the world. The hacker had decoded nearly
48,000 passwords from a list of 186,000 encrypted ones _ in what
computer experts say is one of the largest known collections of
filched access codes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just amazed by the sheer number of passwords he had,''
said Michael Kleber, the system administrator who spent several
weeks investigating the breach at Evans Hall, UC Berkeley's math
building.
</P>
<P>
   The June break-in, which is being investigated by the FBI,
underscores how easy it is for cyber prowlers with just basic
technical skills _ and plenty of time on their hands _ to penetrate
and manipulate computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   While the hacker apparently didn't seek out classified
information or break into government accounts, he or she was
decidedly hungry for more passwords, trotting the globe
electronically in a quest for greater access.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology he was using is not sophisticated, but what's
interesting here is the scope,'' said Doug Tygar, a computer expert
at Carnegie Mellon University who will join the UC Berkeley faculty
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm impressed by his persistence to keep something running for
that long,'' Tygar said. ``The stamina to collect this number of
passwords is pretty awe-inspiring.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities believe the hacker is operating from somewhere in
Europe because the computer systems that were first compromised
belonged to European universities.
</P>
<P>
   From there, the hacker broke into accounts at a noted Silicon
Valley company, an Internet service provider in Indiana, UC
Berkeley, UCLA, the California Institute of Technology, the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology and Harvard University.
Another 80 percent of the cracked passwords found at UC Berkeley
belong to accounts yet unidentified.
</P>
<P>
   Kleber said the intruder gained access to the Internet through
Telenordia, an Internet service provider in Sweden. The cyber
prowler left a computer trail through England, Denmark and South
Korea.
</P>
<P>
   The hacker wasn't detected until June 29 at UC Berkeley, where
Kleber was notified by the graduate student that his account had
been broken into.
</P>
<P>
   Kleber notified the FBI, and the agency's computer crime squad
in San Francisco is investigating, said spokesman George Grotz.
</P>
<P>
   Carnegie Mellon University's Computer Emergency Response Team,
or CERT, which monitors computer security violations nationwide,
publicized the breach on its Web site last month.
</P>
<P>
   The intruder had compiled a list of 186,126 accounts and
encrypted passwords _ most of which were non-UC Berkeley accounts _
and, at the time of Kleb-er's discovery, had decoded 47,642 of
those passwords, according to CERT.
</P>
<P>
   Kleber found that in some cases the intruder had installed
``trojans'' or ``back door'' entrances, allowing immediate re-entry
into the compromised systems.
</P>
<P>
   These were used with ``John the Ripper,'' the password-cracking
program, and ``packet sniffers,'' programs that intercept passwords
typed in by account users.
</P>
<P>
   Password-cracking programs are used legitimately by system
administrators to make sure user passwords can't be easily cracked.
Packet sniffers are key tools in diagnosing problems with slow
networks. But used nefariously by hackers, the programs actually
undermine the systems they were designed to protect.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are plenty of ways to take care of the vulnerabilities
that exist today,'' said John Vranesevich, founder of AntiOnline, a
computer security group. ``It's not that the hackers are using
methods that aren't known, but system administrators for the most
part haven't been putting a big enough emphasis on security.''
</P>
<P>
   Computer experts acknowledge that identifying the hacker will be
a difficult, if not impossible, task.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without law enforcement help, it's pretty much slim-to-none,''
said UC Berkeley graduate student David Wagner, a founding member
of Internet Security, Applications, Authentication and
Cryptography, or ISAAC, a computer security research group on
campus. ``It's a matter of patience and luck and being able to
trace it all back.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, ISAAC revealed a major security flaw in Netscape's Web
browser that could have allowed scofflaws to intercept bank account
and credit-card information on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Two other high-profile incidents have also renewed concerns
about computer security. In March, hackers attacked computers
nationwide running Microsoft network software at NASA, the Navy and
colleges including UC Berkeley. Last month, two Cloverdale
teenagers pleaded guilty to hacking into U.S. government
computers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
