<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYRIGHTS-SKIRMISHES-SFCHRON(W/GAYGOP) </SLUG>
  
 SKIRMISHES OVER GAY RIGHTS
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gays rights advocates scored one of their biggest political
victories ever last month when the House rejected an attempt to
overturn President Clinton's executive order banning discrimination
against gays in federal agencies.
</P>
<P>
   But the amendment was just one in a series of high-profile
battles over gay rights: attempts by conservatives, both in and out
of Congress, to raise the issue before the November elections.
</P>
<P>
   -- Senate Republicans have held up the nomination of openly gay
San Francisco businessman James Hormel to be ambassador to
Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
   -- Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., publicly compared
gays to kleptomaniacs and alcoholics _ and other GOP leaders,
including House Majority Leader Dick Armey, supported Lott,
referring to Old Testament condemnations of homosexuality as a sin.
</P>
<P>
   -- The House passed an amendment last month written by North
Coast Rep. Frank Riggs, R-Calif., punishing San Francisco for its
policy requiring city contractors to provide domestic partner
benefits. The bill would deny money currently provided by the
Department of Housing and Urban Development unless the city drops
the policy.
</P>
<P>
   -- A conservative group placed full-page ads in newspapers last
month urging gays to become ``reformed'' through faith and prayer. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
