 NEWS AND FEATURE SUMMARY No 2471- August 13, 1998   We are offering
the following articles for sale. Please contact us for availability
your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. SUDAN CRISIS Special two-part report on the Sudan famine. By
Hilary Mackenzie. From The New York Times on the Web. Photos
available.
</P>
<P>
   A. Enmeshed in Conflict and Drought, Southern Sudan Starves Ten
years after a famine claimed 250,000 lives, the Sudan faces a new
catastrophe. In a country divided by 15 years of civil war and
devastated by two years of drought, aid officials say 2.6 million
people face starvation. B. At Epicenter of Famine in Sudan, A
Wrenching Struggle to Provide Aid At World Vision's Thiet feeding
centre, it is nurse Karen Easterday's task to determine who will
receive food and who will be turned away. Easterday, who has worked
as a volunteer at relief centres for several years, weaves her way
through the crowd to pick out the worst cases ... 2. ALOE : THE
ALL-STAR OF MEDICINAL PLANTS Over the centuries, some plants have
achieved well-earned reputations for treating human maladies. Few
plants may be used both internally and externally but the aloe -
the multi-talented member of the lily family that is native to
Africa and the Mediterranean area - has a proven track record. By
Charles Dickson. 750 words. 3. STUDY FINDS NO BENEFIT WITH
HIGH-DOSE BREAST CANCER THERAPY Many medical centres and doctors
are treating women with high-risk breast cancer with a
controversial regimen of extremely high-dose chemotherapy. Some
researchers say this approach has not been adequately tested and
may be doing more harm than good. Dutch researchers report the
results of a trial that compared conventional chemotherapy with the
new high-dose regimen. The high-dose treatment, they conclude, is
no better than conventional chemotherapy and should not be
routinely used. By Michael McCarthy. The Lancet News Service. 1,000
words. 4. WHY INDIA IS NOW A NUCLEAR POWER While the end of the
Cold War transformed the political landscape of Europe, it did
little to ameliorate India's security concerns. The rise of China
and continued strains with Pakistan made the 1980s and 1990s a
greatly troubling period for India. If nuclear deterrence works in
the West, why won't it work in India? By Jaswant Singh. Foreign
Affairs magazine. 2,000 words. (The author is senior adviser on
defence and foreign affairs to Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari
Vajpayee and a member of Parliament for the Bharatiya Janata
Party.) 5. GIFTED CHILDREN : LITTLE GENIUSES, BIG PROBLEMS They
learn Chinese or Japanese at age 4, display passionate interest in
politics or philosophy, and do complex maths. Yet gifted children
also often suffer from their intelligence. Schools may fail to
challenge them, and the result can be boredom, apathy and
alienation. That can lead to rage-filled outbursts and bouts of
depression. Nor do parents have an easy time of it. Having a gifted
child can be an expensive and frustrating experience. From Der
Spiegel. 1,000 words. English translation available. 6.
BACK-TO-SCHOOL BARGAINS With many children due to return to school
in the next few weeks, here are some creative tips to help parents
save money on clothing, lunches and other school-related purchases.
By Leah Ingram. 1,400 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
MUSTANG SALLY Sally Hershberger is ``the closest thing to a female
superstar the hair world has ever had.'' She has created the
hairstyles of Hollywood stars such as Meg Ryan and Tom Cruise and
has worked on numerous magazine cover shoots. Ready for a new
challenge, she is embarking on her own product line. Interview by
Dana Wood. From Women's Wear Daily. 800 words + photos.
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
AH-SO SICK IN GAY PARIS ``My raw throat felt like a tractor had
rolled through it on caterpillar treads. My vision was blurred; I
was alternately sweating and freezing. Was I really going to be
sick all day? ....'' By Carolee B. Morrison. A personal account of
feeling ill during a trip abroad. 1,300 words. 9. THE TOUR DE
FRANCE'S SHATTERED LEGEND The 1998 Tour de France cycle race was
undermined by a doping scandal and came perilously close to
imploding. There is certainly no way it will be able to go ahead in
1999 as though nothing had happened, writes Jean-Marie Colombani.
From Le Monde. (English translation available.) 600 words.
</P>
</TEXT>
