<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The air was heavy with perfume
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The first indication that this wasn't going to be a
typical hotel stay was at the front desk of the Hyatt Regency at
Reunion Square, a hotel hard by downtown and within walking
distance of the Texas School Book Depository. The clerk, who is
from Cork County, Ireland, according to her name tag, hands me a
letter welcoming me to the hotel. The letter announces that the
Hyatt is hosting the annual Mary Kay Inc. conference, and that more
than 1,000 are attending over the next several days.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the letter says, at certain times elevators will be
extremely crowded, phone lines will be busy, and checking in or out
could be a problem. The clerk then directs me toward the elevators,
which are being
</P>
<P>
   guarded by two security men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell them I said it was OK to use the elevators,'' she says
with a lovely accent belied by a rather dubious set of teeth.
</P>
<P>
   I finish reading the letter as I shoulder my way through a crowd
of women wearing prom-like dresses and plenty of makeup. Someone
made a killing on glitter, sequins and velvet for this convocation.
</P>
<P>
   The letter suggests that I might consider taking the stairs
during busy times. Since I've been assigned to a room on the 22nd
floor, the place is going to have to be on fire before I lumber up
and down nearly two dozen stories.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, the security men let me pass. I get on an elevator
relatively quickly, and am joined by a set of Mary Kay women
apparently intent on breaking the Guinness record for most folks
crammed into a single elevator.
</P>
<P>
   We stop at nearly ever floor. I am concerned that a spark of
static electricity will somehow ignite the overwhelming cloud of
hair spray and perfume in the elevator. We will go up in flames
quicker than a hay meadow during this drought if that should occur.
</P>
<P>
   I get off without incident, though my sinuses protest the
assault of a dozen different types of perfume.
</P>
<P>
   Later, I venture back to the lobby, again riding with a crowd of
Mary Kay women, all wearing name tags and most decked out in what
look like prom dresses _ except for the most part the women are
more than a few years and pounds past attending a prom. So am I, of
course.
</P>
<P>
   I meet with my co-workers in the lobby, one of whom hands me a
pink business card a Mary Kay consultant from Kingsport, Tenn., has
given her.
</P>
<P>
   She's a bit miffed the woman took one look at her and determined
she needed Mary Kay's services. You have to admire their
aggressiveness.
</P>
<P>
   In the lobby, groups of women are taking turns getting their
photo taken in front of a large glass ball whose purpose I can't
determine. Decoration, I guess. One woman walks by wearing a
diamond tiara, as if she had just won the Mary Kay Inc. beauty
contest, though I don't know if there is one. A few husbands lurk
about, most looking as if they would rather be somewhere else,
though I don't know that for sure either.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Kay women, judging from this gathering, come in all shapes,
sizes, races and ages. I look up the company's Web page later and
find out there are more than a half-million Mary Kay Beauty
Consultants in 27 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Its international headquarters is in Dallas, in a 13-story
building that contains about 600,000 square feet. That's about like
five Wal-Mart Supercenters for point of reference. Retail sales are
more than $2 billion,
</P>
<P>
   and the company owns the best-selling brand of facial care
products and cosmetics in the United States, with 10 percent of the
market.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Kay Inc. has been listed for years as one of the ``100 Best
Companies to Work For in America'' by Fortune magazine. In the past
few years, the company has given away hundreds of thousands of
dollars for cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   Pink Cadillacs are everywhere on this landmark summer day _ the
first time the thermometer has dipped below 100 degrees in about a
month _ lining the circle drive, in the pay-lot where I'm parked,
and out on the street. Mary Kay has the largest commercial fleet of
GM passenger cars in the world, with 10,000 cars valued at more
than $150 million. The company has added a pink Grand Prix, a red
Grand Am and lately a white GMC Jimmy sports utility vehicle to its
fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Parked by my car out in the lot is a Honda whose owner has
posted a sign on the back windshield. It reads, ``This time next
year I'll be driving a Mary Kay red Grand Am.''
</P>
<P>
   Good for her. I hope she makes it.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches (Texas)
Daily Sentinel. His e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
