<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Is it Lt. Blassie's Medal of Honor?
 &HT;    (For release Aug. 16, 1998)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is no greater sacrifice a person can make for his country
than giving his or her life for it. And that's what Air Force 1st
Lt. Michael J. Blassie did over Vietnam in 1972. But, was what he
did worthy of the Medal of Honor, the highest award this country
can bestow on a military hero?
</P>
<P>
   Blassie's remains recently were removed from the Tomb of the
Unknowns at Arlington National Cemetery, where they had rested
since 1984. Finally identified through DNA testing, he was reburied
near his family home in Missouri with full military honors.
</P>
<P>
   For the Blassie family, the moving ceremony would have appeared
to be closure to the ordeal they had endured for 26 years, now
knowing that Michael indeed had died and the whereabouts of his
remains. But it hasn't ended there.
</P>
<P>
   The family wants the Medal of Honor to come out to Missouri with
Michael.
</P>
<P>
   And that has caused complications, which it should.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the four Unknowns at Arlington were presented with
Medals of Honor _ not for what each of them did in battle, but as a
representation of all who had fallen in battle and not been
identified.
</P>
<P>
   Morally, if not technically, the awarding of the Medal of Honor
to the Unknowns was a generous mistake. According to Ronald D. Dake
of Mt. Pleasant, S.C., executive director of the Congressional
Medal of Honor Society, the route to the Medal of Honor begins with
a recommendation, by name, of a potential recipient followed by the
testimony of two unimpeachable witnesses to a heroic action. None
of that happened with Lt. Blassie, or any of the other three
Unknowns.
</P>
<P>
   For what is trying to be stated at the Tomb of the Unknowns, it
can be understood that those requisites could be waived. But if the
medal is awarded to a representative Unknown, can it remain with
that person once he becomes known?
</P>
<P>
   Blassie's sister, Patricia Blassie, is pushing the campaign for
the medal, just as she did to compel the government to exhume the
body in the tomb for DNA testing on her strong belief that it was
her brother.
</P>
<P>
   She agrees that giving the medal to an Unknown is symbolic but
insists that her brother was that symbol for 14 years and,
therefore, has earned it. Some veterans groups oppose this, and
Secretary of Defense William Cohen is in a quandary and has called
for a study of the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Understand that Lt. Blassie already has been awarded the Silver
Star for his gallantry in action, and that has gone home to the
family.
</P>
<P>
   The unease by the veterans groups is not specifically about Lt.
Blassie but about the approximately 3,500 Medals of Honor awarded
since the Civil War. When one considers the heroics above and
beyond the call of duty of these recipients, it can be seen as
depreciating the award to have Lt. Blassie retain it.
</P>
<P>
   The remains later identified as those of Lt. Blassie were
chosen, at random, to be the Vietnam Unknown by a Marine Corps
Medal of Honor winner, a sergeant. The Korean War Unknown was
chosen in 1958 by an Army sergeant from among four unidentified
Americans; the World War II Unknown was chosen the same year by a
Navy hospital corpsman from two remains, and the World War I
Unknown was selected in 1921 by an Army sergeant from among four
Americans still buried in France.
</P>
<P>
   It is only by chance as to whose remains are chosen for the Tomb
of the Unknowns. And with DNA testing, it probably will be
difficult, but not impossible, to find another Vietnam War unknown
to replace Lt. Blassie in the tomb.
</P>
<P>
   But, the effort should be made. To have the Vietnam War tomb
empty would further add to the bitterness of that war's veterans.
And the Medal of Honor, perhaps too casually awarded to the
Unknowns in the first place, should stay above that tomb as part of
its symbolism.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
