<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Americans ought to impeach themselves, not Bill Clinton
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I remember writing these words sometime in October of 1992:
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we really want to elect as president a man who has
essentially admitted being unfaithful to his wife?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer, as we must all remember, was a resounding ``Yes!''
In fact, Bill Clinton's acknowledged dalliances (we all knew what
he was saying on ``60 Minutes'') did not seem to hurt him with any
demographic group or in any state in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's goal in politics has always been getting elected, not
governing. Why is anyone surprised when we hear of yet another
marital transgression, particularly when it has been demonstrated
that the voters just don't care?
</P>
<P>
   If you don't say ``no,'' or slap your child's hand when he keeps
putting it in the cookie jar, you've given him tacit approval to
get all the cookies he wants. You can't watch him do it for six
years, then pretend to get upset. It just won't work.
</P>
<P>
   You can book it that Clinton and Paula Jones had an encounter _
likely consensual _ and ditto for a long affair with Gennifer
Flowers. There are a half-dozen others along the way _ at least. We
don't know how many of them are forever holding their peace.
</P>
<P>
   Nor would it surprise me to find out, in some later revelation,
that Clinton isn't getting his cookies from someone other than the
first lady even as all this is going on.
</P>
<P>
   To prove that I am not smarter than anyone else, while I did
write those words before the 1992 elections, I also came back to
write a ringing endorsement of Clinton a few weeks later. This is
back when I believed that Clinton really wanted to govern. In 1996,
I wrote another endorsement, but this time it was less than
enthusiastic. It was based more on Bob Dole's weaknesses than
Clinton's strengths.
</P>
<P>
   The point is that almost all of us knowingly overlooked
Clinton's affairs. Perhaps a few people voted against him simply
because he had had an extra-marital affair, but it was not the
deciding factor for most.
</P>
<P>
   So now the nation is squirming with the titillating details of a
Clinton affair in your newspapers and on television daily. (I hope
the dress doesn't end up at the Smithsonian someday, alongside the
inaugural gowns worn by first ladies.)
</P>
<P>
   Some of us are acting surprised. Some from the Republican Party
are even talking about impeachment because Clinton did not admit to
the affair in a deposition in a civil case.
</P>
<P>
   Hmmmm, a married man not admitting to an affair, now there is
something amazing. If Clinton gets ousted for that, dozens of
senators and congressmen from both parties are in deep, deep
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   What Clinton has done with the precocious Monica Lewinsky _ and
I have no doubts he did darn near everything _ is not right, but
the American public by popular vote has told him that it is fine
with us.
</P>
<P>
   Want to impeach somebody? Impeach yourself. Impeach your
neighbors. Impeach the Electoral College. Impeach every person who
voted for Bill Clinton. We got exactly the person we voted for.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall (Texas) News
Messenger.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
