</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: An exemplary family
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This thing could go badly awry yet, I suppose, but for now it
appears the families of those two little girls switched at birth in
Virginia are going to work the matter out sensibly and in mutual
caring. While they do, the rest of us, following the story at a
distance, might usefully pause for a moment and think about what we
mean by family.
</P>
<P>
   For, first, here are two 3-year-olds reared in apparent love by
biological strangers, and the life of one was already further
complicated by the recent deaths of her parents in an automobile
accident; she had come into the care of two sets of grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate reaction to the discovery of the maternity-ward
mix-up was confusion, some understandable anger and agony over what
to do.
</P>
<P>
   We could all expect, from too many examples, that this story
would soon head down a twisting legal road, amid a din of
gavel-blows and recriminations, ending more than likely with horrid
TV news pictures of one child or both being forced in tears from
homes they always had understood were their own.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not this time. Both families have agreed that the
children's feelings come first, and a child's feeling for the
familiar is absolute. Yet realizing that both have an interest now
in the other child as well, the families are working on mutual
visitation and the creation of a de facto extended family that both
acknowledges and transcends biology.
</P>
<P>
   (The prospects are improved, he says in a surly aside, by the
fact that the families are keeping their lawyers discreetly aside
and are meeting together instead.)
</P>
<P>
   We are at the leading edge of another political season in which
great clouds of demagoguery will be huffed on the topic of ``family
values,'' with implied and often explicit contempt for persons who
have not arranged themselves suitably for a 1950s sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study confirmed the obvious, that the number of
unmarried couples continues to rise. Every such twitch in the
statistics sets off the alarmists, and since as a nation we have
fallen to constantly taking our social temperature, we are
generally convinced that we must be terminal. We have, as a people,
pioneered social hypochondria.
</P>
<P>
   What really seems to be happening is that we are developing new
living formats for different parts of our lives. Traditional
marriage continues to be the overwhelming choice for the
child-rearing part, and if the pregnancy often proceeds the vows,
well, we are not the first people to find that pregnancy can be as
much a cause of marriage as a consequence.
</P>
<P>
   For the rest, we adhere, disband, mingle and hive off as suits
our other interests and needs in their time. It is not clear that
any of that is quite as awful in its consequences as our busybodies
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ozzie and Harriet'' and ``Father Knows Best'' could have made
no sense whatsoever out of the lovely muddle of a family that that
young single mother, with her former boyfriend back in the mix, and
four grandparents are cobbling together in Virginia. But it looks
as though two little girls are going to be well cared for by it and
well loved in it.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it is worth remembering that ``values'' is the noun.
``Family'' is only the adjective.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 1119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
