<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1928 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEEWAX-COMMENTARY14-C     08-13 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-COMMENTARY14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Keep Georgia's prisons out of private hands
 &HT;    (Eds: This ran as an unsigned editorial in Thursday's Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.)
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In recent years, government bashing has become so
fashionable that many people now believe industry can do everything
better than government.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the private sector can outperform the government in
many areas. But not in all. Some burdens are too weighty to be
picked up by companies that have to pay more attention to the
bottom line than to the public good.
</P>
<P>
   For example, most Americans would not dream of allowing private
companies to decide whether to launch a war, although the Pentagon
is notorious for buying $600 hammers. We don't ``outsource'' our
Army by hiring low-wage generals from other countries. The decision
to wage war is so grave, it must be made only by officials who
derive their power directly from our democratically elected
government.
</P>
<P>
   The war on crime is a serious matter as well. Incarcerating
human beings to protect the citizenry is a burden that should be
borne only by government, not by profit seekers. Unfortunately,
about half of all states, including Georgia, have embraced the idea
that prisons can be safely run by private companies.
</P>
<P>
   This month, Georgia's first private prison, owned by Cornell
Corrections Inc., opened in Charlton County. Another company,
Corrections Corporation of America, will open two more prisons, one
in Coffee County and another in Wheeler County, in December.
</P>
<P>
   But even as these prisons are getting started in Georgia,
taxpayers in other parts of the country are finding out just how
dangerous and expensive privatization can be:
</P>
<P>
   _ Last week in New Mexico, inmates beat five guards in a
Corrections Corporation of America prison. A 15-member state
tactical team had to go in to restore order.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last month in Youngstown, Ohio, six inmates _ including four
convicted murderers _ broke out of a prison run by CCA. In its
first 17 months of operation, the Ohio prison has had 13 stabbings,
including two homicides.
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1996, two convicted sex offenders escaped a CCA prison in
Houston. While Texas officials were told the prison was going to
hold undocumented immigrants, it turned out that CCA had shipped in
more than 200 sex offenders from Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Because of such outrages, CCA's stock has been taking a beating,
falling from about $44 a share last fall to $16.87 Wednesday.
Though weakened, the company, founded 15 years ago in Nashville,
soon will be in charge of about 3,200 prisoners in southeast
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   But CCA is not an extreme example among prison companies; other
prison owners have similar records. For example, in April, state
officials in Colorado closed a juvenile prison run by Rebound Corp.
after the investigation of a 13-year-old inmate's suicide led to
evidence of multiple instances of physical and sexual abuse. In
Louisiana last month, state officials took control of the Tallulah
Correctional Center for Youth, owned by Trans-American Development
Associates, to stop the extreme neglect and brutality documented
there.
</P>
<P>
   All over the country, evidence is growing that many private
prisons are poorly run. Since the prison break in Ohio, Republican
Gov. George Voinovich has explored ways to shut down CCA, but he
has been told by the state attorney general that Youngstown is
stuck with the privately owned safety hazard.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, government officials can also do a lousy job of
running prisons; we have plenty of evidence of that in Georgia,
where credible evidence has suggested that Georgia Department of
Corrections head Wayne Garner led a brutal and unprovoked assault
on prison inmates. But at least when a penal institution is run by
the government, elected officials have to answer to voters. But how
does the public hold private prison owners responsible for their
actions?
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly, nobody really knows. Many legal experts seriously
question whether a private corporation has the constitutional right
to hold people against their will. And no one is certain what would
happen if a prison company declared bankruptcy and announced it
could not pay its workers. Would the guards walk off the job and
leave the prison doors open?
</P>
<P>
   For private prison operators, public safety is not the No. 1
mission. Making money for stockholders is. That means private
prisons are inherently more dangerous; they have financial
incentives to house more dangerous prisoners and cut guard costs.
Ohioans realize that now. Here's what happened in Youngstown:
</P>
<P>
   CCA built a medium-security prison to hold convicts transferred
from the overcrowded jails of Washington. The prisoners were
supposed to be serving sentences of less than 10 years. In other
words, Youngstown was supposed to get bad guys who weren't
hideously bad.
</P>
<P>
   But violence has repeatedly rocked the prison. In March,
Youngstown joined a suit by inmates against CCA. In court, CCA's
chief of security, Robert Adams, testified that his prison never
rejected a single inmate from Washington, which is how convicted
murderers ended up in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   And why would CCA take in killers? Because Washington paid good
money to get those convicts out of its sight. Murderers are profit
sources for CCA.
</P>
<P>
   CCA also has a profit motive to cut expenses for things such as
books and tutors. It's not in the stockholders' best interests to
spend a lot of money on prisoner rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   When convicted criminals are released into society, they can
either become productive taxpayers or continue to be dangers to
society. Private prisons have no real incentive to turn convicts
into workers. In fact, their stock gains when society sees an
increase in criminal behavior, not when the supply of prisoners
dwindles.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, for all of their cost cutting, private prisons don't
even save taxpayers' money, according to a study by the General
Accounting Office, a federal watchdog agency. After examining the
books of private prisons in five states, the GAO found no clear
evidence that taxpayers get any significant benefits from
privatization.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, political leaders are starting to wake up to these
problems. Last week, the Republican-led House approved an amendment
that would require a federal study of privately run prisons. The
measure still requires Senate approval. This week, Attorney General
Janet Reno ordered an in-depth, independent review of CCA's
security and management procedures at its Ohio prison.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, private prisons are just getting established. Every
legal option should be explored now to stop this mistake before it
goes any further.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
