<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Thursday, Aug. 13, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Friday and Sunday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   QUAKE (San Francisco) _ If the latest temblor to rattle Northern
California shakes people out their complacency about earthquake
safety, then it has done more good than harm, emergency officials
said. ``It lets people know we should always be ready for the big
one,'' said Sherman Ackerson, spokesman for the San Francisco
Police Department. By JIM HERRON ZAMORA and Le'VADA GRAY.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   INTEL-WEB (San Francisco) _ Think the World Wide Web is slow?
Intel is paying mainstream Web publishers to make it even slower.
In an effort to sell more chips with more power, the computer chip
maker is pouring more dollars into a program to entice Web site
creators to post large, complicated graphics on their sites. This
slows down a computer's processor when they are downloaded from the
Internet. By MAX BEER.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDER-TRADING (San Francisco) _ The founder of the
biotechnology firms Alza Corp. and Affymax NV settled insider
trading charges related to the 1995 sale of Affymax by agreeing,
along with five friends and family members, to pay $1.85 million in
penalties. By VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-SNEAKERS (San Francisco) _ It must be the generational
difference. But Daniela Faggioli's 18-year-old debutante daughter,
Max Boyer, loved the white rubber-trimmed anthracite sneaks that
Giorgio Armani was showing with his Emporio line. Daniela hated it.
``Why sabotage a good look?'' she asked. By CYNTHIA ROBINS.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-FELICITY (Albany, N.Y.) _ ``Felicity,'' a one-hour drama
premiering this fall on the WB network, could suffer by comparison
to Fox's ``Ally McBeal'' comedy and the powerful but brief ``My
So-Called Life.'' Then again, if an audience is actually drawn in
by the comparisons to this drama, odds are it will stick around
after its individuality emerges. By MARK McGUIRE. (For release
Sunday, Aug. 16)
</P>
<P>
   STONES-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ ``How are you going to satisfy the
30-year hunger of your Russian fans by giving just one concert in
Moscow?'' The Rolling Stones were asked at their Moscow press
conference. ``It's a nibble. It's a start,'' Mick Jagger swiftly
fielded the question, acting consummately as spokesperson for the
band. By VICTOR TURKS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-MARK-McGWIRE (Albany, N.Y.) _ The elderly man wrote to the
St. Louis Cardinals requesting a bat _ a Mark McGwire bat. To use
as a prosthetic. With all the attention, McGwire waffles between
thanking the fans for embracing him everywhere he goes and wishing
they would give him space enough to avoid feeling like a ``caged
animal.'' By STEVE CAMPBELL.
</P>
<P>
   RAC-GLOBAL-ECONOMY (Saratoga Springs, N.Y.) _ You want to know
where the global economy is headed? Go to the yearling sale at the
Saratoga Springs Racecourse. When oil prices were high, Middle
Easterners dominated the auction. When Japan's economy was buzzing,
the Japanese were the players to watch. But oil is not as expensive
as it once was and Japan is struggling. Now, experts say, it's the
Europeans' turn. By JANE GOTTLIEB.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ A few socio-political topics
that ought not slip away without some reflection: In the Unclear on
the Concept category, we have a group of so-called conservative
Roman Catholics wreaking emotional havoc at Auschwitz in Poland. By
STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
</TEXT>
