<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 11:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1934 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CD-REVIEWS14-COX     08-13 2033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CD-REVIEWS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Liz Phair never made a more enjoyable album
 &HT;    (Eds: This column is compiled from reviews by staff members of
The Atlanta Journal-Constitution and the Austin
American-Statesman.)
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Liz Phair
</P>
<P>
   ``whitechocolatespaceegg''
</P>
<P>
   Matador/Capitol
</P>
<P>
   Don't tell me all the magic's gone,'' Chicago's hip
singer-songwriter Liz Phair warbles on the title track to her third
full-length album, which hit stores this week. Two songs later, on
``Perfect World,'' she sings, ``I know I was born to lead a double
life/And when I find it, I know I'll make sense of me'' in her
trademark flat, nasal tone.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Love Is Nothing,'' which takes the album's theme of
relationship ruts to an extreme, Phair wonders, ``Would I lie to
make the day blur into night?'' On ``Go on Ahead,'' she explores
both sides of cohabitation, of lovers walking like ghosts in their
own homes, but then feeling close when they're sleeping together.
``It's a death in our love that has brought us here/It's a birth
that has changed our lives,'' she sings in this song about being
``in way over our heads with this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, ``whitechocolatespaceegg's'' lead single, ``Polyester
</P>
<P>
   Bride,'' weighs the choice between domesticity and adventure in
favor of the latter. With maturity and responsibility comes fear:
Doubt permeates this album, whose title seems to refer to Phair's
new delightful, disposable family of three. The shell protects, but
it is, after all, only a shell.
</P>
<P>
   Our favorite ``lo-fi'' sexual politician, who switched the
dynamics of boy-meets-girl so brilliantly on 1993's ``Exile in
Guyville,'' hasn't entirely devoted herself to the sinking feeling
that bliss is a myth. ``Whitechocolatespaceegg's'' two best songs _
``Johnny Feelgood'' and ``What Makes You Happy'' _ find a reckless
Phair, still falling for the wrong guy for all the right reasons.
The album ends with Phair going back even further, with a
mysteriously irresistible slumber party sing-song, ``Girls Room,''
as if calling for a lost innocence that she realizes wasn't really
that innocent.
</P>
<P>
   Phair's straightforwardly nonlinear lyrics and defiantly off-key
voice have always suggested that life is a sequence of hazy events,
just as her deadpan presentation mirrors the numbing effect of
experiences piled high. On her new record, however, the spirit of
true optimism can be found in the spare, yet creative backing, that
strives to show that fulfillment can be found in simple, tugging
songs, if only for three minutes at a time. Even the album's
weakest tracks _ the roots sendup ``Baby Got Going,'' the
self-explanatory ``S---loads of Money'' and the modern rock
sleepwalk ``Big Tall Man'' _ offer something of merit, if only a
sturdy melody.
</P>
<P>
   On her first full album since 1994's disappointing
``Whip-Smart,'' Phair displays a depth to her writing that makes
her vocals all the more engaging. No longer able to shock with her
bluntness, she opts to enlighten with an unflinching
self-examination that'll have you humming along.
</P>
<P>
   Liz Phair has never made a more enjoyable album, even as she
contemplates the crossroads, after choosing her direction, and
wondering ``Who am I? Who's this guy?'' When she sings that ``Love
Is Nothing,'' she's really telling you that it's the only thing. _
Michael Corcoran
</P>
<P>
   The Lemonheads
</P>
<P>
   `The Best of the Lemonheads: The Atlantic Years'
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic
</P>
<P>
   The Sugarcubes
</P>
<P>
   `A Collection'
</P>
<P>
   Elektra
</P>
<P>
   If loud guitars and angst-ridden singers are all we remember
about the so-called alternative-rock revolution of the late '80s
and early '90s, then the Lemonheads and the Sugarcubes were gypped.
As proved by new best-of collections from each of these
self-admitted candy-poppers (the sweetness is even in the names),
they were everything they set out to be, and sometimes more.
</P>
<P>
   For Iceland's Sugarcubes, their ``more'' was innovation. Best
known as the band that spawned current electronic-music queen Bjrk,
the Cubes hit the U.S. scene in 1988 with the quirky, rhythmic
single ``Birthday'' and later offered such energetic MTV hits as
``Regina'' and ``Hit,'' all of which are included on ``A
Collection.'' While the group only had the goods for one memorable
album _ ``Life's Too Good,'' from which five songs appear here _
they enjoyed scattered moments of brilliance, on songs such as
``Planet'' and ``Walkabout,'' that make this best-of a worthy
effort.
</P>
<P>
   The Lemonheads' surplus quality was how good of a rock band they
turned out to be, at least during their 1992-93 incarnation. Songs
like ``Confetti'' and ``The Great Big No'' feature that rare, tight
pop-trio energy (Fastball, anyone?).
</P>
<P>
   Without that, the Boston-based band was nothing more than a
vehicle for the soft-hearted, coy musings of Evan Dando, which was
plenty for some fans _ young women, in particular. As audaciously
melodic tracks such as ``Into Your Arms,'' ``It's a Shame About
Ray'' and the acoustic ``Ride With Me'' show, Dando was then a
first-rate pop singer whose warm voice matched his nice-guy
approach. Really, what other straight (OK, semi-straight) guy could
have pulled off the delightful ``Big Gay Heart,'' perhaps the best
of this best-of?
</P>
<P>
   Say what you will of these giddy popsters and their
career-milking greatest-hits CDs, just don't interrupt their fans'
lasting enjoyment of humming along. _ Chris Riemenschneider
</P>
<P>
   Snoop Dogg
</P>
<P>
   `Da Game Is to Be Sold, Not to Be Told'
</P>
<P>
   No Limit Records
</P>
<P>
   Long before this album hit the stores, it was a big record.
Master P's signing of Snoop Doggy Dogg, probably the most popular
artist in gangster rap, elevated P's independent and successful No
Limit Records label to a higher level. And Dogg's departure from
the notorious Death Row Records was the final nail in the coffin of
what was one of the most successful purveyors of violent, graphic
and drug-laced rap.
</P>
<P>
   But a big record isn't always a great record, as evidenced by
``Da Game Is to Be Sold, Not to Be Told.''
</P>
<P>
   Dogg's teaming with No Limit's in-house production team, Beats
by the Pound, is too often the lulling and unmemorable experience
you'd expect when you match Dogg's languid delivery with equally
lazy rhythms. Not that Dogg rapped any differently on Death Row.
But when Dr. Dre was on the production boards, his keyboard-based
``G-Funk'' always had the kind of power that insisted you listen to
the low-key rapper. And that, coupled with hooks such as those on
``Gin and Juice,'' made even menacing lyrics easy to sing along to.
</P>
<P>
   Here, ``Gin and Juice II'' is an orchestrated yawner complete
with timpani rolls. Dogg's labelmate Mystikal proves more imposing
on ``Tru Tank Dogs,'' and his other new labelmate, Mia X, is as
compelling on the cautionary tale ``Slow Down.'' Dogg finds his
stride only when he's reminiscing, as on the muscular ``Woof!''
That's also true for the well-written reworking of Boogie Down
Productions' ``Love's Gonna Get'cha,'' titled ``Doggz Gonna Get
Ya,'' and on ``DP Gangsta,'' a take on NWA's ``Gangsta, Gangsta.''
</P>
<P>
   NWA, remember, included Dr. Dre. Are you starting to notice the
connection _ or, better yet, what's missing?
</P>
<P>
   _ Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   The Tony Rich Project
</P>
<P>
   `Birdseye'
</P>
<P>
   LaFace
</P>
<P>
   When Tony Rich made his bow in 1996, many wrongly welcomed him
into the then newly titled ``retro soul'' category, a place where
other young and pioneering artists such as D'Angelo and Maxwell
dwelled.
</P>
<P>
   The funny thing was that ``soul,'' or black, radio slammed the
door on Rich and his acoustic guitar-based ``Nobody Knows.'' It
didn't have enough beat, enough ``bottom,'' programmers said, to be
played alongside Marvin Gaye-inspired Maxwell and the Hammond
organs and old Stevie Wonder sway of D'Angelo.
</P>
<P>
   It also wasn't this record. ``Birdseye'' is a beautiful
testament to Rich's musical and lyrical growth.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling the worn road of depicting the progression of a
relationship, it starts with the moment he walks into the Atlanta
Live club and sees a woman with Halle Berry's eyes (``Birdseye'').
In ``Silly Man,'' they're ``making love like instruments.'' Then,
after professing how happy he is (``If You're an Angel''), he
questions it on ``Bed of My Heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Simultaneously, Rich successfully navigates his way through funk
(the title track), early Prince (``Cool Like That'') and soul
(``Blue Butterfly''), stalling only on a few retreads from his
quirky debut (``Ain't No Laughin' ''). _ Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   FOLK
</P>
<P>
   Gillian Welch
</P>
<P>
   `Hell Among the Yearlings'
</P>
<P>
   Almo Sounds
</P>
<P>
   Musically, this Nashville singer-songwriter's second effort
strays little from the meticulous country-folk and bluegrass sounds
of her Grammy-nominated 1996 debut, ``Revival.'' Indeed, her
adherence to tradition may be a bit too strict _ some songs have a
hermetically sealed, museum-piece feel. It's in the lyrics that
Welch gets adventurous, delving into the dark side of human nature.
``Caleb Meyer'' deals with the attempted rape of a mountain woman,
while the heartbreaking ``One Morning'' observes a Kentucky mother
as she watches her long-gone son ride up on horseback. As he draws
near, she discovers that he's dead from gunshot wounds.
</P>
<P>
   POP
</P>
<P>
   Lena Horne
</P>
<P>
   `Being Myself'
</P>
<P>
   Blue Note Records
</P>
<P>
   Lena Horne has lost a few notes through the years, but it
doesn't matter on ``Being Myself,'' a disc on which she's clearly
having fun. And yet emotions run deep in this mixture of pop
standards and blues tunes. Horne is sassy on ``As Long as I Live,''
melancholy on ``Autumn in New York'' and reflective on
``Imagination.'' And don't miss her ``Sleepin' Bee,'' which begins
with a hum and builds to an all-out buzz. Horne, now 81, has
decades of tales to tell from her years as a recording artist and
stage and screen actress. They're all here, a burbling subtext that
gives each phrase, each lyric waves of meaning. Our only regret? We
get just 38 minutes of that old Horne magic.
</P>
<P>
   VARIETY
</P>
<P>
   Various artists
</P>
<P>
   `Legends of Ukulele'
</P>
<P>
   Rhino
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to believe, looking at this homely little instrument,
but once upon a time the ukulele ruled. Starting with the Hawaiian
music boom of the early 1900s, the instrument crested in the 1940s
with Arthur Godfrey, who eventually sold 9 million of his plastic
ukes. This disc has plenty to argue its case, from virtuoso jazz to
humble folk to aromatic old chestnuts such as ``Do I Love You? Yes
I Do!'' Skip the obligatory Tiny Tim track and go right to the
ineffable Ohta San and ``Little Grass Shack.'' The production and
selection are impeccable, and the way overresearched liner notes
are from Jim Beloff, author of ``The Ukulele: A Visual History''
and contributor of the noirishly cute ``For the Love of Uke.''
</P>
<P>
   ROCK
</P>
<P>
   The Knack
</P>
<P>
   `Zoom'
</P>
<P>
   Rhino
</P>
<P>
   They're back. The West Coast crew that gave us ``My Sharona''
returns with a new set of slick, formulaic Cheap Trick imitations.
And somehow they manage the impossible: ``Zoom'' makes ``Sharona''
sound like a rock masterpiece. Just a click short of self-parody,
the Knack's keg-party mix of scattershot-fuzz guitar, sing-song
melodies and brick-handed drumming are as cliche-laden as ever.
Even the lyrics on ``Zoom'' are stone-dumb. Sample: ``Can I borrow
a kiss? I'll pay it back with interest.'' Sheesh. It's almost
enough to make you wonder what Toni ``Mickey (You're So Fine)''
Basil's up to these days. Almost.
</P>
<P>
   Eve 6
</P>
<P>
   `Eve 6'
</P>
<P>
   RCA/BMG.
</P>
<P>
   This L.A. power rock trio is getting a lot of mileage from its
omnipresent MTV video for ``Inside Out,'' but, unlike a lot of the
bands on the video channel, Eve 6 has legs. The group of
18-year-olds, fronted by vocalist-bassist-lyricist Max Collins,
could be labeled Hanson with distortion guitar pedals. Collins and
crew show amazing musical maturity and tightness that demonstrate
they've been studying. The memorable melodies coupled with witty,
insightful, angst-riddled lyrics prove once again that there's
nothing like the experience of being a high school outcast to
produce great rock 'n' roll.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
