</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-STELLA14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Movie review: Bassett, Jamaica heat up well-made love story
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ah, what a difference a groove makes.
</P>
<P>
   With her semi-autobiographical, older woman-younger man love
story, ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back,'' novelist Terry McMillan
delivers an audience-friendly romance that's as much a fairy tale
as the Cinderella saga ``Ever After.'' What a change from her sour,
male-bashing ``Waiting to Exhale.''
</P>
<P>
   A buffed Angela Bassett is back from that 1995 release to play
40-year-old Stella Payne, a driven, high-powered San Francisco
stock broker and single super-mom who has fallen into a robotic,
joyless rut. Prompted by a television ad, and scolded that life is
too short by her best friend Delilah (Whoopi Goldberg), Stella
flies off to Jamaica, mon, hoping to trade in that rut for a
groove.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the idyllic surroundings of an upscale resort, she gains
the attention of handsome, charming hunk Winston Shakespeare (Taye
Diggs), a Jamaican half her age. Though wary and riddled with
guilt, she takes him into her bed and, gradually, into her life.
</P>
<P>
   They have vast cultural and economic differences, but the issue
that preys on Stella is the age disparity. Of course, if she only
took the time to see more Hollywood movies, she'd realize that with
the roles reversed, such a generation gap is almost the norm. Get
over it, Stella, and you go for it, girl.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there has to be some conflict to pad the movie out to
feature length, so Stella's self-doubts are reinforced by her
snippy sisters and by Winston's haughty mother, only one year older
than Stella.
</P>
<P>
   McMillan and co-screenwriter Ron Bass, the ``Waiting to Exhale''
adaptation team, flesh out the story by enlarging the role of
Delilah and tailoring it to Goldberg's wise-cracking earth-mother
persona. Just as Stella's love life improves, Delilah's health
takes a downturn, a guaranteed tear-jerker. The script gives Stella
and Winston momentary flare-ups of disagreement, but for the most
part their differences get swept away. Few Hollywood movies ever
went broke assuring audiences that love conquers all.
</P>
<P>
   First-time director Kevin Rodney Sullivan wraps the fairy tale
in a visual high gloss. It may already be too late, but consider
buying stock in Jamaica, which is bound to get a boost in tourism
after this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Bassett's stock will also soar. She looks terrific, and handily
carries the movie, with a few great flashes of temper and even more
looks of ecstasy. Diggs makes his feature debut and shows every
sign of staying power.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Stella'' receives the same attention that ``Waiting to
Exhale'' got, its sociological significance will be hotly debated.
But it's just an old-fashioned Hollywood love story with a cultural
face lift. It's well-made and satisfying, but hardly profound.
</P>
<P>
   Hap Erstein writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 1124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 11:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1937 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-LUNCH14-COX     08-13 1294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-LUNCH14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Experts pack healthy school lunches
 &HT;    By Michele Chan Santos
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The big question when it comes to packing lunch
for your kids is: How do you know they're eating it? They may
cheerfully tote their lunch to school every day, but you may not
know if they're actually eating what you give them, trading your
carefully chosen foods for what other kids brought or throwing them
away.
</P>
<P>
   Our health experts, all parents, recommend packing only items
you know they will eat. If you want to introduce a new, healthy
food item, do it on a weekend or at dinner first. Once you know
they like it, or at least will tolerate it, you can put it in their
lunches, says Marsha Beckermann, sports nutritionist for the
University of Texas Athletic Department.
</P>
<P>
   You can try asking them, too.
</P>
<P>
   Naturopathic physician Gerard Luna, father to 15-year-old Rene
and 8-year-old Ari, used to ask his kids if they ate what he had
made for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd give me a straight answer,'' Luna says. Sometimes they
would say ``I didn't like that, so I threw it out or traded it,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   He advises parents to keep trying, perhaps giving them the food
in a different form: ``Maybe sliced instead of diced will work,''
Luna says.
</P>
<P>
   His family is vegetarian, so his children's lunches often are
different from those of their friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter has become a kind of little novelty at
lunchtime,'' Luna says. Ari will unpack her tamari dips and other
unusual lunch foods, to the interest of her classmates. ``She
always has a different thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary McGill, a registered nurse and mother to 9-year-old Jackson
and 4-year-old Grayson, recommends making a list of foods in each
food group that your children like. Try different combinations to
make their lunches.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Todd-Meyer, nutrition team leader at Whole Foods Gateway,
recalls that when one of her daughters was in the fourth grade, she
would bring her lunch home at the end of the day, untouched. She
sat down with her daughter and they made a compromise: the daughter
would bring her lunch three days a week and buy it at the cafeteria
two days a week.
</P>
<P>
   Todd-Meyer changed what she put into the lunches, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Check with them. Try some different things,'' she advises.
``We settled on what made us both happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Children sometimes need to try foods 12 to 18 times before they
accept them, says registered dietitian Susie Jastrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Always introduce a new food served with one of their
favorites,'' Jastrow says. And remember that kids' taste buds are
more sensitive than yours.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is bitter to you, it is 10 times more bitter to them,''
Jastrow says. ``Listen to what they're saying. They usually tell
you the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   What does a trainer's kid eat?
</P>
<P>
   Bob Moore
</P>
<P>
   Job: Personal trainer, owner of Fit Source
</P>
<P>
   Children: Kate, 22; Kevin, 21; Kelly, 12; Kayla, 10, and Colin,
8. (Moore packs lunches for Kelly, Kayla and Colin, although
sometimes he lets them get the school lunch.)
</P>
<P>
   Typical lunch: Turkey sandwich on whole-wheat bread, grapes or
an apple, box of raisins and milk (bought at school).
</P>
<P>
   For a treat: Fig Newtons or cookies
</P>
<P>
   Tip: ``Start them young in treating fruits and vegetables as
dessert-type things.''
</P>
<P>
   What does a nurse's kid eat?
</P>
<P>
   Mary McGill
</P>
<P>
   Job: Registered nurse
</P>
<P>
   Children: Jackson, 9, and Grayson, 4
</P>
<P>
   Typical lunch: Leftover grilled chicken with honey-mustard
dressing sandwiched in a dinner roll, frozen grapes (will defrost
by lunchtime), pretzels, apple slices with peanut butter and a
yogurt smoothie (yogurt, banana and strawberries blended together).
</P>
<P>
   For a treat: Angel food cake with strawberries
</P>
<P>
   Tip: ``My kids love applesauce.'' Buy the small individual
containers of applesauce, McGill says.
</P>
<P>
   What does a school nurse's kid eat?
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Adams
</P>
<P>
   Job: School nurse for Houston, Zilker and Barton Hills
Elementary schools.
</P>
<P>
   Children: Loretta, 2. (Adams packs lunch for Loretta to take to
day care.
</P>
<P>
   Typical lunch: Two ounces of chicken, 4 cucumber slices and 2
tomato wedges.
</P>
<P>
   Tip: ''Sweets should be a treat. A lot of parents pack gummi
bears. That's not OK.''
</P>
<P>
   What does a holistic healer's kid eat?
</P>
<P>
   Gerard Luna
</P>
<P>
   Job: Naturopathic doctor
</P>
<P>
   Children: Rene, 15, and Ari, 8. (The whole family is
vegetarian.)
</P>
<P>
   Typical lunch: Nori roll (made with seasoned rice and nori, the
green seaweed wrapper used for sushi) stuffed with tofu, greens,
cilantro, mint and sunflower sprouts, spring rolls (vegetable rolls
made with rice paper), sliced fruit, nuts or chips and soy or rice
milk.
</P>
<P>
   Tip: ``You need to work with your own kid. It starts at the
grocery store, helping them make healthy choices. Getting them
involved makes them more likely to eat what you do put in their
lunch box.''
</P>
<P>
   What does a dietitian's kid eat?
</P>
<P>
   Marsha Beckermann
</P>
<P>
   Job: Registered dietitian and sports nutritionist, University of
Texas athletic department
</P>
<P>
   Children: Chris, 15 and Daniel, 13 (both play football and
baseball).
</P>
<P>
   Typical lunch: Chris and Daniel usually eat the hot lunch at
school. This is a lunch she would pack for a field trip _ for one
of her sons: two boxes of apple juice (frozen the night before),
two peanut butter and jelly sandwiches, two smoked turkey
sandwiches, banana, apple and a bag of baby carrots.
</P>
<P>
   For a treat: Cranberry fruit newtons or graham crackers.
</P>
<P>
   Tip: ``Some people are so hung up on fat. But there can be some
fat in their meals at noon to get them through four o'clock. Stop
torturing your kids with every fat-free thing at lunch _ they'll be
starving by 2:30. Allow for some cream cheese, allow some yogurt.''
</P>
<P>
   What does a Whole Foods team leader's kid eat?
</P>
<P>
   Mary Couto
</P>
<P>
   Job: Associate nutrition team leader, Whole Foods Gateway
</P>
<P>
   Children: Christina, 24, and Karla, 21
</P>
<P>
   Typical lunch: Karla is lactose-intolerant, so Couto had to
devise ways to build a healthy lunch without any dairy products:
turkey sandwich with soy cheese, blue corn chips, celery sticks
with peanut butter, cut-up watermelon and a box of rice milk.
</P>
<P>
   For a treat: Trail mix with dried fruit and nuts
</P>
<P>
   Tip: ``Smoked tofu is great. You can eat it straight, or heat it
up. Once they taste it, they'll like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tips for packing a healthful school lunch
</P>
<P>
   Be creative. Try a sandwich made with pineapple cream cheese on
a cinnamon raisin bagel, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Pack sandwiches using a variety of whole-grain breads.
</P>
<P>
   Select low-fat milk products, lean meats and water-packed tuna
for lunches.
</P>
<P>
   If your kids want soda pop, try substituting bottled fruit juice
(like black cherry juice) mixed with carbonated water.
</P>
<P>
   Try different green, yellow, red and orange fruits and
vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Replace chips with low-sodium pretzels or a mixture of cereal,
raisins and nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh strawberries are a good source of Vitamin C. Include some
in a small container.
</P>
<P>
   Dried fruit and raisins are great snacks. So is string cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Try including bean dips with chips, carrot sticks and celery
sticks.
</P>
<P>
   Buy 100 percent juice, instead of ``juice drinks,'' which are
mostly sugar, food coloring and water.
</P>
<P>
   In some schools, kids don't get to eat lunch until 1 p.m. Make
sure their breakfast has some protein in it _ nuts, leftover meat
from dinner, eggs or yogurt _ to help them make it to lunchtime.
</P>
<P>
   Wrap a tortilla around your child's favorite fillings and send
that. Or stuff some pita bread with sandwich filling.
</P>
<P>
   Michele Chan Santos is a staff writer for the Austin
American-Statesman, Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
