</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILNER-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thoughts about Modern Library's best books list
 &HT;    By Jay Milner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 100 best English-language novels of the 20th Century, as
drawn by the editorial board of the Modern Library, has been passed
around by the Associated Press and other services causing a lot of
discussion, pro and con, and in between, as was, I'm sure, the
purpose of making the list in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   In case you missed it, the number one novel on that list is
``Ulysses,'' by James Joyce. Number two is ``The Great Gatsby'' by
F. Scott Fitzgerald, and three, four and five are ``A Portrait of
the Artist as a Young Man'' by Joyce, ``Lolita'' by Vladmir
Nabokov, and ``Brave New World'' by Aldous Huxley.
</P>
<P>
   Various newspaper book pages around the country have been asking
staff members and local dignitaries to comment on that list and, in
turn, name their own top five or ten favorite novels of the past
century. I'm a semi-intellectual, former college professor and
current book commentator, but don't really claim to be a full
fledged ``Book Critic'' for a number of reasons, among them that I
haven't read half the books on the Modern Library list. But I do
read a lot, probably more than the average bear, and my top one
hundred English language novels would be a bunch different from the
Modern Library board's.
</P>
<P>
   For example, I definitely would have included in the top one
hundred William Faulkner's Snopes trilogy a ``The Hamlet,'' The
Town'' and ``The Mansion.'' The Modern Library list includes
several Faulker books, but not
</P>
<P>
   those three. Maybe because they are too funny.
</P>
<P>
   I also would include ``To Kill a Mockingbird'' by Harper Lee,
and ``Look Homeward Angel'' by Thomas Wolfe. The latter is a book
that has caused a lot of young folks over the decades to decide to
become avid readers. It's even inspired a few to become writers.
</P>
<P>
   Also, I would include the Border Trilogy by Cormac McCarthy of
El Paso, and ``Cold Mountain'' by Charles Frazier, although both
are so current some ``critics'' are reluctant to pass judgment
until they'd been around longer.
</P>
<P>
   I've never been one who believed a book had to be several
generations old before it could be judged properly, although I see
what they mean when some say that.
</P>
<P>
   The Modern Library list includes Jack London's ``Call of the
Wild.'' I guess I'd go along with that, although I read London's
other Klondike adventure, ``White Fang,'' first and have always
loved it best; so, I would sub it for ``Call of the Wild.'' But
that's nit-picking.
</P>
<P>
   I also would include at least one Larry McMurtry novel a
probably ``Lonesome Dove,'' although, in my mind, it's a close race
with ``Leaving Cheyenne.'' So, maybe I would put both on my best
one hundred list. Why not?
</P>
<P>
   I'd also add the late Billie Lee Brammer's ``Gay Place.'' I
agree with the Modern-Library board's selection of Robert Penn
Warren's Louisiana political thriller ``All the King's Men,'' but
would argue that Brammer's Texas
</P>
<P>
   political epic belongs there, too.
</P>
<P>
   And how about F. Scott Fitzgerald's ``The Great Gatsby'' being
picked way up there at number two? If you are one of those who
believes F. Scott was too popular or shallow to be rated so high on
a list of best novels of the past century, you should go back and
read Gatsby again. It is, indeed, a gem. I might even move it up
one to first place.
</P>
<P>
   If that statement causes you to frown, do as I suggested above.
Read it again. And remember it isn't just that Robert Whathisname
movie. It's a novel.
</P>
<P>
   If you disagree with any or all of the above, don't hesitate to
drop me a line at this newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Milner writes for the Lufkin Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
