A1942 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-PARADISE14-COX     08-13 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-PARADISE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Movie review: Point of `Return to Paradise' is lost
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm not sure what the monetary unit of Malaysia is, but I know a
movie as phony as a three-dollar bill when I see it.
</P>
<P>
   That would be ``Return to Paradise,'' a preposterous morality
tale about three reckless American college graduates who frolic
around Malaysia getting high, before idealistic Lewis (Joaquin
Phoenix) stays behind and the other two, Sheriff (Vince Vaughn) and
Tony (David Conrad), return to the States.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, the returnees are informed by a cagey lawyer
named Beth (Anne Heche) that Lewis was found with their joint stash
of hashish, arrested, accused of dealing drugs and is about to be
executed. The only way they can save him is to return to Penang and
share the responsibility in a Third World hellhole of a jail. As a
plot convenience, they have only eight days to make up their minds
and save Lewis' life.
</P>
<P>
   Written by Wesley Strick (``Cape Fear'') and Bruce Robinson
(``The Killing Fields''), based on a 1990 French film, ``Return to
Paradise'' features clumsily conceived, inconsistent characters
whose motivations are alternately transparent and downright opaque.
Cinematic paradise, it ain't.
</P>
<P>
   At first, docile, high-minded Tony dutifully agrees to go back,
while irresponsible Sheriff wants no part of it. Beth _ whose
motives for being involved in the case remain annoyingly unclear
for too long, then prove patly personal _ despises Sheriff for his
lack of conscience and sense of obligation. At least she does until
she falls in love and sleeps with him. Such affection fogs
Sheriff's brain enough to change his mind, convincing him to give
himself up to Malaysian justice. Then it is Tony's turn to get cold
feet.
</P>
<P>
   For a little media-bashing, there's a persistent newspaper
reporter (Jada Pinkett Smith) on the trail of the story. She wants
the scoop badly and will gleefully jeopardize Lewis' welfare to get
it. Chances are you not only won't like any of these characters,
but you won't understand their actions well enough to care much
about them.
</P>
<P>
   Directing this muddle is Joseph Ruben (``Sleeping With the
Enemy''), who never develops the necessary tension of the deadline
negotiations. Nor does he have much patience for the details and
texture that might have lent this tale some credibility.
</P>
<P>
   As the attorney with a hefty expense account, Heche does do some
acting: Her cool cracks on cue, and she gets to play overwrought a
lot. But no amount of fevered expressions can convince us that Beth
would be suddenly, hopelessly attracted to Sheriff. Vaughn and
Conrad are perfectly adequate, though occasionally interchangeable.
And while the captive Phoenix doesn't have as much screen time as
his pals, he gets to emote wildly in a scene that demonstrates his
tenuous hold on reality.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, there's a gripping movie in this ``Midnight
Express''-like story of life choices, friendship and personal
responsibility. Too bad ``Return to Paradise'' isn't it.
</P>
<P>
   Hap Erstein writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
