A1943 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNGRESTLESS-WRITER1     08-13 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNGRESTLESS-WRITER14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `There's no story too tough to tell'
 &HT;    By Loretta Grantham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Kay Alden knows everything. Everything.
</P>
<P>
   Like if Mrs. Chancellor's going to lose the mansion! If Neil's
going to tell Dru to take a hike! If Miguel's going to learn that
Veronica's really the murderous maid! If Grace is going to lure
Nicholas into the sack!
</P>
<P>
   Alden, head writer of ``The Young and the Restless,'' has been
with the show since 1974.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had the luxury of getting to know some people without
them knowing what I do,'' says the Chicago-based mother of three.
``I think some of them think I don't work because I have such a
flexible schedule and can go to most of the kids' things.''
</P>
<P>
   The perfect cover to spy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh no, it's not like that,'' says Alden, laughing. ``It's very
rare that you just lift a situation straight out of real life. The
minute you put a story into the show, it becomes the characters'
story.''
</P>
<P>
   Alden _ a Kansas native who started watching ``As the World
Turns'' at age 12 _ was a doctoral candidate at the University of
Wisconsin when she met ``Young and Restless'' creator Bill Bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was doing a dissertation on daytime TV as a mediator of
social change, so I called him for an interview. I remember being
amazed that he answered his own phone and agreed to talk to me.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, Bell returned the call with a job offer.
</P>
<P>
   Alden leads conference calls each week with writers in L.A., New
York and Hawaii. After they devise story lines for about five or
six shows, their scripts are sent to another stable of writers who
fill in details, add production notes and research minutiae ``like
finding out Victoria's middle name because we'd forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   Answer: Nicole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young and Restless'' head writer Kay Alden on:
</P>
<P>
   Which role she'd portray if she were an actress: `If I could
play any character, it would be Nikki (who debuted in 1978 and is
now married _ again _ to tycoon Victor Newman). I've been with her
for so long, and what I love about the character is how she's
evolved. When she was young, she was remarkably egocentric. We've
watched Nikki grow up and develop compassion, yet she still hasn't
lost her fire.'
</P>
<P>
   A common soap device _ amnesia: `It became such an industry
standard for a while that I found myself cringing when we used it,
but the thing that makes it so irresistible is that it allows
characters to do the ultimate search into themselves. At various
points in our lives, we've all felt that need. It's not just about
some poor sucker who lost his memory. It's about rediscovering an
identity.'
</P>
<P>
   Tackling tough issues on the show: `I believe that if you
construct a story on an issue that is compelling and involves
characters that your audience is committed to, there's no story too
tough to tell. One of the huge, huge values of daytime television
is its ability to educate people about what's going on. The first
divorce I ever had contact with was on As the World Turns when I
was a kid.'
</P>
<P>
   Loretta Grantham writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
