<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 11:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1945 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNGRESTLESS-MAIN14-     08-13 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNGRESTLESS-MAIN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Why the Young and the Restless never gets old
 &HT;    By Loretta Grantham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Imagine swinging a sledgehammer every
day at the fair and hitting the bell every time for 10 years. Not
only that, but you wow the same spectators into returning again and
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Young and the Restless,'' in a sense, has done just that.
This month, the CBS soap is celebrating 500 consecutive weeks _
nearly a decade _ as TV's No. 1 serial.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bell, who cut his teeth writing for ``Days of Our Lives,''
created the show _ originally titled ``The Innocent Years'' _ with
his wife, Lee. But the pair then decided that political
assassinations and Vietnam had stripped America of its naivete, so
they opted for youth and angst.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Young and the Restless,'' which debuted in 1973 and has
won an unprecedented five Emmys for best daytime drama, also boasts
many soap opera firsts _ a rape (Chris Brooks), a vasectomy (Victor
Newman) and a case of bulimia (Traci Abbott), just to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, tackling tough issues is part of what propelled ``Y&AMP;R''
to the top, along with glamorous locales, hip background music and
relentless attention to detail (such as each character having a
driver license from Genoa City, Wis., in case a wallet is opened on
set).
</P>
<P>
   The main draw, though, is endearing characters _ folks so
complex and confused that you can't help but stay curious.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you write a soap, you're obviously never done,'' says
head writer Kay Alden, who joined the show in 1974. ``But if you
construct a story that involves characters your viewers are
committed to, they'll always come back for more.''
</P>
<P>
   `God, I feel so restless'
</P>
<P>
   _ On March 26, 1973, medical student Snapper Foster lent an ear
to his waitress friend, Sally McGuire, who speaks the soap's very
first words: ``Kind of a drag, isn't it? Stuck in a place like
Genoa City.'' (Pause.) ``God, I feel so restless.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Genoa City, Wis., really exists. ``Young and Restless''
creators Bill and Lee Bell borrowed the name after driving through
the wee town on the way from Chicago to their weekend house in Lake
Geneva, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Young and the Restless'' theme song _ dubbed ``Nadia's
Theme'' after Olympic gymnast Nadia Comaneci performed a floor
routine to it in 1976 _ was originally titled ``Cotton's Theme'' in
the film ``Bless the Beasts and the Children.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Tom Selleck starred as Jed Andrews from 1975-76, and David
Hasselhoff played Snapper Foster from 1975-82. Lake Worth, Fla.,
native Deidre Hall (now Marlena Evans Brady on ``Days of Our
Lives'') was Barbara Anderson from 1973-75.
</P>
<P>
   Nuts that bolted: they came, they killed, they split Genoa City
</P>
<P>
   David Kimble (Michael Corbett)
</P>
<P>
   When we met secretary David Kimble in 1986, he seemed so
mild-mannered. But once he found out heiress Nina Chancellor was
worth the big bucks, he schemed to marry her _ and vowed to cut up
anybody who got in his way (i.e., Cricket Blair). Turns out ol'
David had killed his former wife, who also was an heiress. Nina
discovered David's evil past, so he faked his death and went to a
plastic surgeon for a new face. (``Can you make me look like David
Hasselhoff?'' he asked.) The all-knowing doc, however, emblazoned
the word KILLER on his forehead. And to make a long story short,
literally, David left _ for good _ after being compacted in a trash
chute.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Carter (Kimberlin Brown)
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Carter was an intermittent whacko, appearing first in
1990, then from 1992-93, then in 1995. First she stole Lauren
Fenmore's husband, Dr. Scott Grainger, by seducing him, faking a
pregnancy and swapping Lauren's baby (fathered by Scott) with one
she'd gotten off the black market. Then she kidnapped Lauren and
was about to murder her when a fire broke out in the Carter
farmhouse, killing a groundskeeper. Sheila even plotted to slay her
mom, who tried to tell Lauren the truth but couldn't because she'd
had a stroke and was unable to speak. Folks assumed Sheila died in
the blaze, but au contraire. She ran off to L.A. and is now on
``Y&AMP;R's'' sister show, ``The Bold and the Beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Loretta Grantham writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
