<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNGRESTLESS-HOOKED14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Why i'm hooked on `The Young and the Restless'
 &HT;    By Loretta Grantham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, FLA. _ I know it's not real. I don't care.
</P>
<P>
   What it is, my friends, is consistent.
</P>
<P>
   Day in and day out, Genoa City, Wis., home of ``The Young and
the Restless,'' awaits me _ 60 minutes of exaggerated escapism, 40
minutes or so if you skip the commercials. Beautiful people,
outrageous scenarios, always there.
</P>
<P>
   Same time, same place.
</P>
<P>
   I was just 8 years old when I met grande dame Mrs. Chancellor,
and 25 years later, I still can't bring myself to call her
Katherine, let alone Kay.
</P>
<P>
   I turned into a teen the year ingenue Nikki Reed appeared, then
three years later, I got my driver license when virile Victor
Newman debuted. As I came of age, those two fell in love.
</P>
<P>
   And within those 8 years, my address changed three times:
</P>
<P>
   Croton Drive.
</P>
<P>
   Felton Lane.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Street.
</P>
<P>
   Because my Dad, you see, was an Army man. From pillar to post,
they say.
</P>
<P>
   But folks in Genoa City stayed put. Or at least a few of them
did _ like Mrs. C., Nikki and Victor.
</P>
<P>
   I moved to Florida in 1987, the same year dapper Rex Sterling
turned up, along with loon du jour Leanna Love.
</P>
<P>
   And although this pair left the show years ago, they remain
loosely linked to that milestone in my life. So, too, does young
mom Sharon Collins, whom I encountered the year I hit 30. As she
bagged a buff Newman heir for a husband, I began to wonder about a
white picket fence of my own.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Young and the Restless,'' to me, is a ritual. A time to
plop down, turn off and zone out _ like a four-hour Sunday football
epic split into five weekday bits.
</P>
<P>
   Throw me the remote, get out of my face, my team is on. And if I
forget to set the VCR, I kick myself _ but just a tad. You see,
there's always tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Same time, same place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Young and the Respite.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hardly rocket science. There's no far-flung relevance here.
Just something to banter about with my mom and sisters, and a
chuckle to share with a colleague or two.
</P>
<P>
   Like me, these women know it's not real. And like me, they
couldn't care less.
</P>
<P>
   Loretta Grantham is a staff writer for the Palm Beach Post, West
Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
