<HEADER>
A1950 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLUMS-REVIEW-LADN     08-13 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLUMS-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEVERLY HILLS COMEDY GOES SLUMMING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 1{ Stars 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Breasts! First-time filmmaker Tamara Jenkins seems
obsessed by them in her clunky, screwball family story, ``Slums of
Beverly Hills.'' If her characters aren't flashing them or asking
guys to touch them, then they're talking about them, constantly,
incessantly, pointlessly. It's a fixation that Joe Bob Briggs would
love _ for about five minutes _ until he realized, like the rest of
us, that there's not a whole lot more to the movie.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Slums of Beverly Hills,'' Jenkins is looking to tell a
poignant, funny, coming-of-age story about the Abramowitz family,
Jewish Joads who move from one crummy, two-story stucco apartment
building to another on the outskirts of Beverly Hills during the
mid-1970s. Father Murray (Alan Arkin) is looking for the good life,
but success seems always around the corner, just out of reach.
Murray has three kids, the suddenly bosomy 15-year-old daughter,
Vivian (Natasha Lyonne); and two sons, Ben (David Krumholtz) and
Rickey (Eli Marienthal), who spend most of their free time staring
at their sister's breasts. (Did they get bigger overnight?)
</P>
<P>
   Murray, who is old enough to often be called the kids'
grandfather, wants to keep the family in the Beverly Hills School
District. ``Furniture is temporary, education is forever,'' he
says. (Never mind that we never once see the kids talk about school
or do any homework. Maybe they're on vacation. Who knows?)
</P>
<P>
   Murray's problem is that he's always running a little short on
cash. So when he learns that his brother's screw-up daughter, Rita
(Marisa Tomei), has escaped from rehab (again), he decides to find
her and take her under his wing _ in return for ample monthly
compensation.
</P>
<P>
   The movie focuses primarily on Vivian and her breasts and her
discomfort over what puberty has wrought. (The '70s backdrop adds
little to the film, other than the music on the soundtrack.) Having
Rita in the house gives Vivian the perfect role model for what NOT
to do and also gives her a chance to learn more about vibrators,
menstruation and tampons. Jenkins, who also wrote the screenplay,
manages the occasional insight into adolescent self-image, and her
script has plenty of good ideas. She just doesn't ably execute many
of them.
</P>
<P>
   The film's fatal flaw is the flat tone of its comic scenes.
Example: Late in the movie a character overdoses on pills, the
paramedics arrive and, yup, high jinks ensue. It takes a great deal
of skill to pull something like this off for laughs and not just
have the audience sit there, mouths scraping the floor, wondering
what in the name of God they're supposed to be feeling.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, it's the Kooky Family Syndrome, all over again.
Contrary to what a lot of filmmakers think, kooky behavior isn't
inherently funny _ even if your message is that kookiness is OK
because, shucks, we're a family. (Nor does the overused comic ploy
of the sing-along always work, but that's an altogether different
gripe about this movie.) Great comedy can come from fully formed
characters, but those are in short supply here. The family's
yearnings for the good life are never adequately thought out or
explored.
</P>
<P>
   We're left, then, with breasts. I never thought I'd use Susan
Skoog's recent coming-of-age yarn, ``Whatever,'' as a benchmark,
but at least in that film, you had a young woman coming to grips
with her adolescence in ways that rang true. And ``Whatever''
didn't need four close-up cleavage shots to make its point. For
some reason, ``Slums of Beverly Hills'' did. Not only were the
shots unnecessary, they were clumsily inserted close-ups of obvious
body doubles whose breasts looked quite a bit bigger than those of
Lyonne and Tomei. (Now she's got me obsessing about breasts.)
</P>
<P>
   Lyonne certainly proves herself game for the raunch. With her
tube socks and halter tops, Lyonne's Vivian looks like an early
incarnation of Roller Girl from ``Boogie Nights.'' The actress
convincingly conveys her character's malaise and enthusiastically
jumps into a scene that calls for her and Tomei to dance in their
nighties and whip around a vibrator to the thumping backbeat of
Parliament's ``Give Up the Funk.'' It's too bad the movie doesn't
pull out of its funk often enough to reward such a brave
performance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
