<HEADER>
A1952 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RETURN-REVIEW-LADN     08-13 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETURN-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORAL DILEMMA... AND A MOVIE, TOO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 2{ Stars 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Say you're a swinging, young, good-looking guy
and, a couple of years back, you took a memorable vacation to
Malaysia where you enjoyed a good solid month of rum, girls and
fine, cheap hash.
</P>
<P>
   And say in your haste to leave the country and make your flight,
you dumped the leftover pot in the garbage and waved goodbye to
Malaysia and farewell to your tree-hugging buddy who was staying
behind to, yes, save the orangutans. And say the local police found
the hash, prosecuted the tree-hugger and sentenced him to death ...
unless _ and it's a big unless _ you return to Malaysia and serve
time in a sinkhole jail.
</P>
<P>
   That's the provocative premise of ``Return to Paradise,'' a
movie that pokes, prods and nudges you throughout its two hours,
practically begging you to answer the question: What would YOU do?
</P>
<P>
   Sad to say, though, the filmmakers have decided that the core
moral dilemma isn't enough to sustain interest and have added
creaky plot contrivances and the year's worst tacked-on love story
to dilute what could have been a pretty good film. That's not to
say that you'll leave ``Paradise'' feeling ripped off. You'll just
wish the writers and directors had respected your intelligence a
little more.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff (Vince Vaughn) and Tony (David Conrad) are the two young
dudes who left Malaysia and returned to their normal lives in New
York only to find, two years later, that their other vacation
buddy, Lewis (Joaquin Phoenix), has been jailed as a drug
trafficker. Lewis' attorney, Beth (Anne Heche), tells the boys that
unless they are willing to return to Malaysia, serve three years
apiece (or one can go back and do six years), Lewis will be
executed. The thing is, THEY ONLY HAVE EIGHT DAYS TO DECIDE! This
after some 700 days have passed since Lewis was incarcerated.
</P>
<P>
   The time frame is an obvious artificial device designed by
director Joseph Rubin (``Sleeping With the Enemy,'' ``The Good
Son'') and writers Wesley Strick and Bruce Robinson to create some
excitement. But the basic story generates enough interest. It's
simply not necessary to keep adding subplots, like having a
newspaper reporter (Jada Pinkett Smith) threatening to break the
story and, in so doing, likely expedite Lewis' execution. It's a
false note _ among many _ that submarines the movie's dramatic
thrust.
</P>
<P>
   The actors do their best with their one-note characters. Conrad
plays the Golden Boy, the guy with the beautiful fiancee, cool
apartment and the most to lose by going back. Phoenix is the
Sensitive Soul who now faces death. Heche has little to do but look
determined, while Vaughn is the cynical cool cat who must face the
hard truths about his abandoned ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the contrivances, there is a certain
inevitability to the film because, if the boys don't go back, there
wouldn't be a movie, would there? That plain fact deflates much of
the manufactured suspense. That it doesn't ruin the film
underscores the movie's inherent strengths _ its actors and its
what-would-you-do? dramatic premise. Other than that, it's
``Paradise'' lost.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 1130EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 11:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1960 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STELLA-REVIEW-LADN     08-13 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STELLA-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STELLA' RIPPLES WITH ROMANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
Our rating: 3 Stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _Like its predecessor ``Waiting to Exhale,'' ``How
Stella Got Her Groove Back'' is a luxuriously appointed soap opera
with just enough sass to make it seem like something more.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps its main plus, in what's emerging as the Terry McMillan
tradition (she adapted both films from her novels, with the help of
screenwriter Ron Bass), ``Stella'' cannily fills an empty niche in
the women's picture world.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Exhale'' was the first major movie to focus on the romantic
travails of middle-class African-American women, ``Groove'' is the
first Hollywood film in a long time to suggest that mature women
can find real happiness with younger men. An impossibly idealized
younger man, in this case, who makes a lot of the trepidation that
goes with ``Groove's'' main move rather unconvincing. But what the
heck? Men have enjoyed this particular movie fantasy for decades,
and there's no denying that this show looks real good viewed from
the feminine perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Angela Bassett plays Stella, who's pretty ideal herself. She's a
40-year-old San Francisco stockbroker who works hard, works out
harder and takes excellent care of her son, Quincy (Michael J.
Pagan), her troublesome sisters Vanessa (``Jerry Maguire's'' Regina
King) and Angela (Suzzanne Douglas), and even her ex-husband's
feelings. Of course, like most fictional superwomen, she has no
time for self-fulfillment (scenes in the book involving a casual
lover were filmed with Danny Glover, but excised from the movie's
final cut).
</P>
<P>
   On an atypical impulse, Stella goes on a Jamaican vacation with
her best friend Delilah (Whoopi Goldberg). Delilah is one of those
earthy, man-hungry, life-affirming movie persons who both
embarrasses and encourages her uptight friend to get a little
looser. But it's the incredibly attractive local fellow Winston
(newcomer Taye Diggs) who really gets the job done.
</P>
<P>
   The son, conveniently, of a respectable doctor, Winston is not
only well-raised but, even more conveniently, at that age (20)
where committing to a career path is less important than, well,
fulfilling Stella's every fantasy. Sincere, patient, a little naive
(which can be a good thing, too) and effortlessly charming,
Winston's even cute when he complains about Stella's mild acts of
condescension _ which are the only things he ever complains about.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the big problems here stem from others' judgments of
Stella's judgment. But the naysaying characters aren't privy to the
shower scene in which lucky audiences get to ogle Winston. It's all
the proof anybody needs that Stella, too, is of eminently sound
mind and body.
</P>
<P>
   Director Kevin Rodney Sullivan, a former actor making his
big-screen debut, keeps things plush, posh and lazily sensual. The
Jamaican sequences come close to feeling like an actual tropical
vacation, while the stateside shots outdo even ``The Parent Trap''
remake in the architectural eye candy and interior decoration
departments.
</P>
<P>
   And Sullivan keeps the performances real, even when the material
gets repetitive and contrived. Yes, there's the ``touching'' death
of a ``beloved'' side character. Indeed, the film's comic relief
oscillates between too broad at some points and too arch at others.
And of course, the story climaxes on the same, forced Hollywood
note as every other commercial romance of the last dozen years.
</P>
<P>
   Flawed as it is, though, ``Groove'' nevertheless charms the
pants off you as effectively as Winston does Stella. And unlike
him, the movie, at least, has flaws it has to work past.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 1134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 11:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1993 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-CLINTON-STAKES-$A     08-13 1902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-CLINTON-STAKES-$ADV16 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE STAKES AS CLINTON TESTIFIES: A PRESIDENCY ENDED OR A
PRESIDENCY DERAILED?
 &HT;    DUPLICATION ALERT: Moving in (w) Washington and (k) commentary
categories
 &HT;    Advance for release Sunday, August 16 
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ His advisors are among the wisest that money and
prestige can secure. He commands the mightiest army the world has
ever known, and he's the undisputed and twice-elected leader of the
last remaining superpower.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, on the eve of what history may well record as the
defining moment of his complex career, William Jefferson Clinton is
a man largely on his own, soberly pondering an excruciating
political, legal and moral calculus upon which may rest his
presidency and his legacy.
</P>
<P>
   After seven torturous months of first denying and then dodging
charges of carnal relations with a former White House intern, the
president is wandering the peril-strewn wilderness of the
conscience, where the centrist compass that has guided his
breathtaking political journey for more than three decades is
suddenly, terrifyingly, useless.
</P>
<P>
   The search for common ground, after all, can be a very different
enterprise than the quest for truth.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one wants to get this matter behind us more than I do _
except maybe all the rest of the American people,'' President
Clinton told reporters at the White House recently, in the only
public comment he's made about his plans to testify on Monday about
his relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am looking forward to the opportunity in the next few days
of testifying,'' Clinton asserted. ''I will do so completely and
truthfully. I am anxious to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Precisely what Clinton plans to tell independent counsel Kenneth
Starr and, via a closed circuit television feed, a federal grand
jury, isn't publicly known. Nor is it clear whether Clinton intends
to share his testimony with the American people, either through a
speech or news conference, or whether he simply plans to testify
behind closed doors and board Air Force One without a public word
to begin his two-week Martha's Vineyard vacation.
</P>
<P>
   What is certain is that, whether Monday becomes seen as
Clinton's moment of truth, whether he emerges in the guise of Slick
Willie or the Comeback Kid, the greatest immediate threat he faces
is not so much a presidency ended, but rather a presidency
derailed. What's at risk for Clinton is nothing less than the very
heart and soul of his success _ his ability to lead from the
center.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of politics revolves around approval and personal
credibility,'' said political scientist Michael Johnston, ''and
that's very much at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   In his rise from obscurity in an Arkansas backwater to the
pinnacle of international power, no gift has served Clinton better
than his knack for combing the counsel of a diverse array of
sources and divining from it all the vital center, the ideological
ground zero. From there, he has repeatedly crafted a working
consensus, employing the combination of rhetorical brilliance and
persuasive genius that have made him, for better or worse, the most
compelling politician of his generation.
</P>
<P>
   As president, he has melded his talents with the times, and
often with notable success, deploying U.S. troops to restore
democracy to Haiti over the objections of a reluctant Congress;
resisting tax cuts and rampant spending to help balance the federal
budget for the first time in three decades; and mixing aggressive
diplomacy with NATO air strikes in Bosnia to end Europe's bloodiest
conflict since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   He's been rewarded with remarkable popularity _ a 68 percent job
approval rating, at last tally _ and a national mood of optimism
both reflected in and buoyed by a soaring economy and the greatest
bull market ever to stampede Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton could simply climb on the back of public consensus
and be hoisted out of his current quagmire, however, he would have
done so long ago. He's not stuck on some split-the-difference
policy matter this time; he's tangled in a legal and political web
with no clear exit.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's gotten himself into a dilemma for which there is no easy
answer,'' said Larry Sabato, director of the Center for
Governmental Studies at the University of Virginia in
Charlottesville.
</P>
<P>
   And, while any immediate potential legal threats to Clinton
appear eminently defendable, perhaps even ultimately winnable, the
effectiveness of the presidency has always depended far more upon
moral authority _ simple public trust _ than merely on skirting the
letter of the law.
</P>
<P>
   ''It terms of the wrongdoing that's out on the table now, we're
talking about fairly dishonorable but reasonably small stuff,''
said Johnston, author of the book ''Political Corruption and Public
Policy in America,'' and a professor at Colgate University, in
Hamilton, N.Y. ''In political terms, it's a very large scandal. He
is in real trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Jan. 21 when allegations first surfaced that Clinton had
an Oval Office affair with Lewinsky, then later urged her to lie
about it under oath.
</P>
<P>
   At first Clinton was staggered by the blow, telling reporters
the next day that there were ''legitimate,'' questions about his
relationship with Lewinsky and that the American people deserved an
explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will give you as many answers as we can,'' Clinton vowed.
''I'd like for you to have more rather than less, sooner rather
than later.''
</P>
<P>
   Within days Clinton reversed course, opting to explain nothing
about what was, beyond dispute, an extraordinary relationship with
a young intern. Instead, he delivered a comprehensive and emphatic
denial of any wrongdoing, then suggested Americans just forget the
whole thing.
</P>
<P>
   ''I did not have sexual relations with that woman, Miss
Lewinsky,'' Clinton declared forcefully in televised remarks from
the Roosevelt Room, as First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton nodded her
approval. ''I never told anybody to lie, not a single time. Never.
These allegations are false, and I need to go back to work for the
American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus began a strategy of denial, stonewalling and lambasting his
leading tormentor, Starr, the federal prosecutor and former judge
who went on to conduct the most intensive _ some say invasive _
investigation in history of the personal life of an American
president.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton launched into a frenzy of activity, all painstakingly
choreographed for the widest possible media coverage, speaking
about crime or education one day, Social Security the next, and
traveling to Africa, Latin America, Europe, China and, early next
month, to Russia, hoping to demonstrate beyond question that he had
indeed gone ''back to work for the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   The facts are a bit more complicated.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his often touted penchant for compartmentalization,
Clinton has been a president diminished by the cloud of suspicion
hanging over him this year, sharply withdrawing from the press _
his key conduit to the American people _ and spending countless
hours and incalculable energy consulting with lawyers on
scandal-aversion tactics, instead of concentrating on the state of
the union.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unfortunately, I suppose, we have great experience at
soldiering on through these kinds of personal attacks,'' White
House political counselor Paul Begala said, insisting that the
White House staff remains focused on substance, despite the
constant distraction of the Lewinsky case.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not pleasant,'' Begala said of the controversy, ''but
it's not paralyzing.''
</P>
<P>
   The image of a man hard at work on global as well as bread and
butter issues, in fact, coupled with the drumbeat of White House
attacks against Starr, even seems to have convinced many Americans
that Clinton is being unfairly persecuted.
</P>
<P>
   ''He calls it the politics of personal destruction,'' said
Begala. ''The best way to respond is to rise above it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's problem is that Lewinsky has reportedly contradicted
him, testifying in graphic detail to an alleged White House affair
she claims lasted more than a year. She reportedly says a dress
that is being examined by the FBI contains physical evidence of an
encounter with Clinton. And Starr is expected to file an exhaustive
report to Congress, possibly within weeks, detailing what else he
has learned of the Clinton-Lewinsky relationship through his
examination of U.S. Secret Service agents and a host of Clinton
compatriots and confidantes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's aides have said repeatedly they know of no reason for
him not to stick to his earlier denial, which he has also told
under oath to a grand jury investigating the claim by former
Arkansas state employee Paula Jones that Clinton, while governor,
propositioned her in a Little Rock hotel. Clinton's lawyers have
denied Jones' charges and her suit has been dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Pointedly, however, Clinton has not repeated his denial of the
Lewinsky matter publicly for weeks, not even when he addressed the
controversy earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   It surely hasn't helped Clinton that he has become more isolated
on the matter as the case has dragged on.
</P>
<P>
   Recent court rulings, in effect, prevent him from confiding in
even his closest staff members and White House attorneys, leaving
the normally wide-ranging Clinton free to seek confidential counsel
only from his wife and the three private attorneys he has hired _
David Kendall, Nicole Seligman and Mickey Kantor.
</P>
<P>
   Even if they weren't billing him by the hour, this is not how
Clinton prefers to make decisions.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton has been truthful, certainly, he has nothing to fear
from the dress, the inquiry or even the personal testimony of
Lewinsky, a self-acknowledged liar .
</P>
<P>
   If Starr can make a convincing, evidence-backed case, however,
that Clinton hasn't told the truth _ either in his sworn deposition
or in his blanket public denial last January _ the politics of
personal destruction could quickly take on new poignancy.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Clinton were to address the nation and say 'I lied in the
Paula Jones deposition,' the republic would have to reflect on what
that means, to commit perjury, which is a felony,'' said William
Reynolds, professor of law at the University of Maryland. ''That,''
said Reynolds, ''is a serious problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, said Reynolds, a country blessed by peace and
prosperity would forgive a contrite Clinton, and, absent public
outrage, the likelihood of impeachment would appear dim.
</P>
<P>
   ''But,'' Reynolds quickly injected, ''I don't think he's a man
who can come clean with the nation if it hurts him. I think he is a
man who is incapable of telling the truth if it hurts him.''
</P>
<P>
   It is that perception, that overarching lack of public trust,
far more than the risk of impeachment, that threatens to undermine
what's left of Clinton's second term.
</P>
<P>
   Seven months of evasion, coupled with lingering questions over
Clinton's plans for Monday, have already left many, like Sabato,
cold.
</P>
<P>
   ''It tells us that maybe we don't know him nearly as well as we
thought we did, and the whole Monica Lewinsky thing makes me think
that I don't want to know him,'' said Sabato. ''I think most
Americans feel that way _ the less I know him, the happier I am.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans is the White House correspondent for Cox Newspapers)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
