<SLUG> BC-TV-FELICITY-$ADV16-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAPPY TOGETHER: `FELICITY' AND THE WB HOPE TO OUT-FOX FOX 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 16)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Hollywood dictates this: When you pitch a
television show, you have to have a comparison, such as ``It's like
Bataan, but a musical,'' or ``It's a cross between `Father Knows
Best' and `Silence of the Lambs.'''
</P>
<P>
   Which leads us to ``Felicity,'' a one-hour drama premiering this
fall on the WB network (Tuesdays, 9 to 10 p.m. Eastern, premieres
Sept. 29). With regret, the shorthand for this show would have to
be ``Ally McBeal and Her So-Called Life Go to College.''
</P>
<P>
   This drama could suffer by comparison to the one-hour Fox comedy
and the powerful but brief ``My So-Called Life.'' Then again, if an
audience is actually drawn in by the comparisons to this drama,
odds are it will stick around after its individuality emerges.
</P>
<P>
   There have been some rumblings that the ``Felicity'' camp is not
too happy with the ``Ally'' comparisons, yet 22-year-old star Kerri
Russell takes them at face value _ and draws distinctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a compliment. It is a huge compliment,'' she said at a
recent network party. ``It's groundbreaking for its genre. It's a
smart show. I'm glad to be compared to a smart show.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only difference is `Ally McBeal' has that great fantasy
element, and our show doesn't have that,'' she continued. ``I
wouldn't want (the audience) to be let down. We're a drama.''
</P>
<P>
   A good drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``Felicity'' may be one show that ABC will regret having passed
on, which it did before WB picked it up. One of the most polished
pilots of the new season, the show has the potential to be a hit
for the WB and its effort to out-youth Fox and go after Generation
Xers' younger brothers and sisters.
</P>
<P>
   The show should twin perfectly with ``Dawson's Creek'' (which
moves to Wednesdays at 8 p.m.) in attracting young viewers to the
WB. Just to make sure the established show's audience finds
``Felicity,'' Scott Foley, who played star quarterback Cliff on
``Dawson's,'' moves over to ``Felicity'' to play a geeky,
love-struck college resident assistant.
</P>
<P>
   The premise for the show is this: Felicity Porter is a
California good girl who plans on following dad's example and
become a doctor. At her graduation she comes across Ben Covington,
whom she always had an eye for but never had the guts to meet. In
signing Felicity's yearbook he admits that he, too, wishes they had
become friends. Is this a nice gesture? Something more? Felicity
has to know.
</P>
<P>
   So after finding out Ben is going to a New York City university
(a poorly disguised New York University), Porter shelves pre-med
and Stanford and on a lark heads off to New York, too, much to the
ire of her parents.
</P>
<P>
   Spur of the moment, irresponsible and irrational. The people who
got their cackles crinkled over ``Ally'' are going to be equally
ticked off by ``Felicity.'' What kind of message is this, you may
ask yet again? Are all women brainless ditzes? But don't be fooled:
This is not a McBeal knock-off.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, it is a coming-of-age story stylishly done with college
life and New York City as a backdrop. As for a character having to
be a role model, ask yourself a question: How together was your act
when you were 17?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you, too, would have taken off after a potential love.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mistake that she makes,'' said co-executive producer
and creator J.J. Abrams, who along with fellow 32-year-old partner
Matt Reeves has a film background (including writing the
anti-Felicity flick ``Armageddon.'') ``The character even says that
in the show. There's a much bigger reason why she ends up
staying.''
</P>
<P>
   McBeal caused a firestorm when the character somehow became the
poster woman for post-modern feminism. McBeal star Calista
Flockhart, who, like Russell, wants to remind people that her
character is just that, a piece of fiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just an actress trying to play a part,'' Flockhart said.
``There's no denying that people are thinking of Ally as a role
model.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, ``Felicity'' does _ but only to a point.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. E-mail:
mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
