r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-NOTES14-COX     08-13 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NOTES14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia couple serve entree spiced with crime
 &HT;    By Don O'Braint
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Buoyed by the success of Diane Mott Davidson's culinary
mysteries such as ``Death by Chocolate,'' crime novels that feature
recipes or descriptions of food have become as ubiquitous as creme
brulee or calamari. The latest entree in the genre is ``Go Close
Against the Enemy'' (St. Martin's, $23.95) by an Athens, Ga.
couple, Takis and Judy Iakovou.
</P>
<P>
   The sleuths in this series are Nick and Julia Lambros, owners of
a restaurant in a college town called Delphi. ``He's olive oil,
she's vinegar,'' says Judy Iakovou, describing their fictional
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Like the authors, Nick is a Greek immigrant married to an
American woman. The Iakovous, former proprietors of Zorba's in
Athens, own the Checkered Cloth Cafe in Arnoldsville and the Silver
Screen Grill in Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   Being a restaurateur is a lot like being a bartender, says
Takis, 48. ``Your regular customers become almost like a family,
and they tell you all about their lives and their experiences. Of
course, we're careful not to abuse confidences. The people we meet
and the stories they tell us become like ingredients in a recipe.
You mix them all up, and the final product is something entirely
different.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple's 1996 debut novel, ``So Dear to Wicked Men,''
focused on immigration, but the second in their series deals with
latent racism in the South: When a young interracial couple
attempts to bury its stillborn baby in the ``white'' cemetery,
deacon Walter Fry protests. An altercation between the deacon and
the mother ensues, and when Fry is found dead, she becomes the
prime suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Racism ``was something we've had a lot of experience with,''
says Judy, 48. ``It may arouse some strong feelings, but we can't
ignore the fact that racism still exists. We'd like to do what
little we can to change that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Iakovous will speak to the Mystery Book Club at 7 tonight at
Borders Books and Music, 3555 Gwinnett Place Drive, Duluth.
770-495-4043.
</P>
<P>
   LOVE, KANSAS STYLE: It's not unusual for publishers to send
unknown authors on book tours to drum up publicity. But it is
unusual to send someone on a tour five months before the book is
published. In Janice Graham's case, it was a way of getting a buzz
going for her novel ``Firebird'' (Putnam, $19.95), while
booksellers were making decisions about what titles to order for
summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of them had read the galleys and were interested in
meeting me,'' says Graham, 50, a Kansas schoolteacher who was paid
$1 million for a three-book deal. ``It was a writer's dream to
actually meet people who have read your book.''
</P>
<P>
   Touted as a romantic tale in the manner of ``The Horse
Whisperer,'' Graham's novel centers on a Kansas rancher and
attorney who is engaged to marry his longtime girlfriend. The
wedding plans are put on hold when he falls in love with a
beautiful concert violinist who returns from Paris for her mother's
funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Like her protagonist, Graham returned to her native Kansas after
living for a time in Paris. But there the similarities end. Graham
spent a year in the Middle East, lived six months in Greece and a
month in Turkey, married and divorced twice and held 13 different
jobs. For two months she lived with a friend in a palm frond hut in
the Sinai desert.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only had canned food to eat,'' she says, ``and we had to
walk to an army base to get our water every day. My whole
metabolism slowed down. I can see myself returning to a place like
that. It was an extraordinarily spiritual place.''
</P>
<P>
   OUT OF THIN AIR: If you're looking for early holiday gift ideas,
you might make a note of Villard's illustrated edition of Jon
Krakauer's ``Into Thin Air.'' The true adventure story of a Mount
Everest expedition that ended in tragedy was on The New York Times
Bestseller List for 52 weeks in hardback. The illustrated edition,
on sale Nov. 25 for $40, will include hundreds of photographs with
the complete text and a new afterword by Krakauer. All of the
author's proceeds will be donated to charity.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
