</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-GOVERNESS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Grab-bag `Governess' takes the wrong road
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The only thing that's truly kosher in ``The Governess'' is its
heroine. And that's just because she's a 19th-century Jew.
</P>
<P>
   This mixed-up movie attempts to deliver a treatise on religious
intolerance and a dollop of feminism within the context of a
fevered bodice-ripper. Nice try, but on the whole, the thing
doesn't hold together.
</P>
<P>
   Minnie Driver stars as Rosina da Silva, who lives in 1840s
London. When her father is murdered, the family is plunged into
debt. Rather than go through with an arranged marriage to a wealthy
but elderly fishmonger, Rosina decides to take the high road. To
Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   In order to get a job, she must hide her true heritage. In the
film's wittiest scene, she gives herself a good Christian name,
Mary Blackchurch. She then accepts a position as a governess with a
wealthy family, the Cavendishes, who live on a remote island.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the elements are in place for a fascinating
fish-out-of-water story. How will this Jewish girl from the city
cope with a situation that's not only foreign to her (everything
from ham for dinner to Sunday church), but could have serious
consequences should she be discovered?
</P>
<P>
   Instead and unfortunately, writer-director Sandra Goldbacher
chooses to explore Rosina's growing interest in Mr. Cavendish (Tom
Wilkinson), a self-absorbed pioneer in the early study of
photography.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's tone lurches from deadly solemn _ the Cavendishes'
offhand anti-Semitism _ to inadvertently comic. Driver acts herself
almost to death. She's clearly an ambitious performer, and this is
her first real lead since her breakthrough film, ``Circle of
Friends.'' But she approaches her not entirely sympathetic
character with a blinkered brio that's ultimately off-putting. She
doesn't capture Rosina/Mary so much as circle and enshrine her.
Plus, for every compelling scene, there are half a dozen that don't
work.
</P>
<P>
   What's left is an over-busy film with under-realized potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Governess''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Starring Minnie Driver. Directed by Sandra Goldbacher. Rated R
for sexual scenes and nudity. At Garden Hills. 1 hour, 54 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Where's Mary Poppins when you need her?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
