<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 11:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2008 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-PARADISE-COX     08-13 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-PARADISE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lots of trouble in `Paradise' has lots of trouble
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The title is just one of many things wrong with ``Return to
Paradise.'' It suggests the further adventures of Brooke Shields
(``The Blue Lagoon'') or Phoebe Cates (``Paradise,'' a ``Blue
Lagoon'' clone) when, in fact, this is a remake of a French drama,
``Force Majeure.''
</P>
<P>
   The picture begins with three Americans _ Sheriff (Vince
Vaughn), Tony (David Conrad) and Lewis (Joaquin Phoenix) _ partying
hard in Malaysia, ``a paradise of rum, girls and good cheap hash.''
</P>
<P>
   But beware with whom you party. Or, more to the point, where.
After five weeks, Sheriff and Tony go home, while Lewis _ described
by Sheriff as a ``Greenpeace tree hugger'' _ stays behind,
intending to travel on to Borneo to help endangered orangutans.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Sheriff and Tony, both working in New York and
long out of touch, are surprised by visits from an earnest and
persistent lawyer, Beth (Anne Heche). She presents them with
startling news and a more startling moral dilemma. The day they
left, Lewis was arrested for trafficking drugs and has been in jail
in Penang ever since. In eight days, he will be executed.
</P>
<P>
   Unless, that is, his traveling companions return to Malaysia and
share the blame, thus technically reducing the amount of drugs in
his possession and no longer classifying him as a dealer. Sharing
the dope, however, also means sharing the sentence. If both go
back, it means three years apiece in prison; if only one, then six
years.
</P>
<P>
   This is a terrific, what-would-you-do premise for a picture. As
Sheriff makes clear in the opening scenes, the three aren't exactly
lifelong buddies, just ``best friends for five weeks'' in a strange
place. At the same time, how easy is it to throw away someone's
life if it is in your power to save it?
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the script is so inept that the setup is all but
thrown away. The movie jerks gracelessly from one scene to the
next. Instead of focusing on the conscience-challenging decision
faced by the two men or, perhaps, on Beth's relentless campaign to
save Lewis, the emphasis shifts to a potential romance between
Sheriff and Beth, which not only seems wrongheaded but also manages
to make Vaughn and Heche, two innately appealing actors, look
stilted and foolish.
</P>
<P>
   A further conflict, in which Beth is pursued by a ruthless,
headline-hungry reporter (Jada Pinkett Smith, effective in a small
role), is introduced but never fully dealt with. Instead, it simply
becomes a plot device.
</P>
<P>
   As the wasted opportunities accumulate, the movie becomes an
exercise in frustration. Maybe they should've called it ``Return to
Scriptwriting 101.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Return to Paradise''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Vince Vaughn and Anne Heche. Directed by Joseph Ruben.
Rated R for language, drug references and a brief sex scene.
Phipps. 1 hour, 49 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A good premise goes up in smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
