<HEADER>
A2009 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-STELLA-COX     08-13 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-STELLA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bassett redeems trip to vapid `Groove' land
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You know you're watching a fantasy when the stunning Angela
Bassett can't believe that a young stud wants to get freaky with
her.
</P>
<P>
   This older woman/younger man dilemma is the thin premise of
``How Stella Got Her Groove Back,'' a screen version of Terry
McMillan's novel that tries to distract us from its lack of plot
with visual opulence. It's directed by newcomer Kevin Rodney
Sullivan with the epic slickness of a two-hour commercial for
Caribbean retreats and Marin County real estate.
</P>
<P>
   Not that there's anything wrong with that. ...
</P>
<P>
   Despite its lavishly artificial tone, McMillan's book is based
on fact: Following a couple of deaths among friends and family, the
40-something author of ``Waiting to Exhale'' took a recuperative
trip to Jamaica and fell in love with a native in his 20s. The two
are now a couple.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happens for Stella Payne (Bassett), a high-powered
Bay area investment banker who makes her clients (and herself)
rich, jogs her hard-bodied self through the park every dawn and
acts as divorced single mother to son Quincy (Michael J. Pagan).
When the kid goes away to spend two weeks with his dad, Stella lets
her workaholism slide and takes a trip to Jamaica with best pal
Delilah (Whoopi Goldberg, as zaftig and irrepressible as Bassett is
trim and serious).
</P>
<P>
   There, Stella gets pursued by a 20-year-old local named Winston
Shakespeare (Taye Diggs), a name that sounds like a marketing
character created to entice literary smokers. Actually, he's a
sweet would-be chef and med student who ups the movie's fantasy
element by being absolutely sweet, perfect and sculpted like ebony
marble.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the problem? Well, there isn't much of one, except for
that 20-year divide. The film, co-written by McMillan and
``Exhale'' screenwriter Ron Bass, squanders its chances for real
conflict. Winston's family turns out to be wealthy, so there's no
class tension for Stella to confront. Quincy pretty quickly becomes
best pals with his mom's new beau. And even Stella's ex-husband
greets the newcomer with a beer and a smile.
</P>
<P>
   In lieu of any genuine drama, the movie throws in vicious
harangues from Stella's inexplicably cruel sister Angela (Suzzanne
Douglas) and goes for easy tears with the Hollywood-style death of
one character.
</P>
<P>
   What's disappointing is that material based on fact evinces
nothing of the complex emotional realities that come with
unexpected loss and love. Given Hollywood's habit of Gwyneth
Paltrow/Michael Douglas-style pairings, it's refreshing to see a
May-December romance with the woman as the older character. (And
it's Winston, not Stella, who gets the gratuitous nude shot.)
Unfortunately, ``Groove'' never wrestles with what such an age
difference might mean in the real world.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say that ``Groove'' is a bust. Its conspicuous
consumption and travelogue views of Jamaica become mesmerizing in
their own right, just like the haute penthouse furnishings in ``A
Perfect Murder.''
</P>
<P>
   And, luckily, there's Bassett grounding the picture with a
glowing performance, sharing with us Stella's unexpected moments of
emotional rediscovery. She makes you believe things are happening,
even when a scene is dead in the water. Diggs is charming as the
boy-toy, and that's all he has to be. Goldberg is in full
love-me-I'm-funny mode, so take that as a recommendation or a
warning. And Regina King gets good comic mileage as Stella's
louder, funnier other sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Angela Bassett, Whoopi Goldberg and Taye Diggs.
Directed by Kevin Rodney Sullivan. Rated R for sexual situations,
nudity and language. 2 hours, 4 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Empty eye candy grounded by the invaluable Angela
Bassett.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
