<HEADER>
A2011 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-PAPERBACKS-COX     08-13 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-PAPERBACKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Warm reception expected for `Cold Mountain'
 &HT;    By Carolyn Nizzi Warmbold
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   After spending more than a year on the hardback best-seller
charts, ``Cold Mountain'' hits stores next week in paperback. The
paperback version of Charles Frazier's surprise blockbuster
(Vintage, $13), with its National Book Award Winner gold seal, is
already an advance-order hot seller. The North Carolinian's first
novel is about an injured soldier who deserts the Confederate army
and embarks on a Homeric odyssey to his love. The Los Angeles Times
called Frazier's work an ``epic sweep, a war-time love story that
refuses to give way to tired sentiment.''
</P>
<P>
   Other new paperbacks _ in stores now or coming soon _ include:
</P>
<P>
   Fiction
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Peachtree Road'' by Anne Rivers Siddons. Harper. $6.99.
It's been a decade since Siddons published the story of the
Bondurant cousins who grew up in a sprawling home on the city's
most famous street. On the cover of the 10th anniversary edition,
author Pat Conroy hails it as ``the Southern novel for our
generation.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Violin'' by Anne Rice. Ballantine. $14. A New Orleans widow
is visited by a violin-playing ghost who whisks her into the 19th
century and madness. Many reviewers found the novel messy,
melodramatic and far below Rice's norm. Fans may not care.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Handmaid of Desire'' by John L'Heureux. Soho. $12.
L'Heureux's witty satire about an English department at a
prestigious West Coast university features battles between the
theorists and the ``fools'' who actually read literature. Our AJC
reviewer found the tale was ``told with splenetic gusto.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Ocean of Words'' by Ha Jin. Vintage. $12. This short-story
collection written by an Emory professor, which earned a
PEN/Hemingway Award, focuses on Chinese soldiers on the
Soviet-China border in the 1970s. Atlanta author Jim Grimsley calls
the work powerful and praises the simple, elegant storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Timequake'' by Kurt Vonnegut. Berkeley $13. A timequake
forces everyone to relive the 1990s in Vonnegut's first full-length
fiction in seven years. The AJC reviewer described it as ``part
autobiography, part meditation, part satire,'' and found that
although it's not Vonnegut's best work, it offers pleasures.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Dreams of My Russian Summers'' by Andrei Makine. Scribner.
$12. This fine coming-of-age tale about a Russian boy in the 1960s
and '70s won the Prix Medicis and Prix Goncourt and was named one
of the AJC's 10 best books of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Reign in Hell'' by William Diehl. Ballantine. $6.99. Martin
Vail takes on the right-wing militia. Some reviewers thought this
book even better than his ``Primal Fear.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Foggy Mountain Breakdown'' by Sharyn McCrumb. Ballantine.
$6.99. Kirkus Reviews describes this as a ``whimsically diverse ...
sketchbook of two dozen tales exploring the quicksilver border
between mystery and magic.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonfiction
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Dark Side of Camelot'' by Seymour M. Hersh. Back
Bay/Little, Brown. $15. This controversial account of the sexual
and political exploits of the Kennedy administration may provide
ironic counterpoint to present D.C. doings. The New York Times
noted that one may quarrel with Hersh's judgments, ``but the man is
a great investigative reporter, no lie.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``T. rex and the Crater of Doom'' by Walter Alvarez. Vintage.
$13. Alvarez made news last year when he concluded that a giant
asteroid, hitting the Earth with the force of 100 million hydrogen
bombs, triggered the demise of T. rex. Reviewers praised the book's
readability and documentation.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Promiscuities: The Secret Struggle for Womanhood'' by Naomi
Wolf. Fawcett. $13.95. A candid exploration of women's sexual
coming of age and of the conflicting messages _ past and present _
directed at young women. The San Francisco Examiner-Chronicle
called this a ``pioneering work.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Napoleon Bonaparte'' by Alan Schom. Harper Perennial. $20.
This scholarly, giant-size, one-volume biography of the famous
general was declared ``a rip-roaring yarn'' by The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Inventing Mark Twain: The Lives of Samuel Langhorne
Clemens'' by Andrew Hoffman. Quill. $16. Our AJC reviewer found
this biography to be ``an intelligent tour through the adventurous
life _ and two-sided psyche _ of an American original.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``To 'Joy My Freedom: Southern Black Women's Lives and Labors
After the Civil War'' by Tera. W. Hunter. Harvard. $15.95. When the
author, a history professor, found an account of the 1881 strike by
black Atlanta washerwomen, it inspired a full-length study that the
AJC reviewer called ``a brilliant reconstruction of New South
history.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 1159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
