<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 11:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2012 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-STELLA-COX     08-13 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-STELLA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Stella' creates a groovy kind of love fantasy for moms
 &HT;    By Laura Dempsey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If The Parent Trap can be called a fantasy film for the children
of divorce, then How Stella Got Her Groove Back stands as a fantasy
film for their mothers.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, based on the best-selling novel by Terry McMillan, is
a fortysomething mom's dream, where the best friend is a
rollicking, supportive Whoopi Goldberg, the 11-year-old son is
mature and understanding, the body is lean and the bank account
full. Even Stella Payne's ex-husband turns out to be a pretty nice
guy, admitting for the record that even though Stella always thinks
she's right, she usually is.
</P>
<P>
   All that and Jamaica, too, make for a pretty pleasurable time
spent in the company of Stella, played by the ever-impressive
Angela Bassett, and her cohorts as she struggles with a ``problem''
of the heart. Oh, that we should all have such problems.
</P>
<P>
   Stella is a hard-working investment adviser, making millions for
her already-rich clients while not doing badly for herself. She
lives with her son, Quincy (Michael J. Pagan), in a designer house
in the hills of San Francisco. When Quincy heads off on a two-week
visit with his dad, he tells Mom to try to have some fun. Little
does he know.
</P>
<P>
   A spur-of-the-moment trip to Jamaica with best friend Delilah
(Goldberg) lands Stella right in Cupid's sightline. He shoots, he
scores, and Stella is off on a one-week fling (she thinks) with the
poster child for everything a woman would ever ever ever want in a
man.
</P>
<P>
   His name is Winston Shakespeare (Taye Diggs) and he says all the
right things at all the right times. Trouble is, he's 20, she's 40.
</P>
<P>
   Age is a problem for Stella, but so is Shakespeare's job and his
mother (who's 41). Stella and Winston spend the movie sorting
things out, riding the waves of a rocky romance held together by
the superglue called chemistry. Believe it, because McMillan's life
story proves that it can happen. Her book was fiction, based on
fact (true, she says, ``in essence but not in particular''), and
from all reports she's still with the guy.
</P>
<P>
   As good as Bassett is, her Stella is not all that fascinating.
She's a drudge, in fact, kept afloat by her relationship with
Delilah and coming to life only when she's messing around with her
sisters, smart-mouthed Vanessa (Regina King) and perfectionist
Angela (Suzzanne Douglas). King, like Goldberg, steals the too-few
scenes she's in, but both of them give the movie a lift.
</P>
<P>
   As for Diggs, there's not much to say. He's perfect, very
convincing as a beautiful young man because he is a beautiful young
man, and he says the nice dialogue with a nice Jamaican accent
(he's from the East Coast). He's the heart of the movie, and one
misstep could have sent everything tumbling down. But he's careful
and very controlled. No worries _ major star in the making (it's
his first feature film).
</P>
<P>
   How Stella Got Her Groove Back sets itself in nice contrast to
another film based on a book of McMillan's. Waiting to Exhale was
the story of four black women and their wide range of problems with
men who, for the most part, were big disappointments. It was also a
blockbuster, widely hailed for its statement about sisterhood and
widely criticized for its male-bashing sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   Stella doesn't have a problem with men, not a bit. (There is a
complaint about taking out the trash, but, hey . . .) Feminists may
flinch, but love has made the world go 'round for a long, long
time. Without it, the groove is gone, face it. And, sure, life can
be lived without a groove, but when Stella gets hers back, it's
time for a celebration. Stella isn't afraid to give us one
</P>
<P>
   ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Angela Bassett, Taye DIggs, Whoppi Goldberg; Director:
Kevin Sullivan
</P>
<P>
   Rated R for sexuality, nudity, language. 124 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
