u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-AIRBUD-COX     08-13 0397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-AIRBUD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No reason to race out with the kids to catch `Golden Receiver'
Rate it ``D'' _ for dog.
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's tough enough being a parent these days without having to
endure agonizingly bad family films such as Air Bud: Golden
Receiver .
</P>
<P>
   Young children will enjoy the sequel to the 1997 hit about a
basketball-playing pooch, but they're an easily satisfied audience.
Put a cute doggie in a football uniform and you've got yourself a
happy little kids' movie.
</P>
<P>
   Adults, on the other hand, will want to flip a coin to see who
has the misfortune of spending a very long 90 minutes watching it
with the kids.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, Buddy the Golden Retriever hits the gridiron
as the star receiver of a hopeless junior high school football
team. In the tradition of every sports comedy from the Bad News
Bears to Major League , the squad miraculously becomes a
state-championship contender. But that's only one of countless
movie cliches trotted out for unsuspecting young viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Buddy's owner, Josh Framm (Kevin Zegers), is threatened by his
widowed mother's budding relationship with the town's handsome
veterinarian, Patrick Sullivan (Gregory Harrison). Jackie (Cynthia
Stevenson) is pulled into the vet's arms by Buddy while in-line
skating, a la 101 Dalmatians .
</P>
<P>
   The sappy, predictable drama is worse than some hackneyed
after-school special, which probably would have better production
values than this cheaply made knockoff.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, the Golden Retriever who inspired Air Bud died last year
of cancer. Here he's replaced by six dogs, two of which also
appeared in the original film.
</P>
<P>
   Slapstick comic relief is provided by a pair of bumbling Russian
circus owners _ clearly patterned after Rocky and Bullwinkle 's
Boris and Natasha _ who attempt to steal Josh's ``amazing'' dog.
</P>
<P>
   A canine shooting hoops with his nose, as the original Buddy
did, is impressive. But catching a ball and running with it is
pretty much what dogs do best. Can't wait for the next movie, in
which Buddy fetches a stick
</P>
<P>
   ``Air Bud: Golden Receiver''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Kevin Zegers, Cynthia Stevenson, Gregory Harrison.
Director: Richard Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Rated PG for slapstick violence. 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
