<HEADER>
A2028 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-PARADISE-COX     08-13 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-PARADISE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Return to Paradise' a loss; Provocative premise falls victim to
formula in dull drama
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   How far would you go for a friend? That's the intriguing premise
of Return to Paradise , a Hollywood remake of the 1990 French film,
Force Majeure .
</P>
<P>
   Three college grads meet on a hedonistic tour of Asia, which
culminates in a reckless spree of hashish and whores in Penang,
Malaysia. Two of the newfound friends, Sheriff (Vince Vaughn) and
Tony (David Conrad), return to New York City, while their
tree-hugging compadre, Lewis (Joaquin Phoenix), stays behind to
help save endangered orangutans.
</P>
<P>
   Leap ahead two years, when a lawyer appears to inform Sheriff
and Tony that Lewis, having been caught with the large quantity of
hash they left behind, has spent the past 24 months in prison.
Unless they return to Penang to share responsibility, Lewis will
hang as a drug trafficker in eight days.
</P>
<P>
   Their moral dilemma, combined with the ordeal of their
imprisoned friend, could have made for a '90s version of Midnight
Express , the harrowing 1978 film about a young U.S. drug smuggler
brutalized in a Turkish prison. Instead, the formulaic drama is
dull and uninvolving.
</P>
<P>
   Return to Paradise centers on Sheriff _ the nickname of
self-described Brooklyn bum John Volgecherev _ a hustling limo
driver and the most irresponsible of the lot. If Sheriff and Tony
both go back to Penang, they each face three years in prison. But
if only one volunteers, he must serve six. Tony, a nondescript
straight arrow, will do the right thing, despite his career and
beautiful fiancee (Vera Farmiga).
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff, on the other hand, ``doesn't have it in him.'' So it's
up to the persistent attorney, Beth (Anne Heche), to persuade him
to make the honorable choice. His decision is inevitable _
otherwise, there wouldn't be much of a movie _ but not without lots
of tiresome agonizing in various New York restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Director Joseph Ruben ( Sleeping With the Enemy ) draws little
emotion from what should be an intense situation. The drama is as
drab as the film's muted tones, and the pacing is unbelievably
slow. Worse still, screenwriters Wesley Strick and Bruce Robinson
tack on a forced and improbable romance between Sheriff and Beth.
It's about as credible as Jada Pinkett Smith's conniving tabloid
reporter, M.J. Major.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Lewis is almost an afterthought, seen only in a handful of
blackout scenes at the grungy but hardly horrific prison, where he
initially appears to be the only inmate. Perhaps the producers were
worried about offending viewers in the large and lucrative Asian
market.
</P>
<P>
   Ruben eventually ratchets up the tension level as Sheriff
embarks on his road to redemption. The story delivers several
surprising and effective twists, along with a pious anti-drug
screed. There's also a veiled reference to former Kettering
resident Michael Fay, who was caned for vandalizing cars in
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, whose father graduated from the University of Dayton,
gives a tremendous performance, redeeming the film, as well as his
character. The tall, handsome actor burst to stardom as the
ultracool ladies' man, Trent, in Swingers and also appeared in The
Lost World: Jurassic Park . Here, he strongly conveys Sheriff's
soulful inner conflict, lending him enough humor and charm to make
the morally indifferent character likable.
</P>
<P>
   The same can't be said for Ruben's drama, which fails to return
on its provocative premise
</P>
<P>
   ``Return to Paradise''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Vince Vaughn, Anne Heche, Joaquin Phoenix; Director:
Joseph Ruben
</P>
<P>
   Rated R for profanity, drug use, some sexuality and a scene of
violence. 109 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
