<HEADLINE>
CBS DEGRADES AMERICA WITH `HOWARD STERN' AND HIS DRUNKEN DWARFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or
fax her at (816) 822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 By MIKE McMANUS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    If you thought TV had gone as low as it could go with prime-time
nudity, ubiquitous coarse language and graphic violence, perhaps
you haven't heard about CBS' new degradation of America, ''The
Howard Stern Show.'' It is scheduled to begin later this month on
Saturday nights at 11:30 p.m.
 &HT;    ''We'll have a lot of nudity and lesbians,'' Stern promised.
''We plan to have a lot of drunken dwarfs on the show....
Television is ready for someone like me. Standards have gone to an
all-time low, and I'm here to represent the change.''
 &HT;    Howard Stern has a daily five-hour radio show aired in 49 major
markets, but also in smaller places such as Fresno, Calif; York,
Pa., and Panama City, Fla. Its crudity and coarseness is difficult
to describe in a family newspaper in a column like this.
 &HT;    Before illustrating what we can expect to see on CBS, based on
what has been on his radio show, I am pleased to report that the
American Family Association has successfully persuaded 3,100 of
Stern's 3,900 radio advertisers across the nation to cancel their
ads.
 &HT;    The depravity of Howard Stern can be fought and defeated if the
good people in this land express their outrage to local CBS
affiliates and to the Stern sponsors.
 &HT;    Don Wildmon, president of the AFA, says that Stern ''is to radio
what Larry Flynt is to porn magazines. In all our years of
monitoring entertainment programs, American Family Association has
never encountered a more raunchy, despicable, degenerate
entertainment than that of Howard Stern.''
 &HT;    For example, in one show Stern describes a porno star with
enlarged breasts due to implants, who strips in his radio studio
and gives a nude massage to another female.
 &HT;    I heard a program in which a man who works in a mortuary called
in to describe having sex with a corpse. ''Did you kiss her?''
asked Stern. ''Did you go to the funeral?''
 &HT;    This week there was a contest to see who had the largest male
member. In another contest, obese women stripped and described
their bodies, in hopes that a plastic surgeon would do a makeover
with liposuction.
 &HT;    Several retarded men served as judges as Stern made jokes about
these sad creatures.
 &HT;    This kind of programming appeals to some men of all classes who
find it amusing. Stern often tops the ratings in local markets.
That makes it a magnet for advertisers of products that men buy --
beer, computers, cars.
 &HT;    AFA's surprisingly successful strategy to fight this trash is
led by Bill Johnson, AFA's Michigan director. He buys tapes of
Stern's show in 20 cities and has part-time staffers listen and
record the advertisers.
 &HT;    Johnson then sends a polite letter with brief descriptions of
the shows, and asks advertisers to cease advertising on them. If
monitoring does not reveal an advertiser has quit, Johnson sends a
second or even third follow-up letter.
 &HT;    In Grand Rapids, where the campaign began, 374 advertisers out
of 401 have yanked their ads. In Los Angeles and Philadelphia,
three-fourths of advertisers have quit.
 &HT;    ''Howard Stern worked for us in Minneapolis,'' Paris Burrell
told me. His firm, Empire Glass, which replaces car windshields,
got 30-40 more calls a week. ''My job is to make those phones
ring.''
 &HT;    But his boss, Richard Chance, a committed Christian, was
convinced by the second letter. ''He felt it was like God talking
to him. We will never be on the Howard Stern show.''
 &HT;    Among national advertisers who have ignored the pleas are
Budweiser, Dunkin' Donuts, Aamco Transmissions and Erols. But Coors
Beer, RC Cola and America Online did quit.
 &HT;    Radio stations typically sign two-year contracts with Stern.
That means if nine of out ten advertisers quit, the station loses
lots of money.
 &HT;    Let's help CBS avoid such a problem. I urge readers to see if
their CBS outlet plans to carry the shock jock. If so, form a
committee to plead for decency with the station manager. And send a
check to AFA, PO Box 202 Fremont, MI 49412.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.1998 Mike McManus
<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
