<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 12:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2074 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STONES-RUSSIA-HNS &LR;      08-13 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STONES-RUSSIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO MOSCOW WITH LOVE: THE STONES STORM RUSSIAN CAPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICTOR TURKS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ ``How are you going to satisfy the 30-year hunger of
your Russian fans by giving just one concert in Moscow?''
</P>
<P>
   The Rolling Stones were asked at their Moscow press conference
in the Hotel Baltschug Kempinski on the bank of the Moska River.
Across the way, the turbanesque onion-tops of St. Basil's Cathedral
swirled toward the gathering rain clouds over Red Square.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nibble. It's a start,'' Mick Jagger swiftly fielded the
question, acting consummately as spokesperson for the band. ``We're
very, very excited. When we first tried to play in Russia in 1967,
someone had seen us in Poland and thought our show as too awful and
too decadent for Moscow. We tried to get in, but Madame Furzieva,
the iron-willed minister of culture, said, `No!' (Nyet!).''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Soviet regime in those days didn't want rock bands at
all!'' ``Things have changed,'' Mick Jagger pointed out, radiating
his customary jolly good spirits. ``We hope it will be a wonderful
show for us and everybody else. We're thankful to be here at
last!''
</P>
<P>
   ``What are your impressions of Russia and its people? And what
about the women?'' a woman journalist shouted.
</P>
<P>
   Ever the artful diplomat, Jagger, 55, considered and said: ``I
think we're impressed with the grandeur of Moscow, and the warmth
... and the beauty of the men and women.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rolling Stones are giving a concert in Moscow? How
exciting! I didn't even know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Had I stumbled into the Moscow Central police station, or a
stadium show by the Rolling Stones? Squads of police in black
leather jackets, matching berets and combat boots were on hand to
ensure that things did not get out of control. It seemed like a
state of siege.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night inside Luzhniki Stadium, site of the
U.S.-boycotted 1980 Summer Olympics, we encountered police
checkpoints at practically every turn. We were frisked, asked to
show our ticket stubs again and again, and made to unzip our
purses, shoulder bags, and back packs. After the show, columns of
boyish police cadets, hooded and caped in the rainy Moscow night,
were to funnel the emerging crowds to the subway station in an
eerily efficient manner. Their stone-faced commanding mounted
officers stood ready in the wings.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, rain came down in the partially domed stadium,
pelting the fans who had opted for field dancing and standing room
near the stage.
</P>
<P>
   But once the house lights went out, the formidable-looking
police presence waned as the Rolling Stones, to a chorus of
whistles, shouts, and cheers, took the stage. The Moscow fans,
fortified with giant-sized cups of draft beer, hot dogs, popcorn,
some ice-cream cones, gave the Stones an absolutely bearish
welcome.
</P>
<P>
   His fly-away locks plastered to his head in the driving rain,
Jagger &AMP; Co. played on, happy to spend the night together with
their Russian fans. The Stones belted out a barrage of their
classic songs Moscow fans had come to hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paint It Black,'' in particular, seemed to go over very well
with the crowd who were swaying to the music and rollicking in a
frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   When Jagger, during ``Miss You,'' proceeded to tongue his
back-up vocalist's outstretched leg, and sucked and sucked on her
wiggling big toe, Moscow went wild.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of a delightful all-out performance that lasted
until just about midnight, Jagger and his eternally scrappy mates,
drenched with rain, dished out plenty themselves to their adoring
fans.
</P>
<P>
   Fireworks cackled to close the historic show, and the fans
cheered, having gotten far more than their rubles' worth, their
faces twinkling in the rockets' red glare.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 1240EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2087 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-13 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LITTLE COMPROMISE MIGHT GO A LONG WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A few socio-political topics that ought not slip
away without some reflection:
</P>
<P>
   In the Unclear on the Concept category, we have a group of
so-called conservative Roman Catholics wreaking emotional havoc at
Auschwitz in Poland.
</P>
<P>
   Angry because there's a move afoot to take down a three-story
cross from this site of one of the Nazis' most notorious death
camps, the Catholics have protested by erecting more crosses. Five
went up last week to bring the total to more than 90.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate goal: 152 crosses to symbolize the 152 Poles who
were killed at Auschwitz.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 152 is a lot. But compared to more than 1 million _ the
number of Jews murdered at Auschwitz _ 152 is minuscule.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the numbers, the Polish government and the Catholic
Church have wanted Auschwitz for their own. For years, they have
insisted that the site should be a memorial for Polish martyrdom or
for a generic crime against humanity. Until just a few years ago,
Pope John Paul II, a native son of Poland, backed attempts to
convert the memorial.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as 1995, at a commemorative ceremony for the
liberation of Auschwitz, former Polish President Lech Walesa made
an entire speech about Auschwitz's history without once referring
to the executed Jews.
</P>
<P>
   C'mon, folks. Would a plaque be so bad?
</P>
<P>
   Moving on to the Ugly American category, we find the United
States' ``rescue effort'' in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
   Terrorists bombed our embassy there on Aug. 7, but managed to
kill far more Kenyans (more than 200) in a nearby office building
than Americans (12). As local rescuers worked against the clock to
find Kenyan survivors, what were Americans doing to help?
</P>
<P>
   According to angry Kenyans, nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Excuses offered by the State Department were: (1) Available
personnel are few and stretched, and (2) U.S. Marines on site must
be used to secure the crime area for an FBI investigation.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt Kenyans are wondering when the U.S. government ever let
a shortage of resources stop it from getting something it wants. No
doubt they can imagine how different the scene would be if the
office building had been a school for American children.
</P>
<P>
   Our last stop is at the Why Politics is a Drag category.
Specifically, the California governor's race.
</P>
<P>
   After vowing not to engage in mud-slinging _ and particularly
not to criticize one another's military record _ Gray Davis and Dan
Lungren have begun to crack. Lungren, a Republican, supposedly took
a jocular swipe at Vietnam vet Davis, the Democrat, by alleging
that Davis had joined the Army to make money. At an Oakland
fund-raiser, Davis reportedly referred ``in jest'' to the
medically-deferred Lungren as ``that draft-dodger.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than endure this sort of penny-ante sniping until
November, what do you say Davis and Lungren agree to a
one-time-only, name-calling free-for-all? It could be telecast
after 10 p.m., so both gents could really let fly.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-abortion Lungren could realize his fantasy and call the
pro-choice Davis a ``baby killer.'' Davis could retaliate by
calling Lungren a ``sexist womb Nazi.'' Then Davis could make fun
of Lungren's seriously receding hair line, and Lungren could
counter with how the almost opalescent Davis looks like he lost a
15-rounder to Dracula.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with facts provided by their staffs, the two could take
cheap shots at one another's parents, wives, kids and close pals,
then criticize each other's table manners, carpentry skills,
dancing acumen and choice of leisure wear.
</P>
<P>
   The session could end with the two men repairing to a large
restroom on whose floor a measured grid was painted. There they'd
engage in the juvenile activity for which 98 percent of political
bickering is just a substitute anyway.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
