<SLUG> BC-FASHION-SNEAKERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION (AND COMFORT) FROM THE GROUND UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It must be the generational difference. But
Daniela Faggioli's 18-year-old debutante daughter, Max Boyer, loved
the white rubber-trimmed anthracite sneaks that Giorgio Armani was
showing with his Emporio line. Daniela hated it. ``Why sabotage a
good look?'' she asked. Why indeed.
</P>
<P>
   The Emporio Armani show was a casual affair, a relaxed luncheon
in one of the private spaces at Le Colonial. Emporio clients who
spend $10,000 or more a year were invited as a treat and presented
with a pair of tortoise-shell sunglasses.
</P>
<P>
   The women, including San Francisco 49er wives Marva Hanks and
Jackie Rice, were treated to the collection that Armani wanted to
show in Paris. The French canceled that show and Armani went on to
produce the event in New York. It is the fall Emporio line,
complete with sneaks that are worn with literally everything.
Pants. Skirts. Casual clothing. And, ohmigawd, evening dresses.
</P>
<P>
   We've known for some time that young, up-and-coming business
women are sporting athletic shoes with their career clothes and
unlike their older sisters, are not changing into pumps when they
get to work. It is a clumsy look, just as wearing tai chi shoes or
Birkenstocks with designer togs makes the wearer look like a slob.
And I'm not all that sure San Francisco's Elegances are going to
take to it. But, as Max Boyer pointed out, ``It's a generational
thing.'' Whatever.
</P>
<P>
   Now, to the clothes. Mr. Armani isn't all that big on color. And
the fall line is stocked with neutrals _ lots of gray, black and an
old gold, which is darker than camel and lighter than rust. His one
splotch of color (besides a gorgeous turquoise and gray cut-out
velvet, belted evening tunic and a trouser suit of black on green
devore velvet) is a marvelous sage or dark seafoam green which he
coupled with gray and with black in a big wooly mohair sweater or
used alone in suits that were cut along the lines of his Black
Label clothing.
</P>
<P>
   The lines are very slim; lapels teensy, rounded and buttoned up
high on the collarbone. Closings are not exactly asymmetrical but a
gentle outward, buttoned curve. Jackets are longer; pants are a
combination of flat front or pleated trousers. The feeling is very
easy, comfortable and very big city sophistication with a youthful
twist.
</P>
<P>
   For evening, Armani designed pieces to go over plain black
dresses, skirts or pants, including a beaded camisole-top
over-blouse; a bolero in the same horizontally beaded
silver-on-black pattern; a show-stopping cage of iridescent sequins
(shown over high-cut body-suit which nobody who wasn't Ashley Judd
could get away with) and the best ensemble in the show: a midnight
blue and black sequined easy jacket worn over a matching sleeveless
top, worn with black silk crepe pants. A real collectible.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of collectibles: St. John Knits are like cashmeres. For
some people, you can never have enough. The St. John ladies all
support Marie Gray, their favorite designer, and at one of her
shows, you're liable to see women of all ages decked out in a
rainbow of boxy knits and Chanel clones _ lots of braid, white
edging around skirt and jacket bottoms and gold. Tons and tons of
gold _ buttons, sequins, beads, belts, pins.
</P>
<P>
   Gray started her company purely as a way to impress her
then-fiance. She knit a dress. Then she got a knitting machine and
made another dress. Fiance, now hubby, Bob Gray, took the dresses
to a buyer he knew who snatched them up. And a way of life was
born.
</P>
<P>
   A dedicated colorist, Gray's fall collection is a long way from
basic black. Redwood (a nice, lively rust), a deep cherry red,
interesting shades of green, from gold-flecked moss to deep
black-scarab, vibrant purples, winter whites and glitter-flecked
gold knits in evening suits and slinky long, mock-turtlenecked
dresses.
</P>
<P>
   The clothes are predictable and predictably loud _ Gray must
have a lot of clients in Texas and Florida _ but when a St. John
design is on, it's really on. The big surprise was the sportwear
with a particularly adorable faux-fur chubby baseball jacket with
knit collar and cuffs and a fabulous moss green iridescent nylon
jacket worn with black slacks and a chartreuse/moss/black striped
turtleneck.
</P>
<P>
   As for the evening dresses, they're getting slinkier and more
graceful without getting tighter. One stunner was a black slink of
knit with a double strap of sequined gold worn with an all-over
sequined gold jacket. Another was a nifty bit of brocaded
chinoiserie with a deep back and high, faux-turtle halter top.
</P>
<P>
   Let's talk glitter here. Gray says her price points are higher
this year ``because women want luxury,'' and she gave it to them.
Probably half the collection is geared for cocktails and evenings,
with beautifully tailored suits paged with rhinestones, sequins
and, in the case of one red and black paisley number, huge chunks
of colored jewels.
</P>
<P>
   Everything was set off by Gray's accessory line. The shoes,
particularly, were feminine and very high.
</P>
</TEXT>
