<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR IMAC USERS, A WAIT FOR THE BUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're one of the thousands planning to buy Apple Computer
Inc.'s new iMac this weekend, try not to be too disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, some of you will go home empty-handed, if the
early buzz is on the level. Apple says it's got 150,000 advance
orders already, and expects to have trouble meeting demand. But
even if you manage to get hold of an iMac, you'll have a problem
buying vital accessories like an external disk drive or a printer.
</P>
<P>
   Apple didn't include a floppy disk drive with the iMac, saying
that customers would buy external drives like the Iomega Zip
instead. But Iomega doesn't plan to have an iMac-compatible Zip
drive available until late this year. Hewlett-Packard Co. was
supposed to have an iMac printer ready to go. Not just yet, the
company told me on Tuesday, though you will be able to buy a $69
adapter that will let the iMac work with traditional printers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite my penchant for sniping at Apple, I don't fault the
company for the accessories shortage. I blame the computer industry
for being so slow to take up the banner of USB.
</P>
<P>
   That's Universal Serial Bus to us English speakers. It's the
port and associated circuitry that connects an iMac to ``peripheral
devices'' like mice, printers, scanners and the like. Apple has
made much of its use of USB, but millions of PCs also have USB
ports in back. The technology has existed for years. Still, there
are few USB products for sale.
</P>
<P>
   This will soon change _ and about time too. Apple's iMac will
drive demand for USB devices. More important, Microsoft Corp. has
gotten religion. USB wouldn't work with earlier versions of
Windows. But later versions of Windows 95 include USB support; so
does every copy of Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   Who needs USB? All of us, and badly. Today's computers are
saddled with outdated ways of linking to external devices. Consider
the serial ports used to hook up modems and mice. They can transmit
data no faster than 115,000 bits every second. That limits the
serial port to fairly low-speed tasks. Parallel ports are about
twice as fast, but still sluggish considering that the computer
flings around millions of bits each second.
</P>
<P>
   If you've got an Iomega Zip drive plugged into your computer's
parallel port, it runs at a fraction of its potential speed. You'd
get much better performance by installing an internal Zip drive,
linked directly to the computer's motherboard. Just rip open your
computer to install it. I bet you can hardly wait.
</P>
<P>
   There are other drawbacks with our present ports. You have to
reboot the computer before it'll accept that new mouse or modem
you've plugged in. In addition, each port accepts &UR;  &LR; just one device
at a time. You can't plug a mouse and modem into the same serial
port, for instance. And while I can run a printer and a Zip drive
on a single parallel port, I can't use them both at the same time.
The average machine has two serial ports and one parallel port. Use
them up, and you've got a problem.
</P>
<P>
   USB is designed to fix all this. You can connect up to 127
devices to a single USB port. You can ``hot-swap'' USB devices,
plugging in new ones without having to reboot. And USB ports can
handle up to 12 million bits of data per second _ plenty fast
enough for external Zip drives.
</P>
<P>
   It's even fast enough for high-speed Internet devices. Order
cable modem service today, and a technician will install an
Ethernet card in your computer to handle the torrent of data. But
installing a next-generation cable modem will take about five
seconds _ you'll just plug it into the USB slot.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; It's no surprise that USB appeals to Apple engineers. They've
long offered a less-advanced version of the same thing. The Apple
Desktop Bus lets you plug up to 16 devices into a single port. On
many models, you can plug the monitor into the computer's desktop
bus port. Then you plug the keyboard into a slot on the monitor,
and the mouse into a slot on the keyboard. And so on.
</P>
<P>
   USB will let PC users do the same, if the hardware ever shows
up. So far I've tested two USB devices. Both installed easily and
worked splendidly. Hewlett-Packard's ScanJet 4100C scanner will
sell for $199 when it lands on shelves this autumn. And you can
already buy the Logitech USB Wheel Mouse for around $40.
</P>
<P>
   But what about USB disk drives, monitors, modems? Just you wait.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (You can send electronic mail to Hiawatha Bray at
bray(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
