<SLUG> BC-MA-TEACHERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTING TEACHING BEFORE TRADITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JORDANA HART  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Jennifer S. Puccetti has a master's degree in public
policy and a bachelor's in political science. She has run the
Chelsea Parent Information Center and served as publicist for the
Boston University-run Chelsea school district.
</P>
<P>
   These days, though, she is the principal at the new Clark Avenue
School in Chelsea, hiring teachers and generally readying the
school for the Sept. 2 opening with more than 500 fifth- and
sixth-graders.
</P>
<P>
   And according to her resume, her only classroom experience has
been teaching English in the Dominican Republic while a Peace Corps
volunteer in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Last school year, the state's alternative certification process
allowed Puccetti and 269 others without a traditional education
background to become certified as teachers and school
administrators. Indeed, according to the state, professional
experience allows many of them to bypass the usual certification
process.
</P>
<P>
   With a statewide chorus for higher standards _ including
required coursework, minimum hours of work experience, and a
mandatory high-stakes certification exam _ the non-traditionalists
teaching and running schools in Massachusetts seems to run against
the current.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is broad support for easing the certification path for
successful mid-career professionals wanting to shift gears. Even
those with traditional backgrounds say such people breathe
creativity into a profession just beginning to cast off some of its
own rigid traditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could be certified and still not have the strengths,'' said
Jocelyn Mouton, director of the Center for Leadership Development,
which trains Boston public school teachers and administrators.
``Sometimes the second-career teachers are better because they
developed a skill in one area, then realized they wanted to teach.
They bring so much from the experiences they have had, whether it
is in science or writing. It is like adding another layer.''
</P>
<P>
   While 12,677 teachers and administrators were certified the
standard way in Massachusetts, 81 of them _ like Puccetti _ were
certified by the state education commissioner, and 189 were
certified by a panel review. Superintendents are the ones who seek
the licenses for unconventional teachers and principals.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a state education department spokeswoman said a
letter and supporting documents from Chelsea Superintendent Douglas
Sears last February extolling Puccetti's work record and life
experience were apparently enough to convince then-Commissioner
Robert V. Antonucci to certify Puccetti not only to be a principal,
but an assistant superintendent or superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   Puccetti would not comment on her background, but she and others
appear to be filling what is otherwise an increasingly shallow pool
of traditionally certified applications. Dissatisfaction with
public schools, urban ones in particular, is keeping away
superintendents and principals, say observers.
</P>
<P>
   According to Peter Finn, executive director of the Massachusetts
Association of School Superintendents, teacher pay increases over
the past few years across the country mean fewer teachers are
seeking to move up the ranks to earn a better wage. Some 95 percent
of superintendents began as teachers, he said, but that number is
likely to change.
</P>
<P>
   Hiring non-educators as administrators is a recent nationwide
trend. Retired military leaders now run the Seattle and Boulder
public school districts. San Diego recently hired a former
prosecutor, while a former city budget director runs the Chicago
schools.
</P>
<P>
   For teachers, certification is no job guarantee, except possibly
for those trained in science, math, or bilingual education. And
because of demand, these are the fields where nontraditional sorts
get plenty of attention.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Ayers, starting his second year teaching sixth-grade math
at the Robert Gould Shaw Middle School in West Roxbury, is one such
teacher. An applied mathematician and engineer by training, the
36-year-old Winthrop native decided four years ago that engineering
was not for him. He knew he could become certified through the
alternative route had he wanted to teach only math, but he decided
instead to become traditionally certified in elementary education
so he can teach any subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``This job is certainly more challenging than engineering,'' he
said. ``Certainly if someone has worked in the field they are
teaching, they bring a lot to the table.'' But he said the
curriculum and pedagogy courses he took at Lesley College and his
student teaching were vital, too.
</P>
<P>
   Teacher union officials were cautious as they praised
alternative certification.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are brilliantly talented people out there who ought to
be teaching, and it would be foolish to put them through a standard
teacher preparation program,'' said Fred Andelman, director of
professional development for the Massachusetts Teachers
Association. ``But the public must be assured that people working
in education need to demonstrate, just as anyone who gets in a car,
that they possess the skills to do the job. That is called
licensure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
