<HEADLINE>
BACK PAIN PUTS HURT ON GOLFERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ The agony that comes with the ecstasy starts in
the backswing as the torso twists one way and the shoulders turn on
another plane entirely.
</P>
<P>
   The combined motion can send golf balls rocketing off toward
another planet. But it also can bring even the most athletic
golfers back to earth in sharp spasms of pain.
</P>
<P>
   Back pain has played a major role this year on the PGA Tour,
shortening the tour schedule of Fred Couples, forcing PGA Champion
Davis Love III to cut back on public appearances and several
events, causing two-time U.S. champion Ernie Els to withdraw in the
middle of a tournament for the first time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   If they stay healthy, all three are among the favorites this
week at Sahalee Country Club. And to make sure that their backs
don't break down over the course of the next four days, the players
have employed their own personal back doctor: Columbus, Ga.,
physician Tom Boers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me to quit giving him publicity because he's too busy
already,'' Love said Wednesday when asked what Boers would be doing
to keep his back healthy going into Thursday's opening round.
</P>
<P>
   The publicity-shy Boers told Golf World magazine: ``I have a
ball seeing all those guys, but it's not my goal to be out there
every weekend in the fitness trailer.''
</P>
<P>
   Boers is so well-known on the PGA Tour because back pain is
probably the biggest health-related problem that professional
golfers face. Couples, for example, has reduced his schedule over
the past four years because of recurring back and disc problems. In
1996, it forced him to withdraw from the U.S. Open, and in 1995, he
was in such pain that he chose not to travel to the British Open.
</P>
<P>
   To make sure he had no serious pain coming into the PGA
Championship, Couples played only two events from mid-June to now:
the U.S. Open and the British Open. He's on medication, and Boers
will help with a stretching and flexibility routine to keep him
from breaking down in agony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take a few pills and roll around on the ground,'' Couples
said, describing the treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Couples first learned of Boers' speciality after the 45-year-old
therapist from Amsterdam began treating Greg Norman for a back
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game of golf is not conducive to natural movement. The
swing is an unnatural motion,'' Norman once said when asked why so
many golfers seem to be plagued by back pain. Others occasionally
on the tender-back list include Phil Mickelson, Tiger Woods, Larry
Nelson, Loren Roberts and Seve Ballesteros.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, Els, Couples and Love have had the most trouble.
That's why Couples has brought Boers to each of the majors he's
played in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom has come out a lot . . . so that is almost every three or
four weeks instead (of seeing him) once or twice a year,'' Couples
said. ``I think he's got me in a good spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Couples' problems began about five years ago at the age of 33.
Nothing took away the pain until Boers began to manipulate joints
in Couples' back. The joints are known as facet joints and run down
the length of the spine.
</P>
<P>
   According to Boers, Couples' facet joints appeared to be stuck
together and were not moving properly with his back. By
manipulating them, Boers was able to free them up to take away the
pain and gradually increase Couples' mobility. Boers also put
Couples on a new exercise routine to keep his back and the joints
moving properly.
</P>
<P>
   His role in bringing Couples back to playing form attracted Els
and Davis to Boers this year after they, too, began to find back
pain forced them to withdraw from tournaments and public
appearances. Neither one was found to have a specific problem, but
both had sore back muscles because of the extensive practice and
playing regimen of the PGA Tour, and because they are both tall men
who spend a lot of time flying and carrying luggage.
</P>
<P>
   Els said Boers never could pinpoint what was causing him the
most pain, but was able to help loosen up his spine, where he would
feel most of the tightness and soreness. Before he saw Boers, Els
was forced to withdraw from the Buick classic in early June.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just came on over a couple of years. I have no (medical)
problem. Everything is in line,'' Els said, proclaiming himself fit
for the test at Sahalee.
</P>
<P>
   Love has seen his back problems put a damper on the year he
intended to enjoy the PGA Tour as the reigning PGA Champion. Now he
and Couples are spending more time on the floor and less time
pounding golf balls at the range.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing more stretching and range-of-motion exercises than
working out,'' Love said. ``I'm trying to keep my back loose, keep
everything stretched out. I'm doing a lot of the stuff like Freddy
is doing _ just spending some time on your back and rolling around.
It does a lot of good.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Els, Love was assured that his back problems aren't as bad
as Couples'.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a bad back; I have a hurt back,'' Love said.
</P>
<P>
   Couples is resigned to dealing with his back pain for the rest
of his golfing career. It comes and it goes, so Couples comes and
goes on the PGA Tour, having played only 14 events this year,
winning twice with a tie for second at the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel like I still have the game to win,'' Couples
said. ``That is the only reason I play. I don't play this game to
come out and just hope my back will do fine. I come out to compete.
And when I stop doing that, I will quit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
