<SLUG> BC-FILM-GOVERNESS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVER'S PERFORMANCE IN `THE GOVERNESS' MAKES IT WORTH SEEING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Governess,'' a gothic romance novel of a film about one
woman's journey toward sexual self-knowledge and identity, is more
visually adventurous than anything.
</P>
<P>
   It features an odd, sometimes bold, performance by Minnie Driver
in her first star vehicle. Whether you can suspend disbelief for
wild flights of fancy will depend entirely upon your feelings about
Driver herself as an actress.
</P>
<P>
   She's in virtually every scene of Sandra Goldbacher's first
feature. Goldbacher was a successful commercials director in London
and her talent with a camera certainly can't be disputed.
Unfortunately, the same can't be said for the film's soap opera of
a story, which is over-the-top, unfocused and lacks plausibility.
</P>
<P>
   In England during the Victorian Era, a young Jewish woman,
Rosina DaSilva (Driver), learns, after the sudden death of her
father, that his excesses have left her mother and sister
penurious. Rosina boldly decides to find work so she can support
her family and pay off their debts.
</P>
<P>
   Realizing she'll be at a disadvantage in the Christian
community, she changes her name to Mary Blackchurch and secures
employment on the Isle of Skye as a governess for the eccentric
Cavendish family.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Cavendish (Tom Wilkinson) is an inventor. He's engrossed in
finding a fixative for photographic developer, an obsession he
invites the bright Rosina to share. She soon falls in love with the
middle-aged man, embracing him with torrid emotional abandon. The
two embark on a heated affair, much to the agony of the young heir,
Henry Cavendish (Jonathan Rhys-Meyer), who has come home from
Oxford and promptly becomes obsessed with his sister's exotic
governess.
</P>
<P>
   There is a potentially intriguing triangle between father, son
and governess at play but the film never delves into psychological
depths that might have made it more interesting and original. ``The
Governess'' stays mainly on the surface of the characters'
motivations.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it feels like Goldbacher became confused over what
she really wanted to convey. The film takes convenient liberties
with Rosina's search for a place in Christian society as well as
the story of a strong-willed woman's struggle for emancipation.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it a true romance, as was Jane Campion's cunning ``The
Piano,'' a film it resembles. Instead it's indecisively
non-committal, even opting for an ``I Am Woman'' ending that
sabotages and negates the complicated, intriguing setup.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, as a statement on women's freedom and struggles, the
real moments in the film go to the marvelous English stage actress
Harriet Walter. She plays Mrs. Cavendish, a shallow, uninventive
society wife who has suffered from exile in a lonely place as well
as from her husband's inattention. More comment is made about a
woman's heart through her pursed, pained face than with all of
Driver's uncorseted, ``liberated'' sexual writhings with the master
of the house.
</P>
<P>
   The Governess. Directed and written by Sandra Goldbacher. Cast:
Minnie Driver, Tom Wilkinson, Harriet Walter, Jonathan Rhys-Meyer.
Sony Pictures Classics. 100 minutes. Rated R for nudity, sexual
content.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
