<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-OMEARA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'MEARA IS CHASING A SPOT ALONGSIDE HOGAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; REDMOND, Wash. _ Mark O'Meara's first contract when he turned
professional 17 years ago was with the Ben Hogan Co., and the
association lasted for six or seven years. Now he's in the 80th PGA
Championship at Sahalee CC with a chance to join Hogan in a more
enduring sense.
</P>
<P>
   Should O'Meara, 41, win this tournament, he would be the only
player except Hogan to win three of golf's four professional major
championships in the same year.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan won the Masters, the US Open, and the British Open in 1953
and bypassed the PGA Championship because the match-play format at
the time placed too much of a strain on legs he had shattered when
his car was hit by a bus five years before. O'Meara, owner of the
1998 Masters and British Open titles, becomes the sixth player to
enter the PGA with two majors in his pocket since the tournament
switched to stroke play in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara's emergence isn't a total surprise, but when he became
the oldest man to win two majors in the same year, it raised a few
eyebrows. He'd won the prestigious Pebble Beach Pro-Am five times,
but his record in majors had been spotty. No more. He's the
favorite to capture Player of the Year honors, and a win at Sahalee
would cement his reputation as one of the game's elite.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara remains unruffled, preferring to spend time with his
family and leave the intense glare of the spotlight to his close
friend and Orlando neighbor, Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could figure that out (why it took so long to win a
major),'' he said, ``I would have done it earlier.'' Then he became
serious. ``I think it's just a little bit of experience and a
little bit of wisdom. It comes with age.''
</P>
<P>
   He showed his resolve at Augusta in April when, paired with
third-round leader Fred Couples on Sunday, he hung around and
seized the green jacket with a 20-foot birdie on the 72d hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was two shots back, so I just tried not to get in my own way
and tried not to let bad shots upset me,'' he recalled. ``I
realized I was going to hit some bad shots, and I think you tend to
recover quicker if you move on and don't carry on with the feelings
that can overcome you. I've learned from that, and I think that's
really been the No. 1 key. When I won, it was a heavy weight off my
chest from that standpoint. I've played well on the Tour and around
the world. That was the one area that was missing in my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though O'Meara made his presence felt in the US Open at San
Francisco's Olympic Club, he finished tied for 32d. But he rose up
at Royal Birkdale for the British Open in blustery winds that blew
over the course at various speeds and in differing directions.
O'Meara had played the course before, so he arrived with
confidence. ``I knew it was a golf course I liked very much,'' he
said, ``and I was hoping to go there and play well but not put the
highest expectations on myself.''
</P>
<P>
   When he beat Brian Watts in a four-hole playoff, O'Meara turned
a special year into something extraordinary. After a drought of 56
majors without a win, he'd broken through in near-historic fashion,
far exceeding his goals as a youth in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to get on the Tour,'' he said. ``If I could
win one tournament, I would have thought I was going to be
successful. I think if my career came to an end and I had never won
a major championship, I probably would have been a little
disappointed. But I've had so many great things happen to me in the
game, it wasn't going to take away from all the good things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that I've won two majors in one year, it's a wonderful
accomplishment. It's great. But you've got to move forward. That's
in the past. Now is the present. We've got the PGA Championship.
We've got a great field here on a neat and different type of golf
course. I think anything is possible. I think the odds are a little
stacked against me. It doesn't stop me from going out there and
trying to give it my best. If I have a chance Sunday afternoon,
hopefully, I can dwell on what I've learned from the Masters and
the British Open.''
</P>
<P>
   Hogan, who died in July a year ago, was an early inspiration to
O'Meara. ``I actually turned pro in the fall of 1980 and I turned
pro at Mr. Hogan's office in Fort Worth,'' said O'Meara. ``I
specifically remember that day. I was the defending champion in the
US Amateur, but I'd lost to Willie Wood. I flew to Dallas, went to
Forth Worth, went to the factory, turned pro in his office, and met
him for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were several occasions where he took me aside or I went
and watched him hit golf balls. He'd watch me. I'd be struggling
with my game and I'd sit down and write him a letter asking for
help or some advice. He'd pick up the phone, call me, and tell me
he wasn't a teacher. He didn't want to teach me anything because he
didn't want to ruin my game. I didn't get to see him play, but the
mystique and getting to know him over the years was a big asset for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his rare double, O'Meara doesn't believe he's a great
player. ``There's been a handful of great players,'' he said.
``There's been a lot of very, very talented players. It's just a
matter of how you look at the word `great.' My impression of
someone who is great is someone who won a lot of major
championships and has done it consistently. They're great. I think
I'm a very good player.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara's life hasn't changed drastically since he won the
Masters and British Open, but nobody mistakes him for Mark McCumber
anymore. ``I feel I'm the same person I was before I went into the
press room on Sunday at Augusta National,'' he said. ``The thing
I've noticed is when I'm out in the public eye, people recognize me
more because of the exposure a major championship brings when you
win. I was raised by a father who's a furniture salesman, who likes
people. I like people. So I don't have a problem with it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
