<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-AIRBUD-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW `AIR BUD' HAS SOME CHARMING MOMENTS AS FAMILY FARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   How can you not love a big yellow dog who wears a goofy football
jersey and helmet and looks pretty weird catching a spiral pass?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Air Bud is back, and this time he's tackling the role of
wide receiver instead of chasing Michael Jordan on the basketball
court.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, he's also being pursued by more than a sports
agent; it seems Russian circus wrangler Natalya (Nora Dunn) needs a
star attraction for her floundering animal show.
</P>
<P>
   As long as ``Air Bud: Golden Receiver'' keeps its eye on the
ball, not the villainess and her moronic right hand man, this
second installment in the life of the sports-loving golden receiver
and his human ``best friend,'' Josh Framm (Kevin Zegers), is
charming family fare. It's only with its old lemon of a sub-plot
that things lag and Air Bud's charismatic tail fails to wag.
</P>
<P>
   Josh is moping around because his recently widowed mom, Jackie
(Cynthia Stevenson), is going on dates with a handsome new vet,
Patrick Sullivan (Gregory Harrison). Air Bud takes to Dr. Sullivan
as much as mom, so Josh is feeling doubly rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, his school football team is failing dismally. Just as
things hit an all-time low, Air Bud decides to switch sports. He's
tired of playing around with basketball players like Blue Edwards
and Lee Mayberry and he's found some new friends in the form of
Seattle Seahawks Warren Moon and Joey Galloway (who have small
roles in the film), and who are happy to show their four-legged pal
the ropes.
</P>
<P>
   Air Bud joins Josh's flailing team, and makes the news in the
process. But his ability to catch a pass also catches the eye of a
Russian circus owner who decides the dog will revive her dwindling
attendance.
</P>
<P>
   The original Air Bud died of cancer, so the canine hero is now
played by six golden retrievers, each handling a different facet of
the dog's personality and talent. Since ``Air Bud: Wide Receiver''
is a sweet comedy about growing up and dealing with loss and
tragedy, it's suitable homage to the first pup who made the
character popular. There's a nice rapport between Kevin Zeger, the
young actor who plays Josh and who has a no-nonsense screen
presence, and his canine companion.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the filmmakers didn't trust their humanistic
little core story and had to mess it all up with the broad _ and
out-of-place _ slapstick humor of the Russian circus subplot to
keep the film from feeling too sad and perhaps, intense, for kids.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a movie that feels disjointed in tone and doesn't
have the continuity to completely sustain itself. Still, it's
enjoyable because the family scenes and the sports action are
touching and a lot of fun. Only with the off-kilter silliness
provided by Nora Dunn does it go ``woof.''
</P>
<P>
   Air Bud: Golden Receiver. Directed by Richard Martin. Written by
Paul Tamasy, Aaron Mendelsohn. Cast: Kevin Zegers, Gregory
Harrison, Cynthia Stevenson, Nora Dunn. Dimension Films. 91
minutes. Rated G.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
