<HEADER>
A2121 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLIMBING-HANGOUT-ART-     08-13 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLIMBING-HANGOUT-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALTITUDE, WITHOUT THE ATTITUDE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARNOLD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH CONWAY, N.H. _ Approximately 400 vertical feet above the
treetops and at the end of his rope, Chuck Stevenson was breaking a
nervous sweat the other day trying to jam the rubber toes of his
climbing shoes between nubbins of quartz and feldspar in the
granite face of Whitehorse Ledge.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson, 43, is a television producer on vacation here with
his wife and young children. As this was one of his two days off
parent duty, Stevenson had decided to hang _ literally _ with other
upwardly mobile souls at one of New England's most popular
rock-climbing hangouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, this is quite good for me,'' Stevenson said after
completing a particularly tricky traverse on his first-ever rock
climb. At the moment, he resembled a fly on short tether, glued to
the granite with his instructor, Joe Lentini, and held safely in
place with an array of stainless steel climbing paraphernalia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it challenging to stay calm,'' said Stevenson, the
CBS-TV producer of ``48 Hours.''
</P>
<P>
   It was no blow to Stevenson's pride that one day earlier, two
dozen Girl Scouts had made the same climb. At this hangout,
everyone picks their own pace, focusing their energy acutely,
mind-cleansingly, on the process of taking one step at a time. The
exercise is frighteningly simple, and on a summer Sunday, as many
as 500 people hang hereabouts as they play the mind/body game.
</P>
<P>
   The hangout is more accurately a pair of ledges, Whitehorse and
Cathedral, which rise a maximum of 850 feet above the west side of
Mount Washington Valley in Echo Lake State Park. The granite
outcropping, which extends about one mile end to end, supports the
business of two large climbing schools and as many as 30
instructors.
</P>
<P>
   At 11 a.m. on a recent Thursday morning, 17 climbers _ about
half of them first-timers _ were feeling their way up Whitehorse
Ledge, while another 40 climbers were on Cathedral Ledge. Twenty
years ago, there might have been a half-dozen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The increasing popularity of extreme sports, and certainly Jon
Krakauer's book,'' have vastly added to rock-climbing's appeal,
said Lentini, the director of the Eastern Mountain Sports Climbing
School and a veteran climber and instructor. Krakauer's 1997
bestseller ``Into Thin Air'' depicts a harrowing climb gone wrong
on Mount Everest _ apparently with enough glamour to encourage
gaggles of daredevils onto the ledges of North Conway.
</P>
<P>
   They recently included the Veillette family of Quebec City _
Jacques and Helene, and their children Francois, 9, and Audrey, 7.
Also present were John Garvey, 30, a biochemist studying at
Brandeis University, and a dozen youngsters from Adventure Quest,
an experimental learning camp based in Woodstock, Vt. Eric Slayton,
who has climbed extensively in Europe and the United States, was
one of Adventure Quest's guides.
</P>
<P>
   At noon, Slayton was preparing to attach Melina Coogan, 13, to
an assortment of climbing gear that would hold her like a
short-leashed dog in a fall.
</P>
<P>
   A good climber _ Lentini, for example _ might fall 100 times
during a summer on these ledges. But because the safety anchors he
installs in cracks for his rope are many and closely spaced, the
tumble is never more than a few feet. Deaths and severe accidents
here are rare _ in part because Whitehorse and Cathedral ledges
have a built-in, self-regulating fear factor. Within a few steps
from the bottom, the novice climbers discover they're over their
heads if they don't have an instructor, who usually works for
either Eastern Mountain Sports or International Mountain Equipment.
</P>
<P>
   As Lentini led Stevenson in 230-foot-long legs (the length of
his rope) up ``The Slabs'' of Whitehorse, time was spent as much on
getting the knots and gear right as ascending the rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at your feet,'' Lentini frequently admonished. ``And
breathe. Oxygen is good!'' The higher they climbed, the lower the
crows seemed to be flying, and the easier the whistles could be
heard from the tourist trains plying the valley below.
</P>
<P>
   To the untrained eye, this pair of ledges resembles a rumpled
monochromatic curtain of granite. But the veteran climber here will
see upwards of 500 routes bearing names that first-time ascenders
believed captured the experience: Thin Air, Grim Reaper, Chicken
Delight, Edge of the World, and Liquid Sky, to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   The only way up Whitehorse is on foot, but the summit of
Cathedral can be reached by an auto road that brings an estimated
10,000 tourists annually to the top. They watch, often nervously,
as guides and students pop into view just a few feet away. And
sometimes they offer critiques.
</P>
<P>
   For example, last summer Brad White, an instructor with the
International Mountain Equipment Climbing School, was ushering a
hefty climber to the top under the curious gaze of a laconic Maine
tourist. Ropes led from White's waist in opposite directions, one
to the climber below, the other, an anchor, to a fence post at the
tourist's feet.
</P>
<P>
   The climber fell, the ropes tightened, and White got twanged
like a bronco rider _ all the while yelling repeatedly to his
client below: ``Don't worry. I've got you!''
</P>
<P>
   After taking in the scene for a while, the Mainer said: ``I'd
say he's got you.''
</P>
<P>
   And then he walked back to his car.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
