<HEADER>
A2122 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-STELLA-SPI &LR;      08-13 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-STELLA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STELLA' IS A MISSED OPPORTUNITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By William Arnold  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The timing of this film version of Terry McMillan's novel, ``How
Stella Got Her Grove Back,'' could hardly be better. It comes,
after all, on the tail end of a media tempest about all the recent
movies cast with aging male stars and much younger actresses.
</P>
<P>
   And it's the exact reverse of that situation: it's a romantic
comedy about the relationship between a successful, professional
woman in her 40s (Angela Bassett) and a 20-year-old man (Taye
Diggs) who doesn't have much going for himself except a winning
personality and a body by Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, it's turned out to be something of a missed
opportunity. It springs to life once or twice in the course of its
two-hour running time, but it's mostly a rough sit: a movie that's
heavy-handed, charmless and incorrigibly mediocre.
</P>
<P>
   The title character, Stella, is a hard-driving, San Francisco
stock broker and divorced mother of one who _ having just suffered
the indignity of a 40th birthday _ is feeling burned-out,
unsatisfied with her job and unfulfilled as a woman.
</P>
<P>
   One vulnerable day, she sees an enticing commercial for a
Jamaica vacation. So she drops everything, wings her way to
paradise and finds Winston _ a hunky Jamaican college graduate who
pursues and finally wins her.
</P>
<P>
   As they gradually fall in love and bound back and forth between
their native countries, the movie explores the impact of their
relationship on their respective families and the difficulties that
arise as they edge toward a life-long commitment.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of scenes along the way are funny and perceptive _ as
when Stella finds herself in a movie theater with Winston watching
a dimwitted youth comedy (something like `Booty Call'') and
realizes with horror that she's the only one in the theater not
howling.
</P>
<P>
   But these moments are few and far between. The script _ by
McMillan and the usually more reliable Ron Bass _ is otherwise so
cliched and predictable that you find yourself constantly saying
the lines in your head just before the actors deliver them.
</P>
<P>
   The first-time direction of Kevin Rodney Sullivan is even more
culpable. The first half of his movie plays like a bad episode of
``The Jeffersons,'' and the last half like ``All My Children.'' He
seems to have no subtlety or sensitivity whatsoever: his scenes are
either buffoonish, cheesy or maudlin.
</P>
<P>
   Saddled with a bad script and worse direction, star Angela
Bassett doesn't have much of a chance. Like the rest of the cast _
Diggs, Regina King, Suzzanne Douglas and Whoopi Goldberg (as
Stella's best friend) _ she always seems to be trying too hard, and
never really connecting.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many movies of the late '90s, this one seems an excuse
for a sound track album. The songs are end to end, and often
obtrusive and inappropriate to the scene. Even when one of the
characters is on her death bed, the radio beside her is blaring a
happy tune. (Her dying words to Stella are ``Turn it up, girl.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``How Stella Got Her Grove Back'' is also a movie in which the
art of ``product placement'' has run amok. It manages to work in
references to Snickers, Oreo cookies, YoYos, Cocoa Puffs and
American Airlines. And if those images of Jamaica as a sexual
paradise get to you, the number to call is 1-800-JAMAICA.
</P>
<P>
   How Stella Got Her Groove Back. Directed by Kevin Rodney
Sullivan. Screenplay by Terry McMillan and Ron Bass. Cast: Angela
Bassett, Taye Diggs, Whoopi Goldberg, Regina King. 20th
Century-Fox. 120 minutes. Rated R for sexual situations and some
nudity.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
