<SLUG> BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
_GOOD HEALTH TIED TO RELIGIOUS VIGOR   
 _HEART GROUP PUTS ITS FAITH IN DIET   
 _EUTHANASIA DATA SAID TO BE INFLATED   
 _CANCER RISK STUDY BOOSTS THE PILL  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 
 Good health tied to religious vigor
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Getting religion could be good for your health, according to new
medical research out of the Bible Belt.
</P>
<P>
   A study of more than 2,000 North Carolina residents aged 65 and
over found that people who read the Bible daily and attended
services weekly were 40 percent less likely to have high blood
pressure, compared with those who were less actively religious.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a large and clinically significant difference, one of
the largest effects thus far identified on cardiovascular health,''
said Dr. Harold G. Koenig of Duke University Medical Center, one of
the authors of the study in the current issue of the International
Journal of Psychiatry in Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers did not find such a positive health effect for
people who practiced their faith by tuning in to religious
television and radio, only for those who worshipped in the
traditional way.
</P>
<P>
   The study is part of a growing body of scientific literature
exploring links between religion and health, but the authors
caution not to take it on faith that there is a cause-and-effect
relationship. More research is needed, they said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Heart group puts its faith in diet
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While religion's role in high blood pressure is a new area of
inquiry, the role of the diet is well-studied _ yet new things are
still being learned.
</P>
<P>
   This week, for the first time, the American Heart Association is
recommending that people eat more fruits, vegetables, and low-fat
dairy products in order to prevent or reduce hypertension.
</P>
<P>
   The association, in the current issue of the journal
Circulation, cited mounting evidence that a low-salt diet rich in
fruits, vegetables, and low-fat dairy foods leads to the greatest
reduction in blood pressure. The Heart Association's longstanding
recommendation to reduce salt consumption is widely known, but
there is still controversy over sodium's role in high blood
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Euthanasia data said to be inflated
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Surveys of physician-assisted suicide and euthanasia may
overstate by as much as 20 percent the proportion of doctors who
have helped to end a terminally ill patient's suffering, according
to a new study by Boston researchers.
</P>
<P>
   During in-depth interviews with 355 cancer specialists, the
researchers found that 20 percent of the 56 oncologists who thought
they had engaged in physician-assisted suicide or euthanasia were
confusing those illegal practices with legal actions _ such as
withholding life-sustaining treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The study also found that some doctors don't understand the
difference between physician-assisted suicide and euthanasia, and
fail to observe proposed safeguards, such as referring the patient
for a psychiatric evaluation, before taking either step.
</P>
<P>
   In physician-assisted suicide, a doctor typically prescribes
drugs knowing a patient intends to use them to commit suicide; in
euthanasia, a doctor personally administers drugs, usually by
injection, to end a patient's life, said the study in the current
Journal of the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   The authors, from Dana-Farber Cancer Institute and the
University of Massachusetts, Boston, wrote that if the practices
were legalized, the ``environment might change and physicians'
awareness of and adherence to safeguards could be substantially
different. Thus, these data can only warn about areas that might be
problematic if interventions are legalized.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Cancer risk study boosts the Pill
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While the birth control pill is known to protect against ovarian
cancer in general, it has not been clear whether it protects
against the hereditary form of the malignancy.
</P>
<P>
   An international study in the current New England Journal of
Medicine provides evidence to answer that question.
</P>
<P>
   Of 161 women in the study who had sisters with hereditary
ovarian cancer, those who had ever used oral contraceptives had
about half the risk of developing the cancer, compared with those
who had never used the pill. Those who had used the pill for six or
more years had a 60 percent lower rate.
</P>
<P>
   For women with potentially cancer-causing mutations in two key
genes, ``The magnitude of the protective effect of oral
contraceptives ... is consistent with that previously found in the
general population,'' write the authors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 1320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
