<HEADER>
A2139 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-MANSION-BOS &LR;      08-13 1774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-MANSION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TIFFANY TOUCH IN THE BACK BAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARGO MILLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A century ago a stretch of Commonwealth Avenue was
paved with grand houses almost guaranteed to offend the
sensibilities of ``cold roast'' Boston. Take the corner of Hereford
Street, with its chateaux kitty-corner across the avenue. The
Burridge mansion, now a retirement residence, was French and white,
the facade fussed with griffins and dolphins. The John F. Andrew
mansion of sober brown brick, designed by McKim, Mead &AMP; White in
1884 and &UR;  &LR; now an MIT fraternity, was said to be the first residence
in the Back Bay to reflect an interest in authentic historical
models, in this case, Italian. Anchoring Commonwealth at
Massachusetts Avenue was the great red-roofed French chateau of the
Ames family, now under renovation as a private residence. Its many
reception rooms included a parlor whose walls were braided in gilt
and buttoned with glass mimicking opals.
</P>
<P>
   Only seemingly less modest, because it was a row house, was the
Ayer mansion at 395 Commonwealth. A $2 million restoration now
under way will once again make it obvious that the lady of the
house had breakfasted at Tiffany's.
</P>
<P>
   This was the jeweler's son, Louis Comfort Tiffany (1848-1933).
He and his studio of artisans are central to the American aesthetic
movement, which was this country's response to Arts &AMP; Crafts in
England, Art Nouveau in Paris, and kindred styles to be found in
every European capital from Vienna to Moscow. A ``Tiffany house''
ought to have put Frederick and Ellen Ayer on the cultural map. But
for Bostonians mired in the pieties of Colonial revival, Tiffany
was too advanced. After prim English Staffordshire and Chinese
Export china, his iridescent blown glass was, well, a bit oily.
Stained glass was suitable for church but not for home. Worse, the
Ayers had mosaic walls where sensible people had wood paneling. Or
so you can imagine the tongues wagging.
</P>
<P>
   The Ayer children would eventually marry into North Shore
society _ Frederick was a considerable horseman _ and in the
family's second-floor library a future World War II general, George
S. Patton, proposed to an Ayer daughter. But for the time being,
cold roast Boston gave the Back Bay newcomers the cold shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   An Ayer descendant thinks there were two reasons. ``New'' money
was one, and there was lots of it, made first in patent medicines
laced with opiates, such as cherry pectoral and sarsaparilla, and
then in wool, the worsteds made at the Washington Mills in Lowell
and the monopoly enforced by the American Woolen consortium. The
second was taste. ``New money and the vulgar new style,'' says
Scott &UR;  &LR; C. &UR;  &LR; Steward of Cambridge, Frederick Ayer's
great-great-grandson, who researched the family for a historical
genealogy called ``The Sarsaparilla Kings.'' Steward thinks
old-money Boston ``looked at the Ayer house and said, `Who are
these people; what's their game?'''
</P>
<P>
   The shell of the Ayer house is severe, a whitish limestone. On
dull days, it looks dull. But when the sun hits the facade, it
breaks out in jeweled effects more to be found in Byzantium than
Boston. Over the front door is a fanlight in a blue, green, and
yellow glass mosaic, and this is framed by a stone mosaic in pink
and rose. When restoration is completed, each window in the
two-story bay will again be transomed in red and yellow mosaic
glass. The corbel under the roof is also mosaic stone. Awaiting
restoration is a frieze of carved and fretted stone that screened
fifth-floor windows. The bronze front doors are gravity itself.
They still open on pure drama.
</P>
<P>
   There can't have been many Boston homes whose front hall could
pass for a stage for music and declamation. You can still see the
oval lined with light-bulb sockets meant to transform the staircase
into a proscenium arch. This touch may follow from the origins of
Ellen Ayer. She was Ellen Banning, of Saint Paul, Minn., and she
was an aspiring amateur actress when the widowed Frederick Ayer
dined with her matchmaking family only to find Ellen had slipped
away to see Edwin Booth in ``Hamlet.'' Ayer gave chase in a closed
carriage, arriving at the theater with a chaperone in tow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frederick Ayer knew men did not force themselves on young
women,'' says Steward. ``He apologized to Ellen for the length he
went to scrape an acquaintance and said he would understand if she
ran away. But as she used to tell it, an inner voice told her to
stay. He was the handsomest man she ever saw (he had piercing blue
eyes). He told her he wouldn't have begrudged her Booth in
``Hamlet'' for anything. But now he wanted to see her home. She'd
had her treat and now he wanted the treat of her company. Later
when they were courting, he asked her what she would like as a
present. He expected she would say diamonds, a spray of diamonds.
But she said, pink roses. That's what he gave her the rest of their
married life.'' Home for the first part of the marriage was in
Lowell, where they lived in heavy, dark Victorian respectability.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewing older members of his family about Ellen, Steward
found she was regarded as ``rather gushy and tiresome and a little
too dramatic.'' She was 30 years younger than her husband. They
both died in 1924. He went first, aged 96. She followed three weeks
later, surviving ``just long enough,'' says Steward, ``so she could
say she died of a broken heart.'' Their deaths, at Thomasville,
Ga., were not unexpected: Bronze coffins had accompanied them on
the train south.
</P>
<P>
   How Tiffany came to decorate the Ayer mansion is not known. Many
jobs followed from the exhibition of his work at the great
Columbian Exposition, held in Chicago in 1893, and Frederick Ayer
was among the throngs attending. ``But if I had to guess,'' says a
Tiffany expert, Alice Cooney Freylinghuysen, ``I would say Ellen
Ayer was more the client than her husband.'' Nor can Freylinghuysen
say for sure whether this is the only Boston house Tiffany did.
Records exist all over America for Tiffany-decorated churches and
public buildings but the documentation of commissions for houses is
scanty, says Freylinghuysen, because of the private nature of
residences. Only two known Tiffany interiors are still intact: the
Ayer mansion, finished in 1902, and the Mark Twain house in
Hartford, which is a decade earlier. Freyling-huysen, who is
curator of American decorative arts at the Metropolitan Museum of
Art in New York, thinks Tiffany's greatest interiors were for the
Fifth Avenue mansion of H.O. Havermeyer, the sugar king, and his
wife, Louisine, a pioneering collector of French Impressionists.
Only shards of Havermeyer opulence remain, and Freylinghuysen had
to borrow widely for the show she organized to mark Tiffany's 150th
birthday (at the Met through Jan. 31).
</P>
<P>
   The Ayers' architect of record was a New Yorker, one A.J.
Manning, for whom Freylinghuysen can find no biographical
information. Tiffany very often acted as his own architect, and in
the Ayer interiors she sees ``the same sense of drama as in the
interiors he did for himself.'' This may have been a bit much for
Frederick Ayer. ``The construction and equipment were pratically
perfect though the architectural results were a disappointment to
him,'' Beatrice Ayer Patton wrote as editor of her father's
memoirs.
</P>
<P>
   A small vestibule leads into the front hall. Ahead, flanked by
Tiffany urns of glowing favrile glass, was the dining room. This is
now the chapel of the Bayridge Residence, operated since 1960 by
Opus Dei, the lay Catholic organization; and Mass is offered for
the 70 university women living in the Ayer mansion (and the house
next door). For information about public viewings, telephone
residence director Marie T. Oates or business manager Rosemary Kite
at 617-536-2586. In late August, Ayer descendants will visit the
house during a family reunion.
</P>
<P>
   To the right is the grand staircase. In a conventional house of
the period you would see a flight of stairs rising to break right
and left at a landing. Not in the Ayer mansion: Tiffany hides these
boring upper reaches behind a great gold mosaic wall. As the sage
said, the journey is more interesting than the arrival. And so from
the front hall, Tiffany first makes you mount a series of white
marble semicircles banded in blue mosaics. We could be in Persia,
in Moorish Spain, in India. Then comes the drumroll leading to the
landing: big white marble blocks that would not be out of place on
a public building, say, the US Capitol. Then the landing itself.
</P>
<P>
   This is a little Greek temple. It is totally fake, all smoke and
(literally) mirrors, and totally magical. The silvery glass columns
are very slightly molded. They conceal long mirrored boxes. Light
playing on the mirrors causes them to reflect the glass columns.
``It's a true three-dimensional picture but in two dimensions,''
says Freylinghuysen, adding that she has never come across quite
this theater in Tiffany's other works.
</P>
<P>
   What the rest of the house looked like in Frederick and Ellen
Ayer's heyday can only be imagined. It was never photographed and
the only known rendering was a little painting, by Tiffany artist
Rene de Quelin, for a proposed smoking room. One of Steward's Ayer
aunts recalls the house as light, with lots of white and full of
color. That it was jampacked is apparent from Ellen Ayer's 1903
room-by-room inventory. The front hall was crammed with furniture
and bric-a-brac. Rugs were piled on rugs. There was a 7-foot-long
stuffed jaguar. You could tell the Ayers had ``traveled.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors had sent Frederick Ayer abroad for his health. They
closed the Lowell house, packed up the children _ Frederick had
four more with Ellen _ and spent two years based in Paris. The
winter of 1897-'98 found them in Egypt and they also visited
Istanbul. Reading Ellen's inventory, Steward has the sense the time
abroad turned into a shopping trip for a new house _ but a Boston
house. It's not known whether Frederick Ayer shopped to the extent
that John Gardner shopped with Isabella Stewart Gardner for what
became Fenway Court. In the event, Ellen got a ``French'' drawing
room, with a suite of white and gold furniture in the new, lighter
Louis XVI style and panels of Cluny lace at the windows. Also a
good many Tiffany wall chandeliers _ Freylinghuysen marvels that
the shades are still intact _ and much else that was Tiffany. Did
the effusive Ellen tell Tiffany about Frederick's blue eyes and his
pink roses and did Tiffany then translate that to the front door of
the new house?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
