<HEADLINE>
MOVING AT NATURE'S PACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I used to feel bad about how lazy I got when I hit Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Jack and I would arrive late Friday night at our cabin in the
woods. By flashlight, we'd unroll our double sleeping bag, place it
on the king-size platform we'd built ourselves, and sink into the
foam mat for a good night's sleep. In the morning, when the sun
streamed in and fresh air blew in through the screens, I'd  &UR; open my
eyes, praise the Lord for paradise, and go back to sleep. When I
got up, somewhere between 10 and 11, I'd eat the breakfast Jack had
prepared over the fire in our outdoor cooking area and make my way
to a hammock, one of two we'd strung between trees near our redwood
table. Then the two of us would read, or rock, or simply watch pine
needles falling from the trees.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually I'd wash the breakfast dishes in stream water Jack
had heated for me on the  &UR; fire; it took at least a half-hour to
clean, rinse, wipe, and put away a dozen objects. Sometimes I'd
find the energy to collect kindling for our evening fire, but when
that was done, there was nothing either one of us needed to do.
Often after lunch, I'd climb back into our sleeping bag and take a
nap. A trip to the general store 10 minutes away was a major event.
Playing cards was our equivalent of a night on the town. After
dark, we'd blow out the candles and go to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   It felt like the minute I hit Vermont, I turned into a slug _ no
energy, no backbone, no get-up-and-go. My limbs felt heavy. My
brain had all the sharpness of a marshmallow. My mind wandered from
tree to bird to sky to the fact that I was ready to eat again. Who
was this lazy ne'er-do-well? I didn't recognize the suddenly
aimless and terminally lethargic creature taking my energetic
place. I was a little ashamed of the fact that there was a sloth
lurking in my otherwise type A personality.
</P>
<P>
   I started looking at this phenomenon differently last summer,
following lunch with a friend's daughter, who was home from Santa
Fe for a brief visit. She was uncomfortable being back in New
England.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not used to this frantic pace any more,'' Ali confided.
``It feels to me like everybody here runs all the time and it
grates on my nerves. I've gotten used to moving at nature's pace.''
</P>
<P>
   Nature's pace. What a stunning idea. Perhaps all this time I'd
believed I was approaching a dead stop, I'd actually been slowing
down enough to enter into the rhythm of the life around me.
</P>
<P>
   Nature's pace. Slow enough to enjoy the song water sings when it
splashes over stones and to notice a peculiar egg mass attached to
a rock in a pond. Slow enough to follow an ant industriously
carrying a crumb home and to appreciate the lovely dance of maple
leaves when the wind blows. Slow enough to be startled by the
brilliance of a myriad stars and to delight in the moon shadows
trees cast upon a meadow at midnight.
</P>
<P>
   When I looked back at our time in Vermont, I used to feel like a
character in a children's book: ``Where did you go?'' ``Nowhere.''
``What did you do?'' ``Nothing.'' But now I see that I was
discounting all the things you can do at nature's pace.
</P>
<P>
   This is what I did last week in Vermont: I picked wild
strawberries gleaming like rubies in the grass, caught sight of a
perfectly camouflaged trout in a curve of stream, came alert to the
sound of crows pursuing an adversary through the trees, noticed
tiny pale Indian pipes growing near moss beside a trail, watched
clouds shifting shapes overhead, became mesmerized by the sight of
sparks from our campfire sputtering into nothingness, breathed in
the smoky fumes that clung like an exotic perfume to my hair and my
hands, and fell asleep so easily it seemed as if I were inhabiting
a different universe.
</P>
<P>
   Nature, our first nursemaid, imprinted herself upon my senses,
hushing me _ (itals)Stop this silly chatter!(unitals), comforting
me _ (itals)Taste this maple syrup(unitals), instructing me how to
hold the world close _ Simply (itals)pay attention(unitals). By
Sunday I felt like a recuperating patient about to be discharged
from a hospital for the soul. It may not seem like much in the
world's measure, but moving at nature's pace recovered feelings I
lose as I rush though my tasks at home: Curiosity. Delight.
Patience. Playfulness. Satisfaction. Gratitude. Peacefulness. Awe.
</P>
<P>
   Adam and Eve abandoned the Garden of Eden when they set off in a
hurry, convinced there was much to do and too few hours to do it
in. Jack and I slow down to nature's pace and find it again, poking
its way out of wild flowers, skimming ponds on dragonfly wings, and
welcoming us back with the flick of a chipmunk's tail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
