<SLUG> BC-REGEN-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`REGENERATION' A TALE OF WAR'S RAVAGES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 3{ Stars 
By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Intelligent and more complex than it appears,
Gillies Mackinnon's adaptation of Pat Barker's acclaimed World War
I novel ``Regeneration'' comes at a most felicitous time. While
``Saving Private Ryan'' is showing filmgoers the effect combat has
on fighting soldiers, ``Regeneration'' brings out their
internalized responses to the horrors of war.
</P>
<P>
   Based on true-life encounters, the story unfolds in and around a
Scottish military hospital, Craiglockart, in 1917, and is peppered
with flashbacks and a climactic move forward to the killing
trenches in France. Several famous characters are working and being
treated for shell shock there, and out of their encounters
psychiatric breakthroughs, deathless poetry and complicated new
perspectives on bravery and butchery are forged.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Pryce plays Dr. William Rivers, a pioneering Freudian
determined to cure his shattered charges through what might be
termed compassionate confrontation _ a process requiring such close
identification with the traumatized that it begins to threaten his
own sanity.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Rivers knows that Craiglockart's star inmate (and
that's precisely what he is) has no mental problems at all.
Siegfried Sassoon (James Wilby), a decorated hero and formidable
writer, has been sent to the sanitarium in order to discredit his
well-reasoned protests against the seemingly endless, intractable
slaughter. The enlightened Rivers appreciates Sassoon's pacifist
viewpoint _ but only to a point; while he struggles to protect the
antiwar firebrand's reputation, he also passionately challenges
many of Sassoon's assumptions.
</P>
<P>
   Another patient, Wilfred Owen (Stuart Bunce), is less critical.
He idolizes Sassoon's political stance and his poetry
unquestioningly. Sassoon recognizes Owen's own writerly gifts, and
if the film has a major flaw, it is the limited amount of screen
time it gives to the mentoring of Owen, who would become the
century's greatest antiwar poet.
</P>
<P>
   More attention is given, quite involvingly, to working-class
officer Billy Prior (``Trainspotting'' vet Jonny Lee Miller), who
comes to Craiglockart mute but soon speaks volumes about the social
prejudices, twisted honor and genuine devotion to duty and comrades
that have created the bloody stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   Scottish director Mackinnon (``The Playboys,'' ``Small Faces''),
working from an adaptation by producer Allan Scott (``In Love and
War''), unerringly captures the tentative mental states of men
who've seen things no one should. The film's gray, autumnal palette
also underscores the rough irony of the process at hand: These men
aren't being treated because the army cares about them, they're
just being brought back up to the functional speed their return to
the trenches requires.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Regeneration's'' most appalling sequence, Rivers observes a
more ``efficient'' military psychiatrist electroshocking a
dumbstruck recruit back into usefulness (in a great, if unintended
bit of pop-culture irony, this blithely sadistic functionary is
played by ``The X-Files' '' ominous John Neville). It's as
horrifying an expression of what 20th-century technology can do to
a warrior's soul as the screaming metal Steven Spielberg deployed
on his Omaha Beach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 1324EDT &QL; 
