u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-13 1621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEST FRIENDS DEFINE A CHILD'S SELF IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The calendar is quickly approaching the month best friends
Lauren Buckley and Iris Butnaru hate. It's not that they dread
school per se; in fact, they both think ninth grade will be
awesome. The problem is, they don't go to the same school and never
have. Since second grade, though, they've gone to the same day
camp, this year as counselors-in-training. When summer ends, so
does their daily contact.
</P>
<P>
   ``We miss each other most at the start of school,'' they say in
unison, then roll their eyes and burst into giggles.
</P>
<P>
   Iris and Lauren spent two summers in the Beaver Summer Program
before becoming best friends. That's when they also discovered they
live within biking distance of each other in Needham, Mass. Ever
since then, they're together as much as possible in the summer, at
one house or the other. The rest of the year, they talk a lot but
rarely see each other. Iris attends Dana Hall, Lauren Ursuline
Academy, and not even their extracurricular activities overlap.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the glue to this best friendship?
</P>
<P>
   ``Iris automatically understands everything about me,'' says
Lauren. ``We think the same,'' says Iris.
</P>
<P>
   How best friends come to be best friends and how and why they
remain so is often a puzzle to parents. Unsure of the dynamics and
ever mindful of potential hurts, we cross the line from being a
sounding board to trying to manage the friendship. In the process,
we risk undermining the benefits there are to be reaped from best
friendships.
</P>
<P>
   Having a best friend is one of the most important things to
happen to a 9- to 14-year-old, says child psychologist Gil Noam, a
professor at Harvard Graduate School of Education and director of
child development research at McLean Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives practice at intimacy,'' he says. ``It also meets a
developmental need by helping them answer questions like, `Who am
I? What am I good at? What do I need help with?'''
</P>
<P>
   The evolution of best friendships begins in the preschool years
when a child might have several best friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a young child, a best friend is the last person they did
something fun with,'' says school psychologist Mary Ann Rafoth, a
professor at Indiana University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Through fourth or fifth grade, something fun continues to be
what brings two children together, especially boys. ``For them,
becoming best friends almost always follows from an acitivity,''
says Rafoth. ``It's based on something very concrete: `What is your
entertainment value to me?'''
</P>
<P>
   For girls, the opposite tends to be true, says psychologist Judy
Jordan of the Stone Center at Wellesley College: ``They decide they
like to be together and then choose an activity to do together. If
the activity stops being fun for one, there's lots of accommodation
to preserve the friendship.'' With boys, it's likely the friendship
would be sacrificed for the activity.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that boys don't develop loyalty; by 12, the typical boy
has one friend he values most, even if he plays with several boys
at a time. For a girl, however, by 10, being entertained becomes
less important than being understood, and a best friendship makes
the leap into sharing feelings and secrets. ``Girls get together
just to talk,'' says Rafoth. ``If boys share secrets, it happens
during an activity.'' Iris says age 10 was exactly when her
friendship with Lauren intensified. ``In fifth grade, I didn't have
a good year,'' she says. ``I'd go to her to talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Because girls' friendships are so intense, there's more
potential for hurt. Jordan says, ``Best friends is a currency: `I
won't be your best friend anymore!' is a terrible threat to hurl.''
</P>
<P>
   It's things like this that prompt parents to leap to action.
``We panic and intervene when we shouldn't,'' says developmental
psychologist Robert Selman, who researches children's friendships
at Judge Baker Children's Center and Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   He tells parents that one function of best friendships is to
help children learn to handle conflict. ``Most of the small stuff,
parents don't even hear about,'' says Selman. ``If your best friend
betrays you, you're learning about trust: `Maybe this isn't the
person to share my secrets with.'''
</P>
<P>
   Boys tend to be more forgiving about perceived betrayals than
girls but that doesn't mean it doesn't hurt them as much or that
the friendship doesn't matter. Selman says boys let time pass, get
involved in an activity, and maybe talk about what happened, maybe
not. Girls agonize: ``Should I call? What should I say?'''
</P>
<P>
   When a child has a best friend, parents have three jobs:
</P>
<P>
   _To facilitate the friendship. ``Give them the time, place, and
space they need,'' says Noam.
</P>
<P>
   _To be available to help process the good and bad. Jordan
defines that as granting them room to figure things out on their
own, with gentle nudges here and there.
</P>
<P>
   _To be alert for red flags. Selman says the most serious
situation is if one child is in control and the other is the
follower, not just once in a while but all the time. The dangers
for the follower are of being manipulated and eventually feeling
badly about himself, and also of doing things that will get him in
trouble, like shoplifting or drugs. The danger for the bully _
``and that's what this really is,'' says Selman _ is that sooner or
later he won't have any friends.
</P>
<P>
   Intervention needs to be gentle. Selman suggests posing
questions: ``It seems to me like John always bosses you around. How
do you feel about that?'' Expect to be scoffed at: ``He's just
kidding,'' ``He really cares about me.'' Even so, it's important to
present your version of reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a kid is so invested in a friendship, the reality of being
best friends is all he sees,'' says Noam. ``Put the reality of
disappointment and frustration out there: `When a person says
negative things about a best friend behind his back, it makes me
wonder how a best friend could trust him again.''' If there's a
longstanding pattern of being bullied by a best friend or a high
turnover of best friendships after age 12 or 13, Selman and Noam
recommend consulting with a professional.
</P>
<P>
   In general, a typical mistake parents make is to see a blowup as
black or white. Jordan says, ``We either invalidate what happened _
`Oh, you're not really mad at Annie' _ or dismiss the friendship:
`You shouldn't be friends with her anyway.'''
</P>
<P>
   She says a better response tunes in to your child's feelings _
``It sounds like Annie really hurt your feelings; I'm so sorry'' _
and also supports the relationship: ``Your friendship has been so
special, maybe there's a way to work this out.'' A daughter is more
likely to engage you in discussion, a son to dismiss it: ``He's a
jerk.'' ``It's not a big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   This is where the gentle nudges come in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Casually drop suggestions,'' Jordan says. For instance,
``Sometimes friendships take a lot of work, don't they?'' or, ``I
wonder how Josh feels ...'' Similarly, if you see something
inappropriate between them, don't interrupt them to point it out
but come back to it later, privately, with your child: ``What you
said was unkind. It's not the way best friends behave.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing when to put your spin on things is tricky. Noam offers
this guideline: ``With best friends, it's often worse to intervene
than to do nothing. But when your child's in pain, look for
openings and be there when he's struggling.''
</P>
<P>
   Iris and Lauren have had few disagreements over the years.
``When we do, it's over boys or something stupid,'' says Lauren.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing worth sacrificing our friendship for,'' adds Iris.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be best friends forever, little old ladies sipping tea
together,'' says Lauren.
</P>
<P>
   Iris says, ``I want to be a doctor, she wants to be an
architect. She'll build my house and I'll deliver her babies.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
SUGGESTIONS FOR PARENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Treating a best friend as part of your family, especially
including him in outings, adds a richness to the friendship.
</P>
<P>
   _The typical child under 11 isn't able to empathize when a best
friend's feelings are hurt. If it's a feeling he's had himself, you
can remind him, ``Remember when ...?'' Otherwise, offer the
friend's perspective, but keep your expectations low.
</P>
<P>
   _Use a best friend's negative behavior to talk about what
characteristics attract and keep friends: ``What's it like to be
friends with someone who lies?''
</P>
<P>
   _Don't discourage a best friendship that crosses age boundaries.
Chronological age doesn't speak to maturation level.
</P>
<P>
   _Sometimes misunderstandings between best friends are a result
of too much time together. Build in some space for them.
</P>
<P>
   _When best friends break up, provide help in putting the
friendship in perspective but back off from the subject quickly.
It's often too painful for them to dwell on.
</P>
<P>
   _Best friends who have been separated during the summer often
have a rocky period when they first come back together.
</P>
<P>
   _Don't be concerned if your older child doesn't have a single
best friend, as long as he has friends who call him and whom he can
call.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ As they learn to walk, babies often walk on their
toes. It helps them feel balanced and usually disappears within a
few months, according to ``The Parents' Answer Book,''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Barbara Meltz's e-mail address is meltz(at)nws.globe.com. Her
columns are now on line at Boston.Com, keyword ``parenting.'' For
photocopies of past columns, send a self-addressed, stamped
envelope to Barbara F. Meltz, The Boston Globe, Box 2378, Boston,
MA 02107-2378. Please specify the column.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
