<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET DEFLATES HIGH-FLYING BANK STOCKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   These days, you take comfort where you can find it.
</P>
<P>
   At Fleet Financial Group Inc., the stock is down more than 11
percent in just the last 3 1/2 weeks. Then again, the stock of
chief competitor BankBoston Corp. is off nearly 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a rebound Wednesday, bank stocks have been getting
crushed since the stock market started selling off in mid-July. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index is down 8.64 percent since July 17, but
the Keefe Bank index has declined 15.05 percent.
</P>
<P>
   All 24 banks on the list, save one, have lost at least 10
percent in that period. In general, the smaller banks have gotten
hit even harder.
</P>
<P>
   Says Nancy Bush, an analyst with Ryan, Beck &AMP; Co.: ``There is a
real fear factor in the market right now, particularly with any
company that has any kind of international exposure.''
</P>
<P>
   With the single exception of the fourth quarter in 1994, bank
stocks have been the place to be this decade. From the start of
1990 through the end of last month, super-regional bank stocks
showed an average total return of 465 percent, easily outdistancing
the S&AMP;P, which gained about 300 percent in that same period.
</P>
<P>
   The stocks were driven by a near-perfect environment for banks:
steadily improving earnings and quality of loans; managements
focused on increasing shareholder value through stock buybacks and
other means; and a decade of merger mania.
</P>
<P>
   Now, that four-letter word _ Asia _ is raising fears the party
could be over. If Asia sparks a slowdown in the US economy,
analysts say, it will almost certainly slow loan demand and hurt
bank revenues. If a slowdown turns into a recession, look for the
banks to face higher loan losses. Any sell-off on Wall Street could
hurt profits in the investment banking, asset management, and
brokerage units the banks have been spending so much money to build
the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Asia, making money in banking has been getting
tougher. The margins in the banks' core lending businesses have
been narrowing with the flattening yield curve _ that is, the
narrowing of the gap between the short-term interest rates they pay
for money and the long-term rates they charge on loans. Competition
to make loans has made pricing extraordinarily competitive. Bank
earnings are expected to grow 10 percent next year, but the rate of
earnings growth is no longer accelerating.
</P>
<P>
   Nervous investors haven't been waiting around to find out.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston, which gets nearly 20 percent of its profits from its
Latin America operations, has been among the hardest hit among the
largest banks, falling from a 52-week high of 58 11/16 on July 8 to
44 11/16Tuesday. It rebounded Wednesday to close at 45 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   ``People sell first and ask questions later,'' said John
Kahwaty, BankBoston's director of investor relations. He says the
bank remains comfortable with Wall Street's current earnings
estimates of $3.20 a share this year and $3.54 next year.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet, on the other hand, has been hurt by concern that a
downturn on Wall Street could cut profits from its discount
brokerage unit, Quick &AMP; Reilly, and its money management unit,
analysts and fund managers say. The bank's stock has fallen from a
July peak of 88 7/16 to 78 1/4 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Eugene McQuade, Fleet's chief financial officer, predicted
profits will be higher in the second half of the year than the
first half, a record period. ``There is nothing happening on the
world front that would cause us to change our guidance'' on
earnings, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asia is a nonissue with Fleet, McQuade said: ``We make more
loans in Brockton than we do in Bangkok.''
</P>
<P>
   James Schmidt, who runs the highly regarded John Hancock
Regional Bank fund, thinks the sell-off among banks is improving
the value of the stocks. For instance, the multiple to 1999
earnings (a ratio of stock price to estimated per-share profits)
among issues in the Keefe Bank index is about 63 percent of the
multiple to earnings for the S&AMP;P 500 index; that multiple was
pushing 75 percent last year, he says. BankBoston, he notes, is
selling at a discount to the Keefe index.
</P>
<P>
   David Ellison, who runs the FBR Financial Services fund, is
looking for bank stocks to move sideways until the Asia shock
subsides. ``There just isn't enough in the fundamental side to make
things go up, or blow up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This has been one ugly period, he admitted. ``But the fact that
people are starting to notice, we must be near the bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   Or so he hopes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thomas H. Lee &AMP; Co., the Boston buyout firm, is close to a deal
to dump Seattle-based Cinnabon Inc. The maker of those tasty but
over-priced sticky buns has been a dog of an investment for Lee,
which owns more than 50 percent of the company. Cinnabon has more
than 300 stores nationwide and sales of just under $100 million. No
word on the buyer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 1328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
