<HEADER>
A2162 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GROOVE-MOVIE-LADN     08-13 1558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROOVE-MOVIE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASSETT TURNS TABLES ON HOLLYWOOD AGE RAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The din of complaints has been building since
Christmas, when filmgoers saw Jack Nicholson romance Helen Hunt and
Woody Allen once again seducing a woman young enough to be, well,
one of his wife's girlfriends.
</P>
<P>
   It increased with the Valentine season pairing of Dustin Hoffman
and Sharon Stone in ``Sphere,'' then reached Dolby theatrical sound
system decibels with the spring releases of ``Bulworth'' (Warren
Beatty-Halle Berry), ``The Horse Whisperer'' (Robert
Redford-Kristin Scott Thomas), ``A Perfect Murder'' (Michael
Douglas-Gwyneth Paltrow) and ``Six Days, Seven Nights'' (Harrison
Ford-Anne Heche).
</P>
<P>
   Old male movie stars paired on screen with actresses a
generation their junior. Feminists hated it. Actresses of a certain
age decried it. People magazine just did a cover story on it. It's
a problem everyone but film producers seems to recognize.
</P>
<P>
   But wait. What's that satisfying sound of relief? Could it be?
</P>
<P>
   Yes! Exhale.
</P>
<P>
   ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back'' didn't set out to be the film
that turned the tables on one of Hollywood's most cherished (think
Bogey and Bacall) sexist traditions.
</P>
<P>
   The second novel by ``Waiting to Exhale'' author Terry McMillan
to be adapted to the big screen, the story of a successful
40-year-old divorcee who finds happiness with a Jamaican man half
her age was loosely based on the writer's own experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stella'' became a movie because ``Exhale'' was a surprise hit
_ at a time, coincidentally, when people were wondering why no
films about upscale African-American life were being made _ not to
counteract a particularly toxic clog of movie-business male ego
displays.
</P>
<P>
   But McMillan and company know how to take advantage of good
timing when they see it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The book is based on an experience I had a few years back when
I went to Jamaica and I met a younger man _ who was not 20!''
McMillan emphasizes. ``But the story was a departure. For me, it
wasn't even about an older woman and a younger man. It was about
how I felt when I got home, which was very guilty because I was
feeling so good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking, `Oh my God, this guy is so young, he's this,
he's that.' Then I started questioning why I was feeling guilty and
what was wrong with this. I hadn't felt that good in years, and why
wasn't I entitled to? Then I started thinking about older men who
date and marry younger women. People make fun of them, but they do
it anyway. Then it became about a woman's sense of entitlement to
her own happiness in general, not just in terms of a younger man.''
</P>
<P>
   Angela Bassett, who also starred in ``Exhale,'' plays the
high-powered San Francisco stockbroker who has everything _
beautiful Marin County home, terrific son (Michael J. Pagan),
supportive and fun-loving best friend (Whoopi Goldberg's Delilah),
problematic but entertaining sisters (Regina King and Suzzanne
Douglas) _ except personal satisfaction. On an impulse, she takes a
rare vacation, with Delilah, to Montego Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Winston (newcomer Taye Diggs), a handsome young local man, comes
on to Stella. Flattered but immediately flattened by ``I'm old
enough to be his mama'' thoughts, she fends off the persistent lad
until, well, she can't anymore. But he's much more than just a
pretty face attached to a beautiful body. Winston's also the
sweetest guy in the world _ and apparently serious about a
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Which is the last thing Stella needs. And what she needs most.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stella expends a great deal of energy making sure that
everything's taken care of,'' says Bassett, who's portrayed
everyone from Lady Macbeth on stage to Betty Shabazz in two films
to Tina Turner in her Oscar-nominated performance for ``What's Love
Got to Do With It.'' ``She's quick on her feet, she makes things
happen, she's even made her relationship with her ex-husband work
so their son can be raised without any bitterness or animosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think she's been putting the needs and desires of others
ahead of her own.''
</P>
<P>
   Well put. But to get to the real question ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Could I? Should I?'' laughs Bassett, who hits the big 4-0
herself on Sunday. ``Date a 20-year-old man? Yes, I would have when
I was single. Sure I would have, if he were mature and sincere and
genuine.''
</P>
<P>
   The age thing was part of the project's attraction simply
because it was such a rare opportunity to play certain emotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This film is hitting at a very interesting time, and you can't
plan that,'' says Bassett, who is married to actor Courtney B.
Vance. ``I just knew, when I first read it, that it is different,
the reverse of what's usually seen. One reason why I wanted to do
it was because it's something seen so rarely; it's been years, back
to black-and-white movies, maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   Even then, not much. And when older women did have relationships
with younger men, such as in ``Sunset Boulevard'' and ``The Roman
Spring of Mrs. Stone,'' they were characterized as ghastly affairs
that inevitably ended badly. Later films, like ``Summer of '42''
and ``Bull Durham,'' were a bit more benign, but they, too, offered
no encouragement that such relationships could possess long-term
viability (although ``Durham'' stars Susan Sarandon and Tim Robbins
_ she is 12 years older _ have been together in real life for a
decade now).
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the double standard has always bugged Bassett.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wonder,'' Bassett says. ``Did she have to be, like,
almost a teen-ager in `Perfect Murder'? Wouldn't `Six Days, Seven
Nights' have worked with Anne Archer? I mean, would it have changed
these movies so much to include fabulous older actresses? Would it
have detracted from them? What's up with these guys, that they
don't find mature women as beautiful as they are?''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Bass, the Academy Award-winning screenwriter (``Rain Man'')
who adapted both ``Exhale'' and ``Stella'' with McMillan, is a
fountain of praise for, at least, Bassett's beauty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't really reverse the situation,'' Bass claims. ``We
don't have an old gal here; Angela Bassett has to stretch to make
you believe that she's 40. She's more beautiful in this film than
I've ever seen her, just breathtaking. She's clearly suitable in
every way as a match for this kid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, if it was a 40-year-old man who looked as gorgeous
as Angela Bassett with a beautiful, intelligent, articulate
20-year-old woman, no one would say a word,'' Bass acknowledges.
</P>
<P>
   People are already talking about one of Bass' upcoming movies,
``Entrapment.'' Something like a May/December take on ``The Thomas
Crown Affair'' (which is currently being remade itself),
``Entrapment'' stars 28-year-old Catherine Zeta-Jones (``The Mask
of Zorro'') as a cop who pretends to be a jewel thief in order to
get close to her prey _ played by Sean Connery, nearly 40 years her
senior.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of generalities batted around about older
man/younger woman situations in movies,'' Bass says. ``Star egos,
men's fantasies; but to me, it's much more about what is
appropriate to the kind of story we want to tell. In that film,
Connery plays the world's greatest thief who is challenged by this
bright woman from the up-and-coming generation. She's undercover,
trying to entrap him, and the fact that she uses her beauty for
that is reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   ``You aren't just saying artificially that every aging male
movie star is going to be attractive to a beautiful 30-year-old,''
Bass adds. ``They're put in a situation of forced intimacy _ and it
is Sean Connery, so it's not unreasonable that true romance would
ensue.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not. But no twists of reason are required to accept the
fact that Angela Bassett and Taye Diggs make one fine-looking
couple. The 26-year-old New Yorker, who makes his film debut in
``Groove'' after a run in the Broadway production of ``Rent,''
found the screen pairing so natural that he's somewhat bemused
about the to-do over it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize there was such a hubbub about this,'' Diggs
says. ``When I was filming, I didn't even let that affect the way I
approached the role. I just played this one Jamaican cat; I didn't
take into consideration that she was older and he was younger
because I don't think the character cares.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to say that I am proud to be a part of this, but I also
think that it's silly,'' Diggs adds. ``It's silly to make a big
deal out of something like this. But dealing with the society that
we're in, with all of its goofy stigmas and stereotypes, I have to
be proud that this movie got made.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though making a stand against old-guy hegemony was not her
intention, no one could be prouder of what ``How Stella Got Her
Groove Back'' accomplishes than author McMillan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had it with the double standard,'' she says. ``I'm sick
of these movies, and Hollywood should really get wind of it. When I
saw Michael Douglas with Gwyneth Paltrow, I just said, `They cannot
be serious.' These great actresses, the studios think they're passe
when they hit 45, 50 years old. But these guys can keep making
movies until everything on 'em is gray and wrinkled. They don't
even need facelifts to get these young girls _ and we're supposed
to believe that?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
