u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISLAND-COLONY-BOS &LR;      08-13 1564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISLAND-COLONY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEDDOCKS ISLAND COLONY A LIFE FROM THE PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By IRENE SEGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEDDOCKS ISLAND _ When Jack and Mary Downey bought their summer
cottage more than three decades ago, a friend asked where exactly
it was. Oh, the Downeys replied, it's right next to the Kennedy
compound.
</P>
<P>
   Ha! Some Kennedy compound! Do the Kennedys summer with no
electricity and no running water and no cars and no telephone
service and outhouses instead of bathrooms? Do they zip via skiff
to their summer homes in 10 minutes from Quincy and 25 minutes from
Winthrop and 5 minutes from Hull? Do they stroll down a grassy path
to an abandoned Army fort? Do they gaze from their beach at the
Boston skyline and the Nut Island sewage treatment plant? Do they
summer alongside abandoned housing? Do they live in an official
state park and federal recreation area?
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe not the Kennedys you're thinking of, the ones with
that compound in Hyannis Port. But the Downeys' neighbors sure do.
So do the Downeys and everyone else in the century-old summer
colony on Peddocks Island, a 1 1/2-mile-long spit of land in Boston
Harbor, 7 1/2 miles from the State House. The colony of 47 cottages
is the waning vestige of an era when the harbor islands were home
to fishermen, soldiers, and vacationers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like you're standing on the other side of Alice's looking
glass,'' says Mary Downey, who will say only that she's in her 60s.
``We're here like the 17th century. It's pitch dark here, and you
see the skyline of Boston with all the lights.''
</P>
<P>
   These days the Peddocks Island cottagers also see the empty
shells of cottages their neighbors have sold to the Metropolitan
District Commission, tangible evidence that today's owners are the
last generation that will spend its summers here. The MDC acquired
the island by eminent domain in 1970, and in 1990 moved to evict
the cottagers by 1992. Controversy led to a committee, which, in
turn, led to a compromise. Whoever owned the cottages in 1990 may
use them for the rest of their lives. Then the state gets them.
Anyone who wants to sell a cottage must sell to the MDC, and anyone
who wants to stay must pay the MDC $400 a year. &QL; 
 &QL; 
A long tradition ends
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two years, 11 cottagers have sold to the MDC for
anywhere from $4,000 to $14,400, depending on the condition of the
property. A 12th sale is almost final. The MDC sees this as the
resolution of the problem, as harbor region supervisor Holly
Richardson puts it, of ``the private use of public land.'' To the
cottagers, is the end of a long tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, 69-year-old Mary Enos, wife of a retired cable splicer,
looks out her cottage at three vacant shells. ``It's lonely,'' she
says. ``These were all people my husband grew up with.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a rustic colony of interconnected families, where
newcomers have been for 20 years and oldtimers boast roots _ and
relationships _ that go back five generations to the Portuguese
fishermen who set up camp here. It's a working-class village where
not much money got you not much house in a great location.
</P>
<P>
   Take 72-year-old Anna Kendall (nee Kennedy, hence the joke about
the Kennedy compound), whose ties go back to 1888. She's related,
via her grandmother's first husband, to the Enoses, whose family
has also been here more than a century. Kendall's daughter,
38-year-old Sheila Martel, heads the island association and lives
in the cabin she bought 20 years ago for $4,500 from her
grandfather's best friend.
</P>
<P>
   The cottages in question are fragile, weatherbeaten structures
of clapboard and tar paper, some freshly painted and others quite
dilapidated. Some were floated from Long Island, another island in
the harbor, in 1887 when fishermen there were displaced by
construction of a public almshouse. Today four cabins are occupied
year-round. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Country life, cell phones
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mary Downey exaggerated with her suggestion that life here
resembles life in the 17th century, when the island provided
pasture for mainland farmers. Three centuries ago you wouldn't have
found batteries, some charged by rooftop solar panels, running
pumps bringing water from plastic rain barrels, or wells to kitchen
sinks. You couldn't buy jugs of drinking water to bring here in
your motorboat. Nobody had a beeper or used a cell phone, as the
Downeys once did, to dial Domino's Pizza on the mainland and
request delivery. ``They wouldn't come,'' laughs Jack Downey, a
retired salesman.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, life here remains rustic, out of synch with the
late 20th century. People read at night by kerosene lantern. For
years, cottagers tapped into a line that took water from Nut Island
in Quincy to the fort at the far end of the island, but that ended
in 1990 when a dredge broke the pipe. Refrigerators and stoves run
on propane. Backyard necessities include wash basins and scrub
boards. Want hot water? Try heating it on the stove or collecting
rainwater in black barrels instead of white or leaving a plastic
bag filled with water basking on the roof of your outhouse so you
can have a warm shower later.
</P>
<P>
   ``My granddaughter is 7, and she wants to know, `if you don't
have a TV, how do you watch videos?' I said, `That's the whole
point,''' says Mary Downey. ``Islanders have a tendency not only to
be more independent but also more self-sufficient. You have to
develop the skills for survival.''
</P>
<P>
   Island self-sufficiency extends to scouring the beaches for
driftwood and other useful items because it is so difficult to
bring furniture there. Kendall's husband, Wesley, 72, a retired
recreation supervisor, built the benches in their yard from
driftwood and braces that a contractor gave him. The Martels built
the picnic table in front of their cottage from driftwood. They
found another washed ashore that's now on their back deck.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an easy life,'' says Sheila Martel, the Kendalls'
daughter, a buyer for Polaroid who one recent Saturday helped mow a
grass road on Peddocks. ``My mother wouldn't let me date anyone who
didn't like the island.''
</P>
<P>
   As beautiful as Peddocks is, with terns nesting on one end and
red-winged blackbirds winging overhead and wayward day lilies from
cottagers' gardens taking root among the wild rose hips and
soapwort, it is not pristine. Harbor water is cleaner than it was _
the other day children delighted to a harbor seal darting among
their rafts _ but after heavy rains the whiff of sewage overflow
from Nut Island still wafts toward the island. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Heyday long gone
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the early decades of the century, Peddocks vaunted two inns
and a general store. One cottage housed a teahouse. Another
reputedly housed a house of ill repute frequented by soldiers from
Fort Andrews. During World War II, submarine nets off the island
protected the shipyard in Quincy, and up to 1,500 Italian prisoners
of war were housed here. In the era before so many women worked
outside the home, families arrived as soon as school ended and
stayed until Labor Day. Men commuted by boat.
</P>
<P>
   That heyday is long gone. Although a few families still live
here all summer, others are weekend cottagers or visit for shorter
vacations. Grown children often live far from Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Then, of course, there's the lengthy, uneasy denouement with the
MDC. Vacant buildings invite trouble, even on small islands. Last
summer, Marie Chiricosta's nephew found drug paraphernalia in her
old cabin. ``I felt sick,'' says 68-year-old Chiricosta. ``When you
know how I worked for that place. To think that it ended up that
way is hard to take.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the remaining families enjoy the time they have left.
They grab a guitar and build a bonfire on the sand _ below the tide
line because you get fire-paranoid on an island with no running
water _ and sing ``Sitting on the Dock of the Bay.''
</P>
<P>
   Children scavenge the shore for periwinkles to string into
necklaces and beach glass to sell to tourists. Jack Downey
remembers the day decades ago when island children ran to him with
a box they had found washed ashore from a Norwegian fishing boat.
Mistaking the Norwegian labeling for German, they interpreted it as
proof that the U-boat captain Heinrich von Fritz featured in
Downey's storytelling was real, after all.
</P>
<P>
   Almost a half century ago, Anna Kendall helped start the
tradition of a Labor Day costume parade to end the summer season.
Now her granddaughter, Alyssa Martel, who dressed as the big rock
last year, and her 6-year-old grandson, Joseph Martel, who was a
bonfire, are talking about putting a raft on a cart, donning
swimsuits, and appearing as a float this year.
</P>
<P>
   By the time cottagers return next summer, the MDC hopes to have
bulldozed the cabins it owns and to have opened a new campground. A
new $2 million pier will be open by then, making the island
accessible to water taxis and ferries two years after a tugboat
accident destroyed the old public dock. Perhaps more owners will
sell to the MDC, and the colony will shrink further.
</P>
<P>
   Martel plans to be back _ ``This is my life'' _ and so does
63-year-old artist Claire Hale of Georgetown, whose family has been
here since 1917 and who wears a ``Peddocks Island Forever''
T-shirt. ``I have 13 grandchildren,'' says Hale. ``They're very sad
about it. I just say enjoy it while we have it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
