<HEADLINE>
AUTHORITIES HOPE QUAKE WILL PROMPT SAFETY AWARENESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM HERRON ZAMORA and LE'VADA GRAY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Emergency personnel in the San Francisco Bay
area hope the region's latest earthquake was enough to jolt people
into thinking about quake safety and preparedness.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Geological Survey said the quake, measuring 5.4 on the
Richter scale, occurred early Wednesday with the epicenter about 90
miles southeast of San Francisco, near San Juan Bautista. The quake
caused some damage to highways but no injuries were reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a minor earthquake, but it lets people know we should
always be ready for the big one,'' said Sherman Ackerson, spokesman
for the San Francisco Police Department. ``In California, you can
never forget about earthquakes ... but it's human nature to focus
on other things.''
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Jerry Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't feel a tremor for a while, it's easy to just go
on with life,'' said Ramirez, a San Mateo County resident who works
in San Francisco. ``No one sits around and thinks about this all
the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross was optimistic that the quake was big enough to
stir interest in earthquake preparedness.
</P>
<P>
   ``This earthquake has been a friendly reminder that emergencies
can and will happen,'' Red Cross spokesman Gregory Smith said. ``We
invite the public to help us meet this challenge by taking the
necessary steps to prepare for this type of emergency.''
</P>
<P>
   Susie Wong, public information officer at the state Office of
Emergency Services, said some people won't be moved by Wednesday's
quake. She said it would take a major earthquake for those people
to get serious about safety preparations.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when we get a lot more interest,'' Wong said. ``It's
something we have to work on each year.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than shaking a few walls and rattling some nerves,
Wednesday's quake caused little damage.
</P>
<P>
   Seismologists said Wednesday that the latest earthquake was the
eighth of its size in the past 60 years, and countless smaller
quakes jiggle the region continually.
</P>
</TEXT>
