<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-LOVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER LOVE AFFAIR? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ The magical moment Davis Love 3d had always
dreamed about happened a year ago in Mamaroneck, N.Y., when he
walked up the final fairway of the 79th PGA Championship at Winged
Foot with the tournament in hand. A rainbow enveloped the course as
Love won his first major title.
</P>
<P>
   Love is here to defend his title at Sahalee CC, and the last guy
to do that was Denny Shute, who beat Jug McSpaden in 1937 when the
tournament was still a match play event. ``It would be a thrill to
have a chance on Sunday, and I'd like to break that record,'' said
Love Wednesday. ``It's going to be an interesting tournament, it's
a completely different golf course.''
</P>
<P>
   Love, whose 66-71-66-65-269 lifted him to a five-shot victory
over then reigning British Open champion Justin Leonard, said the
course (par 70, 6,906-yard) requires accuracy because of the trees
and deep rough that line the fairways. ``Straight works,'' Love
said. ``It's the main thing. You just have to hit a lot of
fairways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we're used to that. In most of the majors, your
accuracy off the tee is a premium. But I think this one is going to
be different. One guy might be comfortable with a 3-wood or a
4-wood, someone else with a 1-iron. It's going to be a lot of that,
trying to get the ball in position off the tee and it's not that
short. For me it's one or two drivers on the whole golf course.''
</P>
<P>
   Love has been beset by a sore back, but he said it feels 90
percent better. ``The lack of playing and cutting back on traveling
has really helped,'' he said. ``I was fortunate it was just hurt
and not a bad back. So once I got the swelling out and the
tightness out, it's gotten a lot better. I feel fortunate. It was
just a tough time when any time I sat on an airplane of hit golf
balls it never got better. It just got worse.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory at Winged Foot erased the label of the best player
never to have won a major championship and did a lot for his
confidence. ``I feel I've been there before,'' said Love. ``You're
still nervous. You still want to win. You're still excited. You
still have to prepare, but you have a more comfortable feeling
going in. I know what it takes, what it's going to take on Sunday
to win here. I've done it before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
