<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BRIGHT FUTURE FOR SAFETY LEE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ If it's true you have to be smart to play
free safety, then the Patriots are academically deep at the
position.
</P>
<P>
   The starter, Willie Clay, attended Georgia Tech. The backup,
Chris Carter, is a medical school student at the University of
Texas. Also in camp is Harvard's Jeff Compas. And to top it off,
Wyoming's Brian Lee is one of only two rookies (along with Peyton
Manning) to earn both All-America and Academic All-America honors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of my parents were teachers,'' said Lee, who's from
Arvada, Colo. ``So it was stressed to me every day that I had to
get my schoolwork done and do my share of studying. I've always
been dedicated to my studies. For me, that's always come first.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who holds a degree in business management, has apparently
been studying the playbook as well. Through two exhibition games,
he's the team's co-leader in tackles with nine (tied with defensive
end Greg Spires). Lately, he's been getting more playing time
because of Carter's injury, which kept him out of Sunday's 28-0
loss to the Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   He's playing regularly and thinks that makes the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely,'' he said. ``Earlier in camp, I'd just be sitting
there. It's hard to learn without being on the field. I've gotten
reps with the twos (second team) or threes (third team), and you
get experience going up against some of the tougher receivers.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-2-inch, 200-pound Lee was signed by the Patriots as a
free agent. It is rare for an All-America defensive back to go
undrafted, and Lee figures it reflects NFL misgivings about his
lack of speed _ 4.5-4.7 seconds in the 40-yard dash. There are
probably other NFL free safeties who aren't considered fast,
either, but they compensate with experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea, really, why I wasn't drafted,'' said Lee, who
returned eight interceptions for 196 yards last season and also had
eight pickoffs the year before. ``I don't know if I should have
been drafted. I don't know why I wasn't drafted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the fastest guy around, so I try to do more by
positioning myself than anything. Sometimes I find myself in a bad
position and I'm watching people go by me, but the longer I've been
out there, the more I'm getting used to things.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee was thrilled to be named an All-American but is prouder of
the academic honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the credit goes to my parents,'' he said. ``They kept me
in class and they set the standard that doing my homework was
important. Most important. My parents are both elementary teachers,
so they stressed good acdemics. I had no choice, but once I got to
college, the good study habits I had continued. Even though as
football players, we all had a grueling schedule in terms of
practice time, I was in a setting in Wyoming where there wasn't
much pressure and everything was pretty easygoing.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his football assets, he said, ``I don't think I bring
anything special. I'm not a speed demon. I'm a solid player who
knows his responsibilities. They can count on me to do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   That's precisely it. Lee isn't fancy. He's not fast or overly
talented. But at every level, he's performend well. He has always
found a way to get to the ball. Against Hawaii last year, he made
11 tackles and intercepted two passes, running one back 56 yards
for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday in practice, Lee intercepted a pass, as he did the day
before. In his dreams, he intercepts a pass in an exhibition game
and impresses the coaches enough to keep him on. But he knows
there's a long way to go before he convinces anyone he's an NFL
player.
</P>
<P>
   Assessing his performance in camp, Lee said, ``I think I'm
improving day by day. I'm not anywhere close to where I want to be.
I was nervous and tentative at first, but the extra reps are
keeping me more attuned to what I'm doing. My play has improved.
All the DBs help me out. Willie and those guys are great. (Larry)
Whigham has really helped me out as far as how much communication
you need on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough job covering these receivers. My heart goes out
to the corners on every play. The receivers are top-level. I can't
give them an inch.''
</P>
<P>
   If he doesn't do it with speed or experience, then what?
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider myself someone who can get the receivers down,''
said Lee. ``I'm the last person out there and I have to get them
down. I'm not a big hitter. I'm not going to hurt anyone out there.
Anyway, every time I try to line someone up for a big hit, they go
right by me. So I try to do things that are technically sound. It
may not be flashy, but it's always worked for me. I've been able to
do my job.''
</P>
<P>
   As a free agent, he had a few job opportunities other than New
England. But being a West Coast kid all his life, he wanted to
explore the world a little. When his agent mentioned New England,
he jumped at the chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounded like the best opportunity for me professionally,''
said Lee. ``It was a location I'd never experienced. I'd never been
out this way. Being out in the Boston area excited me. Even if I
don't make it, it's something I wanted to experience.''
</P>
<P>
   If he doesn't make it, Lee has at least experienced an NFL camp.
He thinks he can hold his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I can play,'' said Lee. ``There's so much talent out
there and so few spots, you never know. There are a lot of DBs
competing. It's going to be hard to make it, anyway. But at least I
can say I took my best shot. If nothing else pops up, I can get on
with my life without any sense that I've left something
unfulfilled.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
