<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERTIMES-EDUCATION-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDUCATION 
 WAR STORIES BECOME LESSONS FOR COMPUTER STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  By PAMELA MENDELS 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The movie debut scheduled for tonight will not be in a glamorous
Hollywood theater. No actors will step out of limousines to the
flash of news cameras. And it is unlikely that reviewers will give
their thumbs up or down to the production.
</P>
<P>
   But there will be plenty of drama at the Digital Clubhouse in
Sunnyvale, Calif., where the stars will be a few unsung heroes of
World War II who have decided to let their stories be told in
mini-documentaries made on computers.
</P>
<P>
   The three-to-five minute movies cannot compare in scope and
budget with ``Saving Private Ryan,'' Steven Speilberg's homage to
the soldiers who participated in D-Day. Still, they are gripping
true-to-life tales wrested from a war that engulfed much of the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, Harold C. Schauer's story. Now an 81-year-old
retired businessman, he was a U.S. Air Force pilot captured and
held in a German prisoner of war camp in Poland. Then there's Rose
M. Lesslie, who as a teen-ager helped build parts for surveillance
blimps, while waiting 39 months for the soldier who she ultimately
married to return home from the Pacific. There's the woman who grew
a Victory Garden, so more food could be spared for the war effort;
the former Red Cross worker, and the ex-Navy man who remembers a
visit from Franklin Delano Roosevelt aboard his troop carrier.
</P>
<P>
   They and others have contributed their recollections to the
World War II Memories Project, which seeks to link veterans and
others who lived through the conflict with tech-savvy young people
who are preserving their stories in short movies created on
computers with editing and graphics software.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought: 'War War II is the defining moment of the 20th
century. Let's see if we can use 21st century technology to
document it,''' said Warren Hegg, executive director of the Digital
Clubhouse Network, a nonprofit organization that teaches digital
literacy through free and low-cost programs.
</P>
<P>
   The hope is that the young people working on the project will
not only hone their computer skills, but also learn something about
the magnitude of the war that happened so many years before they
were born.
</P>
<P>
   Hegg says the idea for the effort was conceived long before
``Private Ryan'' was released, when, two years ago, a Clubhouse
volunteer asked his grandfather to work with him on a mini-movie
about the older man's experience of being wounded at the grueling
Battle of the Bulge.
</P>
<P>
   Hegg decided there must be many others, veterans and civilians,
who had similarly important or moving stories to preserve, and that
if these tales were not recorded soon they would die off with the
aging generation that lived through them.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this summer, the Clubhouse began to seek people from the
World War II era to share their stories _ advertising at senior
centers and other places with a poster showing the familiar Uncle
Sam pointing his finger and saying ``We Want You Again.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, nine of them began working with small production
crews, including teams of Clubhouse volunteers as well as students
from two computer classes at nearby Cogswell Polytechnical College,
who elected to participate in the project as part of their
coursework.
</P>
<P>
   Schauer, meanwhile, enthralled his producers with a story that
began when he was a 24-year-old B-24 pilot on a mission to destroy
a German munitions factory in Hungary. It was the summer of 1944.
Schauer, a second lieutenant, led a crew of 10 men whose plane was
shot down. One man was lost; another, who ultimately lost a leg,
was hospitalized and later repatriated.
</P>
<P>
   Schauer parachuted out of the plane about 70 miles from
Budapest. Like seven others who were aboard, he eventually ended up
in a prisoner of war camp _ in Schauer's case, one for American,
British and other officers near what is now Wroclaw, Poland.
</P>
<P>
   Schauer spent the next nine months of his life in the hands of
the Germans, convinced, like his fellow prisoners, that the Allies
would win the war but always wondering when. He and his fellow
inmates _ who he says were treated relatively well by their captors
_ followed the progress of the war by listening to BBC news reports
from a smuggled-in radio at night. It wasn't until April 1945 that
the prisoners, then in a camp in Germany, were liberated by
soldiers from Patton's army.
</P>
<P>
   The prevailing mood, Schauer says, was not fear, but boredom.
``We'd walk the perimeter of the camp and think a lot about what
was the first meal we'd have when we got home,'' he recalled. In a
world where bread, cereal and Red Cross-issued tins of Spam were
the standard diet, Schauer said, he pined for steak and French
fries.
</P>
<P>
   Amy R. Jones, one of the producers of Schauer's story, is a
23-year-old studying computer and video imaging at Cogswell. She
said that learning his story gave her a sense of the idealism that
must have prevailed during the war years and that is somehow
missing in the 1990s. ``They wanted to go and fight because they
felt strongly about it,'' Jones said. ``You look around today and
no one feels strongly enough about something to say: 'OK. I want to
go into battle and risk my life.'''
</P>
<P>
   Another of the producers, John C. Matuk, said he felt an
immediate bond with Schauer, because he, too, is a veteran, having
served in the Navy during the Persian Gulf war. One aspect of
Schauer's story that interested him, Matuk said, was the ingenuity
of the prisoners, who were able to do things like fashion a small
stove out of the tin cans that held their rations.
</P>
<P>
   The movie about Schauer will feature a photograph of that stove,
as well as a picture of the cover on the menu the prisoners made
for their Thanksgiving 1944 dinner _ a picture of a can of Spam
looking slightly like a turkey.
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   RELATED SITES: (each address preceeded by http://www.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Digital Clubhouse:digiclub.org/
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   (Pamela Mendels, a Manhattan-based writer, covers education,
government, censorship and civil rights issues for CyberTimes.)
</P>
