<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERTIMES-ARTS-AT-LARGE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTS(AT)LARGE 
 PROTEST AIMS TO PAINT THE WEB GRAY 
</HEADLINE>
  By MATTHEW MIRAPAUL 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Ann Stretton is angry, she sees gray instead of red.
</P>
<P>
   Stretton is infuriated when the graphics she creates and
displays online are copied and reproduced elsewhere on the Web
without proper acknowledgement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been blatantly plagiarized, mimicked and ripped off,''
Stretton fumed in a telephone interview from her studio in Madison,
Wis. ``Sometimes it just makes you want to pull everything off''
the Web, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Stretton, an artist who freelances as a Web designer, is a
member of the Digital Divas, an online organization of 50
tech-savvy women. When talk on their message board turned to
copyright violations earlier this year, Stretton suggested making a
Web-wide gesture that would promote respect for the intellectual
property of the artists, musicians, authors and programmers who
post their creations on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   As conversations continued, the idea for Grey Day was born. The
Digital Divas are asking adherents to their cause to replace the
opening pages of their Web sites with gray pages for a 24-hour
period on October 1. The pages will be a monochromatic metaphor for
``pulling everything off'' as a protest against those who copy and
disseminate original work without permission, credit or
compensation.
</P>
<P>
   The action is intended to demonstrate that the Web would be as
colorless and dull as an empty gray browser window without the
fluorescent images, bluesy melodies, purple prose and silvery code
supplied by the creative community.
</P>
<P>
   Through little more than a word-of-mouth campaign since the
event site was launched in late April, Grey Day has gained more
than 2,500 supporters, according to Timmi Sommer, a graphic artist
and Web designer in Lancaster, Calif. To expand the reach of the
effort, the site's home page offers information in a dozen
languages.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the supporters to date are individuals, but there are
some notable exceptions, including Microsoft in Australia, the
Internet directory Bigfoot and the rock band drivin n cryin.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Young, who designed the Atlanta band's site, said, ``When
you maintain rare pictures, people are apt to copy them without us
ever knowing it. I've come across pages where they use an image off
our page even though we explicitly state that permission must be
granted.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it was not conceived as such, the event represents
another example of the evolving tension between those who seek to
maintain the anything-goes spirit of the early Internet and those
who are conscious of the more commercial nature of the mass medium
it is rapidly becoming.
</P>
<P>
   As a group, the Digital Divas are not proposing a particular
solution to the problem of copyright infringement other than
education, hoping that an increased awareness of the value of
intellectual property will reduce the number of violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it is just plain ignorance,'' Stretton said. ``I
don't mean ignorance as a bad word. They (copyright violators) just
don't know. Mainly, those are the people we're targeting. You can't
change someone who's decided to be a thief.''
</P>
<P>
   Sommer actually opposes legislative attempts to deal with the
issue, preferring a more personal approach. ``We do not want some
fool up in Washington making legislation that will turn the Net
into something it was not built to be,'' she said. ``We can police
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Sommer recently discovered that all of the images from one of
her online art galleries had been republished, in modified form, on
a Swedish site. ``They were giving them away,'' she recalled. ``And
then it's the domino effect. The people who visit there take them
and it goes on and on and on.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than retain a lawyer, she contacted the couple
responsible for the site. After an exchange of e-mail messages, the
Swedes apologized and her material was removed.
</P>
<P>
   As always, she said, common courtesy could have prevented the
</P>
<P>
   episode. ``You write the artist, you ask permission,'' she
explained. ``Nine out of 10 times, that person will say yes. Most
people respond to direct communication.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, when she uncovers a violation of her copyright, a
polite request to take down the graphics generally does the trick.
``In the three years I've been on (the Web), I haven't had one
(violator) that's refused,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   While there has been scant resistance to the initiative, Faith
Kaminsky, a Manhattan attorney and aspiring Web artist, said a few
have accused her Diva colleagues of promoting censorship, a charge
she said misrepresents the group's goals.
</P>
<P>
   But Tony DeGidio, a lawyer in Toledo, Ohio, has a different
concern than censorship.
</P>
<P>
   DeGidio represents the Online Guitar Archive, commonly known as
OLGA. The Internet-based repository for user-submitted song chords
and lyrics was shuttered on June 9 after a large music publisher
threatened legal action over alleged copyright violations.
</P>
<P>
   DeGidio conceded that few could quibble with the concept of
respecting intellectual-property rights. But he also argued that
the financial interests of the individual artist should not
necessarily prevail over the benefits a creative work provides to a
wider society. In some interpretations, sharing copyrighted
material is a ``fair use'' under the law that encourages further
creativity.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Internet turns gray, one should not dwell so much on
the poor authors who have lost their income from licensing and
royalties,'' DeGidio said. ``They should more importantly consider
the loss that society has suffered by not having the Internet that
day.''
</P>
<P>
   The event was itself inspired by a color-oriented antecedent.
Since 1995, supporters of the Day Without Art Web Action have
recognized World AIDS Day by blackening their pages on December 1.
Many artists also support the Electronic Frontier Foundation's
anti-censorship campaign by displaying a blue ribbon on their
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Stretton said the Digital Divas expect the event to become an
annual one. To give proponents a visual means of showing their
support, she designed a simple logo, a black button, that can be
added freely to Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   The button now appears on many of the 2,500 sites. Ironically,
Stretton receives no credit for the design, a situation she happily
accepts.
</P>
<P>
   But another development has probably served to remind her of the
need for the online event.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strange thing is,'' she said, ``I've seen the button being
used in ways that don't link it to Grey Day.''
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   RELATED SITES: (each address preceeded by http://www.)
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   _ Grey Day:www.greyday.org/
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Matthew Mirapaul is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.)
</P>
