<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHE MAKES OPPONENTS CRY UNCLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WELLESLEY, Mass. _ Her 81-year-old grandmother and three of her
younger cousins watched her play for the first time Tuesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   For years, they've been hearing about the family's first
professional athlete, but it wasn't until the Corel WTA Tour made a
stop at Babson this week that members of the Shaughnessy clan
finally got to see Meghann play tennis. She beat Australia's Nicole
Pratt, 6-2, 6-0, and today plays Corina Morariu in the round of 16.
</P>
<P>
   In the interest of full disclosure, I am Meghann's uncle and
there will be nothing objective about this column. Having been on
vacation for three weeks, I figured I'd take the easy route back
and interview someone who's not a threat to bash me over the head
with a Louisville Slugger. My 19-year-old niece seemed like safe
subject matter.
</P>
<P>
   Meghann is ranked 14th in the US and 84th in the world. She may
not be quite ready to beat Martina Hingis and Monica Seles just
yet, but our planet is a big place and there's a lot of competition
out there.
</P>
<P>
   It's a tickle to have a professional athlete in the family,
particularly when you make a living covering sports. Shaughnessy
family members are trained to check the small type in the back of
the sports page every week. That's how we learn that Meghann played
Irina Spirlea in Berlin and Henrietta Nagyova in Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
   Most families have children who play sports. How many parents of
Little League ballplayers dream about Joey Junior getting to the
majors and smacking one over the wall at Fenway? How many mothers
of tiny gymnasts imagine they're looking at the next Kerri Strug?
How many New England skating dads wonder if the 4-year-old on
double runners might someday be Nancy Kerrigan?
</P>
<P>
   What are the odds of making it this far? The Corsi family of
Newton knows the answer. Ditto for the Merlonis of Framingham, the
Curleys of Duxbury, the Wolterses of Holliston, and the Amontes of
Hingham.
</P>
<P>
   Meghann is just starting to make her way in the pro tennis
world, but she's already played in the main draw of the US Open and
will be there again late next month. In junior competition, she won
the US Tennis Association 16-and-under Clay Court Championship when
she was 14 and made it to the Frech Open final three years later.
Her rank has been going up steadily for the last six months, and
she hopes to ultimately break into the Top 10.
</P>
<P>
   Her gene pool gave her a nice jump start. Meghann's dad played
four years of college baseball and basketball and hit for the
Orleans Cardinals in the Cape Cod League in 1968. Her mom is a
former model and a professional nutritionist.
</P>
<P>
   I see Meghann now _ a 5-foot-11-inch world traveler who looks
great in skirts and hits her serve harder than Randy Johnson throws
his fastball _ and I remember a tiny baby born in a tiny town in
Virginia in 1979. It was Walton's Mountain stuff. She was a
droopy-eyed blond toddler, always trying to keep up with two older
brothers.
</P>
<P>
   When she was 2 1/2 years old, Meghann and her mom visited my
wife and me in Washington. We took her to the Smithsonian and went
to great lengths to explain the importance of a Conestoga wagon.
Meghann said, ``Who cares?'' and ran off. Saying goodbye that day,
my wife bent down and asked Meghann for a ``smack.'' Showing early
signs of a strong forehand, Meghann busted her aunt right in the
chops.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in Arizona, she was an unusually talented and
competitive girl. When she was 8, she regularly beat me in games of
HORSE on her driveway basketball court. By the time she was 10,
Meghann was traveling around the country as a finalist in
NBA-sponsored pop-a-shot competitions.
</P>
<P>
   But tennis was her love. I remember kicking her butt on a
hardcourt surface when she was about 4 1/2 feet tall and thinking
to myself, ``This is the last time I'm ever going to beat this
kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Now she travels around the world with her coach, Rafael Font de
Mora, playing 35 tournaments annually and spending the rest of the
time in Florida, working on her shots and upper-body strength. She
loves Paris and Spain but doesn't think much of England because
``the food is terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Her lifetime prize money is $105,926, but that hasn't nearly
covered three years of expenses, and Meghann figures she won't be
operating in the black until she cracks the top 50. Morariu, her
opponent today, is ranked 35th in the world and has beaten her in
past competition.
</P>
<P>
   I'll keep my distance. The kid's already dealing with enough
pressure, and there's no cheering in the press box. But if Meghann
Shaughnessy wins the Boston Cup, Steve Burton, Bob Lobel, Mike
Barnicle, and Bud Collins can stay home.
</P>
<P>
   I get the inside scoop.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
