<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-CYBERTIMES-TRAVEL-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL LOG  
 AN ANSWERING MACHINE ON YOUR BELT 
</HEADLINE>
  By STEPHEN C. MILLER 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is becoming impossible to hide. Advances in wireless
communication keep us in touch no matter where we are. The latest
wonder or intrusion, depending on your point of view, is the
Pocketalk portable answering machine.
</P>
<P>
   Pocketalk is like a pager on steroids that allows your callers
to leave messages in their own voices. Its functionality is like
that of a regular answering machine, except that you don't need a
phone to retrieve your messages, and you can clip it to your belt
or drop it in the bottom of your purse. Conxus Corporation provides
the service based on a unit designed by Motorola.
</P>
<P>
   The advantage of Pocketalk is that you know who called. The
frustration of a pager, even an alphanumeric one, is that you only
get a phone number or a short text message. If you don't recognize
the phone number, or the message is cryptic, you are not sure how
urgent the call was. Newer cellular phones come with voice mail
service, but that's an extra charge on top of the monthly fee and
the per-call charge. Pocketalk fills the gap for people who want
something more than a pager but don't need or can't afford a cell
phone.
</P>
<P>
   You purchase the Pocketalk unit for $49 and then pay a monthly
fee of $19.95 for unlimited messages. As with cellular service, the
fee covers reception in your local calling area, which can be quite
large. For example, the service in New York City covers a good
chunk of Connecticut, New Jersey, Long Island and the northern
suburban communities. The service isn't available everywhere yet,
but it covers most of the major metropolitan areas. Later this year
nationwide service will be available for an additional fee.
</P>
<P>
   I tested the unit recently and found that it worked as
advertised. I got a phone call from a friend who was lost and
needed directions for our meeting. In the middle of his message, he
said, ``Wait a minute, I'm going through a tunnel.'' It turns out
he was calling my wireless answering machine from his wireless cell
phone. I called him back from a regular old wired telephone and
gave him the correct directions.
</P>
<P>
   As with a pager, you can choose to be notified of an incoming
call by an audible tone or vibration. There are buttons on the unit
for replaying messages, adjusting the volume of playback, stepping
through messages, deleting messages and locking messages so they
can't be deleted. Conxus says that you won't miss any of your
messages if you leave the calling area, because the company stores
them in its computers and will download them to your unit as soon
as you return.
</P>
<P>
   The Pocketalk unit will only hold three minutes of messages. If
you don't lock an old message, it may be overwritten when the time
limit is reached. In your outgoing message, it's probably best to
tell your callers to be brief.
</P>
<P>
   My other minor complaint about the Pocketalk is that it uses a
9-volt battery for power. I always carry a supply of AA and AAA
batteries to power everything from my portable CD-ROM drive to my
Palm Pilot. The 9-volt varieties are the size of four AAAs and take
up too much room. Why don't I just use a rechargeable battery? In
some locations, like a small village in Senegal for example, it's
not easy to recharge batteries. And yes, I was able to buy
Duracells in that same village, but they didn't have 9-volts.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, technology is making it harder to hide from the world. But
actually, a device like the Pocketalk could allow you to hide out
from many annoying phone calls. No more dinnertime calls from
telemarketers with their scripted employees who call back
repeatedly even after you hang up on them. No calls from your
brother-in-law asking to borrow money. It is the equivalent of a
private line, where only those you really want to hear from can
contact you. Darn, I gave the number to my editor.
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   RELATED SITES: (each address preceeded by http://www.)
</P>
