<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-CYBERTIMES-LAW-JOURNAL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CYBERLAW JOURNAL  
 NO RUSH TO UPDATE COPYRIGHT LAW, EXPERT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  By CARL S. KAPLAN 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Congress is poised to pass a complex new law to protect the
owners of music, art and prose from the evils of mass duplication
on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But I. Trotter Hardy, a law professor who recently concluded a
government-financed study of the problems of copyright protection
in the digital age, thinks the new law is a big mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rush to legislation concerns me,'' said Hardy, a professor
at the College of William and Mary School of Law in Williamsburg,
Va., and a well-respected Internet scholar. In a recent interview,
he said he believed the current copyright law, which is written in
general terms, is ``broad enough'' to combat today's Internet
copyright pirates as well as the unforeseen rogues around the
technology bend.
</P>
<P>
   ``An amended copyright law creates complexity and invites
further amendments'' from special interest groups, Hardy said.
``After a point, it becomes very hard for average people to keep up
and know what the new law means and how the new parts are related
to the old parts.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardy, a calm and unpretentious academic, added that the
proposed law passed by the House earlier this week singles out the
new technology of the Internet -- digital information. ``That's a
mistake because technology evolves,'' Hardy said. ``In time the new
law may become unstable.'' .
</P>
<P>
   The Digital Millennium Copyright Act, passed by the House on
Aug. 4, ratifies international copyright treaties on digital
information signed at the World Intellectual Property
Organization's Geneva conference in December 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the House bill grants Internet service
providers like America Online immunity from copyright infringements
made by their customers, so long as the ISP had no knowledge of the
misdeeds. It also makes it a crime for someone to create or sell
any technology that could be used to crack a copyright protection
device, like an encryption system, although the bill includes an
exemption for certain encryption researchers.
</P>
<P>
   A Senate version of the bill, passed last May, differs from the
House bill in some respects, including the exemption for encryption
research. Congress will have to smooth out the wrinkles before
submitting the legislation to President Clinton for approval.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy's two-year study, ``Project Looking Forward: Sketching the
Future of Copyright in a Networked World,'' was financed by the
U.S. Copyright Office. He said concern about a new technology's
potential for mass copying, which he calls ``decentralized
infringement,'' is not a new phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   In his 304-page report, he pointed out that technological or
social change sometimes can bring about a situation where the
``cost'' of engaging in behavior defined as copyright infringement
goes down. When that happens, the ``incidence of the behavior goes
up.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 19th century, for example, it was common for
``hit-and-run'' theater groups to travel to small towns in the
United States and give unauthorized performances of plays. The
technology of communications and transportation in those
pre-telephone, pre-airplane days, Hardy wrote, ``was such that it
was hard for a rights organization in, say, New York, to learn of a
traveling troupe performing for one or two days at a small town in
the Midwest in time to do anything about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, photocopy machines in the 1950s and 1960s and home
audio- and videotape recordings beginning in the 1970s frustrated
the ability of copyright holders to enforce their rights.
</P>
<P>
   How should the legal system respond to the challenge of new
duplication methods? Hardy said he believed the best answer is a
``technological fix'' that makes unauthorized copying a lot harder.
In the Internet realm, he said he favors the use of encryption,
digital watermarks and other tools that foil would-be copiers, be
they pirates or innocent but misguided Internet users. He also
believes that the principles of current copyright law already
enable copyright owners to go after many Net pirates and anyone who
has substantially assisted them in making copies.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that government could increase the penalties for
unauthorized copying in an attempt to deter the mass behavior, or
throw in the towel and declare certain copying activity lawful.
``But I don't see the need to do those things,'' Hardy said,
``because technology may change tomorrow'' and a new, efficient
preventive measure may become available.
</P>
<P>
   If copyright owners cannot perfectly police the market, Hardy
said he, for one, can live with the leakage. ``We live with a lot
of decentralized infringement now -- just look at photocopying, for
example,'' he said. The gap in enforcement provides an incentive to
develop new technologies to trump infringers, he believes.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy is not a newcomer to law and technology issues. Before
attending law school at Duke University, he worked as a computer
programmer and standards troubleshooter for 10 years. After
clerking for a judge at the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Fourth
Circuit, he began teaching at William and Mary in 1982. About five
years ago, he launched a popular and busy electronic mailing list
devoted to cyberlaw issues. He is also editor and founder of The
Journal of Online Law, an electronic publisher of scholarly essays
on law and technology.
</P>
<P>
   In researching his report, Hardy interviewed more than 80
corporate and government leaders involved with the Internet. That
experience did more than help him to recommend a ``go slow''
approach to fiddling with copyright laws, he said. He also came
away from the project with a healthy respect for the unknowable
future. Indeed, the two lessons go hand in hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned, I guess, that nobody really knows where the Net is
going,'' he said. ``I talked to a lot of scientists. They were so
busy trying to figure out today's problems. Nobody had a
perspective on three to five years in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   RELATED SITES: (each address preceeded by http://www.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Journal of Online Law: edu/law/publications/jol/
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   (Carl S. Kaplan, a New York-based lawyer and journalist, was a
business reporter for New York Newsday.)
</P>
