<HEADER>
A2207 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS &LR;      08-13 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WHAT'S BUGGIN' YOU?' MIKE BOHDAN KNOWS, AND HE TELLS ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What homeowner or apartment dweller, in the city or country, has
not been bothered, frightened, angered or eaten out of house and
home, at one time or another, by a pest?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are a lot of pests around: ants, termites,
bedbugs, beetles, crickets, silverfish, and what many consider the
worst of all, cockroaches. Those are just the bugs.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are mice and rats, moles, gophers, even a stray
coyote or two, squirrels, birds, and chipmunks, which may be cute
but can raise the dickens in tha garden.
</P>
<P>
   Often when a home is invaded by such critters, the first
reaction is to call an exterminator.
</P>
<P>
   And that is where Michael Bohdan comes in. He is an exterminator
who lives and works in Plano, Texas, and has written a book,
``What's Buggin' You?'' his guide to home pest control.
</P>
<P>
   It is $12.95, a good buy because it contains 240 pages of
information on how you can battle the pest that happens to be
``buggin''' you. If you can't get it in a bookstore, you can get it
from the publisher, Santa Monica Press, PO Box 1076, Santa Monica,
CA 90406-1076; &UR;  &LR; telephone 800-784-9553.
</P>
<P>
   Being a pest control man, Bohdan knows just about everything
there is to know about pests and how to deal with them. There's
nothing wrong with his ego, either, when he says, ``Heck, I may
just be the world's most famous exterminator,'' thanks to
appearances on the ``Tonight Show'' and in other media.
</P>
<P>
   He is also proprietor of the Cockroach Hall of Fame in Plano,
which is featured in the book. So are a lot of funny stories Bohdan
spins throughout the book.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to pests, he is all business, and his advice
is above all, practical. He is also not against using insecticides,fungicides, and other chemicals when and where they are needed. As
with all chemicals, he says, follow the label instructions, use
great care, and protect yourself. He is an enthusiastic supporter
of diatomaceous earth, which kills insects by cutting their
exoskeletons and causing death by dehydration.
</P>
<P>
   Bohdan starts out with idea of prevention, and low-impact
treatment, sometimes before the pest becomes a pest. For instance,
seal all entry points to keep the critters out. Caulk suspected
joints, fix window cracks and openings, fix broken screens. Fill
weep holes and other small openings with copper mesh or copper
wool, which will keep out bugs but allow the holes to do their
thing, such as provide drainage.
</P>
<P>
   It seems hopeless to try to cover or fill every opening, but it
is possible, and the more you do the more you will keep out bugs
and other critters; after all, rodents such as mice and rats can
enter very, very small openings, Bohdan says.
</P>
<P>
   Keep down humidity; insects thrive on it, says Bohdan. Control
temperatures, too.
</P>
<P>
   Outdoors, he adds, is a good place to continue your fight
against pests. Shrubs and flowers circling your house are pleasing
to the eye, but also to the thousands of bug eyes scouting for a
good meal or breeding ground.
</P>
<P>
   If possible, install a band of pea gravel or sand at least 12
inches wide along your foundation to act as a barricade against
insect entry. Try to avoid planting broad-leafed ivies around the
perimeter. Their wide, shade-giving leaves provide a fine honeymoon
suite for amorous black widow spiders, rats, mice, roaches, and
carpenter ants.
</P>
<P>
   General sanitation in the garden _ keeping lawns mowed, old
plants clipped, and picking up debris _ will go a long way in
discouraging insect pests.
</P>
<P>
   Bohdan devotes two full pages on protecting your pantry, partly
because pantry pests are difficult to control and eradicate (there
is no magic bullet to use indoors), and partly because pantries
contain foods, the stuff you live on.
</P>
<P>
   Ventilate your cupboards to keep humidity down, says Bohdan.
Regularly wipe or vacuum shelves. Keep crumbs off surfaces and out
of those little nooks and crannies.
</P>
<P>
   Opened packages of old food are probably the biggest source of
pantry bug infestations. All stored food should be in containers
with tight-fitting lids. Check packaged items weeky during the
summer and monthly in winter.
</P>
<P>
   Know what you are up against: Beetles feed on prepared cereals,
biscuit mixes, herbs and spices, dried fruits and flour; weevils
prefer rice, unmilled wheat, and dried beans and peas. Mites eat
just about anything. Cheese skippers like cheese, fish, and cured
meats. Moths don't consume foods, but their larvae are fond of
dried fruits, nuts, cornmeal, and other grains.
</P>
<P>
   Store only what you will use in a few months. And as gross as it
may be, pull out your refrigerator and stove once in a while to
sweep out the gunk, junk, crud, and spuds that have fallen back
there. There's nothing a bug likes more than a dimly lit, romantic
meal under a major appliance. Of course, don't try to pull out a
gas stove.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I don't mean to scare you here, but I will,'' says
Bohdan. ``Even if you make sure all food in your kithen is sealed
off from bugs, you still may not be bug-free. A lot of things
around the house are edible for bugs: spices, Christmas dough
ornaments, `popcorn' packaging material, medication, stuffed
animals, even table centerpieces made with dried flowers and seed
pods. So, if you can, inspect these items regularly for signs of
insect life. You _ and your teddy bear _ will be glad you did.''
</P>
<P>
   With all this information under your belt, you might ask, why
bother with an exterminator?
</P>
<P>
   Bohdan answers that despite being a pest control operator, ``I
can remain objective when it comes to the right and wrong times to
call a pro. ... After all, anyone can lay down a few roach
stations, if that's the solution of your insect troubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a time to be brave, macho, or cheap. If you don't
feel confident treating your problem on you own, it's worth the
extra few dollars to bring in a pest control operator rather than
bungling the job yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a question of common sense.''
</P>
<P>
   If you can do it yourself, Bohdan says he applauds your efforts
and wishes you well.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 200 pages of the book make up an encyclopedia of home and
garden pests, including ants (nine types are listed), beetles (also
nine), cockroaches (eight), flies (seven), moths (four), rodents
(six), and termites (four). Altogether, 95 pests are listed.
</P>
<P>
   With each critter, Bohdan describes it and tells us its size
range, then lists preventative and low-impact treatment, and
chemical treatment. Where there is no chemical treatment, he says
so.
</P>
<P>
   The material is helpful and, above all, practical, with a large
dose of common sense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
