<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-POIROT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUM DISEASE LINKED TO MUCH OF WHAT AILS US
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some of the more than 200 types of bacteria that live in the
human mouth may be responsible for more than bad breath and
unsightly smiles.
</P>
<P>
   The same common bacteria that eat away enamel and gums are being
linked to heart disease, stroke, diabetes and spontaneous pre-term
births.
</P>
<P>
   When studies linking periodontal disease with what we
traditionally think of as more serious medical problems began
trickling in about 18 months ago, many dentists asked permission to
doubt or at least to wait for more proof before sounding the alarm.
</P>
<P>
   But, last week The Compendium of Continuing Education in
Dentistry published a special supplement, ``Periodontal Aspects of
Systemic Health,'' that points up why we all need to take oral
hygiene seriously.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence adds up to warrant serious consideration of the
internal damage that the buildup of bacterial plaque on the teeth
can cause. Without being overly dramatic, it looks like periodontal
disease _ which is really an infection of the gums _ can be a major
threat to our general well-being.
</P>
<P>
   The compendium is published monthly and approved by the American
Dental Association and the Academy of General Dentistry to provide
continuing-education credit for dentists, including periodontists,
the specialists in dental surgery who treat the gums, bones and
other structures that support the teeth.
</P>
<P>
   The link between periodontal disease, the most common of all
human diseases (about half of all adults show signs of gum disease)
and certain systemic diseases is not really new, but evidence
continues to accumulate, says Dr. Walter Cohen, chancellor of
Allegheny University of the Health Sciences in Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have now reached a period in our history when research is
bringing medicine and dentistry closer together with data that is
cogent to physicians and dentists and, most importantly, to our
patients,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   He sees the need for physicians to stop using tongue depressors
simply to look past the oral structures into a patient's throat and
for the dentist to learn more about the systemic diseases that lie
beyond the teeth and gums.
</P>
<P>
   Studies show, for example:
</P>
<P>
   _The bacteria that cause gum disease can cause blood clots that
can trigger heart attacks and strokes.
</P>
<P>
   _When you reduce or eliminate oral infections in diabetic
patients, you can reduce their insulin requirements.
</P>
<P>
   _Any infection, including periodontal infection, can impair
fetal growth. One recent study estimates that gum disease in the
mother may be responsible for many of the low-birth-weight,
premature births for which there is no other explanation _ up to 10
percent of the estimated 250,000 premature babies born weighing
less than 5.5 pounds each year.
</P>
<P>
   The collection of studies was published after a symposium at
which the country's top periodontal disease researchers reported on
their work. The meeting was sponsored by the Colgate-Palmolive
Technology Center in Piscataway, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like it's time to get serious about flossing.
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot writes on health issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 1354EDT &QL; 
