<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2235 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MARK-McGWIRE-HNS &LR;      08-13 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MARK-McGWIRE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 McGWIRE'S WOES DON'T AMOUNT TO A HILL OF BEANIE BABIES  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The elderly man wrote to the St. Louis Cardinals
requesting a bat. Well, not just any bat. A Mark McGwire bat.
</P>
<P>
   To use as a prosthetic.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire and his fellow players should be happy people are taking
such a healthy interest, considering how fresh the scars are from
the last time baseball played its fans for suckers. Instead,
McGwire waffles between thanking the fans for embracing him
everywhere he goes and wishing they would give him space enough to
avoid feeling like a ``caged animal.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of fans show up to the ballpark hours before Cardinals
games to watch McGwire take batting practice. Some of them have the
bad manners to boo when he neglects to launch any baseballs toward
Uranus. McGwire decided one day last week to give himself a break
from the wear and tear that it takes to wage a candidacy for Home
Run King. To 25,969 people at Milwaukee's County Stadium that day,
it was like showing up for Tony Bennett and getting Tony Danza.
</P>
<P>
   The fans booed and heckled McGwire's understudy, John Mabry, on
sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think I paid $80 to watch you hit?'' one fan yelled at
Mabry, who later would deposit a ball into the outfield seats. Home
Run King for a day, which is a lot different from holding down the
job for a year.
</P>
<P>
   With each passing day, the wait of the baseball world seems to
drag down McGwire and Ken Griffey Jr. a little more. Roger Maris
dethroned Babe Ruth with 61 home runs in 1961, losing clumps of
hair from stress in the process. Maris had to do it the hard way,
against the wishes of a public that deemed him an unworthy
successor to Ruth or competitor to Mickey Mantle.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire and Griffey play to adoring crowds, yet they seem
anything but poised to break the record. They bristle at the
unrelenting expectations and scrutiny, not realizing how small they
actually are in the scheme of things.
</P>
<P>
   Next to Smoochy the Frog, Stretch the Ostrich and Pinky the
Flamingo, Griffey and McGwire are nobodies.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe knowing the country is more into Beanie Babies than
three-run blasts would help put things in perspective for McGwire
and Griffey. Griffey and the Seattle Mariners are the No. 2 road
attraction in the American League, drawing an average of 30,579
fans per game entering Tuesday. The Cardinals are the third-biggest
road draw in the National League, with 31,801 fans per game.
</P>
<P>
   Beanie Babies promotions have brought in more than 39,000 fans
per game this season in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Collectors have been paying upwards of $5,000 for some of the
retired Beanie Babies. The Beanie Babies page on the Internet
reports more than 1.9 billion hits. Devotees breathlessly click in
to see the diary entries of Beanie Baby of the month, Whisper the
Deer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such an awesome day already!'' Whisper reported in a 6:39
a.m. entry Tuesday. ``I know for sure that we're having buckwheat
pancakes for breakfast! That always starts my day off right! ...
Early (the robin) woke me up so I could watch the sun rise with her
and Strut (the rooster). It was really awesome to watch. I love
sunrises. Don't you?''
</P>
<P>
   Under the circumstances, it's a miracle anybody has time to
notice McGwire or Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals have scheduled a Smoochy the Frog giveaway for
Friday _ the same day the San Diago Padres are bringing Waves the
Orca Whale out of retirement. Two days later, the Cincinnati Reds
are luring Rover the Dog out of retirement. The Atlanta Braves may
be drawing more than 41,000 fans per game at home, but that isn't
stopping them from staging an Aug. 19 Chip the Cat giveaway. Three
days later, the New York Mets are giving the public more of what it
wants _ namely, Curly the Bear.
</P>
<P>
   And the Beanie Babies phenomenon is hardly a fluke. Frankly,
Americans will take a doll over a historical home run chase any
time. The Postal Service recently circulated ballots for events to
be featured in an upcoming series of stamps. One of the 1960s
winners was Maris, with 342,958 votes.
</P>
<P>
   The Barbie Doll got 350,115 votes.
</P>
<P>
   If only Maris had known: More people were interested in what
Barbie was wearing than in whether he could top 60 homers. When
Maris did hit No. 61 off Tracy Stallard on the final day of the
season, it was before a crowd of 23,154.
</P>
<P>
   Knowledge is power, so McGwire and Griffey should relax. Stop
fighting themselves and the attention they get. Be happy that
people are interested, and rooting for them. There are worse things
in life than fielding a daily dose of questions along the lines of,
``So, do you think you can do it?'' Try being the one asking those
questions, or coming up with alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey's manager, Lou Piniella, likens the daily home run watch
to ``a nagging wife _ or husband. You come in and know they're
there. There's no escape.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as that's the mind-set, look for Griffey to continue to
slide. Griffey has homered once in 17 games, giving him 41. He's on
a pace to finish with 57.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, for his part, had homered once in 11 games before going
deep against the New York Mets' Bobby Jones on Tuesday night. What
was a 70-something pace has shrunk to 65. The Chicago Cubs' Sammy
Sosa has 46 homers, leaving him one behind McGwire. Sosa has
managed to get this far without approaching each day as a root
canal-in-waiting. In a related development, Sosa had gone deep nine
times in the past 16 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pressure is shining shoes and washing cars to support my
family,'' said Sosa, who grew up in the Dominican Republic. In the
scheme of things, the problems of a prospective Home Run King
simply don't amount to a hill of Beanie Babies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
