<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MIRANDA-RULE (Washington) _ The so-called Miranda rule requiring
police to tell suspects of their right to remain silent has
prevented law enforcement officers from solving thousands of
violent crimes since it went into effect in 1966, says a
Dallas-based think tank, the National Center for Policy Analysis,
in a new report. By NICOLE TSONG.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Hilton Head, S.C.) _ South Carolina has benefited
from the clout of two long-serving senators. Is it really ready to
abandon that power for two-term Republican Rep. Bob Inglis, a
crusader for term limits who seeks to dump five-term Democratic
Sen. Ernest F. ``Fritz'' Hollings? By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
</TEXT>
