   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BOMBING-EMBASSIES _ TEL AVIV, Israel _ In the wake of the tragic
week-old bombings in Kenya and Tanzania, the U.S. State Department
has heightened security at embassies around the world. From
Swaziland to Egypt to Malaysia, the paranoia gripping emabssies
appears to be inescapable. President Clinton Wednesday ordered a
report on the safety of U.S. embassies in order to ask Congress for
emergency funding after deadly bomb attacks. What's being done to
make the embassies at least appear more secure? Are some of our
most important embassies really secure? Also, just how are embassy
employees coping with the knowledge that they are being likened to
``No. 1 with a bullet on the terrorist Hit Parade?'' (Kaplow
w/foreign staff, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SCANDAL-REPORTERS _ WASHINGTON _ They slogged through
Whitewater despite a public that often preferred to hear less
rather than more about presidential scandal. They weathered the
backlash of the Clinton White House and sometimes faced resistance
from fellow reporters and their own publications. Now the handful
of journalists who have followed a trail of Clinton controversies
for six years are seeing their work lead to the first-ever
appearance by a president before a criminal grand jury. The
persistence of fewer than a dozen reporters has been largely
responsible for keeping the issue of Clinton's conduct before the
country. (Malone, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION _ MIAMI _ Pro-choice group and abortion providers seek
a preliminary injunction to stop enforcement of new state law that
bans ``partial birth abortions.'' Plaintiffs say law is so vague
that it could serve as a ban on all abortions, regardless of the
term of pregnancy. Hearing in federal court to last Thursday and
Friday, with plaintiffs calling five doctors, four of them abortion
providers in Florida, and state calling two doctors. (Ocker, Palm
Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   HOGS _ Farmers for Fairness, a tax-exempt group comprised of
wealthy hog farmers founded two years ago to ``educate'' North
Carolina voters about pig farming, is appealing a North Carolina
law requiring it to disclose its donors and register as a political
action committee. It is also fighting to keep its tax exemption.
The appeal will test the ability of North Carolina and other states
to regulate issue advertising in local elections. (Foskett, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NEWS-QUESTIONS _ What are the words to the Howdy-Doody theme?
How can I contact Trent Lott? What brand of golf ball did Alan
Shepard hit on the moon? (Bessonette, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED WEDNESDAY.
</P>
