<HEADLINE>
YEARLING SALE OFFERS A GLIMPSE OF WHO'S HOT, WHO'S NOT IN GLOBAL
MARKETPLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE GOTTLIEB  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ You want to know where the global
economy is headed? Go to the renowned annual yearling sale at the
Saratoga Springs Racecourse.
</P>
<P>
   When oil prices were sky-high, Middle Easterners dominated the
auction. When Japan's economy was hot, the Japanese were the
players to watch. But oil is not as expensive as it once was and
Japan is struggling.
</P>
<P>
   Now, experts say, it's the Europeans' turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look around you can see the changing economic power,
without having to read The Wall Street Journal,'' Henryk
deKwiatkowski, owner of Calumet Farm of Lexington, Ky., said
Tuesday afternoon. ``You can come to Saratoga ... and see a good
barometer of the economy as is stands today. You don't see the
Middle Eastern and Japanese buyers as much, and the European
economy is better.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Fasig-Tipton Co. auction this week, the Middle Eastern
and Japanese buyers who have made a splash in the past decade were
replaced by Irish and British business people.
</P>
<P>
   At Tuesday's opening night session, the Thoroughbred Corp. spent
$1.7 million on a chestnut filly sired by Storm Cat out of a Gone
West mare, Gone to Venus, topping last year's highest sale price of
$1.4 million. The owner of the Thoroughbred Corp. is Ahmed bin
Salman of Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   A chestnut colt fetched $900,000 from Shadwell Estate Co. Ltd.
of Thetford, England.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Celtics coach Rick Pitino spent $200,000 on a chestnut
colt.
</P>
<P>
   The yearling sale director, Bill Graves, said the high sale
prices signaled a strong start.
</P>
<P>
   People in the industry anticipated a strong showing as well from
another significant horse buyer: the American. ``The clique of
Irish and English buyers might come in and buy the top 5 percent of
the horses, but the vast majority, the 95 percent, of the horses
will be purchased by Americans,'' said Walter Burke, owner of
Valley View Farm in Ocala, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   In advance of Tuesday night's bidding, the auctioneers hoped for
a 10 percent boost in last year's $27.7 million gross sales,
according to Terence Collier, marketing director of Fasig-Tipton.
</P>
<P>
   He was hopeful that several horses would bring between $1
million and $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish players, whom Collier called the most powerful in the
world, have established a thriving conglomerate of stud farms
throughout Europe, North America and Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Horse buyers and sellers from the United Kingdom have always
figured prominently in American sales, more visibly so in the early
1980s. However, their dominance was supplanted by the horse-buying
flurry of wealthy, oil-rich Arabs. The Japanese soon came on strong
as well, thanks to the strength of their market. But, Collier said,
the Arab purchasers are less apt to do so because they already have
the yearlings they need to start their own breeding industry.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese are still alive in American sales, as evidenced by
the recent $4 million purchase of a yearling by an entrepreneur
from that country, and the first-ever yearling sale in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   But economic vulnerabilities in Asia and the Mideast have left a
wider berth to the Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's only in the last year or so since the Japanese economy
has taken a bit of a setback,'' said Collier. He cautioned that the
cycle will likely shift once more when the European conglomerates
have all the studs they need.
</P>
</TEXT>
