<HEADLINE>
.
</HEADLINE>
  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following stories
today for use by NYTimes News Service clients. They will move in
the ``e'' entertainment news file. For questions, contact Jimmy
Johnson at the Daily News, (818) 713-3695. 
. 
GROOVE-MOVIE (Los Angeles) _ ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back''
didn't set out to be the film that turned the tables on one of
Hollywood's most cherished (think Bogey and Bacall) sexist
traditions. The second novel by ``Waiting to Exhale'' author Terry
McMillan to be adapted to the big screen, the story of a successful
40-year-old divorcee who finds happiness with a Jamaican man half
her age was loosely based on the writer's own experience. By Bob
Strauss. 
. 
NUDE-GROOVE (Los Angeles) _ Another advantage of playing the mature
female partner in a movie romance: You don't have to get naked for
the love scenes. ``I didn't want to take all my clothes off and
show it up on a big ol' screen for all the world to see,'' says
Angela Bassett, star of the sensual romance ``How Stella Got Her
Groove Back.'' ``Especially not after `What's Love Got to Do With
It,' and all the attention I got based on my physicality in that
movie. By Bob Strauss. 
. 
STURGES-FILM (Los Angeles) _ Comedic screenwriter/director Preston
Sturges receives his due with a centennial tribute that,
coincidentally, follows his snub from the AFI's top 100 American
films of all time. By Bob McCarthy. 
. 
STELLA-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ Like its predecessor ``Waiting to
Exhale,'' ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back'' is a luxuriously
appointed soap opera with just enough sass to make it seem like
something more. 3 Stars. By Bob Strauss. 
. 
SLUMS-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ This story about a father who moves
around apartment to apartment to keep his three kids in Beverly
Hills schools is a kooky family comedy that mainly obsesses with
women's breasts. 1{ Stars. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
RETURN-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ ``Return to Paradise'' pokes, prods
and nudges you throughout its two hours, practically begging you to
answer the question: What would YOU do? Sad to say, though, the
filmmakers have decided that the core moral dilemma isn't enough to
sustain interest and have added creaky plot contrivances and the
year's worst tacked-on love story to dilute what could have been a
pretty good film. 2{ Stars. By Bob Strauss. 
. 
REGEN-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ Intelligent and more complex than it
appears, Gillies Mackinnon's adaptation of Pat Barker's acclaimed,
World War I novel ``Regeneration'' comes at a most felicitous time.
While ``Saving Private Ryan'' is showing filmgoers the effect
combat has on fighting soldiers, ``Regeneration'' brings out their
internalized responses to the horrors of war. 3{ Sstars. By Bob
Strauss. 
. 
POP-BEAT (Los Angeles) _ Singer-guitarist Juliana Hatfield says
times are hard for new artists. ``It's so sad,'' she said. ``New
bands don't have a chance to develop and if they don't have a hit
right off the bat, they're finished even before they've started.''
By Fred Shuster. 
. 
DISCS-MUSIC _ Brian Setzer's 17-piece big band is one of the
longest-running and best of the premillennium swing outfits.
Instead of taking a purist, archival approach, the jazz-tinged
rockabilly guitarist-singer adds a postmodern vibe to such
standouts as the Louis Prima hit ``Jump Jive an' Wail,'' the
grinder ``Sleepwalk'' and Rosemary Clooney's ``This Old House''
with ``The Dirty Boogie.'' By Fred Shuster. 
. 
LEBOWSKI-VIDEO (Los Angeles) _ ``The Big Lebowski,'' the latest
from the Coen brothers (``Fargo''), is out on video this week, and,
along with ``There Something About Mary,'' is the funniest film of
the year, a loopy, entertaining and, yes, even warn and fuzzy
takeoff on film noir, Busby Berkley musicals, male fantasies and
almost anything else the Coen brothers (Joel and Ethan) can jam in.
By Rob Lowman. 
. 

