<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POP-BEAT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NO `BED' OF ROSES FOR NEWCOMERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Singer-guitarist Juliana Hatfield says times are
hard for new artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so sad,'' she said. ``New bands don't have a chance to
develop and if they don't have a hit right off the bat, they're
finished even before they've started. The competition is so
fierce.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatfield's self-produced new album, ``Bed'' (Zoe), due out Aug.
25, was just issued. Last year, she released a one-off indie EP,
``Please Do Not Disturb'' (Bar/None).
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Hatfield stepped out of Boston's jangle-pop Blake
Babies, the group she founded with other students from the
prestigious Berklee School of Music.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, ``My Sister,'' a track from Hatfield's solo
album, ``Become What You Are'' (Mammoth/Atlantic), set the tone for
a generation of female alt-rock singer-songwriters.
</P>
<P>
   Hatfield's new album came together after she left
Mammoth/Atlantic. She'd been associated with those labels since her
earliest days as a musician.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took a long time to get off Atlantic,'' Hatfield, 31, said.
``The whole regime of people who I'd known for so long had left. I
didn't feel a lot of excitement about me anymore at the label.''
</P>
<P>
   MADCAP DREAMS: Dreams are coming true for local pop-rock trio
Madcap.
</P>
<P>
   The band, which formed three years ago, is about to release a
new album, ``On My Own'' (Pardigm).
</P>
<P>
   Madcap _ which appears at 7 p.m. Saturday in a free record
release show at Backside Records (139 N. San Fernando Blvd.,
Burbank) _ has toured throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the local scene is pretty friendly,'' said Madcap
bassist Lee LeBaigue, 23, of Reseda. ``There's a group of bands
that like to play together and we have some support there.''
</P>
<P>
   LeBaigue said Madcap's primary influences range from Crass to
the Beatles to Capt. Beefheart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a pop-punk band without that annoying little kid
sound,'' he said. ``We're a little more grown up.''
</P>
<P>
   FAIR, WITH SNOW FORECAST: Phoebe Snow will headline the 18th
annual Sunset Junction Street Fair in Silver Lake at 9 p.m. Aug.
22. The fair takes place between the 3600 and 4400 blocks of Sunset
Boulevard from 10 a.m. to 11 p.m. Aug. 22-23. Information: (213)
661-7771.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 1445EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
