<SLUG> BC-LEBOWSKI-VIDEO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE COENS STRIKE AGAIN WITH `BIG LEBOWSKI'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When first we encounter Jeff Lebowski (Jeff
Bridges), it's late at night in an empty Los Angeles supermarket,
and he's checking out the milk. Dressed for bed (complete with
floppy slippers), he furtively looks around and then opens a carton
and takes a sip.
</P>
<P>
   Next, we see him at the cash register making out a check for all
of 89 cents. This is clearly a man who doesn't live on the edge but
around the edges of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Big Lebowski,'' the latest from the Coen brothers
(``Fargo''), is out on video this week, and is, along with
``There's Something About Mary,'' the funniest film of the year _ a
loopy, entertaining and, yes, even warm and fuzzy takeoff on film
noir, Busby Berkeley musicals, male fantasies and almost anything
else the Coen brothers (Joel and Ethan) can jam in.
</P>
<P>
   Set during the Gulf War, the film is often in danger of spinning
out of control with its crazy plot twists, but the Coens always
redeem themselves with eye-opening visuals and off-the-wall humor.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Bridges' Lebowski is not the big guy of the title.
This Lebowski is a long-haired refugee from the '60s who would
rather be referred to as Dude and whose life revolves around
bowling, getting high and listening to whale sounds to soothe his
(un)complicated existence. But this comes to an end when a couple
of thugs break into his apartment and rough him up, saying that his
wayward wife hasn't paid up on the gambling debts she owes porn
king/mobster Jackie Treehorn (Ben Gazarra). Eventually, it dawns on
them that the Lebowski they want is rich and Dude isn't. They leave
him a present, however, by urinating on his throw rug.
</P>
<P>
   ``That rug really pulled the room together,'' declares Dude's
friend and bowling partner, Walter (John Goodman), a Vietnam War
veteran with a hair-trigger temper. So, with Walter's incessant
urging, Dude heads off to find the other Lebowski and get
compensation for his rug.
</P>
<P>
   The big guy of the title turns out to be another Jeff Lebowski
(David Huddleston), a wheelchair-using millionaire, and the Dude's
visit to him plunges him into a complicated kidnapping mystery (too
complicated to go into here).
</P>
<P>
   The gambling debts and the millionaire in a wheelchair echo the
plot of the Humphrey Bogart classic ``The Big Sleep,'' which itself
has a complicated plot that still has film buffs scratching their
heads. Only this time, instead of a sharp Philip Marlowe on the
trail of the truth, we have a clueless Dude who's still groggy from
his big sleep from reality.
</P>
<P>
   But if the story turns in ``The Big Lebowski'' are maddening
though fun, the acting turns are sublime, starting with Bridges,
who is so convincing in his lethargy and spaciness that you wonder
if you're seeing the real Jeff Bridges here. Bridges doesn't so
much act the role as inhabit it. But those who have followed the
versatile actor's career from when he first burst upon the scene in
``The Last Picture Show'' (1971) know that he's been
underappreciated.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman _ the veteran of other Coen films, ``Raising Arizona''
and ``Barton Fink'' _ is wonderful as the manic-depressive Walter,
who always looks as if he's about to explode at any minute. To this
mix, add the always superb Steve Buscemi as the dim-witted third
member of the bowling team; a laconic and amused Sam Elliot as the
cowboy-narrator; John Turturro in a pink jumpsuit as Jesus, their
archenemy in bowling and a convicted pedophile; and Julianne Moore
as the Big Lebowski's daughter Maude, an artist and sex enthusiast.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in a gang of black-clad nihilists, a famous TV
scriptwriter in an iron lung, an attack marmot, a hilarious funeral
scene and a great soundtrack _ from Bob Dylan to Kenny Rogers to
the late Townes Van Zandt _ and you have one of the most original
films in a while. Originality and offbeat ideas have never been a
problem with the Coens, although making films that have a heart has
at times. But, in ``The Big Lebowski'' the Coens surprisingly add
some warm colors to their absurdist palette, and what the
cowboy-narrator says about the Dude's story can be said about the
film: ``This is how the whole darn human comedy perpetuates
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   SPEAKING OF SURPRISING: The idea of Adam Sandler in a
sweet-natured romantic comedy may seem like an incongruity, but
somehow we have ``The Wedding Singer,'' which came out on video
last week. Sandler, who showed signs of breaking out of the
adolescent humor trap in ``Happy Gilmore,'' plays a failed rocker
turned wedding singer who is dumped by his fiancee and falls for a
waitress (Drew Barrymore). Set in the '80s, the film has a fun
soundtrack and, unlike with most of Sandler's films, you don't have
to be under 14 to enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   DVD WATCH: The last two major studios are joining the DVD camp.
Fox and Paramount have announced that they are releasing their
first digital video disc titles this fall. Fox will release ``Hope
Floats'' and James Cameron's ``The Abyss'' among its first six
titles, while Paramount will offer 10 films, including ``Star Trek:
First Contact'' and ``Face/Off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
