<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SOAPS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL MONICA'S CHILDREN:SCANDAL GIVES BIRTH TO SOAP OPERA IDEAS  
 (EMBARGOED FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Illustrations are being sent to NYTNS clients)  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVE WALKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - The world has turned nearly 250 times since Monica
Lewinsky joined the cast of our long national soap opera. Unlike a
story line on a real soap, the Monica Lewinsky/Linda Tripp/Bill
Clinton saga appears headed for a resolution.
</P>
<P>
   How many more days of our lives will pass before it all ends?
And how will the end come?
</P>
<P>
   Since the president has employed television producer and
director Harry Thomason as his own personal script doctor, ``The
Arizona Republic`` asked other television professionals to pitch
their own treatments for the ongoing melodrama. (Its title?
``Leaves of Grass,'' of course.) We asked each writer how they'd
untangle such an implausible plot.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Esensten, co-head writer for the CBS daytime drama
``Guiding Light,'' instantly filled in some of the missing
back-story. In Esensten's (obviously fictional) version, Lewinsky
would be revealed as the initial pursuer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton was the complete gentleman with her,'' said Esensten.
``She was getting more and more frustrated. She knew and felt that
the man had had so many affairs. But he kept telling her that she
misunderstood. She finally said, `You either capitulate to my
attention or I'm going to say you did anyway.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, 'Please don't do that. That would be a terrible
mistake.' ''
</P>
<P>
   She did it anyway. Now, for the soapy flourish.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason Bill took such an interest in her in the first
place, the reason he'd been protecting her all along, the reason
that he's been telling the truth and knows that she's been lying,''
said Esensten, ``is that she's his illegitimate daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we'd do. We'd play the hell out of it. It would
take months to resolve.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Guiding Light'' might not play the hell out of a certain, uh,
seedy aspect of the real-life soap, said Esensten. The dress, the
DNA-carrying stain _ that whole tangent may be too sordid even for
daytime television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd think we'd have to handle it more gingerly,'' said
Esensten. ``When you get to something so specific, we have what we
call the `ick' factor. We can show all kinds of sexual acts and
allude to all kinds of double-entendres, but when you feel
something is wrong in the pit of your stomach, that's the `ick'
factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some places we draw the line. I think we'd play
lipstick on a shirt. Semen on a dress? I think we'd draw the
line.''
</P>
<P>
   In Esensten's drama, Lewinsky's character would get to shirk
some of the responsibility for her actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a soap writer, I would probably play up the way she grew up
and the household she grew up in, and I would probably make the
mother the villain of the piece,'' she said. ``We are all a product
of where we came from.''
</P>
<P>
   As for The Man from Hope, he'd make a ``fabulous'' soap opera
character ``because he is the kind of character women always
forgive,'' Esensten said. ``If one is to believe that he's not been
true to his wife, that makes him a villain in the eyes of most
women. There are some men who will forever be forgiven. Whatever it
is he's got, it works on soaps, and, apparently, in the polling
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would cast him in a second for our show. In fact, I might
suggest it to him if he's going to be out of a job soon.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Page Turner &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the FBI will discover that there has been a vast
conspiracy against President Clinton _ not by the so-called `right
wing,' as Hillary mistakenly believes, but by forces far more
devious and dangerous,'' said Philip Taylor, a Scottsdale, Ariz.,
resident and veteran television writer.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor shot his detailed (but plainly farcical) take on the
tale, through which he weaves a media mogul and the box office fate
of a major motion picture, to us via e-mail. It can be read in its
entirety on the ``Republic's'' online annex, Arizona Central
(www.azcentral.com).
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, who's recently done scripts for the syndicated
action-adventure drama ``Soldier of Fortune'' and the CBS series
``The Magnificent Seven,'' concocted a terrible secret for
Lewinsky's mother, Marcia Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   In his scenario, Lewis had a ``brief fling with an Atlanta
businessman'' while on a long-ago promotional tour for one of her
tawdry books, Taylor said. ``The result of this liaison was a
rather chubby baby called Monica.''
</P>
<P>
   The businessman: Ted Turner.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1995, it was Turner who pulled a few strings behind the
scenes, and got Monica a job as a White House intern,'' Taylor
said. ``Monica did not want to work in the White House. In fact,
she wanted to be a television anchorperson, but Turner insisted
because he had a darker purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   The darker purpose: An anonymous ``inside source'' to improve
CNN's ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monica was instructed to get as close to the president as
possible, bring him gifts, endear herself to him in every way,''
said Taylor. ``Unfortunately, Monica did her job too well, and
became thoroughly obnoxious.''
</P>
<P>
   After her transfer to the Pentagon, Turner schemed to turn
Monica's relationship with the president into a promotional stunt
for the January release of the film ``Wag the Dog.'' (Produced by
New Line Cinema, one of Turner's many media holdings, ``Wag the
Dog'' tells a story frighteningly similar to the real events of
Monicagate. Now we know why.)
</P>
<P>
   Turner convinced Monica to play along by A) revealing that he
was her father and B) promising her Bernard Shaw's anchor chair.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Tripp and literary agent Lucianne Goldberg eventually make
an appearance in Taylor's treatment, of course, as does the
infamous dress. (Which actually belongs to Hillary Clinton, who
last wore it the night of a Barbra Streisand concert.)
</P>
<P>
   According to Taylor's dark design, the July resurgence of the
Lewinsky story was engineered to hype the video release of ``Wag
the Dog.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Turner's conscience does bother him now and again,'' said
Taylor. ``But whenever it does, he donates a huge sum of money to
the United Nations, and he feels better right away.''
</P>
<P>
   In a postscript, Taylor calls his interpretation of events
``pure speculation, salted with a few known facts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But it just goes to show how rumors start,'' he said. ``When
those `anonymous sources' begin blabbing, even the president finds
it hard to come clean.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, if you see Monica Lewinsky with her own talk show,
and Marcia Lewis and Linda Tripp on The ``New York Times''
bestseller list, just remember: some writers will do anything to
see their name in print _ including me!'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
`Beach' parties  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fans of NBC's ``Sunset Beach'' know that a shadow version of
Monicagate has been unfolding on the soap for several months.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Tomlin, executive producer of the Aaron Spelling property,
said his show jumped on the story almost immediately. There's a
Monica character (Sara Cummings), a Clinton character (a mysterious
U.S. congressman named Blythe, as in William Jefferson Blythe
Clinton and with whom Cummings has had an affair) and a conniving
Linda Tripp character (who secretly tapes Sara's confession of the
affair).
</P>
<P>
   Where does it say that satire has to be subtle?
</P>
<P>
   A snapshot of Blythe hugging a beret-wearing Cummings has played
an important part in the ``Sunset Beach'' subplot. And the Linda
Tripp character's name? Melinda Fall.
</P>
<P>
   The Tripp/Fall character is played as a tacky dresser who's
``very sort of harsh and over-the-top,'' said Tomlin. Her
motivation is that ``this woman herself was in love with the
congressman all these years and never made a move,'' Tomlin said.
``She assumed he was a happily married man, and was betrayed by her
friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty outrageous. All through this thing, we've
portrayed (the Tripp character) as a woman who's totally out for
herself.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Monica/Sara has been written as ``sweet and young and
all that stuff,'' said Tomlin. ``Our Monica character is not
written perhaps as opportunistically as the real Monica.''
</P>
<P>
   Her future, in fact, likely revolves around a hometown love
interest closer to her own age.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we'll strive for now is getting the most mileage as we
can out of the love story,'' said Tomlin. ``We've got a young girl
who has been essentially wronged by these people in Washington. She
goes to Washington as a total innocent, she was used by this guy
and this woman, and she's suffering the consequences. She just
wants to get on with her life. She's not at all looking to get
anything out of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're looking to do is a love story, basically.''
</P>
<P>
   Feedback from viewers ``has been fairly positive, because
they're having fun with it. We're not playing it like a
dead-serious story,'' Tomlin said. ``You do get the line, `We're
tired of it in real life, why are you putting it on the show?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Upcoming soap opera plot twists are at least as carefully
guarded as grand jury testimony, so Tomlin couldn't exactly say how
Congressman Blythe will pay for his sins, if at all. In fact,
``Sunset Beach'' may just wait until reality writes an ending for
this particular subplot, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, many of the soap's characters _ including Monica/Sara
and Tripp/Fall _ spent last week trying to escape from a sinking
cruise ship.
</P>
<P>
   As of this past Friday's episode, a full accounting of survivors
wasn't yet possible, and sharks had been sighted circling the
lifeboats. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dave Walker is television writer for The Arizona Republic. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
