A2327 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-PARADISE-SPI &LR;      08-13 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PARADISE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RETURN TO PARADISE' IS A PLEASANT SURPRISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's extremely rare these days to have a star-heavy Hollywood
movie that revolves around a clear and perhaps
impossible-to-reconcile moral dilemma. For this reason alone,
``Return to Paradise'' comes as something of a pleasant surprise.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is no slam dunk by any means. The reach of its script
definitely exceeds its grasp, it never makes us completely believe
its bizarre situation and it doesn't quite click into place as
something more than a TV problem-movie-of-the-week.
</P>
<P>
   But it's full of surprises every step of the way, it carries a
powerful emotional punch and it serves as an engaging star vehicle
for Vince Vaughn and Anne Heche _ who make their sketchily written
characters come alive, and develop an appealing romantic chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   The story is about a trio of young Americans _ Sheriff (Vince
Vaughn), Tony (David Conrad) and Lewis (Joaquin Phoenix) _ who, as
the film opens, are having a summer of tropical fun in Peninsular
Malaysia, with a liberal amount of hashish involved.
</P>
<P>
   Cut to two years later. Sheriff is back in New York driving a
limousine; Tony is an apprentice Manhattan architect; and neither
has heard anything from Lewis, who stayed on in Malaysia to work
for an orangutan protection project in Borneo.
</P>
<P>
   One night, a young attorney (Anne Heche) hires Sheriff's limo
and drops a bombshell on him: It seems Lewis was arrested with
their collective hash stash shortly after the other two left, and
has spent the last two years in an unspeakably awful Penang prison.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the Malaysian authorities intend to hang him in a
matter of weeks, unless either he or Tony or both come back to
tesify that he was not a dealer, and shoulder part of the blame.
The deal is three years for each of them, or six years if only one
can be convinced to return.
</P>
<P>
   So the movie becomes this no-win moral dilemma in which the two
men are asked to make an extraordinary sacrifice for someone they
barely know _ egged on by this persistent and mysterious woman who
seems willing to go to any length to convince them.
</P>
<P>
   As this plays out, the script _ which was adapted from Pierre
Jolivet's 1989 French-language drama, ``Force Majeure'' _ seems to
have more than a few pieces missing, and never really tells us
enough about any of its characters to work as a cogent drama.
</P>
<P>
   It also never quite convinces us that: a) the U.S. State
Department would completely ignore the execution of a young
American with no criminal record; b) Malaysia would pose such a
deal to stay the execution; or c) anyone would ever be noble enough
to go along with it.
</P>
<P>
   But if you can jump over this considerable credibility gap,
``Return to Paradise'' is often a riveting movie, fueled by the
usual solid direction of Joseph Ruben (``Dreamscape''), top-notch
production values, and an especially poignant love story that
develops credibly in the midst of the turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a film that forces us to question what we might do in
such a nightmarish situation; and thus becomes a sobering
cautionary tale. Like ``Red Corner'' and ``Midnight Express,'' it
tells us that being an American carries no special privileges in an
increasingly draconian Third World.
</P>
<P>
   Return to Paradise. Directed by Joseph Ruben. Screenplay by
Wesley Strick and Bruce Robinson. Cast: Vince Vaughn, Anne Heche,
Joaquin Phoenix, David Conrad, Jada Pinkett Smith. Polygram. 109
minutes. Rated R for drug scenes and mature subject matter.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 1453EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
