<SLUG> BC-FILM-GOVERNESS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVER'S PERFORMANCE IN `THE GOVERNESS' MAKES IT WORTH SEEING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Governess,'' a gothic romance novel of a film about one
woman's journey toward sexual self-knowledge and identity, is more
visually adventurous than anything.
</P>
<P>
   It features an odd, sometimes bold, performance by Minnie Driver
in her first star vehicle. Whether you can suspend disbelief for
wild flights of fancy will depend entirely upon your feelings about
Driver herself as an actress.
</P>
<P>
   She's in virtually every scene of Sandra Goldbacher's first
feature. Goldbacher was a successful commercials director in London
and her talent with a camera certainly can't be disputed.
Unfortunately, the same can't be said for the film's soap opera of
a story, which is over-the-top, unfocused and lacks plausibility.
</P>
<P>
   In England during the Victorian Era, a young Jewish woman,
Rosina DaSilva (Driver), learns, after the sudden death of her
father, that his excesses have left her mother and sister
penurious. Rosina boldly decides to find work so she can support
her family and pay off their debts.
</P>
<P>
   Realizing she'll be at a disadvantage in the Christian
community, she changes her name to Mary Blackchurch and secures
employment on the Isle of Skye as a governess for the eccentric
Cavendish family.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Cavendish (Tom Wilkinson) is an inventor. He's engrossed in
finding a fixative for photographic developer, an obsession he
invites the bright Rosina to share. She soon falls in love with the
middle-aged man, embracing him with torrid emotional abandon. The
two embark on a heated affair, much to the agony of the young heir,
Henry Cavendish (Jonathan Rhys-Meyer), who has come home from
Oxford and promptly becomes obsessed with his sister's exotic
governess.
</P>
<P>
   There is a potentially intriguing triangle between father, son
and governess at play but the film never delves into psychological
depths that might have made it more interesting and original. ``The
Governess'' stays mainly on the surface of the characters'
motivations.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it feels like Goldbacher became confused over what
she really wanted to convey. The film takes convenient liberties
with Rosina's search for a place in Christian society as well as
the story of a strong-willed woman's struggle for emancipation.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it a true romance, as was Jane Campion's cunning ``The
Piano,'' a film it resembles. Instead it's indecisively
non-committal, even opting for an ``I Am Woman'' ending that
sabotages and negates the complicated, intriguing setup.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, as a statement on women's freedom and struggles, the
real moments in the film go to the marvelous English stage actress
Harriet Walter. She plays Mrs. Cavendish, a shallow, uninventive
society wife who has suffered from exile in a lonely place as well
as from her husband's inattention. More comment is made about a
woman's heart through her pursed, pained face than with all of
Driver's uncorseted, ``liberated'' sexual writhings with the master
of the house.
</P>
<P>
   The Governess. Directed and written by Sandra Goldbacher. Cast:
Minnie Driver, Tom Wilkinson, Harriet Walter, Jonathan Rhys-Meyer.
Sony Pictures Classics. 100 minutes. Rated R for nudity, sexual
content.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 1454EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 14:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2334 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-MARIUS-SPI &LR;      08-13 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MARIUS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MARIUS AND JEANNETTE' IS HARD TO RESIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ghost of the great French writer and filmmaker Marcel Pagnol
hovers happily over ``Marius and Jeannette,'' a hard-to-resist
French romantic comedy that moves into the Varsity today for a
one-week run. The film was nominated in seven categories at the
1998 Cesar Awards, France's version of the Oscars.
</P>
<P>
   Pagnol receives no credit, but the film's title seems to be a
tribute to his most famous character, Marius; it's set in that
character's working-class section of Marseilles; and it's infused
with Pagnol's distinctive flavor and spirit.
</P>
<P>
   This updated Marius (Gerard Meylan) is a watchman at a cement
factory that used to be the main employer of this part of the
Estaque section of Marseilles, but has since been abandoned for
unknown economic reasons and is about to be demolished.
</P>
<P>
   Jeannette (Ariane Ascaride) is a big-hearted, loud-mouthed,
twice-wed, single mother of two children who lives nearby, and is
just about to lose her job as a store checker by blowing off steam
at her stuffy boss (Pierre Banderet).
</P>
<P>
   The pair _ both in their 40s _ meet cute one day when Jeannette
sneaks into the factory and steals two cans of paint. Marius
catches her in the act, but lets her go, and then impulsively drops
the paint off at her house. A romance begins.
</P>
<P>
   To complete the Pagnolian neighborhood ensemble, there's two
other couples who play a large part in the story: a battling
husband-and-wife (Jean-Pierre Darroussin and Frederique Bonnal),
and a retired teacher in love with a communist concentration camp
survivor (Jacques Boudet and Pascale Roberts).
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Robert Guediguian (who grew up in the Estaque)
dedicates the film to working people, and most of his characters
are marginal communists and socialists trying to keep the faith in
a post-communist world and an increasingly right-wing France.
</P>
<P>
   The film's political subtext is extremely subtle, however, and
the director paints his scenes with the lightest of brushstrokes _
making sure to quickly puncture his more poignant moments or bleak
observations of life with jabs of cheerful humor.
</P>
<P>
   The characters of ``Marius and Jeannette'' are all especially
well cast. And star Ascaride (director Guediguian's wife) generates
just the right earth-mother charm and panache to carry the film.
She deservedly won the 1998 best actress Cesar for her performance.
</P>
<P>
   Marius and Jeannette. Directed by Robert Guediguian. Screenplay
by Guediguian and Jean-Louis Milesi. Cast: Ariane Ascaride, Gerard
Meylan, Pascale Roberts, Jacques Boudet. New Yorker Films. 102
minutes. In French with English subtitles. Unrated.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 1454EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2341 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTEL-WEB-HNS &LR;      08-13 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-WEB-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEL PROMOTION STIRS ETHICAL DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Think the World Wide Web is slow? Intel Corp. is
paying mainstream Web publishers to make it even slower.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to sell more chips with more power, the Santa
Clara, Calif.-based computer chip maker is pumping money into a
program to entice _ some say pressure _ Web site creators to post
large, complicated graphics on their sites. Web content creators
are heeding the call.
</P>
<P>
   The program, dubbed ``Optimized Content,'' encourages Web sites
to use large, complicated graphics that slow down a computer's
processor when they are downloaded from the Internet. An
accompanying message informs a user that a faster, Pentium II
microprocessor would make those pictures run smoother and faster.
</P>
<P>
   Optimized Content is also another ember in the slow-burning
debate over the mixing of advertising and editorial content on Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they're asking us to do is turn our sites into a
demonstration of their products,'' said Peter Horan, a senior vice
president of Boston-based IDG, publisher of computer magazines like
Computerworld and PC World, the ``for Dummies'' how-to book series
and their related Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to optimize our content for our readers, not for
Intel,'' Horan said.
</P>
<P>
   The program, formally called ``Intel Inside Optimized Content,''
subsidizes advertising on sites that post large, complicated
pictures and special effects. According to Intel, the program is
designed to encourage Web sites to design content that ``on a
faster processor provides a perceivable benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheri Maat, manager of Intel's ``Intel Inside'' program, said
the company is not interested in controlling a site's content.
``We'd be a lot smoother if we were going to do that,'' she said,
adding that the program is meant to seduce a user into buying a
faster processor.
</P>
<P>
   Intel normally reimburses PC makers 50 percent of their
Web-based advertising costs when they use the ``Intel Inside'' logo
on Web-based ads. Under the Optimized Content program, Intel kicks
in 75 percent of a PC maker's ad costs if the Web site features
complicated graphics. The qualifying sites have to contain wording
that says a Web page is better viewed with Intel's faster Pentium
II-equipped machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hell of an incentive,'' said one Web editor who asked
not to be named. ``PC companies are going to advertise on sites
where they pay only 25 percent of the costs, as opposed to sites
where they have to pay for half of the ad.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign, launched last September, was updated July 15. The
program has been embraced by many of the giant Web publishing
concerns, including Wired Digital, Ziff-Davis, C/Ne, and CMP Media.
Web sites that use the program say it's simply a way to help
introduce cutting-edge technology to Web users.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would never, absolutely never, compromise our editorial
integrity,'' said Dan Farber, vice president and editor-in-chief of
ZDNet, the on-line presence of Ziff-Davis publications. ``The whole
basis of our success is the quality and respect of our journalistic
ethics.''
</P>
<P>
   Farber said Ziff-Davis joined the Intel program after creating
an elaborate three-dimensional site map for the ZDNet Web site.
Farber points out that there is a simpler site map available for
users and that no other pages in the ZDNet Web site are optimized.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turns out that that particular site map qualifies us for
the program,'' Farber said. ``No content is being altered for it.
No user is being forced to have their experience of ZDNet slowed
down. This whole thing has been blown out of proportion.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Andrew De Vries, spokesman for Wired Digital, said the
Intel program was used briefly last year, but a major Wired Digital
site, fully qualified under the Intel program, is slated to unwrap
soon.
</P>
<P>
   `Generally, we design content that's good for our readers,'' De
Vries said, ``but we also keep advertiser considerations in mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Horan said the seduction of ad dollars can cloud editorial
judgment at Web sites.``They don't view it as a conflict,'' he
said, ``but IDG does. How much of a site is inconsequential? Either
you cross that line or you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the inaugural issue of the media watchdog magazine Brill's
Content, Web sites, especially the giant portal pages of Yahoo and
Excite, were criticized for failing to indicate which advertisers
paid to be designated as recommended links.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape has raised eyebrows when it began a smart Web search
feature that automatically recommends sites to users that in some
cases and without notice are financial partners of Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things start small,'' Horan said, ``but they grow. We
have to start openly discussing them before it ruins the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a discussion that could happen sooner rather than later.
According to Ad Age magazine, Intel devotes an estimated $7.5
million to subsidized Web site advertising. Maat said 60 percent of
subsidized Web advertising goes to optimized Web sites.
</P>
</TEXT>
