<P>
   MOUNT-ART-EXHIBIT (New York) _ ``William Sidney Mount: Painter
of American Life'' at the New-York Historical Society; the first
comprehensive consideration of this artist's career. By Holland
Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   NY-ETHNIC-ENTERTAINMENT (New York) _ If all New Yorkers share
one experience, it's the sensation of suddenly feeling like a
tourist without leaving the city. Take an alternate route, turn an
unfamiliar corner, peek into an open doorway, and suddenly you
could be in Tokyo or Timbuktu, with strangers chatting in an
unknown language while intriguing scents waft from a kitchen. New
York is Dakar north and Budapest east; there are contingents from
Ireland and Uzbekistan, Lebanon and Peru. And they hold on to the
places they left behind by gathering for music, theater or movies
from the old country, wherever that might be. By Jon Pareles.
</P>
<P>
   NY-SARATOGA-HORSES (Undated) _ One finds worlds within worlds in
Saratoga Springs, N.Y., a fabled watering hole for high hats and
hot tipsters over the better part of the last two centuries. There
are the ancient mineral springs, the Revolutionary War sites, the
New York City Ballet and the National Museum of Dance, the hushed
forests and cricket-echoing parks, and the signposts of a civic
history involving blinkered cads, visionary patrons and some of
America's most prominent family dynasties. From the last week of
July through the first week of September, however, the Saratoga
story narrows down to a phrase: horse racing. By Mindy Aloff.
</P>
<P>
   STORIES-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ ``Collected Stories,'' with
Uta Hagen, at the Lortel Theater. Reviewed by Ben Brantley.
</P>
<P>
   WOODSTOCK-CONCERT (Bethel, N.Y.) _ A billionaire who now owns
Yasgur's farm was hoping to tempt yuppies back with ``A Day in the
Garden'' concert. But ticket sales have been slow. Maybe an
alchohol-free concert that ends by 7:00 p.m. and lets children
under 12 in for free just isn't a real concert experience. By
Andrew Revkin.
</P>
<P>
   WEST-POINT-NOVEL (West Point, N.Y.) _ When Lucien Truscott's
first novel, ``Dress Gray,'' was published 20 years ago, the
potboiler of homosexuality and scandal at West Point scandalized
the military establishment and made its author a pariah at the
academy. Now, he's published another steamy tale of academy life,
``Full Dress Gray,'' but this time he's being invited back for book
signings, coffee and dinner with the superintendent. By Frank
Bruni. (1500 words)
</P>
