<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DIALOGUE ON BLACK DIALECT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   G.J. Savage's e-mail is heavy on statistics and racial buzz
words, light on logic and tact. He was one of a great many to
respond, some in adulation, others in stark anger, to last month's
essay addressing black American dialect, slavery's effects on
language, Magic Johnson's recently axed late-night talk fest, and
that old reliable potboiler, race.
</P>
<P>
   Quips G.J., with a snarl, if such can be picked up from words on
a computer screen: ``I guess, what with me being white, 75, and
male, I just don't get it.''
</P>
<P>
   What irks G.J. is the idea that a black American dialect exists,
and that it represents yet another form of racial separation by
black folk _ who ought to be, in his estimation, utterly ecstatic
to slip quietly into the splendid ways of European Americans.
</P>
<P>
   G.J. was humming along quite nicely, actually, writing of Martin
Luther King Jr.'s call for integration and such, until he wrote
that ``descendants of slaves should be thankful that it (slavery)
happened in the South, as opposed to Africa, because if their
ancestors hadn't been traded by their black captors they would have
been killed instead, and there would be no descendants enjoying the
great benefits of our country.''
</P>
<P>
   There were others like that one, but you get the general,
miseducated idea. Jose and Elizabeth Hawkins of Arlington. Texas,
were struck by other things, though, suggesting, among others, that
``The origins of the English spoken by the descendants of African
immigrants should be a field of serious study'' if the language I
described exists and has really been handed down from past
generations. It does, and it has.
</P>
<P>
   They agree that a black vernacular, shaped and sharpened through
an all- black existence, whether through forced separation,
economic hardship or ideology and culture, has nothing to do with a
lack of education in ``proper English.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Williams, who is black, agreed. ``I, too, have the same
situation where we `talk the talk' when we are around our
brothas,'' he writes. ``But we do have jobs where we have to use
the `proper English.' I work in a university setting, and proper
English is appropriate when speaking to students and colleagues.
But I find myself resorting to `black English' when speaking to the
brothas.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael, 30-something and raised in what he describes as ``a
Dallas ghetto,'' says he did have a choice. But to him, it was
``change or be subject to criticism and lost opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   James Kirchner, a white linguistics professor at Wayne State
University in Detroit, worked in factories for years with lower- to
lower-middle-class blacks and has had enough exposure to the
dialect ``that I can produce it in spurts during which people tell
me it sounds like some other person's voice is coming out of my
mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Such an experience gives him some credibility when explaining
structural principles to students or to schoolteachers who often
have to deal with students who speak in the black English
vernacular.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main point I make is that this is not simply `lazy
speech,' but like all dialects of all language, it has regular,
complex rules and structure and can be spoken correctly or
incorrectly.''
</P>
<P>
   He gets less resistance to this idea from white students than
black. ``My black students tend to be deeply embarrassed by the
mere existence of this dialect (at least publicly),'' he writes,
``and draw their social distinctions largely based on it.''
</P>
<P>
   What surprises him most is the very idea that knowing and
speaking more than one dialect makes someone some kind of cultural
sellout. ``America seems to be one of the few places in the world
where anyone feels this way. In Germany, France, Italy and hundreds
of other countries, it's a foregone conclusion that people have to
learn a second (standard) dialect in order to function in the
larger society.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Irish, too, was ``amazed at how quickly the white guys (in
the military unit he was based in)'' picked up ``dis'' and ``dat''
and ``ax'' ( for ask).
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the country doesn't become too homogenized and we lose
our regionalisms and ethnic slang. I know as an Anglo Hispanic of
age 62, I still lapse into barrio slang (in Spanish) depending on
the association.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As a black man,'' writes Chris Lark, ``I feel African-American
culture has got to grow beyond `whassap, brah?' Building on a
street culture is fine, but where is this street taking us to? Why
aren't there other ways of keeping us `black' than just bad use of
language?''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Hammock goes deeper, with a warning. ``Language usage and
accent unfortunately stereotypes people ... Becoming `bilingual' is
one answer. But doesn't doing that perpetuate prejudice and, in the
case of blacks, racism? I can't think of a good answer.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is television critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
