<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TITANIC-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CHAMBERMAID ON THE TITANIC': A SENSUAL STORY THE HEART TELLS THE
HEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Our need for stories _ and not just any old anecdotes but
transporting tales of passion, heroism and loss _ may be as
essential to our well-being as our need for food. It is an appetite
that embraces not just the classic fairy tales and adventure
stories that are handed down through the generations but our own
personal narratives. The little storm-tossed autobiographies we
compile help us explain and validate passions that might otherwise
have no meaning once they've died.
</P>
<P>
   As skeptical as we may be about the boastful tales others spin
about their romantic exploits, there is a part of us that hungers
to believe and to be imaginatively swept by the most far-fetched
fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   That is the profound notion explored by Bigas Luna's ``The
Chambermaid on the Titanic,'' whose title misleadingly suggests a
low-rent offshoot of James Cameron's blockbuster hit. The movie,
adapted from a novel by Didier Decoin, tells the story of Horty
(Olivier Martinez), an impoverished foundry worker in northern
France who wins a company athletic contest. First prize is a
round-trip ticket to Southhampton, England to witness the maiden
voyage of the Titanic.
</P>
<P>
   The ugly underside of the victory is its provision of
transportation and luxury hotel accommodations for only one. Horty
must leave behind his adoring wife Zoe (Romane Bohringer) on whom
his boss has sexual designs.
</P>
<P>
   Horty has barely settled into his Southhampton hotel room, when
there is a knock on his door. A beautiful young French woman in a
maid's uniform explains apologetically that she is a chambermaid on
the ship who needs a place to sleep because all the local hotels
are filled. Horty allows the woman, Marie (Aitana Sanchez Gijon),
to stay with him and donates the bed while he moves to an armchair.
</P>
<P>
   But in the middle of the night, Marie invites Horty to join her
and attempts to seduce him. Although he resists her advances, he
has such vivid erotic dreams that the following morning, when he
awakes and finds her gone, he wonders what transpired. Just as the
Titanic is about to set sail, he sees a photographer taking a
picture of Marie. Accosting the photographer, he retrieves the
picture as a souvenir.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to France, Horty finds himself promoted to a less
demanding job at the foundry and bitterly accuses his wife of
having given in to the boss. Shortly after the news of the
Titanic's sinking, Horty shows his fellow workers his photograph of
Marie. When they pester him for sexual details, he impulsively
begins concocting a feverishly erotic story of the ultimate
one-night stand with this dream lover who was lost at sea.
</P>
<P>
   As he elaborates the tale, day after day, it attracts growing
crowds, and eventually paying customers. Horty's life changes when
he is discovered by a flamboyant traveling actor and storyteller
named Zeppe (Aldo Maccione) who takes him on the road and
eventually into the theater with a glossy production designed
around his increasingly melodramatic tale.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chambermaid on the Titanic'' has great fun suggesting how
how good stories tend to get ``better'' over time. It also enjoys
playing tricks on us by flashing back to the one- night stand with
soft-core flashbacks that make us wonder if it's true.
</P>
<P>
   As time passes, Horty's fantasy becomes such a fixture in his
consciousness that it becomes true, even if it didn't happen. Zoe,
who follows him on the road and eventually plays Marie on stage, is
rightfully jealous of a dream she could never come close to
matching. The movie forcefully reminds us of the degree to which
any grand passion is rooted in fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   But the film never finds a visual vocabulary to match the
elegance of its ideas. The flashbacks and fantasy sequences are
standard soft-core fluff. And although Martinez and Ms. Gijon, who
play the lovers, are splendid looking, they are both cool cookies
whose faces betray little genuine passion.
</P>
<P>
   Released in the wake of the ``Titanic'' phenomenon, the movie
also works as a mocking commentary on the hoopla surrounding
Cameron's film. A maritime disaster that took place 86 years ago
has consumed so much media attention it might just as well have
happened last year. Put a star-crossed pair at the epicenter of a
tragedy and you have a commercial formula that will never wear out
its welcome. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE CHAMBERMAID ON THE TITANIC'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Bigas Luna; written (in French, with English
subtitles) by Luna, Cuca Canals and Jean-Louis Benoit, based on the
novel by Didier Decoin; director of photography, Patrick Blossier;
edited by Kenout Peltier; music by Alberto Iglesias; production
designers, Walter Caprara and Bruno Cesari; produced by Yves
Marmion and Daniel Toscan du Plantier; released by Samuel Goldwyn
Co.
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 96 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: This film is not rated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Romane Bohringer (Zoe), Oliver Martinez (Horty), Aitana
Sanchez Gijon (Marie), Didier Bezace (Simeon) and Aldo Maccione
(Zeppe).
</P>
</TEXT>
