<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2519 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOUNT-ART-EXHIBIT-2TA     08-13 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOUNT-ART-EXHIBIT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS AMERICAN AS 19TH-CENTURY PIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ American 19th-century art is rarely as simple as it
looks. A Thomas Cole landscape seems straightforward enough, with
its mountains, forests and moody skies evoking an inspirational
lift, a nostalgic sigh.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, its impulses are urgent and unsettling, full of
personal disquiet, political directives, spiritual yearning.
</P>
<P>
   Few artists of the period offer challenges as deceptively
disguised as William Sidney Mount (1807-1868).
</P>
<P>
   Mount's subject wasn't the American landscape; it was the
American figure, or, more accurately, the American character, with
its multifarious virtues and defects, generosities and prejudices,
as viewed in the turning-point decades leading up to the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   Mount more or less invented American genre painting, with its
emblematic narratives of everyday life. In doing so, he paved the
way for artists as varied as Winslow Homer, Thomas Eakins, Edward
Hopper, Horace Pippin and Norman Rockwell.
</P>
<P>
   But genre as a style was, until fairly recently, the last
underprivileged frontier of American art historical study. Perhaps
that explains why ``William Sidney Mount: Painter of American
Life'' at the New-York Historical Society is the first
comprehensive consideration of this artist's career in many years.
</P>
<P>
   Organized by Deborah J. Johnson, president of the Museums at
Stony Brook on Long Island, where the bulk of Mount material
resides, the show of 50 paintings, drawings and prints is an ideal
size: big enough to capture the texture of a career, small enough
to let a visitor see everything and still feel fresh enough to go
back to the start and look again.
</P>
<P>
   And that is what one might be inclined to do with a show that
tells so suggestive a story of an artist and his time. Mount was
from Setauket, on Long Island, the son of a farmer who also
operated a tavern and a store. Plagued by ill health, he never
married, didn't travel much, mostly lived with relatives and died
where he was born.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't a recluse, though, or a hayseed. He was a
sophisticated painter who calculatedly played a country-cousin
role. An 1832 self-portrait shows an unpretentiously attractive,
intelligent face, the brow broad and clear, the eyes bright and
looking straight ahead.
</P>
<P>
   It is the self-confident but unromantic demeanor of a young
professional _ he could be a city clerk or a small-town worthy _
who had already tasted success and knew that he had worked hard to
achieve it.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, like many early American artists, Mount started out in
a humble but respectable artisan trade, in his case as an
apprentice sign painter for one of his brothers in Manhattan. He
never forgot his roots in a vernacular tradition: he declared, with
democratic bravado, that he wanted ``to paint for the many, not for
the few.'' But he was ambitious, and other possibilities beckoned.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, naturally, was the European Grand Manner. As a
young man, Mount aspired to being a history painter, at the time
regarded as the noblest calling in the plastic arts. He enrolled at
the recently established National Academy of Design and pursued his
goal, as an early biblical painting inspired by the
Romantic-Classical work of Benjamin West reveals.
</P>
<P>
   Titled ``Christ Raising the Daughter of Jairus'' (1828), the
work caused a major flutter when he exhibited it at the Academy,
though it's hard to see why. It's a tired, bad, old-fogeyish piece.
The figures are stock creations; the emotions the stuff of cut-rate
melodrama.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he suspected that he was on the wrong track, working
against his own grain. For whatever reasons, he went back to Long
Island and, with frequent Manhattan excursions, stayed.
</P>
<P>
   And there he became the history painter he wanted to be, on his
own terms. He began to make, as the art historian Barbara Novak has
observed, something monumental of contemporary fact, not with
high-flown, borrowed rhetoric, but (as Mount himself said) ``with
the industry of a reporter.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that his academic interest declined; far from it. He just
slyly turned it on its head. He based a funky little 1830 painting
of fighting, bloody-nosed schoolboys, for example, on the heroic
figures in Jacques-Louis David's iconic ``Oath of the Horatii.'' A
lesson book in the painting titled ``Grammar Simplified'' lets us
in on the joke.
</P>
<P>
   More important, he began to draw every incident and detail from
near at hand. For his first genre piece, ``Girl With a Pitcher''
(1829), he used his younger sister, Ruth, as his model, posing her
near a rough-hewn shed.
</P>
<P>
   The slightly later and hugely successful ``Rustic Dance After a
Sleigh Ride'' is set in a second-floor bedroom of his family's
home. His eye for the delicacies of quotidian design is tireless,
from the eyelash curl of a door fixture to the piping on the sleeve
of a shirt.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the balance he was after between high and low began to
jell, as is clear in one of his best early paintings, ``Dancing on
the Barn Floor'' (1831). Two young people are engaged in a rustic
pas de deux _ the man has the upward-and-outward look of Mount's
self-portrait _ as a smiling fiddler plays, and you can almost hear
Scots-Irish jigs and reels charging the air.
</P>
<P>
   But what holds the eye is the barn itself, an elaborate
structural puzzle of interlocking planes and taut, flexed lines.
This is the first of Mount's paintings in which country
architecture becomes a character in itself, and one can sense him
struggling _ the endless perspective drawings he did in these years
are proof _ to get it exactly, effortlessly right.
</P>
<P>
   The barn's geometry _ solid, logical, built to last _ was a
reassuring emblem for a society still clinging to an agrarian
self-identity, especially as that identity was changing.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1830s, America's wilderness was all but mythical. Cities
were swollen with immigrants. A class of wealthy, bourgeois
merchants, many of them politically conservative, was on the rise.
The rift between North and South had appeared; slavery was an
inflammatory issue.
</P>
<P>
   All of this finds its way into Mount's narratives, which
increasingly become topical commentaries and morality tales. Some,
like ``Bargaining for a Horse,'' are gibes at the American
character, in this case its shrewd, close-to-the-chest business
practices.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Others, like the repellent ``Catching Rabbits (Boys Trapping),''
are editorials on party politics. The admonition here is that the
Whigs were catching gullible voters while the Democrats (with whom
Mount was at the time aligned) were in disarray.
</P>
<P>
   The meanings of such images, obvious to Mount's patrons, who
basically hired him as a storyteller, must be teased out and
guessed at today. Yet beginning in the 1830s, he produced a number
of paintings, many of which show black Americans playing a central
role, that carry a deep, disturbingly ambiguous resonance today.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most famous of them is ``Farmers Nooning'' (1836), a
depiction of five farmers relaxing on a late-summer afternoon.
Three young men lounge in the shade of a tree. A sleeping black man
lies stretched out on a haystack in full sunlight. A boy in a
tam-o'-shanter leans over him, about to tickle his nose with a
blade of grass.
</P>
<P>
   Mount's Grand Manner preoccupations are in play: the pose of the
sleeping man recalls the image of a sensuous nude goddess by
Correggio then in wide circulation. And his fastidious structural
concerns are apparent. The diagonals of distant crisscrossed fence
posts and a leaning rake handle echo the sleeper's balletically
raised arm; the languid curve of his body is repeated in a scythe
hanging from the tree.
</P>
<P>
   The painting is one of the first sympathetic depictions of a
black figure in all of American art, but the scene is far from
being an idyll. The black man's figure is shown exposed,
unprotected, acted upon, as women traditionally were depicted in
painting. (Mount used a virtually identical image in the later
``Dance of the Haymakers,'' but here the figure is that of a
standing white man.)
</P>
<P>
   The art historian Elizabeth Johns, in her fascinating book on
American genre painting, has read him as a racial stereotype
typifying indolence, and the scene itself as an anti-abolitionist
statement. The nose-tickling child, borrowed from Dutch genre
painting, may stand for reformist forces threatening to awaken the
black slave to a dangerous self-awareness.
</P>
<P>
   Did the artist intend these racial and topical readings? It's
hard to say. He rarely wrote about his attitude toward race, though
he had an abiding affection for his black neighbors on Long Island.
His anti-abolitionist sentiments are a matter of record, but his
reasons for holding them seem to have been complicated rather than
merely knee-jerk.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reality, his depictions of blacks grew in
psychological depth, culminating in two of his finest works, both
from the mid-1840s. In one, ``The Power of Music,'' a middle-age
black man in overalls stands leaning against a barn door, absorbed
in the sound of fiddling inside.
</P>
<P>
   In the other, ``Eel Spearing at Setauket,'' a black woman stands
in the prow of a skiff, spear poised over the water, while a white
child steadies the boat with an oar behind her.
</P>
<P>
   This painting, with its eggshell sky and dun-colored landscape
is both a Luminist masterpiece _ a moment of time is frozen in
light _ and a memory piece, commissioned by the New York lawyer
George Washington Strong as an evocation of his own youth.
</P>
<P>
   It is Mount's only picture of a black woman, and here the
artist's commentarial impulses seem, for once, to be in abeyance.
The result is history painting, American-style, perfected: laden
with sociological data but as still as a classical frieze.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1850s, Mount painted some half-length pictures of black
musicians, like the portrait of a violinist titled ``Right and
Left.'' They depicted their sitters with an animated dignity. But
their references were to minstrel shows and cliched associations of
blacks with music. Conceived as designs for prints, they were meant
to appeal to the European taste for American exotica.
</P>
<P>
   These works aside, Mount's output from the 1850s shows a talent
in decline. Pictures tend to look fussy or bland, as if he had lost
his self-confidence, and with it his touch. By this time, the vogue
for genre-as-history that Mount pioneered was in eclipse.
</P>
<P>
   The task of providing an American self-image had landed
decisively on the landscape machines of Hudson River School artists
like Frederic Edwin Church, whose star was high when Mount died at
60.
</P>
<P>
   The Hudson River painters are, of course, crucial to any
understanding of what made America tick before and after the Civil
War, and they have the advantage of being conceptually opaque and
malleable. You can take them as you wish, as mirrors and shapers of
political sentiment, as searching philosophical statements, or,
collectively, as a kind of lulling transcendentalist mood music.
</P>
<P>
   Mount's work is different. His art is not one of high ideals but
of observations and of opinions, which range from middle of the
road to reactionary. The world he painted, even at its quietest,
jangles with human tension. It is peopled with party animals and
gawky lovers, practical jokers and upright yeomen, demure lasses
and contentious drunks.
</P>
<P>
   The faces of his Long Island folk may be as fresh as apples, but
they hide mundane corruptions: resentments, self-serving
assessments, the dark stuff behind the hearty American ``Hi!''
</P>
<P>
   What you think you see in Mount's work is, in sum, rarely what
you are actually getting. Every situation and gesture is coded (and
because history adds its own input, now double- and triple-coded).
</P>
<P>
   Some of the meanings are probably lost for good; others just
don't matter anymore. But from all of the culturally specific
hustle and bustle, Mount distilled a handful of big-thinking and
unanswering pictures.
</P>
<P>
   In them he really did capture something of America's youthful
but uninnocent heart. And he got at issues, large and small _ race,
political morality, the double-edged power of popular culture _
that are still right on the table, unresolved. What (italics)he(end
italics) made of all of this, he doesn't really say. And in the
end, his willingness to let his art be casually inscrutable _ to
keep a faint ``I know what I know'' reserve behind its homely,
bucolic cheer _ is the most provocative thing about him. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)``William Sidney Mount: Painter of American Life''
remains at the New-York Historical Society, 2 West 77th Street, at
Central Park West, through Oct. 25. It travels to the Frick Art
Museum in Pittsburgh (Nov. 13 to Jan. 10), and to the Amon Carter
Museum in Fort Worth Texas (Feb. 5 to April 4). The exhibition was
organized by the Museums at Stony Brook and the American Federation
of the Arts.(end italics)
</P>
</TEXT>
