<HEADLINE>
`AIR BUD': A GRIDIRON HERO WHO BARKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Production notes at end)  
 (JT)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't tell the new Air Bud, aka Buddy, but he doesn't look all
that good in a football uniform. Maybe it's the shoulder pads.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that, ``Air Bud: Golden Receiver'' is a fine sequel to
``Air Bud,'' last summer's sentimental children's movie in which
the title dog metamorphosed from abused clown's assistant to adored
family pet to basketball star. But this time around it's the boy's
story; the dog's mastery of a new sport is almost a subplot.
</P>
<P>
   Josh (Kevin Zegers, the only major cast member from the original
film still around) is in the eighth grade now and looking good,
living happily with his young widowed mother (Cynthia Stephenson)
and his preternaturally adorable baby sister (Alyson MacLaren) in
the idyllic town of Fernfield. Then a new veterinarian comes to
town. Dr. Patrick Sullivan (Gregory Harrison) seems like a nice
enough guy, but Josh reevaluates him when he starts dating Mom. He
knows it's serious when he learns she has given the doctor a place
on her telephone's speed dial.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason Josh takes up football is to get away from this
budding romance. And his team, the Timberwolves, needs all the help
it can get. Buddy's ability to catch a pass in his mouth and run
like the wind for a touchdown may save them, or it may be their
new-found confidence and spirit.
</P>
<P>
   But into every pet star's life a bad guy must fall, trying to
steal him. In this film, there are two and they're driving an
ice-cream truck. Natalya (Nora Dunn of ``Saturday Night Live'') and
Popov (Perry Anzilotti) are Russian circus people looking for a new
main attraction. They do this in the style of Boris and Natasha of
``The Bullwinkle Show.'' This is not a criticism. In fact, it's
delicious when Ms. Dunn announces, ``That was our boy and dog,''
because it sounds just like ``moose and squirrel.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other ridiculous grown-ups for young moviegoers to
laugh at _ the school principal whose screeching soprano murders
``The Star-Spangled Banner,'' bumbling referees, Tim Conway and
Dick Martin in cameos as game announcers _ but the adult leads are
treated with respect and affection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Air Bud: Golden Receiver'' is a simplistic movie. You can see
the plot developments coming a mile away. And the exposition isn't
always graceful (yes, we need to see the newspaper clipping about
Josh's father's death, but what is a framed 8-by-10 of Dad doing in
the garage?). But the film is pleasantly sweet and occasionally
sharp. (``We'll be the laughingstock of the league,'' one player
complains when it's suggested that they put a dog on the team.
Another boy points out that they already are.)
</P>
<P>
   Buddy (played, according to the cast list, by four golden
retrievers: Rush, Zak, Chase and Chance) is in excellent form. And
if the sight of juvenile football players celebrating touchdowns by
rolling over on their backs and kicking their limbs in the air (in
imitation of Buddy's usual joyful response) doesn't make you smile,
you're a big old grouch.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   AIR BUD
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Richard Martin; written by Paul Tamasy and Aaron
Mendelsohn; director of photography, Mike Southon; edited by Bruce
Lange; production designer, Rex Raglan; produced by Robert Vince;
released by Miramax Films. Running time: 91 minutes. This film is
rated G.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Kevin Zegers (Josh Framm), Cynthia Stevenson (Jackie
Framm), Gregory Harrison (Patrick), Nora Dunn (Natalya), Perry
Anzilotti (Popov), Alyson MacLaren (Andrea) and Robert Costanzo
(Coach Fernelli).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
