<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STELLA-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HOW STELLA GOT HER GROOVE BACK': SHE'S 40, HE'S 20 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back'' is far from the first
Hollywood movie to flaunt the look and attitude of a glitzy travel
brochure. But it may be the first to blatantly portray a tropical
paradise as a sexual mecca beckoning tired American businesswomen
to shed their clothes and inhibitions and roll around with the
local talent.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment she plops herself down at a luxury hotel in
Jamaica, Stella (Angela Bassett), a beautiful, in-shape 40-year-old
San Francisco stockbroker and divorced mother of one, is pursued by
an impeccably courtly 20-year-old hunk named Winston (Taye Diggs).
</P>
<P>
   If Winston has nothing better to do than lounge around hotel
swimming pools waiting for the perfect older woman to appear and
make his indolent life more exciting, he is definitely no gigolo.
The handsome, well-mannered, soft-spoken (and presumably brave,
clean and reverent) son of an affluent local surgeon and his
haughty wife, Winston is biding his time before possibly going to
medical school. He also happens to have the body of a god. And at
various points in the film, which is the directorial debut of Kevin
Rodney Sullivan, the camera pans droolingly over the young man's
well-toned flesh.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent preview screening of the movie, such moments
elicited a collective gasp and squeal from women in the audience.
These soft-core flourishes aren't half as revealing as what a male
strip club might provide, but they still give the movie the flavor
of a Chippendales-in-the-Caribbean promotion.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, adapted by Terry McMillan from her
semi-autobiographical novel, is pointedly boundary-breaking in its
positive portrayal of a May-September relationship between a
younger man and an older woman. And while it presents the rosiest
possible view of such a relationship, it doesn't completely shy
away from the downside. When Winston impulsively introduces Stella
to his parents, the young man's mother, who is just a year older
than Stella, is brutally condescending.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when Winston goes to live with Stella in her gorgeous
home in Marin County, he is more interested in playing video games
with her 11-year-old son, Quincy (Michael Pagan), and consuming
junk food than in following grown-up pursuits. Then there is the
financial discrepancy. Winston appears to have some means (he
produces some pretty expensive gifts for Stella), but even after
she loses her job with a brokerage house, he can't compete with her
level of spending, and he begins to resent it.
</P>
<P>
   In a halfhearted subplot intended to double the movie's suds
quotient, Stella's oldest friend and traveling companion, Delilah
(Whoopi Goldberg), who works in window display (and pulls stunts
like stuffing the crotches of the mannequins modeling Calvin Klein
underwear), is diagnosed with liver cancer but doesn't tell her
friend. A mawkish death-bed scene awkwardly tries to camouflage the
movie's basic lack of interest in Delilah, whom Ms. Goldberg plays
with her customary down-home gusto. That twinkling crocodile grin
hasn't lost its power to charm, shtick though it may be.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bassett's Stella is the best thing in the movie. Proud,
combative and fiery, but also quite vulnerable, she is the farthest
thing from a predatory sensualist in search of kicks. Ms. Bassett
portrays this high-strung superwoman with such intensity that she
makes her almost believable.
</P>
<P>
   Diggs imbues Winston with an easy grace and dignity. But his
performance is too soft-spoken and embellished with too many vacant
smiles for his character to emerge as anything more than a misty
romantic fantasy. Even when he loses his temper, Winston is
impossibly, reassuringly nice.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `HOW STELLA GOT HER GROOVE BACK'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Kevin Rodney Sullivan; written by Terry McMillan and
Ron Bass, based on the novel by Ms. McMillan; director of
photography, Jeffrey Jur; edited by George Bowers; music by Michel
Colombier; production designer, Chester Kaczenski; produced by
Deborah Schindler; released by 20th Century Fox. Running time: 99
minutes. This film is rated R (under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It has sexual situations and one scene
of topless dancing in a disco.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Angela Bassett (Stella), Taye Diggs (Winston), Regina King
(Vanessa), Whoopi Goldberg (Delilah), Suzzanne Douglas (Angela) and
Michael Pagan (Quincy).
</P>
</TEXT>
