u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLUMS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     08-13 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLUMS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SLUMS OF BEVERLY HILLS': A GIRL FROM THE WRONG SIDE OF THE GLITZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tamara Jenkins' playfully autobiographical ``Slums of Beverly
Hills'' begins with the spectacle of Murray Abramowitz (Alan Arkin)
overseeing the purchase of his daughter Vivian's first bra. It's a
moment, like many in the film, that leaves Vivian (Natasha Lyonne)
wide-eyed and aghast, incredulous over what goes on in her family.
</P>
<P>
   And no matter how such a father-daughter episode might play
today, the film is set in a 1976 that it remembers as a more
innocent time. In this atmosphere, Murray's behavior is simply
overbearing and nosy beyond belief.
</P>
<P>
   With a wry air of having been here and done this, Ms. Jenkins
(who developed her story at the Sundance Director's Lab) then leads
her audience on a guided tour of the nomadic habits of the
Abramowitzes, whom she has described as ``Jewish Joads.''
</P>
<P>
   No ``Grapes of Wrath'' setting here, though: the film's
characters simply wander from one garishly named apartment to
another on the fringes of Beverly Hills, where the divorced Murray
is determined to keep his daughter and two sons. He claims he's
doing this for the sake of a good school district, and Arkin makes
his stubborn, meddlesome character so utterly ingenuous that it's
possible to believe him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to show the sweetness and weirdness of people who
will do anything to maintain their dignity,'' Ms. Jenkins has said.
And her idiosyncratic family story does exactly that, while also
chronicling every embarrassment that heralds Vivian's sexual coming
of age. Unusually frank in this regard, the film (which makes ample
use of body doubles) watches Vivian tentatively experiment with the
boy next door, a guy named Eliot (Kevin Corrigan), who is proud of
his Charles Manson T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   It also notes Vivian's amazement at the way Rita (Marisa Tomei),
her zany, glamorous cousin who is just out of rehab, flounces about
in the buff, even in the Abramowitz living room.
</P>
<P>
   Since Vivian isn't one to flounce, she experiences a sexual
awkwardness that is very much akin to her family's socioeconomic
uncertainty. She's an outsider everywhere, and the film treats her
predicament with affectionate humor. Ms. Lyonne (the young narrator
in Woody Allen's ``Everyone Says I Love You'') makes this smart,
rueful young woman a beacon of sanity in the midst of the film's
well-drawn eccentrics, who congregate most hilariously in a variety
of dinner-table episodes.
</P>
<P>
   In one of these scenes, Jessica Walter plays a perfect Beverly
Hills specimen whom Murray is trying to date. In another, Carl
Reiner and Rita Moreno play Rita's parents, who frankly let Murray
know which Abramowitzes are wealthy and which are not.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to know what's coming next in a film that devotes one
sequence to breast-reduction surgery and a couple of others to
Vivian's discovery of the vibrator (courtesy of Rita).
</P>
<P>
   And Ms. Jenkins, who makes her writing and directing debut with
wit and confidence, keeps the small surprises frequent and the
coming-of-age perspective sharp. (One surprise is how little the
film shows of Beverly Hills, except when the Abramowitz family
piles into a car to flee from one apartment to the next.) She makes
the most of an especially ingratiating cast, with Ms. Tomei very
charming and funny as Rita, Corrigan as slyly flirtatious as a
Manson fan can be, and David Krumholtz as the wisecracking brother
who fits right into the Abramowitz ethos.
</P>
<P>
   All of them, especially Ms. Lyonne and Arkin, project a crazy
sincerity that turns this personal and nostalgic comedy into a very
true story indeed.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SLUMS OF BEVERLY HILLS'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Tamara Jenkins; director of photography,
Tom Richmond; edited by Pamela Martin; music by Rolfe Kent;
production designer, Dena Roth; produced by Michael Nozik and Stan
Wlodkowski; released by Fox Searchlight.
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 91 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Slums of Beverly Hills'' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It includes nudity,
profanity and a few sexual situations.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Natasha Lyonne (Vivian), Alan Arkin (Murray), Marisa Tomei
(Rita), Kevin Corrigan (Eliot), Carl Reiner (Mickey), Rita Moreno
(Belle), David Krumholtz (Ben) and Jessica Walter (Doris).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
