<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BOOKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATHER OF PUBLIC RELATIONS IS SUBJECT OF STARTLING BOOK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA MCUSIC 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You may not know Edward Bernays, but he certainly knew you.
</P>
<P>
   Probably no other person, dead or alive, has influenced the
American public so much, yet is known by so few.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his famous uncle, Sigmund Freud, Bernay is unlikely to be
mentioned in schoolbooks. Yet his influence over Americans' daily
habits and thoughts in the 20th century is profound.
</P>
<P>
   Did you have eggs and bacon for breakfast (or at least dreamed
you had)? Thank Eddie Bernays.
</P>
<P>
   Did you take up smoking to stay slim, ladies? Bernays thought up
that concept.
</P>
<P>
   Did you support the Persian Gulf War? You probably didn't know
that some rich Kuwaitis hired Hill and Knowlton to rally the
American public into fighting Iraqi President Saddam Hussein. The
public relations firm learned how to do that from Bernays, the
Father of Public Relations .
</P>
<P>
   Bernays is profiled in a thought-provoking book titled ``The
Father of Spin: Edward L. Bernays and the Birth of Public
Relations'' (Crown, 306 pages, $27.50).
</P>
<P>
   Author Larry Tye, who took a year's leave from The Boston Globe
to write the book, did ample research on his subject. In addition
to a personal interview before Bernays died in 1995, Tye
interviewed more than 100 relatives, friends and co-workers of the
spinmeister.
</P>
<P>
   Tye also sorted through the more than 800 boxes of personal and
professional papers in which Bernays outlined the strategies and
tactics for the cases he handled. He left the boxes to the Library
of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The result of this research is a richly detailed portrait of a
man whose influence is felt worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bernays demonstrated to an entire generation of budding PR men
and women the enormous power that lay within their grasp,'' Tye
writes. ``If housewives could be guided in their selection of soap,
so could husbands in their choice of a car. And voters in their
selection of candidates. And candidates in their political
posturing. Indeed, the very substance of American thought was mere
clay to be molded by the savvy public relations practitioner, or so
it seemed.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernays' revolutionary ideas were based on discovering trends
and capitalizing on them. He called it ``crystallizing public
opinion,'' and it proved to sell products ranging from soap and
hair nets to presidential candidates and war.
</P>
<P>
   Those concepts came indirectly from his famous psychiatrist
uncle, Freud, Tye concludes. The Father of Psychoanalysis and his
quick nephew had numerous long discussions while walking in the
Viennese woods at the beginning of Bernays' career during the
1920s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much as Freud had revolutionized the way the world thought
about individual behavior, so Bernays was able to transform
attitudes toward group action,'' Tye writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used his uncle's ideas in the commercial realm to predict,
then adjust, the way people believed and behaved. Never mind that
they didn't realize it. In fact, all the better.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus Bernays came up with slogans such as ``Reach for a Lucky
(cigarette) Instead of a Sweet'' to entice women to become smokers.
He organized massive soap-sculpting contests to get children
interested in Ivory soap. Representing Mack trucks, he lobbied
Congress for billions of dollars to construct a national highway
system.
</P>
<P>
   The latter became a model for lobbying by powerful political
action committees today, Tye writes.
</P>
<P>
   Many readers will feel uncomfortable with such a documented and
detailed look of how the American public became so malleable.
</P>
<P>
   Tye is quick to point out that some issues in the book are
larger than Bernays.
</P>
<P>
   His book is not just about Bernays, but about America, Tye
writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is about how public thought is routinely shaped or, some
might say, manipulated by singular powers in our culture,'' he
writes. ``And so it is by necessity a book about democracy in the
era of the spinmeister.''
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 1640EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
