<HEADER>
A2548 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISNEY-ANIMALKINGDOM-     08-13 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-ANIMALKINGDOM-1100(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY'S NEWEST KINGDOM SUFFERS FROM HEAT, HUMIDITY, UNCOOPERATIVE
ANIMALS
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by ANIMAL KINGDOM-BOX) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Long before you reach the park, you glimpse the
145-foot-tall Tree of Life that serves as the centerpiece of
Disney's ambitious Animal Kingdom. Even from a mile away, its
majesty is evident, and the closer you get the more impressive the
tree becomes.
</P>
<P>
   The core of the Tree of Life is six steel columns from an oil
rig. The steel is wrapped in Styrofoam and covered with additional
layers of concrete and plaster. A team of 11 sculptors spent 12
months carving 325 individual animal shapes into the
concrete/plaster ``bark,'' and they were fine craftsmen. The detail
in each carving is beyond belief, and the resulting images achieve
photo-ready perfection surpassing the powers of Mother Nature.
</P>
<P>
   It is fair to guess that most visitors to Animal Kingdom since
the park opened this spring consider the Tree of Life their fondest
memory. After all, they probably had an hour or more to study it in
detail while they waited in the soggy Florida heat to see a 3-D
show about bugs in a theater under its ``roots.'' At least the
carved animals on the tree hold still for a Kodak moment. The real
animals in the park, more interested in shade and privacy than
posing, are far less cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   This is the reason Animal Kingdom so far is as much tarnish on
the Disney crown as an additional, sparkling jewel. Disney's
reputation is founded on make-believe, taking visitors into fantasy
worlds that are fun and impervious to any sort of unpleasantness.
All the corporate millions it has poured into Animal Kingdom can't
prevent rhinos from voiding their bowels within sight and smell of
the paying customers _ if the customers even see the rhinos.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the adjacent Magic Kingdom, Epcot Center and MGM/Disney
Studios, Animal Kingdom opens for the day at 7 rather than 9 a.m.,
with good reason. Animals are more likely to move around in the
early morning when it's cool.
</P>
<P>
   First-time visitors will be struck by the immensity of Animal
Kingdom: at 500-plus acres, it is five times the size of Magic
Kingdom or Disneyland. Many have correctly likened the park layout
to the face of a clock. Entrance Plaza is at 6; Safari Village,
with restaurants and gift shops clustered about the Tree of Life,
is in the exact center of the clock face. Dinoland is at 4, Asia at
1, Africa at 11 and Camp Minnie-Mickey at 8. To get anywhere in the
park, it is necessary to begin in Safari Village and cross bridges
to reach another section. Only Asia, still to be completed, and
Africa are on the same ``land mass''; an elaborately-designed
river/moat encircles Safari Village and forms the basis of the
Discovery River Ride that invariably requires 60-120 minutes of
waiting in line and 20 minutes of floating about looking at trees,
shrubs and places where interesting animals might have been spotted
had they chosen to show their snouts in public.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the worst idea to be at the park for its 7 a.m.
opening. The animals are more lively, but that's not the primary
reason.
</P>
<P>
   Animal Kingdom's attractions are divided among fake and real
things. The 3-D It's Tough to Be a Bug! show under the Tree of Life
and Dinoland's Countdown to Extinction, a phony-but-fun thrill ride
reminiscent of MGM/Disney's ``Star Wars'' wow-a-thon, are perfect
to the ``nth'' detail and habituated by people and polythene
figures that perform on cue. At any given time during the day,
you'll wait in line to get into them: Fifteen minutes seems like
the shortest duration, with 30 minutes common and, in the case of
It's Tough to Be a Bug!, an hour to 90 minutes by early afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   But line up for the Kilimanjaro Safari or Discovery River Ride
any time after 8:30 or so, and you might as well resign yourself to
a minimum hour wait, with two hours distinctly possible. Because
these rides are supposed to feature the ``real'' animals, they are
where early arrivals rush _ only to find there often aren't that
many animals to see.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Animal Kingdom doesn't abound in furry or feathered
creatures. But its sheer size, necessary to reproduce the animals'
natural habitats, works against convenient proximity to guests.
Disney has imported 4 million native trees and shrubs from around
the globe; what corporate imagineers saw as stage props turns into
camouflage for hoofed and winged ``cast members.''
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, after a 90-minute wait finally ends with the
boarding of an open-air jeep, Kilimanjaro Safari turns out to be a
20-25 minute ramble through reconstructed African veldt and a
chance to see some giraffes, small elk, a zebra or two and,
perhaps, a brief glimpse of rhino or elephant anatomy. A chart on
the inside of the jeep alerts riders to look for lions, leopards
and other more exciting creatures, but their appearances are,
apparently, sporadic to the point of rumor.
</P>
<P>
   This strains the imaginations of teen-age ``safari guides,'' who
are reduced to chirping, ``Look, there are more giraffe!'' when it
is obvious the twisting tour road is simply bringing the jeep back
by the same bored-looking trio of leaf-chewers that have been
sighted previously.
</P>
<P>
   How to perk up a much-ballyhooed ride that fails to live up to
its advertised excitement? Disney falls back on artificiality. At
the end of Kilimanjaro Safari, there is a hokey ``help catch
poachers'' add-on that concludes with a teen-age ``park ranger''
pointing a plastic gun at some mannequins in a truck. Surely the
corporate imagineers can do better than this.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery River is worse. It has the longest wait times, and
once aboard an open, flat-bottomed boat, there's nothing to do for
15 minutes but listen to the guide assuring passengers the flora
and fauna they're seeing is ``just like'' the real jungle.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 1645EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
