u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     08-13 0413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE YOUNG GIRLS OF ROCHEFORT': REVIVING A SUNNY FRENCH
CONFECTION  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As psychedelic in its way as the Beatles' album ``Sgt. Pepper's
Lonely Hearts Club Band,'' which was released in the same year
(1967), the French musical ``The Young Girls of Rochefort'' is a
garish but charming curiosity that pushes giddy Gallic romanticism
to the brink of camp. Created by Jacques Demy with the composer
Michel Legrand (the same team that concocted ``The Umbrellas of
Cherbourg'' three years earlier), the movie is a sun-drenched,
candy-colored, singing and dancing valentine to the Hollywood
confections of Vincente Minnelli.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Deneuve and her sister Francoise Dorleac (who died
shortly after the film was completed) play beautiful, talented twin
sisters named Delphine and Solange, both waiting for true love to
sweep them into the land of happily ever after. Delphine (Ms.
Deneuve) is a dance teacher whose prince charming, a dreamy-eyed
artist and sailor named Maxence (Jacques Perrin) with dyed blond
hair, has already painted a picture of the true love he has yet to
meet.
</P>
<P>
   Solange (Dorleac), a composer of frilly pianistic kitsch, falls
in love at first sight with a touring American concert pianist
named Andy (Gene Kelly). Solange and Andy first collide in a music
shop run by Simon (Michel Piccoli), the long-lost true love of the
twins' mother, Yvonne (Danielle Darrieux), a local cafe owner who
refused to marry him because his last name was Dame. This modern
fairy tale doesn't just rain happy endings, it pours them.
</P>
<P>
   Filmed in the French coastal city of Rochefort, the movie
features several sweeping dance numbers through the sunlit streets
(Kelly is too old for his role but still dances brilliantly), as
well as a lovely but much too insistent theme song that is known
today by the title ``You Must Believe in Spring.''
</P>
<P>
   With its overdubbed vocals and tinny orchestrations sometimes
augmented with wordless bubbly Swingle Singers-style vocals, the
score belongs very much to the period. But as it goes along, the
movie, which has been carefully restored, works its way under your
skin, and you root for those happily ever afters, inevitable though
they may be.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Young Girls of Rochefort'' is playing at Film Forum, 209
West Houston Street, South Village. Information: (212) 727-8110.
Tickets: $8.50; $4.50 for Film Forum members.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 1645EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2552 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISNEY-ANIMALKINGDOM-     08-13 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-ANIMALKINGDOM-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
ORLANDO, Fla.: the real jungle. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Hours of line-waiting are exacerbated by the sheer effort it
takes to move from one part of Animal Kingdom to another. The park
is huge _ as it should be. Maybe the animals don't cooperate, but
Disney has given them all the room they need to wander. (Last fall,
Disney received considerable bad publicity when animal-rights
adherents protested the deaths of 29 animals that were either en
route to Animal Kingdom or briefly in place in the still-unopened
park.)
</P>
<P>
   But Animal Kingdom's immensity means guests, even families with
small children and/or older visitors, have to walk long stretches
just to get from one place or another. Besides strollers for
toddlers, there's no means of transportation other than on foot.
Magic Kingdom veterans are used to turning a corner between
Fantasyland and Tomorrowland. Walking from Dinoland to Camp
Minnie-Mickey seems like an Anaheim-to-Orlando trek by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Physical exertion is compounded by the steamy Florida weather.
Most of the time, it is uncomfortably muggy at best. Factor in
1998's sizzling summer, and by midafternoon in Animal Kingdom, it
feels as though you're moving around with your entire body wrapped
in a soggy towel.
</P>
<P>
   Disney hasn't failed to notice. The company traditionally
equates ``free'' with ``sinful,'' but at various points in Animal
Kingdom there are stands giving away paper cups of ice water. Small
cups, to be sure, but still free.
</P>
<P>
   Except for installing moving sidewalks or providing trams, there
isn't much Disney can do to reduce the amount of walking Animal
Kingdom requires. But adding those amenities would badly detract
from the authentic wilderness atmosphere the company has spent
hundreds of millions to create.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Sore feet, overheated brows and uncooperative animals are all
part of the Animal Kingdom experience, but only part. The park has
a lot of good things going for it; these are just easy to overlook
because of the obvious discomforts.
</P>
<P>
   Besides whiny kids and grouchy grown-ups, the Animal Kingdom
pathways teem with colorful performers. African storytellers
conjure all sorts of exotic jungle visions to those who'll stop
long enough to watch and listen. Strolling bands play unusual
instruments, producing engaging if unfamiliar tunes. Some sort of
odd-looking bird-men stride along on stilts. It's a fabulously
bizarre bazaar.
</P>
<P>
   The stage shows, especially ``Journey Into Jungle Book,'' are
first-class, from costuming to sound. These are generous both in
length and entertainment, full-blown Broadway-quality fun. The
20-30 minutes you spend enjoying them in the covered outdoor
theaters offer a welcome respite from the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Gorilla Falls Exploration Trail's staggered dioramas offer
better chances to glimpse various animals than the overhyped
Kilimanjaro Safari. True, the gorillas and their other hairy
cohorts aren't much in evidence. But there is plenty of colorful
signage and peripheral exhibits _ charts, models and so forth _ to
make you feel the 20-30 minute stroll has been worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible there has never been any 3-D show better, or at
least more enjoyable, than It's Tough to Be a Bug! In the cool
theater under the Tree of Life, all the special effects are
dazzling. 3-D-glasses-wearing audience members guffaw, shriek and
applaud as they experience being splashed with bug acid, stung by
hornets, buzzed by bees and gassed by stink bugs. It sounds
moderately awful but is nothing but sheer fun. Yes, there are a few
interesting facts offered by a plastic ant narrator. But mostly
it's slapstick, an eight-minute serving of welcome folderol.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Animal Kingdom is marketed by Disney as a great opportunity for
educational adventure. Those terms needn't be incompatible. Epcot
Center has thrived precisely because kids are brought there by
parents or other adults to learn and have fun at the same time. But
even Epcot doesn't rely on real wild animals. By striving for
authenticity, Animal Kingdom falls short on convenience. This can
work at a zoo, but Disney patrons want more cooperation for their
money.
</P>
<P>
   Because the company seems to poll every second visitor to the
park, Disney is undoubtedly aware of the mixed response from most
Animal Kingdom visitors. It has some plans for immediate change _
new attractions are due to open soon in the Asia area, for
instance. There will undoubtedly be more pretend stuff like It's
Tough to Be a Bug! and Countdown to Extinction, prime entertainment
operating under rigid human control.
</P>
<P>
   But animals are going to follow their own instincts, not Disney
dictates. Walt Disney World spokeswoman Jennie Hess says attendance
so far has surpassed expectations, although Disney never reveals
specific figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call (Animal Kingdom) a new species of theme park,'' Hess
says. ``It's not a zoo. It has sheer entertainment and other
elements of Disney woven in with a whole new adventure with
animals. That's what we want to do _ let people know what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney understands its challenge is to reconcile the
expectations of park visitors to the vagaries of animal behavior.
Either it will, or a few years from now comedians will probably
begin referring to Animal Kingdom as EuroDisney II.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
