<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2561 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HENRY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     08-13 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HENRY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HENRY: PORTRAIT OF A SERIAL KILLER 2': THAT'S JUST HIS MANNER. 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The minute Louisa (Carri Levinson), the young bespectacled
schoolteacher, walks in the door, you know she's too prim and
repressed not to mean trouble. By the end of the movie, she's bound
either to blossom into a ravenous sexual being or to kill somebody.
Too bad the same thing isn't as clear about Henry (Neil Giutoli).
</P>
<P>
   Audiences at ``Henry: Portrait of a Serial Killer 2'' know about
Henry from the beginning because his first scene is a calm
nighttime murder of a woman in the woods. But seen later having
dinner and sleeping at a shelter for the homeless, Henry looks
harmless. He is, in fact, completely capable of being creeped out,
even putting his head under the covers when in the bed next to his,
an elderly man makes an unwelcome sexual visit to another.
</P>
<P>
   So it's understandable that Kai and Cricket, the couple Henry
meets when he takes a job delivering portable toilets, invite him
home for meatloaf and to stay a while until he can get a place of
his own. Pretty soon Kai (Rich Komenich) has also invited Henry to
join him in his work moonlighting as a hired arsonist.
</P>
<P>
   And pretty soon after that, Henry has shown Kai how emotionally
satisfying killing somebody can be after a hard day of being
treated like an insignificant slug. Early in the film, Kai asks
Henry, ``Is cleaning out toilets for $40 a day all you want out of
life?'' Little does he know.
</P>
<P>
   None of the people in this movie seem to have given a lot of
thought to their ethical standards. They're petty criminals, drug
dealers who slip LSD into other people's drinks, parents who beat
up other parents over their children's disagreements. But Cricket
(Kate Walsh) at least has limits.
</P>
<P>
   When she notices the growing bond between Henry and Louisa, her
live-in niece, Cricket tells Kai to give him his walking papers.
The film then asks the question, ``What do you do when you want the
serial killer staying at your house to leave?'' Predictably the
results include stabbing, dismemberment and blood gushing from
mouths and throats.
</P>
<P>
   The film is a sequel to John McNaughton's ``Henry: Portrait of a
Serial Killer'' (1990), which earned some positive reviews, if only
for cinematic technique. But no major players in the earlier film
have returned for this one. The writer and director (Chuck Parello)
is new, as are the producer, cinematographer, editor and cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Henry 2'' is a passable psychological slasher movie for fans
of the genre, but Giutoli makes Henry's coexisting woundedness and
amorality fascinating to watch. It's even believable when after one
character shoots herself in the head in front of him, he's visibly
upset.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `HENRY: Portrait of a Serial Killer 2'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Chuck Parello; director of photography,
Michael Kohnhurst; edited by Tom Keefe; music by Robert F.
McNaughton; produced by Thomas J. Busch and Parello; released by
Margin Films.
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 85 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Henry: Portrait of a Serial Killer 2'' is rated R
(Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult guardian). It
includes profanity, sexual situations and numerous scenes of
graphic, brutal violence. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Neil Giutoli (Henry), Rich Komenich (Kai), Kate Walsh
(Cricket), Carri Levinson (Louisa), Daniel Allar (Rooter) and
Penelope Milford (Woman in Woods).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 1651EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
