<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0219 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2572 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-ETHNIC-ENTERTAINME     08-13 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ETHNIC-ENTERTAINMENT-ART-4TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER COUNTRY HEARD FROM 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If all New Yorkers share one experience, it's the
sensation of suddenly feeling like a tourist without leaving the
city. Take an alternate route, turn an unfamiliar corner, peek into
an open doorway, and suddenly you could be in Tokyo or Timbuktu,
with strangers chatting in an unknown language while intriguing
scents waft from a kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   New York is Dakar north and Budapest east; there are contingents
from Ireland and Uzbekistan, Lebanon and Peru. And they hold on to
the places they left behind by gathering for music, theater or
movies from the old country, wherever that might be.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those events invite outsiders, like ``The Last
Empress,'' a lavish Korean music-theater spectacle currently at the
New York State Theater. Most others serve their own constituencies,
unrecognized by the city's self-described mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   They flourish from midtown Manhattan to the fringes of the other
boroughs, and they generally greet outsiders with curiosity,
indifference or mild amusement. Still, a performer never minds
seeing a new face in the audience.
</P>
<P>
   The places and events below offer possibilities for cultural
globe-trotting in the city. Some are large public events, some
neighborhood haunts. And if you feel as if you've wandered off the
subway into another country, well, that's how you know you're in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Homesick Brazilians head for the center of Greenwich Village on
Monday nights, when two weekly events take place a few blocks
apart.
</P>
<P>
   At the Cafe Wha, a basement club that has persisted on Macdougal
Street through eras of hippies and yuppies, the Monday night draw
is a band that usually features the buoyant singer Vanessa
Falabella. The house band plays Brazilian pop hits from the last
three decades, featuring material by the songwriters of Brazil's
tropicalia pop revolution.
</P>
<P>
   This is some of the most casually sophisticated music (and
lyrics, for those who speak Portuguese) of the 20th century. While
various singers and instrumentalists take turns in the spotlight,
and the audience joins in on favorite refrains, the crowd divides
its attention between music and shmoozing.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd pours down the staircase, packing the room by midnight;
conversation buzzes but doesn't overwhelm the music. In true
Brazilian style, every greeting is an embrace.
</P>
<P>
   Things are more boisterous around the corner at the Elbow Room,
which used to be the Bleecker Street Theater. The club's Monday
nights feature Ogans, a band from Bahia with 11 members, 9 of them
drummers, that's modeled on a Bahian band, Timbalada. The dancing
starts as D.J. Binho warms up the crowd with recent Brazilian hits,
and it explodes when the band takes the stage at 11:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   As the beats of sambas, Bahian sambareggae and the peppy new
Bahian pop called axe boom from the stage, impromptu line dancing
takes over the front of the room while couples on the sidelines
explore sinuous hip-to-hip maneuvers. To tell the Brazilians from
the Brazilophiles, see who's singing along in Portuguese and watch
the light, double-time quick-stepping of true samba dancers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Belly Dancing and Kebabs
</P>
<P>
   Cedars of Lebanon in Manhattan is a restaurant most of the week,
but on Saturdays it turns into a Middle Eastern supper club, with a
fixed-price menu ($35 for eight appetizers and a kebab entree) and
a performance that brings Hollywood glitter to belly dancing.
</P>
<P>
   A good Arabic pop band starts playing around 10 p.m., working up
momentum with oud, vocals and kinetic drumming. Then the stage is
extended into the middle of the room, and out come the three belly
dancers in satin and sequins, with veils and, in one number,
glittering red canes.
</P>
<P>
   The audience watches with studied impassivity as the women shake
and shimmy, though there's an appreciative murmur when one of them
comes out to dance with a three-tiered candelabrum on her head.
After an audience member showers bills on the dancers, the
bartender steps up to the stage with a feather duster to sweep the
money into a neat pile.
</P>
<P>
   Indian Fantasies
</P>
<P>
   One of the few old New York movie theaters that hasn't been
turned into a multiplex is the Eagle Theater in Jackson Heights,
Queens, an Art Deco-style survivor with about 700 seats. And
although its marquee is blank, the theater is still active.
</P>
<P>
   It's a showcase for popular Indian films from the hyperactive
movie studios of Bombay, affectionately known as Bollywood, as well
as some films from Pakistan. The theater also occasionally presents
local Pakistani musicians performing pop, folk and light classical
music.
</P>
<P>
   Samosas, Indian dumplings, are sold at the Eagle's refreshment
stand alongside popcorn and nachos, and early arrivals head for the
back section of seats, the better to take in the large screen and
cope with the over-amplified sound.
</P>
<P>
   A typical Bollywood film is a genre-bending combination of
comedy, musical and action; the plot pauses for madcap production
numbers, as high-concept as music videos, with the actors
lip-syncing to the voices of ``playback singers'' who have become
famous in their own right.
</P>
<P>
   In the film playing now, ``Pyaar To Homa Hi Tha,'' a slapstick
comedy-romance-musical, there's one nutty sequence on a tilting
airplane that even includes a ``Macarena'' parody. The movie
doesn't have subtitles, but every so often the actors switch to
English for a line or two, and the frothy plot isn't hard to
follow.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentallly, one of India's top playback singers, Asha
Bhosle, is to perform Saturday night at Alice Tully Hall. With
12,000 songs in her catalog, she claims to be the most recorded
singer in history. Her sweet, smooth, girlish voice doesn't reveal
any wear and tear.
</P>
<P>
   Another side of South Asian culture in New York can be sampled
Friday night at S.O.B.'s in SoHo when D.J. Rekha and others take
over the turntables for an all-night bhangra dance party. Bhangra
combines traditional music from the Indian subcontinent with
up-to-date dance music in ever-shifting East-West hybrids. It gives
young South Asians a taste of home in a modern context.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Russian Revelry
</P>
<P>
   The nightclubs of Brighton Beach, Brooklyn, offer a perpetual,
slightly surreal Russian wedding party in settings that trumpet
their opulence. It's all there: the fancy-dressed families that
look like someone's in-law's cousins, the towering platters of food
and steady drinking, and the band that tries to please everyone
from grandma to the kids.
</P>
<P>
   Groups arrive and settle in for fixed-price banquets, working
their way through acres of smoked fish, bushels of pierogi and seas
of vodka, periodically hitting the dance floor to try to work off
the effects.
</P>
<P>
   Two leading Slavic nightclubs are the Odessa and the National.
The Odessa, a few blocks beyond the main Brighton Beach strip, has
the feeling of a ballroom on a cruise ship: medallioned ceilings,
crystal chandeliers, compass points inlaid in the dance floor and
swags everywhere. Of course, there are disco lights, too.
</P>
<P>
   The band, with a synthesizer at its core, plays schmaltzy
ballads growled in Russian, blippy quasi-disco dance music and,
every so often, a hora that has the men dancing with arms around
one another's shoulders, kicking high into the air, while the women
gingerly join them, doing the best they can in high heels.
</P>
<P>
   The National, which offers valet parking, aims for a Las
Vegas-circa-1976 look, with white gauze and artificial vines
interlacing the ceiling and multicolored lights on the walls.
</P>
<P>
   Late one recent Saturday night, after two women in the band had
sung ``Happy Birthday'' _ in Spanish! _ an actual wedding party
from the private room upstairs gradually dispersed, offering the
spectacle of the bride, still in her gown and train, trying to
squeeze through the revolving doors. The Russian accordion heritage
came in handy.
</P>
<P>
   Parisian Tango
</P>
<P>
   La Belle Epoque is a restaurant with a French name and
turn-of-the-century-style French decor, complete with a
wrought-iron staircase and Parisian street signs. But on Friday
nights, it dedicates itself to the elegance, sensuality and
suppressed menace of the tango; after all, Paris has long been a
tango stronghold.
</P>
<P>
   Argentines and other serious tango aficionados gather to dance
to a live band, with the traditional bandoneon (tango accordion) at
its core.
</P>
<P>
   A few novices take advantage of the early-evening tango lessons.
But once they're over, people who know their tango crowd the tiled
dance floor. Recently, a woman in a skin-tight red dress danced
with a suave man in a gray suit, welded with him hip to hip or
suddenly cocking one knee to twitch a pointed toe in the air.
</P>
<P>
   In another couple, the woman leaned on her partner, to be
dragged across the floor for a few bars of music, then shared a
deep dip like a controlled swoon.
</P>
<P>
   On the sidelines, silver-haired men shared quiet conversations,
occasionally taking an impassive look at the dancers. Even when the
band took a break, and tango records were played, the dancing
continued. If it's not a classic tango palace _ there are no knife
fights or crimes of passion in the shadows _ the couples on the
dance floor were too intent on their steps, and their partners, to
mind.
</P>
<P>
   Irish Jigs and Reels
</P>
<P>
   Ireland's national symbol is a harp, and more than a few of New
York's bars with Irish names present music regularly, from rowdy
rock to ardent singer-songwriters.
</P>
<P>
   A mainstay of Irish traditional music has been the Friday night
series at the Blarney Star in TriBeCa, a long, narrow basement room
where inexpensive bar food and foaming pints are served. The
acoustic-tile ceiling, though not handsome, helps the sound of each
instrument come through clearly; the beauty of Irish music is in
its details of trills and slides.
</P>
<P>
   At the Blarney Star, musicians visiting from Ireland and Celtic
traditionalists from the New York area delve into the abundant
heritage of jigs and reels, hornpipes and slow airs. When Moving
Heart, from County Clare, played the Blarney Star two weeks ago,
its members carefully explained the provenance of each tune,
sometimes noting regional variations.
</P>
<P>
   The audience, mostly a generation older than the musicians,
listened intently, and when the dance tunes revved up, feet started
to tap, decorously but firmly.
</P>
<P>
   Irish music fans will be out in force this weekend at Lincoln
Center Out of Doors, which is presenting a day of Irish music
Saturday beginning at 2 p.m. The best-known performer is Tommy
Makem, appearing both in the afternoon and at 9:20 p.m., who will
have the crowd singing along on old ballads and rebel songs.
</P>
<P>
   DJs in the Garden
</P>
<P>
   New York has subcultures of affinity as well as ethnicity. One
subculture that rarely gathers by daylight, the
fashion-art-collegiate-dance nexus, is making an exception this
summer at P.S. 1 Contemporary Art Center, the art and performance
space in Long Island City, Queens.
</P>
<P>
   A Saturday afternoon series, ``Warm Up,'' that continues through
this month, offers music by disk jockeys and occasional live
musicians. Sponsored by the designer Agnes B., ``Warm Up'' presents
some DJs who aim for dance-music propulsion, others who prefer to
generate atmosphere and noise.
</P>
<P>
   They fill the courtyard with anything from ratcheting
drum-'n'-bass dance music to untempered noise, which goes nicely
with the sound of the subways rumbling nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Thin, nonchalant, carefully accessorized people in their 20s,
with cryptic T-shirts or jokey handbags, sit at the feet of the
disk jockeys or wander in the courtyard amid towers of castoffs
built by an art group called Gelatin. (``Climb at your own risk,''
a sign says.) Kebabs and corn on the cob sizzle on a grill.
</P>
<P>
   A few wander into P.S. 1 for an exhibition of drawings and
projects by Gordon Matta-Clark, the architectural visionary who
suggested, among other things, buildings held aloft by balloons.
His ``Open House,'' a Dumpster divided into rooms, is also in the
courtyard. The coolest of the cool find their way inside a tower
made of old refrigerators; look for the door of a beige Hotpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Salsa's Midtown Citadel
</P>
<P>
   As radios and boomboxes proclaim, New York is one of salsa's
world capitals, as much a center of Latin music recording and live
performance as Miami or any point south. And the quintessential
salsa experience is to dance to a live band, driving home its
mambos or merengues with horns and percussion.
</P>
<P>
   The Copacabana, a famous name even at a different Manhattan
location, is a state-of-the-art salsa club, booking major names
from Puerto Rico, the Dominican Republic, Colombia and, of course,
New York, and presenting them with a superb sound system.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The setup is like a large disco, with hefty bouncers outside
checking ID's and dress _ jeans and sneakers are frowned upon _
before guests pass through a metal detector. The club has a huge
oblong dance floor with tables around the perimeter where big
spenders order bottles of rum or champagne.
</P>
<P>
   The ceiling is covered with disco lighting rigs; behind the
stage, a glittering backdrop generates endless golden starbursts.
</P>
<P>
   Between songs, a disk jockey mixes salsa and dance music sung in
English, but the bands stick to salsa, merengue and Latin pop. And
the dance floor is, invariably, packed, with men in jackets or
designer sportswear and women in tight dresses.
</P>
<P>
   Couples whose ages range from their 20s to their 50s share dance
after dance. Sharply dressed men approach unattached women and
guide them, with hands raised, into the graceful crowd. In case of
overflow, there's a second bar off the main room, with its own
tennis-court-size dance floor.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese Opera
</P>
<P>
   There's an opera house in midtown that's not part of Lincoln
Center. It's the Taipei Theater, tucked into the McGraw-Hill
Building, and for seven years it has been offering Chinese opera,
sponsored by the Chinese Information and Culture Center, a group
connected to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   The theater's regular season features Chinese opera, with its
grand costumes, stylized acting and athletic feats. But this
weekend it has a different program. The Formosa Aboriginal Song and
Dance Troupe, with members from various tribes of the island, is
presenting two rituals: the Ceremony of the Short Men,
commemorating the Saisat tribe's near-genocide of the Short Men
tribe, and songs of the Ami tribe to solemnize, among other things,
news gathering and headhunting.
</P>
<P>
   Jamaican Spirit and Fire
</P>
<P>
   Jamaican reggae has long since conquered the world, leaving its
backbeat in rock and country music, spawning reggae bands from
Japan to Brazil. But its largest, most dedicated audience is still
from Jamaica, and since the 1980s reggae has re-emphasized its
origins by turning toward dancehall, with rapping in a thick
Jamaican patois that can leave non-Jamaicans uncomprehending.
</P>
<P>
   A daylong festival at the Forest Hills Tennis Stadium on Sunday
will survey some of reggae's finest current performers, notably
Buju Banton, who has moved from dancehall boasting to positive
thinking and fuses the reggae groove with all sorts of outside
styles.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also includes the romantic crooner Beres Hammond, the
hip-hop-influenced toasters (rappers) Bounty Killer and Shaggy, the
long-running vocal group Steel Pulse, the South African reggae
singer Lucky Dube and, as a bonus, a handful of soca (soul-calypso)
singers from around the West Indies. Together, they should cover
the spectrum from romance to righteousness.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Korean Pageant
</P>
<P>
   ``The Last Empress,'' at the New York State Theater, is musical
theater filled with national pride. It's about nothing less than
the transition for Chosun, Korea's old name, from isolation and
traditionalism to modernity, ending with a takeover by the Japanese
and a vow to rise again.
</P>
<P>
   (Korea did survive, of course.) It's like a reply to Stephen
Sondheim's ``Pacific Overtures'' and, with the cagey, determined
and ultimately doomed Empress as its heroine, an Asian version of
``Evita.''
</P>
<P>
   Hints of older Korean pop and traditional music merge with
show-tune pomp; every scene is a grandly costumed tableau, with
supertitles to help the half of the audience that doesn't speak
Korean. It merges the dignity of Asian theater with Broadway
razzle-dazzle, satisfying both Asian and American tastes.
</P>
<P>
   A Mexican Cantina
</P>
<P>
   The shortest land route across Latin America might just be
Roosevelt Avenue in Jackson Heights, Queens, which spans Mexico and
Colombia, Ecuador and the Dominican Republic. The area around 82nd
Street is lined with Hispanic stores, restaurants and clubs, geared
primarily to the people who live and work in the neighborhood. The
area is so compact that children selling roses to couples on the
town work the entire strip, end to end.
</P>
<P>
   Plaza Garibaldi could be a cantina in a small Mexican city; it
serves modestly priced food to a working-class crowd, mostly groups
of men interspersed with a few couples. But unlike most Mexican
restaurants, it has a stage that's a stucco fantasy, resembling a
cave with a view over mountains.
</P>
<P>
   There, a band plays until 4 a.m. each night, moving from
clip-clopping cumbias and the oom-pah beat of rancheras to ardent,
lovelorn boleros. Unfortunately, it has a synthesizer instead of an
accordion.
</P>
<P>
   There's a small dance floor in front of the stage, but on a
recent Friday night it stayed empty; the audience applauded the
singers but preferred to ruminate over heartbreak and hard work at
their tables.
</P>
<P>
   West Indian Carnival
</P>
<P>
   Brooklyn turns into the West Indies every Labor Day when the
annual West Indian-American Carnival parades down Eastern Parkway
for a crowd of up to a million people. This month, the preparations
grow feverish. Ornate costumes are being sewn and steel-drum
orchestras are rehearsing as the latest crop of party tunes arrives
from the English-speaking Caribbean and from Brooklyn's own
recording studios.
</P>
<P>
   On the weekend before Labor Day, there are major concerts, on
the grounds of the Brooklyn Museum of Art, of steel bands, reggae
and calypso; those lineups are still being arranged. But many
performers are already in town.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday at Roseland in Manhattan, the World Soca Monarch
Competition will bring together top singers from many islands,
competing for an $8,000 prize. Soca, or soul-calypso, is the
modernized, faster and, sometimes, less thoughtful version of
calypso, which has traditionally merged wry social commentary with
dance music.
</P>
<P>
   The Mighty Sparrow, the pioneer of modern calypso who won so
often that he is out of the competition, is on the bill, which also
includes Ronnie McIntosh, Iwer George and Denyse Plummer from
Trinidad and Tobago, along with competition winners from recent
carnivals in Barbados, Antigua, Grenada and St. Vincent.
</P>
<P>
   They will be singing about local and international politics,
about preserving island culture and about the best ways to party.
</P>
<P>
   Steel-drum, or pan, bands emerge at carnival time, carrying on a
tradition that dates back to World War II, when Trinidad was a
naval refueling port and musicians hammered leftover oil barrels
into ringing, resonant instruments. While steel bands go marching
by during the carnival parade, their practice sessions offer a
chance to hear them up close and at length in some of the world's
most jubilant music.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One session takes place on Sunday evenings at Volume II, an
outdoor setup in the middle of a Caribbean neighborhood in
Flatbush, Brooklyn. It's an asphalt lot ringed by chain-link fence
and razor wire, decorated with the plastic pennants used for
gas-station openings. Neighbors come out on stoops and sidewalks
across the street, listening to the music while skipping the
admission charge.
</P>
<P>
   At one end of the lot, a booming mobile sound system is set up,
with a disk jockey playing island hits through the afternoon and
early evening while people sip beer and occasionally give in to the
rhythm and dance.
</P>
<P>
   At 9:30 last Sunday, the Casym Steel Orchestra took over for a
half-hour medley of this year's repertory. Most of the band members
are teen-agers, with a front line of girls who bent
conspiratorially over their drums when the music decrescendoed,
then straightened up, grinning, as the melodies swelled and pealed.
The beat, tapped out on drums and cowbells and brake shoes, was
irresistible; even the band members danced as they played.
</P>
<P>
   ``You like this music?'' a gray-bearded man asked an obvious
outsider. When the answer was an enthusiastic yes, he smiled and
danced away with the rump-shaking strut Trinidadians call
``wining,'' a preview of the carnival to come. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
