<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIRL-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WHEN I WAS A GIRL': TEMPESTS OF ADOLESCENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fred Koehler is such a natural in ``When I Was a
Girl, I Used to Scream and Shout'' you forget now and then that the
play is not about him.
</P>
<P>
   As the title broadly suggests, the comedy-drama, by the Scottish
writer Sharman Macdonald, is, among other things, a bittersweet
look back at the turmoil in the life of a confused teen-age girl.
But Koehler, playing Ewan, a drifting young slacker unimpressed by
any satisfaction of life that doesn't involve the physical, draws
disproportionate attention to Ewan's plight with a canny,
effortlessly honest performance. It's endearing in spite of itself.
</P>
<P>
   The play, which made its debut in 1984 at the Bush Theater in
London, is having its American premiere in a production by the John
Montgomery Theater Company, under the direction of Patricia
Minskoff. With a cast that also includes the excellent Roberta
Maxwell as a self-involved matriarch who remains a bit of an
adolescent herself, the play gets the intelligent handling it
deserves. The intimate space in which it is being staged, on the
12th floor of an office building on West 26th Street, fairly
duplicates the cramped quarters of the Bush, a tiny innovative
theater above a pub on the outskirts of central London.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I Was a Girl'' will feel to some women like some aspect
of their own story. Ms. Macdonald fills the work with the kind of
memoir-specific characters and places that endow it with a
comforting authenticity. It's actually two distinct narratives:
one, a present-tense tale of grown-up Fiona (Robin Morse), reunited
with her mother, Morag (Ms. Maxwell) and her childhood friend Vari
(Juliet Pritner) on a tense vacation in the Scottish coastal town
where she grew up, and the other, the coming-of-age story of
Fiona's lonely, scarring upbringing.
</P>
<P>
   The two strains intertwine in the murky details of Fiona's
disastrous pregnancy at the age of 15, a condition the young girl
conspires to achieve in a misguided scheme to punish her mother and
a perverse effort to assert her independence.
</P>
<P>
   Although the events leading to Fiona's babymaking are plainly
documented onstage _ in one of the coldest and clumsiest seductions
in the annals of modern romance, Fiona all but entraps the eager if
unwitting Ewan in furtherance of her plan _ Ms. Macdonald remains
intriguingly vague as to the aftermath. These melodramatic aspects
don't interest her.
</P>
<P>
   The play, in fact, is largely about the question of control, of
one's own body and others' hearts; in a series of flashbacks to
their pre-adolescent and teen-age years, Ms. Morse and Ms. Pritner
perform childish examinations of one another, giggle over bodily
functions and drill on the particulars of sex. The scenes between
adult Fiona and Morag, both deserted by Fiona's father, extend the
mother-daughter struggle of their earlier life together; it's a
measure of the sophistication of Ms. Macdonald's script that they
ultimately wrestle to a draw.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Maxwell is never less than a pleasure to behold as the
egocentric Morag, a mother who appears alternately tender and
buffoonish, seeking her child's acceptance even as she obsesses
over her own desirability: ``Cut my head off, I'd look 19,'' she
says. But Ms. Morse, who struggles with a Scottish accent, and Ms.
Pritner, who does better with hers, never seem to be performing on
the same stage; they act at such different pitches, it's as if they
were broadcasting on separate radio frequencies. They never achieve
the joined-at-the-hip intimacy their parts demand.
</P>
<P>
   They might take some pointers from the flawless Koehler. He does
wonders with the incidental (and quite tricky) role he's been
handed. The sleep-deprived gaze, the cold-climate pallor, the
stooped shoulders: They're touches that enliven the lump Ewan is
supposed to be. In the sequel, as in real life, you'd surely be
curious to know what happens to him.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: `WHEN I WAS A GIRL, I USED TO SCREAM AND
SHOUT'
</P>
<P>
   By Sharman Macdonald; directed by Patricia Minskoff; assistant
to the director, Carole Caprio; sets by Charles Townsend Wittreich
Jr.; lighting by John Tees III; costumes by Anne Guay; sound by
Raymond Schilke. Presented by the John Montgomery Theater Company.
At 134 W. 26th St., Suite 1202, Manhattan. WITH: Roberta Maxwell
(Morag), Robin Morse (Fiona), Juliet Pritner (Vari) and Fred
Koehler (Ewan).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 1703EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2597 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATL-REVIEW-BILLY     08-13 0445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATL-REVIEW-BILLY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A light-as-gossamer Hollywood `Kiss'
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Billy's Hollywood Screen Kiss'' is a flirty little film that's
about as substantial as a vacation fling. It has a good heart and
an appealing manner, but there's no staying power.
</P>
<P>
   Billy (Sean P. Hayes) is a movie-struck photographer from the
Midwest who has recently moved to Los Angeles. But, as he points
out in his droll introduction, all anyone notices about him is that
he's gay.
</P>
<P>
   Billy is also a romantic, still looking for that special guy. He
thinks he's found him when, one day in a coffee shop, he meets a
young waiter named Gabriel (Brad Rowe, a gorgeous-boy blend of Brad
Pitt and Rob Lowe circa 1985).
</P>
<P>
   But is he or isn't he? Gay, that is. Gabriel keeps talking about
his girlfriend back in San Francisco and doesn't seem to have, as
Billy puts it, ``the show-tune gene.'' But as Billy's friend Perry
(Richard Ganoung) says, ``He talks straight, but every once in a
while, you get a vibe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A vibe,'' it seems, is all Billy can get as hunky Gabriel
keeps himself tantalizingly available without ever committing to a
real relationship or admitting his true sexual orientation. Things
come to a head when Gabriel is hired for a swimsuit shoot on
Catalina Island by a famous _ and flaming _ fashion photographer
(Paul Bartel) and Billy can't keep himself from checking up on his
new friend.
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Tommy O'Haver calls his movie ``a trifle,'' the
way Spike Lee calls his films ``a joint.'' True enough. ``Billy's''
is a flyweight at best. More problematical, it's all too familiar.
We've seen Billy before in too many gay romantic comedies: the
lovelorn nice guy who's more cute than drop-dead good-looking and
who inevitably falls for some seemingly unattainable hunk.
</P>
<P>
   The title comes from Billy's proposed photo series in which gay
men re-create famous clinches from the movies. For instance,
Gabriel and former Andy Warhol stalwart Holly Woodlawn imitate Burt
Lancaster and Deborah Kerr on the beach in ``From Here to
Eternity.'' There're also several movie-themed fantasy sequences
featuring an overacting trio of lip-syncing drag queens.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is all very ``like me! like me!'' And pastel-themed.
And unthreatening. And instantly disposable. ``Billy's Hollywood
Screen Kiss''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Sean P. Hayes. Directed by Tommy O'Haver. Rated R for
language, sex and drug references. At Phipps. 1 hour, 32 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Harmless, mildly enjoyable and instantly
disposable.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 1703EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2608 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT &LR;      08-13 1337
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ The director Frank Darabont had an experience common
to many filmgoers this summer when he was watching Steven
Spielberg's wrenching World War II drama, ``Saving Private Ryan.''
He found himself mesmerized by the character of Jackson, the
Bible-quoting sniper with an angular face and an ambiguous
humanism.
</P>
<P>
   Darabont was so impressed that he quickly offered the actor who
plays Jackson, the little-known Barry Pepper, a part in ``The Green
Mile,'' a new film he wrote and is directing about a group of
guards on Death Row in 1935 and their unusual prisoner. Darabont,
whose last film, ``The Shawshank Redemption,'' won several Oscar
nominations, had Pepper read for the role of the guard Percy, who
is a misfit and a loner. But he found that the role did not fit the
actor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had an innate sweetness and a real soulful light in his
eyes,'' Darabont said of Pepper, who is 28. ``It wasn't working.
But he was a perfect Dean, who's maybe the most sensitive of the
guards. Barry can play anything, but it's much harder to be an
interesting good guy than an interesting bad guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Actors can quickly become hot after a compelling performance,
but usually not this quickly. Pepper has been acting just a few
years, and he has suddenly won a prominent part alongside, for the
second time, Tom Hanks, who plays the head guard in ``The Green
Mile,'' which is based on a novel by Stephen King. The film is
being shot on the Warner Brothers lot here and is expected to be
released next summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to meet Frank originally on Percy because I knew
if he offered it to me I'd have to take it, and I feared being
typecast as a sort of evil character,'' Pepper said. ``It was a
difficult choice, but I decided to leave my ego at the door and do
what I always do, which is bring a little of my dad to my
character. I was so totally flattered that they saw some
sensitivity and asked me to do Dean.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepper credits his unusual upbringing and his father's
adventurousness for giving him the inner strength that comes
through in Jackson and got him the part as Dean. He grew up in
Canada, eating largely wild game, like moose, venison and duck.
When he was 5, his father built a 50-foot sailboat and packed up
the family; they sailed for five years throughout the South
Pacific. Pepper was educated partly by his parents and partly at
schools where they stopped, in places like Rarotonga and New
Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   Pepper and his family eventually moved to the west coast of
Canada, where his parents built a farm. He found his calling in
college.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to play the victim,'' he said. ``I look for the
choices the character makes for himself. Even if you play a
villain, you do an injustice to him if he's just, like, programmed
to do those things. It's always more complex.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Death and Life &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Martin Brest saw ``Death Takes a Holiday,'' the 1934 film, some
20 years ago and felt he always wanted to make a movie about how an
encounter with death, fully personified, might tell you something
about life. It took a little longer than he expected, and he has
kept busy directing movies, including ``Scent of a Woman,''
``Midnight Run'' and ``Beverly Hills Cop,'' but now Brest has
finally shaped his figure of that profound force, and it looks a
lot like Brad Pitt.
</P>
<P>
   Brest's loose interpretation of ``Death Takes a Holiday,''
called ``Meet Joe Black,'' is really a sort of cinematic essay that
might be called ``The Education of Death.'' The living and the dead
learn a few things about love and life in this film, which takes an
unusual approach to the subject at a time when most movies are
absorbed by gritty realism, not metaphors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meet Joe Black,'' which is being released by Universal on Nov.
13, pits the powerful head of a media empire, William Parrish,
played by Anthony Hopkins, against the mysterious Joe Black, played
by Pitt. The issue for Parrish is coming to terms with the end of
his life, while the issue for Joe is coming to terms with Parrish's
daughter, Susan, played by Claire Forlani.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty years ago, I saw the original movie and thought about
doing something,'' Brest said. ``Fifteen years ago, I wanted to
remake it. Ten years ago, I began in earnest to work on a script.
But I ultimately decided I didn't want to do a remake, just to deal
with the same core subject matter.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``I didn't want to do this fish-out-of-water story
about death because that can tend toward the sophomoric. The
problem was when you think about making death real, you're faced
with a lot of heavy-handed choices. It took us a long time to get
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Brest said his movie also went against the grain of many films
these days by using no special effects, in spite of the
supernatural subject matter. The story, he said, relied solely on
Pitt's wide-eyed exploration of his character and Hopkins' slow
coming to terms with what he is up against. ``It's very
minimalistic,'' Brest said. ``It's all about the interaction of the
characters. Anthony created a sort of universal father figure. We
wanted to go for a certain elegance.''
</P>
<P>
   Brest said the real trick was to focus on the notion that death
cannot be described as what comes after life, as a portal to an
afterlife, but as the sum of a life, with the rest unknown. That
straightforwardness was ultimately how Joe Black was defined. ``I
don't believe in an angel of death,'' Brest said. ``Brad solved the
problem and played him as a sort of blank slate. That seemed like
death.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Junkie's Journey &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If you want to get a good idea of the sort of humor that makes
``Permanent Midnight'' a dark comedy, as the producers describe it,
the opening credits are a great place to begin. In a cheerful
script, the title is slowly written out on a white background, as
though it were blood being squirted from a junkie's syringe.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the Hollywood of the television writer Jerry Stahl,
the protagonist, played by Ben Stiller, of this unsentimental
rendezvous with self-destruction, and welcome to a world of
filmmaking that tries to elevate the viewer's consciousness by
following a junkie on his descent into the darkest recesses of
heroin addiction, and back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Permanent Midnight,'' which will be released by Artisan
Entertainment on Sept. 18, is based on the autobiography of Stahl.
It is not an easy film to watch, even with the presence of
Elizabeth Hurley and Maria Bello. But then David Veloz, the writer
and director, did not intend it to be just a thrill ride.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he could have conveyed some of the bleakness of Jerry's
addiction to heroin without being so graphic _ in one desperate
scene, Jerry is shown shoving a needle directly into his neck,
while his baby cries in the car beside him _ Veloz insisted that
averting the camera's gaze might have romanticized this terrible
habit and made the story a mere hallucination rather than a living
nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``The earlier versions were much more brutal and in your face,''
said Veloz, 36, one of the writers of ``Natural Born Killers.''
``We don't show him doing some of the other, much worse stuff that
he did.''
</P>
<P>
   In that respect, the movie has something in common with two
other grimly realistic movies out this summer, ``Saving Private
Ryan'' and Neil LaBute's independent film ``Your Friends and
Neighbors,'' also starring Stiller. These films all offer moral
credos whose power comes not from images of how such principles can
shape a better life, but of how horrific life can be when the world
slips its moral bearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The broader the audience you try to reach,'' Veloz said, ``the
more diluted and homogenized the message.'' Still, he added, the
movie, which presents a jaundiced view of Hollywood, does offer a
sort of redemption, since Jerry kicks his habit. He becomes a
cliche on talk shows, but, Veloz said, ``he comes out a whole
man.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
