<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2628 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT &LR;      08-13 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BABE RUTH': BASEBALL'S ENDURING ENIGMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: production notes at end of review)  
(Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
 (bl)  
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sixty-three years after his major-league career ended, 50 years
after his death, Babe Ruth remains a contemporary baseball
presence. He is invoked daily this summer. His Yankees are once
again trampling everything in their path. Fans and politicians
jabber about the future of the ball park that was built on his
exploits. And as several sluggers bang out home runs at a
prodigious pace, they endure constant comparisons with Ruth, who,
whatever the record book says, remains the heart's champion.
</P>
<P>
   So it's a fitting moment to revisit the man still widely revered
as the best ballplayer of them all. HBO does just that on Sunday
night, with an hourlong documentary, ``Babe Ruth.''
</P>
<P>
   The familiar story lopes along _ from the Baltimore bad boy to
the Sultan of Swat to the fallen hero lying in state at Yankee
Stadium _ told through the expected blend of archival film and
talking heads. If you care about Ruth, you've been here.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the story is just too familiar. Here's the Babe with the
Red Sox, a successful pitcher beginning in 1914 who is moved to the
outfield because he is an even better hitter. He is sold to the
Yankees in 1919. (Why did Boston give up this miracle player? We're
not told.) He makes history. He makes friends, although he can't be
bothered learning anybody's name and calls nearly everyone ``kid,''
which he pronounces ``keed.'' He makes money, although he spends it
as fast: on food, drink, women and other things he enjoys.
</P>
<P>
   He loves to wade into an adoring crowd, especially when a camera
is handy. Here are scenes of Babe with children, with a dog, with a
cow. But hardly anyone, it seems, thought to film him playing
baseball. There are a couple of often-seen shots of his swing and
his home run trot, with the doff of the cap as he rounds third.
</P>
<P>
   In 1923, Yankee Stadium opens to accommodate the throngs he
attracts. He hits home runs in numbers never dreamed of, reaching
60 in 1927. In the third game of the 1932 World Series he seems to
point to the stands then hits a homer. Was his gesture a fearless
promise, quickly kept? No one knows.
</P>
<P>
   His skills eventually decline with age. In 1935, the Yankees
have no more use for him. He's heartbroken, and plays one last
season with the Boston Braves. By then, the only thing he knows how
to do is be Babe Ruth, so he works as a glad-hander. In his last
years, less interesting but more copiously filmed, he is honored
finally by the Yankees. Prematurely old in his 50s, a man who
started playing big-league ball before the jerseys bore numbers, he
watches as his No. 3 is ceremonially retired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Babe Ruth is the only guy that lived up to his reputation,''
says Tommy Henrich, a Yankee of a later era. But who can provide
deeper insight? Not the other aging men who sit before the camera
here. Even redoubtable wordsmiths like Heywood Hale Broun, Studs
Terkel and Pete Hamill are reduced to platitudes. ``To me, the Babe
is still alive,'' says the veteran sports broadcaster Bill Mazur.
Yes, but why?
</P>
<P>
   What was it about this vulgar childlike barrel of a man that
connected physically with a baseball and emotionally with the guy
in the top row of the bleachers? Maybe the question will never be
answered. Maybe that's why people still care.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BABE RUTH'
</P>
<P>
   HBO, Sunday night at 9 p.m. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ross Greenburg, executive producer; Rick Bernstein, senior
producer; produced by George Roy and Steve Stern, Black Canyon
Productions; music by Brian Keane; Liev Schreiber, narrator.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 1712EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2636 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOMBING-EMBASSIES-081     08-13 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMBING-EMBASSIES-0814-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FROM BEIRUT TO MOSCOW TO MEXICO, U.S. EMBASSIES REVIEWING
SECURITY
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In Beirut, where bombers struck twice in the 1980s,
all U.S. embassy staff live on an isolated 14-acre compound
surrounded by walls and roadblocks.
</P>
<P>
   But, in Jerusalem, the U.S. consulate compound sits close to a
crowded downtown road where Israeli security guards try to keep
traffic moving and inspect the bottoms of parked cars with mirrors
attached to long handles.
</P>
<P>
   Staff at both sites, one representing the new fortress-like U.S.
missions and the other displaying the problematic urban
circumstances of the older ones, are reviewing their so-called
``security posture'' after the bombings at embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath, the mood at many American embassies around the
world appears to be one of forced calm, as most try to take a
``business-as-normal'' approach to their jobs while dealing with
``a heightened state of alert.''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Secretary of State Patrick Kennedy told reporters at a
briefing this week that security was being beefed up at embassies
worldwide, while several are temporarily shutdown following serious
threats that had been received from Kuala Lumpur to Cairo to
Mbanane.
</P>
<P>
   Surveillance cameras, security staffing and physical barriers
are among a host of things being studied. ``We're talking about
procedures; we're talking about people; we're talking about
physical changes, technical upgrades. There's a full panoply,''
Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   About $400 million is allotted for embassy security and
maintenance each year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, following the bombing of the U.S. Marine compound in
Lebanon a task force set up to study security at U.S. embassies
abroad recommended $3.5 billion in improvements -- of which
Congress has appropriated less than $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Since the report, 27 new buildings have been constructed to meet
these standards, Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign service workers are used to being careful. In many
places, they must ride in bulky armor-plated Chevrolet Suburbans or
face restrictions about areas of their towns that are off limits.
The U.S. Department of State receives about 30,000 threats a year.
</P>
<P>
   But the foreign service is also a close worldwide community.
Those killed or injured in Kenya served other places with diplomats
in Tel Aviv and elsewhere. Also, embassies tend to resemble each
other in form -- the walls, the guard houses.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that the U.S. embassy in Amman, Jordan is a
new, fortress-like compound, isolated and surrounded by two walls,
embassy press officer Stephen Thibeault said, ``We see the TV
coverage . . . It's easy to imagine that could be us instead of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   In Egypt, a country with one of the largest U.S. missions and
also a possible source for the Africa bombers, embassy staff
working in dispersed sites have been consolidated in the main
compound.
</P>
<P>
   A taped message at the U.S. embassy in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia,
asks for ``increased vigilance on the part of all Americans'' and
tells them keep a low profile, vary the times and routes they
travel, and watch out for suspicious mail.
</P>
<P>
   In Swaziland, where the U.S. embassy in this land-locked African
monarchy received the second telephone bomb threat in three days
Thursday afternoon security concerns have been heightened since
bomb blasts.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department official called the 2:20 p.m. call a
``crank,'' however, and said it was considered a copycat of one
received Tuesday morning when the embassy was evacuated. After
Tuesday's telephoned bomb threat, the embassy was ordered to close
a little after 4 p.m. by the State Department for precautionary
reasons. It operated as usual Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The embassy occupies the top two floors of a bank building on a
busy downtown street.
</P>
<P>
   Mbabane police responded to the afternoon threat and for the
second time this week had bomb-sniffing dogs comb the building for
possible bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Khisimusi Ndolvu, regional commander of the Mbabane police
force, said that security at the embassy property has been
increased to 24-hour guard since last week's blasts. ``Security is
up to its highest levels,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, security outside the sprawling U.S. embassy compound
was noticeably tighter Thursday, with an increased presence of
Russian police.
</P>
<P>
   The embassy compound covers a city block and fronts the 12-lane
Garden Ring road, one of the busiest thoroughfares in Moscow. This
week, Russian police cars blocked the curbside lane closest to the
embassy and more security personnel appeared on the sidewalk in
front of the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its proximity to the busy road, which encircles the
center of the city, the embassy is ranked by the State Department
among the most vulnerable U.S. missions worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   A new embassy is under construction on a site adjacent to the
current embassy and will be built with modern security features --
including buildings set back from the street and reinforced walls,
doors and windows.
</P>
<P>
   After the bombings in Africa, the embassy issued a warning to
its employees, urging them to be aware of security concerns and
report anything suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all been reminded of the risks, and since we're all in
the foreign service we know them pretty well. But I'd say the
bombings (in Africa) have definitely had their affect on people and
made us all more alert,'' said an embassy employee who asked not to
be named.
</P>
<P>
   Embassy officials would not comment on additional security steps
that have been taken this week, however.
</P>
<P>
   Nor would they in Mexico City, where the U.S. has one of its
largest embassies. ``If we tell you, we tell the bad guys,'' one
source said.
</P>
<P>
   But sources there did say there is a feeling that the building,
which houses busy visa application offices and various diplomatic
missions, is generally safe -- although it is not set very far back
from Reforma Avenue, one of Mexico City's main thoroughfares.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, a spokesman for the U.S. Embassy in London said
business was ``normal'' in the aftermath of the attacks in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the London spokesman, speaking on the condition that his
name would not be used, refused to comment about whether any
additional security measures had been implemented since the
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course everybody has been apprehensive here, but we know
that these things happen,'' he said. ``We've been through this many
times. But we know we're being taken care of as well as can be.''
</P>
<P>
   (Cox Newspapers foreign correspondents Charles Holmes, Bert
Roughton Jr., Susan Ferris and Joyce Barrett; and Washington
correspondent Samar Abulhassan contributed to this report.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
