<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2638 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-VIDEO-2TAKES-NYT     08-13 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-VIDEO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO: GRIT, TOIL AND TROUBLE; NEW RELEASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Videos arrive from all points on the compass, which always makes
for interesting contrasts. This month, for example, a generally
humdrum assortment of mainline movies gets a nice spin from two
different kinds of films that themselves come from very different
places.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brother's Kiss,'' recently released by BMG, is an example of a
smaller movie project that went out and made as much of itself as
it possibly could, attracting some big-name talent like Marisa
Tomei, Rosie Perez and Cathy Moriarty on a relatively modest
budget.
</P>
<P>
   A collaboration between actor Nick Chinlund and director Seth
Zvi Rosenfeld, it tells the story of two brothers reared in New
York's East Harlem, the younger of whom, Mick (Michael Raynor),
survives after a fashion as a police officer and the older, Lex (
Chinlund), succumbs to drugs and other destructive tendencies
despite his brother's loyal attempts to save him.
</P>
<P>
   The movie unfolds ``as a series of finely observed scenes of
Lex's deterioration,'' Stephen Holden wrote in The New York Times
when ``Brother's Kiss'' opened last year. Chinlund, who is in his
mid-30s, spent part of his childhood in East Harlem as the son of
an Episcopal priest who ran drug rehabilitation programs. He
commissioned Rosenfeld, who also had spent time there, to write a
one-act play based on what they had seen of life in the area. Later
it was turned into a screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shot the film in my neighborhood,'' Chinlund said. ``My
mother's house was the home office.'' He and Rosenfeld also mined
their contacts. ``Seth knew John Leguizamo and we both knew
Marisa,'' Chinlund said. ``We met Rosie at the Sundance directors'
lab.''
</P>
<P>
   Leguizamo plays a drug dealer, and Ms. Tomei is a drug-torn
young woman who takes up with Lex. Ms. Perez portrays Lex's wife
and the mother of his child. ``But Cathy Moriarty was first,''
Chinlund said. Ms. Moriarty plays the brothers' alcoholic mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brother's Kiss'' had good reviews and a decent theater run.
``It's about a man who can't ask for help but has to do everything
for himself,'' Chinlund said. ``That's a common thing these days,
and it's not talked about.''
</P>
<P>
   Gritty personal films often work on video, but from another
quarter entirely this month comes the kind of film that has always
worked spectacularly. Thirteen years after its theatrical release,
Disney is issuing the 1985 animated feature ``The Black Cauldron''
for the first time on videocassette.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, what took so long? To grow new crops of young
viewers, the studio regularly shuttles its big animated films in
and out of video. But ``The Black Cauldron,'' which earned bad
reviews when it opened and was one of the least successful of the
studio's major animated titles, has been withheld.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's not so surprising. ``Oh, you're so, so, so
boring,'' a princess tells Taran, a would-be knight who strives to
keep the magic cauldron from the evil horned king. That might have
been one problem, and there were others, ranging from a darker mood
to a failed early attempt to integrate ``Star Wars''-type special
effects into animated films.
</P>
<P>
   Disney doesn't elaborate on the delay. ``We wanted to fit it
into the schedule at an appropriate time,'' a studio spokeswoman
said this week.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 1714EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2639 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-ECONOMY-0814-C     08-13 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ECONOMY-0814-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'BLACK THURSDAY' IN MOSCOW AS MARKETS CONTINUE TO NOSEDIVE
 &HT;    EDs: With optional add.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Panic again swept through Russia's rickety financial
markets Thursday forcing a temporary freeze in trading of stocks
and foreign currency.
</P>
<P>
   The continued sell-off by investors prompted the nation's
Central Bank to take urgent steps to protect the ruble in a day of
market turmoil that the state-owned ORT television called ``Black
Thursday.''
</P>
<P>
   With Russian stocks and bonds in a weeklong freefall, some
analysts questioned whether the government, struggling to prevent
bankruptcy, would be able to restore confidence in its fledgling
markets and avert a devaluation of the ruble.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's main stock index dropped more than 10 percent in the
first hour of trading. After a 45-minute halt, trading resumed and
the exchange ended the day down 6.5 percent to its lowest level
since April 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, White House spokesman Michael McCurry said, ``It
is critical that the Russian government act quickly to restore
confidence in their economy, and that is something we have
communicated with Russian officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The international community has a big stake in seeing that
Russia gets their economy moving in the right direction,'' he told
a briefing, adding that Treasury undersecretary David Lipton, had
flown to Moscow this week to meet with Prime Minister Sergei
Kiriyenko, and officials from the finance ministry and the central
bank.
</P>
<P>
   Expressing frustration in government attempts to stem the
bleeding, Kiriyenko told reporters Thursday: ``Unfortunately what's
happening on the markets belongs in the realm of psychology. There
are at present no financial grounds for a deterioration in the
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Kiriyenko conferred by telephone with President Boris Yeltsin,
who is on a fishing vacation in Russia's north. He also met with
opposition leader Gennady Zyuganov, leader of the Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   Zyuganov agreed to proceed with an emergency parliamentary
session next week to consider austerity measures sought by the
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``An absolutely urgent situation has arisen,'' Zyuganov said.
``If there is devaluation of the ruble and a collapse of banks, the
impoverishment of the people will follow.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the market slide means little to most Russians.
Financial trading is almost exclusively a bazaar for the very rich
and for risk-taking foreign investors. It has not been felt among
consumers, as prices remain stable and the ruble has edged up only
slightly, trading at nearly 6.3 to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   But the erosion of investor confidence has complicated the
cash-strapped government's predicament as it seeks simultaneously
to pay state workers, bolster the currency and make its scheduled
repayments on foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
   A $22.6 billion loan package arranged by the International
Monetary Fund this summer was designed to give the government
several months to seek economic reforms, improve tax collections
and avert a crisis.
</P>
<P>
   But it has failed to calm the tumultuous markets, whose decline
has made a bad situation worse for Yeltsin's government.
</P>
<P>
   The Central Bank has been forced to fortify the ruble by dipping
into its hard currency reserves, which it said fell by $1.4 billion
last week to $17. billion. It also placed new rules on commercial
banks which restricts currency trading, designed to protect the
ruble.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Russia has about $20 billion in debt payments due to
foreign banks due this year.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation has been worsening because of the prospect of
what some officials call 'default,' or official admission of
bankruptcy by the government,'' said Andrei Illarionov of the
Economic Analysis Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts contend that under the current pressure the
government must revalue its currency to attract more dollars and
other strong currencies to its weakening markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The meltdown in Russian financial markets has reached the
terminal phase,'' George Soros, a closely watched international
financier who has heavily invested in Russia, wrote Thursday to
Britain's Financial Times newspaper. He urged a ruble devaluation
accompanied by Western aid for Russia to stabilize the currency.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts differ over just what affect a devaluation would
have. While it could brighten the government's financial outlook,
it also send shock waves through the economy, producing
hyper-inflation and social unrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``A devaluation of the ruble 'would have severely negative
consequences' for the economy,'' the international credit-rating
service Moody's said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Moody's and Standard &AMP; Poors downgraded their investment
rankings for Russia, reflecting the eroded confidence in the
financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
