<HEADER>
A2643 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-VIDEO-2NDTAKE-NY     08-13 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-VIDEO-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: this week.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW VIDEO RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   Kundun
</P>
<P>
   Martin Scorsese's account of the early life of the 14th Dali
Lama is essentially two films. The first unfolds as a dazzling
union of Tibetan settings and religious imagery joined by the
synergy between Roger Deakins' glorious cinematography and Philip
Glass' ethereal electronic score. The second film is a somewhat
less satisfying chronicle of the Dali Lama's youth until 1959, when
he was forced to flee Tibet ahead of Chinese invaders. Characters
remain at an emotional arm's length, especially the young leader,
named Tenzin Gyatso when he is discovered at age 2{. A bright and
mischievous child, played at various ages by four Tibetan actors
(including Tulka Jamyang Kinga Tenzin, above), he never fully
emerges from behind tutors and protectors. ``To call `Kundun' the
most religiously stunning storybook ever filmed,'' Stephen Holden
wrote in The New York Times, ``is not to say it's a great movie.''
</P>
<P>
   1997. Touchstone. $104.16. 134 minutes. PG-13. Closed captioned.
PG-13. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Borrowers
</P>
<P>
   Around the Lenders' household, the disappearance of small items
like gloves and Monopoly cards signals another foray by the
Borrowers, a family of tiny people who live under the floorboards
and emerge to explore and help themselves to the materials they
need for, say, scaling the side of a refrigerator. But Borrowers
and Lenders have a mutual problem in the person of Ocious P.
Potter, a comically odious lawyer (played to the hilt by John
Goodman) who wants both families evicted but gets a comeuppance
straight from ``Gulliver's Travels'' in a film that ``enjoys the
sheer ingenuity of its little heroes'' (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   1997. Polygram . $22.95. 83 minutes. Closed captioned. PG.
Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Newton Boys
</P>
<P>
   Moving on from the likes of ``Slacker'' and ``Dazed and
Confused,'' Richard Linklater has come up with a big-budget film
about three brothers (Matthew McConaughey, Skeet Ulrich and Ethan
Hawke) who, while not being particularly daring, dangerous or
demented about it, just sort of fell into robbing banks because it
was fun to do and seemed like a smart business move. That leads to
a gentler genre piece than one might have expected from Linklater,
who ``seems simply to want to tell a story that looks like a junior
`Sting.''' (Maslin). 1998. Fox. $104.16. 122 minutes. Closed
captioned. PG-13. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Niagra, Niagra
</P>
<P>
   The lovers-on-a-rampage theme gets a new twist in Bob Gosse's
fascinating, often repellent film. A victim of Tourette's syndrome,
the teen-aged Marcy (Robin Tunney) acts explosively and
unpredictably, swilling bourbon and gulping any pills she can get
her hands on. Her meek companion, Seth (Henry Thomas), can only
blame extreme parental abuse for his own problems in a story that
belongs to Ms. Tunney, whose performance ``is a tour de force so
uncompromising that your sympathy for the character periodically
gives way to a sickening sense of disgust'' (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1997. Artisan. 93 minutes. Closed captioned. R. Release date:
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time or appeared on television.
</P>
<P>
   POCAHONTAS II: JOURNEY TO A NEW WORLD. Produced more quickly and
cheaply for video than they would be for the big screen, sequels to
even the biggest animated hits often bypass theaters. In a
follow-up to her $347 million original adventure (in worldwide
box-office receipts), Pocahontas sets sail for England, where she
turns heads and prompts a romantic standoff between John Smith and
an English diplomat. 1998. Disney. $26.99. 72 minutes. Closed
captioned. No rating.
</P>
<P>
   NENETTE AND BONI. Claire Denis' film about the intense growing
pains of an embattled teen-age brother and sister living in
Marseilles evokes adolescence, Stephen Holden wrote in The New York
Times, ``with an uncanny feel for the jagged emotional rhythms of
youth.'' 1997. New Yorker. $89.95. 105 minutes. French with English
subtitles. No rating.
</P>
<P>
   STAR POWER: THE CREATION OF UNITED ARTISTS. The lunatics were
taking over the asylum in the opinion of at least one investor, but
in 1919 Mary Pickford, Charlie Chaplin, Douglas Fairbanks and D.W.
Griffith got together to form United Artists. Hugh Munro Neely's
documentary, narrated by Roddy McDowell, moves from the days when
``flickers'' sold by the foot to the era of the stars. 1998.
Unapix. $19.98. 55 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   JOE COCKER LIVE: ACROSS FROM MIDNIGHT TOUR. ``Feelin' All
Right,'' ``Up Where We Belong'' and ``With a Little Help From My
Friends'' are a few of the songs filmed in Berlin. 1998. Fox
Lorber. $24.98. 90 minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
