<TEXT>
<P>
   GEORGIA -- PAROLE. Nearly 3,100 of every 100,000 Georgians were
on probation or parole at the end of last year, the fourth highest
rate of community supervision in the nation. (EMBARGOED until 4:30
p.m. Sunday) (Possible) Williams
</P>
<P>
   MASSACHUSETTS -- VINEYARD. President Clinton will visit Martha's
Vineyard next week and local leaders want him to know there is more
to the island than a destination place for the rich and famous.
(Working-Maybe early next week). Preston
</P>
<P>
   MICHIGAN -- TEAMSTERS. Tom Leedham is the first to admit that
the biggest obstacle between him and the presidency of the 1.4
million-member Teamsters union, the largest trade-union in the
country, is his name. Wolfberg (working) MULTICHANNEL -- In a
crackdown of allegedly fraudulent entertainment business ventures,
federal officials last week charged that two cable networks bilked
investors and illegally diverted funds. Maggi
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS -- CENSUS. Hispanic businesses have grown rapidly in the
Valley area over the past five years, according to local business
leaders, and they expect the results to be evident in the results
garnered from a questionnaire the Census Bureau will send out
Monday. Marlin/Feldman
</P>
<P>
   VIRGIN ISLANDS -- HANGINGS. The State Department is staying out
of a human rights dispute involving a recent hanging in the eastern
Caribbean. (Working) Williams
</P>
<P>
   WISCONSIN -- OBEY AND JOHNSON. One is a powerful ranking member
of the House Appropriations Committee, the other is a freshman
hanging on for his political life. But Democratic Reps. David Obey
and Jay Johnson are two congressmen who need each other this
November. Marlin
</P>
