<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FRIDAY BUSINESS BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release Friday, August 14, 1998, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   All stories have moved, except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS-AIRLINES _ Airline stocks have fallen with the market for
the last month, with some analysts wondering about how the stocks
will fare if the economy slows sharply. Analyst James Parker of
Rodinson-Humphrey thinks that in a slowdown, regional airlines will
fare better. (Schnieder, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). ETA: 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   SPACE _ DAYTON, Ohio _ This week's flight test of a miniature
future space shuttle underscored the shifting emphasis in research
at Wright-Patterson Air Force Base from aircraft to space vehicles.
The nearly full-size model was tested in New Mexico, but
Wright-Pat's recently reorganized Air Vehicles Directorate is a
partner in the effort. Structures, materials and electronics work
that used to focus on airplanes is supporting the research, which
could pave the way for an unmanned military space plane able to
maneuver in and out of the atmosphere, change orbits, and fly
itself back to its home base. (Gaffney, Dayton Daily News). 8-10.
WITH ILLUSTRATION. ETA: 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   HONDA _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Honda Motor Co. Thursday will unveil its
new Acura TL luxury sedan which will be built at the company's
assembly plant in Marysville. The TL model, introduced earlier this
year at the North American International Auto Show, will go on sale
in the fall. The Marysville plant, which employs 5,800 workers,
currently builds the popular Honda Accord and has been operating at
capacity. We talk with Honda officials about the impact of Acura
production for the plant, area suppliers and who they are targeting
with the new Sedan. (Wagner, Dayton Daily News). 12. ETA: 9 p.m.
</P>
