<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2655 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURRAY-COLUMN15-COX     08-13 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Paris is a kick on the road
eastward
 &HT;    (Eds: First in a series of reports from Europe.)
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Just in time for my arrival, 1 million cheering
Frenchmen, women too, had turned the Champs Elysees into a sea of
Gaullic humanity, garlic too.
</P>
<P>
   For me?
</P>
<P>
   Well, not entirely.
</P>
<P>
   It seems the French had finally won something _ the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the cheer: ``Today the World Cup _ Tomorrow the World
Saucer!''
</P>
<P>
   Loses something in translation, I suppose.
</P>
<P>
   There hadn't been such a turnout in Paris since the last time
the Germans paraded.
</P>
<P>
   (My favorite French-American joke: New Orleans has such a French
influence that recently when the mayor learned that a delegation of
some dozen German government officials were arriving, he
immediately drove to the airport and surrendered the city.)
</P>
<P>
   The World Cup, lest we forget, is soccer _ what the French call,
zee keek ball.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know why more Americans don't follow the game of soccer.
It's not that complicated:
</P>
<P>
   You kick the ball, you chase the ball, a riot breaks out and
1,200 fans are hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   That's oversimplification, but you get the general idea.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt it's the low-scoring aspect of soccer that turns
Americans off, what with the game's 24-minute shot clock.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, on this particular day, it seemed that all the world
were soccer fans.
</P>
<P>
   I've been on Times Square at New Year's Eve. I'd been in the
Baghdad airport when the last plane out of Iraq was boarding.
</P>
<P>
   Never seen such a crowd before.
</P>
<P>
   Young people were hanging from street lamps and traffic lights.
Heaven knows where the old folks were. Most likely trampled into
the Champs Elysees.
</P>
<P>
   It was like being caught up in a violent ocean. Suddenly you'd
find yourself being swept one way and then another.
</P>
<P>
   I'm a big guy in every direction, up and down and from side to
side. It was all I could do to stay on my feet, much less stay in
any one spot.
</P>
<P>
   Most everybody had their faces painted in an Indian style of war
paint that featured the French tri-colors, same as their flag: red,
white and blue stripes.
</P>
<P>
   Very symbolic for the French: Red is for red wine, white is for
white wine, blue is for Blue Nun.
</P>
<P>
   I was a short ways down the street from Arc de Triomphe, that
above-ground underpass Paris is so proud of. Thank goodness my
hotel was only half a block off the Champs Elysees.
</P>
<P>
   Nice location, nice hotel. Maybe you've heard of it, the Leonard
Earl.
</P>
<P>
   Well, actually, you wouldn't have, not by that name. The sign
outside says LE WARWICK.
</P>
<P>
   But some American friends and I never could figure out what the
LE stands for. We figured Leonard Earl is as good a guess as any.
</P>
<P>
   For a fact, I usually stay in small hotels on the Left Bank. But
this trip I was on my way to Moscow, with a brief stopover in
Paris. I was treating myself. I already knew how I'd be treated in
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The itinerary called for a couple of days in Moscow with
friends, then on to St. Petersburg, where the bones of the last
czar were being interred, and from there I'd be heading on to
Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania before finally ending up in Warsaw.
</P>
<P>
   Eat, drink and be a soccer fan. For tomorrow I'll be in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
</P>
<P>
   AWEW18A(at)prodigy.com; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
