<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2709 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT &LR;      08-13 0412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Aug. 14, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some relief from the recent heat will arrive in the Pacific
Northwest on Friday as a cold front approaches the coast. Highs
across western Washington will be nearly 10 degrees cooler than
Thursday. However, hot air will remain over the interior Northwest
and California, where ample sunshine will again boost readings to
near record levels. While a lonely shower may form over some of the
higher mountain peaks, it will remain dry in the valleys.
</P>
<P>
   Muggy air will cover much of eastern Texas and the Deep South.
Clusters of showers and thunderstorms with downpours will erupt
near and south of a stalled front that extends from the western
Gulf coast to the Carolina coast. Isolated storms will also
percolate Friday afternoon in the sultry air embracing Florida.
</P>
<P>
   A stream of humid air flowing north through the Appalachians
will cause an increase in clouds along with scattered showers and
thunderstorms. Moist Atlantic air will cause clouds to expand from
the Middle Atlantic states to southern New England as strong high
pressure erodes to the east. Temperatures will average a bit below
seasonal levels.
</P>
<P>
   An eastward moving cold front will trigger a broken band of
strong thunderstorms from the western Great Lakes to the eastern
Plains on Friday. Noticeably cooler air will arrive in the wake of
the front. Elsewhere, the monsoon circulation will continue to
support scattered mountain thunderstorms in the central and
southern Rockies. Farther east, sinking air currents will promote
ample sunshine in the southern Plains. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Summer Spate
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, 3.62 inches of rain deluged Burlington, Vt., breaking
the city's all-time 24-hour rainfall record for August. So far this
summer, 22.64 inches of rain have fallen, which is just shy of the
all-time summer mark set in 1892. With a persistent jet stream over
Canada, northern New England has been in the beaten path of
traveling disturbances. These jet stream disturbances have sparked
numerous thunderstorms which have affected Burlington. The summer
spate of rain has boosted the city's 1998 rainfall to 38.84 inches,
the greatest recorded total for the January through August period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 1732EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2718 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SARATOGA-HORSES-AR     08-13 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SARATOGA-HORSES-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDER THE SPELL OF THE HORSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 Mindy Aloff is the dance critic for The New Republic.  
 By MINDY ALOFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One finds worlds within worlds in Saratoga Springs, N.Y., a
fabled watering hole for high hats and hot tipsters over the better
part of the last two centuries.
</P>
<P>
   There are the ancient mineral springs, the Revolutionary War
sites, the New York City Ballet and the National Museum of Dance,
the hushed forests and cricket-echoing parks, and the signposts of
a civic history involving blinkered cads, visionary patrons and
some of America's most prominent family dynasties.
</P>
<P>
   There is so much to learn and do that, for much of the year, it
might be observed that Saratoga's quadripeds of distinction are its
tourists, creeping toward their beds at the end of another
exhausting day of sightseeing, rest and relaxation.
</P>
<P>
   From the last week of July through the first week of September,
however, the Saratoga story narrows down to a phrase: horse racing.
For major stakes races, 50,000 people a day attend the Saratoga
Race Course. Some are infants in arms, and even the youngsters are
occasionally tapped to handicap winners.
</P>
<P>
   After a recent brief Saratoga sojourn, I traveled back to New
York on the train in the company of a couple of racing enthusiasts,
one of whom told of overhearing a young mother at the track,
wondering in the presence of her toddler which mounts she should
bet on.
</P>
<P>
   ``One! Seven!'' the child cried out spontaneously. What was he
thinking? No one knew, but his mother, who had no other source of
advice, put down a few dollars on No. 1 to win and No. 7 to place.
Both horses were long shots individually, and the odds of the
exacta were astronomical. Nevertheless, she won $950: No. 1 won and
No. 7 placed.
</P>
<P>
   Saratoga offers three ways to study horses in tense competition.
You can watch them ``run as fast as they can run'' _ as one racing
fan put it _ in the stately grandeur of the racecourse, whose
origins go back to the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   You can watch them trot as fast as they can in the harness races
at the Saratoga Equine Sports Center, built in 1941. And you can
watch them do nearly everything a horse might be asked to do during
a cavalry charge _ trot, canter, gallop, make hairpin turns, rear
out of the way of disaster _ in the context of professional polo,
played in lush fields.
</P>
<P>
   I had never witnessed any of these spectacles live before; at
Saratoga, I experienced them all.
</P>
<P>
   Polo turned out to be the biggest surprise _ from my frame of
reference, virtuosic Lindyhopping raised to a martial power. At
dusk one evening, I bought a ticket to an exhibition game of
world-class players at Lodge Field, near the harness raceway, and
took a seat on bleachers next to a grassy hill.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered nearby were perhaps 75 spectators, mostly couples and
families. (More were seated across the field, under a festive
tent.) Some people had set up lounge chairs and spread out full
picnics over the grass, complete with wine goblets, as if they were
in their backyards watching a croquet game.
</P>
<P>
   Although the mallets and the hard ball of polo suggest elements
of croquet, as well as of golf, the sport itself is fast and
furious; when the ball flies in action it can be lethally hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Horse racing was polo's midwife and landlord, as it still is
to some extent at Saratoga,'' the historian Edward Hotaling wrote
in his comprehensive and deliciously readable 1995 saga, ``They're
Off! Horse Racing at Saratoga'' (Syracuse University Press).
</P>
<P>
   ``It has always been an expensive, therefore elite, sport but is
no less dangerous for that, involving rare skills _ fast stops,
quick turns, powerful hitting _ and rough, often dirty tactics,''
Hotaling continued. ``Mere playboys couldn't play, nor could many
horses.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, this game between teams called the Cotswolds and the
Wildcats cost $5, not much more than the cover charge for a day at
the racecourse. Given the battlefield conditions of polo, however _
with 1,200-pound animals corkscrewing on a dime to avoid slamming
into one another, while mallets rain down about their heads and
riders belt out curdling screams _ it's amazing that any creature,
equine or human, could be persuaded to tolerate the situation for a
minute, much less the seven and a half minutes of a period, or
chukker. (There are six chukkers in a polo game, and players ride
different ``ponies'' _ actually, thoroughbred horses _ for each
period.)
</P>
<P>
   At one point, I got very close to polo indeed, as the ball
crashed over the low field barrier and smashed into a picnic basket
with a resounding crack. I found this somewhat alarming, yet the
basket's owner simply shrugged and threw the ball back into play.
Polo people are tough.
</P>
<P>
   They're also public spirited. When the game concluded, the
announcer requested the audience's help to replace the hundreds of
divots that the mallets had torn from the turf, and the audience
got right up and complied. It was kind of fun matching divot to
dirt patch, like working a jigsaw puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was this a crowd entirely made up of polo connoisseurs. I
asked the ticket taker what the rules of the game were, and she
answered: ``I have no idea. I just love to watch the horses.''
Whatever the rules, the score was Cotswolds 16, Wildcats 6.
</P>
<P>
   From Lodge Field, I walked across a parking lot to the Chariots
restaurant to watch the harness races at the Equine Sports Center.
Chariots, which overlooks the raceway's grandstand, serves its
patrons dinner as they follow the races through a picture window
or, in close-up, on television right at the table.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Although other diners seemed to enjoy this arrangement quite a
lot, I found that I wasn't happy until I moved outside near the
track fence, where I could focus on the exquisite high-stepping
gait of the trotters absent an intervening barrier.
</P>
<P>
   Harness racing, with the drivers isolated in their sulkies from
the horses on a track that curves upward slightly at the sides, is
nowhere near as dramatic as the galloping unions of jockeys and
mounts on a flat course.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the trotting racer, placing its hooves with pinpoint
precision in strict 4/4 time under the pressure of the clock, has
the dainty look of someone practicing the English quickstep, and
for a dance fan their races can be mesmerizing.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was at the raceway that I spotted the only live
ballet dancers I saw in Saratoga: two adolescent girls standing by
the fence, practicing fifth-position sous-sous in clunky sports
shoes _ their waist-length ponytails bobbing above their
filly-slender legs _ while they cheered out moral support to their
favored steeds.
</P>
<P>
   Ballet dancers and schooled horses have a long technical as well
as a poetic connection, going back to the academic step-vocabulary
and ornate floor patterns shared by court dancers and mounted
knights in the horse carrousels of Renaissance Europe.
</P>
<P>
   At the National Museum of Racing and Hall of Fame, an
illuminating video about equine anatomy extends the metaphor by
pointing out that a horse actually runs on the tips of its toes,
``like a ballerina,'' as the bones of its feet proper are located
above the hooves, which are the equivalent of toenails.
</P>
<P>
   I forgot to bet at the harness raceway, but on one of my three
visits to the Saratoga Race Course I walked up to a window and put
down $2 on each of two horses in sequential races.
</P>
<P>
   One of my picks, Star of Broadway, sort of buffed her hooves in
the stretch; in that race she was more Lamplight of Broadway. The
other horse, the Groom Is Red, also lost handily; in that race,
however, I almost achieved something. The bet was for a friend; in
making it, I deliberated between the two names I thought she might
like, the other being Cat Thief.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I decided that since my friend was allergic to cats,
she wouldn't bet on a feline name. Cat Thief came in a brisk first.
</P>
<P>
   I'm an expert at almost winning. On a previous day, I had
intended to put down $2 on Financial Lady in the third, a horse
recommended by John Prizzi, a commentator and writer on racing, to
a crowd of about 100 during one of the free daily public
handicapping sessions offered at a nearby restaurant, Siro's.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until Financial Lady won the race, though, that I
remembered I had wanted to bet on her, thereby teaching me an
important track rule: you can't win if you don't play.
</P>
<P>
   To tell the truth, I was so overwhelmed by the formal beauty and
intricate culture of the racecourse that it's a wonder I remembered
to bet at all. I wanted to learn everything about everything. I
took one of the hourly public tours of the far-stretch barn area
and another, guided walking tour of the course grounds.
</P>
<P>
   One morning, I arrived at 7:30 to eat a hearty buffet breakfast
in a restaurant near the grandstand, where I could also watch the
horses being exercised and listen to an analyst-historian's
commentary of racing's past and present.
</P>
<P>
   I even attended the races. There are nine daily races (except
Tuesdays) at the course, starting at 1 p.m. Each race takes about
two minutes, and the attendant procedures and ceremonies _ the
exhibition of the horses in the paddock, the reviewing parade
before the crowd, the weighing-in of the jockeys, the approach of
the contenders to the starting gate _ take about three-quarters of
an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The moment I began to wait for was the instant when the pack
rounds the turn into the stretch, where the whole scale of the
picture up-ends and the race is theatrically transformed from an
ensemble of distant miniatures into a collection of individual
dynamos.
</P>
<P>
   The major dramas, of course, frequently take place at the finish
line, but not the major magic. If it's magic you seek in racing,
you win every time.
</P>
<P>
   It's the magic of racing, even more than the winning, that may
help to account for the presence of enthusiasts who have made their
way to the racecourse each August for six or seven decades.
</P>
<P>
   I met two such people: Alfred Gwynne Vanderbilt II and his
friend Jane duPont Lunger. Over a lifetime of experience as
onlookers and participants in various aspects of racing, they have
formed ideas about what makes a winning race horse tick and what
helps a fan endure over the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need a good trainer, a horse with good bloodlines and a
lot of luck,'' Mrs. Lunger said, speaking as the owner of the
Christiana Stables in Maryland, whose distinguished mares and
fillies over 61 years have included the greathearted Go for Wand.
``And you've got to be optimistic. That's what keeps me going. Even
when you have a bad day, you've got to go on.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanderbilt, the former chairman of the New York Racing
Association, attended his first horse race around the age of 12,
when he was taken to the track by his grandfather, and apart from a
few years when he was in the service during World War II, he has
followed racing avidly ever since, becoming an authority on the
sport.
</P>
<P>
   Among the many leading race horses he has owned was the
legendary Native Dancer _ inspiration for, among other things, a
Balanchine ballet.
</P>
<P>
   In making predictions, Vanderbilt wants to know this information
about a horse, in order: the names of the trainer, the jockey, the
owner, the sire and the dam. Cues to a horse's bloodlines may be
embedded in the name itself, he explained.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the ``n'' and the ``l'' of the horse named Handel
are clues to the parentage: Hansel and Secretarial Queen (by
Secretariat).
</P>
<P>
   I asked Vanderbilt what, about racing, had provoked his
immediate devotion as a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the races as a whole,'' he said, ``not the betting, not
the horses separately, but the whole thing: the people, the crowds,
the jockeys, the colors. I loved it. I just thought, wow! And I
still do.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A Sampling of What Gives Saratoga Its Special Flavor &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here is information about visiting Saratoga Springs, N.Y.:
</P>
<P>
   The Horses
</P>
<P>
   SARATOGA RACE COURSE, Union Avenue, (518) 584-6200. Thoroughbred
racing daily except Tuesdays, starting at 1 p.m., through Labor
Day. Tickets go on sale at 8 a.m.; gates open at 10:30 a.m.
Saturdays and Sundays, at 11 a.m. weekdays. Admission: $2.
</P>
<P>
   SARATOGA EQUINE SPORTS CENTER, Crescent Avenue, (518) 584-2110.
Harness racing Tuesdays through Saturdays in August. Nine races
nightly, post time 7:40 p.m. Open 9 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. and 6 p.m.
until races end. Admission: $2; $3 for the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   SARATOGA POLO ASSOCIATION, (518) 584-8108. Games are played at
Lodge Field, at the Saratoga Equine Sports Center on Crescent
Avenue and at Whitney Field, at Bloomfield and Denton Roads. Games
Friday at 10:30 a.m. (Whitney) and 6 p.m. (Lodge), Saturday at 6
p.m. (Whitney) and Sunday at 10:30 a.m. and 5 p.m. (both Whitney).
Admission: At Whitney, $8 a person or $20 a car; $5 for the elderly
and free for children under 12. At Lodge, $5 a person. Take
binoculars and a hat with a brim. Tailgate picnics welcome.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL MUSEUM OF RACING AND HALL OF FAME, 191 Union Avenue,
across from the racecourse, (518) 584-0400. Open daily, 9 a.m. to 5
p.m. through Labor Day. Admission: $5; $3, students and the
elderly; children under 5 free.
</P>
<P>
   Attractions
</P>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPA STATE PARK, entrances on Route 50 (Ballston Avenue)
and Route 9 (South Broadway), (518) 584-2535. Open 24 hours. Park
administration building hours are 8 a.m. to 5:30 p.m. daily. Free.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL MUSEUM OF DANCE, 99 South Broadway, (518) 584-2225.
Open Tuesdays through Sundays, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Admission: $3.50;
$2.50 for students and the elderly; $1 for children under 12. This
weekend, free events celebrate the 10th anniversary of the New York
State Summer Schoolof Dance: Saturday, a master class (9 to 10:30
a.m.), etudes showcase (10:45 a.m. to 12:15 p.m.), panel discussion
(2 to 4 p.m.) and faculty and guest concert (7 p.m.); Sunday, four
workshops, noon to 2 p.m. Call for details.
</P>
<P>
   SARATOGA PERFORMING ARTS CENTER, Saratoga Spa State Park, Route
50 (Ballston Avenue), (518) 587-3330. Summer home of the New York
City Ballet and the Philadelphia Orchestra. The ballet season has
ended; the orchestra plays Friday and Saturday at 8:15 p.m., its
final performances of the season. Tickets: $15 to $45 inside; $10,
lawn.
</P>
<P>
   YADDO, Union Avenue (just off Exit 14 from I-87), (518)
584-0746. Open daily from dawn to dusk. Admission is free. Informal
tours meet at the large garden fountain every Tuesday, Thursday and
Saturday at 11 a.m. Larger groups may arrange tours by calling in
advance.
</P>
<P>
   CANFIELD CASINO, Congress Park. The first floor of this historic
building includes the casino parlor and dining room, which may be
rented for private functions through the City of Saratoga Springs,
(518) 587-3550. The remainder of the floor and the upper two floors
house museum exhibitions on the history of Saratoga Springs,
Congress Park and the casino and are administered by the Historical
Society, (518) 584-6920.
</P>
<P>
   Museum hours: Mondays through Saturdays, 10 a.m. to 4 p.m.;
Sundays, 1 to 4 p.m. Admission: $3; $2 for the elderly and free for
children under 12. Admission includes a tour of the first-floor
casino rooms, conducted every Monday, Wednesday and Friday at 1:30
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS PUBLIC LIBRARY, 49 Henry Street (off Spring
Street). (518) 584-7860. Hours: Mondays though Thursdays, 9 a.m. to
9 p.m.; Fridays, 9 a.m. to 6 p.m.; Saturdays, 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.
Closed Sundays through Labor Day, then open 1 to 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   LYRICAL BALLAD, 7 and 9 Phila Street, (518) 584-8779. A book and
print store open Mondays through Saturdays, 10 a.m. to 6 p.m.;
Sundays, 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. until Labor Day, then 11 a.m. to 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   URBAN CULTURAL PARK VISITOR CENTER, 297 Broadway, (518)
587-3241. Open daily, 9 a.m. to 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Getting There
</P>
<P>
   BY CAR. Take the Gov. Thomas E. Dewey Thruway to Exit 24 and
continue on the Northway (Route 87 North) to Exits 13N, 14 or 15.
</P>
<P>
   BY TRAIN. Amtrak offers a round-trip package from Manhattan
every Saturday through Sept. 5. The train leaves Penn Station at
7:45 a.m. and arrives in Saratoga Springs about 11:30 a.m.; the
return train to New York departs at 6:42 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The $48 round-trip fare includes grandstand admission to the
Saratoga Race Course, a program magazine and free shuttle service
between the race track and the train station. In addition, Amtrak
has a variety of daily trains to and from Saratoga Springs, with
one-way fares of $36 or $45. Information and reservations: (800)
872-7245.
</P>
