<HEADLINE>
ART WORLD NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (mk) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stores and theaters were hardly alone in suffering
from the collapse of an elevator support tower last month at the
Conde Nast building under construction at Broadway between 42nd and
43rd Streets. The International Center of Photography Midtown at
43rd Street and Avenue of the Americas was also forced to close the
day of the accident, and could not reopen until Tuesday, a full
three weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   Willis Hartshorn, the director of the center, is now worried
that people will think the museum is still closed. Although the
entrance is clear, and photographs and signs about exhibitions
appear in the windows, scaffolding remains around part of the
building.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quandary is how to let people know we're open again,''
Hartshorn said, adding, ``We're losing money daily.''
</P>
<P>
   For three weeks the institution was paying salaries to staff
members who were not allowed to come to work, while going without
revenue from its $5-a-person admission fee or from bookstore sales.
The center lost about $20,000 in revenue, Hartshorn estimated, and
will lose more if people continue to think the center is closed.
</P>
<P>
   The museum is exhibiting ``Matthew Brady's Portraits: Images as
History, Photography as Art'' and ``A Bronx Family Album: The
Impact of AIDS'' by Steve Hart.'' The Brady show closes on Sept. 6
and the Hart show on Nov. 15. Hartshorn said neither would be
extended.
</P>
<P>
   He said he doubted that the center would recover its financial
losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can line up with everybody else in the area who suffered,
but I'd say getting anything back is unlikely,'' he said. ``And if
we do, it will take years.''
</P>
<P>
   Starry, Starry Tote Bag
</P>
<P>
   The National Gallery of Art in Washington is bracing for what it
predicts will be some of the biggest crowds in its history when
``Van Gogh's Van Goghs: Masterpieces from the Van Gogh Museum,
Amsterdam'' opens on Oct. 4.
</P>
<P>
   The show, featuring the largest collection of van Gogh's
paintings to be seen in the United States in some 25 years, will
include 70 works lent by the Van Gogh Museum.
</P>
<P>
   The Amsterdam museum is lending the paintings because, beginning
on Sept. 1, it will be closed for eight months for renovations and
the addition of a wing.
</P>
<P>
   Paintings to be exhibited include ``The Potato Eaters'' (1885),
``The Bedroom'' (1888), ``Wheat Field with Crows'' (1890),
``Fishing Boats on the Beach at Saintes-Maries-de-la-Mer'' (1888)
and ``Self-Portrait with Felt Hat'' (1887-88). These iconic images
will also appear on the widest range of merchandise ever offered at
the National Gallery.
</P>
<P>
   While the museum has generally been conservative in its
commercial offerings, for this show it will sell everything from
watches and vases to mouse pads and computer screen savers, in
addition to the standard selection of posters, postcards,
calendars, tote bags and wrapping paper. For the first time there
will be a special van Gogh shop in a gallery across the hall from
the show in the West Building.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything has been produced under the auspices of the Van
Gogh Museum,'' said Keith Webb, head of business activities. ``They
have decided to go all out and create a line of products in
anticipation of their reopening. Normally we create our own
products; this is the first time someone else has done the hard
work for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting into the show, which closes on Jan. 3, will not be easy:
Though admission is free, daily passes will be required. Beginning
on Aug. 30, advance passes will be available on Sundays from 11
a.m. to 6 p.m. and Mondays through Saturdays from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.
at the East Building pass desk at Fourth Street and Constitution
Avenue N.W.
</P>
<P>
   Advance passes will also be available beginning Aug. 30 through
Ticketmaster, with a $2.75 service charge for each pass and a $1.25
handling fee for each order. There is a limit of six passes per
order.
</P>
<P>
   For those who prefer to try their luck, the gallery will also
hand out a limited number of same-day passes every day the show is
open. These may be obtained on a first come, first served basis,
and the same limit of six passes a person applies. Those may be
picked up at the West Building pass desk, in the rotunda on the
main floor.
</P>
<P>
   Expansion at Stanford
</P>
<P>
   The Stanford University Museum of Art in Stanford, Calif.,
recently received $10 million from the late philanthropist B.
Gerald Cantor and his wife, Iris, for its $37 million expansion and
renovation, and will be renamed the Iris and B. Gerald Cantor
Center for Visual Arts at Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   The Cantors have also given the university more than 180 works
by Rodin over the years.
</P>
<P>
   The museum, which has been closed since it was damaged in the
1989 earthquake, is being enlarged with a 42,000 square-foot-wing,
an enhanced Rodin sculpture garden and new outdoor sculpture-garden
areas. The wing, designed by James Stewart Polshek &AMP; Partners of
Manhattan, will house galleries for the museum's special
exhibitions and the modern and contemporary art collection, as well
as an auditorium, cafe and bookshop. The building is scheduled to
open in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``We plan to become more active in the community and less
contained within the university,'' said Thomas Seligman, the
museum's director. ``This is a university museum but also a
regional museum, and now we will be able to offer education to
people in the Stanford area as well as to the university.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum's permanent collection includes about 20,000 objects
from ancient through contemporary. The emphasis is on contemporary
work, Seligman said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the recent gifts to the museum are a Richard Diebenkorn
painting, ``Ocean Park No. 4,'' from Phyllis Diebenkorn, the
artist's widow, and a Claes Oldenburg sculpture, ``Soft Inverted
Q,'' which was given to the museum by Robin Quinn Gates, a
collector in the Bay area.
</P>
</TEXT>
