<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Friday, Aug. 14. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-BOMBING (Nairobi, Kenya) _ What we know so far from the
Nairobi bombing investigation. By Raymond Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-MEMORIAL (Andrews Air Force Base, Md.) _ To the strains
of ``Nearer My God to Thee,'' the remains of 10 Americans killed in
Africa last week were borne back to their home soil on Thursday and
received at a solemn ceremony by President Clinton. By Katharine Q.
Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   CONGO-REBELS (Kinshasa) _ Power was cut to Kinshasa on Thursday,
and rebels fighting the government of President Laurent Kabila said
they were the ones responsible. If their claims are correct, it
means the rebels could be a real threat to the capital for the
first time since the revolt began last week. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECON (Moscow) _ Developments in Russia's market meltdown:
Prices plunge on the main stock exchange; the central bank acts to
protect the ruble amid calls for a devaluation; Moody's downgrades
its rating on Russian debt. By Michel Wines. With: MOSCOW-ASSESS
and RUSSIA-MARKETPLACE.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTHCARE-SUIT (Washington) _ A federal appeals court, in a
nationwide class action, expands the rights of Medicare patients,
ruling that they are entitled to immediate hearings and other
protections if they are denied care by an HMO. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-PRIVACY (Washington) _ The federal government accuses
an Internet company with 2 million customers of lying to them about
privacy protection. The FTC says that the company, Geocities, ran
contests aimed at children that were really designed to gather
personal information that would be resold to other companies. By
Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   WESTERN-LAND-TRUSTS (Clark, Colo.) _ Here and across the
mountain west, tourism and the second-home industry have spurred a
land rush that is carving up the ranch land that composes
heart-stopping Western vistas, threatening the very landscape that
draws so many people to the Rockies. The pressures are so powerful
that they are forging alliances of two longtime adversaries:
cattlemen and environmentalists. Together they are adapting a tool
long used to preserve open space in the crowded East, land trusts,
to save the West's privately owned wide-open spaces by keeping
cattle grazing on them. By James Brooke.
</P>
</TEXT>
