<SLUG> BC-STORIES-THEATER-REVIEW-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`COLLECTED STORIES': OF LOVE AND LITERARY BETRAYAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at the end of review. 
(js) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Some things you don't touch.''
</P>
<P>
   The simple sentence seems to bruise the air in the new
production of Donald Margulies' ``Collected Stories'' that opened
Thursday night at the Lucille Lortel Theater. The words aren't a
warning. It's too late for warnings by this time.
</P>
<P>
   The voice that shapes the declaration is raw and ravaged, as
deep and forbidding as an underground cave. The face of the
speaker, who has just told the story of a relationship with someone
long dead, is aghast, open and utterly unprotected looking. A
violation of something sacred, at least in one woman's mind, has
already occurred, and the aftermath is as unsettling as the sight
of a bleeding wound.
</P>
<P>
   The face and voice belong to Uta Hagen, and their status as
precision instruments, used for sounding subterranean depths of
character, has been confirmed time and again over the last six
decades. Ms. Hagen, one of the major American theatrical talents of
this century and a celebrated teacher of acting, is the woman who
won her first Tony Award for her 1950 performance in Clifford
Odets' ``Country Girl,'' who played Desdemona to Paul Robeson's
Othello and who created the role of the earthy, ego-shredding
Martha in ``Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?''
</P>
<P>
   Yet watching her in Margulies' two-character play about a
venerable fiction writer and her too-eager disciple, you don't
experience that self-conscious feeling that often arises in the
presence of living legends. Ms. Hagen refuses to coast on the aura
of her own history.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, at 79, she invests her role with the concentrated focus
and energy of a rising young star in a make-or-break performance.
There is some question, as there was when she spectacularly
returned to the New York stage several years ago in Nicholas
Wright's ``Mrs. Klein,'' as to whether this play, a lesser effort
from the author of such fine, probing works as ``Sight Unseen'' and
``The Model Apartment,'' is worthy of the love and attention she
has lavished on it. The effect sometimes suggests a 150-watt bulb
screwed incongruously into a small reading lamp. Still, one happily
takes Ms. Hagen wherever one finds her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Collected Stories,'' first seen only a year ago in New York in
a Manhattan Theater Club production starring Maria Tucci, is a love
story of sorts, a chronicle of a relationship that reaches that
level of intensity at which its participants are all too capable of
injuring each other, perhaps irreparably. At least that's the play
that Ms. Hagen and her co-star, the talented Lorca Simons, are
performing under the direction of William Carden.
</P>
<P>
   On the page, ``Collected Stories'' seems far more facile and
formulaic, traits also evident in the director Lisa Peterson's
elegant interpretation of it for the Manhattan Theater Club,
despite the best efforts of a miscast Ms. Tucci. The work was
inspired, Margulies has said, by the debate surrounding David
Leavitt's 1993 novel ``While England Sleeps,'' which was obviously
patterned after the autobiographical writings of Stephen Spender,
the English poet. Spender sued, and the novel was revised by
Leavitt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Collected Stories,'' accordingly, could easily have taken the
title of Brian Clark's earlier (and unrelated) play, ``Whose Life
Is It, Anyway?'' Margulies' comic drama is set in the Greenwich
Village home of Ruth (Ms. Hagen), a fiction writer whose slender
but acclaimed output, as described here, brings to mind the stories
of Grace Paley. Ruth has established a ritualized, self-contained
existence in the well-worn, book-cluttered apartment (the generic
set is by Ray Recht) where she has lived for 30-some years.
</P>
<P>
   The balance of that life is disrupted when Ruth takes on Lisa
(Ms. Simons), her gifted and ungainly student in a creative writing
class at Columbia University, as her assistant. Lisa brings an
overwhelming devotion, curiosity and willingness to learn to the
job. During the six years over which the play occurs, Lisa elicits
the total confidence of her mentor and even gets the older woman to
venture into what had always been forbidden ground for Ruth: the
story of her sad love affair as a young woman with the
self-destructive poet Delmore Schwartz.
</P>
<P>
   You can probably imagine to what professional use Lisa puts this
slice of personal history. There are, in fact, very few surprises
in ``Collected Stories,'' which emerges as a cross between ``All
About Eve,'' with its portrait of a star betrayed by her protegee,
and the high-culture soap opera of the ballet movie ``The Turning
Point.''
</P>
<P>
   Margulies carefully sets up the elements for the final, highly
wrought showdown between the two women. Throughout the play, Ruth
unwittingly sows the seeds for arguments that can and will be used
against her, from her declaration that writers must be
``scavengers'' of other people's lives to her casually asking, in a
conversation about Woody Allen's love affairs, ``Why is gossip so
delectable, anyway?'' It is also to the playwright's credit that he
doesn't overweight the work's central debate in one direction or
another.
</P>
<P>
   There is also, however, a gratingly naive quality in the way
these women talk about their work and the literary milieu they
inhabit, as though Margulies were taking a busload of tourists
through a theme park called Writer's World. There are callow
references to ``the muse'' and thuddingly dropped names that range
from E.L. Doctorow to the New York Times senior book critic Michiko
Kakutani.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   When Ruth, describing audience reactions to readings by writers,
comments on ``the self-indulgent laughter of people who want you to
know that they get everything,'' you realize that you have heard
just that sound throughout the performance of ``Collected
Stories.'' The one sustained example we are given of Lisa's
``mature'' writing is appallingly cliched, but then so is its
thinly disguised source, a memory monologue delivered by Ruth. You
have difficulty believing that either woman could ever have gotten
published.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the intensity and conviction of the performances
here burn right through the clunkier dialogue, which includes the
confrontational zinger, ``This isn't about you and me, and you know
it!'' Ms. Hagen and Ms. Simons sustain a rich subtextual dialogue,
between a woman in search of a daughter and a girl longing for a
spiritual parent, that is obviously the product of long,
investigative rehearsal, and it is impossible not to be moved by
it.
</P>
<P>
   It could be argued that, on some level, these actresses don't
serve Margulies' text as effectively as their predecessors, Ms.
Tucci and Debra Messing, did at the Manhattan Theater Club. Ms.
Simons never quite grows into the womanly confidence that Ms.
Messing chillingly conveyed at the play's end. And whereas Ms.
Tucci portrayed Ruth as dauntingly gruff and closed-off at the
work's beginning, Ms. Hagen brings a maternal warmth and
self-parodying wryness to the earliest scenes that make Lisa's fear
of her teacher seem way out of proportion.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the emotional current between the performers takes
on a sweeping, electric life of its own. You find yourself paying
less attention to the dialogue than to the finely graded code of
gestures and vocal inflections with which these women chart the
rise and fall of a friendship. The sensation is not unlike what
happens when you listen to an opera in which the voices capture
ineffable shades of feeling that go way beyond the libretto.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, you may be hard pressed after the play ends to remember
anything specific that Ms. Hagen's character has said. But you
won't forget the blend of pride and vulnerability that infuses her
every moment onstage.
</P>
<P>
   You'll remember the way she holds her head back to keep the
tears from rolling off her face; the quick, astonished inhalation
of breath that immediately turns into a self-protecting frostiness;
the exaggerated, supplicatory grandeur with which Ruth pours a
glass of wine for the young woman whose feelings she has just
inadvertently wounded, and, above all, the elegiac poetry, equal
parts defeatedness and hope, that Ms. Hagen brings to the basic act
of bolting and unbolting a door in the play's final scene.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   COLLECTED STORIES
</P>
<P>
   By Donald Margulies; directed by William Carden; sets by Ray
Recht; costumes by Mirenda Rada; lighting by Chris Dallos; sound by
Robert Auld; production stage manager, Pamela Edington; production
supervision, Progressive Productions; associate producer, Skylight
Productions. The HB Playwrights Foundation production presented by
Chase Mishkin, Sonny Everett, Steven Levy, Leonard Soloway, by
special arrangement with Lucille Lortel. At the Lucille Lortel
Theater, 121 Christopher Street.
</P>
<P>
   With: Uta Hagen (Ruth) and Lorca Simons (Lisa).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
