<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANIMATION MEETS CHARM IN WHIRLIGIGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn; Mass., Pa., Tenn., Nev.)   (af)  
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On Sunday, Skinner Inc. of Boston auctioned off an
Uncle Sam whirligig, or wind toy, for $12,650 at its sale of
American Furniture and Decorative Arts.
</P>
<P>
   In fine condition, the 72-inch-tall carved wood and sheet-metal
sculpture depicts Uncle Sam sawing a log resting on a sawbuck.
Standing beneath a flagpole, Stars and Stripes flapping away, this
Uncle Sam is quite the dandy.
</P>
<P>
   He has long, wavy blond hair and wears bold red-and-white
striped pants, a long blue tail coat and a white top hat with a
star-studded blue hatband. He braces his foot on a log meticulously
painted to show individual rings of growth. The log moves back and
forth as the wind hits an elaborate mechanism underneath, a
carousel of wind paddles.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on its complex design, Stephen Fletcher, the head of
Skinner's Americana department, said, ``It must have been made by
an engineer-savant.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike much early American folk art, this charming Uncle Sam is
dated and has a provenance. It was carved in 1900 by a bicycle
repairman from Wilmington, Mass., who was called Henry Wilson
Sargent but was always known as ``Henny Penny'' because he charged
a penny a minute for his repair work.
</P>
<P>
   Whirligigs, three-dimensional, wind-driven articulated toys,
have been created by artists, self-taught and otherwise, for more
than 200 years in this country.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1995 Viking Studio book ``Folk Art in American Life,'' by
Jacqueline Atkins and Robert Bishop (the late director of the
Museum of American Folk Art in New York), the authors try to
distinguish the weather vane from the whirligig. They write:
``These small, animated statues or structures were created strictly
for amusement, for, unlike weather vanes, they do no more than
signal that the wind is blowing or not blowing. They also allow a
great deal of scope for creative expression.''
</P>
<P>
   The authors write that no 18th-century examples seemed to have
survived, but that whirligigs were ubiquitous by the 19th century.
They quote a reference to one in Washington Irving's ``Legend of
Sleepy Hollow,'' from 1819: ``Thus, while the busy dame bustled
about the house, or plied her spinning wheel at one end of the
piazza, honest Balt did sit smoking his evening pipe at the other,
watching the achievements of a little wooden warrior, who, armed
with a sword in each hand, was most valiantly fighting the wind on
the pinnacle of the barn.''
</P>
<P>
   There are a few outstanding collections of whirligigs in museums
in this country, notably the Smithsonian, the Abby Aldrich
Rockefeller Collection at Colonial Williamsburg, and the Shelburne
Museum, in Shelburne, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   The Shelburne boasts a whirligig trade sign: A woman seated at a
spinning wheel moves her foot up and down on the treadle as the
wind turns the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, Bishop became close friends with the New Yorkers
Dorothea and Leo Rabkin, and they recently donated their
1,200-piece folk art collection, including several whirligigs, to
the Museum of American Folk Art. Rabkin, an abstract artist, has a
special take on the sculptures.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can feel the innocence in the execution of the figures,''
he said. ``The men whittled as the women sewed quilts. They were
farmers. They didn't have TV or radio, so they carved.''
</P>
<P>
   Acquiring antique whirligigs today is far more difficult than it
was 40 years ago, when the Rabkins started. A few usually turn up
at the Americana sales in October at the auction houses, and
Christie's will have some examples in a single-owner folk art sale
in January, but folk art dealers rarely have many for sale.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the Steve Miller American Folk Art Gallery, at 17
East 96th Street in Manhattan, has only one 19th-century whirligig,
a standing figure in a stovepipe hat. Miller said it was probably
what is known as a ``Sunday toy'' from Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Pennsylvania Dutch were very religious, and thought it was
sinful for children to play with toys on the Lord's day,'' he
explained. ``The parents would mount the whirligigs on the lawn, so
the children could look outside and see them move in the wind. This
one is well carved, and good ones are scarce.'' The price is
$12,500.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Aarne Anton, the owner of American Primitive, a gallery at 594
Broadway, in SoHo near Houston Street, also has only one
19th-century whirligig at the moment, a carved wood policeman with
a tiny star on his chest. His arms spin in the wind. He costs
$7,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's wonderful is the animation achieved by the whirligig as
it spins,'' said Anton, who pointed out that whirligigs often have
a message. ``Sometimes they pay tribute, and sometimes they are
poking fun at the subject.''
</P>
<P>
   Anton has 20th-century whirligigs, including one made with
abstract geometric forms and another with Barbie dolls. ``A lot of
whirligigs had propellers and complex movements,'' he said.
``Unfortunately, they were often the ones that would self-destruct
in a heavy wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Whirligigs appeal to contemporary artists, who tend to label
them kinetic sculpture. The Noyes Museum of Art in Oceanville,
N.J., outside Atlantic City, is currently showing 26 contemporary
examples in ``Blowin' in the Wind: A Juried Exhibition of
Whirligigs,'' through Aug. 30. The curator, Stacy Smith, said,
``It's fun, it's accessible artistically, and the sculptures are
clever.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara and Ted Alfred of Sevierville, Tenn., have some pieces
in the show, including ``Golfing on the Moon,'' in which an
astronaut hits a golf ball in front of a space ship. Alfred
recalled that he and his wife began to make whirligigs after his
retirement in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barbara accepted the responsibility of doing the sanding and
the art work,'' he said. ``It was up to me to do the wood work,
carving and the mechanics.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith said whirligigs are often made by husband and wife
teams; one usually makes the sculpture and the other, the
mechanism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our First Ambassador to France,'' made by Janice Fenimore, an
artist from Madison, N.J., has Benjamin Franklin dancing a minuet
with a voluptuous French woman, peering over his spectacles at her
breasts, which are barely contained by her decollete gown.
</P>
<P>
   As their arms move, the two get closer together and his nose
nearly touches her cleavage. Another of her works, ``T.J. At
Home,'' is a model of Monticello, complete with columns. When the
propellers move, the dome is raised and Thomas Jefferson pops out
like a jack-in-the-box.
</P>
<P>
   Now whirligigs are going avant-garde. From Aug. 31 to Sept. 7,
more than 10,000 people are expected to congregate at the annual
Burning Man Festival in the Black Rock Desert in northern Nevada.
(It is called Burning Man because each year a five-story wood
figure is erected, then consumed in a bonfire on the final night of
the fair.)
</P>
<P>
   A free-form Woodstock-style festival focusing on art rather than
music, it attracts people who arrive with tents and sleeping bags
for a week of self-expression. This year, among other programs,
participants plan to construct a whirligig village called
Gigsville. (Tickets: $100 a person. Information: (415) TO-FLAME or
on the Internet at http://www.burningman.com)
</P>
<P>
   The Burning Man Festival expects a lot of interesting
whirligigs, but not too many Uncle Sams.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
