<SLUG> BC-FORMOSA-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMOSA ABORIGINAL SONG AND DANCE TROUPE: SPINS AND CLAPPING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The culture and history of the nine aboriginal tribes
of Formosa, believed to be the original inhabitants of the island
of Taiwan, were fast disappearing when a group of young aborigines
decided to preserve them. In 1991, the group began to collect,
study and reconstruct the dances and songs of their elders. And so
the Formosa Aboriginal Song and Dance Troupe was born.
</P>
<P>
   The company returned to the Lincoln Center Out of Doors festival
on Wednesday afternoon, after a five-year absence, for an hourlong
performance on the Fountain Plaza stage. The program built toward a
rousing climax. But in general the material remained more ritual
than entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   How to bridge the gap and turn ceremony into theater without
betraying the quality and aims of the original? The Formosans
haven't solved that difficult problem yet. But the attention and
care brought to the work by the young performers and their tribal
instructors was evident and nearly carried the day.
</P>
<P>
   The first half of the program was devoted the Little People's
ceremony of the Saisiat tribe. To untutored ears, the songs were
long, very even wails of chanted sounds. The gradual ranking and
circling of the singers' stately processionals was interesting, as
was the integration of spins and lilting pelvic thrusts into much
slower, simpler travel. The performers' red-and-white embroidered
shifts were handsome. And there was magic to the way the group
disappeared at the end. But there was little suggestion of emotion
or narrative, despite specific harvest and nationalistic themes.
</P>
<P>
   The song and dance that followed, abstracted from the Amis
tribe's celebration of New Year as practiced over several days by
Kiwit villagers, was comparatively, and enjoyably, raucous. Wearing
caps crowned with a few tall waving feathers, the men began by
bursting onto the stage and into the audience. Back on the stage,
they built quickly to a climax of driving bodies, ranked with
vividly costumed women who entered later, their upper torsos
dipping and straightening and their feet in fast, sometimes complex
sideways travel that ended in exciting shifting patterns and
rhythmic clapping. Yells peppered the air.
</P>
<P>
   The Formosans will perform again through Sunday, in somewhat
different programs, at the Taipei Theater, McGraw-Hill Building,
1221 Avenue of the Americas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 1739EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
