<HEADER>
A2740 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAYDN-STRING-QUARTETS     08-13 1226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAYDN-STRING-QUARTETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: THE HAYDN QUARTETS, PLAY BY PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The 68 string quartets of Haydn present a classic
instance of great music more heard about than heard. For
generations, many commentators, historians and knowing musicians
have cited these works as among the greatest achievements in all of
music. My colleague Bernard Holland recently wrote that Haydn was
the supreme master of the string quartet, greater even than Mozart,
Beethoven and Bartok, and this assessment is shared by many.
</P>
<P>
   Then why are these works so neglected? Even young musicians who
should know better have taken them for granted. Just ask the
pianist Peter Serkin.
</P>
<P>
   Serkin comes from seven generations of musicians, including his
father, Rudolf Serkin. Naturally, growing up in a family with such
a reverence for the masters, and being a typical baby boomer,
Serkin felt compelled to rebel. Musically, the rebellion took the
form of an intense and very natural curiosity about contemporary
music.
</P>
<P>
   But when Serkin's father observed his young son immersing
himself in all the works of Webern and Stravinsky, and the string
quartets of Schoenberg, he got ``terribly upset,'' Peter Serkin
recalled once in an interview. His father admonished him, saying,
``But you don't even know the string quartets of Haydn!''
</P>
<P>
   While Serkin rejected this kind of linear musical thinking (the
idea that one must study Bach in order to move on to Beethoven,
Brahms and so on), he realized his father was right. He didn't know
the Haydn string quartets. So he got the scores and recordings,
started listening, was enthralled and has remained so ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, audiences should be grateful to the Mostly Mozart
festival for the current special series of 6 p.m. concerts at Alice
Tully Hall, which began July 29 and will present all 68 Haydn
string quartets over this summer season and next. The programs last
no more than an hour without intermission. There is open seating.
To date there have been 12 programs by five different ensembles
including the Takacs, Emperor, Vellinger, St. Lawrence and Amernet
String Quartets. Friday night and Saturday at 6 p.m., the Colorado
String Quartet will conclude this summer's offerings.
</P>
<P>
   It is a rare opportunity, and the two programs I attended
Tuesday and Wednesday by the Amernet were immensely satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   There were other composers' string quartets before Haydn's great
ones, but they were, mostly, part of a tradition of household
music, and played for private enjoyment. Whether the house was the
modest residence of a Viennese merchant or the palace of a prince
did not essentially change the function of the music.
</P>
<P>
   But Haydn composed almost all his string quartets for private
performances by exceptional musicians, including himself, usually
on second violin, in the employ of Prince Esterhazy, a wealthy
Hungarian nobleman who was a passionate music lover and amateur
string player. Still, Haydn did not want to sacrifice the fun of
playing chamber works. So there is a jocular, genial surface
quality to the music that is often mistaken by listeners today, and
even some performers, as being all there is.
</P>
<P>
   But to engage the players, Haydn filled his quartets with
invention, surprises, unexpected harmonic turns, skittish rhythmic
patterns and unabashed stretches of virtuosic passage work.
</P>
<P>
   On another level, however, Haydn was writing for his own
intellectual stimulation, and what engaged him most was the
technique of thematic development, whereby the first-stated ideas
of a piece (a melodic motive of just a few notes, or a rhythmic
figure) are germinal elements that generate every subsequent bit of
the composition. So a four-movement, 20-minute string quartet
emerges as a rigorous, interrelated and organic whole, as
substantive as any symphony.
</P>
<P>
   This is the aspect of Haydn's string quartet writing that his
good friend Mozart and his former student Beethoven marveled over.
Each of them dedicated six quartets to the acknowledged master.
</P>
<P>
   But the problem for audiences today is that when a Haydn quartet
is played at all, it is usually offered as merely a pleasant
curtain raiser for the real works to follow: quartets by Beethoven,
Brahms, Shostakovich and such. This is why the format of the
festival is so beneficial. Just two, or sometimes three quartets
are played as an entire program, so it is impossible not to listen
with fresh focus. Yet the early evening hour, the informality and
the brevity rescue these programs from pedagogical trappings.
</P>
<P>
   The Amernet concerts provided the special pleasure of
experiencing these works with gifted, eager young performers who
are, no doubt, still in the process of getting to know them. The
players, brought together at Juilliard in 1991 by their chamber
music teacher, Joseph Fuchs, are a wonderfully diverse group: Kyoko
Kashiwagi, an intensely focused violinist from Tokyo; Marcia
Littley de Arias, a violinist from Greenville, N.C.; Alabama-born
Anne Marie Hudson, a violist, and Javier Arias-Flores, a boyish
cellist from Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   The Amernet, currently in residence at the Cincinnati
Conservatory, is already an accomplished and intelligent ensemble.
Their fine performances were most notable for the quality of
unjaded discovery that came through so vividly. Indeed, during the
Quartet in F (Op. 17, No. 2), Arias-Flores smiled nearly
continuously, as if he could still not get over how inventive the
wonderful cello part was.
</P>
<P>
   In two programs they played two quartets from Opus 17, which
were written in 1771 when Haydn was pushing 40, and two quartets
from Opus 64, written almost 10 years later. The music is
astonishing. The minuet of the Quartet in E from Opus 17 could not
seem more breezy on the surface, but just try to keep track of the
phrase structure in this long theme. Haydn disguises the internal
asymmetries with fairly regular four-bar units. The Adagio of the
Quartet in B Minor from Opus 64 is a radiant theme with three
extraordinary yet subtle variations. It points right to the sublime
slow movements of the late Beethoven quartets, and is every bit as
rich. Moreover, there is an economy of statement in this music that
perhaps only Stravinsky has equaled since.
</P>
<P>
   In its two concerts, the Colorado String Quartet will play two
more quartets from Opus 64, and three from Opus 17. And it was very
satisfying to read in the program notes by Peter A. Hoyt a tribute
to another overlooked musician, Haydn's right-hand man at the
Esterhazy court, a brilliant Italian violinist for whom Haydn
conceived the virtuosic first violin parts of the earlier quartets,
a man indispensable to Haydn's development as a string quartet
composer: Luigi Tomasini.
</P>
<P>
   OK, I admit, the spelling is not quite the same: Luigi's last
name lacks the extra ``m'' that appears in the byline of yours
truly. But I have always liked to think that our family trees
crossed roots back there somewhere. Mostly, I try to imagine what
it must have been like to be in some elegant sitting room at the
Esterhazy palace, hearing these musicians play Haydn's string
quartets when they were new.
</P>
<P>
   The Mostly Mozart series is providing as good a sense as we are
likely to get of what it must have been like.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
