<SLUG> BC-MEATLOAF-PROTEST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEATLOAF DINNER IGNITES A PROTEST AT SOUTH TEXAS JAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ Some 70 inmates, apparently upset at being
served meatloaf, staged a rowdy protest at a South Texas jail
Wednesday night and spent hours banging on cells and shouting
threats at guards, the sheriff said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   There were no injuries and none of the prisoners escaped, but
dozens of extra guards were called in to restore order, Webb County
Sheriff Juan Garza said. At least four inmates were expected to be
charged with enticing a riot in a detention facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not their moms or wives who give them whatever they
want,'' Garza told a news conference, then served samples of a
jailhouse cheeseburger and broccoli.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no fire or disruption of property. It was noise,
yelling, screaming and making threats,'' Garza said. ``We consider
this a minor thing that could have escalated.''
</P>
<P>
   Arturo Ortiz, who is the county jail's head cook and a former
chef at the stylish La Posada Hotel in this city on the U.S.-Mexico
border, said he did not understand what all the fuss was about.
</P>
<P>
   ``We eat well here. The portions are fantastic,'' he said as he
oversaw the preparation of Thursday's lunch of cheeseburgers,
french fries and buttered broccoli.
</P>
<P>
   ``The food is the best,'' said Ortiz, who couldn't believe a
dinner of meatloaf with carrot sauce and vegetables would prompt a
protest.
</P>
<P>
   Garza said the menus are approved by the local health department
and the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you give them first-class food and the price goes up, of
course we'll be criticized,'' said Garza, who estimated it costs
about $1.25 per inmate for each meal.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the lunch sample, Garza produced a jail menu that
included such dishes as Salisbury steak, baked chicken and
spaghetti with meat sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Guards planned to meet with the inmates to discuss their
grievances.
</P>
<P>
   Garza said about 70 of the 550 inmates in the jail turned rowdy.
Of the 70, 16 were members of a known Texas prison gang, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the trouble started moments after the inmates, who eat
in their cells, were served the meatloaf Wednesday night. Some of
them refused to eat their meals, and their brown plastic trays were
removed and returned to the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   There were no complaints at breakfast Thursday, the sheriff
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
