u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SARATOGA-SPRINGS-N     08-13 0478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SARATOGA-SPRINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINGS? YES, INDEED 
</HEADLINE>
   (With NY-SARATOGA-HORSES)  
 (af)  
 By MINDY ALOFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Although the horses dominate Saratoga Springs, N.Y.,
at this time of year, there are many other attractions:
</P>
<P>
   The Waters
</P>
<P>
   Some historians conjecture that American Indian tribes
discovered the mineral springs running under what was essentially
swampland as early as the 14th century and made them a site of
pilgrimage. (Saratoga is a Mohawk word, meaning ``place of swift
waters.'')
</P>
<P>
   You can make a tasting tour of various springs, each with a
distinct flavor, from crusty to crystalline, by way of public
fountains reverentially positioned in Grecian-style pavilions.
</P>
<P>
   At the Lincoln Mineral Baths or the Crystal Spa, you can
marinate yourself in healing fluids; at Crystal, you can also be
wrapped in skin-restorative vegetation as if you were a very
precious pickle.
</P>
<P>
   Parks and Gardens
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the Saratoga Spa State Park, a national landmark that
harbors, among other amenities, the National Museum of Dance and
the Saratoga Performing Arts Center, summer home of the New York
City Ballet and the Philadelphia Orchestra, Saratogians themselves
consistently recommend a tour of the gardens of Yaddo, the colony
for writers and artists that was established by Spencer Trask and
his wife, Katrina.
</P>
<P>
   The Trasks also have a presence in lovely Congress Park, through
a sensuous fountain called ``The Spirit of Life,'' which Mrs. Trask
commissioned in her husband's memory from the architect Henry Bacon
and the sculptor Daniel Chester French, the team also responsible
for the Lincoln Memorial in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   French remembered the Apollonian head of his voluptuous Saratoga
naiad as ``the best thing of the kind I ever made.''
</P>
<P>
   Saratoga's History
</P>
<P>
   The opulent Canfield Casino in Congress Park houses the
excellent displays of the Historical Society. The casino itself is
a lovingly maintained palace of chance from the 19th century, when
Saratoga was, among other things, an unregulated gambler's
paradise.
</P>
<P>
   An antiquarian book and print store called Lyrical Ballad is a
source of reading pleasure. And don't miss Saratoga's new public
library, a model of sensitivity to the area's tradition and to
human comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Its holdings include rare materials in the Saratoga Room, a fine
section on classical music and perhaps the largest collection of
racing mysteries by Dick Francis outside the author's own.
(Borrowing privileges are available for temporary visitors.)
</P>
<P>
   Creature Comforts
</P>
<P>
   Downtown Saratoga Springs is dense with small shops, historic
inns and restaurants. Some of the loveliest gifts, however, may be
found in the gift shops of the museums.
</P>
<P>
   Especially recommended: the Visitor Center for paper
reproductions of fanciful antique cards and fans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
