<P>
   HEALTH-POIROT-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Some of the more than 200 types of bacteria that live
in the human mouth may be responsible for more than bad breath and
unsightly smiles. The same common bacteria that eat away enamel and
gums are being linked to heart disease, stroke, diabetes and
spontaneous pre-term births. By CAROLYN POIROT. Story has moved in
``l'' lifestyle category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   F I N A N C I A L &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-BOOKS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ You may not know Edward Bernays, but he certainly knew
you. There likely is not another human, dead or alive, who has
influenced the American public as much, yet is known by so few.
Unlike his famous uncle, Sigmund Freud, Bernays' name is not likely
to be learned in school. Yet his influence over Americans' daily
habits and thoughts in the 20th century is deeply profound. By
TERESA MCUSIC. Story has moved in ``f'' financial category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   T R A V E L &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-ANIMAL KINGDOM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ So far, Animal Kingdom is as much tarnish on the
Disney crown as an additional, sparkling jewel. Disney's reputation
is founded on make-believe, taking visitors into fantasy worlds
that are fun and impervious to any sort of unpleasantness. All the
corporate millions it has poured into Animal Kingdom can't prevent
rhinos from voiding their bowels within sight and smell of the
paying customers _ if the customers even see the rhinos. By JEFF
GUINN. Story has moved in ``t'' travel category. (Accompanied by
ANIMAL KINGDOM-BOX.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
