<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2784 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-3TAKE     08-13 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTEWORTHY FILMS  
 (JT)  
 &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The New York Times of
new or noteworthy movies playing this weekend. Ratings and running
times are in parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``ARMAGEDDON,''  &LR;  starring Bruce Willis, Ben Affleck, Liv Tyler
and Steve Buscemi. Directed by Michael Bay (PG-13, 144 minutes).
This big, showy, spirit-crushing summer extravaganza includes not a
single heartfelt moment, unless you count its sequence set in a
strip club. Imminent doom (courtesy of an approaching asteroid)
becomes the excuse for rampant flag-waving, gung-ho patriotism and
a notion of heroism that has nothing whatever to do with real
courage. Willis gets the film's noblest lines for the same reason
that he probably got the set's biggest trailer. Affleck tries
gamely to seem mad about Ms. Tyler, who serves as window-dressing
at NASA headquarters. Totally predictable elements _ loud noises,
frequent explosions and bright computer-screen colors _ seem as
inevitable and deadly as the asteroid while they create the
illusion of escapist fun (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``BASEKETBALL,''  &LR;  starring Trey Parker and Matt Stone.
Directed by David Zucker (R, 105 minutes). In David Zucker's funny,
gross-out spoof of professional sports, Parker and Stone are two
hapless post-adolescent dudes (the latest variation on Wayne and
Garth) who invent a silly driveway hybrid of basketball and
baseball that becomes a national obsession. The film is essentially
two movies stuck together. One is a dumber-than-dumb teen-age
comedy crammed with farcical sight gags and raunchy adolescent
humor. The other is a no-holds-barred satire of professional sports
and the greed, egotism and pomposity surrounding them. As in his
``Naked Gun'' series, Zucker's comic strategy is to fire off a
machine-gun volley of jokes of all shapes and sizes, trusting that
enough will land to keep the audience on the edge of a giggle
(Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``DR. DOLITTLE,''  &LR; starring Eddie Murphy and Oliver Platt.
Directed by Betty Thomas (PG-13, 85 minutes). When this Dr.
Dolittle talks to the animals, they pile on the back talk, thanks
to the stellar cast of vocal talent (Ellen DeGeneres, Garry
Shandling, Paul Reubens, John Leguizamo) that keeps the wisecracks
flying. And Murphy plays straight man with hilarious aplomb. This
good-humored family film is formulaic but steadily funny (and a lot
less corrosive than ``The Nutty Professor''), thanks not only to
Murphy's understated timing but also to expertly computer-enhanced
performances from the animal cast (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``EVER AFTER: A CINDERELLA STORY,''  &LR; starring Drew Barrymore,
Anjelica Huston, and Dougray Scott. Directed by Andy Tennant
(PG-13, 120 minutes). The clever notion of reinventing Cinderella
as a self-motivated powerhouse who doesn't need a fairy godmother
to get ahead has been reduced into a bland mishmash of comedy and
soap opera. Drew Barrymore is appealing as Danielle, a plucky,
resourceful, slightly tomboyish 16th-century French girl who knows
how to stand up for herself. But her wimpish prince ( Scott) isn't
much of a prize to crow over. And why is Leonardo da Vinci (Patrick
Godfrey) traipsing around France with the ``Mona Lisa'' under his
arm, giving advice to the lovelorn? The most orthodox refugee from
the standard fairy tale is Anjelica Huston's haughty stepmother
(Holden).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``EVEREST,''  &LR; directed by David Brashears with Greg
MacGillivray (not rated; 45 minutes). If life in New York City
doesn't provide enough in the way of thrills, those in search of a
vicarious near-death experience can make their way to the Sony Imax
Theater at Lincoln Square (1998 Broadway, at 68th Street) for a go
at ``Everest.'' There, images of the world's highest mountain _
29,028 feet _ find a frame worthy of the peak's spectacular, lethal
beauty: the 8-story-high, 100-foot-wide screen. This account
focuses mainly on the efforts of three people to scale the peak in
1996 despite yawning chasms of ever-shifting ice, thundering
avalanches, the perils of air so thin that it addles the brain, and
sudden, blinding storms. While this expedition was on the mountain,
as many articles and books were later to relate, other teams made
their way into the so-called death zone, at 25,000 feet, where a
violent storm overtook them. Eight people perished in the worst
single disaster on the mountain. ``Everest'' makes it possible for
armchair adventurers to share the risks and glory of the team's
climb toward heaven (Lawrence Van Gelder).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``THE GOVERNESS,''  &LR;  starring Minnie Driver and Tom Wilkinson.
Directed by Sandra Goldbacher (R, 114 minutes). It is the early
1840's, and Rosina (Minnie Driver), a headstrong young Sephardic
Jewish woman living in London, poses as a gentile to get a job as a
governess for the Cavendish family on a remote Scottish island.
Falling in love with the skittish, devoutly Christian head of the
household (Tom Wilkinson), a gentleman inventor with whom she has a
stormy affair, she becomes his collaborator in the invention of
photography. The ravishingly handsome film works on several levels:
as a proto-feminist fable, a meditation on still photography and
its relation to real life, and a portrait of lovers whose religious
difference becomes an unbridgeable emotional gap. Ms. Driver holds
the picture with a solid performance that falls short of great
(Holden).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``GONE WITH THE WIND,''  &LR; starring Vivien Leigh, Clark Gable,
Olivia de Havilland, Leslie Howard and Hattie McDaniel. Directed by
Victor Fleming (G, 220 minutes). There's still a lot of robust life
left in this 1939 David O. Selznick adaptation of Margaret
Mitchell's romantic novel of the Old South (possibly as it never
existed) just before, during and after the Civil War. Not a great
film but a satisfying one. The performances by Vivien Leigh, Clark
Gable and Hattie McDaniel are ravishing, and there's grandeur in
the meticulous physical production. The movie shows its age most
unfortunately in the uneven quality of the Technicolor prints,
which, though new, go sort of pinkish more often than they should
(Vincent Canby).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``THE LAST DAYS OF DISCO,''  &LR;  starring Kate Beckinsale and
Chloe Sevigny. Directed by Whit Stillman (R, 112 minutes).
Stillman's smart, fretful, patrician characters turn up midway
between ``Metropolitan'' and ``Barcelona'' in a film that
charmingly mixes post-college career worries with improbable
discomania. A delightful cast engages in nonstop flirtation and
hair-splitting debate, rendered with Stillman's usual acuity and
humor. Ms. Beckinsale, an English actress with a flawless American
accent here and diffidence that's just as perfect, holds court
beguilingly at the center of a bright and amusing crowd. The ideal
film for anyone willing to entertain the notion that the spread of
environmentalism was sparked by the revival of ``Bambi'' during the
disco generation's formative years (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``LETHAL WEAPON 4,''  &LR; starring Mel Gibson, Danny Glover and
Rene Russo. Directed by Richard Donner (R, 125 minutes). In the
full perspective-warping heat of the summer movie season, this
turns out to be one of the nicer blow-'em-ups around. The
characters are funny and likable, and they all live on earth. The
formula still has some zip. The stars, with the welcome new
addition of Chris Rock as a young detective who has literally
married into the ``Lethal Weapon'' family, play their roles with
breezy finesse. And the story, about slave smuggling and Chinese
gangsters, is a flamboyant, fight-filled adventure fueled by
kidding camaraderie and constant forward motion. Bear in mind that
this is still a film whose idea of high drama is watching a car get
pushed in front of an oncoming train (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``MAFIA!,''  &LR; starring Jay Mohr, Lloyd Bridges and Christina
Applegate. Directed by Jim Abrahams (PG-13, 86 minutes). This
sendup makes an offer you could probably refuse, but its
Mad-magazine-style hit-or-miss humor works well enough to be
reasonably bright. It's true, though, that a Mafia movie satire
without a single horse's head in a bed and without anyone who
sounds like Joe Pesci has left a few stones unturned. Concentrating
mostly on the ``Godfather'' films and ``Casino,'' Abrahams throws
in anything from canned meatballs by Spalding to vomit gags. Lloyd
Bridges, to whose memory the film is dedicated, has the role of a
dapper don and shows one last time how sporting and debonair he
could be (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``THE MASK OF ZORRO,''  &LR; starring Antonio Banderas, Anthony
Hopkins and Catherine Zeta-Jones. Directed by Martin Campbell
(PG-13, 130 minutes). Travel back to the days when swashbuckling
was serious business, when boyish adventure films still had their
innocence and when the bravado of thrilling stunt work was all a
movie needed in the way of special effects. Hopkins is marvelously
game as the film's dashing senior Zorro. Banderas was born to play
the aging hero's jokey, hotblooded protege. And he meets his match
in the story's heroine, whose beauty is inevitably described as
``beyond compare.'' This robust old-fashioned adventure should
appeal to older children, but beware of a few needlessly grisly
touches (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``THE NEGOTIATOR,''  &LR; starring Samuel L. Jackson and Kevin
Spacey. Directed by F. Gary Gray (R, 115 minutes). In a twist on
the Hitchcockian maxim, this thriller takes two extraordinary
actors and places them in surprisingly ordinary circumstances. In a
film whose title should have been plural, both stars play seasoned
hostage negotiators who are caught up in a by-the-numbers battle of
wits. Amazingly, both these shrewd, maverick actors are cast as
nice guys, team players and clean-cut family men. The movie's
brisk, familiar look of a police story, heavy with close-ups, that
escalates to a paramilitary operation will look right at home when
it comes to the video screen (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``NIGHTS OF CABIRIA,''  &LR; starring Giulietta Masina. Directed by
Federico Fellini (not rated, 117 minutes). Anyone dismayed by the
hyperkinetic emptiness of summertime film spectacles will find the
antidote in this 1957 Fellini masterpiece. It has been refurbished
and revived by the same team that brought back ``Contempt'' last
year, and they display the same acumen in reissuing a film of
special prescience; though it was shot in black and white amid the
poverty of postwar Italy, neither the style nor the searching of
``Cabiria' has grown dated at all. In a prize-winning and
heartbreaking performance, the star plays a scrappy Roman
streetwalker who drifts almost magically among the film's
astonishingly varied realms. There is more grace and courage in the
famous image of Masina smiling through her tears than in all the
fire-breathing blockbusters Hollywood has to offer (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``THE OPPOSITE OF SEX,''  &LR; starring Christina Ricci, Martin
Donovan, Lisa Kudrow and Lyle Lovett. Directed by Don Roos (R, 100
minutes). Wicked, foulmouthed and very funny, this gleefully
acerbic comedy finds that Ms. Ricci has morphed enchantingly from
nasty little Wednesday of ``The Addams Family'' into Lolita's evil
twin. Voluptuous and scheming, her poisonous Dedee narrates this
film and announces immediately that she won't be developing a heart
of gold. Which is, of course, mostly a lie. The film brutally
skewers preconceptions about gay and straight life, then lets its
characters intermingle in sweetly unexpected ways. Donovan and Ms.
Kudrow, as unlikely comrades brought together by Dedee's treachery,
deliver the zingers from Roos' screenplay with deadpan panache
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``THE PARENT TRAP,''  &LR; starring Lindsay Lohan, Natasha
Richardson and Dennis Quaid. Directed by Nancy Meyers and written
by David Swift, Ms. Meyers and Charles Shyer (PG, 128 minutes). A
super-cute remake of the old Hayley Mills hit, this time given a
privileged shelter-magazine gloss by the ``Father of the Bride''
team of Ms. Meyers and Shyer. Ms. Richardson and Quaid beam
appealingly as parents who somehow managed to separate their twins
at birth without a twinge of guilt, and who seem to have spent all
of the intervening 11{ years shopping. In her dual role as English
and American sisters (one lives in a grand London town house, the
other on a big Napa Valley vineyard; nobody lives in a coal mine),
the spirited Ms. Lohan commandeers the movie as if she had been
taking shrinking-violet lessons from Sharon Stone (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``SAVING PRIVATE RYAN,''  &LR; starring Tom Hanks, Matt Damon, Tom
Sizemore, Jeremy Davies, Edward Burns and Adam Goldberg. Directed
by Steven Spielberg (R, 168 minutes). Spielberg's soberly
magnificent new film is the finest war movie of our time. Turning
back the clock to restore passion and meaning to the genre, he
works in a spirit of urgent communication to look at war as if it
had not been looked at before. Tour-de-force battle scenes are
frank without sensationalism, and the same great storyteller who
made you believe there was an extraterrestrial hiding in the closet
has made this an irresistibly vibrant, gripping tale. Hanks
continues to astonish with admirable modesty, and the rest of the
casting is comparably inspired. As he did with ``Schindler's
List,'' Spielberg has made a landmark film of devastating power
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``SMALL SOLDIERS,''  &LR; starring Gregory Smith, Kirsten Dunst,
Dennis Leary and Phil Hartman. Directed by Joe Dante (PG-13, 105
minutes). This ably animated film about action-figure toys who
virtually come to life should have been a sure thing. There are
innocent echoes of ``Toy Story'' and darker ones of the director's
own ``Gremlins'' pictures, which had the witty balance of mischief
and horror that ``Small Soldiers'' strangely lacks. The voice
talent here is extraordinary, with the casts of ``The Dirty Dozen''
and ``This Is Spinal Tap'' playing rival toy factions, and Tommy
Lee Jones and Frank Langella as their respective commanders. But
the story remains unfocused and grows too wan for horror, too
creepy for lighthearted fun. Another reason not to laugh is
Hartman's performance in the fatuous role that was his last
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``SNAKE EYES,''  &LR; starring Nicolas Cage and Gary Sinise.
Directed by Brian De Palma (R, 99 minutes). An assassination, a
fixed heavyweight boxing bout, and a perfectly timed hurricane
named Jezebel collide apocalyptically one night in Atlantic City
where hellfire rains over a hotel and casino appropriately called
the Millennium. Here is where Rick Santoro ( Cage), the sleazy
police detective in charge of security, discovers his best friend (
Sinise) could also be his nemesis and he has to make hard moral
choices. This entertaining pop fable, which recalls the director's
``Blow Out,'' isn't believable for a second, but it has a pulpy
energy that keeps on chugging (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``THE SPANISH PRISONER,''  &LR; starring Campbell Scott, Rebecca
Pidgeon, Ben Gazzara and Steve Martin. Directed by David Mamet (PG,
112 minutes). The most engaging of Mamet's cinematic puzzles begins
with an X-ray at an airport security check. And the audience will
wish it had a similar device for reading the characters' sneaky
minds. No such luck: the mystery here, in a handsome and
Hitchcockian film named for an elaborate con game, stays tricky to
the very end. Scott plays the inventor of a lucrative, stealable
scientific process, with Gazzara as the boss who's in no hurry to
compensate him for it. In an ensemble cast working entirely on the
calculating Mamet wavelength, Martin plays a rich, debonair mystery
man who tells the inventor all about his pretty young sister. In
her performance as a pert, unaccountably off-kilter secretary, Ms.
Pidgeon perfectly embodies the film's sleight of hand (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``THERE'S SOMETHING ABOUT MARY,''  &LR; starring Cameron Diaz, Ben
Stiller and Matt Dillon. Directed by Peter and Bobby Farrelly (R,
119 minutes). Sometimes Western civilization declines in
deliriously funny style. Hence this proudly obnoxious comedy is a
hoot in every sense, deserving a smidgen of disapproval and a whole
lot of helpless laughter. Set in motion by a prom, a crush and a
cruel, cruel zipper, this paean to low humor works ridiculously
well because it never stoops to being mean-spirited or (despite all
appearances) authentically inane. The principal cast is bright and
appealing, with Ms. Diaz at her most beautiful and blithe. Do note
that this film strives hard for something to offend everyone, and
that tolerance for the Farrellys' zit jokes is unfortunately
required (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``TITANIC,''  &LR; starring Leonardo DiCaprio, Kate Winslet and
Gloria Stuart. Directed by James Cameron (PG-13, 197 minutes). For
once, a much-touted event movie is exactly that: a glorious
throwback to the days when epic storytelling really filled the
screen. Despite the astonishing technological advances behind
Cameron's great visual spectacle, gimmicks are never allowed to
intrude on the film's central illusion, that the audience is drawn
back into the Gilded Age and intimately involved in the fateful
voyage. For all its painstaking historical detail, this ``Titanic''
proves anything but quaint, thanks to the phenomenal immediacy of
its sights and the pure Hollywood hokum of its story. As two young
lovers whose romance is skillfully interwoven with historical
detail, Ms. Winslet and DiCaprio are a duo with serious chemistry.
With his ``Gone With the Wind''-caliber ambitions, Cameron dared to
dream of the impossible and came up with the movie of the year
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``THE TRUMAN SHOW,''  &LR; starring Jim Carrey, Laura Linney and Ed
Harris. Directed by Peter Weir and written by Andrew Niccol (PG,
104 minutes). The ultimate in high-concept ingenuity. Hosannas and
cartwheels for this ingenious media-age fantasy are over the top,
but by comparison with Hollywood's usual notion of summer movie
fare, it's definitely a dazzler. Carrey, refreshingly free of
shtick, gives an instantly iconic performance as a guinea pig for
an entertainment-happy nation, a man whose whole life is a fraud
contrived by Harris' so-called ``televisionary.'' Carrey's innate
edge of volatility gives the material, from a screenplay of
transfixing sci-fi intensity, its trace of danger. Ms. Linney, as
the actress playing a wife whose bluff could be called at any
moment, is the story's spookiest character as well as its perkiest.
Weir unifies the story's many nuances with great finesse (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``WESTERN,''  &LR; starring Sergi Lopez and Sacha Bourdo. Directed
by Manuel Poirier (not rated, 121 minutes). What a tenderhearted
delight is ``Western,'' the best-kept secret in town. Don't be put
off by that misleading title: Poirier's road movie is actually set
in western France, where two funny and hapless outsiders wind up
joining forces and embarking on a wonderfully droll journey. The
story begins when a salesman from Spain is outsmarted by a wily
little Russian hitchhiker. It's an introduction that hardly has the
makings of a beautiful friendship. But that's exactly what develops
in a funny, romantic film filled with cozy intimacies and lovely,
wide-screen images of the French countryside. Looking for love,
these two lonely travelers find it in the most sweetly
unpredictable ways. Audiences are liable to fall in love, too
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``THE X-FILES,''  &LR;  starring David Duchovny and Gillian Anderson
and Armin Mueller-Stahl. Directed by Rob Bowman (PG-13, 115
minutes). Conspiracy theorists, consider this: what if the
hush-hush atmosphere and Internet mania surrounding the first
``X-Files'' feature film were part of a giant scheme to hide the
uneventfulness of a summertime sci-fi fizzle? It's as possible as
much of what this spinoff film has to offer. If devotees of the
television series approach the film with enough baggage for a
six-week safari, maybe they can deepen the experience of watching a
middling action-adventure with brand-name appeal. But this film
will strike true X-fanatics as watered down, and remains fairly
bewildering to the uninitiated. And, no, Scully and Mulder don't
quite take their working relationship to a higher plane (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
