<HEADER>
A2793 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWIS-PRINT-REVIEWNYT     08-13 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-PRINT-REVIEWNYT </SLUG>
  
 CATCHING '30s NEW YORK WITH LIGHT AND SHADOW  
 (af)  
 By GRACE GLUECK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New printmakers of the 1920s and '30s caught the
spirit of New York in that era with quite the pizazz of Martin
Lewis (1881-1962), an Australian who came to the city at 19 and
made it his own.
</P>
<P>
   Buildings, views, neighborhoods, street gangs, storefronts,
rooftops, shoppers, workers, idlers, relationships, even the
weather, seem especially staged for Lewis, who got it all down in
black and white, capturing people and architecture in the etching
and drypoint techniques of which he was a master.
</P>
<P>
   One of his best-known mood pieces is ``Glow of the City''
(1929), a night scene in which a woman, dressed in flapper fashion
with bobbed hair, stands on a fire escape, gazing dreamily at the
metropolis around her.
</P>
<P>
   Over her head are lines of drying clothes; lights shine from
nearby apartment windows, and in the distance looms a symbol of the
city's prosperity, an illuminated skyscraper that brightens the
sky.
</P>
<P>
   The composition _ reminiscent of earlier work by John Sloan _
has the look of a 1920s Broadway stage set and a lyrical poignancy
that evokes Tin Pan Alley tunes of the period.
</P>
<P>
   That the Brooklyn Museum of Art owns one of the best public
collections of Lewis' prints seems a good enough reason for the
show it has assembled, ``Martin Lewis' World: Cityscapes on
Paper.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lewis is not the only artist represented: his world is
augmented with photographs from the period by other intense
urbanites like Berenice Abbott, Lewis Hine, Arthur Leipzig, Walter
Rosenblum and Adolf Fassbender. By means of strategic juxtaposing,
an attempt has been made to relate their subjects to those of
Lewis' prints.
</P>
<P>
   Although the time frame is from 1919 to the early 1950s, the
show's focus is on the '30s. Things were rough; the Great
Depression held the country in a stranglehold.
</P>
<P>
   But Lewis, although all his life a Socialist, was not one to
dwell on the downtrodden in his work. What he appreciated most were
the streetscapes peculiar to Manhattan, and sometimes its boroughs
and suburbs. He particularly liked night scenes in which he could
use his skills at rendering light and shadow.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Spring Night, Greenwich Village'' (1930), for example,
passers-by cast long silhouettes on the sidewalk in the light cast
by storefronts.
</P>
<P>
   The feel of New York in the small hours is conveyed by ``2
a.m.''(1932), in which three cloche-hatted women cross an all but
empty avenue as a sanitation worker washes it down with a powerful
hose (shades of the past!).
</P>
<P>
   The dark bulk of the not-yet-completed Empire State Building,
stagily illuminated from behind, is the subject of ``Manhattan
Lights'' (1931), its starkness relieved by the relaxed presence of
two women and a child. Hanging next to it is Lewis Hine's 1931
photograph ``New York From the Empire State Building at Night,'' a
dramatic shot taken from high up through girders and cable supports
that frame an exhilarating city panorama far below.
</P>
<P>
   The effects of weather were also a Lewis specialty, maybe
influenced by Japanese prints. ``Stoops in Snow,'' a 1930 scene in
which bundled-up pedestrians slog past a row of brownstone stoops
capped in white, is streaked with lines of falling snow, as is the
1932 photograph paired with it, ``Trolley in Snow,'' by John Albok,
which shows a streetcar lashed by a heavy winter storm.
</P>
<P>
   And in ``Windy Day'' (1932), pedestrians on what looks like
Fifth Avenue are attacked by playful gusts that ruffle their
clothes and send scraps of litter flying.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, a commercial artist until his mid-'40s, when he took up
printmaking in a serious way, was one of the few artists to devote
himself almost exclusively to the graphic medium. At his best, he
was a wonderful illustrator and chronicler whose vision of the city
rings true; at its least, his work is a kind of corny urban
regionalism comparable to that of the Midwestern painters, his
contemporaries, who celebrated rural life in what they called
``America's heartland.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, one of Lewis' great virtues is that he saw
New York as a heartland, too.
</P>
<P>
   As for the photographs in the show, standouts include Arthur
Leipzig's views of children playing games, Walter Rosenblum's shot
of adolescent rooftop recreation, D.J. Ruzicka's awesome glimpse of
lower Manhattan buildings through a pattern of crisscross cables
that enclose a high-up construction site, and Charles H. Zapata's
``Meeting'' (1940s), a couple of ordinary men in a street encounter
as seen from a nearby alley. You could cut the nostalgia here with
a knife, but it's a pleasant wallow.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)``Martin Lewis' World: Cityscapes on Paper'' remains at
the Brooklyn Museum of Art, 200 Eastern Parkway, at Prospect Park,
through Oct. 25.(end italics)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 1806EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
