<HEADER>
A2811 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRIATHLON-TRIALS-2TAK     08-13 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIATHLON-TRIALS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE TIMES THE PAIN! THREE TIMES THE GAIN? 
</HEADLINE>
  (duplication warning: also sent with `e' code) 
 (bl)  
 By JOE GLICKMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1982, the sport of triathlon was about as popular in the
United States as llama racing. But 11 hours into the fifth annual
Ironman Triathlon _ a 2.4-mile swim, 112-mile bike ride and
26.2-mile run _ the women's leader, Julie Moss, 23, wobbled down
Alii Drive on the Big Island of Hawaii and collapsed two miles from
the finish. Refusing medical attention, she picked herself off the
road, staggered a few more steps and crumpled again like a suit
slipping off a hanger.
</P>
<P>
   Her total body meltdown occurred on ABC's ``Wide World of
Sports'' and the audience was riveted. Would she still win? Could
she finish? Would she live? Somehow, she managed to struggle over
the remaining two miles. As she approached the finish line, she
began crawling, and Kathleen McCartney, the winner nobody
remembers, hobbled by. Thirty agonizing seconds later, Julie Moss
pulled herself across the line, becoming perhaps the most
celebrated second-place finisher of all time.
</P>
<P>
   I'll leave it to the psychologists to explain why such a
wrenching display of self-flagellation captured the public's
imagination, but it put the young sport on the map. The next year,
the field doubled, and 12 million households tuned in and saw two
of the most aerobically fit men on earth, Dave Scott and Scott
Tinley, race virtually side by side for nine hours. This was the
flip side of ``the agony of defeat.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, millions have participated in thousands of
triathlons, which has come to mean any event that combines
swimming, cycling and running, usually in that order.
</P>
<P>
   Triathlon, which makes its Olympic debut in 2000 in Sydney,
Australia, is big in Japan, South America, New Zealand, Canada,
Mexico and Europe. While the Hawaii Ironman _ the sport's glamour
event _ takes the pros 8 to 9 hours and mere mortals 11 to 15
hours, there's a prolific calendar of shorter races around the
country that are demanding but doable for anyone who can swim, bike
and run.
</P>
<P>
   The Ironman, which requires nearly Herculean effort to prepare
for and complete, is another beast entirely. After all, it resulted
from a naval officer's bar bet trying to settle an argument about
who was fitter: the runner, cyclist or swimmer.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, a friend cajoled me into entering a short-course
``tri'' in Northern New Jersey: a half-mile swim, 25-mile bike
race, 5-mile run. Setting up my gear in the transition area, a
roped-off space where the athletes would change after the swim and
bike, I was wowed by the rows of high-tech bicycles, some of which
cost as much as a used car. Many had ultralight disk wheels and
aero handlebars, which cut wind resistance by allowing the rider to
assume a forward, praying mantis position.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies that belonged to these sleek machines were also
striking. Unlike high-mileage runners who look perpetually hungry
and have little or no upper body mass, or hammerhead cyclists who
tend to have bulgy thighs that dwarf their lean torsos, or
wide-shouldered swimmers with skinny legs, these cross-training
``tri-geeks'' were both lean and proportionally muscular. Simply
put, they looked better than most of the single-sport devotees I
knew.
</P>
<P>
   The race's start was wild: 500 hyper athletes in swim suits,
goggles and bright red bathing caps thrashing over and around one
another like salmon spawning upstream. I survived the swim and
cycled competently, but when I donned my running shoes and
attempted locomotion, my thighs were so laden with lactic acid that
I ran like Frankenstein hustling to catch a bus.
</P>
<P>
   I did a few more triathlons, then stopped. The sport appealed to
me since it developed the total athlete, but training properly for
three disciplines was time-consuming. And having such a gadgety,
gear-intensive hobby would mean getting a second job (which first
would mean getting a first job). Triathlon, once the province of
southern California beach boys, had become the quintessential yuppy
sport. (In fact, a recent survey reported that the average annual
income of triathletes is $90,000.) When the $30 entry fees doubled,
I decided to sweat elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   And yet each year as I watched the assembled field of endorphin
junkies try to go the distance at the Ironman, I'd get caught up in
the hyperbolic commentary, and fantasize about doing it, at least
until the telecast was over. This summer, while running in
Brooklyn's Prospect Park with a friend who has completed two Hawaii
Ironmans and is trying to qualify for a third, I found myself
promising to join him in July at a half-ironman triathlon in
Kingston, N.Y., 90 miles north of New York City. The hilly course
in the Catskills featured a 1.2 mile-swim, a 60-mile bike ride and
a 13.1-mile run.
</P>
<P>
   This was not my most sensible idea. I'd swum six times in the
previous six months and only cycled for transportation around town.
``How often are you running?'' queried my friend, a 50-year-old
architect who trains as much as 30 hours a week. ``Twice a week,''
I answered, ``but I have been kayaking a lot!'' ``Sounds like
you're ready!'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Remembering the physiological distress I experienced in my first
triathlon, a month before the race I called Troy Jacobson, a
six-time Ironman and the fourth American finisher in Hawaii in
1997. Jacobson, 29 and a former collegiate football player, coaches
more than 100 clients in 30 states and five countries via the phone
and e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   We talked about my fitness background, allotted exercise time
and goals. ``To see significant changes, I like my athletes to
commit to a four-month program, but we can get you to the finish in
four weeks . . . I think,'' Jacobson said over the phone from
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, I received an e-mail with a custom-built
training schedule divided into day-by-day, sport-by-sport workouts.
``Remember,'' he said, ``let the plan guide you, not control you.''
</P>
<P>
   In normal life one rarely goes for a run right after a long bike
ride, much less a ride and swim. Jacobson's regime was intended to
condition you to do just that. During the week, I usually did two
of the three sports for about two hours in total. For example, on
Wednesday I'd do a 90-minute bike ride, take a 5-minute rest (five
minutes more than in an actual triathlon) and go for a 30-minute
run, a workout created to teach my legs to run with fatigue.
Thursday might include a swim in the morning and a two-hour bike
ride in the evening. Saturdays, the toughest day on the schedule, I
tried to do all three sports. Mercifully, Monday was a day off.
</P>
<P>
   At 7 a.m., on what was already becoming a hot July Saturday,
about 300 people stood on the rocky banks of the placid Hudson
River for the start of the Second Annual Hudson Valley Triathlon.
Waiting anxiously for the gun to sound, I remembered what Jacobson
had told me two days earlier. ``Experience the distance and be
conservative throughout the race,'' he cautioned. ``This is a
super-challenging event on a difficult course. When you feel like
you're overextending yourself, back off.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jacobson, a 6-foot 170-pounder who has about as much body
fat as a greyhound, also told me to stay focused: ``You want to
reach a level of intensity where your mind says slow down and the
body doesn't have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Having logged virtually no pool time prior to the race, I
started slowly and never sped up until I rounded the orange turn
buoy and realized that we'd been bucking a stiff current. When I
hit the beach running, the clock said I'd been in the water for 51
minutes, 16 minutes behind the lead swimmer in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Donning a helmet, cycling shorts and shoes, along with a bike
jersey loaded with packets of carbohydrate gel, I took to the road
to begin the longest leg of the race. To me, cycling is the most
enjoyable of the three sports. Passing slower riders, feeling the
jolt of energy when another cyclist comes whirring by, charging the
hills and pedaling hard down the other side at speeds of 30 and 40
miles an hour, I experienced the same thrill I felt riding my bike
when I was a child.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty miles into the scenic ride, however, my rear sought a
lounge chair and my thighs a masseuse. All I could do was distract
myself, which I did by chatting with an Australian rugby player
turned New York City hair stylist. We averaged 19.7 miles an hour
and roughly three topics of conversation every 10 miles, covering
the 60 miles in 3 hours 2 minutes, 36 minutes slower than the
fastest rider.
</P>
<P>
   Hurrying into my running shoes, I left the transition area side
by side with the hair stylist, both of us looking decidedly
uncoifed. Considering that I'd just spent three hours on a bike, my
legs felt relatively fine, but heading up a nasty hill I had a side
stitch that sent pain through my gut with each step. Two miles into
the run, my companion said, ``No worries, mate!'' and pulled away,
leaving me to continue grimly on.
</P>
<P>
   At the six-mile mark I did what I hate to do in a race: I
walked, albeit for only 30 seconds. Plodding up the short, steep
hills was the worst. Over the last three miles I reminded myself
that the pain, while intense, stops virtually the moment you cross
the finish line. Managing pain is a part of endurance sports,
perhaps even the point.
</P>
<P>
   I completed the half-marathon in 1 hour 47 minutes _ 11 minutes
slower than the overall winner _ and crossed the line in 5 hours 48
minutes: 103rd out of the approximately 300 who started.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, I hobbled around, eating bagels and drinking water
nonstop as a steady stream of competitors rounded the final turn.
One fellow I talked to sounded chagrined even though he finished in
the top 30. ``It was emotionally traumatizing,'' he acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Another chap, who'd placed 76th overall, was beaming. The secret
to his success, he said, was eating raw chopped beef and eggs:
``It's given me the strength and endurance to train and race
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   My architect friend _ who finished four minutes behind me _ met
me near a bowl of sliced oranges, and we discussed what we often
talk about: training, pain and the meaning of it all. When a lean
72-year-old man in a flowered bathing suit crossed the line, we
stopped to applaud. He'd been out there for just over seven hours.
``When you finish the Ironman in Hawaii, you've come close to
realizing your potential,'' said my weary architect friend. ``You
don't often get to do that in everyday life.''
</P>
<P>
   By Land or By Sea
</P>
<P>
   The New York Triathlon Club has staged more than 220 multi-sport
events since 1984. To get a complete listing of its races, write to
Box 467, Mount Marion, N.Y. 12456, or call (914) 247-0271.
MetroSports magazine, which is free at bike shops and gyms, offers
a complete list of races on the East Coast. Call (212) 627-7040 or
e-mail: metrosport(AT)aol.com. To receive personal coaching from
Troy Jacobson call (410) 583-8957 or e-mail: trnrt(AT)aol.com. His
web address is: www.coachtroy.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
