<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CDC survey: ``We are seeing too many kids at risk,''
 &HT;    By J. Matthew Aldag
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- More American teenagers are smoking marijuana - and
at a younger age - than just two years ago, according to a new
youth survey by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, nearly one in five say they have carried a weapon,
driven a vehicle after drinking and considered suicide, the
national survey found.
</P>
<P>
   While most findings released Thursday differed little from a
similar survey conducted two years ago, health experts said the
survey highlights concerns about the incidence of teen automobile
deaths, suicides, tobacco and drug use, as well as dangerous sexual
activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing too many kids at risk,'' said Laura Kann, chief
of the Surveillance Research Section for the CDC. ``Too many kids
practice behaviors that place them at risk for unnecessary
mortality and morbidity,''
</P>
<P>
   Among the findings of the Youth Risk Behavior Surveillance,
which surveyed more than 16,000 U.S. high school students about
their activities in the past 30 days:
</P>
<P>
   -- 50 percent said they had at least one alcoholic drink, and 33
percent had five or more. Black students were significantly less
likely to report consuming alcohol, while alcohol use increased
with age in all ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   -- 17 percent said they had driven after drinking, and 36
percent had been driven by a person who had been drinking.
</P>
<P>
   -- 36 percent reported smoking at least one cigarette, and 16
percent reported smoking on at least 20 of those 30 days. 70
percent reported trying cigarettes, even ``a puff or two.'' White
students were found to be more likely to smoke than blacks or
Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   -- 18 percent said they had carried a weapon such as a gun,
knife or club. Males were more likely than female to carry weapons.
Hispanics and blacks were more likely than whites to carry a gun.
</P>
<P>
   Surveyers, who asked teens at 151 schools nationwide to fill out
confidential questionnaires, also queried students about their
activities in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   It found that during the past 12 months, one in five teens said
they had seriously considered committing suicide, while 15 percent
reported coming up with a specific plan. Female students were
almost twice as likely to say they had contemplated suicide. In
addition, the CDC survey found 37 percent reporting being in a
physical fight, with the highest incidence among males, Hispanics
and blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Other key findings:
</P>
<P>
   -- 48 percent of all students said they had had sex; 16 percent
had four or more partners; and 7 percent had lost their virginity
by age 13. About 43 percent of sexually active teens reported not
using a condom the last time they had sex.
</P>
<P>
   -- 27 percent of students said they felt overweight, and nearly
40 percent were currently trying to lose weight.
</P>
<P>
   -- 19 percent admitted to rarely or never wearing a seat belt.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
