<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Nature is hinting that cool days are approaching
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cool mornings have given us delusions that summer is wearing
down and fall is imminent. I have my grandchildren to keep me
posted about school opening, but I look elsewhere for word on the
end of summer.
</P>
<P>
   As one who brags about Atlanta's weather because it is
constantly changing, I won't be reluctant to see some evidences of
fall. We already have it in those horticultural earlybirds, the
sourwoods. Little bushes on road banks turned red and gold when I
wasn't looking, and the big sourwood trees are laden with
end-of-summer panicles of bloom. (I hope the bees have noticed and
are stocking up for that best of all honeys, the glorious white
gold sourwood.)
</P>
<P>
   But there are summer delights that we all hate to give up. The
hot weather, hated by one and all, at least gave us something to
talk about, and when the rains started, city people were as
relieved and happy as if they had country gardens and fields to
worry about. I saw a woman on a MARTA train who said aloud to her
accompanying daughters, ``Thank God for thunder and lightning.''
</P>
<P>
   A summer thunderstorm, breaking the heat, can be welcome to some
of us. My mother, a fearless woman where most things were
concerned, rated thunder and lightning with snakes, and fled both
when she could. I remember that she hung quilts over the windows,
pulled the switch that controlled electricity in our house, got in
bed, and covered up head and ears. I kind of enjoy the
pyrotechnics, especially if accompanied by rain.
</P>
<P>
   The other morning I was having coffee on my back porch, when I
heard a scratching on the roof. Cats? Birds? Squirrels? It was the
first tentative fingers of a fine, lusty rainstorm.
</P>
<P>
   In no time at all, the scratching had turned to a musical drum
beat and a trickle of icy water descended on my head. I began
pushing chairs around and moving cushions, but it was pointless. A
rainstorm knows my tin roof leaks and makes the most of it, dousing
everything. I don't mind. Sitting on a damp chair with your feet in
a puddle is very cooling.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, all food is to be found at all seasons nowadays, but
I think it appropriate to eat watermelons in summer only. And
blackberry pies ... ah, a summertime specialty. There's another
one, not known to legions of unlucky people _ mayhaw jelly. A
genius named Estella Brown, who lives in Quitman, sent a friend of
mine a case of her mayhaw jelly, and I lucked into a jar.
</P>
<P>
   It is the queen of jellies, made of those elegant little
apple-tasting fruits that grow in marshy places in South Georgia,
Florida and Alabama. I picked them as a child, filling my pockets
and feasting as I walked, but they are best made into jelly. Its
beautiful to look at, gleaming red gold on the pantry shelf _ if
you can put your one and only jar away that long. I keep mine on
the counter within reach when I have hot biscuits.
</P>
<P>
   Figs are one of the bounties of summer. My tree, which I forgot
to prune last fall, is an ungainly, funny-branched specimen, but it
does have a few figs, smallish ones just right for jaybirds to
pick. The fat, opulent ones I remember from my childhood didn't
show this year, and I think I know why. Figs are said to be
sociable trees, which do better when they are close to the house
and can hear song and human conversation. I have been away a lot,
and putting the radio where the tree can follow the Braves' games
may not be sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   A fig tree may be an opera buff instead of a Braves fan. I'll
experiment if summer will linger long enough to give me time.
</P>
<P>
   Celestine Sibley's column appears Mondays, Wednesdays, Fridays
and Sundays in Living.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
