<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-GaFARM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A tasty new cookbook tours Georgia's farms and kitchens
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- t may be the first cookbook to come with its own food source.
</P>
<P>
   When you pick it up, you hear a noise you can't quite put your
finger on. It sounds dry and scratchy, like cat claws on a hardwood
floor or maybe sugar rasping around inside a packet. Opening the
spiral binding, you find the culprit: An envelope of watermelon
seeds glued to the inside back cover, alongside an invitation to
plant them in the good earth of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   What else would you expect of a cookbook from the state
Agriculture Department?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Best of Georgia Farms'' (CI Publishing, $18.95) was
inspired by the recipes that have run for years in the Farmers and
Consumers Market Bulletin, the homey newspaper that the agency
sends free every week to a quarter of a million Georgians. But the
322-page book is more than a statewide recipe swap. It has history,
personality profiles, literary excerpts, itineraries for food tours
like Apple Alley, the Peach Blossom Trail and the rice plantation
ruins of the coast. All that, and half a dozen varieties of seeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to make it participatory: Tour it, grow it, cook it,
eat it,'' says Fred Brown, a native Georgian who co-wrote the book
for the state with Sherri M.L. Smith. (The two recently
collaborated on another beautiful volume, ``The Riverkeeper's Guide
to the Chattahoochee.'') Brown, a longtime guidebook publisher,
caught the agriculture department's eye with a cookbook he did for
the Dillard House restaurant in Rabun County.
</P>
<P>
   The idea this time was to reconnect Georgians with their farming
past and present, the authors explain over a lunch of collards,
black-eyed peas and sweet potatoes at the Atlanta State Farmers
Market. It's easy to overlook, amid the asphalt sprawl of the
capital city, but agriculture remains Georgia's largest industry,
even if relatively few people still live on the farm.
</P>
<P>
   At Cagle's Dairy in Holly Springs, one of the many places the
authors visited, the city children who go for tours sometimes don't
even know where milk comes from, Brown says. ``They think it comes
from the supermarket.''
</P>
<P>
   The book, then, is remedial education for a state increasingly
dominated by its urban islands. Among the highlights:
</P>
<P>
   -- Classified ads from seven decades of the Market Bulletin
appear in the margins, telling the story of Georgia's changing
agriculture. One 1934 ad has the ominous headline: ``Kudzu Plants
Wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Georgia's recent governors are represented with recipes from
Lester Maddox's skillet-fried chicken to Jimmy Carter's microwave
peanuts. The former president reminisces about his boyhood on the
farm, including his favorite chore (pruning watermelon vines) and
least favorite (''mopping'' cotton to kill boll weevils with
arsenic dripped from rag mops). He also contributed a sketch
showing the layout of the Carter farmstead, down to the three-hole
outhouse.
</P>
<P>
   -- Columbus artist Garry Pound illustrated the book with line
drawings of people, places and livestock that appear in color on
fold-out pages, like post cards for the palate.
</P>
<P>
   Lunch finished, the authors head out into the market stalls to
deliver a book to one of Pound's most colorful subjects. Virginia
Debard, a melon-shaped woman who's been selling produce here for
almost 30 years, examines the likeness, grins and pronounces it
``about as big as I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown opens the book to another illustration that shows Debard's
stall with a sign touting ``white dirt, $1'' next to the Vidalia
onions. She's fresh out of it today, but she usually stocks plastic
bags of chalky white kaolin from Washington County. In keeping with
market regulations, she tells customers that it has many uses as a
pigment or stomach settler but is not, strictly speaking, a food.
``They still walk away eating it like ice cream,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted that while ``Georgia Farms'' encourages
people to get reacquainted with the soil, it does not have any
recipes that call for dirt. The seeds, of course, are another
matter.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some favorites recipes from the book.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Sawdust Pie
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings Preparation time: 15 minutes Cooking time:
25-30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Would this seem as interesting if it were called Pecan Meringue
Pie? We think not. Two Bulletin readers, Etta Gore of Walthourville
and Trilba Cordell of Wildwood, sent the recipe in about the same
time 3 1/2 years ago. The name? The pie looks like sawdust when
it's baked.
</P>
<P>
   7egg whites, unbeaten
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2cups graham cracker crumbs
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2cups finely chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2cups flaked coconut
</P>
<P>
   19-inch deep dish unbaked pie shell
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees. In large deep-dish bowl, mix egg
whites, sugar, crumbs, pecans and coconut and stir by hand. Pour
into pie shell and bake for 25 to 30 minutes until glossy and set.
Do not overbake. (It is firm near the edges but moist and chewy in
the center.) Serve warm with sliced bananas and whipped cream.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (without garnish): 542 calories, 8 grams protein, 29
grams fat (percent calories from fat, 48) , 67 grams carbohydrate,
no cholesterol, 270 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Squash Dressing
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings Preparation time: 15 minutes Cooking time: 40
minutes
</P>
<P>
   2cups sliced yellow squash, cooked and drained
</P>
<P>
   2cups crumbled cornbread
</P>
<P>
   110 3/4-ounce can cream of chicken soup
</P>
<P>
   1small onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup melted margarine
</P>
<P>
   3eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon ground sage, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. In a bowl, combine squash,
cornbread, soup, onion, margarine, eggs and sage. Pour into a
greased 8-inch pan. Bake 40 minutes. _ From Mrs. M.F. Eller,
Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 324 calories, 8 grams protein, 23 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 65) , 21 grams carbohydrate, 138
milligrams cholesterol, 872 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Apple and Plum Pork Tenderloin
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 25 minutes Marinading time:
30 minutes-2 hours hours
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   1pound pork tenderloin, cut into 1/4-inch slices
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon water
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon oil
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup chopped celery
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup julienne-sliced red bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup chopped green onions
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup apple cider
</P>
<P>
   1cup cored, sliced cooking apples, unpeeled
</P>
<P>
   1cup pitted, sliced ripe plums, unpeeled
</P>
<P>
   In medium bowl, combine soy sauce, ginger, pepper and pork.
Refrigerate for between 30 minutes and 2 hours. Meanwhile, in a
small bowl, combine brown sugar, cornstarch and water. Heat oil in
large skillet over medium-high heat. Add pork and discard marinade.
Cook pork 5 to 7 minutes or until browned. Add celery, red pepper,
green onions and apple cider. Cover and simmer for 3 minutes. Add
apples, plums and cornstarch mixture. Cook 5 minutes on very low
heat, stirring constantly, until mixture is thickened and fruit is
crisp-tender. _ From the Agriculture Department test kitchen
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 232 calories, 23 grams protein, 5 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 21) , 23 grams carbohydrate, 63
milligrams cholesterol, 313 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Best of Georgia Farms'' is available in stores, or you can
order it from the Agriculture Department by calling 800-282-5852.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
