<HEADER>
A2817 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SINGLE-COX     08-13 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINGLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Book: Single woman are finding out that they do not need a man
 &HT;    By Carolyn Nizzi Warmbold
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ours is a culture steeped in romance. From bodice-ripper novels
to bridal magazines, from kissing couples on the silver screen to
fairy tales that end ``they lived happily ever after,'' the message
is that it's preferable to be a twosome.
</P>
<P>
   The reality, however, is that an increasing number of women are
ending up like Scarlett O'Hara in the closing scene of ``Gone With
the Wind'': Without Rhett. And frankly, my dear, some of them don't
always give a damn.
</P>
<P>
   As Marcelle Clements recognizes in her new book, ``The
Improvised Woman: Single Women Reinventing Single Life'' (Norton,
$26.95), the numbers of single women over 18 in this country are on
the rise: from 38 million in 1990 to nearly 43 million now. Of
those, close to half have never married, and more than 11 million
each are widowed and divorced.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of women (almost 59 million) are married, but,
Clements writes, for every three married women in America two are
single. (Though her study did not cover single men, U.S. Census
Bureau figures show their numbers have risen from 31 million in
1990 to 36 million.)
</P>
<P>
   Stereotypes about single women abound. They have been seen as
man-hungry spinsters, predatory divorcees, or lovelorn working
women who, as Clements puts it, would ``go out looking for Mr.
Right and come home with Mr. Goodbar.''
</P>
<P>
   Clements, however, senses ``that the desperate single belongs to
the past.'' In seven years of interviews conducted with a
``mosaic'' of more than 100 single women _ identified by first name
and last initial _ she found that many choose the single life.
</P>
<P>
   It's not only that there are fewer single men than women, or
that the more educated or prosperous a woman is, the less likely
she is to marry or remarry. Gen-Xers like Ally McBeal want a career
first, divorced women may find they are happier alone or are too
busy raising kids to date, and older women often value their
independence. Like Valentine J., a 94-year-old widow, told
Clements: ``if a woman meets someone and she's older _ 60, say _ I
think she should have an affair. Not tie herself down to
marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   Some unattached women, to quote Daphne Merkin in a recent New
Yorker article about Clements' book and the popular novel ``Bridget
Jones's Diary'', may have ``a primal female fear of ending up
manless and alone.'' But most of Clements' subjects were more
ambivalent about the solitary life. Some day their prince may come.
Or he may not.
</P>
<P>
   Clements, 50 and single, discovered she preferred living alone
to going through another nasty breakup after she ended a long
relationship. Like many of her subjects, she didn't rule men out of
her life, but she wasn't looking either.
</P>
<P>
   The journalist, critic and essayist noticed similar attitudes
among friends and decided to write a book. ``The Improvised Woman''
details her findings and comments from women about romance, family,
home, money, careers and old age, and touches on a spectrum of
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Billiana M. remarks that ``I was lonely in my marriage, and I
would prefer to be lonely alone.'' Many worry about financial
security in old age or ending up as bag ladies. For some, sexual
encounters have become regretfully rarer over time.
</P>
<P>
   Clements' most tantalizing conclusions have to do with politics
and the economy. ``The change in the status and psyche of single
women from Cosmo icon to powerful sociocultural player is one of
the most significant trends of the end of the American century,''
she writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still fixated on the fact that women earn only 70
percent of what men do,'' she says. But that's often enough to
attract advertisers. Single women travel and buy jewelry, stereos
and cars, and nearly 54 percent who live alone own their own homes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she admits that ``single women have no collective sense
of being a pivotal social force'' and characterize their decisions
as personal. That may be because their lives and needs are so
diverse.
</P>
<P>
   William H. Frey, a University of Michigan demographer, agrees
that the single-women factor is important in advertising, but
believes that marketers will want to differentiate.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of public attention, he says, has been focused on the
young single once represented by Mary Tyler Moore, and now by Ally
McBeal, with disposable income and lavish tastes. But with baby
boomers growing older, and women having greater life expectancies
than men, ``this older group will be an increasing force for
marketers, advertisers and politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, lonely singles may find little consolation in being
powerful sociocultural players and agree with Clements' married
friends who called the topic ``such a sad story.'' To be sure,
there's ambivalence among the women themselves. ``How would I feel
if Anna turned out to be single?'' muses the divorced Felicia C.
about her 11-year-old daughter. ``Sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Clements found a buoyancy in her subjects and ``a sense of
hope and adventure even among the women who were scared.''
</P>
<P>
   And most seemed generally satisfied with their solitude.
Billiana M., noting that ``sometimes we're on the light side, and
sometimes we're on the dark side,'' admits remarriage is possible.
``But it would have to offer me something that's far better than
this,'' she says, ``and this is so damn good.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
