<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2830 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARS-COLLECTING-NYT &LR;      08-13 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-COLLECTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAR COLLECTING: AT TOP SHOWS, AS GOOD AS NEW ISN'T NEARLY GOOD
ENOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
  (duplication warning: also sent with `f' code) 
(bl) 
 By MICHAEL LAMM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ Columnist Ellen Goodman once wrote that
some contestants in the Miss America Pageant owed their beauty not
to their Maker, but to their remaker: Miss Florida's nose came
courtesy of her surgeon. So did Miss Alaska's. Miss Oregon's
breasts came from silicone.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the stunning automobiles that win top honors at
high-profile collector shows _ like the Pebble Beach Concours
d'Elegance here Sunday _ owe their beauty not so much to the
companies that manufactured them, but to the well-heeled collectors
who have had the cars essentially remanufactured. Most of the cars
have been restored not to their original factory condition, but to
a level of perfection considerably above that. They are far better
than they were when new.
</P>
<P>
   This overrestoration of vintage cars is no secret. It has been
done for years, and since the 1970s it has virtually become a
requirement for car owners intent on winning trophies. Concours
judging has become a serious matter as the value of collector cars
has risen in the last two decades. But overrestoration is a
peculiarly American practice, since Europeans readily accept cars
that show the wear of regular use.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to define ``restoration,'' as the term is applied to
vintage automobiles, though it may include the refinishing of a
car's body and chassis, the rebuilding of any or all mechnical
parts and the refurbishing of the interior. Overrestoration is even
more difficult to pin down.
</P>
<P>
   But Jay Heumann, who has served for decades as co-chairman of
the Pebble Beach Concours, acknowledges that concours-level cars
are overrestored today. He suggests that the trend began around
1975, in large part because of a rivalry between two prominent
collectors, J.B. Nethercutt, a cosmetics executive, and the late
Bill Harrah, who built the Harrah's casino company.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Harrah owned one of the world's largest collections
of vintage cars, some 1,400, many of which were publicly displayed
in Nevada. Nethercutt, the chairman of Merle Norman Cosmetics, also
owned (and still owns) one of the world's finest and most valuable
car collections, including the ``20 Grand'' Duesenberg. (Its name
derived from the considerable sum it cost when new in 1933.) Since
both employed staffs of full-time restorers and personally oversaw
the restoration work, they vied to outdo each other on the judging
field. This led to restoring cars to an ideal _ ``perfection,''
Heumann calls it _ rather than to authentic, original condition.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, restorers tried to bring cars back to the condition
they were in when they left the factory. In the cases of
custom-bodied Duesenbergs, Pierce-Arrows and 16-cylinder Cadillacs,
few people really knew what the original condition was like, so
Harrah and Nethercutt could go to extremes without raising
eyebrows.
</P>
<P>
   But in seeking cosmetic and sometimes mechanical perfection, the
two rivals set the standard for all auto restorations. Professional
restorers who did not meet or beat Harrah's gold-star standards
were unlikely to win trophies. And as time went on, the standards
moved higher and higher.
</P>
<P>
   Heumann points out that in the close-knit community of old-car
aficionados, competition is driven by an inseparable mix of money
and ego. Winning not only makes a car more valuable, but gives the
owner _ and his restoration shop _ bragging rights and an edge in
future competitions.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Ema, a restorer and historian of Duesenbergs, Cords and
Auburns in Orange, Calif., said, ``If we were to take a brand-new
classic off the showroom floor'' and judge it in a concours, ``we
would probably give it between 85 and 90 points today.'' With
restoration standards as moving targets, cars that received 100
points in judging 10 years ago might get 95 points today.
</P>
<P>
   Overrestoration is fairly easy to spot. Carl Steig, the national
head judge of the Classic Car Club of America, said that flawlessly
painted or powder-coated frames and axles were now nearly
universal. Stamping and draw marks on mechanical components are
filled in and hidden under a mirror-like finish. Frames and axles
were not that well finished at the factory, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other common examples of overrestoration include smooth,
polished engine blocks that originally had textured surfaces and
minor flaws as a result of being cast in sand. Nuts and water
jackets are often chrome-plated, and wood screws are turned so that
the slots in the screw heads line up perfectly. The seams and
piping of upholstery are perfectly straight. Modern acrylic
urethane paints and clear-coat finishes give a smoother, wetter,
more plastic look than the varnishes and nitro-cellulose lacquers
of yesteryear, which are not now widely used because of
environmental regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Moser, chairman of the master judging committee of the Model
A Ford Club of America, said it was often easier to overrestore a
car than to bring it back to showroom condition. That is because it
is harder to find out how the car actually looked when it left the
factory than to simply make every detail as perfect as humanly
possible. Not only is good, honest research hard work, but an
authentic restoration, as opposed to an idealized one, might not be
as impressive to the car's owner or the concours judge.
</P>
<P>
   Several national clubs have established classes for original
automobiles _ that is, cars that have not been restored or have
perhaps been restored minimally. The Porsche Club of America and
the Ferrari Club of America now have preservation classes for
original cars. In these, cars with faded paint or slightly tatty
upholstery are judged separately from those with all-out
restorations. The problem, though, is that it is often difficult to
tell what is original, what was restored years ago and what the
owner has touched up recently.
</P>
<P>
   Although most major concours and car clubs do not deduct points
for overrestoration, the Model A Ford Club of America does. That
club has amassed a huge body of photos and other materials that
show what Fords looked like during and just after assembly. Paint
runs were common. Tacking strips used for attaching soft pieces
like fabric tops sometimes contained bent tacks.
</P>
<P>
   And when Ford upholsterers sewed 1,000 sets of seats a day,
seams went every which way. So at least with Model A's, the cars
that are judged closest to perfect are those that fall far short of
perfection, as the club's hefty book of judging standards spells
out.
</P>
<P>
   So far, though, deducting points for overrestorations is rare.
Several years ago, a collector discovered an unrestored Duesenberg
Model J with its engine compartment untouched and totally original.
Suddenly, everyone realized just how overrestored most Duesenberg
engines had become. But the time and money had already been
invested in these beautiful classics, so there was little chance
that the clock could be turned back and standards would be lowered.
</P>
<P>
   It is that momentum _ that resistance to back-pedaling _ that
keeps restoration standards chugging ever upward. And the most
idealized restoration usually does win.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 1827EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0276 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2832 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARS-COLLECTING-NYT &LR;      08-13 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-COLLECTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAR COLLECTING: AT TOP SHOWS, AS GOOD AS NEW ISN'T NEARLY GOOD
ENOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
  (duplication warning: also sent with `a' code) 
(bl) 
 By MICHAEL LAMM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
