<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUBON-LOSS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPING TO STEM LOSSES, AU BON PAIN TO SPLIT, SELL CAFE CHAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Au Bon Pain Co. plans to split into two companies and
sell its Au Bon Pain chain of 263 cafes to a New York investment
firm for about $78 million.
</P>
<P>
   The move would allow the publicly traded company to focus on its
fast-growing suburban division, whose cafes operate under the names
St. Louis Bread and Panera Bread. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   On completion of the transaction, the company- owned restaurants
and franchise business that go by the Au Bon Pain name would be
sold to Bruckmann, Rosser, Sherrill &AMP; Co., a private investment
firm.
</P>
<P>
   Plans call for the St. Louis Bread division to continue to
operate as a publicly traded company under the leadership of
co-chairman and chief executive Ron Shaich, who said he will unveil
a new name for the company at a later date.
</P>
<P>
   Au Bon Pain cafes tend to be located in densely crowded urban
business disticts; they are designed to rapidly serve sandwiches
and baked goods to customers pressed for time. Many of the cafes
see a big falloff in business on the weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Acquired in 1993, St. Louis Bread is a seven-day-a-week
operation aimed at suburbanites. With a similar but slightly
pricier menu than Au Bon Pain, the St. Louis Bread chain, with
shops in the Northeast and Midwest, strives for an atmosphere that
encourages customers to linger.
</P>
<P>
   While St. Louis Bread has shown great potential for rapid
growth, sales at Au Bon Pain cafes have been ``stagnant,'' said Kim
Galle, an analyst with Adams Harkness &AMP; Hill.
</P>
<P>
   According to Shaich, both Au Bon Pain restaurants and St. Louis
Bread will benefit from the proposed sale.
</P>
<P>
   Under its new owner, Au Bon Pain restaurants will get capital
for the extensive remodeling needed to boost sales.
</P>
<P>
   And as a stand-alone company no longer overshadowed by Au Bon
Pain, St. Louis Bread's ``extraordinary growth story will be
exposed to investors,'' Shaich said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very positive development,'' Galle said.
</P>
<P>
   Shaich said cash from the sale will be used to pay down the
publicly traded company's debt of about $55 million and rapidly
expand the St. Louis Bread division.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few years, franchisees have committed to open
about 450 of these stores, Shaich said; by the end of the year,
there should be 129 stores in the St. Louis Bread division.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Given Au Bon Pain's problems, it was unlikely that there were
many interested buyers, Galle said. Under the circumstances, $78
million seemed to be a reasonable price, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shaich's company said it expects to record a loss of about $20
million on completing the transaction in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking St. Louis Bread away from Au Bon Pain will end a
17-year partnership between Shaich and his co-chairman Louis Kane.
</P>
<P>
   Kane will join the company that Bruckmann, Rosser plans to form
to run the Au Bon Pain restaurant division.
</P>
<P>
   Of his parting with Kane, Shaich said: ``This isn't a
personality story at all. We love each other. We're sad to do this.
But we think this is the best strategy to allow two very different
businesses in very different places in their growth cycles to
really fulfill their destinies.''
</P>
<P>
   Mostly a morning business when it first opened in the early
1980s, Au Bon Pain later expanded its menu to include lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost a sandwich shop now,'' said Ron Paul, president of
Technomic Inc., a restaurant consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Because of intense competition, Paul added, ``It's very
difficult to make money in the sandwich business.''
</P>
<P>
   There are fewer players in the niche occupied by St. Louis
Bread, though that may soon change, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A call to Bruckmann, Rosser was not returned. According to
published reports, the firm owns large interests in the California
Pizza chain and a medical equipment company.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Au Bon Pain reported that it lost $779,381 in the
second quarter on revenues of $53.9 million. For the same quarter a
year ago, Au Bon Pain lost $165,605 on revenues of $54.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   On Nasdaq, shares of Au Bon Pain closed at 8 3/8, down 3/8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
