<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOORAY FOR SENIORITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HILTON HEAD, S.C. _ Here in the lush, sunny Palmetto State,
voters understand the local benefits that can result from the
institutional memory, political savvy and sharp elbows that come
with congressional seniority.
</P>
<P>
   Term limits? Forget it.
</P>
<P>
   Residents joke that they are blessed to be served in Washington
by living legends _ ``one is a legend; the other is living.''
</P>
<P>
   The incomparable Republican Sen. Strom Thurmond is in his eighth
term, making him the longest-serving senator in history, the oldest
person ever to serve in Congress, chairman of the powerful Armed
Services Committee and fourth in line for the presidency. Now 95,
he functions slowly these days but looks forward to turning 100 one
month before he finally retires in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest ``Fritz'' Hollings, the longest-serving junior senator in
history, is a relatively jaunty 76 after 32 years in office during
which he rose to become senior ranking Democrat on the Commerce
Committee (he was chairman until the GOP seized control of the
Senate.) He is up for re-election this fall and is generally
considered one of the four most vulnerable Democratic incumbents.
</P>
<P>
   Pollsters report that the race between five-term Hollings and
three-term GOP Rep. Bob Inglis is tight, with Hollings dependent on
a strong black voter turnout because Inglis leads Hollings among
white voters. Inglis is making an aggressive pitch for black
voters, but they were still 78 percent for Hollings in an
independent May poll.
</P>
<P>
   An informal survey of a dozen participants at a recent South
Carolina Association of Counties conference here, however, suggests
that Hollings' seniority and long record of constituent service
will ultimately carry the day for him.
</P>
<P>
   Those interviewed unanimously predicted he would win, although
several said they were Republicans who would not vote for him.
Unlike Thurmond, who switched parties in 1964, Hollings has
remained a conservative Democrat even though South Carolina has
increasingly become a Republican bastion.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the county officials were reflecting a national mood that
seems disinclined to upset any political boats this year. Maybe
they simply like Hollings, whose conduct and voting record they
have observed up close for three decades. Maybe they are so
accustomed to Hollings' presence in Washington they can't imagine
any other.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, they did not indicate any feeling that Hollings has
gotten old and stale, a sentiment that would be greatly to Inglis'
advantage if it were widespread.
</P>
<P>
   Many county officials said Inglis should wait his turn and is
really running against Hollings to build statewide name
identification for a run in four years for the empty Thurmond seat.
</P>
<P>
   Inglis has a problem. He was elected to the House as a crusader
for term limits. If he wins the Senate seat and applies to himself
the automatically curtailed service he demands of others, he will
never accumulate the internal power that comes with lengthy
seniority and to which South Carolinians have become accustomed.
Inglis supports the notion that 12 years, or two terms, is the
longest that senators should be allowed to serve.
</P>
<P>
   Inglis, 38, is leaving the House after serving out a
self-imposed six-year term limit.
</P>
<P>
   Hollings has called Inglis ``totally hypocritical (because) he
campaigned last election for both term limits and Sen. Strom
Thurmond.''
</P>
<P>
   Inglis replied feebly that Thurmond deserved an exception from
the rule because he is ``really different from most long-term
incumbents.'' This difference is not readily apparent, except for
the fact that Thurmond is older.
</P>
<P>
   The term limits issue looked like a winner for Inglis when he
took it up six years ago. But it is no longer popular, even with
House Republicans, who made it part of their ``Contract with
America'' in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP-controlled House has twice rejected a constitutional
amendment to limit members' terms. The Supreme Court has ruled that
qualifications for Congress must be uniform across the nation and
therefore can be set only by a constitutional amendment.
</P>
<P>
   The argument for term limits was based on a foolish premise that
experience automatically leads to arrogance and long incumbency
automatically leads to isolation and corruption. The rallying cry
was ``fresh thinking.'' It assumed that unseasoned legislative
judgments are necessarily the best judgments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ticking of the clock has a way of focusing the mind,''
Inglis once said. How useful this is for the national good is
questionable. What Inglis' mind focused on was how to get Hollings'
job after Inglis was forced to give up his own.
</P>
<P>
   Like many members who limited their service in advance, Inglis
was not groomed for the Senate's internal leadership structure or
assigned to the most powerful committees, where stability and
experience are important. Party leaders didn't bother with him
because he wasn't going to be around long enough to learn the
ropes. Six years are simply not enough to figure out how to make a
mark in that high-pressure, competitive environment.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Inglis languished on the unpopular budget committee and
the judiciary committee, which may have its moment in the sun if
there are impeachment hearings against President Clinton but is
otherwise usually a political backwater.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 1840EDT &QL; 
