<HEADLINE>
AUTO INSURERS TO SEEK 15.5 PERCENT INCREASE FOR '99 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Barring some last-minute change of heart, the state's
auto insurance industry is preparing to seek a 15.5 percent
increase in rates for next year.
</P>
<P>
   While the industry almost always asks for a much bigger rate
increase than it receives, the size of the request this year is a
strong signal that companies believe current rates are well below
the level needed to turn a fair profit.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Rinehimer, president of Premier Insurance Co. in Worcester,
said the rate needs of the past four years do not go away just
because the insurance commissioner has imposed rate cuts. ``You
have to keep going back and asking for what you need,'' he said.
Last year, the state approved an average 4 percent cut in rates
after the industry had sought an increase.
</P>
<P>
   Rinehimer said most companies have offered discounts to good
drivers and groups off of state-set rates by drawing on their
reserves. He said many companies have been forced to discount to
retain customers.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Scott Harshbarger, who will make his rate
recommendation to the state insurance commissioner later this year,
said he could not imagine how the industry could justify such a
large increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fight this battle every year on behalf of Massachusetts
motorists,'' he said. ``The industry comes in with a high request,
my experts examine it thoroughly, cut out the fat and come up with
a recommendation that is fair.''
</P>
<P>
   The Automobile Insurers Bureau declined comment on its rate
request until the official filing is made today, but industry
sources said the 15.5 percent figure has been backed by the
actuarial committee and by the governing committee.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance commissioner will set rates in December based on
input from the industry, Harshbarger, and the State Rating Bureau,
an agency within the Division of Insurance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
