<SLUG> BC-QUAKER-FABRICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUAKER FABRICS TO BUILD NEW FALL RIVER PLANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHANA R. SCHOENBERGER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Upholstery maker Quaker Fabrics Corp. said Thursday it would
build a new factory in its hometown of Fall River, which offered
tax incentives and other benefits to seal the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The company hopes to break ground on the facility, to be located
on 25 acres Quaker purchased this week in southeast Fall River, in
nine to twelve months, president and chief executive Larry Liebenow
said. Quaker will then expand the manufacturing and distribution
center as needed over the next several years.
</P>
<P>
   Liebenow declined to disclose the purchase price of the land,
which he said is still under negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   As the factory comes on line, Quaker plans to add 700 to 800
manufacturing and management jobs on the site, hiring mainly Fall
River residents, Liebenow said. The company currently employs 2,400
workers, making it the largest employer of Fall River's
38,000-member labor force, according to Mayor Edward M. Lambert Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The promise of new jobs is good news for Fall River, a onetime
textile town now short on employers. Lambert had staked his plans
for economic revitalization on the Gay Head tribe's proposal to
operate a high-stakes bingo hall in town. Although the tribe said
the facility would generate 1,000 new jobs, the Fall River city
council rejected the project in April, saying gambling would be bad
for the city.
</P>
<P>
   Quaker needs more manufacturing space because the company, which
makes yarn and fabric for furniture, has been steadily expanding
its market share both at home and abroad. Liebenow estimates
Quaker's share of the ``jacquard'' fabric market at 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The company hopes to expand further in markets such as Canada,
Mexico, and Europe, Liebenow said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're confident we can continue growing the business both here
and internationally,'' Liebenow said. ``That's why we're working on
the capacity side of it.''
</P>
<P>
   To entice Quaker to build the plant in Fall River, where it
already has 1.5 million feet of factory space, the municipal
government is currently working on a tax incentive package.
</P>
<P>
   The city also promised to spend about $750,000 on
infrastructural improvements, including roads and sewer systems,
Lambert said. State economic development officials will likely kick
in some of the money for the construction, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The industrial-zoned land is currently undeveloped, Liebenow
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lambert said the city will reap multiple benefits from the
Quaker factory, the company's sixth plant in Fall River.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very significant announcement for us,'' Lambert said.
``Quaker is a very good employer.''
</P>
<P>
   Quaker's stock closed at 10 5/8, up 1/8, after earlier hitting a
52-week low of 9 3/4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
