<SLUG> BC-CANCER-ONCOLOGISTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLDER BREAST CANCER PATIENTS RELYING ON ONCOLOGISTS' WORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nearly all older women with breast cancer find information on
cancer care from their oncologists helpful. A sizable proportion,
meanwhile, find their primary care doctor to be among the least
informative sources on that topic, according to a new Boston study.
</P>
<P>
   That finding has implications as primary care doctors are being
asked to serve as managed-care gatekeepers and follow-up providers,
according to the researchers from Boston Medical Center, New
England Medical Center and the Everett, Mass. research firm DM-STAT
</P>
<P>
   ``As our nation moves toward models of care that increasingly
rely on primary care physicians, these front-line physicians will
need to have access to up-to-date, high-quality information
regarding cancer care appropriate for different subsets of
patients,'' say the authors in an article in the latest issue of
the journal Cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The finding is also troubling because older women are more
likely to have long-standing relationships with their primary care
doctor _ and are thus probably more reliant on them _ than with
their oncologist, according to the study led by Dr. Rebecca A.
Silliman of the geriatrics section of Boston Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   The study, based on interviews with 300 women from the Boston
area, most of whom are white and well-educated, aims to better
describe the factors affecting older women's breast cancer care.
</P>
<P>
   About 60 percent of breast cancers are diagnosed in women age 60
and older, but earlier studies have found that older women are at
greater risk of getting less than definitive care, compared with
younger women, according to the new study.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to assessing women's observations about the quality
of information from physicians and other sources, the researchers
looked at social factors affecting the women's emotional health and
their ability to cope with treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Paralleling findings in other studies, the report found that
women who are widowed or who have never married, or who do not have
social supports through church or other activities, may be less
emotionally equipped to deal with breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Physicians may be able to help overcome some of those obstacles
to recovery, however, through better communication with their
patients, according to the study.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physicians may need to work harder to involve their older
patients in care decisions than their younger patients,
particularly those who have additional insecurities regarding their
own communication skills and those who lack social support,'' the
researchers write.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
