<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0290 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2869 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILTON-PAY-2NDTAKE-KA     08-13 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILTON-PAY-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ the Port Authority.
</P>
<P>
   According to a chronology contained in the agreement between
Hilton and the government, the Port Authority selected Hilton over
the Boyd Group and the Promus Corp. in January 1993. In late
January or early February of that year, Anderson met with a Hilton
official at a local restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The official was not named by authorities Wednesday because he
was not charged, and Hill said no further proceedings were
expected.
</P>
<P>
   The chronology states that the Hilton official ``thanked
Anderson for his help in obtaining the Kansas City project, told
Anderson that Hilton rewards its friend, and asked Anderson what he
personally wanted from Hilton in return for his support.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement continues, ``Anderson replied that he wanted
Hilton to fund a seminar//fashion tour to be conducted in
conjunction with the Black Expo Tour,'' a trade show in which
Anderson organized the Kansas City stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``They then agreed on a sum of $1 million to be paid by
Hilton,'' the agreement states. ``Anderson understood that his vote
had been `financially secured' by HHC (Hilton) for future
developments.''
</P>
<P>
   In February, Hilton later agreed to fund a ``social/minority
grant'' for five years, at $250,000 a year. The Hilton employee
``explained to Anderson that a lump sum payment of $1 million was
not possible at that time.''
</P>
<P>
   In March 1993, the Hilton employee resigned. But ``before
leaving,'' the agreement states, ``he conveyed Hilton's commitment
to fund the seminar//fashion show to an employee of HKCC
(Hilton).'' Anderson also spoke to other Hilton officials about the
grant, the agreement states, including Hilton Hotels' president and
chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although there is no evidence that (Hilton) employees were
aware of a specific quid pro quo,'' the agreement states, ``all of
these individuals agreed to honor the commitment and accede to
Anderson's request.''
</P>
<P>
   Hilton announced the grant to Perspectives in July 1993, and
sent the check in August. Because the payment came after Anderson's
vote on awarding the casino to Hilton, Hill termed it a reward
rather than a bribe, and said Anderson ``was paid to influence his
future support as Port Authority chairman.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill said prosecutors didn't pursue individual Hilton employees
because none of them individually benefited from the arrangement
and because none of them still work for Hilton. Some of the
employees resigned after the payment became known, and others
resigned during the gaming commission hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Though no Hilton officials were charged, Hill said, ``I think
it's a fair inference that they knew what was going on. They knew
what was intended to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradshaw, Hilton's lawyer, said Hilton officials ``had no
knowledge it was a bribe or illegal payment....We don't believe the
company is guilty of anything.''
</P>
<P>
   After Anderson denied any illicit dealing at the commission's
hearing in October 1996, the casino was granted a license.
</P>
<P>
   But last year, Anderson was convicted of bribing former Jackson
County Legislator James Tindall and Kansas City Councilwoman D.
Jeanne Robinson. He then decided to cooperate with investigators in
hopes of reducing his potential prison sentence of six to seven
years.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Hilton's total payment of $655,000 was not a
fine. Steve Taylor, executive director of Casino Watch, a Missouri
anti-gambling group, called Hilton's payment ``chump change.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like they're soft-pedaling around,'' he said. ``To
use the job issue as an excuse not to prosecute is ludicrous.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said the payments give ``the gambling industry a bad
name.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement between Hilton and the government will not have
any immediate effect on Hilton's casinos in Atlantic City, New
Jersey or New Orleans, though officials said they were still
considering action.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Furlong, spokesman for the New Jersey Division of Gaming
Enforcement, said officials in his state have been closely
following the situation in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will want to study the agreement to see if any action is
appropriate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana gaming officials hadn't heard about the agreement
Wednesday, and weren't sure what if any effect it might have on the
Hilton casino in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're constantly reviewing the suitability of license holders,
and this is something that could come up in a suitability
hearing,'' said Denise Bottcher, spokeswoman for the Louisiana
Attorney General's Office.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Nevada Gaming Control Board did not return a
phone call seeking comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
