<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: RUSSIA'S CONTINUING ECONOMIC TREMORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also RUSSIA-ECON and RUSSIA-MARKETPLACE) 
(js) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ There is something about Russia's financial crises that
won't quit, no matter how much money is thrown at them, no matter
how hard the government tries to do what its creditors expect.
</P>
<P>
   Less than one month after the International Monetary Fund
promised a package of $22.6 billion in loans and credit to rescue
the ruble from the brink, a new wave of panic has set in, sending
shivers through the little that is left of Moscow's shattered
financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   Once again the air is filled with talk about devaluation and
default _ two options that could destroy investor confidence,
unleash a new round of inflation and rob Russia of its fragile
political stability.
</P>
<P>
   What went wrong? Was the IMF package too little too late, as
some have argued? Have the government's revenue-raising and
belt-tightening efforts proved too feeble? Or with world markets in
turmoil and oil prices falling, was the timing of this summer's
crisis just bad luck?
</P>
<P>
   On one thing most analysts are now agreed: Faith in the current
value of the ruble, now 6.3 to the dollar and slipping, has been
shattered. Foreign investors have already fled the Russian market,
those Russians with savings are keeping them mostly in their
mattresses or abroad and now Russian banks are running out of money
to repay loans that are backed by fast-folding government bonds.
</P>
<P>
   An ill-timed and vaguely worded announcement on Wednesday night
by a deputy director of the Central Bank, limiting access of some
banks to foreign currencies, was the final straw.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the kind of vague statement that sets off panic,'' said
Anders Aslund, senior associate at the Carnegie Endowment in
Washington. ``Hearing that, anybody with any sense would pick up
their rubles and trade them for dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   A breakdown in the banking sector in the last week was the
second shoe to drop as the government moved to tighten its fiscal
and monetary policy. Even before the summer, many banks were
running short of cash, reverting to a risky game of using
high-interest government bonds as collateral for loans from foreign
lenders. As the bonds lost value, lenders demanded more collateral,
which some banks here could not provide. The Russian bankers,
fearing a devaluation, began to buy dollars at an increasingly
frantic rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that there are a lot of banks that are hitting
the wall,'' said Tom Adshead, director of research at the
Moscow-based United Financial. ``It is all about liquidity. If I
borrow from people, I have to have enough cash on hand to pay them
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IMF did solve the problems with the government. What
nobody realized was that waiting behind the corner was this banking
system with terrific problems as well. It is as if they dodged the
left hook but then ran straight into the right hook.''
</P>
<P>
   Another spark to the panic was a letter by George Soros, the
international financier, who has come to Russia's aid in the past.
The letter, which was published in The Financial Times of London on
Thursday, called for a controlled devaluation of the ruble, backed
up by another injection of $15 million in aid.
</P>
<P>
   Soros, in a telephone interview from Long Island, said his
letter was a response to the quickening financial turmoil, not _ as
some in Russia suggested _ because of his own financial interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no intention of selling any rubles short,'' he said,
referring to a market maneuver that would make money if the ruble
weakened further. ``The reason I wrote the letter was to issue a
wake-up call'' to major potential donors, he said. ``While the
Russian government is doing everything in its power to deal with
the situation, they can not do any more without help from abroad.''
</P>
<P>
   Soros said the newest crisis was a result of two conflicting
problems: ``You have the budget crisis and you have the banking
crisis,'' he said. ``To deal with the budget crisis, you need very
tight fiscal and monetary policies. To deal with the banking
crisis, you need liquidity. You need a lender of last resort and in
this case, the Russian government does not have the resources.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Soros' proposal, which he said is ``under discussion'' in
Moscow and abroad, a currency board would fix the value of the
ruble to a foreign currency and strictly limit the issuance of new
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The currency board, by providing additional funds to the
Russian government, would enable the government to meet its
obligations,'' he explained. ``It would also impose strict
discipline, which would re-establish confidence in the ruble.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts doubt whether either the government or the Central
Bank will ever relinquish control over monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
   But Deputy Finance Minister Oleg Vyugin on Thursday defended
Soros' proposal. ``Devaluation is an idea which should be
considered only in a package,'' Vyugin said. `` Soros did not call
for devaluation as such.''
</P>
<P>
   So far the edge of panic on the markets has not spread to the
street, and news reports on Russian television Thursday night were
reassuring. But as the situation sours, more analysts are saying
that either a devaluation, or a freeze on new government bonds, or
both, becomes more likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a devaluation is inevitable unless there is another
intervention from the West, which is unlikely,'' said Al Breach, an
economist at the Russian-European Center for Economic Policy. ``But
the problem now is capital, and you are not going to solve the
capital problem by devaluing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the IMF package, the markets were in total crisis,'' he
said. ``Then after the IMF package, investors went from being
fearful to being greedy, and wanted to get all their money out. But
you can't get blood out of a stone, and you can't run an economy
with interest rates of 50 percent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
