r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILTON-PAY-2TAKES-KAN     08-13 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILTON-PAY-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILTON AGREES TO PAY $500,000 TO AVOID CRIMINAL CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM JACKMAN  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The owners of the Hilton Flamingo casino
agreed Wednesday to pay the government $500,000 to avoid criminal
charges that a Hilton executive rewarded a local official for his
support for the casino.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with Hilton Hotels Corp. said the agreement was
unprecedented in its history, but was not an admission of guilt.
Nevertheless, Missouri state gaming regulators say they will review
the agreement to determine the company's suitability to operate the
Flamingo.
</P>
<P>
   The owners, two Hilton subsidiaries, Hilton Gaming Corp. and
Hilton Kansas City Corp., also agreed to pay another $155,000 as
the costs of the federal investigation and set up an internal
training program to educate employees about how to respond to
public officials seeking money.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the public official was then-Port Authority
Chairman Elbert L. Anderson. The agreement said that in 1993,
Anderson arranged for Hilton to make a $250,000 grant to K.C.
Perspectives. The company was owned by Anderson's business
associate and lover, Michelle Lathan.
</P>
<P>
   The Hilton employee who worked out the agreement with Anderson
is no longer with the company.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors revealed Wednesday that Hilton agreed to make four
more similar payments to Lathan's company, totaling $1.25 million.
Those payments were never made, prosecutors said, because Lathan's
company collapsed amid the unrelated bribery investigation that
later snared her and Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Stephen L. Hill Jr. said the potential impact of
an indictment on Hilton employees nationwide was a major
consideration in his decision not to seek criminal charges against
Hilton.
</P>
<P>
   If Hilton were convicted of criminal charges, Hill said, gaming
authorities in the states where Hilton has casinos would likely
move to shut down Hilton's casinos, throwing thousands of employees
out of work nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Missouri gaming officials said Wednesday they would
reopen hearings into Hilton's Kansas City casino. Acting Executive
Director Mel Fisher said, ``We'd certainly be interested to know
what the (federal) grand jury testimony is,'' and that the
commission would move ``as promptly as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill said he would ask a federal judge to provide recent grand
jury testimony to the Missouri Gaming Commission. He would not say
who gave that testimony or what was said.
</P>
<P>
   Gaming officials in New Jersey and Louisiana said they would
consider reviewing the licenses.
</P>
<P>
   The man at the center of the investigation was Anderson, who
testified twice before federal grand juries in recent weeks. After
that testimony, negotiations began in earnest between prosecutors
and Hilton's lawyers, resulting in the deal unveiled Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said another reason he agreed to the deal, rather than seek
criminal charges, was that the money paid by Hilton was
``comparable if not greater than what a court could legally impose
after a conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors termed the settlement a pre-trial diversion
agreement, in which the government agrees to defer prosecution if a
defendant abides by certain conditions. The two subsidiaries
entered into the agreement. Hill said his office had entered
similar agreements with corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Hilton lawyer Thomas Gallagher said Hilton had never entered
such an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Hilton officials clearly were happy with the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pleased,'' said Jean Paul Bradshaw, a local attorney
representing Hilton. ``We feel like it is a better resolution than
some sort of criminal proceedings, because we don't think that was
merited.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradshaw said the Missouri Gaming Commission's declaration of
renewed hearings ``doesn't surprise us, because we've kept the
gaming commission here and in other jurisdictions aware of what was
going on. We gave them a copy of the agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, when the Missouri commission was deciding whether to
issue a license to the Flamingo, it conducted hearings at which
Anderson testified. He said Hilton's $250,000 payment to K.C.
Perspectives was legitimate and not intended to influence him as
head of the Port Authority. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
