<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-ECONOMY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTMENT CAMP GIVES YOUNGSTERS UP-CLOSE LOOK AT ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK DAVIS  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Management and labor leaders of a major car
maker squared off in Kansas City on Wednesday morning. The urgent
talks led to a last-minute contract offer that won support from
union negotiators and the roomful of workers who attended. The vote
averted a strike by 80,000 employees of Specific Motors Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The tense session might have seemed real, except that hardly
anyone there was old enough to get a driver's license. They were
children, taking part in the Bull &AMP; Bear Investment Camp at the
Bruce R. Watkins Cultural Heritage Center.
</P>
<P>
   The camp is a weeklong clinic on the economy, business and
investing conducted by Douglas Coe, president of Moody Reid Inc., a
brokerage firm in Kansas City. Coe's camp, in its fifth summer,
includes a mock stock market, role-playing sessions like the
labor-management talks, team and individual competitions for
``Douglas dollars,'' and a camp-ending auction in which students
bid against each other with their winnings.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's auction includes a Sony PlayStation, 35mm camera, AMC
movie tickets and other donated prizes. At stake are the lessons
these youngsters will need as earning, saving and spending adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned this myself but I never thought about teaching
them,'' said James Vivian, whose daughters _ Deborah, 12, and
Esther, 11 _ are attending the camp.
</P>
<P>
   Coe's teaching methods motivate the students and let them make
decisions. Two teams each invest an imaginary $100,000 in imaginary
stocks that mirror real life companies on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Spike (as in Nike) Shoes Inc. is having trouble with threats
that basketball legend Michael Jordan, who stars in Spike
commercials, might retire. Its latest plan is to ask Tiger Woods to
endorse a high-top golf shoe with removable spikes for an
after-round game of basketball.
</P>
<P>
   CyberSoft Inc. struggles with an antitrust investigation that
might hold up release of its Doors 98 software. Million Dollar
Productions Inc. can't find peace with Will Smith and Sean
``Puffy'' Combs, the co-stars of its upcoming sequel ``Independence
Day II.''
</P>
<P>
   As these and other ``news'' stories develop through the week,
Coe reads media reports on the latest developments. Students
portraying stock analysts had been briefed the day before and tried
to help their teams guess how the stock market would react.
</P>
<P>
   Other team members, playing economists, got an update from Coe
on the likelihood the Federal Reserve would raise interest rates at
its meeting the next day as well as tips on what Fed action, or
inaction, would mean to the market.
</P>
<P>
   With each installment of news Wednesday, Coe released the
results of the previous day's market moves: Munich Mining _ whose
gold mines passed a core sample test _ doubled for the second day
in a row. CyberSoft tumbled 35 percent. Million Dollar Productions
jumped 50 percent. Spike Shoes fell 25 percent. Specific Motors
lost 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Students groaned or cheered depending on how their team had
invested the day before.
</P>
<P>
   Have no doubt that these kids are soaking up Coe's message. They
were caught up in the contract talks at Specific Motors.
</P>
<P>
   ``All right, check this out. We need you all because if you lose
your jobs how would you support your families?'' said Daniel
Masterson, 15, playing the role of Specific Motors' chief operating
officer.
</P>
<P>
   Union leader Jaron Moore, 13, countered that the company didn't
care about the workers but needed them to make more money. He
emphasized the $1.7 million personal bonuses the executives had
gotten.
</P>
<P>
   Moore and his fellow labor leaders asked for 45 percent of the
profits from Specific Motor's soon-to-be released electric car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty,'' gasped Jeremy Parker, 16, in character as the
company's chief executive officer and unable to even utter the
entire amount.
</P>
<P>
   Worker Brittany Dayton, 10, asked if each employee could have an
electric car.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, management offered a 21 percent share of the electric
car profits for the union pension plan, a 7.4 percent raise and
higher medical benefits. Workers, following the lead of their
negotiators, accepted overwhelmingly.
</P>
<P>
   Coe had counseled each side separately and would announce the
next day the stock market's reaction to the vote. After a small
break, Coe talked to the students about international investing
then opened the Bull &AMP; Bear Market for each team to reshuffle its
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears, after only two days in the mock market, were up to
$178,195. The Bulls had $168,500. But the pounding in the mock
market Tuesday led both teams to protect gains rather than risk
another bad day. The Bears kept half their money out of stocks and
the Bulls _ ignoring their monicker _ kept 89 percent in cash.
</P>
<P>
   But summer's almost over, kids. The auction comes Friday and
soon it's back to school. If only someone were holding camp for the
parents....
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
