<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service calls your attention to the
following religion features moved during the last week.
</P>
<P>
   For retransmission of these stories, call 888-346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEWS AND FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JEWS-DIVORCE-NYT (New York) _ A look at the dispute surrounding
two Orthodox rabbis' efforts to help women whose husbands refuse to
grant them a religious divorce. By Nadine Brozan.
</P>
<P>
   GAYS-CHRISTIANS-NYT (Washington) _ A look at the origins of the
newspaper ads about ``former homosexuals'' who ``overcame'' their
sexual orientation through prayer and the help of Christian
``ex-gay ministries.'' By Laurie Goodstein.
</P>
<P>
   PRISON-RELIGION-TEX (Dallas) _ A Texas evangelical coalition is
bidding to turn a privately run prison in Venus, Texas, into a
faith-based operation that would offer participating inmates job
training, counseling and education built around a Christian
ministry. By Mede Nix.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-CHURCHES-HNS (San Antonio, Texas) _ A small but growing
number of Christians worship regularly in private homes rather than
conventional church buildings. They say intimacy, total
participation and lack of formal ritual make home churches much
more like churches described in the New Testament and help their
faith seem more active. But today's generation of home church
groups is doing something new: communicating over the Internet. By
J. Michael Parker.
</P>
<P>
   ANGLICANS-REVIEW-NYT _ Before the world's Anglican bishops
wrapped up their once-a-decade gathering Saturday, they offered a
glimpse of what Christianity may well look like in the next century
from a global perspective. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   SPIRITUAL-ELDERING-BOS (Rowe, Mass.) _ The Spiritual Eldering
movement, which sponsors lectures, workshops, and seminars around
the country, was founded a decade ago in Philadelphia by founder
Rabbi Zalman Shachter-Shalomi. The nondenominational movement uses
an eclectic mix of spiritual and consciousness-raising techniques _
drawn from the psychology of Erik Erikson and Carl Jung and belief
systems as disparate as shamanism, Buddhism, Hasidic Judaism and
medieval Christianity _ to get men and women from midlife on to
rethink their lives and cultivate a dynamic, positive, and socially
responsible attitude toward the aging process. By William A. Davis.
Photo.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-YOUTH-TEX (Fort Worth, Texas) _ Although the scene of
Youth WAVE church in Hurst may owe some of its flavoring to musical
grunge gurus, the smell of teen spirit exudes no sourness here. In
this independent church that ministers to 13- to 25-year-olds,
pastors Spencer and Cyndy Nordyke purposefully channel this teen
spirit as an expression of Christian spirituality. By Tara Dooley.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-CAMPMEETING-COX (Covington, Ga.) _ Faith, food &AMP;
fellowship: the Salem Campground is more than just a place to meet.
By Gayle White.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS (Undated) _ In a new book, author Roger
LeBlanc argues that the spread of dissent throughout the church on
issues ranging from the role of women to human sexuality is eroding
papal authority and endangering the church's future. By Diego
Ribadeneira.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT (Undated) _ The left-leaning
Unitarian-Universalist Association, which has no creed and
proclaims that each person has a right to seek spiritual truth, is
at odds with the Boy Scouts of America, which has told the
association that it can no longer award merit-badge-style religious
emblems to Unitarian boys in Scout troops. The BSA objects to
Unitarian concerns about the Scout oath's references to God and
country. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
