A2881 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      08-13 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS TIME, THE SAMPLE OF ALASKA WILL BE BIGGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: There was a time in the last century when the lust for
gold and the willingness to risk all in hunting it drew men north
by the tens of thousands to what was then the last U.S. frontier.
</P>
<P>
   A few found their fortunes in Alaska. More found suffering and
disappointment. Many paid for the adventure with their lives.
</P>
<P>
   I have been there one time only, a dozen years ago, and that was
only for three days.
</P>
<P>
   A plane carried me in comfort up the western coast of the
continent, where mountain ranges loom up sharply and glaciers creep
down their sides to cave into the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   I had a friend in Anchorage, a former journalist colleague who'd
spent more than half a lifetime in the northernmost state. And
after I'd discharged the small duty that had brought me there, he
undertook to show me a little of the place he'd come to love.
</P>
<P>
   Given Alaska's immensity, seeing only the least fraction of it
was all that time allowed.
</P>
<P>
   We took Highway 1 out of Anchorage northeast to Palmer, then
more eastward to Glennallen. The springtime weather was uncertain,
but for short periods the sky would clear and the splendor of Mount
McKinley, the loftiest North American peak, could be briefly seen.
</P>
<P>
   Near Tahneta Pass, we located through binoculars a band of white
Dall sheep in a slanting alpine meadow. And closer to the road,
perched comfortably on ledges that could not have been more than a
hand's breadth wide, were several wild goats.
</P>
<P>
   At Glennallen we changed onto Highway 4, bearing south to the
harbor at Valdez.
</P>
<P>
   Valdez is the terminus of the Alaska pipeline, carrying crude
oil from the north slope. It was from there, you will remember,
that the loaded Exxon tanker blundered onto the rocks, was holed,
and spilled much of its cargo in one of the worst environmental
catastrophes to that time.
</P>
<P>
   Our visit was before that misfortune, however, and I remember
Valdez as raw but fairly unspoiled. Small fishing vessels
shouldered up to the pier to unload their catch for processing, and
bald eagles in astounding numbers perched like crows on every post
and roof comb, waiting for scraps.
</P>
<P>
   We passed an overnight in the one motel, a minimal but clean
establishment, then retraced our route to Anchorage, and I caught
my plane.
</P>
<P>
   It had been only a sample, but enough to spark a yearning to see
more.
</P>
<P>
   I thought of Alaska five years later, at the end of a Siberian
river expedition, when, after 2,700 miles, our party reached its
destination on the Arctic coast. It occurred to me then that the
distance from there to the 50th U.S. state was only half that of
the distance back to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   In the days immediately ahead I finally will get to Alaska again
_ with my family this time, and for a longer stay. We'll still see
only a fraction of that remarkable place. But it will be a larger
fraction, and seen in greater depth.
</P>
<P>
   It should be a splendid time _ at the end of summer, just as the
autumn starts to turn. And I promise to make careful notes, so that
nothing of it will get away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 1855EDT &QL; 
