<HEADER>
A2883 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      08-13 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SETTING A CYBER-ERA EXAMPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: I've seen the face of the New Millennium Worker, and
he's a 57-year-old former Marine.
</P>
<P>
   More than a year ago, Digby Willard sent me an e-mail. Something
I wrote about teamwork pushed his button. We exchanged more notes.
I assumed he was a stereotypical Generation X-er because of his
comments on ``virtual corporations'' and ``teamwork in
cyberspace.''
</P>
<P>
   Memo: Be careful about assumptions.
</P>
<P>
   This man is no X-er. He was in the worst of things in Vietnam.
Yet here's a guy with a cutting-edge workplace gospel.
</P>
<P>
   Willard, who owns Digby Willard Engineering Inc., a small,
home-based consulting firm in Roeland Park, Kan., buzzes with an
Energizer Bunny zeal to re-educate and redefine himself. The work
world is changing, and he intends to more than go with the flow. He
intends to channel it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to keep the attitude of `you've got to keep
growing,' but I try,'' Willard says. ``I start by trying to
maintain a pretty high level of physical fitness. I use that as a
rationale: If I can compete with younger people physically _ and I
can _ I should be able to compete with them intellectually as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't leave the intellectual competition to chance, though.
He's working on a master's degree in engineering management (his
(BEGIN ITALS)fourth(END ITALS) master's degree). Just two years
ago, he completed his third master's, that one in mechanical
engineering.
</P>
<P>
   Within the last few years he's taken business, finance and
marketing classes at Johnson County Community College and at the
University of Kansas Edwards Campus. And he's participated in the
Kauffman Foundation's entrepreneurial development program.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yes, he's also hired two top-notch telecommuting engineers
(both of them mothers who were eager to work part-time while they
cared for their young children at home), set up a company Web site
and started a multi-pronged marketing campaign, including the
development of a potential-client database.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people consider me intensely self-confident, arrogant,
even,'' Willard says, adding quickly, ``I need every bit of it. It
gets me through every day.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not, as they say, your father's Oldsmobile. This is the
New Millennium Worker talking, if you believe the pontifications of
workplace consultants. They and Willard sound a lot alike. Here for
example, are Willard's bullet points for leading a successful team
of telecommuting workers:
</P>
<P>
   Seek out exceptionally well-qualified individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Give assistance as necessary in setting up a home office.
</P>
<P>
   Pay well for performance.
</P>
<P>
   Give complete flexibility of schedule. Results are all that
count.
</P>
<P>
   Results are all that count. That could be the title of every
other management book that hits the shelves these days.
</P>
<P>
   Willard began his engineering career in his late 30s. He started
his own business in his mid 50s. He says he's ``still just a few
weeks from running scared'' as far as income goes.
</P>
<P>
   I'd bet on his success. Talk about adapting. Talk about lifelong
learning. Talk about being cyber-savvy. Talk about any workplace
trend of the late 1990s. Then just ask Digby Willard how it's
going. He's probably given it a test drive already.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 1856EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
