<P>
   FOR FRIDAY AMs
</P>
<P>
   Business Day Front Page (coded ``f'' unless otherwise noted): &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Lede story)
</P>
<P>
   CENDANT-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Cendant says it has completed an
internal probe of its accounting fraud and that it has restated its
earnings for the past three years. It lowers its 1997 earnings by
28 cents a share and cuts 14 cents from 1995 profit and 18 cents
from 1996 profit. By Diana B. Henriques.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (Display)
</P>
<P>
   PEPSI-BOTTLERS (Kinston, N.C.) _ Pepsico's independent bottlers
have been fighting an uphill battle against Coca-Cola Consolidated,
the second-largest Coke bottler in the United States, which can
afford big marketing campaigns and price wars in the fight over
shelf space and vending machines. Now, 12 years after Coke moved to
a centralized ``anchor bottling'' model, Pepsico is considering a
spinoff of its company-owned bottling operations, which might then
acquire independent bottlers _ which are already consolidating. By
Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos and a graphic are being sent to NYT
photo/graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 7:30 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (Bottom)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-CORRUPTION (Undated) _ Earlier this year, it seemed that a
sweeping corruption investigation might send a good number of
Japan's mighty philosopher kings _ the bureaucrats who largely run
the country _ to prison. But these days, despite a Cabinet change,
nearly the only government employee who has gone anywhere is
Katsuhiko Kumazaki, the prosecutor who led a much-heralded
investigation into scandals involving expensive free entertainment
paid for by businessmen who wanted the bureaucrats' favor. By
Sheryl WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (Bottom Right)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ How a Russian devaluation would
affect Wall Street. And what investors in the Russian market are
doing right now. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (See also RUSSIA-ECON, RUSSIA-ASSESS and MARKET)
</P>
<P>
   Here are tonight's columns:
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ A growing sense of crisis in the Russian
economy helped push U.S. markets lower Thursday. The Dow Jones
industrial average closed at 8,459.50, its lowest point of the day,
down 93.46 points, or 1.1 percent. By Sharon R. King.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET)
</P>
<P>
   (See also RUSSIA-MARKETPLACE, RUSSIA-ASSESS and RUSSIA-ECON)
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ A weaker dollar and the third part of the
Treasury's quarterly debt auctions kept prices of government
securities depressed for the second consecutive day. Also weighing
on prices is the Federal Reserve's monetary-policy committee
meeting next week. By Robert Hurtado.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   LEVIS-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ In its quest to remain hip with
America's youth, Levi Strauss &AMP; Co. is introducing a campaign
infused with an unconventional, streetwise attitude for its Silver
Tab line of clothing. By Courtney Kane.
</P>
