<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Friday, Aug. 14. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   EXCLUSIVE-CLINTON-LEWINSKY (Washington) _ Details to come. Story
is exclusive and competitive. We will move it promptly at 10:45
p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.
</P>
<P>
   The story runs under a 2-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead:
</P>
<P>
   photo reefer to: AFRICA-MEMORIAL (Andrews Air Force Base, Md.) _
To the strains of ``Nearer My God to Thee,'' the remains of 10
Americans killed by the terrorist bomb in Kenya are borne home and
received at a solemn ceremony by President Clinton. By Katharine Q.
Seelye. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
With 3 photos.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-BOMBING (Nairobi, Kenya) _ The FBI agent in charge of
solving the bombing of the U.S. Embassy here says that the bureau
has found fragments of the truck that carried the explosives and is
piecing together a picture of what happened in the seconds before
the bomb went off. By Tim Weiner and Raymond Bonner. (Scheduled to
move by 8 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECON (Moscow) _ Stock and bond prices plunge into
freefall, taking with them any hope of averting depletion of the
government's finances and a meltdown of the banking system. By
Michael Wines. (Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
With: MOSCOW-ASSESS and RUSSIA-MARKETPLACE.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTHCARE-SUIT (Washington) _ A federal appeals court, in a
nationwide class action, expands the rights of Medicare patients,
ruling that they are entitled to immediate hearings and other
protections if they are denied care by an HMO. By Robert Pear.
(Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Reefer: INTERNET-PRIVACY (Washington) _ In the government's
first Internet-privacy enforcement action, the FTC says a popular
site on the World Wide Web run by GeoCities lied about how it would
use the personal information it collected from more than two
millions subscribers, both adults and children. By Joel Brinkley.
(Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   CONGO-REBELS (Kinshasa, Congo) _ Rebels hostile to President
Laurent Kabila apparently knocked out all electrical power to the
capital and tighten their hold on a strategic region outside this
city. By Howard W. French. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``i''
news file.)
</P>
<P>
   WESTERN-LAND-TRUSTS (Clark, Colo.) _ Here and across the
mountain west, tourism and the second-home industry have spurred a
land rush that is carving up the ranch land that composes
heart-stopping Western vistas, threatening the very landscape that
draws so many people to the Rockies. The pressures are so powerful
that they are forging alliances of two longtime adversaries:
cattlemen and environmentalists. Together they are adapting a tool
used to preserve open space in the crowded East, land trusts, to
save the West's privately owned wide-open spaces by keeping cattle
grazing on them. By James Brooke. (Scheduled to move by 7:30 p.m.
ET in ``a'' news file.) With map, graphic and photo. 1,900 words.
</P>
</TEXT>
