<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0310 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2908 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEPSI-BOTTLERS-ART-2T     08-13 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEPSI-BOTTLERS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTTLING BATTLE: COKE INVADES NORTH CAROLINA PEPSI COUNTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic on
Pepsi and Coke market share in 15 metro areas is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINSTON, N.C. _ This is the capital of Pepsi country, where
babies born at regional hospitals go home with Pepsi birth
certificates, along with the state-issued ones. They grow up
playing Pepsi-sponsored Little League and develop a taste for
barbecue, hush puppies and one of the more unusual indigenous
snacks: a package of salted peanuts poured directly into a bottle
of Pepsi-Cola, to be drunk and chewed all at once.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsi signs dot the flat landscape of cornfields and tobacco
farms, now shimmering in the summer heat. Over the 63 years since
the Pepsi-Cola bottling franchise was first awarded here, per
capita consumption of Pepsi products, mostly Pepsi-Cola and
Mountain Dew, has grown to more than 400 8-ounce servings per
person, per year; in the rest of the nation, it is 270.
</P>
<P>
   But Pepsi's hold on the area is not as solid as it once was. For
three years, Pepsi's bottler in these parts, the family-owned
Minges Bottling Group, has been competing against Coca-Cola
Bottling Co. Consolidated.
</P>
<P>
   This Coca-Cola affiliate covers a 12-state swath of the South,
had sales of $802 million last year and, as a publicly traded
company in which Coca-Cola Co. holds a 30 percent stake, can afford
big marketing campaigns and price wars in the fight over shelf
space and vending machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like David and Goliath,'' said Jeff Minges, president of
Pepsi-Cola Bottling Co. of Kinston, one of three within the Minges
Group.
</P>
<P>
   It is a problem that Pepsico Inc., No. 2 to Coca-Cola in the $50
billion domestic soft-drink business, recognizes. Twelve years
after Coke moved to a centralized ``anchor bottling'' model,
Pepsico is planning to spin off its company-owned bottling
operations. The new bottling company may then acquire small
independent bottlers.
</P>
<P>
   Many small bottlers _ like the convenience stores and other
retailers they sell to _ are already consolidating: There were 180
independent Pepsi bottlers in 1987 while today there are 121,
according to Beverage Digest, an industry newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   (Wednesday, Pepsico said it had agreed to buy full ownership of
its eighth-largest bottler, Pepsi-Cola Allied Bottlers Inc. in
Latham, N.Y., a suburb of Albany. Terms were not disclosed.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a much more difficult, competitive environment than it
has been historically,'' said Philip Marineau, president of
Pepsi-Cola North America.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Pepsi-Cola was invented 100 years ago some 30 miles to the east
of here in New Bern, where a pharmacist named Caleb Bradham
happened upon a formula that the public embraced.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Pepsi's dominance in the area can be credited to Hoyt
Minges, now 74 and taking a back seat to his sons and nephews, who
are the third generation of the family in the bottling business.
Hoyt, who started working with his father, M.O. Minges, in 1943,
won award after award from corporate headquarters for increasing
consumption, a record often helped by thirsty farm workers.
</P>
<P>
   But things began shifting after the local Coke bottler sold his
business to Coca-Cola Consolidated. This spring, a tussle erupted
between Coke and Pepsi over which soft drink company would have
exclusive pouring rights at East Carolina University, in nearby
Greenville. (Pepsi won the rights, for $7 million, but only after
corporate executives got involved.) Billboards proclaiming that
Coca-Cola and barbecue are ``perfect together'' have popped up
along the main roads, and Coke vending machines, some depicting
North Carolina lighthouses on their broad fronts, are
proliferating.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is this perception that eastern North Carolina is Pepsi
country,'' said Lauren Steele, a spokesman for Coca-Cola
Consolidated. ``We are out to change that.''
</P>
<P>
   At nearly every supermarket and convenience store, the windows
and aisles, and sometimes even the light poles in the parking lots,
are plastered with evidence of the struggle. A 24-pack of Pepsi at
one Piggly Wiggly supermarket in Kinston was $6.99; a 12-pack of
Coke was less than half as much, at $1.99.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Minges, Hoyt's middle son, finds the consolidation and the
subsequent clout of his Coca-Cola competitors much on his mind. He
says the deep roots that he and his relatives have in their
communities are invaluable in business dealings _ ``You know the
mayor personally'' _ and the family has tended the business
carefully, operating debt-free most of the time and competing
tirelessly against Coke and others. But it is also clear to him, as
it is to Wall Street, that large-scale, well-financed bottling
operations offer increased efficiency for customers and corporate
strategists alike.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsico chairman and chief executive Roger Enrico announced last
month that the company would begin studying a spinoff of its
company-owned bottling operations. He called the move ``a critical
part of our long-term growth strategy.'' Analysts expect the
spinoff to occur by December or January.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our research shows this fragmented bottler network of Pepsi's
has been the key issue in terms of Pepsi's recent performance and
market share versus Coca-Cola,'' Bill Pecoriello, an analyst for
Sanford Bernstein, said. The proposed spinoff bottler ``will be the
consolidator,'' he predicted. ``Over time, these small bottlers
will sell their business to this company.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepsi is considering the spinoff at a time when Coca-Cola is
facing increased scrutiny over the way it has moved its expensive
bottling factories to its own spinoff, Coca-Cola Enterprises.
Critics such as Albert Meyer, an accountant and investment analyst,
say Coke and the bottling company are actually one entity, and for
accounting purposes should be consolidated.
</P>
<P>
   The Financial Accounting Standards Board, which sets the
nation's accounting rules, is expected to release a draft of a new
rule later this year that would force companies with very close
ties to consolidate their financial statements. Although it might
be many months or even longer before such a rule took effect, a
consolidation of this kind at Coca-Cola could cut the company's
short-term earnings and could force it to reclaim billions of
dollars of debt that now resides with Coca-Cola Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for Coca-Cola declined to comment Thursday on the
accounting issues. They have said previously that Coca-Cola
Enterprises is an independent company and that their accounting is
proper. And at Pepsi-Cola, Brad Shaw, a spokesman for the company
in Somers, N.Y., said: ``The two primary forces driving our
interest in a separate bottling company have nothing to do with
accounting. Our interest is being driven by the large size and
continuing consolidation of our retail customers, as well as the
continuing consolidiaton of our competition.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   While members of the Minges family, whose two other companies
are in Greenville and New Bern, say they have no plans to sell,
Jeff Minges says he expects the spinoff to mean more support from
corporate headquarters for companies like his.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope Pepsi-Cola will be able to focus more on the bottler
network,'' he said. ``And hopefully, they can financially support
us and put more field people in the system.''
</P>
<P>
   His brother, Tyrus, manages the bottling company in New Bern,
while a cousin, Tom Minges, runs the business in Greenville.
Another cousin, John F. Minges III, who is also the family
historian, is quitting to pursue a career in the nonprofit world.
</P>
<P>
   The life of a local bottler has changed markedly from what it
was in 1943. Pepsi-Cola, which accounts for 75 percent of the
Minges Group's sales, has had recent problems with identity and
market share, both of which are eroding in the face of Coke's
aggressive marketing, especially that aimed at young people. Coke
has a 43.9 share of the domestic market, according to Beverage
Digest, while Pepsi's is 30.9.
</P>
<P>
   Turnover at the high levels of Pepsico has irritated bottlers,
who tend to prefer long, well-developed relationships with the home
office as they go about their business. They not only package soft
drinks, but also distribute them to stores, vending machines,
restaurants and other outlets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty years ago, it was pretty much a relationship between the
route salesman and the store manager,'' Jeff Minges said. ``The
little stores, they're all gone. Those stores are what built our
business. You'd go in and buy a pack of Nabs and a Moon Pie and a
Pepsi.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, it's much more complex. ``Look at all the brands
you've got, and look at all the different-sized bottles and cans,''
he said. `` But a store manager can't make a decision because it's
all dictated by a chain.''
</P>
<P>
   David Bright, a 21-year-old route salesman, works for a general
manager in New Bern who has been known to dress up as a Pepsi can
for local parades. For Bright, getting Pepsi on the shelves of the
local Target and Wal-Mart involves a delicate dance between him,
the store manager and the Coke salesman. Certain shelves might hold
Coke one week, Pepsi the next. It's up to Bright to keep an eye on
what happens, and he finds Coke increasingly aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   Marineau thinks that ``there could still be small family
bottlers in the Pepsi system _ they have that entrepreneurship, and
Pepsi blue runs in their veins.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some changes have put fresh pressures on small bottlers.
This year, they were asked to sign a renegotiated franchise
agreement that gives Pepsico control of lucrative fountain accounts
that the bottlers used to handle. Most bottlers, including the
Minges family, have signed; about 20 are still holding out.
</P>
<P>
   As part of asserting itself in the fountain business, Pepsico
also sued Coca-Cola Co. in U.S. District Court in Manhattan in May,
accusing it of antitrust violations and unfair domination of the
food-service distribution area of the fountain business. (Coke has
moved to have the lawsuit dismissed.) Pepsi also sued one of its
bottlers, Central Investment Corp., after saying that it had
threatened to enter the first lawsuit on Coke's side.
</P>
<P>
   The company also introduced a new blue can for Pepsi-Cola this
year, expanded test markets for a lemon-lime drink called Storm,
announced a new diet drink called Pepsi One and bought the
Tropicana juice business from Seagram Co. All of these moves are
examples of innovation that, in theory, keeps consumers paying
attention to the brands.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, demand for vending machines and other cold-drink
equipment is growing as both Coke and Pepsi ratchet up their
emphasis on what are known as immediate-consumption sales, which
have some of the highest margins in the business. That could push
some smaller bottlers toward consolidation with others.
</P>
<P>
   ``In neither system is there a strategy to eliminate smaller
bottlers,'' said Beverage Digest publisher John Sicher. ``But there
is a strategy to grow the business, and the tools required to grow
the business, in some cases, will be more likely found in the hands
of a larger, consolidated bottler.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Pepsi spinoff is coming half a generation after
Coke put together a similar plan with Coca-Cola Enterprises,
executives at Pepsi appear confident that their plan will work for
their products. ``I don't think we're too late,'' Marineau said.
``We can succeed in this marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the members of the Minges family, they express cautious
confidence in the reconfigured world of Pepsi. ``I'm excited about
the future,'' Tom Minges said. ``I feel better than I have in a
long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
