<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News service for Friday, Aug. 13. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
GOP-ARMY (Washington) - Military training? For U.S. congressmen?
Two Arizonans, J.D. Hayworth and Jim Kolbe, were among a group of
about seven GOP federal lawmakers who shipped out to army bases in
1995 and 1996 to learn the art of strategic thinking and
battlefield decision-making. This was the brainchild of Newt
Gingrich and the GOP leadership, and Kolbe's office, for one, says
it has helped them handle stressful situations such as dealing with
environmentalist demonstrators. But now, the Pentagon's Inspector
General's office says the Army improperly provided the services
without charging the politicians and that it was far too partisan
because no Democrats received any training. Hayworth was so
enthusiastic about the training that he took along 18 staff
members. By JEFF BARKER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BISKIND-ABORTION (Phoenix) - Phoenix abortion doctor John Biskind
has his medical license revoked following the death of one patient
in his care and the near-abortion of a full-term baby while working
at an abortion clinic owned by a New York doctor. uBiskind was
facing a hearing next month to determine if the state should yank
his license, but he agreed to admit to the state's allegations and
end the matter. By SUSIE STECKNER and JODIE SNYDER. Story will move
in the ``A`` category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
PERMITS (Undated) - After being acquitted last year for trespassing
on Mount Graham while praying for his daughters passage into
womanhood, Wendsler Nosie hoped the University of Arizona would
lighten up. Instead, the university, in an attempt to protect its
controversial telescopes, is requiring ``prayer permits,'' a policy
that Nosie and other traditional Apaches say is an attack on their
religious freedom. Nosie and 50 young Native Americans from across
Arizona will run 100 miles Saturday from the San Carlos Apache
reservation to the top of Mount Graham, to pray. And they will not
attempt to acquire permits to do so. By STEVE YOZWIAK. Story will
move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
GUN-CHEAT (Undated) - A young Valley woman, hailed last year as a
national NRA shooting champion, is disqualified in this year's Ohio
tournament for having falsified her score. By BILL HERMANN. Story
will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CLINTON-SOAPS (Undated) - What if the Clinton/Lewinsky scandal
actually was a plot line on a soap opera? `Sunset Beach' has
already incorporated a scheming character named Melinda Fall (as in
Linda Tripp.) One writer said she'd cast Bill Clinton immediately
because he's the kind of man who women will always forgive.
Producers and/or script writers tell us how they'd wrap up the big
plot line and what the Big Creep's fate would be. WITH
ILLUSTRATIONS. By DAVE WALKER. Story moved in the ``A'' and ``E``
categories. (EMBARGOED FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 16) &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
NOTARO-COLUMN (Undated) - It was my husband who saw it first.
``Hey,'' he said, leaning toward the TV. ``Isn't that your old
boyfriend?'' It's a question he asks me a lot, especially if he's
watching ``Cops`` or ``America's Most Wanted.`` ``I told you, just
because some guy on the news walks out of a trailer without a shirt
on, has a beer in his hand and is being questioned by the police
doesn't mean I've dated him,'' I shouted from the kitchen. ``I
think this is the guy who had the snakes,'' he yelled back. A thin
shiver coiled up my spine. The snakes. They belonged to my first
boyfriend, a big guy with a mohawk, since this was during the
mid-80s and boyfriends with snakes and mohawks were just part of
the deal. By LAURI NOTARO. Story moved in the ``L'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
PI-MOVIE (Undated) - ``Pi`` is one of the best movies I have seen
in a long time, but do not go and see it. You probably won't enjoy
it. If that is an odd endorsement, well, ``Pi`` is an odd movie. It
is a thriller about mathematics. There are no car chases, no
fireball explosions, no dinosaurs. It is about an obsessive recluse
living in a shabby apartment in New York, who spends his life
trying to discover the mathematical meaning of the world, between
the attacks he suffers from debilitating migraines. 5 stars. By
RICHARD NILSEN. Story will move in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
