<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GUNS-AND-JAILS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO GUN PLAY  
 (THIS EDITORIAL WILL APPEAR IN FRIDAY'S ARIZONA REPUBLIC) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Who could not be
</P>
<P>
   sympathetic with the plight of James Brunen?
</P>
<P>
   The Scottsdale, Ariz., businessman was arrested on July 23
entering Nogales, Sonora, Mexico, and has been in jail ever since.
</P>
<P>
   That's a Mexican jail, ladies and gentlemen, the very thought of
which would probably qualify for cruel and unusual punishment
anywhere in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Brunen says he mistakenly left some ammunition in his car, a
transgression for which he has already spent $15,000 and the
discomfort of surviving in a rat-infested prison cell.
</P>
<P>
   His wife has been making frequent visits with bottled water,
canned food and medical supplies, bringing cash to help pay for a
bigger cell.
</P>
<P>
   `He had to buy a breath of fresh air. He had to buy protection
for his food. He had to buy the right to use a phone and the price
went up every day,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She warns American travelers to make sure they are not packing
weapons if they head south of the border.
</P>
<P>
   `It's very dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes.
</P>
<P>
   While we sympathize with Brunen's plight _ and the plight of the
other Americans jailed in Sonora for violating Mexico's strict gun
laws _ the responsibility for much of their suffering rests on
their own shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   After all, signs are posted all over the place warning travelers
not to bring guns or ammunition into Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Stories of immediate and unpleasant incarceration in Mexico for
the discovery of guns have been circulating for years throughout
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   It does not take much to fathom the importance of knowing
whether your vehicle contains any ammunition or weapons when
entering Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The simple fear of ending up in a Mexican jail is sufficient
motivation for most people to exercise extreme caution when
approaching the border.
</P>
<P>
   Look.
</P>
<P>
   At least by American standards, Mexico runs a crooked game and
everyone knows it.
</P>
<P>
   If you sit down at the poker table, you should not be surprised
to learn the odds are against you.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican police are notorious for being corrupt. That is a
regrettable fact. It is also a regrettable fact that Mexico does
not exhibit an American sensitivity for the rights of the accused _
especially those like Brunen unfortunate enough to land in their
jails.
</P>
<P>
   The 29 Americans sitting in Sonora jails for allegedly violating
Mexico's strict gun laws are reminder of what can happen if you are
charged with taking ammunition across the border. Carrying even a
single round of ammunition into Mexico can mean a jail sentence of
up to five years.
</P>
<P>
   It's not fair. No argument there. But the Mexicans, after all,
do not require that Americans leave their brains on the northern
side of the border.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 1916EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
