<SLUG> BC-FBC-OLEMISS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Changes bring optimism to Ole Miss
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Traditions die hard at Ole Miss, where some Rebels
fans ignored pleas from coach Tommy Tuberville last season to stop
waving Confederate flags during games. But the extent of his
commitment to reversing the fortunes of a program that hasn't
finished atop the SEC since the dark days of the civil-rights
struggle may have gained more converts.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not just because Tuberville enters his fourth season
with Mississippi's first bowl game in five years, a victory over
Marshall in the Motor City Bowl, to culminate an 8-4 campaign. He
also turned down an offer worth an estimated $850,000, more than
twice his 1997 income, to assume the reins at Arkansas, his native
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being from Arkansas, I would have regretted not listening,''
Tuberville said. ``But last season for us was miracle part one.
We're hoping this year, it will be miracle part two.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss of 12 seniors, including unsung quarterback Stewart
Patridge and running back John Avery, drafted in the first round by
the Miami Dolphins, means Tuberville will have to continue his
overachieving reputation in Oxford. Although the Rebels are off
NCAA probation and finally restocking their roster, they will have
fewer than 70 players on full scholarship this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt like we were playing iron-man football,'' senior
cornerback Gary Thigpen said about playing through the sanctions.
``It's been an uphill battle to get to the level we're at now. Now
that we're off probation, we feel like we can compete with (top
SEC)-caliber teams.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why Tuberville wanted to put an end to waving the Stars
and Bars, which he thinks hinders recruiting. No Confederate flags
are pictured in the media guide, and any reference to the ``Dixie''
fight song also has been excised. However, Colonel Reb, the
venerable mascot, won't be retired anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   On the field, the changes will have to be more than cosmetic.
Ole Miss returns arguably the best tight end in the country, junior
Rufus French. Sophomore Romaro Miller is set to take the reins from
Patridge, who surprised Tuberville by winning the job over the
highly touted former Parade prep All-American.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we had a group of seniors who wanted a bowl and
laid it on the line for us,'' he said. ``This year, we have a loss
of that leadership. It's going to be interesting to see who steps
up for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller played in just three games in 1997, completing 11 of 27
passes, but he excelled in the spring game. ``We want him to get a
great start, but you don't know what will happen,'' Tuberville
said. ``Our goal is to bring him along slowly.''
</P>
<P>
   Replacing Avery, who rushed for 862 yards, will be a more
sizable task. Deuce McAllister and Tony Cannion earned letters, and
they will get competition from redshirt freshman Joe Gunn.
</P>
<P>
   Ole Miss must replace six defensive starters, including all
three regulars at linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the new faces, however, Ole Miss doesn't figure to
be overlooked any longer. The Rebels start off at home with Memphis
and Auburn before settling into a league schedule that will take
them to Alabama and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not sneaking up on anybody now,'' Thigpen said.
``Instead, they're looking out for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming Saturday: Alabama
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
