A2923 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-DEBERG-CO     08-13 1325
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-DEBERG-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons' DeBerg, 44, gets first comeback test in Detroit
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Mark Olson was jogging around the practice fields at
Suwanee about 10:45 the other night, when a noise at midfield
stopped him in his tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Olson, an intern with the Falcons public-relations staff, heard
a shuffling sound and noticed a shadowy figure moving quickly, a
blur in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   ``It scared me to death,'' said Olson, who thought he was seeing
a ghost.
</P>
<P>
   It's not far from the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-four-year-old quarterback Steve DeBerg, who has risen from
the NFL dead, was on the practice field, dropping back to pass, as
if the lights were on with 60,000 fans in the stands. He was
rehearsing for tonight, when he is expected to play three quarters
in the Falcons' exhibition game at Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   DeBerg, who hasn't played since 1993, is the oldest man
currently seeking employment as a player in the NFL. And he's older
than five head coaches _ Tampa Bay's Tony Dungy, Oakland's Jon
Gruden, Pittsburgh's Bill Cowher, Tennessee's Jeff Fisher and San
Francisco's Steve Mariucci.
</P>
<P>
   Most players in NFL camps are battling to prove they're good
enough to play. DeBerg is out to prove he's no fool.
</P>
<P>
   If he makes the team, he will be the second-oldest man to play
in the league. When George Blanda played for the Raiders in 1975 at
age 48, he was used mainly as a kicker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing a lot of extra work, lifting or running, because if
I do get an opportunity to play, No. 1, I don't want to embarrass
myself, and No. 2, I don't want to get hurt,'' DeBerg said,
explaining his late-night workout. In fact, it has been a routine
for more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   DeBerg was drafted by Dallas in 1977, was cut and was picked up
by San Francisco. After backing up Jim Plunkett there, he became
the starter in 1978. He passed for a career-high 3,652 yards in
1979.
</P>
<P>
   After being unseated by Joe Montana, DeBerg was traded to
Denver, where he backed up John Elway under coach Dan Reeves. He
later went to Tampa Bay ('84-87), Kansas City ('88-91), Tampa Bay
('92, three games in '93), and Miami (five games in '93).
</P>
<P>
   He finished 13th in NFL history with 33,782 passing yards, 10th
in completions with 2,844 and 11th in attempts with 4,965.
</P>
<P>
   DeBerg tried coaching in 1995-96 and became an assistant with
Reeves in New York. In 1997, he was recently divorced, restless, a
little fat and out of work. So he decided to get in shape. Part of
his routine involved old quarterback drills. He lifted, ran, threw
into nets. And he started thinking about a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sent a letter out (in June) to quite a few NFL teams just to
let people know I'd been working out,'' he said. ``I really felt
like if anybody gave me a workout they'd be impressed with how I
threw, but I didn't know if I'd get a look. At 44, it was going to
have to be a unique opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next day, Dan (Reeves) called, and said, 'Steve, what is
this empty envelope?' And I said it was supposed to be a letter
explaining that I'm interested in re-starting my career. I had no
idea Dan was in a predicament with his quarterback situation _ that
was pure coincidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta was looking for a backup quarterback. Starter Chris
Chandler missed all or parts of six games last season with
injuries, and the Falcons lost them all. Tony Graziani, the backup,
had a passer rating of 3.7 in his rookie season.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta responded by signing veteran Mark Rypien, but the
Falcons were informed that family problems would put his career on
hold. That's when DeBerg's empty envelope arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``The closer we got to training camp, with what we had as far as
what we were willing to spend, which was nothing, there were very
few people that fell into the category (of having experience with
the Falcon offense),'' Reeves said. ``We probably would have done
nothing if it hadn't been for a scenario like Steve DeBerg...
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave him one of the longest workouts ever, and he just
threw the ball great. If a guy can do it, I don't care if he's 25
or 45.''
</P>
<P>
   DeBerg signed on July 6, a day before mini-camp.
</P>
<P>
   Graziani remains the backup, and DeBerg is No. 3. More
competition arrived Wednesday, when the Falcons acquired rookie
John Dutton, a sixth-round pick waived by Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's game might not make or break DeBerg. He hopes the
Falcons will not be hasty with a decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe I can contribute more than almost any player in the
NFL as a backup quarterback who doesn't play,'' he said. ``There
may be more talented backup quarterbacks; that remains to be seen.
I know what to do, but can I actually do it? Again, we'll see.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, since I signed so fast, I'm kind of rushing things.
I'm not where I want to be, where I will be. I'm actually shooting
for October. I can help.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of coaches have never been under center. When you've
done it, and you can explain it in a way that is easily
understandable, I can help teach how to read defenses faster,
improve ballhandling skills, a lot of things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has incredible knowledge,'' said Chandler, 32, the NFL's
No. 2-rated passer in '97. ``He comes across very clearly. I feel
like the luckiest quarterback in the league to have him around,
except for the Kenny G and Bob Seger he plays in the morning. His
kind of stuff, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   DeBerg has been eating alone, usually reading a playbook, the
financial pages in a newspaper or the living section. He seems
almost mellow. The image doesn't match his reputation.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, he was arrested in New York on a DUI charge, which was
dropped. DeBerg underwent alcohol counseling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pretty footloose and fancy-free away from football, but
football has always been very, very serious to me,'' he said. ``I
left a bar, and I was trying to get to the Lincoln Tunnel, and I
got going the wrong way on a one-way (street), and a cop came.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have a beer once in a while, but I have a totally
different approach to alcohol. I love to have fun, but I learned I
don't have to be intoxicated to have fun. You can also have a lot
more fun the next day. It's about maturing and growing up.''
</P>
<P>
   DeBerg marvels at how players have changed since he first came
into the league. Ephraim Salaam, the youngest Atlanta player, was
10 months old at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Players then did it more for passion. The money thing has
changed it a lot,'' he said. ``When I first came into the league,
players had offseason jobs to support their football income. My
first contract in 1977 was for $18,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``NFL players have tremendous egos. Take a quarterback, any
position, really, but just take a quarterback. An organization
says, 'We'll give you $2 million.' He wants $2.5 or he says he's
going to retire. Wait a minute. You're going to retire? How does a
guy in the corporate world who works 12 hours a day, six days a
week, and makes $125,000 busting it -- understand that?''
</P>
<P>
   DeBerg is laughing now, grinning so hard that his deeply tanned
face looks ready to tear, and his bright white teeth seem huge. His
sharp blue eyes are invisible behind a squint. It's obvious he is
having fun.
</P>
<P>
   And why not? As he said, the money of the modern era ain't bad.
</P>
<P>
   He negotiated a $25,000 signing bonus with Atlanta, and while
the $325,000 salary he'll earn if he makes the team is the NFL
minimum for a player with his experience, it'll pay for several
SCUBA or snow-skiing trips, maybe a little more sailing or
water-skiing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tease these (coaches) I was on the staff with in New York,''
DeBerg said. ``I say I got the best coaching job in the world. I'm
getting paid way more than those guys; I put in about a third of
the time, and I get to enjoy the actual performance end of it. I
got the system beat, I really do.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as he can avoid the Lions.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
