<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JONES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former democratic congressman slams Clinton, calls for his
resignation
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Washington _ Former Democratic Rep. Ben Jones was the darling of
conservative talk show hosts Thursday after he penned a forceful
letter in a Capitol Hill newspaper calling on President Clinton to
step down.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who once campaigned for Clinton, said the president's
refusal to answer questions about his alleged sexual relationship
with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky has ``done a lasting
disservice to this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will testify Monday, via closed-circuit television,
before a grand jury that is examining the alleged affair and
allegations that Clinton lied about it under oath and encouraged
others to do so.
</P>
<P>
   In an open letter to Clinton published in the Roll Call
newspaper, Jones said if the allegations are true, as he believes
they are, there is only one way the president could repair the
damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do the honorable thing. Step down. The nation will be
grateful,'' Jones wrote.
</P>
<P>
   There was no reaction from the White House. Neal Boortz, Sean
Hannity and Rush Limbaugh, however, were only too happy to read or
quote from Jones's letter.
</P>
<P>
   Hannity interviewed Jones for his afternoon program from New
York.
</P>
<P>
   The actor-turned-congressman-turned-actor said, in a separate
interview, that he put on paper what ``an awful lot of Democrats''
are feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone in this party has to stand up and say we're better
than that,'' he said. Actually Jones, who played a spin-happy media
consultant in the movie ``Primary Colors,'' has been saying that
for months.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Sabato, a political scientist at the University of
Virginia, said he first saw Jones's letter in Roll Call's on-line
edition early Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It stunned me because, while he's not a significant figure,
he's the first Democratic office holder, former or current, to call
for Clinton to resign,'' Sabato said. ``It may be just a footnote
or it may be the first leak in the dike.''
</P>
<P>
   After two-terms in the House of Representatives, Jones lost a
Democratic primary in 1992, so he never served in Congress when
Clinton was in the White House. He ran a longshot campaign against
Newt Gingrich in 1994 and filed ethics charges against Gingrich
that eventually led to the speaker's reprimand by the House and
$300,000 penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Jones is without his own personal battles. He has
freely discussed his drinking problem and the battery charge filed
by one of his four former wives. ``My philosophy was, 'When on thin
ice, dance!''' he wrote in Roll Call.
</P>
<P>
   So he has some empathy with Clinton in the area of ``personal
moral excesses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All that does is make him an adulterer and hypocrite,'' Jones
said. ``That's not an impeachable offense. But perjury is and
obstruction of justice is.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he fears the country would be divided by impeachment
proceedings, should they occur, or be left with a ``hobbled
president with no credibility and no moral standing.''
</P>
<P>
   Those prospects prompted him to suggest a third way,
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   As he told Clinton in his open letter, ``Mr. President, I have
bad news for you. The last dog has died.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
