u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIO-MAIN-COX     08-13 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIO-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Universities ready to sow crop of biotech researchersBy Andy
Miller
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Emory University plans to turn the former Georgia
Mental Health Institute campus into a greenhouse for young
biotechnology companies, helping them grow to maturity and, as a
result, produce multibillion-dollar dividends for the state.
</P>
<P>
   The 42-acre site will become a biotech development center on the
42-acre GMHI property, which the university is purchasing from the
state. The land deal is expected to close this month. Hiring for
the facility and some center activities could begin this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the center, which will be jointly run by Emory and
Georgia Tech, is to help nurture early-stage biotech research
companies and then nurture them into economic maturity. Project
leaders hope the center will jump-start Atlanta's sluggish biotech
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Emory will pay $2.9 million for the GMHI property. Renovations
to its 17 buildings are projected to cost up to $28 million and
some new construction is likely. The biotech center's backers
estimate its impact to Georgia's economy will be $2.8 billion over
10 years, with that money coming from the creation of new jobs and
increased tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Such development ''incubators,'' for biotech and other
industries, nurture young companies with space, expertise and
services to help them grow. Georgia Tech already has one for high
tech companies, called the Advanced Technology Development Center.
</P>
<P>
   The biotech incubator will also provide funding and management
help. ``We're going several levels above what most incubators do,''
Dennis Liotta, vice president for research at Emory, and one of the
project's planners, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The center will combine Georgia Tech's technology and
engineering capabilities with Emory's biomedical expertise,
expanding the collaborative research the two institutions already
pursue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a beautiful marriage,'' said William Todd, president
of the Georgia Research Alliance. ``Georgia Tech has engineering,
but no medicine; Emory has medicine, but no engineering. They need
each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The metro area and Georgia have lagged in biotech development
despite having key ingredients, including research universities,
medical centers, the prestigious Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention, the Research Alliance, and an entrepreneurial climate.
</P>
<P>
   Venture capital is now more available here, but traditionally
has been scarce, as is commercial laboratory space. Only a handful
of biotech companies have evolved in metro Atlanta _ most small and
yet to produce any significant revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The state has received just 2 percent of all U.S. research and
development spending in biotech _ or life-sciences companies that
produce diagnostic tests, medical devices and drugs. California and
Massachusetts account for about half of that R&AMP;D spending.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, though, Cousins Properties broke ground on a lab and
office complex in Alpharetta. So far the complex has attracted
Norcross, Ga.-based AtheroGenics, which is developing treatments to
help prevent heart attacks and strokes.
</P>
<P>
   The Emory-Tech center could serve as a pipeline of companies to
such a biotech park, said Emory's Liotta.
</P>
<P>
   The incubator project would give new and startup firms some
initial funding and access to about 40,000 to 50,000 square feet of
laboratory space, along with room for the operations of about 10
companies. The center would also provide a management team to help
companies with strategic planning. The center is expected to occupy
most of the 42-acre campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a lot easier for small companies to get started
without having to hire a full-time CEO,'' said Don Giddens of
Georgia Tech, chairman of the joint biomedical engineering
department of Tech and Emory. ``Faculty are not business people.''
</P>
<P>
   The biotech center, Liotta said, ''will take the (initial) high
risk, because no one else wants to.'' The center will take an
equity stake in the companies, he added.
</P>
<P>
   After the initial biotech studies are completed, Liotta said,
``we will filter out a lot of bad technologies.'' That's when
venture capitalists would come calling, attracted to the pool of
technologies, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta hasn't been a place where venture capitalists have
stopped off and visited,'' Liotta added. ``The center will serve as
a magnet for people investing in new technologies.''
</P>
<P>
   Another investment opportunity would come from offering a mutual
fund of the center's biotech companies, Liotta said. ``If one of
the companies hits, you've got a good return on investment.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of a biotech ``incubator'' is fairly common, said
industry expert Bill Reardon, of PricewaterhouseCoopers in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   At least a dozen have cropped up around major cities, with
varying structures and degrees of success, Reardon said.
</P>
<P>
   The Emory-Tech proposal of a management team is positive, along
with the commitment of funding, he said. ``I've seen other
locations struggle with the model.''
</P>
<P>
   For an area to develop in biotech, it needs not only money and
research universities, but also proximity to health-care
institutions, Reardon said. ``Doctors are needed from an idea
perspective and for clinical trials.''
</P>
<P>
   And biotech growth tends to feed off itself, as companies'
success spurs others to follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``This field has all the promise for the first part of the 21st
century that the information technology revolution has done for the
last part of this century,'' Todd said.
</P>
<P>
   The center will also work with Georgia's other universities and
medical centers, along with the CDC, the American Cancer Society,
the National Arthritis Foundation and other groups.
</P>
<P>
   The terms of Emory's agreement with the state includes a clause
that Emory can't resell the property without state approval. GMHI,
which delivered short-term hospital care for people with mental
health problems, was closed in June by the state of Georgia because
of high operating costs.
</P>
<P>
   Emory co-developed GMHI in the mid-1960s and conducted some
research there, as well as providing some mental-health services
there. Emory's psychiatric work is expected to continue on the
campus.
</P>
<P>
   There were no other formal bidders for the GMHI property, said
Rod Bowlden of the State Properties Commission. He cited the
legislation that authorized its sale, which restricts the campus
use to a government or educational entity.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
