<HEADER>
A2928 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIONATIONAL-COX     08-13 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIONATIONAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Biotech future still as bright as everBy Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Biotechnology is often touted as the industry of the
future, but that future has taken its own sweet time getting here.
</P>
<P>
   In the late-1980s, the sector was seen as the next wave of
high-tech innovation, the conjunction of biology and commerce that
would spawn many hundreds of companies and create tens of thousands
of jobs _ all while radically reshaping human health.
</P>
<P>
   With the millennium nearing, biotech is like a sapling _
promising, pretty and still very small.
</P>
<P>
   But the growth is real. Biotech, like some other high-tech
industries before, has been concentrated in a few areas of the
country. What those regions tend to have in common are strong
medical facilities and universities.
</P>
<P>
   It should not be surprising then that San Francisco has the most
publicly-traded biotech companies _ 61, followed by Boston and New
England with 54 and San Diego with 33, according to Ernst &AMP; Young.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey has 22 biotech companies that are nurtured and
sometimes funded or bought by the huge pharmaceutical companies
along Route 1. The Washington-Baltimore corridor has about 20
public biotech companies.
</P>
<P>
   In the South, there are more recent _ and thus far, more modest
_ efforts at spurring biotech in Texas, Alabama, North Carolina and
Florida as well as Georgia. All have produced a smattering of
companies.
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina, where the Research Triangle Park has vied for
status as a high-tech center, the North Carolina Biotechnology
Center was founded by the state in 1981. That center has spent much
of its energy luring biotech companies from elsewhere to either
move headquarters or do their manufacturing in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The center's $10.5 million-a-year budget comes mostly from the
government, said spokesman Barry Teater. Together with NationsBank,
the state is putting together a venture capital fund aimed at
raising $30 million for biotech firms, he said.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina now has nearly 60 home-grown biotech companies,
most of them tiny, but expects its biotech sector to mushroom in
the next few years, Teater said. Between 10,000 and 20,000 people
work in biotech in the state, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia has just a handful of biotech and biomedical companies.
However, the state has several overlapping organizations that aim
to boost that presence, including the Consortium for Plant
Biotechnology Research, the Georgia Biomedical Partnership, the
Georgia Biotechnology Center and the University of Georgia
Biotechnology Program.
</P>
<P>
   Even at its most successful, biotech is dwarfed by older
industries and can boast only a virtual handful of jobs and a faint
economic impact.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, investors have pumped a lot more money into biotech
than they have recouped. Only a few biotech companies are
profitable, and many are years away from having a product in the
market to sell.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 140,000 people work in biotech in America, a
workforce smaller than that of IBM.
</P>
<P>
   The biotech industry here includes 1,274 companies _ including
317 that have gone public, according to the Biotechnology Industry
Association. About one-third of those companies have fewer than 50
employees. About two-thirds of all biotech companies have fewer
than 135 employees.
</P>
<P>
   The association calculates that the biotech industry as a whole
lost $4.1 billion on total U.S. revenues that add up to $17.4
billion _ less than the yearly sales at BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the promise is real enough.
</P>
<P>
   Science has made such dramatic strides that biotech can
potentially apply to more than just diagnosing and treating human
illness. For example, micro-organisms can be used to remove
contaminants from soil, air and water. The genetic technology of
DNA is used to improve the yield and quality of plants.
</P>
<P>
   Cloning is probably the best-known biotech advance, but that
controversial procedure overshadows biotech treatments for anemia,
cystic fibrosis, leukemia, hemophilia and hepatitis. Some of those
are in the market, saving lives and turning profits.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike some other industries with state support _ like
tourism _ biotech can boast jobs with better-than-average pay. The
average pay for a biotech job is $50,000 a year, according to the
Biotechnology Industry Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Biotech companies look for highly trained scientists to do
research. Even manufacturing in biotech requires technicians with
skills and education. But the industry is simply not
labor-intensive _ a biotech assembly line runs with only a few
helping hands.
</P>
<P>
   So a successful biotech company can sells millions of dollars of
product without the large workforce that would be needed in the old
blue-collar manufacturing jobs making textiles or cars.
</P>
<P>
   Still, while the industry has been slow to develop the trend is
in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   For example, product sales in biotech last year increased 20
percent from the years before, while revenues jumped by 19 percent,
said Dan Eramian, a BIO spokesman. ``There aren't too many
industries that can claim that kind of growth.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
