<SLUG> BC-PARADISE-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RETURN TO PARADISE' A RETURN TO INTELLIGENCE FOR AUDIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN SCHOFER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - What would you be willing to do for a friend? How far
would you go? This is the question Anne Heche and Vince Vaughn
struggle with as she tries to persuade him to return to Malaysia
and save a buddy in the tense drama ``Return to Paradise.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff (Vaughn), Lewis (Joaquin Phoenix) and Tony (David
Conrad) are college graduates who meet and become friends while on
vacation. There, the three enjoy a virtual paradise of cheap women
and cheap drugs. Afterward, the men go their separate ways, but two
years later it is learned that Lewis never made it out. He has been
imprisoned on drug charges and now faces the death penalty in eight
days.
</P>
<P>
   And it is up to his attorney, Beth Eastern (Heche), to persuade
Sheriff and Tony to return to Malaysia to share a part of the
responsibility for the drug charges. If they do, Lewis' life will
be spared and each man will have to serve only three years in
prison. However, if only one of the men goes back, that one has to
serve six years.
</P>
<P>
   This, then, becomes the ethical question: Would you go back?
Would you face the horrors of a third-world prison where you might
face torture or death?
</P>
<P>
   These are complex issues, and in order for the audience to
become involved, they have to care about the characters.
Unfortunately, the film's convoluted story never fully gives the
audience that chance.
</P>
<P>
   The film's screenwriters (Bruce Robinson and Wesley Strick) must
have stolen a page right out of Screenwriting 101. The film's story
seems to be more about plot twists than character development. At
every turn, a roadblock is thrown up, until at times it becomes
difficult to see where the road is going.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, when it looks as if Eastern has lost her chance to
convince Sheriff, he falls in love with her. The audience never
really sees a relationship evolve, it is simply a twist to keep
Sheriff in the story. And just when you think the love story will
move the story forward, M.J. (Jada Pinkett Smith) appears as a
reporter determined to turn Lewis' plight into a media crusade.
Other than this, M.J. has nothing to do but appear occasionally to
remind everyone that she's still there. With all the plot twists,
one begins to wonder if the filmmakers weren't paid by the hour.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the plot contrivances (and enough cigarette smoking to
pay for a national tobacco settlement), ``Return to Paradise'' is
still a solid drama. All the actors give convincing performances in
a piece that could have very easily become melodramatic.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn and Heche manage to have chemistry in spite of being
forced together by the storyline. They are the foundation that
supports the film, along with the central issue of what would you
do in this situation?
</P>
<P>
   In a summer filled with mindless action movies (with few notable
exceptions), it is refreshing to see a drama that invites the
viewer to think, to consider tough questions and even tougher
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Return to Paradise'' is rated R for violence, strong language,
sexual situations, and brief nudity. 3 stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
