<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0327 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2934 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIOVENTURE-COX     08-13 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOVENTURE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Investment paying off for Georgia biotech company; more may
benefit
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A $1 million investment by venture capitalists four
years ago provided just the jump start needed to get AtheroGenics
running.
</P>
<P>
   Without it, the Norcross, Ga. biotechnology firm, which is
involved in the research and development of products to diagnose
and treat heart disease, may not exist today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would not exist without venture capital,'' said Connor
Seabrook, director of finance and administration. ``When you have a
company with no product and no revenues, it's very important that
you have an investor to provide the capital.'' To date, the company
has received about $15 million in venture capital funds.
</P>
<P>
   But in the future, attracting capital could become a bit easier
for firms like AtheroGenics because of the plans by Emory
University and Georgia Tech to develop a biotechnology center,
which experts say could attract more venture capital dollars to the
area. One component of the center, which will be located on
Briarcliff Road at the site of the former Georgia Mental Health
Institute, will be a incubator program designed to nurture young
business startups. In recent years, the Southeast _ particularly
Atlanta _ has shown up more on the radar screens of venture
capitalists. Part of that increase is due to the burgeoning
technology and health care industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the venture capital money has gone into service and
telecommunications,'' said Stephen Fleming, a general partner with
Alliance Technology Ventures in Atlanta, an early investor in
AtheroGenics. ``We are beginning to see the start of a strong
community of venture_funded startups in biotechnology.''
</P>
<P>
   Alliance invested about half of its initial $35 million fund in
biotechnology firms. It plans to invest about a third of a second
$75 million fund that is still being raised in biotechnology as
well.
</P>
<P>
   But while the presence of the center is likely to catch the
attention of more venture capitalist, experts warn not to expect a
flood of money. At least not right away.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kinds of developments (biotechnology) are very long term
in nature,'' said Ralph Wright, a general partner with Cardova
Capital Partners in Atlanta. ``By nature, they are are heavily
involved in the regulatory process so it's not pure science. While
the center will have a positive effect, the degree of success
remains to be seen. These things are not predictable.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other industries, many of the drugs that biotech produces
must pass through a long pipeline. They must undergo years of
tests, perhaps starting on animals before human trials can begin.
Only then can they be vetted and approved by regulators _ and that
clearing last hurdle can take many months.
</P>
<P>
   While biotech companies have gotten increased coverage in the
media, they have received only a smattering of the billions of
venture capital dollars that have flowed into technology, service
and communications firms.
</P>
<P>
   For instance in 1997, venture capitalists invested $655 million
in biotech firms, compared with $2.7 billion in communications
companies, according to PricewaterhouseCoopers, which tracks
quarterly venture capital investment .
</P>
<P>
   ``Relatively speaking, this is just a small part of the
technology landscape,'' said Kirk Walden, national director of the
PricewaterhouseCoopers Money Tree Survey. Developing a product and
getting FDA approval to use on humans could take as much as 15
years, Walden said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A venture capitalist typically likes a horizon of not more
than five years for an exit strategy,'' he said. ``It sort of takes
a special branch of venture capital firm that can wait longer than
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the center will spur interest, ``it won't catch up
to communications or software anytime soon,'' Walden said. But the
``beauty of biotech investment is that when it does pay off in a
huge way, it almost certainly is good for humanity as well as being
good for your investment.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
