<HEADER>
A2935 &Cx1f; tth-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-SPOT-SPI &LR;      08-13 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SPOT-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Friday, Aug. 14, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Tina May at (206) 448-8355.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-JOBS (Seattle) Developments in The Boeing Co.'s
cost-cutting plans.
</P>
<P>
   By Karen West. (story will move in the ``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-ASSEMBLY (Seattle) Boeing announces another consolidation
of facilities which could mean more job losses, in addition to the
news that it will establish 737 assembly line in California.
</P>
<P>
   By Karen West and James Wallace. (story will move in the ``f''
category)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-GORTON (Washington) Sen. Slade Gorton's advocacy for
Microsoft is being rewarded with campaign contributions from
company executives. During the first six months of this year, 23
Microsoft executives have contributed to Gorton, even though the
state's 70-year-old senior senator isn't currently a candidate for
anything and hasn't announced whether he plans to seek re-election
in 2000. The contributions are far more numerous than ever received
by Gorton from the Redmond-based software giant. In 1997, he
received contributions from eight Microsoft executives, in 1996
none, and in 1995 he received just one contribution, from the
company chairman and chief executive officer, Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Paulson. (story will move in the ``w'' category)
