<SLUG> BC-PI14-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PI' IS A MIND BENDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD NILSEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - `Pi` is one of the best movies I have seen in a long
time, but do not go see it. You probably won't enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   If that is an odd endorsement, well, `Pi` is an odd movie.
</P>
<P>
   It is a thriller about mathematics. There are no car chases, no
orange fireball explosions, no dinosaurs and no hurtling comets.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, it is about an obsessive recluse living in a shabby
apartment in New York City who spends his entire life trying to
discover the mathematical meaning of the world, between the
debilitating migraine attacks he suffers.
</P>
<P>
   It is an obsessive film about obsession, claustrophobic and
oneiric. These are characteristics that mean the film is not made
to enjoy on any level familiar to Hollywood studios. If enjoyment
is to be found, it must be sought on the level of aesthetics and
ideas.
</P>
<P>
   At that level, the film is as exciting as any ``Terminator''
movie.
</P>
<P>
   First-time filmmaker Darren Aronofsky manages to keep us
engrossed in his quirky story in three main ways.
</P>
<P>
   First is the visual style of the film. It is shot in grainy,
high-contrast black and white with a hand-held camera. The pictures
jump around on the screen like flocks of frightened birds. There is
almost no gray in the picture: Everything is reduced to a
washed-out white or an inky black. It has the look of lack of
sleep. `Pi' is graphically one of the most adventurous films in
recent years. It almost redeems the years of MTV we have been
subjected to.
</P>
<P>
   There is something owed to the look of ``Eraserhead,'' but `Pi'
is less intestinal, more cerebral.
</P>
<P>
   Also a part of the style is the integration of music and sound
with the visuals. `Pi' is a loud, cacophonous film, and the film's
composer, Clint Mansell, or its sound designer, Brian Emrich,
deserve an Oscar for the way they manage to keep the music on the
edge of being sound effect and the sound effect on the edge of
being music.
</P>
<P>
   Aronofsky's second success is in creating a very real,
believable and sympathetic main character. Max Cohen (Sean
Gullette) is not just a misfit, he is a very individualistic and
ideosyncratic misfit. No mere stereotype, he has his pique, his
softnesses, his confusions, his certainties. And most of all, he
has his migraines.
</P>
<P>
   Those who suffer the problem will sympathize painfully with Max
as he recognizes his warning signs, and the helplessness he feels
as the attacks take their inevitable course.
</P>
<P>
   It is never completely clear _ not to Max and not to us _ where
the delusions brought on by migraine end and where reality begins.
</P>
<P>
   The third successful aspect of the film is its ideas. They are
fascinating. Max believes that mathematics offers the key to
understanding the universe:
</P>
<P>
   ``One: Mathematics is the language of nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two: Everything around us can be represented and understood
through numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three: If you graph the numbers of any system, patterns
emerge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Therefore: There are patterns everywhere in nature.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Max's working hypothesis.
</P>
<P>
   He works with various irrational numbers, primarily `Pi,` the
ratios of the ``Golden section,'' and the Fibonacci series, to
understand the organizing principle of creation.
</P>
<P>
   But as Max gets closer to discovering the mathematical basis for
reality, several other interested parties want to cash in.
Mysterious people from Wall Street want to use Max's research to
predict the stock market. And a cadre of cabalistic Jews wants to
use the research to regain the secret name of God.
</P>
<P>
   Max does not share their interest in profits or prophets, but he
finds himself uncomfortably drawn into their dual webs.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, Max finds guidance and a little peacefulness
playing the Japanese game of go with an older mathematician, who
once gave up the same manic search Max is pursuing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you lose scientific rigor,'' he warns Max, ``the math
just becomes numerology.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the fuzzy edge between rationality and mysticism that is
at the core of the film _ and at the core of the world it creates _
a dreamlike, raw-edged, timeless world you will not be able to get
out of your head. The film is rated ``R'' for its intensity and
some violence. 5 stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
