<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STELLA-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STELLA' NOT STELLAR, STILL FUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MELISSA MORRISON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - The first 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   of ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back'' are pure high-calorie,
four-star fun.
</P>
<P>
   We have Stella (Angela Bassett, Oscar-nominated for ``What's
Love Gotto Do With It``), a fabulously beautiful 40-year-old with a
glam job, an adorable son, a hilltop Bay-area house, a Calvin Klein
wardrobe, and granite abs _ the kind of woman for whom ``Vogue'' is
a way of life.
</P>
<P>
   She's in need of a break from her high-powered schedule, though,
so within minutes of the opening credits, she's off to Jamaica with
her deliciously foul-mouthed best friend, Delilah (Whoopi
Goldberg).
</P>
<P>
   The ensuing three-quarters of an hour is spent watching Stella
giggle with Delilah, bathe in the turquoise Caribbean and _ after
some requisite dodging and parrying _ make love beneath the
mosquito netting with Winston Shakespeare (Taye Diggs), a sculpted
medical student who cooks and has a lilting West Indian accent. In
short, he's the human equivalent of Death By Chocolate. He's also
only 20, but on Fantasy Island, that's of little concern.
</P>
<P>
   This high-gloss portion of the movie is enough of an excuse to
sit in an air-conditioned theater in August. But it scores
additional points for the way it slyly tips the Hollywood balance.
The same month that ``People'' magazine has a cover on ``older men
with younger women'' movie couples _ Harrison Ford and Anne Heche,
Robert Redford and Kristin Scott Thomas, Jack Nicholson and Helen
Hunt, Warren Beatty and Halle Berry, etc. _ ``Stella'' puts a woman
who was around for the Checkers speech with a man who can't legally
buy beer. And, when Stella and Delilah check out the boys of
Montego Bay, the camera slides over biceps and brawn with a
technique normally reserved for junior-high boys whose binoculars
are trained on the girls' locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Then the rest of the movie happens, and the fantasy screeches to
a halt like a needle being dragged across an LP. A tragedy occurs
that changes the tone of the movie from hot to cold, but with no
particular purpose to the story served.
</P>
<P>
   The tone changes yet again after Stella brings her boy-man home
to San Francisco. The difference in their ages (and incomes) rears
up. They fight. They make up. They fight again. They make up again.
There's nothing in any of these displays _ which make`` Stella''
overlong at two hours _ that shows us why exactly Stella and
Winston should sustain a relationship beyond a few postcards.
</P>
<P>
   If there were, ``Stella'' (based on the book by Terry McMillan,
the former University of Arizona prof who also wrote ``Waiting to
Exhale``) would have been a much different movie: an exploration of
what an older woman and younger man have to do to hurdle the
obvious barriers.
</P>
<P>
   That would have been an interesting movie, no doubt. But the one
promised by ``Stella'''s first part had its merits, too. They were
of the double-rich-cheesecake variety, but on a marquee menu of
graying men landing nubile women without a thought to what a few
decades between them might mean, what could it have mattered, just
this once? If only ``Stella'' had stuck to its diet.
</P>
<P>
   ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back'' is rated R for profanity,
nudity and adult situations. 3 stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
