<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2945 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UGAFEATURE-COX     08-13 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGAFEATURE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UGA's Mitchell a 'model citizen' after earlier trouble with law
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Kawika Mitchell still remembers the long, lonely
laps on the Lake Howell High School track near Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly four years ago, Mitchell appeared destined to become
another statistic: a promising high school athlete wasting his
talents. But those long runs helped Mitchell steer his life back on
the right track and led him to a spot on the University of Georgia
football team.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, who was born in Honolulu _ his first name means
``David'' in Hawaiian _ and moved to Florida after his parents
separated when he was 8 years old, was expelled from Lake Howell
High as a 15-year-old freshman. By then, he already had been
arrested and made several trips through the juvenile justice system
for petty theft crimes.
</P>
<P>
   He was shunned by classmates, teammates, neighbors and coaches
and found himself ``hanging with the wrong crowd'' and his problems
continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really getting in trouble,'' Mitchell said. ``I didn't
have any goals and didn't think much of the future. I wasn't
thinking about anything, really.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really fearful that I would lose him,'' Judy Wilbur,
Mitchell's mother, said from her home in Casselberry, Fla. ``I
thought it was only a matter of time before he was dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, a 6-foot-2, 240-pound freshman linebacker, says his
life hit bottom in 1994. After missing 34 days of school in two
nine-week periods at Lake Howell High, Mitchell was expelled after
the first semester of his freshman year. He left with an 0.6
grade-point average, after spending more time in trouble than in
the classroom. His problems included his behavior toward his fellow
classmates, which often lead to confrontations at school, as well
as more incidents involving theft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have any feeling for others,'' he said. ``I really
didn't care about anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I turned around, there was a telephone call to come
pick him up because he was in trouble again,'' Wilbur added.
</P>
<P>
   For the next few months, Mitchell ran on the track alone,
pondering his future.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was out of school, I didn't have any friends,''
Mitchell said. ``I was basically by myself. I was lonely. I
realized that I wasn't going to have any friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilbur, who says she nearly lost her job as a teacher's
assistant at an elementary school because of time spent looking
after her son, refused to give up on the youngest of her six
children. Neither did Mitchell's girlfriend of more than four
years, Billie McCook, or his older sister, Venus Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   Wilbur attempted to enroll her son in Excel Alternative School
in nearby Sanford, Fla., which is designed to curtail dropouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wouldn't even accept him, because his behavior was so
bad,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Wilbur persuaded an admissions officer in the Winter
Park Adult Education program to accept Mitchell, even though he was
younger than the school's 16-year-old age requirement. Mitchell
took classes there for a short time, raising his GPA enough to make
a strong case for returning to Lake Howell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wanted him back there,'' Wilbur said. ``The coaches
didn't want him back. They didn't trust him. He had to go back
there and work through a lot of people talking about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilbur convinced Lake Howell principal Don Smith that he should
give her son a second chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``His mother had come to me and asked me to take him back,''
Smith said. ``She was very sincere in that he needed a second
chance and would take advantage of it. I often hear that, but you
seldom see it. It's one of those situations where you take a chance
and hope that it works out.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell didn't play football his sophomore year, instead
concentrating on his classwork. By his senior year, remarkably, he
had raised his GPA to 3.5. He was voted vice president of the
student government and also was a peer counselor for troubled
youths. He was named to the academic honor roll three years in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the stories you like to hear about,'' said Smith, who has
worked in education for 31 years. ``But I've never seen a
turnaround to this extreme. He's a very, very good young man.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell returned to the Silver Hawks football squad as a junior
and blossomed into one of the state's top linebacker prospects. As
a senior, he had 110 tackles, three sacks and two blocked kicks. He
was the team's lone captain for the 1997 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we were going to lose the kid,'' Lake Howell coach
Mike Bisceglia said. ``A lot of the kids that start out in the
direction Kawika did don't turn their lives around. But Kawika was
conscientious enough to know that he wasn't doing the right things.
He turned out to be a model citizen.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell received scholarship offers from Notre Dame, Alabama,
Florida and Georgia Tech. After spurning Gators coach Steve
Spurrier's invitation of an official visit to the Florida campus,
Mitchell signed with the Bulldogs.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, he is expected to contend for playing time in a thin
Georgia linebacker corps, which lost starters Greg Bright and
Brandon Tolbert to graduation. Although he's not as heralded as
fellow freshmen Boss Bailey of Charlton County or William
Witherspoon of Panama City, Fla., Mitchell could battle for time at
outside linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   If not, Mitchell says, he will concentrate on school work. He
intends to major in landscape architecture in Athens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing that a lot of kids who get trouble, people just
give up on them,'' Mitchell said. ``That's why they don't care
anymore. If there's support there for you, you can turn your life
around.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kawika Mitchell file
</P>
<P>
   _ Birthdate: Oct. 10, 1979.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hometown: Casselberry, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   _ Height/weight: 6-foot-2, 240 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   _ Position: Linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   _ Miscellaneous: Born in Honolulu. First-team Class 6-A
all-state in Florida and a member of the AJC Super Southern 100
last season. One of three Floridians in the Bulldogs' highly-touted
freshman class.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
