<SLUG> BC-EMBASSY-BODIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMBER RECEPTION FOR BODIES OF TEN EMBASSY BLAST VICTIMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ESTELLA DURAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANDREWS AIR FORCE BASE, Md. _ President Clinton led the nation
in a somber moment of remembrance, paying tribute to the 12
American victims of the twin embassy bombings even as the
investigation of the explosion continued.
</P>
<P>
   FBI officials said Thursday the first pieces of evidence from
the bombings in Nairobi and Dar es Salaam would arrive in
Washington this weekend for testing.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,000 mourners stood in silence at the Andrews Air Force
Base hanger as 35 pallbearers brought the five flag-draped caskets
of 10 victims out of a gray military cargo aircraft and placed them
into 10 identical black hearses.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the grief on the warm tarmac came a startling realization _
the relatives of those who died were not alone in their sadness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our family,'' said Sharon Blake, whose cousin, Jean Rose
Dalizu, died in Kenya last week, ``really grew today.'' Dalizu's
body remained in Kenya for burial, and the body of Air Force Senior
Master Sgt. Sherry Lynn Olds, was sent to her native Florida
Wednesday, in accordance with her family's request.
</P>
<P>
   The 12 Americans were among 250 who died in the blasts last
Friday, and more than 5,000 people were injured.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of the family members gathered here Thursday to hear
tributes from the president, Secretary of State Madeleine K.
Albright, and Secretary of Defense William Cohen, Blake said in an
interview that she felt her family was not alone in its mourning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt like someone of their family died, too,'' she said of
the speechmakers.
</P>
<P>
   In his tribute, the president spoke about each person who died,
mentioning small details about their lives. He said, for example,
that Dalizu was ``an embassy administrator who married a Kenyan and
stayed in close contact with her children back in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Harris Hamilton's family suffered a double tragedy,
when her uncle, Julian Bartley, and his son, Julian ``Jay'' Bartley
Jr., died in the bombing. ``You really had a sense that everybody
was suffering the same grief,'' Hamilton said.
</P>
<P>
   Former US Ambassador to Kenya William Harrop added: ``Everyone
there, whether they were part of the State Department or not, felt
a loss.'
</P>
<P>
   Harrop, who was the first ambassador to Kenya in 1980, said
America's embracing of the victims' family members will perhaps
lead to more awareness of the dangers of diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good point for the country to have that feeling of
solidarity and coming together to grieve (with) these people,'' he
said. ``Perhaps more people are understanding now that diplomacy is
a high-risk profession.''
</P>
<P>
   Some family members wore blue ribbons in memory of their loved
ones, and Lori Dalizu, Jean Dalizu's oldest daughter, cried as she
held a large, framed photograph of her mother.
</P>
<P>
   As a chaplain led the group in prayer, another woman clasped her
hands and shook them as she looked up to the sky as if searching
for an answer from God.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton was visibly shaken as he spoke from a lecturn
between the hearses and underneath an American flag hanging from
the ceiling. He reminded the audience that those who died lived for
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came to honor 12 proud sons and daughters who perished half
a world away, but never left America behind, who carried with them
the love of their families, the respect of their countrymen, and
above all, the ideals for which America stands,'' he said. ``We
must honor the memory of those we mourn today by pressing the cause
of freedom and justice for which they lived.''
</P>
<P>
   He shed light on the victims' personalities with details about
their lives. Those who died, the president said, included Dalizu
and the Bartleys, ``a senior diplomat who I had the honor to meet
twice, and his son, who worked proudly alongside him this summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Another victim, the president said, was an Army sargeant who
``told his own father that if anything ever happened to him, he
wanted his ashes scattered in the Pacific off Big Sur because that
was where he met his beloved wife.''
</P>
<P>
   The president promised that the United States would not let
terrorists bully America.
</P>
<P>
   ``America will not retreat from the world and all its promise,
nor shrink from our responsibility to stand against terror and with
the friends of freedom everywhere,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The embassy in Nairobi will be rebuilt at another site, a senior
US official said Thursday, and other embassies will be rebuilt to
meet security regulations.
</P>
<P>
   He assured the country that the United States is determined to
punish the terrorists who caused the explosions.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what it takes, we must find those responsible for
these evil acts and see that justice is done,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After he spoke, the president walked with his head bowed to
stand next to Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Albright, who wore a black dress and a red, white, and blue
ribbon tied into a bow, said terrorists may take lives, but not the
ideals people live for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terror can turn life to death, laughter to tears and shared
hopes to sorrowful memory,'' she said. ``It can turn a building to
rubble, but it cannot change America's determination to lead or to
strive with others to build a world where there is more hope and
prosperity, freedom, and peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said the Americans who died in the explosions were heroes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They knew the dangers of their profession, yet they risked
life and limb for us all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   An Air Force band played ``America, the Beautiful'' while some
saluted and others held their hands over their hearts to watch the
trail of black hearses drive away.
</P>
</TEXT>
