<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Friday, Aug. 14, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Tina May at (206) 448-8355.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-JOBS (Seattle) Developments in The Boeing Co.'s
cost-cutting plans.
</P>
<P>
   By Karen West. (story will move in the ``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-ASSEMBLY (Seattle) Boeing announces another consolidation
of facilities which could mean more job losses, in addition to the
news that it will establish 737 assembly line in California.
</P>
<P>
   By Karen West and James Wallace. (story will move in the ``f''
category)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-GORTON (Washington) Sen. Slade Gorton's advocacy for
Microsoft is being rewarded with campaign contributions from
company executives. During the first six months of this year, 23
Microsoft executives have contributed to Gorton, even though the
state's 70-year-old senior senator isn't currently a candidate for
anything and hasn't announced whether he plans to seek re-election
in 2000. The contributions are far more numerous than ever received
by Gorton from the Redmond-based software giant. In 1997, he
received contributions from eight Microsoft executives, in 1996
none, and in 1995 he received just one contribution, from the
company chairman and chief executive officer, Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Paulson. (story will move in the ``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-JUSTICE (Washington) The trial of Microsoft should be
delayed for two weeks beyond the scheduled Sept. 8 start date,
lawyers for the government and the company told a judge yesterday.
According to several people involved with the case, the lawyers
proposed the delay in a conference call with U.S. District Judge
Thomas Penfield Jackson. Jackson, who has been anxious to keep the
trial on schedule, has not yet decided whether to approve the
delay.
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Paulson. (story will move in the ``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BRILL-GATES (Undated) Bill Gates and Microsoft's public
relations effort are the cover story in the second edition of
Brill's Content magazine.
</P>
<P>
   By Warren Wilson. (story will move in the ``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RAC-COLUMN-VECSEY (Auburn, Wash.) On Emerald Downs. Where the
track stands, how it is trying to create a new tradition of horse
racing in a tough market. The Longacres Mile is run on Aug. 23.
</P>
<P>
   By Laura Vecsey. (story will move in the ``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-SEAHAWKS (Cheney, Wash.) Warren Moon is back, which means
Jon Kitna also is back _ to battling for the No. 2 spot with John
Friesz. Kitna will start Saturday's game against the 49ers, but
Moon will take over the No. 1 offense Monday.
</P>
<P>
   By Clare Farnsworth. (story will move in the ``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBC-HUSKIES (Seattle) Huskies have their first full-squad
workouts this weekend. Willie Hurst and Jelani Harrison, two
freshman running backs, will get a chance to play a lot. The team
needs help at that position.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARINERS (Chicago) Mariner pitching coach Stan Williams
laughed when recalling his first meeting with the M's pitching
staff, when he told them they could finish the season with a
composite earned run average under four runs a game. ``They must
have thought I was an alien,'' Williams said. The Mariners were the
laughingstock among major-league pitching staffs, especially the
bullpen which regularly blew leads and cost Nardi Contreras his
job. But since May 1, the staff ERA is 4.48, slightly above average
in the offensive-minded American League. The slow and meticulous
climb to respectability has reached the point where bad
performances, like Tuesday night and Wednesday afternoon in Toronto
where seventh-inning pitching collapses led to back-to-back losses,
are considered a glitch instead of a trend.
</P>
<P>
   By Jim Street. (story will move in the ``s'' category)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
