<HEADER>
A2964 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-ADVISERS-BOS &LR;      08-13 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ADVISERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON BACKERS EASING OFF ON TOTAL INNOCENCE STANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On the day Monica S. Lewinsky told a grand jury she
had sex with President Clinton, his former press secretary, Dee Dee
Myers, said the former White House intern had no reason to lie
since she had full immunity from prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Myers's remarks last week on CNBC's ``Rivera Live'' not only
departed from her previous public statements but also reflected an
evolution in her thinking about the sex scandal as it has unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   With the president preparing to testify to the grand jury Monday
via closed-circuit television, many of his former top aides have
been strongly suggesting his earlier denials of an affair may not
be truthful.
</P>
<P>
   For them, the presumption of innocence has fallen during the
past six months _ diminished by news reports about Lewinsky's
testimony, the re-emergence of a dress being tested by the FBI for
genetic material, and other corroberating evidence from independent
counsel Kenneth W. Starr's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The one-time aides have used the airwaves to urge Clinton to
come clean with the grand jury and the American public.
</P>
<P>
   Former White House chief of staff Leon Panetta and top adviser
George Stephanopoulos have been consistent in their calls for
Clinton to make a public statement so the matter can be put behind
him and the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the American people think that there's more to the
story than the president has said,'' Stephanopoulos said on a
recent edition of ABC's ``This Week.'' He added: ``I think that's
pretty clear.'
</P>
<P>
   Now add Myers to the growing list former White House aides whose
feelings about the Lewinsky affair have placed them at odds with
their former colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Myers, in an interview Thursday, said, ``I owed it to him as an
American citizen and as my former employer and friend to wait for
the evidence before drawing a conclusion. Over the last six, seven
months, the leaks about the purported evidence have not been
exculpatory, and I was disappointed the president was not able to
deny that there could be DNA evidence on the dress.
</P>
<P>
   Myers said that as Clinton prepares to testify, ``the message I
and others have tried to send is that he knows more about what the
facts are than we do.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``It's beginning to defy common sense to suggest that
the president's statement on this so far has been complete.''
</P>
<P>
   Meyers said her earlier comment on television that Clinton
hasn't denied the possibility of a stain on Lewinsky's dress
``because he can't. If he could have, he would have'' did not
``make anybody happy'' at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   While such comments may unnerve White House aides, Myers and
former Clinton associates appear in sync with most Americans. Polls
show a majority of the public believes Clinton and Lewinsky had an
affair but are critical of Starr for expanding his investigation of
an Arkansas land deal to pursue it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said from the beginning that it was nothing but a
nickle-and-dime, petty sex investigation,'' Clinton defender James
Carville said in an interview this week.
</P>
<P>
   Carville, a consultant to the president's 1992 campaign, said he
felt vindicated by reports that Starr plans to submit a tightly
focused report on the Lewinsky matter to Congress, rather than
attempt to show a broad pattern of obstruction of justice. ``I've
been right all along, and the only personal feeling I have is of
vindication,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he believes the president did not have an affair
with Lewinsky, Carville said, ``That's what he said, and until he
says something differently, I will believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Caputo, former press secretary for Hillary Rodham Clinton,
said: ``We don't know what's fact and what's fiction. Until that
time, I believe that I should take the president at his word.''
</P>
<P>
   Neel Lattimore, the first lady's former deputy press secretary,
said he would be ``disappointed and hurt'' if the truth is
different than what Clinton has said. But, he said, ``I refuse to
go there. I'm not preparing myself for the worse, nor am I
preparing to dance in the streets. Gloating only gets you in
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Lattimore acknowledges that a ``huge fear'' exists
among former and current White House aides that the allegations
against the president may be true. ``I wished that everyone who has
worked for the president and Mrs. Clinton would be part of this
circle that is surrounding them. Evidently, that's not the case.
That's wishful thinking,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As news reports circulated that Clinton may stick to his earlier
denials of sex with Lewinsky when he testifies to the grand jury,
one former aide reportedly snuck into the White House late one
night to urge him not to testify.
</P>
<P>
   ``My view is he shouldn't even testify, and my backup view is
testify and go on vacation,'' Carville said, adding that he was not
the former aide who made the late-night visit to Clinton. ``I was
in France,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Panetta was not the former aide either. Last Sunday,
on CBS's ``Face the Nation,'' Panetta said the president's pledge
to testify truthfully and completely would help avoid a
constitutional crisis. He also said he hoped Clinton would share
that testimony with the American people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has a special bond of trust with the American
people,'' said Panetta. ``He owes them an explanation as to what
this relationship is all about, and I think that will help,
hopefully, expedite a conclusion to this whole mess.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, said Panetta, ``We are in for a very, very long
process that could go another four to six months in the Congress
with testimony, with hearings, with continuing speculation as to
what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman James Kennedy said such talk among former
aides has been commonplace through Starr's investigation and
conflicts with his personal view of loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``In exchange for having the access and opportunity to serve the
public, you should be discreet and not critical of those whom
you're working with, even after you leave,'' he said. ``Over the
course of six months, there has been nonstop opinionating about
every minute aspect of this investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   But are those at the White House listening?
</P>
<P>
   Said Kennedy: ``We really haven't spent much time listening to
speculative talk before, and I don't think we are going to do that
now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
