<SLUG> BC-U.S.-BOMBINGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ATTENDS ARRIVAL OF BODIES FROM KENYA BOMB BLAST 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the bodies of Americans killed in the bombing of
the U.S. Embassy in Kenya came home Thursday, President Clinton
called them adventurous spirits who ``relished the chance to see
the world and make it better.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They perished in the service of the country for which they
gave so much life,'' said a teary-eyed Clinton, who recounted
poignant details about the lives of the men and women killed in
last week's bombing in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
   Ten of those bodies arrived at Andrews Air Force Base, Md.,
outside the nation's capital, where the president, family members
of the dead, State Department employees and other dignitaries
awaited in a hangar lined with 10 black hearses.
</P>
<P>
   As the band played ``Nearer My God to Thee,'' escorts from the
five branches of the military carried the coffins wrapped in the
U.S. flag from the gray military aircraft that had returned them
from abroad.
</P>
<P>
   After the ceremony, the bodies were flown to Dover Air Force
Base, Del., where autopsies will be conducted on the bodies before
they are returned to the families.
</P>
<P>
   One of the U.S. victims, Jean Alizu, 60, who was married to a
Kenyan, will be buried in the East African country. Another victim,
Air Force Senior Master Sgt. Sherry Lynn Olds, 40, was flown
directly to Florida Wednesday at the request of the family.
</P>
<P>
   Before the ceremony, Clinton and first lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton met with 100 family members in a private session.
</P>
<P>
   In his public remarks, the president repeated his vow that the
perpetrators of the bombings of the embassies in Kenya and Tanzania
would be tracked down. No Americans were killed in the second
embassy bombing in Dar es Salaam, the capital of Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what it takes, we must find those responsible for
these evil acts and see that justice is done,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who spoke before the
president, harshly condemned the bombings as the work of
unprincipled terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make no mistake. Terror is the tool of cowards. It is not a
form of political expression and certainly not a manifestation of
religious faith. It is murder, plain and simple. And those who
perpetrate it, finance it or otherwise support it, must be opposed
by all decent people,'' said Albright, who accompanied the bodies
from Ramstein Air Base, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen, who spoke first, said that ``we
can never allow terrorists to diminish our determination to press
on with the inspiring work of those who have been taken from us.''
</P>
<P>
   The speakers also noted that 245 Kenyans and Tanzanians died as
a result of the blasts.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony took place as officials debated the security of
U.S. embassies around the world. Earlier this week, Undersecretary
of State Thomas Pickering acknowledged that the U.S. Ambassador to
Kenya, Prudence Bushnell, had expressed concern that the embassy in
Nairobi was not secure.
</P>
<P>
   Colleagues and family who had come to mourn the deceased said
they were always aware that overseas assignments posed great risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a fear come to realization, It was always in the back
of our minds,'' said Lynn Powell, a relative of two people killed
in the embassy blast _ Counsel General Julian Bartley, 55, and his
21-year old son, Jay, who had a summer job at the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   Powell said that the senior Bartley's daughter was visiting her
in Nashville, Tenn., when the bombing occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very emotional,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Adams, a State Department employee who attended the
ceremony, said she was well aware of the security problems in
Nairobi because she worked there from 1991-93.
</P>
<P>
   Adams said she always felt insecure in the building because it
was in the middle of the bustling city, unlike many other nations'
embassies which were located behind gates on large lots in
Nairobi's suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   But Adams said her concerns were dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me the panic attack I had was (because of) the
altitude,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Adams said she knew several of the people killed in the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep thinking something like that could happen to me,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Dwayne King, a 26-year-old State Department intern, said the
bombings have not discouraged him from trying to enter the Foreign
Service and possibly go to Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the dangers of being on the front line,'' said
King, who attends law school at Temple University in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The president noted that those who died were a diverse lot. They
included Louise Martin, a 45-year old epidemiologist from Atlanta
who worked to save African children from disease, and Molly Huckaby
Hardy, a 51-year old grandmother from Georgia who was on her last
overseas assignment.
</P>
<P>
   One of those who died, Army Sgt. Kenneth Hobson II, a Missouri
native and veteran of the Gulf War, had requested that his ashes be
scattered in the Pacific Ocean off California's Big Sur, because
that is where he met his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Others who lost their lives in the attack were:
</P>
<P>
   Marine Sgt. Jesse Aliganga, 21, of Tallahassee, Fla, a security
guard.
</P>
<P>
   Prabhi Kavaler, 45, born in India and a naturalized American who
worked for the general services office at the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   Arlene Kirk, 50, of South Bend, Ind., who had just returned from
a six-week vacation to her job as a fiscal officer for the Air
Force.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle O'Connor, 36, who worked for the General Services
Administration. She will be buried in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Shah, 38, a political officer from Chicago who was planning
to attend the 20th anniversary of his high school graduation in
Cincinnati this fall. His former classmates plan a memorial service
for him at the time of the reunion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
