<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2971 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-STURBIN-TEX     08-13 1963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-STURBIN-TEX </SLUG>
 
LARRY McREYNOLDS, MIKE SKINNER RAISE GRADES IN TEAM CHEMISTRY 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Larry McReynolds never would say this, because Larry McReynolds
is too classy a guy. But before the 1998 NASCAR Winston Cup season
is over, Dale Earnhardt will regret the Sunday when he signed off
on the deal that dumped McReynolds as his crew chief.
</P>
<P>
   And here is another prediction. Before the 1998 Winston Cup
season is over, McReynolds and his ``new'' driver, Mike Skinner,
will win a race before Earnhardt and his ``new'' crew chief, Kevin
Hamlin, do.
</P>
<P>
   Chalk it up to that most elusive of elements _ team chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   Car owners increasingly contend that team chemistry is more
important than all the high-tech shocks, springs and setup numbers
in their guarded possessions. Car owner Richard Childress gave
McReynolds all the approved doodads money could buy for Earnhardt's
No. 3 GM Goodwrench Service Plus Chevrolets during a working
relationship that began at the start of the 1997 season.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt and McReynolds managed to win the 1998 Daytona 500
together in February, an emotional milestone for the sport's second
seven-time Cup champion. But by early June, both
Earnhardt//McReynolds and Skinner//Hamlin were failing team
chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   Childress announced on June 8 that heading into the Miller Lite
400 at Michigan Speedway he was swapping crew chiefs in a bid to
jump-start both teams. At that point, 13 races into the 33-race
schedule, Earnhardt was an uninspiring 12th in points. Skinner _
who had suffered through grinding crashes at Atlanta Motor Speedway
and Texas Motor Speedway _ was wallowing in 38th.
</P>
<P>
   As the tour returns to Brooklyn, Mich., for the Pepsi 400 on
Sunday, both programs have righted themselves. In the seven races
since the swap, Earnhardt has qualified among the first-round top
25 on six occasions. Qualifying was one of his glaring problem
areas while working with McReynolds. Earnhardt also has notched
three top-10 finishes, including a fifth in the Brickyard 400 at
the Indianapolis Motor Speedway, and has climbed to ninth in
points.
</P>
<P>
   With some added straight-line Chevy SB2 horsepower, maybe
Earnhardt can begin to run up front with points leaders Jeff
Gordon, Mark Martin and Dale Jarrett and think about winning races
again.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner already is knocking on that door. His career-best
third-place finish during The Bud at The Glen on the road course in
Watkins Glen, N.Y., on Sunday was his third top-five result in the
last four races. And it was a prime example of the rapport that
will earn Skinner and McReynolds their first victory together
before the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Reprising the strategy that carried Geoff Bodine and former crew
chief Paul Andrews to victory at The Glen in 1996, McReynolds tried
to steal one on fuel mileage over the twisting 11-turn, 2.45-mile
layout. McReynolds gambled that Skinner could stretch his fuel
mileage over the final 39 laps of the 90-lapper into a decent
finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry said to forget about winning the race, to get a good
finish and go on,'' said Skinner, who surrendered the lead to
eventual winner Gordon on lap 87. ``I think Larry McReynolds
delivered a message _ chemistry is everything. And we have some
great chemistry. Larry is a communicator. We communicate well with
the car.''
</P>
<P>
   Skinner's recent surge has moved him to 32nd in points _
admittedly light years away from Earnhardt, much less Maximum Jeff.
But in the seven race-span since the swap, Skinner's results in the
No. 31 Lowe's Monte Carlo rank him a respectable 11th in points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't beyond our expectations,'' McReynolds said, quite
modestly, on Tuesday. ``This is a good little race team. I knew
that before Richard relocated me here. It's a very young, very
aggressive team. They haven't got caught up in the Winston Cup rut
yet _ telling you how they did things in 1970-something. They have
an open mind.''
</P>
<P>
   McReynolds added that unlike Earnhardt and his burgeoning
business interests, he and Skinner make quality time to talk about
their race car during the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stressed to Dale to come work more at the shop,'' said
McReynolds, who has guided various Cup drivers to 23 victories
since 1986. ``I think the days of the driver walking up on Friday
morning and saying, `Hey guys, what kind of week did you have?' are
on the way out. The days of what I call the `helmet driver' is
drifting farther and farther away.''
</P>
<P>
   McReynolds said he remains convinced Earnhardt still has the
desire to win races. But Earnhardt also apparently has remained set
about the elusive feel he is seeking inside a race car. With the
exception of the Daytona 500 on Feb. 15, McReynolds never did quite
figure it out, and he was handed a failing grade in team chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   McReynolds never would say this. But before the 1998 Winston Cup
season is over, Earnhardt will regret that. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE BUZZ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Final makeup of the 1999 NASCAR Winston Cup schedule remains one
of the great mysteries of life. But NASCAR president Bill France
Jr. confirmed another piece of the puzzle Sunday, when he said The
Bud at The Glen would be staged for the 14th consecutive year at
Watkins Glen (N.Y.) International next summer. Officials at Texas
Motor Speedway had already announced that the Primestar 500 would
be run on March 28 in Fort Worth. The consensus of the rumor mill
is that the schedule will grow by only one race, to 34, with the
addition of the Miami-Dade Motorsports Complex in Homestead, Fla.
All other venues currently on the schedule are rumored to return in
1999. One scenario involving Homestead has that race slotted for
Nov. 7, pushing the traditional season-ending NAPA 500 at Atlanta
Motor Speedway back to Nov. 21 _ two weeks later than this year's
finale. ...
</P>
<P>
   It is an understatement to say the majority of Cup drivers were
pleased the 1,200 Goodyear Eagle radial wet tires stacked in the
garage area at Watkins Glen International never were used for the
first time during The Bud At The Glen on Sunday. In the event of
rain, NASCAR officials had planned to halt the race, bring the cars
into the pits and have the crews mount the treaded tires and
install a windshield wiper motor/blade to go racing. The cars
already were equipped with a red brake light inside the rear
windows. Championship contender Dale Jarrett said trying to race in
the rain remains out of place in this series. ``I don't even know
if you can race in the rain. We wouldn't know what to do,
basically,'' Jarrett said. Incidentally, native Texan Terry Labonte
tested the same Goodyear radial wets on the half-mile at
Martinsville (Va.) Speedway. But Stu Grant, general manager of
Goodyear worldwide racing, said the tires ``didn't appear feasible
for short ovals.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   Mike Helton, NASCAR's vice president for competition, said
recent rumors about cancellation of the Pepsi 400 at Michigan
Speedway this Sunday were unfounded. Questions surfaced after three
fans were killed and six injured by flying debris from the
open-wheel Championship Car of Adrian Fernandez after a wreck
during the Championship Auto Racing Teams' U.S. 500 on July 26.
``Things can happen and I don't want to put odds on it ever
happening again in any kind of motorsport,'' Helton said. ``But our
position is there was nothing that was going to stop us from going
back there to race.'' Track management has added four feet to the
catch-fencing since the tragedy, raising the level to 17 feet.
Helton said that decision was made by Penske Motorsports, not
NASCAR. ...
</P>
<P>
   Pioneer team owner Bud Moore, like NASCAR, is celebrating his
50th anniversary in the sport this summer. Moore plans to return to
the series at the Michigan Speedway this weekend with Ted Musgrave,
who finished 19th in his last race for team owner Jack Roush at The
Glen. Moore said Musgrave, who has been replaced by
rookie-of-the-year contender Kevin Lepage, remains under contract
to Roush through December. ``They're `loaning' us Ted Musgrave to
run at Michigan. I'll put it that way,'' said Moore, whose drivers
have won 63 races and 45 poles during his tenure. ...
</P>
<P>
   Team Tabasco's Darrell Waltrip will switch from a Chevrolet
Monte Carlo to a Pontiac Grand Prix for the remainder of the
season, beginning at Michigan Speedway. The change comes at the
order of Paul McIlhenny, whose Tabasco brand has sunk considerable
sponsorship money into promotions featuring a Pontiac (formerly
driven by Todd Bodine). The team switched to the Chevys owned by
Texan Tim Beverley after his Tyler Jet Motorsports acquired
majority ownership of ISM Racing from Bob Hancher before the
Brickyard 400.CART
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of the four-race International Race of
Champions Series, two-time and reigning NTB Trans-Am champion Tommy
Kendall has been without a full-time ride in 1998. But Kendall said
former Championship Auto Racing Teams champion Jimmy Vasser has
become an ally in his search for an open-wheel test. ``Jimmy can't
believe that I don't have anything going,'' said Kendall, who
started 30th and finished 17th in The Bud at The Glen in the No. 46
Chevy fielded by Team Sabco. ``He's been telling me who I need to
talk to and he's been pitching my name around _ like at (team
owner) Chip Ganassi. But Chip doesn't want to hear it. Chip says,
`I've got two drivers.''' However, both Vasser and Target/Chip
Ganassi teammate Alex Zanardi, the reigning CART champion and
runaway points leader, are exploring their options for next
season. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FAST LAPS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NHRA TO STOMP BRISTOL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a bid to jazz up interest in its annual nonpoints all-star
race, the National Hot Rod Association plans to pit Top Fuel
dragsters against Funny Cars during the inaugural Winston No Bull
Showdown at Bruton Smith's Bristol (Tenn.) Dragway next summer.
</P>
<P>
   The Winston Invitational was held in the spring at Rockingham
(N.C.) Dragway for the past 10 years. ``The Rock'' is being
replaced by the quarter-mile track known as ``Thunder Valley.'' The
revised race format definitely smacks of the promotional style of
Smith, whose NASCAR holdings include Texas Motor Speedway in Fort
Worth. For instance, the racing on July 8-10 will be conducted at
night and offer the highest guaranteed purse in NHRA history.
</P>
<P>
   Winner of the Top Fuel vs. Funny Car showdown will receive
$200,000 from a total purse of $727,000. A 24-car field of Top
Fuelers and Funny Cars is planned, and the event also will feature
separate 16-car fields in Pro Stock and Pro Stock Truck, and eight
Pro Stock Bikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bruton's vision, we all know what that's been in Winston
Cup,'' NHRA president Dallas Gardner said during a teleconference
on Wednesday. ``We expect that when Bruton Smith does something
with a facility, it automatically goes to the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith has committed more than $10 million to renovate Bristol
Dragway, located within walking distance of his half-mile Bristol
Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   The NHRA plans to implement some type of handicap system based
upon elapsed time to even up the competition between the dragsters
and Funny Cars, which seven-time Winston Funny Car champion John
Force said are from 300 to 400 pounds heavier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to have an equal playing field. If they do that,
we'll give them something to see,'' Force said. ``It's going to be
a race like nobody's ever seen. One thing we all like is the purse.
I told Bruton it's like a big casino. We get to go there and make
some serious money.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LAST WORDS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all the testing you guys (in the media) say I've been
doing in Formula One and Indy-cars. Just kidding.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Jeff Gordon, on the secret of his three-race winning streak
over NASCAR Winston Cup road courses
</P>
</TEXT>
