A2974 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRESIDENT-FORBES-BOS &LR;      08-13 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESIDENT-FORBES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORBES, PRESIDENCY IN MIND, TAKES THATCHER TO THE HEARTLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ The heartland never seemed so foreign.
</P>
<P>
   Scotland Yard detectives stationed themselves discreetly in the
Marriott ballroom, having measured the number of steps from the
entrance to the head table. A rendition of God Save the Queen
rippled out across the room. And, sprinkled among the American
flags, were Union Jacks.
</P>
<P>
   Reaching across the sea to energize his presidential ambitions,
millionaire publisher Steve Forbes brought Lady Margaret Thatcher _
former Prime Minister of Great Britain, Cold War icon and Ronald
Reagan accolyte _ to this Midwestern city.
</P>
<P>
   The joint appearance, at a fund-raising lunch for local
Republicans running in the fall elections, was a savvy political
move by a man determined to polish his conservative credentials,
don the Reagan mantle, and broaden his Republican base in a state
that kicks off the presidential nominations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting harder and harder to impress Iowans, but even for
us, this is one of the most dramatic events in state history,''
said Steve Chubbs, state Republican chairman.
</P>
<P>
   It could also signal a turnaround for Forbes, a presidential
candidate in 1996 and likely contender in 2000. Entering late in
the 1996 race and relying mainly on an ad blitz, Forbes made a
mediocre showing in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, Forbes is doing whatever he can to woo
Republican activists and lay claim to a fiscally _ and socially _
conservative agenda here. What better way than to invite Thatcher,
viewed by many Iowans as a hero of the postwar era.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in the principles personified by Lady Thatcher and
Ronald Reagan,'' Forbes said at a press conference before the
lunch. ``If we follow their principles and renew them, American and
the world will benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes's local standing already has improved, Grubbs said, and
this mega fund-raiser could bolster his position. The lunch was
expected to net almost half a million dollars _ a hefty sum for
local candidates in a midterm elections.
</P>
<P>
   Iowans seemed to agree that the event was an attention-grabber
and a clear signal that Forbes was committed to party team
building.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's really important to the grass-roots here, and important
to the candidate because of the caucuses are led by grass-roots,''
explained Libby Jacobs, a 40-year-old corporate relations director
for a financial group.
</P>
<P>
   Having played host to Nikita Khrushchev in 1959 and Pope John
Paul II 20 years later, Iowa is anything but unaware of _ or
unwelcoming to _ foreign dignitaries. State Republicans took the
opportunity to bestow upon Thatcher the Ronald Reagan Freedom
Without Borders Award.
</P>
<P>
   Thatcher gave a half-hour speech to a standing ovation, touching
on her experiences working with Reagan, conversations with Mikhail
Gorbachev, negotiations with the Chinese over Hong Kong, and her
connection with America throughout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reagan conservatives, Thatcher conservatives and Forbes
conservatives all belive in the same fundamental thing,'' she said
during her acceptance speech. ``It is the essential right to life,
to liberty and to freedom...which comes from the great creator.''
</P>
<P>
   Grubbs, as well as Thatcher's people, wanted to make it clear
that the former prime minister was appearing in Iowa simply as a
``guest'' of her longtime friend. There would be no press
conference, no interviews, and no advocacy _ in short, no meddling
in the political process.
</P>
<P>
   While Iowans gave Forbes points for bringing Thatcher in, it was
obvious the Iron Lady was the draw, as evidenced by the
$250-per-plate charge, or the $1,000 that some couples paid to have
their books signed and picture taken with Thatcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to see Lady Thatcher, who I have so admired all these
years,'' said Evelyn Fisher, 60, who runs a sand and gravel
company.
</P>
<P>
   Electoral politicking already has heated up in Iowa this year,
with presidential hopefuls having spent 150 days so far in Iowa,
compared with 50 at the same time in the 1996 pre-election cycle,
according to Hugh Winebrenner, a Drake University professor and
expert on the Iowa caucus.
</P>
<P>
   According to Winebrenner, the Republican Party, with so many
potential presidential candidates and no clear front-runner, is
successfully raising money and attracting dozens of visits by
national political figures. In addition to Forbes, Iowa this week
hosts Elizabeth Dole, Lamar Alexander and former President George
Bush. August will see House Speaker Newt Gingrich, Missouri Senator
John Ashcroft, and New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Although Forbes said he will not announce whether he runs until
early next year, he has been busy since 1996 laying the groundwork
for a campaign, with personal appearances in every state,
demographically targeted TV and radio ads, and a barrage of faxes
and op-eds. Spearheading the effort is his Americans for Hope,
Growth, and Opportunity, an issues organization with over 130,000
contributors and $10 million raised so far.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes's staff said the publisher wants to reignite the Reagan
Revolution and take it into the millenium. In addition to flogging
his favorite issue _ the flat tax _ Forbes has seized on school
choice, attacking affirmative action, and promoting a ban on
so-called partial-birth abortion in an effort to ``prove he isn't a
moderate in conservative clothing,'' Winebrenner said.
</P>
<P>
   It looks like Forbes's strategy is paying off.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are a lot more open than they were four years ago,''
said Steve Scheffler, field director of the Christian Coalition in
Iowa. ``He's been talking about social issues, and that's
resonating with a lot of people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
