<SLUG> BC-GRAMM-SECURITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAMM TO CONSIDER ENHANCING SECURITY FOR U.S. FACILITIES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, who derided U.S.
embassies as overpriced ``marble palaces'' during his failed 1996
presidential run, will consider President Clinton's forthcoming
funding request to enhance security for U.S. facilities, Gramm
spokesman Larry Neal said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of bombing at the embassies in Kenya and Tanzania,
the administration has pledged to request an emergency
appropriation to increase security at overseas installations.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm, who during his unsuccessful campaign also castigated
foreign-service workers for ``renting long coats and high hats,''
has always supported funding to ensure that U.S. embassies are safe
from terrorist attack, Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm's often stinging criticisms of State Department funding
have been directed at overspending on ``inappropriate luxuries,''
such as expensive furniture, Neal added.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Mike McCurry, addressing past criticism
that the United States spends too much money on embassies, said
Thursday that many Americans erroneously believe that up to 15
percent of the U.S. budget goes to U.S. involvement overseas when
the actual figure is only 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``You frequently hear the argument, `Why are we spending all
that money overseas?' and the answer is because we're doing very
important work overseas,'' McCurry said. ``And we need places to do
it, and those places need to be secure and they need to be
adequately funded.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 250 people, including 12 Americans, were killed in the
bombings in Nairobi, Kenya, and Dar es Salaam, Tanzania, last
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton on Wednesday called on several federal agencies to
report back to him within a few days on any additional funds that
might be needed to enhance security at U.S. embassies, particularly
those in high-risk areas such as the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm, while chairman of the Senate's State Department funding
subcommittee in September 1995, sharply criticized Clinton's budget
request of $2.16 billion for the department and its embassies for
fiscal year 1996. The senator also criticized the $32 million the
United States spent to furnish its embassy in Bangkok, Thailand, a
price nearly equal to the $38 billion it cost to build the
facility, which opened in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the American people were more interested in law
enforcement and fighting drugs than in building marble palaces and
renting long coats and high hats,'' Gramm said in September 1995.
The Senate Appropriations subcommittee on the State Department,
which he chaired, then voted to slash $258 million from the
president's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   However, Gramm supported the president's request that $9.7
million be earmarked for security enhancements for U.S. embassies,
Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   The senator's comments at the time drew criticism from
then-State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a gratuitous, simplistic and opportunistic attack,''
Burns said. ``Every foreign service officer in this building was
deeply offended by those remarks.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
