<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VANISHED-RAPIST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAPIST WHO RAN IN 1986 FINALLY SENTENCED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Fla.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHEN KIEHL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Twelve years ago, after pleading guilty to
raping an eight-year-old girl, George C. Sowyrea apparently decided
he didn't want to do the time for his crime.
</P>
<P>
   Free on bail for about a month after entering his plea in 1986,
Sowyrea vanished, and eluded detectives for more than a decade _
until an anonymous caller tipped off police.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, after spending more than 10 years in Clearwater, Fla.,
Sowyrea finally faced sentencing in a Middlesex County courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a white cardigan sweater and khaki pants, Sowyrea,
58, shuffled into the hearing Thursday looking very much like a
benign, silver-haired grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   But that facade quickly crumbled as his victim, now 21, took the
witness stand. Through tears, she told Superior Court Judge Charles
Barrett how Sowyrea shattered her young life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have had a hard time understanding how he could destroy me
for his sick, selfish sexual pleasure,'' she said. ``I changed
schools, I moved to Florida, but I still could not escape him.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she has had many sleepless nights in the last 13 years,
wondering if Sowyrea was harming other children. ``My never-ending
nightmare is finally ending,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sowyrea sat expressionless through her statement. He also showed
no emotion when Barrett sentenced him to 10 years in prison for the
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Sowyrea, a former firefighter, must serve six of those 10 years
and enroll in a sex offenders treatment program, the judge ruled.
Sowyrea was also forbidden from having any contact with the victim
or her family and from any supervised contact with children under
18.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courtroom, the victim said she was disappointed in
the sentence. She had urged the judge to sentence Sowyrea to 13
years served for the 13 years she said she served.
</P>
<P>
   After he was convicted in 1986, Sowyrea first went to Maine,
where he defaulted on a drunken driving charge, said Melrose Police
Chief Richard Smith.  &UR;  &LR; He then moved to Florida, where he lived
alone and worked for a landscaping company. In 1992, Melrose police
suspected he was in Florida, but they could not find him.
</P>
<P>
   The case languished until about four months ago, when Melrose
police received an anonymous call telling them that Sowyrea was
living in Clearwater.
</P>
<P>
   The Tampa-St. Petersburg Violent Fugitive Task Force immediately
went to the address given by the caller and arrested Sowyrea, who
was using the alias George Seaver. He was extradited to
Massachusetts on April 3.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who reopened the case in 1992, said he was determined to
solve it. ``It bothered me that we had never been able to get
closure for the victim and her family,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Middlesex prosecutor Kevin Ryle had asked Judge Barrett to
sentence Sowyrea to 12- to-15 years in prison. But defense attorney
Arthur Kelly argued for leniency.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said Sowyrea is an old man ``consumed with remorse and
sorrow'' and noted that his client did not commit any crimes while
living in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Sowyrea was a Stoneham firefighter from 1973 to 1981, when he
resigned because of personal problems, Kelly said. In 1981, he
said, Sowyrea and his wife divorced, and Sowyrea's life ``began to
unravel.
</P>
<P>
   Sowyrea was dating the victim's mother at the time of the rape,
Kelly said. The mother began to testify Thursday, but quickly broke
down in tears and said she could not continue.
</P>
<P>
   She and her children live in Florida now, and her daughter noted
the irony that they moved there to escape Sowyrea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
