<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. RETREATS FROM PLEDGE TO BACK UP ARMS INSPECTORS IN IRAQ 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Iraq's challenge to the United Nations has
become more acute, the Clinton administration has retreated from
its pledge of immediate military punishment if Iraq interferes with
arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, senior administration officials said, the act that
would bring U.S. retaliation has shifted to Iraqi moves to produce
weapons of mass destruction or threaten its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our overall policy is to contain'' Iraqi President Saddam
Hussein, a senior administration official said this week after
Baghdad had said it was, in effect, ending inspections.
</P>
<P>
   ``That hasn't changed,'' the official said, ``and we may very
well end up using military force. If he threatens regional
stability or his neighbors, we're prepared to act. And we continue
to have a robust force in the region prepared to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the administration says, it is asking the
Security Council and U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan to respond
to Iraq's violation of its Feb. 23 pledges to cooperate with the
inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``In February, Kofi was proud of his ability to forestall a war
with his personal intervention and guarantee,'' a senior
administration official said. ``As long as Iraq doesn't do anything
stupid, what's wrong with letting him try to fix it?''
</P>
<P>
   The official argued that letting the secretary general push Iraq
is ``the best way at this point to insure a united and forceful
U.N. response'' that would also involve traditional advocates for a
softer approach to Baghdad, in particular Russia and France.
</P>
<P>
   With the Security Council on record as threatening the
``severest consequences'' if Iraq violates the February accord,
which Annan has conceded that Baghdad has done, ``we don't have to
worry about going back and getting approval for a use of force,'' a
senior official said.
</P>
<P>
   In the last crisis, the official said, ``we ramped up militarily
first and then had to backtrack and build up diplomatic support.''
This time ``we can ramp up the diplomacy first in a way that is
harder for critics and opponents to object to and that doesn't
allow Saddam to set the timetable.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The United States is urging a Security Council meeting by the
end of the week to respond to letters sent Wednesday by the leader
of the inspection team, Richard Butler, and his counterpart at the
International Atomic Energy Agency. Those letters informed the
council that neither agency could any longer carry out
investigations and that both were limited in monitoring Iraq's
actions. The letters asked the council for instructions.
</P>
<P>
   If efforts by Annan and the council fail to insure Iraqi
compliance, another official said, it should be easier than it was
six months ago to keep the Security Council united and secure broad
support for military action, if necessary, against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said they had expected Saddam to challenge the
February agreement. After that crisis ended with Annan's
intervention, the senior Clinton foreign-policy team tried to draft
their new approach to the next crisis. ``We do learn from our
experiences,'' a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
   Six months ago ambivalence among Arab countries, opposition by
many allies to the use of force against Iraq and doubts expressed
in the United States made clear to Washington the need for broader
support. The notion of bombing Iraq and killing civilians over the
principle of access by inspectors was not sufficiently convincing,
some officials said. That prompted a shift in emphasis, to
retaliation for active Iraqi misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
   Although the United States continues to insist that Iraq live up
to its commitment to provide unrestricted access for weapons
inspectors, the officials stress the ability of the United States
to monitor Iraqi behavior through intelligence and satellite and
U-2 spy plane photos.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we determine that Iraq is reconstituting its program of
weapons of mass destruction or its missile delivery systems or
threatening its neighbors, we can respond with the force we
currently have,'' an official said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also noted an irony. Washington's position might have
been more difficult to defend if Saddam had cooperated with the
inspectors, who could have then declared Iraq free of chemical and
nuclear weapons and missiles to deliver them. That would have made
it harder to counter French and Russian demands for at least a
partial lifting of sanctions in response.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
