<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONDA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Honda unveils new Acura
 &HT;    By Mike Wagner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Honda Motor Co. on Thursday launched the Acura
3.2TL, the newest vehicle in its arsenal that's expected to capture
a large chunk of the luxury sedan market.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese automaker has begun manufacturing the new Acura
exclusively at its assembly plant in Marysville, Ohio, which
already makes the No. 1 selling Honda Accord.
</P>
<P>
   The Marysville plant is expected to produce about 40,000 new
Acuras per year for the U.S. and another 30,000 that will be
exported to Japan and other Asian nations.
</P>
<P>
   The Acura TL model, introduced earlier this year at the North
American International Auto Show, will go on sale in about three
weeks. The vehicle's sticker price is expected to be about $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   Honda officials said the new Acura creates additional job
security for the company's 13,000 workers at four plants in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``These vehicles don't compete against each other, so when one
is down, the other can pick it up. We've been running at full
capacity here for quite some time, but that's a nice challenge to
have in this industry,'' said Ron Shriver, plant manager of the
Marysville factory.
</P>
<P>
   The new Acura also is good news for many Dayton-area companies
that supply components to Honda. More than 400 U.S. companies
supply parts for Honda's Ohio-made vehicles. Honda also operates a
motorcycle factory in Marysville and an engine plant in Anna. The
new 3.2-liter V6 engine for the new Acura will be produced at the
Anna plant.
</P>
<P>
   Acura's TL follows the Acura CL, which has been built at Honda's
plant in East Liberty since 1996. The East Liberty plant also
produces the Honda Civic.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Lambert, spokesman for Honda of America Manufacturing in
Marysville, said the company made room for the new Acura sedan by
shifting Accord station wagon production to Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Wagner writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
