<SLUG> BC-SPACE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Air Force base focuses on space vehicles
 &HT;    By Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ This week's flight test of a possible future
spaceplane underscored the shifting emphasis in research at
Wright-Patterson Air Force Base from aircraft to space vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   A 22-foot-long, 90 percent scale model of the so-called Space
Maneuver Vehicle was tested Tuesday in New Mexico, but the Air
Vehicles Directorate at Wright-Pat is a partner in the $12 million
research program.
</P>
<P>
   The directorate's Trans-Atmospheric and Space Office tested the
vehicle's structural design last September. Wright-Pat research is
also developing and testing advanced structures, thermal protection
systems and guidance systems for the space plane.
</P>
<P>
   The other partner is the Space Vehicles Directorate at Kirtland
Air Force Base in New Mexico. Both are units of the Air Force
Research Laboratory, which also has its headquarters at Wright-Pat.
</P>
<P>
   The program is focusing on a Boeing Co. design that addresses
the Air Force's interest in reusable spaceplanes that could be
launched quickly and perform a variety of missions. It reflects the
Air Force's vision of itself as an integrated force that operates
routinely in the air and space.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Gen. Richard Paul, commander of the Air Force Research
Laboratory, has said the lab will support the vision by shifting
resources from aviation to space research.
</P>
<P>
   In Tuesday's test, a helicopter dropped the pilotless vehicle
from 9,000 feet above Holloman Air Force Base. Guiding itself, the
2,600-pound craft glided on stubby wings to a 180-mile-per-hour
runway landing. Space Vehicles spokesman John Brownlee said the
1.5-minute flight simulated the approach and landing phases of a
return from orbit.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Air Force's interest in spaceplanes, the program's
future is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, what we have funded is three free flights,'' said
Harry Karasopoulos of the Air Vehicles Directorate at Wright-Pat.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force would have to get new funding to go to the next
phase, which would add a rocket to the spaceplane and ultimately a
booster for flights to orbit.
</P>
<P>
   But the White House has shown little support for spaceplane
research. President Clinton vetoed a line item in this year's
budget for a related program called the Military Space Plane.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy R. Gaffney writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
