<SLUG> BC-HARRELSON-JUDGE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE IN HARRELSON CASE WITHDRAWS IN CONTROVERSY 

</HEADLINE>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By THADDEUS HERRICK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ A federal judge who was to decide whether Charles
Harrelson should get a new trial withdrew from the case Thursday
because he played basketball with actor Woody Harrelson, the
convicted killer's son.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Fred Biery of San Antonio stepped aside amid
mounting controversy after he acknowledged playing several
one-on-one games with Harrelson at his hotel gym during a three-day
hearing in Denver last week.
</P>
<P>
   Harrelson, who starred in the basketball movie ``White Men Can't
Jump,'' is paying his father's legal costs. The elder Harrelson is
serving two life terms for the 1979 murder of U.S. District Judge
John Wood, who was shot in the back with a hunting rifle.
</P>
<P>
   Biery on Wednesday had given lawyers for both sides the chance
to anonymously request that the case be reassigned. But Thursday,
following a growing furor that included stinging editorials in the
San Antonio Express-News and the Houston Chronicle, Biery made the
move himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The buck stops here,'' Biery wrote in his order. ``The court
does not wish to put counsel in the position of having to make that
decision. Even if neither side were to seek reassignment, the
controversy would continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrelson's bid for a new trial was then assigned to U.S.
District Judge Orlando Garcia of San Antonio, who indicated a new
hearing was not likely. The Denver hearing focused on Harrelson's
claim of ineffective council, in particular the role a local lawyer
who was also a suspect in the Wood murder played in Harrelson's
defense
</P>
<P>
   The pickup game occurred after the final day of the hearing at a
downtown Denver health club affiliated with the Embassy Suites
Hotel, where Biery and others involved with the Harrelson hearing
were staying.
</P>
<P>
   Though Biery refused to talk Thursday, he said earlier in the
week that he and Harrelson met by chance in the gym and decided to
play after a short chat. Though the actor who won his fame on
``Cheers'' expressed some reluctance, Biery told him they could
play as long as they did not discuss his father's case.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say Biery's actions gave the appearance of
impropriety, which the judicial code of conduct says federal judges
must avoid. In Thursday's editions, the Express-News ran a cartoon
of Biery and Harrelson on the basketball court under the title,
``White Man Can't Judge.'' In it, Biery says, ``Say Woody, how
'bout some hoops?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Biery could have walked away from the game with Harrelson, but
he didn't,'' said the newspaper in an editorial, calling on the
Clinton appointee to ``walk away from the case if he is truly
concerned about the perception of fairness.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Biery said Wednesday in a letter to the lawyers
involved in the case that ``For the past 20 years of judicial
service, I have `called them as I see them' based on the facts and
the law irrespective of the people involved.'' He also acknowledged
socializing with several witnesses who testified against Harrelson.
</P>
<P>
   Biery is known to local attorneys as a judge who may play golf
with them on the weekend only to rule against them Monday morning.
In San Antonio's relatively small legal world, he is known as
sociable, accessible _ and athletic. He played basketball in high
school and at Texas Lutheran College.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end it's up to him to set his own standard,'' said
Charles Silver, a law professor at the University of Texas. ``Is he
not supposed to play basketball with the lawyers who practice in
his courtroom?''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more predictably, Harrelson lawyers said the criticism
of Biery was undue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept of appearance of impropriety is being maligned
here,'' said David Michael, a San Francisco defense attorney who
heads the team representing Charles Harrelson. ``Federal judges
socialize. To isolate them is to remove human nature from the legal
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors involved in the case declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   But critics said Biery ought to have known better, especially
since he recognized the sensitivity surrounding the Harrelson case
when he moved the hearing from San Antonio to Denver for reasons of
fairness.
</P>
<P>
   They argued that a judge concerned about the implications of
holding the hearing in a San Antonio courthouse named after Wood
ought also to be concerned about the implications of pickup
basketball with Woody Harrelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does not take a law degree and years before the bar to
understand that appearances do matter in the relationships between
judges and those who appear before them in court,'' said the
Chronicle editorial on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXXXXXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
