</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGO-REBELS-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBELS TIGHTEN HOLD ON REGION OUTSIDE KINSHASA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINSHASA, Congo _ Rebels apparently knocked out all electrical
power to the capital Thursday and tightened their hold on a
strategic region outside this city.
</P>
<P>
   Ministers in the government of President Laurent Kabila insisted
that the problem was a mere technical fault. But the electrical
failure was taken by most here, from the angry crowds in the
streets to the diplomats in their offices, as proof that official
claims of recent advances in the war were fictitious and that the
end was near for Kabila's government.
</P>
<P>
   There was no independent confirmation of the rebel breakthrough
in the 10-day-old insurgency, but as the sun set on this capital of
5 million, near total darkness, along with a distinct air of worry,
settled over the city.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels said they had broken out of positions to the
southwest of Kinshasa where they were said to have been encircled
by government troops, and seized the Inga dam, by far Africa's
largest hydroelectric generator.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the power went out, at about 3 p.m., rebel
communiques from the headquarters of the uprising in the far
eastern city of Goma began asserting that they had also taken the
strategic western cities of Matadi, which is about 200 miles from
here, and Boma.
</P>
<P>
   By controlling Boma and Matadi, the rebels can stop many of the
food supplies and foreign imports that reach the rest of the
country by way of the seaport at the mouth of the Congo River and
the rail line and national road that links it with the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats said Thursday night that if the rebels'
assertions were confirmed, Kabila would have trouble defending
Kinshasa. Moreover, if the pattern of recent conflicts here
continues, they said, the capital could itself ``fall'' with little
or no fighting, save last-minute looting by panicked government
forces as they flee.
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday night it was reported that Kabila had dismissed
the new military commander, Celestine Kifwa, his brother-in-law,
who replaced the commander dismissed just weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would seem like this rebel/Rwandan force has tricks up its
sleeve that nobody around here even thought of,'' said one Western
diplomat. ``Hitting the Inga dam is already the second thing in
that sort of vein.''
</P>
<P>
   The first big surprise of the war, which began abruptly on Aug.
2, was the opening of a far western front almost immediately after
the rebels captured a string of eastern towns along the border with
Rwanda. Flying commandeered commercial jets across the country,
they quickly captured a major western military base at Kitona.
</P>
<P>
   From the outset, Congolese officials have denounced the uprising
as a thinly veiled Rwandan invasion of their country. Western
diplomats have been muted in their criticism of Rwanda, but they
have generally acknowledged that Congo's eastern neighbor, once
Kabila's most important patron, has been a crucial backer of the
insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila, long an obscure guerrilla leader in eastern Zaire, as
this country was formerly known, seized power in May 1997 after a
seven-month rebellion against Mobutu, the longtime dictator. That
rebellion, like the current one, was strongly supported by Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila has since fallen out with his sponsors in both Rwanda and
its neighbor, Uganda, in part because of what they say is his
failure to control rebel incursions against those two countries
from Congo's vast eastern hinterlands.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For his part, Kabila insists that Rwanda has territorial and
economic designs on his country, the third-largest in Africa.
According to Kabila, Rwanda first sought to control his government
through a cadre of Congolese officials of Tutsi heritage, and when
that failed, simply decided to annex or take de facto control of
the east.
</P>
<P>
   After several days of relative quiet on the battle front, the
day seemed to begin auspiciously for Kabila and his supporters.
Following several days of heavy mass recruitment of young
volunteers for the war effort, the government convened a news
conference at which it presented a large group of generals who had
served under Mobutu and were now promoting the new government's
cause.
</P>
<P>
   During a detailed briefing Thursday morning, one minister
painted a confident picture of the western front, saying that the
government had killed hundreds of rebels and was now essentially
mopping up recently invaded areas near the capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rwanda, which planned this whole thing, is at its peak
readiness, and Congo, which was caught by surprise, is at its
lowest point in preparation,'' the minister said. ``But they are in
trouble already, and things are going to get a lot worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the power went out Thursday afternoon, Information Minister
Desire Mumengi attempted to put the best face on the situation,
saying during a hurried telephone interview: ``What we have is a
technical problem. The experts are working and will have power
restored shortly.'' But as midnight approached, the city remained
dark.
</P>
<P>
   A number of senior government officials were already reported to
be making contingency plans for fleeing the capital. Although it
could not be officially confirmed, a knowledgeable expert in local
transportation said that Kabila had sent several close family
members to the southern city of Lubumbashi, the capital of his
native region.
</P>
<P>
   With no electricity, the government has been deprived of the
ability to communicate to the population by national radio, if only
to contain a wave of panic.
</P>
<P>
   According to well-informed business people, conditions began to
sour for the government earlier in the day when troops in the west
began to panic after a brief engagement with the rebels near Boma.
Stealing whatever vehicles they could commandeer, the fleeing
troops made for the country's major port at Matadi, which is the
capital of Lower Congo Province.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh government troops had been sent to that city overnight by
rail, but rather than being deployed to the front, they quickly
found themselves fighting a rearguard action to stop the flight of
their own comrades.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that the commander for the whole western front fled
yesterday,'' one businessman with extensive contacts in Matadi said
Thursday. ``This sent the troops into a panic. The government has
sent some other commanders down there, but the situation was
already getting out of hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Another government effort at reinforcement collapsed when a
munitions supply flight to Matadi had to be aborted after rebels
fired on the cargo plane. It later reportedly made an emergency
landing in Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
   By late Thursday afternoon, from their headquarters in the
eastern city of Goma, the rebels were claiming to control virtually
all of the southwest, including Inga, Boma and Matadi.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has very little time to turn this situation
around,'' said one Western diplomat. ``It is not like it has no
cards left at all, but the sentiment shifts here very quickly, and
when cities start falling, it gets to be very difficult to stop the
momentum.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
