<HEADER>
A3004 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFINERY-1STLEDE-COX     08-13 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFINERY-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Refinery revived in Louisiana
 &HT;    (EDS: CORRECTS to ``...upriver....'' in lede.)
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GOOD HOPE, La. _ A little ways upriver from New Orleans, some
5,000 workers have been resurrecting an oil refinery that lay
dormant for 15 years. When it is complete, it will process 230,000
barrels of crude oil a day.
</P>
<P>
   To those unfamiliar with the oil industry, those facts probably
are irrelevant. But insiders are raising their eyebrows and
stepping in for a better look because this is the first major
American refinery to go on line in 20 years. As such, it represents
the largest single addition to American oil refining capacity in
two decades.
</P>
<P>
   The revived refinery is a sign of the times. Not too long ago,
there was a glut of oil products on the U.S. market. Today, there
is a 2 billion barrel deficit every day in the United States,
caused by increased use of oil and gas and a decrease in the
nation's refining capacity.
</P>
<P>
   But refining profits are on an upswing, and demand, which lately
has been increasing about 2 percent a year, will only increase,
experts say, as long as the economy stays strong and Americans
continue to favor gas-guzzling luxury cars and sport-utility
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   And just as the oil industry has reinvented itself after the
bust years of the late 1970s and 1980s, so too has TransAmerican,
which owns the facility. The refinery went bankrupt in 1983 thanks
to incredibly bad timing: The bottom fell out of the oil market
just as the company had completed a $1 billion expansion and
doubled its refining capacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shut the plant down in 1983 and mothballed it,'' said Gary
Karr, vice president of refining. ``At that time, we didn't know
how long we'd be down. But the intent all along was to restart the
refinery.''
</P>
<P>
   This time around, TransAmerican is placing itself in a niche.
The refinery will process heavy, sour crudes from overseas _ mostly
Venezuela _ into gasoline, kerosene, diesel fuel and heating oil.
Heavy crudes are more complicated to handle but are more profitable
because they are cheaper to buy than the oil most American
refineries process.
</P>
<P>
   When the refinery is fully operational, it will produce more
than 200,000 barrels a day, offsetting 10 percent of the nation's
daily deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Because the environmental permit process has become so strict
within the last decade, there probably won't be much competition
coming on line any time soon. TransAmerican escaped that problem by
spending millions of dollars over the past 15 years keeping permits
active.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are hurdles. The refinery is in deep debt; it took
a capital investment of almost $700 million to get the refinery
rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a financial point of view, there is a significant amount
of debt on the refinery, but doing business as we do gives us an
advantage,'' said Glen McGinnis, chief operating officer for
Trans-American. ``There's nobody that can take as much of the
percentage of the crude as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Wall, spokesman for the Louisiana Mid-Continent Oil &AMP; Gas
Association, said some of the other refining companies are
surprised by TransAmerican's move to go back on line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they are wondering why they would make that investment
at this time _ oil prices are fluctuating pretty wildly right
now,'' Wall said. ``It's a pretty bold step.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur ``Bud'' Tower of Howard, Weil, Labouisse, Friedrichs
Inc., a New Orleans investment firm, said this move is typical of
TransAmerican's owner, Jack Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been attempting to make a go of this refinery for many
years,'' he said. ``Clearly conditions now favor opening it, as
opposed to four years ago. But I'm not sure it says anything about
where the industry is going. Is somebody else doing to build a
grass-roots refinery in the United States? I seriously doubt it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley would not be interviewed, but McGinnis said he is well
aware that people are watching TransAmerican.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our competitors started out by saying, `You're
crazy,''' he said. ``But in the last six or eight months, as we've
gotten closer to finishing, the other refineries have become
believers.''
</P>
<P>
   And the company is determined to make it happen and to make it
happen on schedule. To attract and keep construction workers, who
are traditionally migrant and often stay in jobs only temporarily,
TransAmerican has been raffling off a new Dodge truck every month.
</P>
<P>
   The refinery's reopening has been a boon to St. Charles Parish,
which was devastated when it closed 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the refinery is back, and once construction is complete, it
will need some 1,000 permanent workers to keep it running.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
