<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT, JUSTICE DEPTARTMENT SEEK TWO-WEEK DELAY OF TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The trial of Microsoft should be delayed for two
weeks beyond the scheduled Sept. 8 start date, lawyers for the
government and the company told a judge Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   According to several people involved with the case, the lawyers
proposed the delay in a conference call with U.S. District Judge
Thomas Penfield Jackson. Jackson, who has been anxious to keep the
trial on schedule, has not yet decided whether to approve the
delay.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for the Justice Department and Microsoft declined to
comment on the conference call. A spokeswoman for New York Attorney
General Dennis Vacco would say only that ``we don't believe there
will be a material delay in the trial date.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department and the attorneys general of 20 states
and the District of Columbia filed lawsuits against Microsoft in
May, accusing the company of illegal anticompetitive practices in
its bid to gain share in the market for Internet browsers.
Microsoft denies any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   A delay in the trial has been widely anticipated for several
days, after lawyers for the New York Times, the Seattle Times, ZDTV
and ZDNet intervened in the case, arguing that a little-known 1913
statute allows the public access to depositions in antitrust cases.
Jackson agreed, and 25 scheduled depositions, including those of 17
Microsoft executives, are now on hold while a federal appeals court
decides whether to uphold his ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the government and the news media are supposed to
file briefs Friday explaining to the appeals court why they believe
the depositions should be open. Microsoft, which has argued that
opening the depositions is legally unjustified and risks revealing
trade secrets and delaying the process, is supposed to reply on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court could decide as soon as Monday whether to
grant Microsoft's request that the depositions be held behind
closed doors, with the option that the news media could later view
the depositions on videotape.
</P>
<P>
   Preparing for the possibility that the depositions will be
public, lawyers for the government and Microsoft held talks
Thursday about the protocol for allowing public access to
depositions, and are hopeful they will reach agreement soon. They
must decide how many people would be allowed to view the
depositions, how those people would be chosen, and whether any
recording devices or computers would be allowed in the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just about everybody generally believes that what ought to be
replicated is access as if this were in a courtroom,'' said Adam
Liptak, a lawyer for the New York Times Co. ``This ought to be no
more or less easy to get in ... than it would be if it were held in
Judge Jackson's courtroom.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
