<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves on deck: Los Angeles Dodgers
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ When: Today at 10:05 p.m. EDT, Saturday at 4:05 p.m. and
Sunday at 8:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ Where: Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   _ TV: TBS will telecast tonight, FOX on Saturday. Sunday's game
will not be televised.
</P>
<P>
   _ Probable starting pitchers: Tonight, RHP Kevin Millwood (13-6,
4.51 ERA; 1-1, 4.15 lifetime vs. Dodgers) vs. RHP Dave Mlicki (6-5,
4.94; 1-2, 5.93 lifetime vs. Braves). Saturday, RHP John Smoltz
(10-2, 3.36; 13-11, 2.85 lifetime vs. Dodgers) vs. RHP Chan Ho Park
(10-6, 3.90; 2-0, 3.86 lifetime vs. Braves). Sunday, LHP Denny
Neagle (11-10, 3.68; 7-4, 2.23 lifetime vs. Dodgers) vs. RHP Darren
Dreifort (6-11, 3.89; 0-3, 10.12 lifetime vs. Braves).
</P>
<P>
   _ Series history: Atlanta trails the all-time series 230-300 but
has won five of the last six season series with L.A.
</P>
<P>
   _ Past meetings: The Braves swept three from Los Angeles May
4-6, outscoring the Dodgers 19-5 and holding them to a .202
average. Michael Tucker homered twice in the series, and Greg
Maddux threw seven shutout innings in the finale.
</P>
<P>
   _ Quickly: The job security of manager Glenn Hoffman, interim GM
Tommy Lasorda and president Bob Graziano all are in jeopardy, and
the Dodgers can barely play .500. The Dodgers had lost three
straight and eight of their last 10 entering Thursday night's game
with Florida, with the Marlins going for a three-game sweep. At 18
games behind San Diego, Los Angeles is the lowest it has been in
the standings all season. . . . The club's big moves simply haven't
panned out. L.A. is 41-38 since dealing Mike Piazza for Gary
Sheffield and Bobby Bonilla and is just 24-22 since firing manager
Bill Russell. . . . There is not a segment of the Dodgers' play
that stands out. The team is hitting .253, 14th in the NL and the
club's on-base percentage (.308) is the lowest in the majors. In
the field, L.A. has committed 112 errors, just four fewer than the
entire 1997 season. And pitching, the pride of the organization,
has been racked by injury. The club ERA of 3.79 is barely average
(seventh in the league) and the club is walking a batter once every
2.5 innings. . . . Second baseman Eric Young remains a tough out,
the fourth-toughest strikeout in the league, once every 16.3
at-bats, and he ranks fourth in the NL with 34 stolen bases. Closer
Jeff Shaw has 34 saves, tied with Chicago's Rod Beck for second
most in the NL behind San Diego's Trevor Hoffman. . . . The Braves
have not faced Dave Mlicki, tonight's starter, yet this year. He is
5-1 since coming to L.A. from New York, getting no decision in his
last outing, an eventual 2-1 victory over Pittsburgh. He has lasted
past the sixth inning only three times in his last seven starts. .
. . On the DL: INF Tripp Cromer (right thigh strain), OF Todd
Hollandsworth (left shoulder surgery), RHP Ramon Martinez (right
rotator surgery), RHP Ismael Valdes (strained right oblique muscle)
and INF Jose Vizcaino (sprained right ankle).
</P>
<P>
   Who's hot: SS Mark Grudzielanek has hit .318 in five home games
since being acquired from Montreal. Closer Jeff Shaw is 11-for-12
in save conversions as a Dodger.
</P>
<P>
   Who's not: OF Gary Sheffield is in a 2-for-18 slide and has not
hit a home run since July 29. 1B Eric Karros has five hits in his
last 28 at-bats. RHP Darren Hall has a 10.32 ERA in his last 11
games.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
