<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION SEES SOLE MATES IN MUTINY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA _ Almost every move the Revolution have taken since the
early days of the franchise has failed. They have the worst
three-year record of Major League Soccer's 10 original teams and
they are last in the league this season.
</P>
<P>
   But they are fortunate that the Tampa Bay Mutiny have followed a
similar path the last two years. Tampa's on-field problems started
when coach Thomas Rongen departed after leading the Mutiny to the
league's best regular-season record in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Mutiny gradually began dismantling the team Rongen created,
and now it is in fourth place in the Eastern Conference with 21
points in 24 games. Rongen went to the Revolution, who have 19
points in 24 games. The combined point total of the two teams is 8
fewer than that of conference leader D.C. United and 12 fewer than
that of MLS's leading team, the Los Angeles Galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   When the Mutiny and Revolution meet Friday night, it will be a
battle of both losers and playoff contenders. Though the Revolution
are in worse position after three-quarters of the season than in
their first two years, they could qualify for the playoffs by
overtaking the Mutiny and Miami in the final eight games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never thought we would be in this situation again,''
Revolution captain Mike Burns said Thursday. ``The expectations of
the coaches, players, management, owners are so much higher than
this. But rather than dwell on what has happened, you have two
choices. You can throw in the towel or you can forget about the
first 24 games and concentrate on the last eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our playoffs. To dwell on the past is giving up, and
I'm not doing that. The morale is pretty good under the
circumstances. It's a good sign that everybody feels we are a
better team than what we have shown. The way the season's gone,
what we have to do is look at what Colorado did last year. They
made a run at the right time. The league is full of teams which
have gone on streaks. If we can put together a couple of wins, we
can go into the playoffs on an up.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the only streaks the Revolution have had lately have been
negative. They set an MLS record for consecutive home defeats with
eight and tied last year's league mark with nine successive
regular-season losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say we have been unlucky, not with our record,'' Burns
said. ``But it is not one area or one player, it's everyone. It's a
combination of everything. We've never been on the same page all
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I've said before, it's disappointing. We're in our third
season and we are in the same situation as Year 1 and Year 2. It's
difficult on players, management, and coaches and everyone else.
The only way to salvage the season is to get into the playoffs, and
it's remarkable we still have a chance to do that. We are in the
same boat as Miami and Tampa Bay and we control our own destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution have had to keep the faith. Their offseason
acquisitions have failed to make a major impact. Rongen seems to
have lost the winning touch he had at Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the start of the season,'' Burns said, ``when you know that
four of the five or six teams make the playoffs, no one thinks they
are going to be the one not to make it. The percentages are so
against you.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look back on the three years, the one thing I would do
is have better players. That's not a knock against this team,
because this is the best of the three teams we have had. It's so
frustrating that some days I want to lose my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Revolution struggle to find answers, their credibility is
being called into question, especially after a 6-1 drubbing in
Columbus Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Burns is attempting to keep his perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather be in D.C. United's or the MetroStars' shoes,
without a doubt,'' he said. ``It's good to play games that mean
something, but it's so much more difficult and hard to feel the
desire even to go to practice when you are losing like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has pressure. We have to be relaxed and realize there
are three teams in this position. We don't want to be in this
situation, but at least we have experience in it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
