<SLUG> BC-MA-MURDER-CONVICTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE'S WORDS OVERTURN MURDER CONVICTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL LANGNER   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Four words uttered by a judge presiding over a 1994
murder trial have led the state appeals court to order a new trial
to a Lawrence man convicted of second-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   In a ruling issued Thursday, the court ruled that Superior Court
Judge Wendie I. Gershengorn should not have used the words, ``or
grievous bodily harm,'' when she issued instructions on what
standard the jurors could use to find defendant Felix Pichardo
guilty of murder.
</P>
<P>
   In an opinion written by Chief Justice Joseph P. Warner, &UR;  &LR; the
court said that phrase lowered the standard for finding someone
guilty of murder in the second degree. The proper standard,
according to the opinion, is that a jury must find that a defendant
should have known his actions were likely to cause death.
</P>
<P>
   If a jury found that a defendant should have expected ``grievous
bodily harm'' to result from his action but the victim died
instead, Warner wrote, that would amount only to manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   The penalty for second-degree murder is life in prison with
parole eligibility in 15 years. The maximum penalty for
manslaughter is 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Stephen O'Connell, a spokesman for the Essex County District
Attorney's office, said prosecutors will review the decision and
decide whether to appeal to the Supreme Judicial Court.
</P>
<P>
   According to evidence presented at Pichardo's trial, he and
several other young men who lived in and near the Hancock housing
projects had fought with a man named Dennis Dietrich the evening of
July 21, 1993. Dietrich was struck by a crowbar and he stabbed one
of his assailants.
</P>
<P>
   Dietrich and the group with Pichardo parted, but one of them
later fired a shot at Dietrich's apartment with a .380
semi-automatic pistol.
</P>
<P>
   That pistol was later stashed under the seat of a car in which
Picchardo and some friends went riding when they came across
Dietrich walking down a sidewalk and about to run into one of
Pichardo's friends. When Dietrich saw that friend, he raised both
hands over his shoulders to show he had no weapon, then turned and
walked away.
</P>
<P>
   After Dietrich's back was turned, evidence showed, Pichardo got
the pistol out from under the passenger seat and pointed it toward
Dietrich. His companions later testified they first heard a click
and then two shots. One of them killed Dietrich.
</P>
<P>
   Pichardo later said he didn't know the gun was loaded, but
Warner in his opinion said that he must have known after the first
shot that it &UR;  &LR; wasn't unloaded. The problem remains, Warner wrote,
whether it was the first or second shot that killed Dietrich.
</P>
<P>
   In her jury instructions, Gershengorn explained that the jurors
had to find that Pichardo had acted with malice. She gave them what
lawyers call the three prongs of malice: that the defendant
intended to kill the victim, do the victim grievous bodily harm, or
should have known that according to common experience, there was a
plain and strong likelihood that death would follow the
contemplated act.
</P>
<P>
   Because Gershengorn had inserted those four extra words, Warner
wrote, ``the jury may have found malice on a lower level of proof
than required by law.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
