<HEADLINE>
FARINA DEFEATS FERNANDEZ IN MUCH-DELAYED MATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WELLESLEY, Mass. _ This was a tennis match that could have been
played on the deck of Noah's Ark. Rain fell, play was halted, rain
fell again, the match was halted again until finally _ on the third
day _ Italy's Silvia Farina was able to defeat the comebacking Mary
Joe Fernandez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no ... never, never!'' replied Farina when asked if she'd
ever had a tennis match last three days. ``It was so difficult
mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more so for Fernandez, who was so upset that the match had
been called Wednesday when she was leading, 5-3, in the third set
that she would not talk to media. And Thursday morning, when Farina
and Fernandez awoke to dry weather and took center court at Babson
College in the Corel Boston Cup, Fernandez had nothing as Farina
took the final four games, winning the third set, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've ever been in a match that took three days
to play,'' said Fernandez, now down to 49th in the world rankings
and making a comeback from wrist surgery last December. ``That made
it very tough to get any kind of momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   To put it mildly.
</P>
<P>
   Farina, the 26-year-old from Milan, had a killer day, playing
two singles matches and a doubles match. Most of all, said the
Italian, she began the day ``by using so much of the energy to beat
Mary Joe. Then I was OK in the second match, but in the third, I
was really ... well, tired.''
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez, the 26-year-old from Miami, had won the first set,
6-1, Tuesday and was up, 4-1, in the second set when rain halted
play. Then on Wednesday after dropping the second set, 6-2,
Fernandez seemed in full control of the match, only one game away
from victory, when the mist became heavier and the courts wetter
and play was again halted for the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really tough to go through this,'' said Farina. ``We
are not used to play like this, to finish the match in three days.
Then you are waiting for the rain. I just try to think my mind away
from the match, to think about other things. Don't think too much
about it. That's what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday morning, ``I had myself a very good warmup before
playing Mary Joe,'' said Farina, ``and I knew the first game was so
very important.'' Indeed, if Farina had lost that game, she would
have lost the match.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez, once ranked fourth in the world, was counting on
doing well in this Boston tour stop, only her third tournament on
the comeback trail. She was irked by her inconsistency.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like being a duck out of water,'' said Fernandez. ``I'm
used to a certain level of play, and sometimes I'll feel it coming
back, but then suddenly, I'll lose it and become tentative, which
is frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Her wrist felt fine, she said, ``and I think it's more mental
than physical at this point. But with time and patience I'll
overcome this ibstacle. And I'm sure, once I get a better feel of
things out here, I'll be equipped to play'' the bigger tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Farina agreed with her opponent's assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, I think Mary Joe had too many up-and-downs,'' said
Farina. ``Like after she won the first set, she start to miss ...
and with no reason. I mean, she was leading but she had
up-and-downs, so I took my chances. I think she needs more matches.
It's tough to come back after injury and be a world player. But she
is still a tough player.''
</P>
<P>
   Farina, the fourth seed, had a choice after defeating Fernandez.
She could have waited until after Lisa Raymond's match with
Romania's Ruxzandra Dragomir to play her next match against Cara
Black of Zimbabwe. But Farina chose to play immediately, losing to
Black, 4-6, 6-4, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   After that match, Farina had less than an hour's rest before
teaming with Germany's Anke Huber in doubles against South Africa's
Nanie De Villiers and Australia's Lisa McShea. That fatigue showed
as Farina-Huber lost the first set, 1-6, before storming back to
take the second, 6-1, and finally _ on their sixth match point _
the final set, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very fatigued,'' said Farina. ``I will sleep well.''
</P>
<P>
   Raymond beat Dragomir, 6-3, 6-3, and will face Corina Morariu in
a quarterfinal Friday afternoon. Morariu defeated Meghann
Shaughnessy, 6-1, 6-2, Thursday. In this morning's first
quarterfinal match, at 11, Mariaan de Swardt of South Africa will
meet Huber, who won in a walkover Thursdayover the ailing Olga
Barabanschikova of Belarus. Black will meet Russia's Elena
Likhovtseva at 7 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 2023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0376 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3018 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STOCKS-AIRLINES-COX     08-13 0376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCKS-AIRLINES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Regional airlines get a vote of confidence
 &HT;    By Craig Schneider
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Worries about the health of the economy have been
driving down airline stocks for the last month. But at least one
analyst is making a distinction between the outlook for big
carriers, like Delta Air Lines (ticker symbol DAL), and for smaller
ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``The regional airlines are less cyclical because they carry
more business travelers. That business is more stable across all
economic environments,'' said analyst James D. Parker of
Robinson-Humphrey in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Business people ``still have to visit their branch offices and
their customers. In fact, they tend to try even harder during these
times.''
</P>
<P>
   Business passengers are also less sensitive about flight costs
than leisure travelers, who tend to cut back on their discretionary
spending and skip a trip, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Parker's assessment differs somewhat from that of CIBC analyst
Julius Maldutis, who asserted airlines will stay strong even in a
downturn.
</P>
<P>
   Parker agreed with Maldutis' point that airlines have been
strengthened by their ability to sell more tickets, at reduced
distribution costs, over the Internet. But Parker asserted that a
recession would soften the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Both Parker and Maldutis are bullish on the industry's future.
But Parker has higher hopes for the regionals, citing their leaner
corporate structure, flexibility, and increasing array of 50-seat
jets that have replaced turboprops.
</P>
<P>
   Currently he has a ``buy'' recommendation on stocks for the
following regionals: ASA Holdings (ASAI), Atlantic Coast Airlines
(ACAI), Midwest Express Holdings (MWH), Comair Holdings (COMR),
Mesaba Holdings (MAIR), and SkyWest (SKYW).
</P>
<P>
   He has a ``hold'' recommendation on these regionals: AirTran
Holdings (AAIR), Ryanair Holdings (RYAAY), Southwest Airlines
(LUV), Midway Airlines (MDWY), and Mesa Air Group (MESA).
</P>
<P>
   Airline stocks retreated again Thursday. Among those of
particular interest in Georgia, Delta Air Lines lost $2.75 to
$114.50, ASA Holdings fell $2.25 to $40.75, and AirTran Holdings
dipped 12 1/2 cents to $5.25.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
