<SLUG> BC-CASPIAN-CASPIAN-WAR-2TAKES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASPIAN SEA OIL RINGED BY THE FIRES OF WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (Second of four-part series)  
 Eds: Photos and graphics are available to New York Times News 
 Service clients  
 By FRANK VIVIANO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Zugdidi, Georgia &QL; 
(Russian-patrolled Abkhazia) &QL; 
The death of Zurab Alpenidze, who was chased down on June 2 by his
own neighbors a few miles from here and cut to ribbons by
machine-gun fire, carries a stunning price tag.
</P>
<P>
   As much as $24 billion in energy revenues hangs on the struggle
that has killed Alpenidze and thousands of his friends, relatives
and neighbors-turned-enemies.
</P>
<P>
   This is the Georgian province of Abkhazia, where the backdrop to
one of history's greatest oil strikes is a vicious civil war _ a
war between ethnic Georgians like Alpenidze and ethnic Abkhazians,
fought on both sides with Russian arms under the gaze of 7,000
Russian soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians, who were sent here as U.N.-approved peacekeepers,
say it is a tribal blood-letting, a Caucasian Bosnia. The war's
survivors call it a Moscow power play, a murderous sideshow to the
discovery of immense oil fields in the nearby Caspian basin.
</P>
<P>
   The war's toll, since 1992, is an estimated 15,000 dead and more
than 300,000 refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the fighting began, 44 percent of Abkhazia's 500,000
people were Georgian,'' says Jemal Mikeladze, chairman of a
refugee-dominated political party in Georgia. ``Today they are
about 17 percent of a population reduced to less than 200,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Until June 2, they included Alpenidze. Members of his family,
who fled their native city of Gali after the slaying, are walking
down an abandoned railroad line when two American journalists
encounter them.
</P>
<P>
   The 31-year-old farmer has just been buried in a shallow grave
beside the track. His widow, Eka, is silent, a framed photograph of
her husband cradled in her arms.
</P>
<P>
   Her brother-in-law Jeiran steps ahead of her and confronts the
reporters. ``Show America what the Russians are doing to us,'' he
cries. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; 3 stars &QC; 
 &LR;   &LR;  Abkhazia occupies the western fringe of a vast hydrocarbon
basin, reaching from the borders of Afghanistan to the Russian
Caucasus, which holds immense reserves of oil and natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   Two questions loom over the region's future: Who owns the
bonanza? Who will transport it to market?
</P>
<P>
   The answers will help shape the global economy in the next
century and the international order that governs it. The terms are
now being set in some of the most intense corporate negotiations
the world has ever seen _ and on a ring of battlefields that
encircles the Caspian basin.
</P>
<P>
   The promise of enormous resource wealth in the Caucasus and
Central Asia, warns Azerbaijan President Heydar Aliyev, is shadowed
by ``armed conflict, aggressive separatism and nationalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Within a 250-mile radius of the derricks and gas fields, six
wars and rebellions are now raging. At the moment, none is more
menacing than the conflict in Abkhazia.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty miles south of Zugdidi lies the Black Sea port of Supsa,
the terminus of a new European-built oil pipeline that will be
completed next year. It is also a critical way-station on a
proposed U.S.-backed Main Export Pipeline (MEP) across Georgia and
Turkey to the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
   To the north, just beyond the Caucacus Mountains, is the Russian
port of Novorossiysk, where Moscow, on the contrary, is determined
to see the MEP routed.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden, mysterious flare-up of the Abkhazian war in May is
explained by an imminent deadline, many Georgians charge: In
October, a decision is due from a cartel of regional governments
and western multinationals on the route of the MEP, which will earn
a fortune in yearly transport fees for the nation that hosts it.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian route, according to Vladimir Stanev, director
general of the Caspian Pipeline Consortium, could bring Moscow $5.5
billion in dividends, $18.4 billion in taxes and an annual $900
million in transport fees.
</P>
<P>
   A pipeline to the Mediterranean, which is longer than the route
to Novorossiysk, could be worth even more to Azerbaijan, Georgia
and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Construction must begin very soon,'' says geologist John
Connor, project manager in Azerbaijan for Chevron Overseas
Petroleum, Inc. ``The proven reserves in the Caspian basin already
exceed the capacity of existing export facilities. One or more new
pipelines will have to be in place by the middle of the next
decade.''
</P>
<P>
   Chaos in Georgia, say many observers, provides a convenient
endorsement of the Russian route.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moscow wants Georgia to be unstable. It's in their interest,''
charges Vakhtang Kolbaia, deputy chairman of the Georgian
parliament. ``Western countries understandably require security for
their investments.''
</P>
<P>
   Security concerns are exacerbated by the visible presence of
hundreds of thousands of refugees, who mill outside of
storm-drenched camps near Zugdidi or on the streets of Tbilisi, the
Georgian capital.
</P>
<P>
   Many are housed in former tourist hotels like the Iveria Palace
in Tbilisi. ``They live six to a room'' _ a space that measures
about 10 feet by 12 feet _ ``and at least half of them have
tuberculosis,'' says Tatyana Vermisheva, a physician at the Iveria
who is also a refugee.
</P>
<P>
   Russian military officers in Abkhazia vehemently deny that there
is a connection between the war and the pipeline. But to the 30,000
refugees who have poured into Zugdidi since late May alone, the
link is as clear as the origin of the Kalashnikov assault rifles
that tore away half of Zurab Alpenidze's face.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pipeline: that's why this is happening,'' says Gocha
Tsurtsumia, a former Georgian militiaman in Abkhazia and now a
refugee. ``There is no other reason. We are burying our friends for
oil ...''
</P>
<P>
   The proof is circumstantial, but compelling. Its chief evidence
is a huge influx of arms smuggled into nations surrounding the gas
and oil fields _ from surface-to-air missiles and anti-tank weapons
to grenade-launchers, anti-personnel mines and thousands of
Kalashnikovs.
</P>
<P>
   They are pouring into a region that is soaked in oil _ and
blood. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; 3 stars &QC; 
 &LR;   &LR;  The map of regional wars and insurgencies, with Abkhazia at its
violent center, includes the homicidal debacle in Chechnya; the
Kurdish uprising in eastern Turkey and the Kurdish civil war in
Iraq; the endless factional struggle in Afghanistan, raging within
a few miles of Turkmenistan's natural gas fields; and the
10-year-old conflict between Azerbaijan and Armenia over the
mountainous Azerbaijan province of Nagorno-Karabakh.
</P>
<P>
   In late July, Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev held talks
with military officials in Armenia, reportedly to discuss the
shipment of S-300 missile systems to that embattled Caucasus
nation. Moscow is believed to have provided Armenia with more than
$1 billion worth of arms since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plans to strengthen military cooperation between Russia and
Armenia, in our opinion, will not further the restoration of peace
in the Caucasus or help resolve the Armenian-Azeri conflict,'' a
spokesman for Azerbaijan's foreign ministry said.
</P>
<P>
   The regional map also embraces simmering rebellions in the
Russian Federation's republics of Dagestan and North Ossetia, which
share borders with Azerbaijan and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The same map is crisscrossed with current or proposed pipeline
routes, and a web of property claims to the richest oil fields.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
