<HEADLINE>
JOB CHANGE PAYS OFF FOR TRAINER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last December, some questioned whether Patrick Byrne made a wise
career move to accept a position as private trainer for owner Frank
Stronach, since it meant giving up his champion juveniles Favorite
Trick and Countess Diana.
</P>
<P>
   It was a good long-term choice, Byrne said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Now his decision looks good in the short run, too.
</P>
<P>
   Byrne has two of the best older horses in training this summer.
Touch Gold, who upset Silver Charm in the 1997 Belmont Stakes, will
run tomorrow in the $1 million Pacific Classic at Del Mar. And at
the other end of the country, Awesome Again just won the Whitney
Handicap at Saratoga after outrunning Silver Charm in a stakes race
at Churchill Downs.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that mix a potentially top sprinter in Wild Rush, and
Byrne is sitting in an enviable position for 1998's stretch run.
</P>
<P>
   ``These horses were developed by someone else, so I can't take
credit for them,'' Byrne said. But he still deserves plenty of
accolades.
</P>
<P>
   Again this year, Byrne can do no wrong. Although he is clearly a
top-rate trainer, his stratospheric 36 percent win rate last year
was thought to be somewhat of a fluke. Yet he is maintaining that
percentage again this year, while juggling many more balls in the
widespread Stronach horse empire.
</P>
<P>
   Touch Gold is unquestionably the star of the stable, Byrne said,
insisting that he is a more talented runner than Awesome Again.
</P>
<P>
   In today's Pacific Classic, 8-5 Touch Gold faces the 6-5 entry
of Gentlemen and Puerto Madero, along with Free House and five
other rivals. His chronic hoof problems of last year appear behind
him, and if all goes well today, Touch Gold could be on a possible
collision course with division leader Skip Away for the Nov. 7
Breeders' Cup Classic, if they don't meet before then.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Awesome Again could tackle Skip Away in Monmouth's
Iselin Handicap on Aug. 30, if Byrne judges the weight assignments
as fair.
</P>
<P>
   Byrne said he plans to keep Touch Gold and Awesome Again running
in different races until the Breeders' Cup program at Churchill
Downs.
</P>
<P>
   Byrne's new career path has seemed even more fortuitous as the
stock of Favorite Trick and Countess Diana has plummeted. Neither
has met lofty expectations as 3-year-olds, although Favorite Trick
captured last weekend's Jim Dandy Stakes at Saratoga for trainer
Bill Mott.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, Favorite Trick's undefeated horse-of-the-year
campaign last season was an impossible act to follow.
</P>
<P>
   But so was Byrne's incredible year, and so far, he is staying on
course quite nicely.
</P>
<P>
   The buzz
Woodman recovers
</P>
<P>
   The condition of Woody Stephens, the 84-year-old former trainer
who has been battling emphysema for years, is improving, according
to wire reports. Stephens, most famous for saddling five
consecutive Belmont Stakes winners, has been carrying a portable
oxygen tank since 1990 and was recently hospitalized in Miami.
Deserved honor
</P>
<P>
   Few racing fans have ever heard of Ansel Williamson, who last
week became only the fourth black to be inducted into the National
Racing Hall of Fame. But his mark on the sport is indelible. In
1875, the ex-slave trained Aristides to win the first Kentucky
Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, Aristides' jockey, Oliver Lewis, also was black.
Rest of the story
</P>
<P>
   What if Pete Rose had been suspended from baseball not just for
gambling on the sport, but for offering bribes to other players to
``fix'' the outcome of games? If Rose had crossed that line, would
there be any controversy about his Hall of Fame credentials?
Probably not.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he picked the wrong sport.
</P>
<P>
   As the NTRA tries to overcome public concerns about the
integrity of racing, the sport's Hall of Fame has just enshrined
jockey Jacinto Vasquez, now 54, who won nearly 6,000 races in a
successful career that ended two years ago. Vasquez, who has been
on the Hall of Fame ballot since 1992, served a one-year suspension
in New York in 1984 for allegedly offering a bribe to fellow rider
Eddie Maple, who testified against him. \Nrailhed:What's in a name?
Robbie Albarado rides with a titanium mesh inserted by surgeons
beneath his scalp to strengthen two skull fractures he sustained in
a spill earlier this summer. On Aug. 1, he booted home his first
winner of the Saratoga meeting. Appropriately, the horse's name was
Skullbuster.
</P>
<P>
   For those willing to back a hunch play, the return was $140 for
a $2 win wager.
Hoofbeats
Pick-Six fever
</P>
<P>
   It worked so well for Hollywood Park that Del Mar has scheduled
its own guaranteed pick-six promotion tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Del Mar has put up a guarantee of a $2 million pool for its
pick-six, which covers races 5-10 and thus includes the Pacific
Classic, scheduled as the seventh race on the program with a 5:42
p.m. CDT post time.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood Park has tried a similar guarantee twice this summer,
and both times the nationwide betting pool topped the $3 million
mark.
Still around
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm might not miss the rest of 1998 after all. Trainer
Bob Baffert is pleased with the way the 4-year-old champion has
bounced back from a disastrous last-place finish in the July 25 San
Diego Handicap at Del Mar.
</P>
<P>
   But even after a fast six-furlong workout in 1:12 1/5 yesterday,
Baffert isn't offering a definitive timetable for the colt's next
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm slowly getting him cranked up again, with nothing
particular in mind,'' he said.
Round two
</P>
<P>
   Coronado's Quest won Sunday's Buick Haskell Invitational, but
look for Victory Gallop to turn the tables in the Aug. 29 Travers
Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   In the Haskell, Coronado's Quest held off Victory Gallop's
trademark stretch rally to triumph by 1 1/4 lengths, but the
distance was only 1 1/8 miles and Monmouth Park's track favored his
early speed. The standout 3-year-olds are expected to be rematched
in Saratoga's Travers, where no such advantages should be present.
The Travers is at 1 1/4 miles over a track where
come-from-behinders usually have a better chance of winning.
Etc.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN will televise the Pacific Classic from 5-6 p.m. ... Media
reports continue to label R.D. Hubbard as the sole owner of
Gentlemen, but he isn't. Former Dallas mayor Robert Folsom has kept
his one-eighth share in the handicap star along with several other
partners. And Folsom also owns a similar interest in Puerto Madero,
giving him a strong one-two punch in today's Pacific Classic. ...
Jersey Girl's streaking career is on hold indefinitely. The
3-year-old filly, owned by Houston brothers Robert and Lee
Ackerley, underwent surgery last Friday to have a stabilizing screw
inserted in a fractured right knee. She has won seven consecutive
races, but won't return to competition unless she can come back at
100 percent. ... Jockey Marlon St. Julien won his 1,000th race last
Saturday at Chicago-area Hawthorne. ... Texas-bred 3-year-old
Thomas Jo tied Delaware Park's 1 1/16-mile track record of 1:41 2/5
in winning Sunday's Francis LaBelle Memorial Stakes. ...
</P>
<P>
   The California Senate has passed a bill that could have
implications to tracks nationwide. If signed by the governor, the
bill will permit California tracks to import full-card simulcasts
from out of state. Currently, California tracks may simulcast from
other states only feature races with purses of $50,000 or higher.
... The shake-up of Illinois racing continues. The 1999 live dates
of Sportsman's Park, which is undergoing a $65 million conversion
to a combined horse-and-auto racing complex, have been transferred
to next-door-neighbor Hawthorne. Meanwhile, Arlington International
has decided for the second year in a row not to seek dates. ...
Minor-league Atokad Park in Nebraska has been closed and sold to an
auction company for $1.2 million. The state's only major track,
AKsarben, closed in 1995. Three tracks remain in the state: Lincoln
Downs, Columbus Downs and Fonner Park.
</P>
<P>
   The Middle Eastern influence might not be as strong nowadays at
American yearling sales, but it is still around. At this week's
Saratoga Select Sale, Prince Ahmed Salman _ nephew of Saudi
Arabia's King Fahd _ paid $1.7 million for the highest-priced
filly, and Shadwell Stud's Sheikh Hamdan al Maktoum of Dubai bought
the top colt for $900,000. ... ABC Sports has signed a deal with
the NTRA to add four new half-hour telecasts of Kentucky Derby prep
races and expand its coverage of the same-day Blue Grass, Wood
Memorial and Arkansas Derby to an hour.
</P>
