<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0381 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3031 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CASPIAN-CASPIAN-POLIT     08-13 1453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASPIAN-CASPIAN-POLITICS-2NDTAKE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ASHKHABAD, Turkmenistan-2NDTAKE-SFCHRON  
 ... economic polices. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By the year 2000, according to Turkmenistan's oil ministry, the
nation plans to export almost $30 billion worth of oil and gas
annually, measured at average price levels for the 1990s. In 1996,
the lastest year for which figures are available, the average
monthly wage in Turkmenistan was approximately $13.
</P>
<P>
   Every cent of the oil and gas revenues will go into a state fund
controlled by Niyazov and his advisers. ``As the president has
pointed out, at the present time it's most important that all the
earnings from the industry should be concentrated in one place,''
the government said recently.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the Turkmenbashi abruptly banned English classes in all
but a few selected schools, most of them reserved for children of
his one-party state's top officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hundreds of teachers were suddenly fired,'' said a scientist.
``No explanation was offered. We can only guess that Niyazov came
to equate English with dangerous foreign influences, with things
like BBC broadcasts and the Voice of America, and decided to shut
the door.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet even among the well-educated, the Turkmenbashi has
defenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``His style of governing may not be to your Western taste, but
the president offers us stability,'' said a young attorney. ``And
with all of this wealth lying around us, we need the kind of
security than only a firm hand can provide.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer's reasoning, with minor variations, is shared by many
of his counterparts across the Caspian basin.
</P>
<P>
   It is the same reasoning that once led the U.S. government and
American firms to invest heavily in the futures of the Shah of Iran
and Indonesia's President Suharto. Like Niyazov, they appeared to
guarantee stability amid the cyclone of change provoked by an oil
boom _ until the cyclone turned on them.
</P>
<P>
   In April, the Turkmenbashi paid his first official visit to
Washington, where he held private meetings with President Clinton,
Vice President Gore, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, Defense
Secretary William Cohen and executives of Exxon and Mobil.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Mobil became the first U.S. energy firm to reach a
production-sharing agreement with the Niyazov regime, joining
Italy's AGIP. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; 3 stars &QC; 
 &LR;   &LR;  The obsession with stability in the Caspian basin is not simply
based on paranoid fears, inflamed by opportunistic strongmen.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to half a dozen unresolved wars and civil conflicts,
the area's periphery is swamped by a rising tide of Islamic
fundamentalism. Its source is not Iran, which observes the dictates
of Shiite Islam, but the extremist fringe of a rival Sunni movement
called ``Wahabism.''
</P>
<P>
   The movement is growing rapidly in the north Caucasus, and has
provoked pitched battles with security forces in Chechnya and the
Russian Federation's republic of Dagestan. A similar Wahabist
campaign is under way just east of the oil-producing nations in
Uzbekistan and Tajikistan.
</P>
<P>
   Although the two largest oil producers, Azerbaijan and
Kazakhstan, are predominantly Muslim, they share a long-standing
tradition of secularism. Veiled women are rarely seen in their
cities, and explicitly Islamic political activism is discouraged or
outlawed.
</P>
<P>
   The worry is that the rapid pace of change set in motion by the
energy boom _ which is creating dangerous new social divisions, as
well as promising new opportunities _ will open the doors to
Wahabist radicalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our countries do not accept extremism,'' Kazakhstan president
Nursultan Nazarbayev said at a press conference in June. ``But this
problem does exist, and we cannot ignore that it does.''
</P>
<P>
   Of more immediate concern across the Caspian basin, however, are
recent memories of the turmoil that erupted with the collapse of
the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   In Azerbaijan, Heydar Aliyev's re-ascent to power in late 1993
followed five years of war with Armenia in the province of
Nagorno-Karabakh and three years of unremitting domestic chaos.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't walk the streets in Baku after evening fell,''
said a former staff member of Pennzoil, a U.S. oil firm. ``They
were full of belligerent young men with guns, self-appointed
`partisans' from Karabakh who were under no one's control.''
</P>
<P>
   Aliyev quickly signed a cease-fire with Armenia, which has
remained in effect despite frequent skirmishes. During the next 24
months, his regime was challenged by three coup attempts; they were
immediately quashed by police and army forces. Former prime
minister Suret Huseinov, who is suspected of organizing the coups,
went on trial July 13 for treason.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Baku is the most secure and prosperous major city in the
region. ``There is a crucial connection between our success in
attracting oil contracts, and the president's power to achieve a
cease-fire in Karabakh and stabilize the political situation in
Baku,'' an Azeri diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   But opposition parties claim that the stability has been
purchased at the cost of genuine democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Azerbaijan's parliament, the Milli Mejlis, is little
more than a cheering section for the president. This spring it
approved his proposal for a controversial package of new laws by a
vote of 89 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Aliyev will run for a second term. The main
opposition party, the Popular Front, is calling for a boycott of
the election unless he rescinds a law authorizing the government
itself to appoint the Central Elections Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Several Popular Front leaders, including the party's chairman
and his deputy, were arrested in May when they marched to the
legislature in a protest demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Senate Foreign Relations Committee has also criticized
the law, which effectively permits Aliyev to control how the
elections are conducted.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Senate committee recently passed the Silk Road
Act, an administration-backed bill that would lift a ban on U.S.
aid to Azerbaijan and give it the status of a ``priority nation''
in American policymaking. ``Stability in this region is of the
utmost importance,'' a Western diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   Georgians offer a similar rationale for backing Eduard
Shevardnadze.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before he became president, we were overrun by the
Mkhedroni,'' says insurance executive Shalva Kochladze, referring
to ``armed groups'' of militiamen that were originally established
to fight in the secessionist war in Abkhazia.
</P>
<P>
   They evolved into gangs that fought bloody turf battles in the
nation's cities. ``The Mkhedroni are gone now, and we have a
crackdown by Shevardnadze to thank for it,'' Kochladze says.
</P>
<P>
   As in Indonesia three decades ago, when Suharto assumed power
amid widespread chaos and bloodshed, peace in the streets is
regarded here as its own vindication. But the trade-off is fragile,
no matter how firm the hand of autocracy _ another lesson from
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   With the passage of time, the argument for strongman rule
inevitably collides with the attractions of change, in the shape of
foreign influences that are almost impossible to suppress in an era
of satellite television and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the primary source of seduction is often the United
States, despite its own obsession with stability in the developing
world and its long history of support for leaders who promise it.
</P>
<P>
   ``America symbolizes a place where you can do anything you like.
Dress as you like, think as you like, act as you like,'' said
Leila, 17, a pre-law student in Baku. ``That must be our future,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Her words were enough to provoke anger in Raschad Bayramov, 19,
who overheard the young woman's conversation with a foreign
journalist. ``She's from a rich family, from the nomenklatura,''
said Bayramov, who described himself as ``old-fashioned'' and not
ashamed of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who gather here do nothing,'' Bayramov added, as
Leila turned her back on him and walked away. ``They live on their
parents' money.''
</P>
<P>
   In that brief exchange are echoes of Iran a generation ago, of
Nigeria and Indonesia today.
</P>
<P>
   The enormous oil boom in the Caspian basin promises to alter
everything in its path _ to erect a new El Dorado in desert wastes,
fuel the economies of the United States and Europe, and re-order
the global economy.
</P>
<P>
   It will also imperil thousands of years of tradition, setting
its defenders against the tide of a glittering but deeply uncertain
future.
</P>
<P>
   From the gas fields of eastern Turkmenistan to the pipeline
terminals that send oil west to America and Europe, the Caspian
bonanza will destroy as much as it builds, and the history of the
21st century will be written.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
