<HEADER>
A3033 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CASPIAN-CASPIAN-POLIT     08-13 1223
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASPIAN-CASPIAN-POLITICS-2TAKES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CASPIAN REGION, BLACK GOLD COMBINES WITH IRON RULE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Last of four-part series)  
 Eds: Photos and graphics are available to New York Times News 
 Service clients  
 By FRANK VIVIANO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; ASHKHABAD, Turkmenistan _ A time-traveler from the 1980s
would be dazed by the capitals of former Soviet Central Asia and
the Caucasus. From Turkmenistan to the Black Sea, an energy boom
has swept through on an enormous wave of dollars, leaving few
reminders of the gray era of Leonid Brezhnev.
</P>
<P>
   Except for his fellow Soviet leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Almost as striking as the effect of the boom _ which has filled
the region surrounding the Caspian Sea with overnight millionaires,
luxury apartment towers, casinos and limousines _ is the area's
utterly familiar cast of strongmen.
</P>
<P>
   The president of Turkmenistan is Saparmurat Niyazov, former
chairman of the Supreme Soviet in Ashkhabad. The president of
oil-rich Azerbaijan is Heydar Aliyev, former Communist Party
secretary and KGB director of his republic. Their counterparts in
the Georgian Republic and Kazakhstan, presidents Eduard
Shevardnadze and Nursultan Nazarbayev, served on the Soviet
politburo.
</P>
<P>
   The past, personified by the men who governed here when the
Soviet Union was a superpower, is in charge of the Caspian basin's
glittering future.
</P>
<P>
   These men are the principal partners of more than 50 major
energy companies and other multinationals _ including Unocal,
Bechtel and Chevron from California, Elf and Total from France,
Britain's BP and Holland's Royal Dutch Shell, Norway's Statoil,
Italy's AGIP and Itochu of Japan _ which are bankrolling and
drilling the Caspian basin's oil and gas fields.
</P>
<P>
   Every one of the region's Soviet holdovers has been accorded a
state visit to Washington by the Clinton Administration, which has
made relations with the Caspian presidents a top foreign policy
priority.
</P>
<P>
   Some have improved their policies and images, and have set out
to modernize their nations. Others have embraced a political model
that is older than Brezhnev's Moscow, and far more autocratic.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere are the anachronism or the autocracy more entrenched
than in Turkmenistan, where the 21st century is dawning under a
regime that could have been inspired by Josef Stalin or Mao Zedong.
</P>
<P>
   The president has gone so far as to rename himself
``Turkmenbashi'' _ ``Chieftain of the Turkmen'' _ in unspoken
homage to China's Great Helmsman.
</P>
<P>
   He has also rechristened Krasnovodsk, his country's main Caspian
seaport, as ``Turkmenbashi City.''
</P>
<P>
   The Turkmenbashi's plump face smiles down from giant posters on
almost every building in Ashkhabad, including its casinos and
foreign-owned hotels. It appears on thousands of banners strung
across the nation's streets, along with an endlessly repeated
slogan that proclaims ``Halk! Watan! Turkmenbashi!'' _ ``People!
Motherland! Chieftain of the Turkmen!''
</P>
<P>
   When a viewer tunes into the government-operated (and only)
Turkmen-language television station, an image of the Turkmenbashi
appears in the screen's upper right-hand corner. It remains there
throughout the nonstop documentaries on the president's activities
that constitutes all of the programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turkmen history has endowed the leader with a whole complex of
psychological qualities that have enabled him to conceive and put
into reality the unique Turkmen notion of neutrality,'' Lyudmilla
Glazovskaya wrote in the spring issue of an Ashkhabad magazine,
alluding to the Turkmenbashi's nonaligned foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   In a nation where ``democracy'' is little more than a ceremonial
word used to describe one man's monopoly on power, the effect of
his personality cult is mind-numbing.
</P>
<P>
   When a referendum was held in 1994 to extend the Turkmenbashi's
rule until 2002 without an election, the official results were
1,959,408 votes in favor and 212 against.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one dared speak out about the referendum,'' said a merchant
in Ashkhabad. ``Almost no one speaks out about anything in our
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond occasional discreet gatherings where Turkmenistan's few
university-educated or foreign-connected citizens express their
dissent _ in secret, at enormous risk _ Niyazov's self-glorifying
rule is passively accepted by most Turkmen. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; 3 stars &QC; 
 &LR;   &LR;  In part, that is because the majority of the 3.8 million
Turkmen do not live in Ashkhabad or Turkmenbashi City, which are
home to the country's 400,000 Russian-speaking residents from other
ex-Soviet republics and the small Turkmen middle class.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the city limits, the average Turkmen's life, for the
moment, is even more unchanging than the roster of Caspian
presidents.
</P>
<P>
   More than 2 million Turkmen live in yurts, camel-skin tents
pitched outside of remote oases on the vast Kara Kum Desert, where
they dine on grilled camel kabobs washed down by camel's milk. They
break camp periodically, to move on to another oasis, or to meet by
the tens of thousands at the Tolkuchka Bazaar.
</P>
<P>
   Located about five miles north of Ashkhabad, the Tolkuchka is
the largest remaining outpost on the ancient Silk Route, the
8,000-mile necklace of trading centers that linked Europe and China
for more than 20 centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Along one end of the unimaginably crowded bazaar _ tolkuchka
translates as ``pushing'' _ modern consumerism is making gradual
inroads, led by cheap wristwatches from Russia,
Turkish-manufactured portable stoves and Iranian soaps and
detergents.
</P>
<P>
   But the principal goods for sale here remain what they were
2,300 years ago, when Alexander the Great rode through on his way
to India. Garbed in long silver-bedecked gowns and head scarves,
women merchandise a vast array of hand-loomed silk and wool carpets
_ ``the most beautiful in the world,'' Marco Polo said after his
visit in the 13th century.
</P>
<P>
   Half a mile away, men in desert tunics and enormous shaggy wool
hats barter over racing ponies, herds of sheep unloaded from rusted
ex-Soviet Army trucks and the inevitable camels. ``Excellent meat,
sir, you won't be disappointed,'' a merchant said, patting his
animal on the hump. ``The price is just $450.''
</P>
<P>
   The merchant's customers showed little interest when asked their
opinion of the Niyazov regime. ``These are people whose ancestral
memory includes history's most tyrannical depots, from Tamurlane
and Genghis Khan to Stalin, and their culture has survived them
all,'' said an academic in the capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their point of reference is a brutal desert, where absolute
obedience to a tribal leader is the line between life and death.
Parliamentary democracy is meaningless to them.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is not meaningless to the academic. Like almost everyone
who spoke with two American reporters in Turkmenistan, he asked
that his name be withheld. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; 3 stars &QC; 
 &LR;   &LR;  The discretion is well-advised. Any affront to the Turkmenbashi
is a serious offense in his dominions.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sister was imprisoned for complaining about a food
shortage,'' a university student said. ``All that she said was,
`What kind of country is it that has so much oil and gas, but not
enough bread?' Two days later, she was in jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Her question, overheard by one of the regime's legions of
undercover spies, was interpreted as criticism of the
Turkmenbashi's economic policies.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
