<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3035 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOODSTOCK-CONCERT-ART     08-13 1367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOODSTOCK-CONCERT-ART-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MORE SEDATE WOODSTOCK TRIES TO LURE YUPPIES, NOT HIPPIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By ANDREW C. REVKIN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHEL, N.Y. _ Twenty-nine years ago, people came here by the
tens, and then hundreds, of thousands, abandoning spray-painted
Volkswagen buses and bumper-stickered cars along clogged roads,
walking for miles to the festival of rock 'n' roll called
Woodstock.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, a few thousand of the original Woodstock
generation and their progeny returned each August to pitch homemade
tents, beat drums, and dance at the hallowed 37-acre concert site,
trying to recapture those free-loving days.
</P>
<P>
   But not any more. Five miles of split-rail fencing sprouted this
summer around Max Yasgur's hayfield, which has been bought and
tamed by a billionaire whose goal with a concert series this
weekend was to leverage the legend of Woodstock, luring
buttoned-down yuppies, not rainbow-clad hippies, to this
long-depressed southern flank of the Catskills.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only thing we have up here in Sullivan County that
has a national brand name,'' said Alan Gerry, 69, a native of the
county who became the ultimate cable guy three years ago when Time
Warner bought his cable television company for $2.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The transformation of the ad hoc concert grounds into a fenced
commercial enterprise appalled many self-described ``Woodstockers''
around the region, who have protested for two years _ through civil
disobedience and lawsuits _ that the field is a public shrine to a
state of mind, not a piece of private real estate where one can
charge admission.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Gerry's done is, he's bought the church and run off the
congregation,'' said Abigail Storm, a bead-wearing Woodstock
pilgrim from the nearby town of Monticello who runs the Woodstock
Nation Foundation with her husband, Daniel Eggink. The nonprofit
group, which exists mainly on the World Wide Web, is devoted to
maintaining public access to the original concert site.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry (pronounced with a hard G, like Gary) said that he
understood the pangs of the traditionalists, but said times had to
change. ``What we're trying to do up here,'' he said, ``is for the
betterment of the many and, hopefully, the inclusion of the few.
But we have to have a chance to get this thing going.''
</P>
<P>
   The festival, called ``A Day in the Garden,'' after a song lyric
by Joni Mitchell, one of the scheduled performers, was clearly
intended to attract a new kind of clientele to a place where
acid-tripping teen-agers once danced naked in the mud and a nearby
lake.
</P>
<P>
   It was being touted as a clean, well-lighted event, with the
first two days of music, on Friday and Saturday, performed by
several graying veterans of the 1969 concert, including Pete
Townsend and Ten Years After, along with several peers, including
Don Henley, Lou Reed, and Stevie Nicks _ kind of an Old-Timers Day
of rock. The Sunday show would feature some fresh-faced bands for
the MTV generation. No more than 30,000 tickets would be sold for
each show.
</P>
<P>
   As an army of workers deployed 400 portable toilets, as
forklifts placed metal sculptures on the neatly mowed grass, as
vendors set up souvenir stalls and a portable automated teller
machine under high-tech tents imported from the Netherlands, the
only Volkswagen in sight was one of the new, pricey Beetles.
</P>
<P>
   The car was painted in a psychedelic swirl of images, but only
because it was a promotional tool for a local FM radio station.
</P>
<P>
   With clean toilets, a ban on camping, and a hilltop beer garden
instead of a drug bazaar, the goal, Gerry said, was to bring a new
surge of monied tourists to the Catskills, paving the way for a
regular series of concerts in years to come, ranging from jazz to
country to, possibly, the New York Philharmonic.
</P>
<P>
   It remained unclear as the weekend approached just how many
paying customers would be coming to Gerry's show. Hotels for miles
around said they were booked for the weekend, with people coming
from across the country.
</P>
<P>
   But for several weeks, sponsoring Hudson Valley radio stations
had been eagerly offering two-days-for-the-price-of-one deals.
Tickets for the veteran rockers had originally been $35 for each
day. Ticket prices for the Sunday show had started at $25,
descended to $10 and now were up to $25 again.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry said that the Sunday show, featuring popular current acts
like the Goo Goo Dolls, was nearly sold out. But sales had only
reached about half of capacity for the first two shows, despite the
discount.
</P>
<P>
   He insisted that those numbers were not a disappointment, adding
that this year was essentially a trial run, that he was in this for
the long haul.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Michael DiTullo, one of Gerry's top lieutenants, explained that
it would take time to shift the demographics of those attracted to
the Woodstock site.
</P>
<P>
   As DiTullo inspected preparations for the show, he painted a
word picture of the ideal visitor: ``Capitalism has been good to
them but they still cherish what the whole Sixties phenomenon was
about.''
</P>
<P>
   He said this was also new territory for a group of executives
more versed in the world of finance and cable television than in
rock music.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're bankers, investment-type people,'' DiTullo said. Waving
a hand past the imported tents, police cars, Porta-Potties, and
fencing, he said: ``This is our research and development.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerry may have rankled aging hippies, but he had the
enthusiastic support of almost every elected official and business
owner in Sullivan County, partly because he had arranged to pay
almost all of the legal, logistical and administrative costs
connected with the event. Altogether, he was pouring more than $5
million into the event through a nonprofit group, the Gerry
Foundation, which he created last year.
</P>
<P>
   For Bethel, the shift to supporting a concert at the hallowed
field represented a dramatic turnaround. The town, essentially in a
state of shock for 28 years after the original event, had gone to
great lengths to turn away the annual impromptu pilgrimage, passing
restrictive ordinances about public gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   But Bethel largely embraced Gerry's upscale vision, which was so
clean and neat that he even decided to close the beer concession on
Sunday, when a big teen-age audience was expected. Town officials
granted him exemptions to the old laws and passed new ones allowing
traffic on public roads around the site to be shut down for what
was essentially a private event.
</P>
<P>
   With many old Catskills resorts shuttered or bankrupt, and the
failure of a recent bid to bring legalized gambling here, cashing
in on the Woodstock legend was seen as something of a last chance
for Bethel.
</P>
<P>
   To deter any unwanted incursions, some 400 police officers and
private security guards were setting up checkpoints on roads for a
mile around to turn back people without a ticket or a local
address.
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted, Ms. Storm and Eggink, 47 and 60, who run a printing
and graphics business with their children, were planning to march
past the checkpoints on Friday, beating a brightly painted bass
drum wheeled on a luggage cart and proclaiming their right to walk
freely to what they said is a sacred site.
</P>
<P>
   But Eggink, stroking his long beard, said the battle for the
soul of the site, and the country, may have already been lost. ``It
might be that our time historically has come, that enough people
have decided that idealism and utopianism are no longer
important,'' Eggink said.
</P>
<P>
   Along Route 17B, there were few signs of the annual influx of
so-called ``rainbow people,'' a wandering clan of vegetarian
pacifists that has regularly camped around the area this time every
summer.
</P>
<P>
   At Hector's Inn, a tavern where many visitors in tie-dyed
clothing have gathered in years past, the only people around the
bar Thursday were three neighbors with silver hair, talking about
their tomato plants.
</P>
<P>
   The only person wearing a tie-dyed T-shirt was the bartender.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
