</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN CRISIS PUSHES U.S. MARKETS LOWER 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also RUSSIA-MARKETPLACE, RUSSIA-ECON, RUSSIA-ASSESS) 
(JT) 
 By SHARON R. KING    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A growing sense of crisis in the Russian economy
helped push United States markets lower Thursday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Russia's stock market fell 6.5 percent. At one point, trading
was stopped for 35 minutes when losses exceeded 10 percent. The
central bank stepped in to protect the ruble and the banking
system, but Moody's Investors Service and Standard &AMP; Poor's
downgraded Russia's foreign debt, which already had been ranked as
``junk.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average closed at 8,459.50, its lowest
point of the day, down 93.46 points, or 1.1 percent. The blue-chip
index, which was up as much as 18 percent for the year at its peak
in July, is now up just 6.98 percent this year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 9.31 points, to 1,074.91,
and the Nasdaq composite index lost 22.99 points, closing at
1,802.54, a 1.3 percent decline. The S&AMP;P and the Nasdaq are up
10.77 percent and 14.70 percent, respectively, for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about the situation in Russia, combined with continuing
problems in Asian economies and expectations of slower earnings
growth among U.S. companies, have contributed to the growing
cautiousness among investors in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asia's clearly at the top of the list,'' Robert Bissell,
president and chief investment officer of Wells Capital Management,
said. ``Russia's in the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   He said institutional investors were concerned that Russia might
devalue its currency. A devaluation could affect banks and
financial institutions worldwide with exposure to the country, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Acuff, equity strategist at Salomon Smith Barney, said:
``Earlier this year people shrugged this stuff off. Now portfolio
managers are paying more heed.''
</P>
<P>
   As a sign of investors' waning belief in the resiliency of the
market, comments by the Goldman, Sachs market guru, Abby Joseph
Cohen, did little to stem Thursday's slide in stocks. Last October
the bullish stance of Ms. Cohen, co-chairwoman of Goldman's
investment policy committee, calmed investors and helped the Dow
Jones industrial average recover from a decline of more than 500
points.
</P>
<P>
   In a note to clients Thursday, Ms. Cohen said stocks were now
undervalued and she does not expect a recession or an uptick in
inflation soon. In addition, the direct impact of events in Asia
and Russia on the United States is likely to remain moderate, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   But that did not seem to buoy the market.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, DuPont, which led both the Dow and the S&AMP;P lower,
warned that third-quarter profits would be at the lower end of
forecasts and below levels from the comparable period last year.
The company pointed to a number of causes for the shortfall,
including declining oil prices, Asia's impact on its polyester
business and declining agriculture business revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, when DuPont reported second-quarter earnings, it
also warned that third-quarter results could falter.
</P>
<P>
   DuPont closed at 55, down 5{ points.
</P>
<P>
   Expectations that earnings will continue to weaken is keeping
some investors on the sidelines, Acuff said, as portfolio managers
hesitate to buy the shares of companies that may soon warn of
problems.
</P>
<P>
   And once again, small-company stocks faltered. The Russell index
of 2,000 smaller-company stocks fell 4.72 points, or 1.2 percent,
to 403.83.
</P>
<P>
   As bearish sentiment becomes increasingly pervasive, analysts
note that portfolio managers are becoming less aggressive about
putting cash to work than they were in previous months. Aggressive
buying on downturns, for fear of missing out on subsequent gains in
the market, were a key factor in propelling stocks to record highs
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   This change in sentiment comes as cash flows into equity mutual
funds are slowing to their lowest levels this year. In the week
ended Aug. 5, $468 million flowed into U.S. equity mutual funds,
down from $648 million in the previous week, according to AMG Data
Services, a California research firm. And in the week ended July
22, investors moved $1.5 billion out of mutual funds, AMG said.
</P>
<P>
   The exodus, along with the general decline in the market, has
trimmed the aggregate market value of mutual funds by $200 billion
to $225 billion in the last three weeks, Robert Adler, AMG's
president, said.
</P>
<P>
   The trend, if it continues, also could herald a sea change in
investors' outlook toward stocks, he said, adding that cash flows
into bond funds have been increasing recently.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
