<HEADER>
A3038 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CASPIAN-CASPIAN-PEOPL     08-13 1270
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASPIAN-CASPIAN-PEOPLE-2NDTAKE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BAKU, Azerbaijan-2NDTAKE-SFCHRON  
 ... in foreign offices. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Our cleaning lady and driver are former physics professors,''
Amy McMaken said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Baku headquarters of San Francisco-based Chevron, finance
and administrative manager Jim Hawkins said that the woman who just
made the coffee is a doctor. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; 3 stars &QC; 
 &LR;   &LR;  About half an hour's drive south of the McMaken apartment, the
main highway to Iran passes an arid peninsula that juts two miles
into the Bay of Baku. Thousands of rusted, abandoned oil derricks
scar the peninsula's treeless hillsides, casting gaunt shadows on
concrete huts that bake under the ferocious Caspian sun.
</P>
<P>
   The derricks are what remains of Azerbaijan's last experience
with Western energy firms.
</P>
<P>
   From the 1880s to 1900 companies controlled by John D.
Rockefeller of the United States and Alfred Nobel of Sweden built
vast fortunes on an earlier oil strike here. At the turn of the
century, 51 percent of the globe's oil came from Azerbaijan.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1920s, when the young Soviet Union seized control of
Azerbaijan, the onshore reserves had been emptied _ leaving behind
silent derricks and blocks of palatial mansions in the capital
city, many of which are now being converted into offices and
apartments by the multinational investors of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Shafaq, a 14-year-old girl, has lived in one of the huts with
her mother and seven other people since 1993, when her father was
killed in the war with Armenia in their native province of
Nagorno-Karabakh.
</P>
<P>
   Each day, everyone but the smallest children joins throngs of
refugees on street corners in downtown Baku, where hotels and
construction crews hire day laborers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nine of us get by on around 150,000 manat ($40) per month,''
Shafaq said. ``It's just enough to eat, and to pay the bus fare to
the city and back.''
</P>
<P>
   The war has been slowed by a fragile 1994 cease-fire, broken
almost weekly by skirmishes around Karabakh. But its mutual ethnic
cleansing is already complete. There are no Armenians left in
Azerbaijan, except those in Karabakh _ technically, 20 percent of
Azerbaijan's land _ and no Azeris left in Karabakh or Armenia.
</P>
<P>
   At least a million Azeris are now refugees in their own country,
almost a fifth of Azerbaijan's population. They are the poorest of
the poor in a nation where enormous wealth is literally gushing
from the offshore seabed.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Deputy Economics Minister Oktay Hagverdiyev said,
``Between 45 and 48 percent of the population lives below the
poverty line in Azerbaijan,'' the richest and most urbanized of the
new oil-producing nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our average per capita income is around $70 a month, including
the proceeds of a rather large black market,`` he said. ``Consumer
surveys indicate that something closer to $100 per person is
necessary these days.''
</P>
<P>
   That's more than twice the income earned by Shafaq's household
of nine people.
</P>
<P>
   But if history holds lessons, the vast gulf between the richest
and poorest is not the ticking Caspian time bomb. As University of
California at Berkeley political scientist Crane Brinton noted in
his landmark study, ``Anatomy of Revolution,'' social firestorms
are more often ignited by rising _ but frustrated _ expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had hope four or five years ago,'' Shafaq's mother said.
``It's lost now. We'll never see our homes again.''
</P>
<P>
   The desperately poor don't harbor expectations. Samaya Jafar
does. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; 3 stars &QC; 
 &LR;   &LR;  The balance sheet of the Jafar family is a case study in Baku's
confusing social realities in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Between them, Samaya and her husband Rauf, an electrical
technician for a Turkish-owned contracting company, take home 4
million manat per month ($1,150).
</P>
<P>
   On the debit side, they are paying off the mortgage on a modest
two-bedroom apartment that was purchased in 1996 for $35,000 _ real
estate nowadays is invariably priced in dollars, rather than manat.
</P>
<P>
   The Jafars must also save for the secondary educations of their
two sons, Ismail and Yussif, at expensive private high schools if
they hope for them to go on to a good university. Once there, the
expenses will soar into the stratosphere. At the recently opened
American University in Baku, tuition is $7,000 per year _ almost 14
times Azerbaijan's per capita annual GDP.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure is made greater by the fact that both boys are
clearly exceptional. At the age of 12, Jussif is fluent in Azeri,
English, Russian, Arabic and Turkish. Ismail, 8, spends hours
riveted to the family's English and Russian encyclopedias.
</P>
<P>
   ``Name a country, any country on Earth,'' his father says to
their American guests.
</P>
<P>
   One of the visitors offers Tuvalu, a tiny island-state in the
South Pacific with a population of less than 10,000. ``The capital
is Funafuti,'' Ismail instantly responds.
</P>
<P>
   Exhausted from a seven-day work week at the market, Samaya
listens quietly from across the dinner table. Her hopes for her
sons, and the toll this exacts, would be familiar to a mother
anywhere. ``Now you see why I sell chickens,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   A visitor also sees that the boys' minds are mirrors of hers,
and that their world view is being shaped in the forge of her
painful compromise between self-esteem and money.
</P>
<P>
   The Jafars cannot live on Rauf's pay and a teacher's salary.
Samaya has tried, endlessly, to find work in the dazzling Baku of
foreign investors and multinational corporations. But she won't
clean floors or make coffee _ ``That's no reason to leave the
market'' _ and every responsible job seems closed.
</P>
<P>
   Western executives confirm that hiring practices are not what
they might be. ``There are no employment agencies,'' said Chevron's
Jim Hawkins. ``The major way we identify potential new employees is
word-of-mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   In many firms, the word is passed on by local staff members, who
are deluged with employment requests from relatives and friends.
``You have to know somebody just to get past the receptionist,''
Samaya said, ``and even then, the first thing they notice is that
I'm almost 40.''
</P>
<P>
   That's too old, in a Caspian basin where anyone over 30 is
regarded as a Soviet anachronism. The glaring exceptions are scions
of the Soviet ``nomenklatura,'' the ex-Communist Party bosses and
their children who governed the region a decade ago and remain an
elite class today.
</P>
<P>
   The chemistry is volatile, fueling resentments between
generations, as well as between the pampered nomenklatura and less
privileged citizens _ and raising early warning signals of the
conflicts that led other oil nations into the social abyss.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want younger people, the 25-year-olds, even if they can't
speak English as well as I do,'' Samaya said of the foreign
multinationals in Baku. ``The idea is that they can be trained,
while I'm beyond the point where training is possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Her sentiments are widely shared among older Azeris. ``Oil?
There's always been oil in our country. It doesn't affect people
like me,'' said a 52-year-old woman at the Central Market, where
she sells used clothing.
</P>
<P>
   But a few blocks away in the Relax Cafe near Fountain Square,
younger Azeris lingered over hamburgers and Cokes _ convinced that
their own lives will unfold to the pattern of Amy McMaken rather
than Samaya Jafar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our generation believes we will all be rich eventually,'' said
Nuriya Huseynova, 18, a student at the private Western University
in Baku. ``Look at Kuwait: Nothing but oil, no other product in
their economy, and everyone has big cars and villas.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
