<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3040 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CASPIAN-CASPIAN-PEOPL     08-13 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASPIAN-CASPIAN-PEOPLE-2TAKES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASPIAN OIL PROVIDES FUEL FOR SOCIAL UNREST 
</HEADLINE>
   (Third of four-part series)  
 Eds: Photos and graphics are available to New York Times News 
 Service clients  
 By FRANK VIVIANO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAKU, Azerbaijan_ The insistence on personal fulfillment, on a
career that enhances self-esteem and inner peace, is supposed to be
a Western preoccupation. A luxury of the developed world.
</P>
<P>
   Then a traveler meets someone like Samaya Jafar, 38, who is rich
from the indirect proceeds of a huge oil boom in Central Asia and
the Caucasus _ and reeling with bitter frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Jafar sells chickens in the Central Market of Baku, about 40 on
a typical day. In Azerbaijan, where per capita GDP is $504 a year,
they bring in the equivalent of $1,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   In the nearby school where she teaches English two days a week,
Jafar's monthly income equals the profits on a dozen chickens.
</P>
<P>
   An economist might regard her as an icon of success, a
prosperous new entrepreneur in an ex-Soviet republic just shaking
off the constraints of 70 years of communism. Her income puts her
well ahead of the national curve, in a nation where salaries
overall have risen by 60 percent since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life,'' Jafar declared, ``is a failure.''
</P>
<P>
   It may also be a time bomb, ticking toward an explosion that
could have massive repercussions. The clock turns on the very boom
that has put $5 chickens into Azeri pots, transformed struggling
teachers into affluent merchants _ and bewildered Azeris and their
ex-Soviet neighbors with its contradictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have years of education and teaching behind me. I want to
use my mind, my imagination,'' Jafar said, in barely accented and
perfectly grammatical English.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why must I sell poultry to give my children a decent life?
What does it mean, that there is no better place for me than a
market stall, amidst such wealth?''
</P>
<P>
   Jafar's question recalls the social distortions that beset many
other developing nations inundated with black gold _ Iran,
Indonesia, Nigeria, Algeria.
</P>
<P>
   Azerbaijani officials are painfully aware of these precedents.
``We're determined to follow the example of Norway rather than
Nigeria,'' said Ali Jarafli, a top executive at the state oil
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a tremendous job ahead of us just to bring our
infrastructure up to modern levels _ transport, communications,
ports, airports, railroads, electric energy, roads and services.
The costs will exceed $10 billion,'' said Oktay Hagverdiyev, deputy
minister of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're so busy dealing with the macroeconomic issues that
other considerations are pushed aside.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief among the other considerations is a crisis in values,
brought about by the abrupt marriage of two very different worlds. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; 3 stars &QC; 
 &LR;   &LR;  If they met, Amy McMaken would understand Samaya Jafar's
bitterness, just as she would understand her own inadvertent role
in it.
</P>
<P>
   McMaken is who Jafar wants to be.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband, Kurt, are certified public accountants,
halfway through a two-year stint in key executive positions at the
Baku office of a major multinational firm.
</P>
<P>
   The apartment assigned to them by their employer is on the first
floor of an elegant 19th century building on Prospekt Neftyanikov,
``Oilmen's Avenue,'' a mile below the market.
</P>
<P>
   When the door is opened, a visitor steps into the pages of
Architectural Digest.
</P>
<P>
   Their firm leased three apartments in the building and connected
them, gutting the contents and renovating to the taste of a
Manhattan interior designer:
</P>
<P>
   Polished hardwood floors and track lighting. A football
field-sized living room. Furniture from Italy and Scandinavia. A
high-tech kitchen that could swallow 30 market stalls. Year-round
climate control and 24-channel satellite television.
</P>
<P>
   In Baku, this is how the other half lives _ the expatriates who
run the oil boom's multinational offices.
</P>
<P>
   Amy and Kurt McMaken are 28 years old. They are, respectively,
in charge of tax consulting and auditing services in Azerbaijan for
one of the world's leading accounting partnerships. Their clients
include several of the most powerful corporations on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Aesthetically, their home is as far as you can get from the
cinder-block slum that abuts the Central Market. Yet in actual
distance it is less than a five-minute taxi ride from Jafar's
chicken stall.
</P>
<P>
   What separates the McMakens from many of their fellow
expatriates is that the contrast makes them uneasy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among Europeans and Americans in Baku, there is often an
`expat mentality' that is deeply embarrassing,'' Amy said. ``It's
an attitude of superiority, a habit of using dismissive phrases
like `these people' in reference to Azeris.''
</P>
<P>
   But bridging the divide, Kurt said, is almost impossible.
``There's a natural tendency for expats and nationals to group
together separately. People were visibly uncomfortable when I
played soccer with our Azeri staffers once.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after their arrival in 1997, the McMakens tried to break
down the barriers by inviting local colleagues to dinner. The
effort fizzled _ in part, because the guests were so intimidated by
their apartment. ``They found it posh beyond all belief,'' Amy
said.
</P>
<P>
   Unofficial estimates place the community of western expatriates
in Baku alone at more than 10,000, with nearly as many scattered
around the capital cities, oil fields and pipeline construction
sites of the Georgian Republic, Kazakhstan and Turkmenistan.
</P>
<P>
   The expats' growing population _ and fat paychecks _ have
spawned an incongruous separate economy of air-conditioned luxury
apartment towers, supermarkets, bars and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   In Baku, foreign workers can dine on sweet-and-sour pork at the
Dragon Palace, blackened redfish at the Ragin' Cajun or enchiladas
at Margaritaville, a Tex-Mex joint. Its Azeri waiters, garbed in
panchos and sombreros, hand out publicity flyers just before supper
time in Fountain Square, the city's central park.
</P>
<P>
   Scots, who number more than 2,700, gather after dark at the
Ranger Pub, named for a Glasgow soccer team, where they gulp down
pints of lager as British sporting events unfold on a giant
satellite-fed television screen.
</P>
<P>
   A beer fetches the equivalent of $6 at the nearby Fountain
Square Steak House, where most of the customers are expatriates and
the owner is an American. The same beer costs 80 cents at an Azeri
bar 50 yards away, where the customers are locals who work for the
multinationals.
</P>
<P>
   The price gap is symbolic of a more ominous distinction between
locals and expatriates. Drawn by salaries that are three or four
times those in the public sector, Azeris by the thousands have
abandoned professional careers for menial jobs in foreign offices.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Legally, the oil sits in a murky void. Landlocked bodies of
water such as the Caspian are not governed by international law,
and there are no universally recognized principles for determining
boundaries on its seabed.
</P>
<P>
   Before 1991, all of the surrounding lands except Iran were part
of the Soviet Union, and had no need to establish separate claims
to the seabed. The Soviet collapse, followed by massive oil and
natural gas discoveries, changed everything _ and led to a mad
scramble for drilling rights.
</P>
<P>
   On one side are the Russians and Iranians, respectively at the
northern and southern ends of the sea. Moscow and Teheran want
joint sharing of revenues by all five Caspian nations, even though
their own offshore areas appear to contain no oil. Among the
current oil producers, only Turkmenistan supports Moscow and
Teheran on the ownership issue.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side are oil-rich Azerbaijan and Kazakhstan, which
have called for a formal division of the seabed according to the
Caspian states' respective national borders. Further complicating
the picture is an accord reached by Russia and Kazakhstan last
month that divides fishing rights in the northern Caspian _ but not
oil _ between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint statement on July 20, Russian Deputy Foreign Minister
Boris Pastukhov and his Iranian counterpart, Morteza Sarmadi,
declared that ``the 1921 and 1940 agreements signed by Iran and the
former Soviet Union stand as valid.'' These agreements require
``the consensus of all five littoral states'' on the Caspian for
any new legal division of the seabed, effectively permitting Iran
and Russia to veto unfavorable boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   Russia and Iran have 210 million inhabitants, huge standing
armies and governments that exert significant influence on the
global stage.
</P>
<P>
   The three oil-producing nations have a combined population of
less than 30 million, insignificant military forces and _ because
of estimated oil and gas reserves second only to those on the
Persian Gulf _ a cast of new overseas friends and backers led by
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The result, in the seabed and pipeline controversies alike, is
the threat of growing friction in the region between the Caspian
basin's two local superpowers and their long-standing rival in the
West.
</P>
<P>
   The joint Russian-Iranian communique reads as a thinly veiled
warning to the Clinton Administration. The statement ``specifically
ruled out interference by any outside party, as a mediator or
otherwise, in drawing up the Caspian legal regime.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. involvement in the region ``is leading the matter toward
open confrontation with Russia,'' Russian Deputy Energy Minister
Valery Garipov warned in April. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; 3 stars &QC; 
 &LR;   &LR;  Most of the nations and major firms with significant stakes in
the outcome give lip service to the principle that ``multiple
pipelines are the ideal,'' as a Chevron executive put it.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in practice, most have committed themselves to specific
routes, with far-reaching economic and security implications.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron, as a partner in the Caspian Pipeline Consortium with
Kazakhstan, supports a $2 billion Russian route from Kazakhstan to
Novorossiysk that is already under construction _ a step that puts
the San Francisco firm at odds with Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The United States government and a majority of American oil
firms have thrown their weight behind the longest and most
expensive proposed pipeline, a 1,030-mile, $3 billion conduit
across Azerbaijan, Georgia and Turkey, from Baku on the Caspian Sea
to the Turkish port of Ceyhan on the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
   Azerbaijan is also publicly committed to the Ceyhan MEP system,
which would tentatively be joined to a proposed $2 billion pipeline
under the Caspian carrying oil from Turkmenistan and Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
   The Ceyhan MEP is expected to cost 50 percent more than the
proposed new Russian system. But advocates point out that it would
avoid the narrow and crowded shipping lanes on the Bosporus strait
between the Black Sea and the Mediterranean, where oil spills would
bring disaster to the most heavily populated area of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Washington formally launched its ``Caspian Sea
Initiative,'' authorizing the U.S. Export-Import Bank and two other
federal agencies to support 65 energy projects in the region. All
are tied to the Baku-Ceyhan route.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, the new Western Pipeline from Baku to the Georgian
Black Sea port of Supsa goes into operation. Like the proposed
Ceyhan route, it bypasses Russia entirely, for reasons that that
have as much to do with international gamesmanship as they do with
money or technical feasibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``The successful completion of the project to transport oil
through the Western route is important, not just from the economic
point of view, but also politically,'' John Leggate, president of
the Azerbaijan International Operating Company, told reporters July
13.
</P>
<P>
   The only existing pipeline courses through Russia, a country
whose dependence on volatile energy revenues is as dangerously high
as that of its tiny, resource-rich former satellites. A quarter of
all Russian tax receipts now comes from oil industry levies and
fees.
</P>
<P>
   Both the country's young prime minister, Sergei Kiriyenko, and
his predecessor, Viktor Chernomyrdin, are former gas or oil company
presidents. The Kiriyenko government hopes to revive a deeply
ailing economy by drawing the bulk of Caspian basin oil to a much
larger new pipeline to Novorossiysk.
</P>
<P>
   Rival pipelines through their own countries are also being
pushed by Ukraine, Romania, Greece, Iran, Pakistan, Afghanistan,
Turkmenistan, China and Armenia. But the primary contenders are the
routes to Novorossiysk and Ceyhan _ each of which plunges into a
battle zone.
</P>
<P>
   Support for a Ceyhan pipeline will drag the American government
and U.S. corporations ever deeper into the Turkish campaign against
Kurdish insurgents, which is already being fought with American
F-16s serviced by U.S. Air Force maintenance crews.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow's route goes directly through troubled Dagestan and
Chechnya, the rebellious Caucasian republic that has defeated the
Russian Army and descended into violent anarchy.
</P>
<P>
   Russian and Chechen spokesmen promise that the oil will flow,
whatever the state of their relations, because neither side can
afford to spurn the lucrative transport fees. In late April,
officials signed an agreement that would pay Chechnya $3.58 per ton
(50 barrels) of oil crossing its territory through the present
pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   With an annual capacity of 5 million tons of oil from Azerbaijan
and Kazakhstan, the deal could bring Chechnya as much as $18
million per year. A Russian MEP, with a projected capacity of 67
million tons per year, would increase the Chechen take to $240
million.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a recent escalation of hostilities suggests that the
agreement is extremely fragile. Unless Russia accepted his terms on
war reparations, Chechen Acting Prime Minister Shamil Basaev warned
in July, he would shut down the pipeline immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, in a shoot-out along the pipeline route between
security forces and Islamic paramilitaries, at least 50 Chechens
were killed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
