<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASPIAN-ADVISORY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  Eds:
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the 150th anniversary of the California gold rush, a new El
Dorado is beckoning half a world away. Only this time, the
substance is oil, not gold.
</P>
<P>
   In a four-part series, Chronicle staff writer Frank Viviano
examines the extraordinary oil bonanza in the Caspian Sea. The huge
oil and natural gas finds there will provide energy to the West for
the next century.
</P>
<P>
   But formidable obstacles stand in the way of the oil getting to
Western markets: war, political rivalries and ethnic tensions
abound throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
   In a monthlong journey of more than 3,000 miles, 100 interviews
and 4,000 photographs, Viviano and Chronicle photographer Tim Kao
documented the oil boom.
</P>
<P>
   The stories will move in the international `i' category, slugged
CASPIAN-OIL, CASPIAN-WAR, CASPIAN-PEOPLE and CASPIAN-POLITICS.
Photos and graphics are available to clients of the New York Times
News Service.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
San Francisco Chronicle
</P>
