<HEADER>
A3047 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONSNOTES14-CO     08-13 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONSNOTES14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons Notebook: Coaches will be looking at running game
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When the Atlanta Falcons take the field tonight in the
Silverdome to play their second preseason game of the summer,
reserve quarterback Steve DeBerg, 44, will get much of the
attention. He's supposed to play three quarters, and after not
playing since 1993, whatever he does will be good for a spot or two
on SportsCenter tonight.
</P>
<P>
   But the evaluation of DeBerg is one of a few primary objectives
the Falcons coaches take into tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The other critical issue is the running game. Atlanta was just
19th in the NFL in rushing last year, despite improvement at the
end of the season. In last week's 31-16 win over Tennessee, the
Falcons had 67 yards on 23 carries.
</P>
<P>
   Take away two Harold Green carries for 21 yards, and a Jamal
Anderson run for 11, and the birds rushed 20 times for 35 yards.
Take away the three scrambles by quarterback Tony Graziani for 15
yards, and the Falcons had 17 rushes for 20 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got to get the running game going,'' coach Dan Reeves
said. ''You've got to be aggressive up front, hitting people and
sustaining contact. You see a lot of offensive lineman standing
around. When the play is over, they still ought to have contact.
You can't just smack 'em once, and lose 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   The first offensive line of left tackle Bob Whitfield, left
guard Calvin Collins, center Robbie Tobeck, right guard Gene
Williams, and right tackle Nate Miller will probably play the
entire first half.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson (eight carries for 21 yards last week), and Byron
Hanspard (seven carries for 11 yards last week) will see
considerable action in the first half as well.
</P>
<P>
   ''Also, you need a running back running to daylight and not
wasting a lot of time doing it,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome aboard, QB
</P>
<P>
   The newest Falcon, rookie quarterback John Dutton of
Nevada-Reno, arrived Thursday, and threw a little in basic drills.
The 6-foot-4, 222-pound native of Newport Beach, Calif., was waived
Tuesday night by the Miami Dolphins, who drafted him in the sixth
round.
</P>
<P>
   He hit 444-of-701 passes (63.3 percent) for 6,276 yards, 42
touchdowns, and 12 interceptions the last two years at Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons claimed him Wednesday after Dutton said he ended up
in the wrong place at the wrong time. The Dolphins will start Dan
Marino, and behind him is Craig Erickson. Battling for the No. 3
job are Damon Huard, who was the Dolphins' No. 3 quarterback for 15
games last year in addition to playing the last two springs in the
World League, and three-year veteran Chad Maye, a fourth-round pick
of the Vikings in '95. He also has been on the roster with the
Cardinals, and
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think it had to do with talent; it was kind of a
numbers game,'' Dutton said. ''(Dolphins coach) Jimmy (Johnson) and
I sat down and had a good talk. he was saying that with Dan being
37 years old, they're going to need some experience at the No. 3
spot (in the event Marino and Erickson go down). They talked as a
staff, and wanted to let me go early so I could save this year,
hopefully.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves was happy to offer a chance, releasing rookie free agent
Brian Brennan of Idaho in order to fit Dutton on the squad.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was a guy we thought a great deal of coming out of college
so it's an opportunity to bring him here and see what he looks
like,'' the coach said.
</P>
<P>
   Aches and pains
</P>
<P>
   Thursday was a repeat of Wednesday and Tuesday, as the same
eight players missed a 50-minute jog-through prior to the game.
They were DT Mark Campbell (knee sprain), RT Corey Louchiey
(groin), WR Keith Crawford (hamstring), WR Tim Dwight (back), DT
William Gaines (back), WR Jammi German (groin), DE Barry Mitchell
(elbow), and CB Randy Fuller (ankle).
</P>
<P>
   None will play Friday night at Detroit, and it's possible CB
Lenny McGill (ankle/hamstring) won't play. If he doesn't, rookie
Elijah Williams likely will be the No. 2 left corner.
</P>
<P>
   Opportunities galore
</P>
<P>
   All those injuries mean some players will get more of a chance
to show their stuff than they otherwise might have. Included in
that group are rookie free agent wide receiver Octavus Barnes, and
receiver Kevin Thornal, who was on the practice squad last year.
</P>
<P>
   Terance Mathis and Tony Martin will start, but won't play much.
The first-string offensive and defensive lines are likely to play
most, if not all the first half, with the only variation being an
alternating situation at left defensive end with starter Lester
Archambeau and John Burrough.
</P>
<P>
   The only change in the starting lineup is that right cornerback
Ronnie Bradford, who missed last week's game with a hamstring, will
be in there.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of other positions, however, will alternate more,
including receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Thornal, who has three catches for 55 yards last week, and
Barnes, who had one catch for 12 yards, are among them.
</P>
<P>
   ''This week was supposed to be my week off since I got so many
reps last week, but the injuries changed things,'' Thornal said.
''I'm going to have to fill all three spots, including the slot
back.''
</P>
<P>
   ''You never wish an injury on anybody, because that's the worst
thing that can happen, and I've been in that situation,'' said
Barnes, who blew out his knee at the end of his sophomore season at
North Carolina. ''But I'm glad I'm getting a chance to showcase my
talents. Most of the time I've been working at the split end
position, but I'll get thrown in at slot some.''
</P>
<P>
   No go, Fernando
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons failed to get their man in former defensive end
Fernando Smith, who decided instead Thursday to sign a contract
with the Jacksonville Jaguars. Atlanta general manager Harold
Richardson and Reeves wanted to add the 6-foot-6, 283-pound Smith,
who had 13.5 sacks the last two years before being released
recently.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's agent, Jeff Durand of Minneapolis, said the Falcons were
one of four finalists, joining the Jaguars, Redskins and Saints.
</P>
<P>
   ''He would have challenged for a lot of playing time, and he
would have helped at tackle and end,'' Reeves said. ''I was hoping
we could get it worked out, but . . . the money is close and a guy
is going to go where he thinks he's got the best chance. He felt
like his chances were best in Jacksonville.''
</P>
<P>
   Where to in '99?
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are fast approaching a decision on where training
camp will be held next summer, as it appears all but certain there
will indeed be construction at the team's Suwanee headquarters this
time next year. What will be under construction is still up in the
air, but with at least one of the three top candidates _ Furman
University in Greenville, S.C. _ asking for an answer within a few
weeks, the Falcons probably make a decision soon.
</P>
<P>
   Furman, Middle Georgia College in Cochran, near Macon, and the
University of Tennessee at Chattanooga are the three sites
considered most likely to get the nod.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll probably make a decision before September . . . because
wherever we go, they've got to get some things done,'' Reeves said.
''Those three are definitely the leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
