<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-TANZANIA-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATER TRUCK DISCOUNTED AS CARRIER OF EXPLOSIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: AFRICA-MEMORIAL, AFRICA-BOMBING, AFRICA-U.S.) 
(js) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAR ES SALAAM, Tanzania _ After initial surmises that the bomb
that exploded here last Friday outside the American Embassy was
attached to an embassy-owned water truck, investigators are
shifting their attention to other possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   But two American security officials who said Thursday that the
water truck was being discounted as the carrier also said that they
had no explanation of how the bomb arrived at the entrance gate.
</P>
<P>
   The theory that the bomb was on the tanker, which was about to
enter the embassy grounds, was proving a dead end, officials said.
They added that investigators had not found parts of a car or
another vehicle that might have carried the bomb. Officials said
they had no witness accounts of a car's arriving at the scene just
before the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   One official suggested that the bomb was ``gas enhanced,''
similar to the bombs used in attacks in 1993 on the Marine barracks
in Beirut, Lebanon, and the American Embassy in Kuwait. Such bombs
are surrounded by canisters of flammable gas that intensify
explosions.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion here caused far fewer deaths and casualties than
the one in Nairobi, Kenya, in part because the embassy is a
reinforced-concrete building that the Israeli government built in
the late 1970s. But the delivery of the bomb to a point as close as
possible to the edge of the compound and its nearly simultaneous
timing with the explosion in Nairobi showed extensive planning, the
officials said. The reconnaissance of the site, the assembling of
the explosives, their transportation to Tanzania and perhaps even
the building of a prototype took an estimated six months, one
official, an expert in counterterrorism, said.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion left a crater 10 feet in diameter in an area that
seems to be just behind where the water truck was idling, awaiting
clearance to enter the gates. The truck never received clearance,
and early reports that a guard was inspecting its undercarriage
with a mirror on a long pole led to the conjecture that the bomb
had been on the truck.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact that the tanker and its undercarriage were swept
forward 50 feet by the blast but not obliterated suggested that the
bomb was not attached to the truck, officials said Thursday. The
truck cab was burned to shreds, probably because fuel had been
stored under it.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have been collecting debris from the site since
Sunday, and the crater at the gate has been scooped wider and
deeper for samples to be analyzed for residues of explosives.
</P>
<P>
   Searching for clues will take months, and after the criminal
investigators no longer need the site the building will probably be
demolished, said the charge d'affaires, John Lange.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One embassy employee, Saidi Rogati, 48, remains missing.
American officials said no trace of Rogati, an assistant driver who
had worked at the embassy for 13 years, had been found.
</P>
<P>
   Co-workers had seen him on the embassy grounds before the
explosion, and the officials say they assume that he died in the
blast. The officials strongly suggested that he was not a suspect.
</P>
<P>
   The indication that the bomb was probably not on the water
tanker was of some consolation to the State Department Diplomatic
Security office, which is responsible for the safety of embassies.
The office's main concern is that terrorists not breach embassy
compounds. If the bomb had been attached to the tanker, that could
mean that the bomb had been planted while the tanker was parked
overnight at the back of the compound.
</P>
<P>
   One striking aspect of the protection at the embassy here, as is
the case in some other African countries, is that the guards at the
perimeter are employees of a company, Ultimate Security. Such
guards, known as askaris, are poorly paid and poorly educated.
</P>
<P>
   One American official described Ultimate Security, which has
contracts to guard many major commercial sites in the capital and
most embassies, as fairly decent but added: ``That said, they are
African guards with a stick. They are trained with Mace. They are
not legally allowed to carry a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 10 people who died here, five were Ultimate Security
guards at the front of the building. No Americans were killed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
