<HEADLINE>
WEAK DOLLAR, DEBT AUCTIONS DRIVE BOND PRICES LOWER  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT HURTADO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A weaker dollar and the third part of the Treasury's
quarterly debt auctions kept prices of government securities
depressed Thursday for the second consecutive day. Also weighing on
prices is the Federal Reserve's monetary policy committee meeting
next week. The price of the benchmark 30-year bond dropped nearly a
half-point, to 107, while its yield, which moves in the opposite
direction, rose to 5.63 percent, from 5.60 percent on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's $10 billion auction of 30-year bonds was the final
and most difficult part of the quarterly debt sales. With yields
already near record lows and investors holding higher-yielding
long-term issues, traders think market participants may be a little
reluctant to buy more. The new 30-year issue was bought at an
average price to yield 5.590 percent, mostly in line with
expectations. Bonds began the session down when the dollar dropped
against the Japanese yen because investors feared the Japanese
central bank would sell dollars to support the yen. A strong dollar
makes Treasury securities more attractive to foreign investors, not
only because of the high return but also because of the potential
gains in currency translation. Still, Treasuries did receive a
small boost from foreign investors seeking shelter from turmoil in
Russian and Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
   Investors keep watching for signs that Asia's slowdown is
weighing on economic growth in the United States. The government
said Thursday that retail sales fell 0.4 percent last month after
rising 0.10 of a percent in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumer spending is the mainstay of the economy and the key
to the economic outlook,'' said Donald Fine, chief market analyst
at Chase Asset Management, ``and the Federal Reserve is highly
unlikely to ease monetary policy until consumption slows
significantly and sustainably from its ebullient pace over the past
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``But while a more accommodative monetary policy does not appear
to be on the horizon, ``neither does a tightening.'' He said the
pace of economic growth appeared to be slowing, in large part
because of the financial crisis in Asia, which would be exacerbated
by a rate rise in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Fed on hold, it has hardly been a surprise that the
bond market has been locked in a narrow range of between 5.60
percent to 5.80 percent,'' he said, adding, ``In the anticipated
absence of an inflationary outbreak on the one hand and signs of
recession on the other, bond yields are likely to remain in this
range for quite some time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 2040EDT &QL; 
