<HEADER>
A3052 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOGS-COX     08-13 1760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    N.C. hog farmers' ads raise concern
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUPLIN COUNTY, N.C. _ Some 3 million pigs populate this rural
eastern North Carolina county, outnumbering people about 75 to one.
That makes Duplin the hog farming capital of the world and gives
state Rep. Cindy Watson, the local legislator here, a district with
one mountain of pork.
</P>
<P>
   But late last year Watson, a 57-year-old interior decorator,
awoke to find herself on the wrong side of the feed trough.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers for Fairness, a tax-exempt trade association of North
Carolina's largest corporate hog farmers, began airing radio and
television ads accusing Watson of voting to pollute the environment
and being anti-hog.
</P>
<P>
   An ad titled ``Flip-Flop Watson'' said Watson was ``misleading
people'' about pollution caused by the $2 billion hog industry.
Over the four months preceding Watson's May primary, Farmers for
Fairness spent $10,000 to $20,000 a week on unregulated ``issue
ads'' in her district, for a total that by some estimates exceeded
$400,000. None of the money was subject to campaign contribution
limits.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the onslaught? Watson was the hog industry's
sharpest critic. In 1997, she pushed for a two-year moratorium on
new hog operations, an effort to contain the industry's exploding
growth while officials studied the environmental problems of hog
waste.
</P>
<P>
   Now Farmers for Fairness is waging a high-stakes battle with the
North Carolina State Board of Elections in a case that election
officials believe could decide their ability to enforce laws
requiring groups to obey contribution limits and barring
corporations from engaging in campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Experts believe the case and another involving North Carolina
Right to Life will have broad implications for other states, most
of which have laws regulating how much individuals can contribute
to candidates and who must comply with contributor disclosure laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``If special interests are permitted to spend money this way and
get away with it, we may as well not have election laws at all,''
says Joshua Rosencranz of the Brennan Center for Justice at New
York University, which is defending state campaign laws in North
Carolina and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina, the state elections board ruled in June that
the Farmers for Fairness media campaign against Watson was intended
to defeat her, a finding the group denied. The board ordered
Farmers for Fairness to register as a political action committee,
disclose its campaign contributions and expenses and refund any
donations that exceeded legal limits or came from corporate
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers for Fairness, also under attack for possible misuse of
its IRS tax exemption, is mulling a decision to defy the board's
ruling and appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The case has made for riveting drama. At an April hearing,
Farmers for Fairness officials alleged that state House Speaker
Harold Brubaker pressed the hog industry for campaign money in
return for promises that the House would not enact new hog
regulations. Then the witnesses testified that the GOP House passed
more regulations on the industry because hog farmers hadn't
contributed enough.
</P>
<P>
   Both the North Carolina Bureau of Investigation and the FBI are
investigating those allegations, which Brubaker vigorously denies.
</P>
<P>
   Watson's ordeal began when she was elected in 1994, becoming the
first Republican to represent District 10 in 100 years. Describing
herself a ``lifelong conservative,'' Watson said she has always
abhorred government regulations.
</P>
<P>
   After her election, however, she was inundated with calls from
her constituents. Children complained of asthma from the stench
created by hog waste. Others said the hog odors were so bad they
couldn't go outside. Some complained their wells were contaminated
by E. coli bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1995, a hog farm in her district accidentally spilled 25
million gallons of hog waste into the nearby New River, the worst
spill in state history.
</P>
<P>
   Enough was enough, Watson decided, and in 1996 and again in 1997
the Republican backed new regulations on the hog industry,
including a moratorium on new operations that expires next year.
</P>
<P>
   Watson says she was simply trying to ``represent the person who
lives next door to the hog farmer as well as the hog farmer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I support the swine industry and its growth, just not at the
expense of the environment or the quality of life in eastern North
Carolina,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The hog industry saw it differently, says Nick Weaver, president
of Farmers for Fairness, which was formed in 1996 during the heat
of the hog debate. The group's mission was to ``educate and inform
the general public and elected leaders about agricultural issues to
help strengthen farming,'' according to IRS filings.
</P>
<P>
   The group's first poll found that only 17 percent of voters
viewed the hog industry favorably. For the first year, the group
launched a series ads statewide that never mentioned individual
legislators and sought to boost the industry's image.
</P>
<P>
   Then in late 1997, the group switched tactics. Instead of
generic ads on hog farming, it decided to target a half-dozen
legislators, including Watson, with negative spots.
</P>
<P>
   The change apparently resulted from the belief, discussed in
closed-door strategy meetings, that the only way Farmers for
Fairness could get the attention of the state legislature was ``to
beat one of them,'' according to the findings of the elections
board.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had all the free press,'' says Weaver, explaining why
Farmers for Fairness singled Watson out. ``We had no other way to
tell people, average John Q. Citizen, that hogs weren't destroying
this state.''
</P>
<P>
   But testimony at the board of elections hearing disclosed that
Farmers for Fairness was interested in far more than Watson's
position on hog farming.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to advertising in Watson's district, the group polled 300
registered voters in District 10.
</P>
<P>
   The survey's second question asked the race of the respondents
(one-third of the district is black). If the answer was not white,
the interview was terminated -- a clear signal that the group
didn't want the responses of black voters, who vote largely
Democratic, but wanted only ``white Republican voters,'' according
to the elections board.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also posed hypothetical matchups between Watson and
local people who had not even declared they might be running,
asking who respondents would vote for.
</P>
<P>
   In February, a second poll was conducted, again targeting 300
white voters in District 10. This poll included a hypothetical
matchup between Watson and Johnnie Manning, a hog farmer who only
six days previously had announced his intention to challenge Watson
in the GOP primary.
</P>
<P>
   The survey asked repsondents if they would be more or less
likely to vote for Watson if they knew ``that she put her husband
on the state payroll.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the survey asked if respondents would be more or less
likely to vote for Manning if they knew that he had been a farmer
``all his life.''
</P>
<P>
   The elections board concluded that these type of survey
questions were ``push polls'' designed to influence voters and
belied Farmers for Fairness's assertion that it simply wanted to
educate voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They blatantly transgressed,'' says Larry Leake, chairman of
the elections board. ``They were doing everything except say 'vote
for, vote against.'''
</P>
<P>
   Farmers for Fairness bumped into several provisions of North
Carolina election law, much of which is common to other states.
Since 1931, North Carolina has banned campaign contributions from
corporations on the premise that entities that can't vote shouldn't
also be allowed to contribute.
</P>
<P>
   State law also requires that any group seeking to ``influence or
attempt to influence the results of an election'' must register as
a political action committee and comply with campaign contribution
limits ($4,000 per two-year election cycle).
</P>
<P>
   Farmers for Fairness argues that it shouldn't comply with the
laws because it was engaging in ``issue advertising'' that, while
mentioning candidates, didn't specifically tell voters to vote for
or against them.
</P>
<P>
   So-called magic words such as ``vote for'' or ``vote against''
have been used by courts to determine if advertising is issue
advertising or ``electioneering'' designed to influence an
election's outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we don't mention the magic words, we have that
right,'' says Weaver.
</P>
<P>
   Leake argues that elections officials and the courts must look
beyond the so-called magic words.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the intent of the message and the activity combined
together,'' he says. ``If you cannot take that step, you are going
to find all campaign financing...will be impossible to enforce.''
</P>
<P>
   Farmers for Fairness is also facing questions from a group of
non-profit organizations, who complained to the IRS last week that
the group abused its tax exemption.
</P>
<P>
   Of the nearly $1.5 million that Farmers for Fairness spent in
its first year, two-thirds was treated as tax deductible to the
corporate hog farmers who contributed, according the the group's
tax return. IRS rules bar trade association members from deducting
expenses that are used to influence elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the camel's nose under the tent of corporations
finding another way to use their treasuries to have a massive
influence on political campaigns,'' says Bob Hall, research
director for Democracy South, which authored the letter to the IRS.
``And if they do it right, they also get a tax deduction.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson lost the May primary to Manning by 18 votes, but the
returns were thrown out because of voting irregularities. She faces
Manning in a re-match Sept. 15. Weaver says he isn't sure whether
Farmers for Fairness will run more ads against Watson, who raised
and spent about $21,000 in her primary.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Weaver says the group's statewide ad campaign was a
success. Hog farmers now have positive approval ratings of over 60
percent, he says, and the group enjoys new popularity in the
General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made some changes in the philosophy of the state
legislature,'' he says. ``We have some friends there now who
previously were not our friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a dozen environmental groups rallied at the Raleigh
Capitol to urge the General Assembly to extend the hog farming
moratorium another 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Watson was the only legislator, Republican or Democrat, who
showed up.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
