<SLUG> BC-NOTRE-DAME-FOOTBALL-ART-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTRE DAME HALO LOSES SOME GLOW AFTER RECENT REVELATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By JOE DRAPE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH BEND, Ind. _ The University of Notre Dame has made
cultural icons of the Four Horsemen, Knute Rockne and The Gipper.
Over 110 years its football teams have captured 11 national titles
and produced 77 all-Americans, all while maintaining a near-perfect
graduation rate.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Notre Dame football has become the touchstone for all
that is good and right about collegiate athletics, and it served as
the very public soul for the 156-year-old university revered as the
pinnacle of higher learning for Catholic America.
</P>
<P>
   But as the football team began practicing Thursday for the 1998
season, which begins on Sept. 5 against defending national champion
Michigan, Notre Dame maintains a tenuous grip on its hallowed place
in the American sports consciousness. Its once-pristine reputation
has been battered by a lawsuit filed by a former assistant coach
that featured sordid testimony about the program, and an NCAA
review of violations involving gifts to players.
</P>
<P>
   While no one is accusing the Fighting Irish of being what's bad
and wrong about college football, the developments have led many to
wonder whether the team with the best winning percentage in college
football history is really any different from any other big-time
program trying to compete at the highest level of a
multimillion-dollar industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that the people in charge didn't understand
that one of their duties was to protect the name of their
institution,'' said Richard Lieberman, the lawyer who successfully
represented the former coach, Joe Moore, in the age-discrimination
suit. ``They decided to put at risk the whole public perception of
who they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was Notre Dame any different than any other football team in
the 90's? Probably not. The names of coaches and players change,
but it's the name Notre Dame that provides the mystique. In my
view, they have taken a hit they may never recover from.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore's suit was indeed a severe blow to the school's image. In
sometimes sordid depositions and testimony, witnesses detailed
bitter fighting and backstabbing among the staff of the former head
coach Lou Holtz, as well as incidents of physical abuse by coaches
against players.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, earlier this month the National Collegiate Athletic
Association found that Notre Dame committed two violations
involving trips and gifts given to five former and five current
players from a 28-year-old South Bend woman. Thursday the woman,
Kimberly Dunbar, pleaded guilty to two counts of embezzling more
than $1 million from her South Bend employer.
</P>
<P>
   None of the players have been implicated in the criminal
proceeding. But along with Dunbar, five former team members have
been named as defendants in a civil suit, including one who has a
2-year-old child with Dunbar.
</P>
<P>
   Besides demoralizing many among the school's 100,000 alumni, the
revelations have been greeted with glee by Notre Dame critics who
were put off by the sometimes holier-than-thou nature of the
football team's zealous national following. Their satisfaction is
no doubt enhanced by the school's failing football fortunes, which
included a 7-6 record last season under the first-year coach Bob
Davie.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame's coaches, players, and administrators now find
themselves in an uncomfortable and contradictory position. While
insisting that they are no different from other programs, they are
trying not to distance themselves too much from the Notre Dame
mystique _ a phenomenon worth a five-year, $45 million NBC
television deal, the only one of its kind, and a rabid national
following.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get concerned when people hold Notre Dame up as if we
operate at a different standard,'' said the Rev. E. William
Beauchamp, the university's executive vice president, who oversees
athletics. ``If everybody says Notre Dame's standard is different
from everyone else's, then I don't like what that has to say about
intercollegiate athletics.''
</P>
<P>
   But Athletic Director Michael Wadsworth concedes that the
extraordinary media attention Notre Dame receives, combined with
its strong academic reputation and rich football heritage, have
fostered higher expectations in both performance and conduct.
``It's a mixed blessing,'' Wadsworth said. ``I'd rather have it
than not. It's what makes us unique. It also sets us up to be
knocked down.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   What prompted this internal dialogue about Notre Dame's
responsibility and opened the football program up to national
ridicule was the $1.3 million law suit filed by Moore, a
66-year-old offensive line coach who was fired by Davie after the
1996 season. Moore contended he was let go because of his age, and
a jury in federal district court in Lafayette, Ind. agreed with him
and awarded him more than $86,000.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Moore's attorneys will file for attorney costs _
$500,000 in fees, $100,000 in expenses _ and front pay that could
reach as much as $350,000. They will also ask to have the coach
re-instated at Notre Dame. A federal district court Judge will
decide on these issues as early as October.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of the Fighting Irish's reputation the case has been
costly. The university countered Moore's suit by claiming the coach
was physically abusive to players and confrontational with fellow
coaches. In stacks of well publicized depositions and at the trial,
the public was treated to a revealing and unseemly look at the
behind-the-scenes rancor at Notre Dame. The testimony included the
following contentions:
</P>
<P>
   _That Moore sometimes brutalized his offensive lineman with
punches and punishing calisthenics. Former offensive lineman Chris
Clevenger recounted in a deposition how Moore twice punched him in
the face, once drawing blood at halftime of the 1995 Blue and Gold
game, a spring exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   _That Moore and the offensive coordinator then, Dave Roberts,
nearly got into a fistfight over Moore's chain smoking before a
1995 game against Washington.
</P>
<P>
   _That Holtz physically attacked former assistant Earle Mosley at
halftime of a 1996 game at Boston College after the running backs
coach got into an altercation with a fan.
</P>
<P>
   _That before a 1996 game against Navy in Dublin, Moore
discovered a group of players gathered together watching a male and
female cheerleader having sex through the window of a hotel room.
He took them out to the parking lot at 1 a.m. and made them do
calisthenics.
</P>
<P>
   _Davie's admission that, as an assistant, he and Moore had a
conversation questioning Holtz's mental stability in his
predecessor's final year and Davie's strong dislike for some of
Holtz's habits and practices.
</P>
<P>
   University officials admit the revelations were embarrassing to
Notre Dame, but say they knew they were coming and ultimately did
the right thing by taking on Moore in court. ``What would have been
wrong is to settle for an unreasonable amount of money, to look
like we hushed it up,'' says Wadsworth.
</P>
<P>
   But Lieberman, the attorney for Moore, said his client was
willing to settle for far less than the $1.3 million before the
suit was filed and asked for a counter offer. Lieberman said Notre
Dame refused. When the case was ordered to court mediation, the
university offered $130,000, which Lieberman said was unacceptable
because Moore had already incurred more than $250,000 in attorney
fees.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the jury's verdict, Beauchamp still insists Moore's case
had no merit, that if the coach ``was 35'' he still would have been
fired. ``We don't like to have those type of things aired publicly,
but what came up in the trial doesn't add up to a great deal,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth dismissed any suggestion that Notre Dame's image had
been irreparably harmed. ``The university's enormous record of
achievement as an academic institution, as an athletic program with
integrity, is bigger than any one coach, player or team,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, administrators concede there is significant concern among
the Notre Dame community. Several alumni, ranging from former
players of Frank Leahy to more recent non-athlete graduates, used
the word ``scandals'' and said they were disappointed by the recent
turn of events. But loyal to Notre Dame, they declined to speak on
the record.
</P>
<P>
   The circle-the-wagons approach extends to the players on this
year's team, who claim that the summer's controversies have not
distracted them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great thing about being a college kid is you don't have
time to read the paper or watch television,'' said Mike Rosenthal,
a captain who testified on behalf of his former offensive line
coach, Moore, at the trial. ``You find solace in the weight room
and work hard. The trial has never been a factor. As far as
testifying, they asked me questions and I just told the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenthal said he places Moore just behind his parents as role
models.
</P>
<P>
   The senior quarterback Jarious Jackson said of the Kimberly
Dunbar case: ``It's not characteristic of Notre Dame football.''
</P>
<P>
   But because of the weight and clout the school's football
program wields nationwide, the troubles resonate far beyond the
campus. Anthony DeMaria, who coaches eight-grade football in a
Catholic School league in Kansas City, where several past Fighting
Irish players have played, is a lifelong Notre Dame fan who is
disillusioned by the recent developments.
</P>
<P>
   ``There always has been a sense that Notre Dame played by the
rules, worked hard and treated each other like a family,'' he said.
``It really disappoints me when things turn out they might be like
everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   As troubling as the lawsuit to Notre Dame supporters is the
Dunbar case. Just today she pleaded guilty to embezzling money from
a local mechanical contracting firm where she was employed. She
reportedly spent some of it to purchase gifts and trips for some
current and former Notre Dame players. Earlier this month, the NCAA
decided that her contact with players was improper because she was
a member of the since disbanded Notre Dame Quarterback Club, which
it considered a ``booster organization.'' Notre Dame, which
reported the players' relationship with Dunbar to the NCAA last
spring, has taken the position that no violations occurred. They
argue that club only held pre-game luncheons and that Dunbar had a
personal relationship with the players including since-departed
Jarvis Edison, with whom she has a child.
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar, her mother and sister, along with Edison, and former
Irish stars of the Holtz-era - Lee Becton, Ray Zellars, Derrick
Mayes and Kinnon Tatum _ were named as defendants in $1 million
civil suit.
</P>
<P>
   Of immediate concern is the status of five current players who
accepted tickets and attended a Chicago Bulls game with Dunbar and
the some of the former players. It is unclear when the NCAA will
decide what, if any, punishment to hand down.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it can happen at Notre Dame, it proves that it can happen
anywhere,'' says Penn State coach, Joe Paterno. ``It takes more
character to play football these days than ever before because the
outside pressures on these kids are tremendous.''
</P>
<P>
   The unsavory headlines have been noticed by Fighting Irish fans,
according to Tim Prister, a 1982 graduate and editor of Blue &AMP; Gold
Illustrated. His popular insider magazine has heard from some of
its 55,000 subscribers covering all 50 states and 22 foreign
countries. ''Support for the program and the team is as low as it's
been before Lou Holtz got here,'' Prister said. ``It's been a
snowball. They went 7-6 last year. There's the court case and the
NCAA ruling. Expectations are very low.''
</P>
<P>
   No one knows that better than Davie, the 43-year-old former
defensive coordinator who succeeded Holtz last season. The crux of
Moore's case concerned statements Davie made to players and others
about the dismissed coach's age _ though an unflattering portrait
of the Irish's new coach as a self-serving assistant also emerged
in the testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Another fallout of the case is the increasingly cranky defense
from Holtz. In appearances on his current book tour, Holtz has made
it clear he's tired of the subtle suggestions that he was
ultimately responsible for Notre Dame's fall from grace. He didn't
return phone calls seeking comment, but in recent interviews has
suggested Davie hasn't been telling the truth.
</P>
<P>
   The current coach is eager to put the summer behind him. He
concedes that he and his staff, as well as his team, have much to
prove this season. He also says directly what his administrators
will not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take very seriously anything that tarnishes the Dome,'' said
Davie. ``At Notre Dame you are judged by a different standard and
that's fair. It is what we sell.''
</P>
<P>
   He also knows that his fall can turn just as brutal as his
summer because the Irish will face six teams that beat them last
year. ``We didn't play very well on the field last year and that's
not characteristic of Notre Dame,'' said Davie. ``We can't control
what people say and write about us in the past. But we can control
what they say and write about in the future.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
