A3062 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABORTION-COX     08-13 0410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Doctors 'confused' over wording in abortion ban law
 &HT;    By Lisa Ocker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Two abortion doctors testified Thursday they would be
afraid to perform even the simplest, safest procedures for fear of
prosecution under a new state law.
</P>
<P>
   Drs. Edward Watson and James Pendergraft said the wording of the
so-called partial-birth abortion ban is so vague that it could
outlaw numerous types of abortion procedures, even those at the
earliest stage of pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   Watson, of A Choice for Women clinic in Miami, and Pendergraft,
of Orlando Women's Center, are among several Florida abortion
providers asking U.S. District Judge Donald Graham to declare the
law unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   A June 30 ruling by Graham temporarily blocked enactment of the
law. The doctors, represented by attorneys from the Center for
Reproductive Law and Policy in New York, asked him Thursday for an
extension of the ruling until a trial can decide the law's
constitutionality.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is language in law, which bans a procedure in which a
physician ``partially vaginally delivers a living fetus before
killing the fetus and completing the delivery.''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Attorney General Kathleen Burgener said the language
was more precise than medical terminology, which sometimes is
misused by physicians.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors disagreed. ``I'm confused by it,'' said Dr. Charles
deProsse, a retired physician and professor from Iowa. ''It doesn't
describe for me a medical procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said most common abortions involve the removal of fetal
material through a woman's vagina, rather than abdominally through
a hysterectomy or Caesarian section. And they testified that they
do not know when in the procedure the fetus no longer is
``living.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, attorney BeBe Anderson from the Center for
Reproductive Law and Policy argued that the law is unconstitutional
because it violates a woman's right to privacy in choosing safe,
commonly used abortion procedures.
</P>
<P>
   The law provides criminal penalties against doctors who break
the law _ including up to five years in prison and $5,000 fines _
and creates the possibility that they could be sued by fetus'
fathers or grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony continues Friday in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-08-13-98 2042E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
