</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAITIANS-HELPERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Investigators looking into Haitian smuggling ring
 &HT;    By Bill Douthat
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DELRAY BEACH, Fla. _ Authorities are investigating a link
between Haitians who are landing on Palm Beach County beaches and
local go-betweens who collect money from families to have their
relatives smuggled into the country.
</P>
<P>
   A team of local and federal law enforcement officials
interviewed Haitian-American community leaders Thursday in an
attempt to identify members of the smuggling ring.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Lincoln, director of law enforcement for the sheriff's
office, declined to comment on the investigation after leaving the
Haitian American Community Council. He said the sheriff's office is
investigating the deaths of two Haitians who drowned Monday when
two boatloads of immigrants came ashore near Jupiter Inlet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on the information that has developed, the (sheriff's
office) is assisting federal agents to see whether there are any
connections in South Florida,'' sheriff's spokesman Paul Miller
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sources in the Haitian-American community in Delray Beach say
two smugglers are known to operate in the area. They use beepers
and have no known offices or residences.
</P>
<P>
   Families pay up to $9,000 or more in advance to arrange for the
smugglers to transport relatives from Haiti to the Bahamas then to
the South Florida coastline, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Dorsonne, the father of the 26-year-old woman who drowned
Monday, said Thursday that Benette Dorsonne had come on her own.
Although he sent his daughter money for living expenses in Haiti,
the family paid no money to smugglers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Douthat writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
