A3064 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-ROSELLECOMO-COX     08-13 0353
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ROSELLECOMO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Roselle Como, wife of Perry Como, dies at 84
 &HT;    By Thom Smith
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUPITER, Fla. _ Roselle Como, wife of entertainer Perry Como,
died Tuesday after suffering a massive heart attack. Mrs. Como, 84,
was buried Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   On July 31, the Comos had celebrated their 65th wedding
anniversary. They had lived in Jupiter since 1957.
</P>
<P>
   Roselle Beline was born to French immigrant parents in the
southwest Pennsylvania mining town of Canonsburg in 1914. From the
moment Perry, then a teenaged barber, asked her to be his first
date at a school dance, she was always ``his girl.'' They married
in 1933, as Como left barbering to sing with Freddie Corlone's
orchestra. When he had doubts about a life on the road, she
convinced him to pursue his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``People forget that I wasn't always a success,'' Perry Como
once said. ``In the early years, there were some rough times when I
thought I'd quit (show) business. Roselle always stood by me.''
</P>
<P>
   As her husband's career flourished, Mrs. Como ran the home and
raised their three children, insulating them from the distractions
of show business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a home,'' Perry said. ``Roselle made it that. The world
that fussed over Perry Como never made it through the front door.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I always knew what I had with Roselle was special,'' Como once
said. ``I worked with the world's greatest talents, and then went
home to the world's greatest woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Mass was served by the Rev. Tom Vengayil, parish priest at St.
Jude Roman Catholic Church in Jupiter, who said the family
requested that services remain private. The Rev. Frank Lechiara of
St. Edwards Church in Palm Beach, a longtime family friend,
delivered the eulogy to an estimated 60 family members and close
friends. Mrs. Como was buried at Riverside Cemetery in Jupiter.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Como is survived by her husband, three children, 12
grandchildren and three great grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Thom Smith writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
