<HEADER>
A3080 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEST-POINT-NOVEL-ART-     08-13 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEST-POINT-NOVEL-ART-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WRITER ONCE SHUNNED RETURNS TO HIS ALMA MATER, WEST POINT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By FRANK BRUNI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST POINT, N.Y. _ Lucian K. Truscott IV has never been shy
about pointing _ or, more precisely, wagging _ his finger at his
hallowed alma mater, which looms tall and imposing above the Hudson
River here.
</P>
<P>
   In a quarter century of novels, newspaper articles and
television appearances, and most famously in his best-selling 1978
mystery ``Dress Gray,'' Truscott has chided the United States
Military Academy and the Army for secrecy and chastised them for
sexism and homophobia, describing flawed societies too often
governed by prejudice and personal ambition.
</P>
<P>
   That holds true in Truscott's new novel, ``Full Dress Gray,''
published by William Morrow &AMP; Co. last month. Once again, the
academy's immaculate grounds are suffused with the stench of foul
play. Once again, its Gothic edifices are cauldrons of duplicity
and deceit, bubbling over with sexual violence.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise is not what's in the pages of Truscott's potboiler.
It's the academy's response.
</P>
<P>
   The academy bookstore has set up two signings for Truscott on
Friday. The superintendent has invited him over for coffee before
the first one. The academic dean has asked him to dinner after the
second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I would never be welcome up there again,'' Truscott,
who graduated from the academy in 1969, said in a telephone
interview the other day from his home in Los Angeles. ``Now they're
in the process of milling a whole new red carpet to run out for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be a bit of an overstatement. But Truscott is certainly
getting a reception unlike any he has experienced in the past, and
his trip to West Point this week reflects a larger, longer journey
that the academy itself has taken, traveling over recent years
toward greater openness and a more measured, sophisticated response
to criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different era in the evolution of West Point,'' said
Brig. Gen. Fletcher M. Lamkin Jr., the academic dean, in an
interview here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Lamkin, dressed in an olive and forest green camouflage uniform,
was all warm smiles as he spoke of his keen interest in meeting
Truscott. ``I find him interesting,'' Lamkin said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he added, ``There's nothing wrong with bringing
controversial people to West Point,'' pointing out that during the
last academic year, both the folk singer Pete Seeger, who protested
vigorously against the Vietnam War, and the gender-bending pundit
Camille Paglia, whose sexual candor rivals Madonna's, gave speeches
at the academy.
</P>
<P>
   Although the academy's current administrators were not around
when ``Dress Gray'' was published, they said their understanding
was that it was greeted with a less tolerant, less sanguine
attitude. Truscott certainly remembers it that way, and news
reports from the time back him up.
</P>
<P>
   Although the bookstore carried the novel, active duty officers
were reportedly forbidden to make public comments about ``Dress
Gray,'' which imagined the murder of a gay cadet at the academy and
an elaborate cover-up by officers to conceal what had happened.
</P>
<P>
   The official academy newspaper ran a prepublication review,
written by a public affairs officer, that described ``Dress Gray''
as an effort to ``foist a story of perversion and intrigue on a
setting totally at odds with such a set of happenings.'' When the
book was subsequently made into a TV mini-series, the setting was
changed to a fictive military institution in part to ward off cries
of protest from West Point.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Andrew Goodpaster, who was the superintendent of the
academy when ``Dress Gray'' was published, said that he could not
recall any official policy regarding the book, but that it was
generally considered an ``assault on West Point.'' He never
contemplated meeting Truscott, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was then regarded as an enemy of West Point,'' Goodpaster,
now retired and living in Alexandria, Va., said in a telephone
interview.
</P>
<P>
   But most cadets interviewed at random at the academy Thursday
had heard little or nothing about ``Full Dress Gray,'' and the
current superintendent, Lieut. Gen. Daniel Christman, talked about
Truscott in relatively flattering terms. ``I've been very impressed
with his writing,'' Christman said.
</P>
<P>
   Christman said that in ``Full Dress Gray,'' Truscott correctly
reasons that ``institutions that stay hog-bound to tradition for no
other reason than that it's tradition quickly become irrelevant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful read on those issues,'' Christman said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 2110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0412 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3081 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEST-POINT-NOVEL-ART-     08-13 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEST-POINT-NOVEL-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WEST POINT, N.Y.: Christman said.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   His complimentary words can be attributed in part to subtle
differences between ``Full Dress Gray'' and its predecessor. The
tone of the new book is less heated, and its protagonist, Ry
Slaight, who was a cadet bucking a corrupt power structure in
``Dress Gray,'' is now part of that power structure, proving that
there are heroes and good intentions in high places.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is plenty for the academy to loathe in ``Full Dress
Gray,'' which involves the mysterious death of a female cadet; a
senior officer engaged in adultery with another officer's wife;
brutal misogyny among male cadets, and intimations of gang rape.
</P>
<P>
   The salient change from ``Dress Gray'' to ``Full Dress Gray'' is
in the climate surrounding each book. Senior officers at the
academy said that in the late 1970s, the academy was smarting from
a widely publicized cheating scandal in 1976. Also, like the Army
for which it was training officers, the academy was still reeling
from an anti-military sentiment in the United States that had
carried over from the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough time,'' Christman said. ``Everything was
tarnished by Vietnam and the overtones of that.''
</P>
<P>
   But the more positive public reaction to America's most recent
war, with Iraq, has relaxed the military's defensiveness. And the
less obvious role of the military in the aftermath of the Cold War
behooves it to take a friendlier approach toward public relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a real knowledge and understanding that at a
time when we are at peace in the world, when there is no massive,
solid support for the military and people question the need for it,
you've got to be more sophisticated in dealing with the public and
the press and critics,'' said Dave Palmer, a retired lieutenant
general who was the academy's superintendent from 1986 to 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the academy gives more access to reporters and camera
crews than it ever did in the past, though it does not throw
caution entirely to the wind. Public affairs officers emphasized
that administrators interviewed for this article were expressing
personal opinions about ``Full Dress Gray'' and not any official
academy position.
</P>
<P>
   The academy's relatively unbothered reaction to ``Full Dress
Gray'' may also acknowledge that while some of the scenarios in
Truscott's novel are riper than reality, the sexual tensions and
transgressions he describes merely echo a spate of actual scandals
in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   And the liberalization of the Army as it pursues better
integration of men and women has nudged many officers closer toward
the end of the political spectrum from which Truscott has always
fired off his critical salvos.
</P>
<P>
   Truscott, 51, the descendant of high-ranking Army officers,
wrote for The Village Voice when he was at West Point, belonged to
a group of cadets who mounted a successful legal challenge to the
constitutionality of compulsory chapel services and was considered
a leftist rabble-rouser.
</P>
<P>
   His relations with superiors in the Army were so bitter that he
was released from his obligation of service and given an
other-than-honorable discharge about a year after he left West
Point.
</P>
<P>
   He described the academy and the military then as sometimes
bullying and mean-spirited societies rife with suspicion toward
anyone with dissenting political views. Academy officials, looking
back at Truscott's record, said he was a rebellious nonconformist
who later admitted, in his writing, to using marijuana as a cadet
and mescaline as an Army officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He probably should have been at Berkeley, not West Point,''
Lamkin said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 2111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0413 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3083 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELTA-PRATT-WHITNEY-C     08-13 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-PRATT-WHITNEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta III: Historic for Pratt
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (a) general news and (f) financial categories.)
 &HT;    By Stephen Pounds
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ When the new Delta III rocket takes off
10 days from today, it will be a milestone for manufacturer Boeing
and its upper-stage rocket subcontractor, Pratt &AMP; Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   For Boeing, it will be the first launch of a rocket that allows
it to send larger, heavier communications satellites into orbit.
For Pratt, the launch will mark the first time that its RL10 rocket
is used as the upper stage by all U.S. commercial launch companies.
Already, the RL10 is used as the upper-stage rocket _ the engine
that pushes the payload into orbit _ on the Titan and Atlas launch
vehicles made by Lockheed Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our entry into the Delta family,'' said RL10 programs
manager Peter Sharf.
</P>
<P>
   What impressed Boeing is the increased power the new RL10B-2
could provide while using less fuel, helping Boeing to almost
double its payload size, said Mark Wilkins, Boeing's Delta III
product team leader.
</P>
<P>
   One Delta III launch is scheduled for this year, with four more
set for 1999. Boeing could accommodate two more next year,
according to Delta III program manager Dan Collins.
</P>
<P>
   With the addition of the Delta III, Pratt is positioned to take
advantage of what has become a growth industry in the 1990s _ the
commercial launch of communications satellites.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola and its partners have been paying for commercial
launches over the past 18 months for their Iridium network, the
string of satellites that will allow users to make wireless calls
and receive pages anywhere in the world. Iridium goes into
operation next month. And other satellite constellations are in the
works.
</P>
<P>
   The RL10, in some form, has been around since 1958, but Pratt
had its biggest production year in 1996, when it made 26. It
delivered 22 last year and expects to ship 20 in 1998, Sharf said.
It hopes to make 20 or more next year.
</P>
<P>
   The RL10 has been one of Pratt's more stable sources of revenue.
The company's Liquid Space Propulsion unit in northwestern Palm
Beach County accounts for $200 million of Pratt's $600 million
annually from space operations, with the RL10 alone contributing
$100 million. About 200 to 300 employees are involved in its design
and manufacture.
</P>
<P>
   The company's next move will be to sell the RL10 to overseas
launch companies, Sharf said. But for now, expanding to Boeing's
Delta line of rocket boosters is satisfaction enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The excitement for us is to get into Boeing world,'' Sharf
said.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Pounds writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
