</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-PRATT-WHITNEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta III: Historic for Pratt
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (a) general news and (f) financial categories.)
 &HT;    By Stephen Pounds
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ When the new Delta III rocket takes off
10 days from today, it will be a milestone for manufacturer Boeing
and its upper-stage rocket subcontractor, Pratt &AMP; Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   For Boeing, it will be the first launch of a rocket that allows
it to send larger, heavier communications satellites into orbit.
For Pratt, the launch will mark the first time that its RL10 rocket
is used as the upper stage by all U.S. commercial launch companies.
Already, the RL10 is used as the upper-stage rocket _ the engine
