<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3085 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLDENBEAR-STOCKS-COX     08-13 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDENBEAR-STOCKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Company that bears Nicklaus' name removed from NASDAQ
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving to (a) general news and (s) sports categories.)
 &HT;    By Phil Galewitz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Jack Nicklaus' publicly traded golf
company was delisted by the Nasdaq Stock Market Thursday because it
no longer meets capital requirements.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Golden Bear Golf Inc., based in North Palm Beach,
will either have to trade on the less visible over-the-counter
bulletin board or in the pink sheets, a daily publication of
infrequently traded, over-the-counter stocks that brokers subscribe
to.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in the Nicklaus lead company stopped trading last month
after the company announced a major revision to its 1997 earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Golden Bear was tossed by Nasdaq because it no longer had at
least $4 million in net tangible assets, that is the total assets
minus their total liabilities, the company said. Assets in this
case do not include goodwill, which is the amount of money a
company thinks its assets might be worth in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Golden Bear (Nasdaq: JACK) said it will not fight the delisting,
which will become effective at the close of business Tuesday. The
company said it will seek to have its securities traded on the
other markets after it files its amended 10-K for 1997 and its
quarterly earnings statement for the period ended June 30 with the
Securities and Exchange Commission. Spokesman Kenshen Bizzelli said
he did not know when the company planned to submit those reports.
</P>
<P>
   Bizzelli played down the significance of being delisted. ``We
see it as a neutral move that will have no impact on the company,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, companies get considerably more visibility on the
Nasdaq, largely because the stock market is listed in most
newspapers around the country along with the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Golden Bear made its debut on the Nasdaq on Aug. 1, 1996. The
company raised nearly $37 million that day to help it buy golf
driving ranges, then its ``core'' business. But Golden Bear
jettisoned all of its 14 centers in June when it became clear it
could not make money on them. At the time, Golden Bear said it
would concentrate on its golf course construction business and
licensing Nicklaus apparel.
</P>
<P>
   In July, the company said it will report a restated loss of
$24.7 million for 1997 to reflect evidence that former management
of a subsidiary falsified financial records. Golden Bear originally
posted a loss of $2.9 million for 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, seven lawsuits have been filed against Golden Bear
in U.S. District Court in West Palm Beach, including two filed
Thursday. All accuse the company of falsifying records. The law
firms of Berman, DeValerio &AMP; Pease of Boston and West Palm Beach
and Weiss &AMP; Yourman of New York filed the suits Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus has been unavailable for comment since Golden Bear's
problems began this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Galewitz writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 2114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
