</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBE-BARNICLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTIVISTS CRITICIZE BARNICLE DECISION, SEEK SMITH REINSTATEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DANIEL A. GRECH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Three activists in Boston's black community held a
press conference Thursday morning decrying a decision by The Boston
Globe to reinstate columnist Mike Barnicle on Tuesday after firing
black columnist Patricia Smith in June for what the activists said
were similar offenses.
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement, Sadiki Kambon, president of the Black
Community Information Center, said that if Smith is not reinstated,
then ``a call would be put out to the community of color to
boycott'' the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday evening, the Black Political Task Force issued a
statement criticizing Barnicle's reinstatement and asking for the
resignation of Globe Editor Matthew V. Storin.
</P>
<P>
   ``With respect to fairness, the Globe's disciplinary actions
simply do not meet the smell test,'' wrote Lloyd H. King, president
of the task force, contrasting Barnicle's treatment with that of
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Storin has maintained that Barnicle's offense _ using
unattributed materials in his column _ was different in magnitude
from Smith's. Smith resigned in June after admitting to fabricating
characters in four columns.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, another black leader, the Rev. Eugene Rivers, invited
Barnicle to ``a reasoned, courteous, and candid conversation''
about the controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle was unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The morning press conference was organized by Kambon, and
included Leonard Alkins, president of the Boston chapter of the
NAACP, and Rodney Mohammad of the Nation of Islam.
</P>
<P>
   Kambon said he believes the Globe was simply looking for an
excuse to fire Smith, an important figure in the black community.
</P>
<P>
   Last week The Globe asked Barnicle to resign after his column of
Aug. 2 was found to contain unattributed material from George
Carlin's bestseller ``BrainDroppings.'' Barnicle said he had never
read the book and was given a month's suspension. But after a video
clip surfaced showing Barnicle recommending the book on WCVB-TV's
``Chronicle,'' Barnicle was asked to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle refused, beginning a week-long standoff and public
relations campaign that ended when Barnicle was reinstated Tuesday
with a two-month suspension.
</P>
<P>
   The activists expressed outrage at Barnicle's tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barnicle mobilized his forces and went hard, going from
getting fired to having a two months' vacation,'' said Kambon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 2117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0418 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3089 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWISSBANKS-NAZIS-NYT &LR;      08-13 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISSBANKS-NAZIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME SANCTIONS AGAINST SWISS ENDED IN WAKE OF SETTLEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif., Pa.)   (bl)  
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A $1.25 billion settlement between Holocaust
survivors and Swiss commercial banks accused of profiting from the
Nazi era led officials in several states to cancel sanctions
Thursday against Swiss financial interests, even though disbursing
the money will take a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in New York, California, Pennsylvania and a number of
other cities and states had threatened to begin imposing sanctions
on Sept. 1, saying they were necessary to pressure the Swiss
because two years of negotiations had not led to a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. State Department had opposed the proposed penalties _
like barring short-term deposits of city and state funds in Swiss
banks _ saying such pressure was hardening attitudes in Switzerland
and souring relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pleased with the agreement'' with the banks, which was
announced Wednesday, said New York City Comptroller Alan Hevesi,
who heads a national committee of financial officers who have been
monitoring the negotiations. He said they ``have unanimously agreed
that we will cancel all planned sanctions.'' Hevesi spoke at a news
conference with New York State Comptroller H. Carl McCall.
</P>
<P>
   In California, Treasurer Matt Fong, who had imposed some
sanctions on Swiss banks a year ago, announced that he was lifting
all investment sanctions effective immediately. Pennsylvania
Treasurer Barbara Hafer said she was also canceling proposed
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish organizations and Holocaust survivors generally welcomed
the settlement as at least partial closure on a painful chapter.
``It is a fair settlement,'' said Rabbi Marvin Hier, the dean of
the Simon Wiesenthal Center in Los Angeles. ``I'm happy this is
over.''
</P>
<P>
   Jewish organizations took pains to stress that the settlement
was neither punishment for the banks nor a reward for survivors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not a question of a settlement; it is not a question of
money,'' said Benjamin Meed, the president of the American
Gathering of Holocaust Survivors and a survivor of the Warsaw
Ghetto. ``This is a question of morality.''
</P>
<P>
   Leo Rechter, 70, who survived the camps but whose father did
not, predicted that most Holocaust survivors would receive little
money. ``I think the Swiss could have done much better,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers for the plaintiffs said the amount roughly
corresponded to the amount of Jews' assets that were seized by the
Nazis and processed through Swiss banks. Joel Sweet, one of the
lawyers, said the settlement could establish an important global
precedent. ``When commercial actors profit illicitly from political
or human rights abuses, they will be forced to pay,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the settlement, the major Swiss commercial banks, Credit
Suisse and Union Bank of Switzerland, agreed to guarantee payments
of $1.25 billion, plus any interest accrued before the payments are
made. As a result of mergers and acquisitions, the two banks now
represent 85 percent of Switzerland's commercial bank activity in
1945, lawyers for the plaintiffs said.
</P>
<P>
   In return, a class-action lawsuit against the commercial banks
in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn and a suit in the Northern
District in California will be dropped, as will a major suit
against the government-owned Swiss National Bank in U.S. District
Court in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement does not resolve a separate suit in the Southern
District of New York against three major Swiss insurance companies,
one of which was recently purchased by Credit Suisse.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the Swiss government nor the National Bank took part in
the negotiations, although evidence indicates the national bank
processed most of the gold looted from Jews by the Nazis, and
neither is expected to contribute to the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Hevesi praised Judge Edward Korman, who several weeks ago began
personally overseeing the talks, for ``putting parties in a room
and apparently not letting them out until there was an agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials familiar with the negotiations said as recently as
Monday that the two sides were still far apart. Negotiations had
broken down in June after the Swiss offered $600 million, a figure
the plaintiffs quickly rejected.
</P>
<P>
   But the sanctions deadline was looming and pressure from elected
officials and other public figures increasing and finally, on
Wednesday afternoon, a settlement was reached.
</P>
<P>
   The money will go, first, to those able to document claims to
dormant accounts in Swiss banks, which often denied survivors or
their relatives access to funds deposited before the war if they
lacked proper documentation. Former Federal Reserve Chairman Paul
Volcker is leading a commission that is attempting to match some
8,000 claims against the dormant accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Morris Ratner, an attorney for the plaintiffs, predicted that
the amount paid out for dormant accounts would prove to be a
``small percentage'' of the total, since so much evidence on
specific claims has been lost or destroyed over the past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the money will be distributed to Holocaust survivors
through a mechanism yet to be determined. That money is considered
a form of ``rough justice,'' or restitution to those who cannot
prove their claims to lost assets, as well as for the profits Swiss
banks made from looted gold and art and from loans to the Nazis
that were used for the construction of slave-labor camps.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 law firms on the case can apply to Korman for fees, to be
paid from the settlement money, although some have indicated they
will not seek compensation.
</P>
<P>
   But no actual payments are likely to go out for some time,
Ratner said.
</P>
<P>
   After the judge gives preliminary approval to the settlement
amount, which could happen as early as next week, the Swiss banks
have 30 days to make the first payment of $250 million. But that
money cannot be distributed until the entire class represented in
the suit _ the hundreds of thousands of Holocaust survivors
worldwide _ have been notified and allowed to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The court will hold a public hearing before approving a plan for
distributing the funds. Ratner estimated that process would take at
least six to nine months.
</P>
<P>
   The average age of Holocaust survivors is approximately 81, and
Meed, of the survivors' group, provided a poignant reminder that
for many survivors, the settlement comes too late. Thursday
morning, he said, he learned that the president of the Krakow
Society of Holocaust survivors had died the previous night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 2117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0419 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3090 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CASTRO-MORTALITY-NYT &LR;      08-13 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASTRO-MORTALITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASTRO DEFIES DOOM WISHES OF EXILES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The first time Elizabeth Gueits heard that Fidel Castro
was dead, she was in school and 6 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the radio they said Castro had died,'' said Ms. Gueits, 32,
an insurance agent. ``We started to jump up and down, but I got
home and it wasn't true.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, she said, she has heard similar reports about 15
times _ ``that he was dying, that he was in the hospital, that he
was in a coma.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Until I see him in a coffin,'' Ms. Gueits said, ``I won't
believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, the adopted homeland of many Cubans who left their
country because of Castro, his death or near death has been grossly
exaggerated periodically for the nearly 40 years of his rule.
</P>
<P>
   Every so often a rumor about his impending demise or actual
expiration spreads like wildfire, only to be debunked by the
appearance of a fit-looking Castro delivering a six-hour speech.
</P>
<P>
   While exiles try to will him dead, and some have even plotted to
kill him, Castro turned 72 today.
</P>
<P>
   The latest collective disappointment stemmed from an article on
July 19 in the Spanish-language El Nuevo Herald, a report that was
reprinted by its sister paper, The Miami Herald, and picked up by
other news organizations.
</P>
<P>
   In the front-page article, a woman identified as a defecting
Cuban surgeon, Dr. Elizabeth Trujillo Izquierdo, said that Castro
had been treated last October for hypertensive encephalopathy, a
potentially fatal illness affecting the brain.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, it turned out, had really been a secretary in a Cuban
paper factory who suffered from ``personality problems,'' her
former husband later said. Roberto Fabricio, El Nuevo Herald's
managing editor, said the woman had duped his newspaper, which told
readers she had produced college degrees, her passport and her
Cuban identity card as ``proof'' that she was who she claimed to
be.
</P>
<P>
   Fabricio said that part of the problem in covering such a story
was the limited access to government information in Cuba, where
Castro's health is treated as a state secret. At the same time, any
news about Castro is of immense public interest here, Fabricio
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one in Miami in terms of the Cuba story is more important
than Fidel Castro,'' Fabricio said. ``The only agent of change that
one can identify in Cuba is the death of Castro.''
</P>
<P>
   When Castro quit smoking cigars a few years ago, many here
speculated it was surely because of lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Based on an interview with an exile leader who cited
``confidential sources,'' El Nuevo Herald reported in another
front-page article in 1996 that Castro had undergone surgery and
chemotherapy for ``extensive lung cancer,'' and that he had six
months to two years to live.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week, the leader, Arturo Cobo, said he
still believed his source, whose identity he said he could not
disclose for security reasons because the person is in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still a month left,'' Cobo said. ``Let's see what
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomas Garcia-Fuste, a radio commentator here for more than 30
years, said that often, sources for information about Castro are
Cuban doctors who offer detailed accounts of the supposed terminal
illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia-Fuste said he had helped spread the rumors himself
because he believed them, even though, he conceded, ``one has to
realize that he has money to pay for the best medicine and the best
medical attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, apparently fueled by a Havana news station's report
of the death of a revolutionary leader, a rumor that Castro had
actually died ricocheted over telephone lines across the Florida
Straits and in breathless radio and television coverage here,
forcing the Cuban Interests Section in Washington to issue a
statement saying Castro enjoyed ``excellent health.''
</P>
<P>
   Luis Fernandez, a spokesman for the Cuban Interests Section,
Cuba's diplomatic mission in Washington, called any talk of an
illness ``lies, propaganda, desire to misinform.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all a grand show to try to confuse and create problems,''
Fernandez said. ``His health is better than ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Francisco Aruca, another radio commentator who owns a company
that chartered flights to Cuba and has participated in dialogues
between exiles and Cuban government officials, blames journalists
who favor a hard line toward Cuba for giving legitimacy to
unsubstantiated reports that he said often served someone's
particular agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Max Castro, a University of Miami sociologist who writes columns
for El Nuevo Herald and is not related to the Cuban leader, noted
that while the Spanish-language press watches for any sign of
frailty in Castro, they missed the fatal illness of the most
powerful exile leader in their midst, Jorge Mas Canosa, until
barely a few months before his death in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``We imagine the one we hate dead,'' Castro said, ``and we deny
the real illness of the one we support.''
</P>
<P>
   Fidel Castro most recently defied his ill-wishers by touring the
Caribbean on an official visit without a hint of discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   But as Aruca, the commentator, said, ``Fidel Castro, sooner or
later, one day is going to get sick and die.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
