<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Umpire criticizes Cox for 'cheap shots' against rookie son
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Services
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Harry Wendelstedt weighed in his son Hunter's
dispute with the Atlanta Braves and Poppa wasn't happy.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hunter Wendelstedt is going to be a great umpire and he's
going to be somebody who's going to do a super job in this league
for a lot of years,'' said the 33-year veteran umpire. ''The cheap
shots that Bobby (Cox) took at him were just that _ cheap shots.
The fact of the matter is, Mr. Cox leads the league in ejections
every year. Everybody can't be wrong. So there's always three sides
to a story.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter Wendelstedt ejected both Cox and John Smoltz July 29 in
Cincinnati when they protested the rookie's call on a Bret Boone
tag play at third base. Wendelstedt stepped on Smoltz's foot as he
made the call and ejected him for making contact before he ran off
Cox, for putting his hand on his chest as he tried to separate him
from his pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   After the game that day, Cox called the incident, ''a case where
a rookie umpire reacted way too quickly to whatever he saw and
didn't realize what he was doing at the time. I think he's a good
kid.'' Informed Thursday of the senior Wendelstedt's comments, Cox
was in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   ''What cheap shots?'' he asked. ''I thought I was being easy on
him. I was trying to help a kid out of a bad situation. Tell Harry
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendelstedt left San Diego Thursday morning to make arrangements
for his father's funeral, after his death Tuesday night. Hunter
Wendelstedt, who was working with his father's crew this week, will
join the rest of the family today.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Wendelstedt has seen Hunter's written report of the
Cincinnati incident and sounded as if Smoltz might be exonerated in
the matter. Though incidents involving contact with umpires are
generally automatic suspensions, the National League office has yet
to rule on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ''In Smoltz's case in my opinion,'' Harry said, ''it looked like
an accident. Somebody stepped on (Smoltz's) foot and he gave a push
to get his foot out. But the umpire didn't even know he was on the
foot. He was busy showing where (Boone's) foot was. This isn't
something that should be blown up.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz, who was ejected for the first time in his career for
arguing with an umpire, remains adamant of his innocence and has
suggested he receive an apology instead of a suspension.
</P>
<P>
   ''If everybody sees what they saw, I didn't bump him,'' Smoltz
said. ''It should be a dead issue.''
</P>
<P>
   ''If (Hunter) had it to do all over again,'' Harry said, ''he
wouldn't have stepped on his foot. I can't speak for him but I'll
tell you this. I taught him how to umpire and I told him if anybody
in any way physically accosts you, then unload. And I still adhere
to that. I tell all my umpires that and I teach my crew the same
thing. It can't be tolerated.''
</P>
<P>
   No-no to the no-no
</P>
<P>
   Through the first five innings Thursday, Glavine had allowed a
walk to Quilvio Veras who was subsequently erased in a double play.
To that point, San Diego had nothing else. Perhaps the biggest
mystery attending the Braves rotations remains how this staff has
not generated a no-hitter (besides the departed Kent Mercker's)
through a decade of strong work. Glavine wasn't really thinking
that way.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know what's going on but I never expect to throw a
no-hitter,'' said Glavine, who now has five career-two-hitters.
''It's one of those things where if it happens, it happens. But I
wasn't going out there in the sixth inning thinking, I got a
no-hitter, I got great stuff, I'm going to throw a no-hitter today.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was kind of thinking, when are you going to give one up and
get this over with. I was just hoping I wouldn't do what I did,
which was get into a jam and have to throw out of the stretch for
the first time in the course of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Hop-a-long Guillen
</P>
<P>
   Walt Weiss was going to get a start at shortstop anyway Thursday
but Ozzie Guillen's right foot was so swollen after he fouled a
ball off it in the fifth inning the night before, to send him back
out there would be cruel and unusual.
</P>
<P>
   ''I couldn't put my shoe on last night,'' said Guillen. ''I
might be a couple days before I can do that. But I can push off.
That's the most important thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Guillen has started 18 of the 32 games since the All-Star break
and hit .320.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
