<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE SECRET SERVICE OFFICERS TESTIFY BEFORE GRAND JURY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also EXCLUSIVE-CLINTON-LEWINSKY) 
(JT) 
 By JAMES BENNET    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Prosecutors briefly questioned several more Secret
Services officers Thursday before the grand jury inquiring into
President Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Four Secret Service officers arrived at the federal courthouse
here Thursday morning to answer just one or two questions each,
said Michael Leibig, a lawyer representing some members of the
Secret Service. At least five more officers appeared for
questioning Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors then met with jurors, without witnesses, for almost
two hours before adjourning for the day. The grand jury does not
normally meet on Fridays, so prosecutors may have been preparing
the jurors for Monday, when they will hear testimony from Clinton.
His testimony, at the White House, is to be videotaped and
transmitted via closed-circuit television to the jury.
</P>
<P>
   Assistants to Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel in the
Lewinsky matter, have been asking agents and uniformed officers
whether they ever noticed Clinton and Ms. Lewinsky alone together.
</P>
<P>
   In his deposition in the Paula Jones sexual misconduct lawsuit,
Clinton said that he could not recall having been alone with Ms.
Lewinsky, the former White House intern, but that it was possible.
</P>
<P>
   Starr is investigating whether Clinton had a sexual relationship
with Ms. Lewinsky, lied about it under oath and tried to cover it
up.
</P>
<P>
   One retired Secret Service officer, Lewis Fox, has said that Ms.
Lewinsky visited the president when Fox was at his post near the
Oval Office on a Saturday in 1995. When he testified before the
grand jury in February, his lawyer, Leibig, said that Fox could not
say absolutely that the two met alone, or how long they were
together.
</P>
<P>
   Leibig, who represents only uniformed officers and not
plainclothes agents, said Thursday, ``I still don't believe anyone
in the uniformed division saw the president in a compromising
position.''
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, President Clinton met Thursday afternoon
with his private lawyers to continue preparing for his testimony on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., who is a member of Judiciary
Committee, sent Clinton a letter Thursday saying that he had grown
concerned about rumors and reports that he might refuse to answer
some questions or perhaps not testify at all.
</P>
<P>
   Specter urged the president to testify completely to help
conclude the investigation. ``It is worth noting the numerous
questions being raised as to whether Saddam Hussein or the
terrorists in Africa are acting because of the perceived weakness
of your presidency or the distraction of the Ms. Monica Lewinsky
matter,'' he wrote. He added that he did not think there was a
``causative link,'' but that the public discussion was ``very
problematic for American leadership abroad.''
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesmen have pointed to Clinton's remark two weeks
ago that he would testify ``completely and truthfully'' as evidence
that he intended to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
