<HEADER>
A3097 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-NYT &LR;      08-13 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WENDELL, BARD OF FLUSHING, NOW CAN CLOSE HIS STANZAS  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ For someone who says he does not necessarily want to
bring attention to himself, Turk Wendell has an unusual way of
going about it.
</P>
<P>
   Forget for a moment the antics Wendell brought with him to the
major leagues. He no longer brushes his teeth between innings or
chews licorice on the mound _ although he still hops high over the
base line coming on and off the field. A few springs ago, Wendell's
manager with the Cubs, Jim Riggleman, asked him to stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he wanted everybody to know me as a pitcher instead of
a weirdo,'' Wendell said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in several seasons with the Cubs, Wendell proved his
competence as a reliever and in one season, 1996, even notched 18
saves as the team's closer. But until recently, about all he was
known for as a Met was being a throw-in in the trade that brought
Mel Rojas and Brian McRae to New York last August. At 31, he was a
low-ranking member of a not very reliable bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   All that has changed, though, in the last few weeks. Wendell has
suddenly emerged as a key player, the one right-handed reliever
Manager Bobby Valentine can reasonably depend on when the game is
close.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday and Tuesday in St. Louis, he struck out Mark McGwire
the two times he faced him, once with McGwire as the tying run at
the plate. On Wednesday night, Wendell not only pitched for the
third night in a row, but also contributed his sixth straight
scoreless appearance in nine days in an agonizing game the Mets
would eventually lose, 5-4, in 14 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell, now 4-0 with a 3.09 earned run average, is obviously
pleased with his elevated role but not quite comfortable with the
attention it brings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earlier in the year, no reporters talked to me,'' he said.
``Now everyone wants to talk to me. When you get the big contract,
guys put a little more pressure on themselves.'' Which, Wendell
seemed to be suggesting, is exactly what he doesn't want to do and
which may be why he played down his dominance of McGwire, the most
fearsome hitter in the major leagues, noting that each time he
struck him out he left a slider over the plate that McGwire could
have crushed.
</P>
<P>
   Around the Mets' clubhouse, Wendell is perceived as something of
a loner. Few of his teammates are aware that one way he attempts to
relax is by writing poetry, something he started doing in 1986,
when he was a sophomore at Quinnipiac College in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a weird way to kind of know I can express my emotions
without having to tell somebody about it,'' he said earlier this
season.
</P>
<P>
   His poems are about baseball, life on the road, relationships
with his family, friends and newborn daughter. There is one he
penned jointly with Deion Sanders on a bus trip when both were in
the minors.
</P>
<P>
   Another early effort, entitled ``Life Is Like a Baseball,'' can
be used as a metaphor for Wendell's bumpy career. It reads, in
part:
</P>
<P>
   Life is like a baseball,
</P>
<P>
   It has many curves,
</P>
<P>
   It has many sliders,
</P>
<P>
   It has many forks,
</P>
<P>
   It has many change-ups,
</P>
<P>
   It gets tossed around constantly,
</P>
<P>
   And it gets hit real hard.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, no one is hitting Wendell hard. What, the Mets
pitching coach Bob Apodaca was asked, enabled Wendell to turn
things around?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think belief in himself,'' Apodaca said. ``It comes down to
that elusive ingredient he injects in himself called confidence.
Also, I think he feels the confidence that Bobby has in him.
Bobby's just been waiting for this to happen. That go-to label has
to be earned. We were waiting for him to earn it. Now he has. He's
now somebody we're very comfortable with. And it couldn't come at a
better time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, he is a little bit of a flake. But he is 100 percent a
gamer. And he wants to pitch in those situations. He has no fear.''
</P>
<P>
   Except, perhaps, of public recognition. But if Wendell keeps on
pitching as he has, he will have to learn to deal with it. ``People
still think I'm a weirdo,'' Wendell said earlier this season.
Maybe, but in New York, people now realize he can pitch.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 2130EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
