<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGANOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jones' home courses on display in 2001
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ The Bobby Jones legacy will receive plenty of
attention in Atlanta in 2001. Both clubs that Jones made famous _
East Lake Golf Club and the Atlanta Athletic Club _ will host major
championships.
</P>
<P>
   East Lake has the 2001 U.S. Amateur and the Athletic Club, as
was officially announced Tuesday by the PGA of America, has been
selected to host the 83rd PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who was alive when the original East Lake Golf Club
relocated to Duluth, Ga. in 1967, would have had difficulty
choosing a favorite between the two spots, according to AAC
president John Koontz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jones always said that the Athletic Club is my home club and
East Lake is my home course,'' said Koontz, one of 11 Athletic Club
members in attendance at Winged Foot Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   Redesigned in 1995 by Rees Jones, the Athletic Club's Highlands
Course last hosted a PGA Championship, won by Marietta, Ga.'s Larry
Nelson, in 1981. It also was the site for the 1976 U.S. Open, won
by Jerry Pate. The Athletic Club's Riverside Course also hosted the
1990 U.S. Women's Open, won by Betsy King.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not redo the course with Rees to get a major
championship,'' Koontz said of the club's two-year, $2 million
renovation. ``We did it for the members.
</P>
<P>
   For architect Rees Jones, Georgia in 2001 will be quite a
showcase. In addition to reworking both East Lake and the Athletic
Club, he designed Ocean Forest on Sea Island, which will host the
2001 Walker Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Pavin out
</P>
<P>
   Corey Pavin withdrew from the tournament because of the death of
his father, Jack, from a heart attack. Pavin was replaced in the
150-player field by Waycross' Taylor Smith. ... Australia's Peter
Senior withdrew and was replaced by Glen Day. ...Today's featured
pairing is an obvious one _ the trio of Masters champion Tiger
Woods, British Open champion Justin Leonard and U.S. Open champion
Ernie Els at 8:55 a.m. ... Two-time PGA champion Larry Nelson is
paired with five-time winner Jack Nicklaus and defending champion
Mark Brooks at 12:31 pm.
</P>
<P>
   Study time
</P>
<P>
   Captain Tom Kite used the PGA practice rounds for some extra
Ryder Cup scrutiny, playing over the last few days with Davis Love
III, Brad Faxon, Leonard, David Duval and Tommy Tolles. ... Els, on
a potential rivlary developing among him and other young players
such as Woods, Leonard and Phil Mickelson: ``This is not like
tennis; you don't play directly against the guy on the other side
of the net. We've got (150) players here. You have to beat those
players and you have to beat the golf course.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
