<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RUSSIAN STOCKS AND BONDS PLUMMET INTO FREE FALL
</P>
<P>
   Russia's stock and bond markets plunged, taking with them hopes
of averting a depletion of the government's finances and a meltdown
of the country's banking system. Capping a week of ominous
declines, the nation's major blue-chip stock index dropped as much
as 25 percent before rebounding some. It ended down 6.5 percent.
The Russian government said the panic was psychological, not
fiscal, and repeated, as it has in recent days, that it had money
to meet its obligations through the fall.
</P>
<P>
   DOW CATCHES TOUCH OF RUSSIAN FLU
</P>
<P>
   Russia's trouble reverberated in the United States, sending the
Dow Jones industrial average down 1.1 percent. The blue-chip gauge
dropped 93.46 points, to 8,459.50, its lowest point of the day, led
down by DuPont. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 9.31
points, or eight-tenths of a percent, to 1,074.91, and the Nasdaq
index declined 22.99 points, or 1.3 percent, to 1,802.54. Treasury
prices fell for a second day because of a weaker dollar.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING AND UNION REACH 737 DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Boeing and its biggest union reached a deal that paves the way
for the company to produce the 737 commercial jet at the former
McDonnell Douglas complex in Long Beach, Calif. Although the deal
was designed to allay union fears of job losses, Boeing also said
it planned to cut even more employees than it had indicated last
month.
</P>
<P>
   TRADE SURPLUS FALLS IN JAPAN
</P>
<P>
   Japan's current account surplus fell in June from May to about
$10 billion, the ninth decline in the last 13 months, as exports to
other Asian nations slowed and imports rebounded from a
two-and-a-half-year low.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA TO INVESTIGATE LIVENT
</P>
<P>
   Securities regulators in Canada said that they are investigating
the accounting problems at Livent, the company based in Toronto
that brought the hit musicals ``Ragtime'' and ``Showboat'' to
Broadway. On Monday, Livent's new management announced that an
internal investigation had found serious accounting problems.
</P>
<P>
   GEOCITIES SETTLES PRIVACY CASE
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission said that Geocities, a popular Web
site, had lied about its privacy policy and reached a settlement
under which the company would stop promising subscribers that it
would not give out personal information.
</P>
<P>
   RETAIL SALES DIPPED IN JULY
</P>
<P>
   Retail sales fell four-tenths of 1 percent in July, reflecting
the General Motors strikes, the Commerce Department said. Excluding
automobiles, sales rose for the sixth time in seven months.
</P>
<P>
   KMART AND GAP POST GOOD RESULTS
</P>
<P>
   Kmart and the Gap reported quarterly earnings that were better
than expected, aided by the strong economy and a return to the
basic fashions favored by their mainstay customers.
</P>
<P>
   LEVI STRAUSS TAKES CUE FROM STREET
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to remain hip with America's youth, Levi Strauss is
introducing a campaign infused with an unconventional, streetwise
attitude for its Silver Tab line of clothing. Instead of using
typical attractive models to showcase the clothes, the campaign
features colorful images of teen-agers displaying their
individuality.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 2132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
