<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0426 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3102 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT     08-13 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: CHERISHED, AND LOST MEMORIES  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By IRA BERKOW    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At the conclusion of the memorial mass celebrated for
Roger Maris in St. Patrick's Cathedral in New York, which took
place two days before Christmas in 1985, Cardinal John O'Connor
asked everyone in the crowded congregation, including the 12
priests at the altar, to stand. He then requested that those in
attendance give ``one last burst of applause to honor this man.''
</P>
<P>
   The plaudit for the former Yankee slugger lasted about a minute.
``Steven,'' O'Connor said, looking at Maris' 8-year-old grandson,
who wore a gray suit and a red tie, ``you were not around to hear
your grandfather applauded in the Stadium, but you'll remember
this, OK?''
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal smiled gently. Steven, seated with his family in
the second row, his feet not touching the floor, nodded solemnly to
the cardinal. Some 13 years later, Steven, the son of Roger's
daughter, Susan, is a stocky 21-year-old student at Santa Fe
Community College in Gainesville, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steven remembers that day,'' his uncle, Roger Maris Jr., said
Thursday by telephone from Gainesville, Fla. ``We all do. I was
only 3 years old when Dad broke the homer record in 1961, so I
didn't hear the cheers then, either.''
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal hadn't mentioned the boos, or, as Roger Jr. would
say, how his father was ``short-changed'' in receiving the
accolades due him. Most of the Maris family lives in Gainesville,
where Roger Sr., after retiring from the St. Louis Cardinals in
1968, and his brother Rudy were given a Budweiser distributorship
by August Busch, owner of the beer company and the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   And Roger Jr., like the rest of the family _ like the rest of
the nation, for that matter _ is being reminded daily this year of
the most renowned and, to some, notorious achievement of his
father's 12-year baseball career. It was when he banged out 61 home
runs in 1961 to break Babe Ruth's single-season homer mark of 60.
Every day Roger Jr. reads how Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa and Ken
Griffey Jr., among others, are hitting home runs that put them in
position to catch or pass his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm enjoying it'' said Roger Jr., now 40 years old. ``I think
it's neat to know that guys have been chasing the record for so
long. You know that Dad has held the home run record longer than
Babe Ruth did. Dad broke the record 34 years after Ruth's record.
And it's been 37 years since Dad hit 61.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the country would like to see the record broken _ it
adds excitement and interest to the game _ but that wasn't the case
when Dad was going for it. He was going up against two baseball
icons, Babe Ruth and Mickey Mantle.''
</P>
<P>
   It is true, and the baseball memories for Roger Maris Sr. were
bittersweet. I spent a day with him in Gainesville in the summer of
1970, two years after he retired from baseball.
</P>
<P>
   I asked him if he followed the Yankees in the standing? ``The
Yankees? Did I ever play for the Yankees?'' He smiled a half-smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I ever had to have good memories about my baseball
career,'' he told me, ``they probably had to be before 1961.'' He
reached the majors with Cleveland in 1957, was traded to Kansas
City the following season, dealt to the Yankees before the 1960
season and traded to the Cardinals after the 1966 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yankees wanted Mickey to break the record,'' he said.
(Mantle, a Yankee hero from the early 1950s, finished the 1961
season with 54 homers.) ``I was never the fair-haired boy over
there.''
</P>
<P>
   He understood that many people didn't want him to break the
hallowed Ruth record. And Commissioner Ford Frick said the record
book would indicate that he broke the mark in 162 games, as opposed
to Ruth's 154 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they say 154 games, which 154 games are they talking
about?'' Maris asked. ``The first 154, the middle 154, the last
154? If it's the first, then I'd still have tied Ruth, because I
didn't hit my first homer until the 11th game. If it was the last
154 or the middle 154, then I'd have broken it anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   While with the Yankees, he said, he was booed at home and on the
road. ``You say it doesn't affect you,'' he said. ``But it does,
finally. All that stopped when I went to the National League.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he didn't think much about the 61 homers. ``It's in the
past,'' he said. ``Maybe it'll become important to me when I'm 65
or 70. Maybe then I'll think about it, and enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't to be. Roger Maris died of lymphatic cancer at age 51.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, records are made to be broken,'' said Roger Maris Jr.
``But, honestly, I'd like to see Dad hang on to this one a little
longer.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
