<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-PEPSI400-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Tale of two drivers continues
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gordon, Martin have extra incentives to win Pepsi 400
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By TERRY BLOUNT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
BROOKLYN, Mich. _ The top two drivers in Winston Cup racing have a
few things on their mind and a lot on the line this weekend at
Michigan Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   For Jeff Gordon, it's a chance to tie a NASCAR record for
consecutive victories and add another major accomplishment to his
list of achievements.
</P>
<P>
   For Mark Martin, it's a chance to honor the man who made him a
race-car driver. Mark's father, Julian, was killed in a plane crash
last weekend, and Martin raced in the Bud at the Glen not knowing
his father had died a few hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
   So the two men at the top of the points standings come to
Michigan with added incentive to win.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon has been winning so much these days that things are
starting to get a little boring. But this weekend is different for
the man who seems to be finishing first everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon heads to one of the few places left on the Cup circuit
where he has yet to win a race. He has driven the DuPont Chevrolet
in 11 races at Michigan Speedway without a victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been close at Michigan so many times, but we haven't
been able to pull it off there,'' Gordon said. ``The odds may be
against us, but I'm going to do everything possible to be there at
the end.''
</P>
<P>
   If Gordon wins the Pepsi 400 on Sunday, it will be his fourth
consecutive victory, tying the modern NASCAR record that is shared
by six other drivers.
</P>
<P>
   But the two-mile, D-shaped oval at Michigan is one of only four
tracks where Gordon has failed to cross the finish line first. It
is the only track of the 13 where the Cup circuit races twice a
year that Gordon hasn't won, meaning there is no speedway in
America where Gordon has raced so many times without winning.
</P>
<P>
   The three other tracks where Gordon has yet to win are Phoenix,
Fort Worth and Las Vegas, but the Texas event is only two years old
and the Las Vegas race was added to the schedule this year. Phoenix
and Michigan are the only tracks where Gordon has raced more than
twice without winning.
</P>
<P>
   But don't get the idea that Gordon hasn't run well at Michigan.
The 27-year-old driver has finished second three times and third
three other times in races at Michigan. His average finish at
Michigan is 5.3, better than any other Cup driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really enjoy racing at Michigan,'' Gordon said. ``The track
is fast, flat, and has wide, sweeping turns. It makes passing a lot
easier.''
</P>
<P>
   The one man who may have the best chance of passing Gordon at
Michigan is Martin, who has won four times at the speedway in the
Irish Hills, including the last two Cup races at Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   But Martin comes to Michigan with a heavy heart. His 62-year-old
father was killed when the private plane he was piloting crashed
six days ago in Nevada. Also killed were Julian's wife, Shelley,
38, and their 11-year-old daughter, Sarah.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, 39, was told of the tragedy by his wife, Arlene, when he
returned home to Florida after the race at Watkins Glen, N.Y.
Martin attended his father's funeral in Arkansas on Wednesday with
his wife and five children, and then flew to Detroit to prepare for
the race. How the shocking death of his father will affect him
remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Julian, who raced on dirt tracks when Mark was a boy, got Martin
started in go-kart racing 34 years ago when Mark was 5 years old.
His father built Mark's first race car when Mark was 15, a year
before Mark was eligible for a driver's license.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father was my hero,'' Martin said. ``There was never a
moment for me and my sisters when we didn't know how proud he was
of us. You couldn't love a son more than he loved me. He is an
unbelievably generous person.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt Martin would love to win this weekend for his father,
but he also would love to end his streak of second-place finishes.
Martin has finished second in each of the last four races.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like they say, second place is the first loser,'' said Martin,
who is 82 points behind Gordon in the series standings. ``I'm tired
of running well and losing. But you can't whine about it. The truth
is, if you finished second in every race, you would win the
championship.''
</P>
<P>
   A majority of most NASCAR crowds like to see Gordon lose, and
this weekend should be no exception. Loyalties among the other
drivers usually are split, but most of the 150,000 fans who will be
on hand Sunday will be cheering for Martin to win because of the
tragic circumstances he has endured this week.
</P>
<P>
   Martin is the first to admit it will take a lot more than fan
support to beat Gordon and the Rainbow Warriors.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may win them all,'' Martin said after Gordon won at Watkins
Glen. ``The guy has us all covered.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon isn't so sure, knowing this track and this week could be
Martin's show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the utmost respect for Mark,'' Gordon said. ``I like to
race him hard, but I also always race him clean. That's the kind of
respect he has always given back to me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
