<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3124 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARENAKED-LADIES14-CO     08-13 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARENAKED-LADIES14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Quirky Canadian band finally gets respect in the States
 &HT;    By Jon Glass
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ If Canada has its own version of the
``American success story,'' Barenaked Ladies is it.
</P>
<P>
   A decade in the making, these north-of-the-border superstars
finally have struck the right chord with U.S. music fans. The
Ladies' quirky alternative rock hit, ``One Week,'' is the summer's
most infectious radio single and their newest album, ``Stunt,''
recently entered the charts at No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never would have expected it, but I'll take it,''
singer-guitarist Ed Robertson said recently from Hartford, Conn.,
where the band is touring with the H.O.R.D.E. festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is a success story. The beauty of it is that we did
it the old-fashioned way.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson and fellow singer-guitarist Steven Page formed the
Ladies in Toronto in 1988 after dabbling in sketch comedy and
songs. They took a name that, if nothing else, would at least
attract curious music fans to their shows. What people found early
on was a sharp blend of pop-rock, country and humor that fueled
atypical live performances. Their fellow countrymen loved it, and
the Ladies' first release, ``Gordon,'' became Canada's first
independent album ever to reach gold status.
</P>
<P>
   Three more releases continued to bring them accolades, praise
and sales success in Canada. But Robertson, Page, bassist Jim
Creeggan, multi-instrumentalist Kevin Hearn and drummer Tyler
Stewart were not getting a response in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   A minor radio hit, ``The Old Apartment,'' finally slipped onto
American airwaves in 1996, and the Ladies made their move. A
calculated plan put the Ladies on the road 10 months of the year to
conquer the United States _ one Yankee at a time if they had to.
</P>
<P>
   American bands like Dave Matthews Band and Hootie and the
Blowfish had done the same thing, but most Canadian acts had not
been able to duplicate that formula.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a perception in the media and music industry that
Canada is Portugal or some other foreign market, when really it's
very similar to the U.S. music industry,'' Robertson said. ``The
only way to circumvent it is to get down here and work at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our country just doesn't have respect.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ladies' unpredictable stage show became the biggest selling
point. Between songs, Robertson and Page would break into rapping,
often covering the pop hit of the day. Spice Girls songs have been
slipping into the mix lately.
</P>
<P>
   Lasting traditions were formed as well. Fans still throw boxes
of macaroni and cheese on stage during ``If I Had $1000000,'' which
refers to not having to eat Kraft dinners again if their dreams
came true.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every Ladies show is different, and that's what fans have come
to expect,'' Robertson said. ``The cool thing is that we've built
the audience that knows that.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a typical Ladies ``tribute'' to Beach Boys founder
Brian Wilson (``I'm lying in bed/Just like Brian Wilson did'') hit
the rock charts, even though it was recorded for their first album
in 1992. It helped push the breakthrough even further.
</P>
<P>
   Then, their release ``Rock Spectacle,'' featuring live versions
of ``Brian Wilson'' and ``The Old Apartment,'' became the band's
first gold album in the United States. A small break from touring
gave them time to record Stunt, which ranges from the peaceful
``Light Up My Room'' to the Squeeze-sounding ``Alcohol.''
</P>
<P>
   The rapping style that was helping make Ladies shows so
different was laid down in the studio for the first time on ``One
Week,'' a playful number about a relationship fight that tosses in
references to Aquaman, ``The X-Files'' and LeAnn Rimes.
</P>
<P>
   H.O.R.D.E., the traveling brigade of roots rock pioneered by
fellow headliners Blues Traveler, is the Ladies' most visible
opportunity yet in their quest to build their American audience.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson said they've already been joined on stage by tour
mates such as Blues Traveler frontman John Popper and have been
frequenting the festival's small workshop stage, where musicians
are left to their own devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``H.O.R.D.E. is that right kind of festival atmosphere that
lends itself to spontaneity,'' he said. ``We're winning over a
bunch of new fans because it's an audience ripe for the picking.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Robertson may joke about the Ladies' ultimate goal _
world pop domination _ it's not so unrealistic anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just been such a good time so far, it's hard to believe
we've been at it for 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Jon Glass writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
