<HEADER>
A3126 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHRISTIAN-HUMOR14-COX     08-13 1526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTIAN-HUMOR14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Would Jesus be laughing?
 &HT;    By Steve Gushee
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The magazine is outrageous, funny and
irreverent. The writers are evangelicals committed to Christ. Their
critics would like them committed to a rubber room.
</P>
<P>
   One issue of ``The Door'' claimed that Bob Dole was the
antichrist. Editors named Beavis and Butt-head theologians of the
decade and called Mother Teresa the loser of the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   A few subscribers canceled for such arrogance, but staff members
think cancellations are evidence they're doing their job. They're
out to demonstrate that Christian humor only appears to be an
oxymoron.
</P>
<P>
   This group of slightly wacky Christians uses laughter, sarcasm
and irony to ridicule religion's sacred cows, deflate pious egos
and expose religious charlatans.
</P>
<P>
   Slapstick humor abounds. Cartoons chastise the pope, Promise
Keepers and the pious. Satire remains the magazine's primary
weapon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of ``The Door'' is to satirize and make fun of
anyone who takes themselves seriously in the name of God,'' said
publisher Ole Anthony. ``I'd like it to smash the idolatry that is
so common in the American church.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony, 60, is president and founder of the Trinity Foundation
in Dallas. That hybrid organization embraces an experimental
Christian community, cares for the homeless, operates a detective
agency and publishes the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   No one automatically escapes the magazine's acerbic wit. Recent
editions have poked fun at Billy Graham, Bill Clinton, Madonna,
Louis Farrakhan, Pat Robertson, Focus on the Family and countless
televangelists.
</P>
<P>
   The latest edition includes a satire of Palm Beach resident
Lowell ``Bud'' Paxson, the ``zillion aire'' born-again father of
the Home Shopping Network.
</P>
<P>
   The ``world's pretty much only religious satire magazine''
prints a mock schedule for Paxson's new, ``alternative'' network,
Pax TV.
</P>
<P>
   Kathie Lee's Christian Chatter airs at 9. All The News You
Should Believe runs at noon. Barney Believes and Sesame Street
Saves fill the after-school slots.
</P>
<P>
   Writers gleefully expose ministers who use God to get rich and
ridicule politicians who insist the Lord is on their side.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Door'' uses humor to attack television preachers who use
twisted theology to heal by telepathy in exchange for money by
mail. The magazine wags a satirical finger at the faithful for
naively accepting such nonsense as religious truth.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the bimonthly magazine can be serious. It carries
legitimate interviews with religious and secular people. The
July/August edition includes conversations with columnist Molly
Ivins, cartoonist John Callahan and respected evangelical author
Keith Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Door'' began as a newsletter for Christian youth workers
27 years ago. It originally was named ``The Wittenberg Door'' after
the place where Martin Luther made his religious protest.
</P>
<P>
   Founder Mike Yaconelli, who produces training programs for youth
counselors, grew weary of the magazine's demands. He gave the
property to Anthony's foundation in January 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Today, ``The Door'' has about 10,000 subscribers and loses
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave ourselves the loser of the year award for taking over
a magazine that loses $30,000 a year,'' Anthony said.
</P>
<P>
   Loyal readers include a broad representation of the population
as well as seminarians and clergy, Anthony said.
</P>
<P>
   They laugh at what they find funny, moan at the silliness,
rejoice when they agree with the target of satire and cry foul when
their ox is gored.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun,'' said the Rev. Simeon Corona, pastor of St. Mary's
Antiochan Orthodox Church in West Palm Beach, Fla. ``Sometimes they
push the line. When they proclaimed Mother Teresa the loser of the
decade, it was a little much.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony means to be outrageous. ``Sacred cows make good
hamburger,'' he wrote. And smashing idols is his ministry.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to publishing ``The Door,'' Trinity Foundation
monitors _ and exposes _ the fraud promoted as faith by many radio
and television evangelists.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony has a private investigator's license. He works to expose
the greed that motivates some media preachers and the lies that
make them popular.
</P>
<P>
   A foundation report on the excesses of evangelist Robert Tilton
was seen on ``Prime Time Live'' with Diane Sawyer in 1991. ``CNN,''
``Time'' and other news agencies have used the foundation to
investigate religious fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation charges networks for expenses only, Anthony said.
Their budget is about $400,000, raised from news media, ``The
Door'' and friends.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those friends are part of what Anthony believes is the
foundation's most important ministry: caring for the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 50 of more than 300 foundation members live in homes
clustered together on a few blocks of the same rundown
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a Christian community in a slum area of East Dallas,''
Anthony said. ``We take in the poor and homeless, but we take them
into our homes _ not into shelters.''
</P>
<P>
   And they live by a code that makes a vow of poverty seem like an
easy way to live. Community members take this vow:
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever I have that you need to use, you can use. Whatever I
have that you need to own, I'll give to you. Whatever you need that
I don't have, I'll help you get it.''
</P>
<P>
   The founder and the foundation's 20 employees each makes $50 a
week plus room and board provided in homes rented by the
foundation, Anthony said.
</P>
<P>
   The unmarried leader of this unusual Christian ministry was
raised as a nominal Lutheran. He says he was an atheist until he
had a conversion experience in 1972. Listening to a speaker, he was
overwhelmed by the graciousness of God.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sitting in a room with about 150 people, and for about
an hour and a half I just sat there and sobbed,'' Anthony said.
</P>
<P>
   He sold his public relations firm and became the host of a
Christian radio talk show. A year later, he quit radio when the
station was sold.
</P>
<P>
   He started Trinity Foundation as a way to offer ``honest''
Christian programming, but the corporation lay dormant for nearly
14 years. He was studying the Bible and teaching a group that
gradually became a community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slowly, the Bible study became a body,'' Anthony said. ``The
body became a community.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, that community exposes religious fraud and publishes
religious satire. But Anthony insists that caring for the poor is
its primary ministry.
</P>
<P>
   ``How the church treats the homeless is how God will treat the
church,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Contact ``The Door'' at www.the-door.org or (800) 597-3667. A
year's subscription costs $29.95.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT WOULD JESUS DO? ROOT FOR UNDERDOG Popular WWJD bracelets,
worn by Christian teens to help their decision-making, is an
acronym for `What Would Jesus Do?' ``The Door'', a magazine of
religious satire, has some answers.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus would visit Disney World, but only on `Gay Day.'
</P>
<P>
   Jesus would drive a Yugo over a Volvo, but he'd probably take
the bus.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus would call pornographic actress Marilyn Chambers and not
Pat Robertson to be a disciple.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus would never wear a diamond-studded cross or gold
crown-of-thorns ring.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus would not be caught dead on TBN or ``The 700 Club,'' nor
would he make a special appearance at a Franklin Graham crusade.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus would not live in either Beverly Hills or Martha's
Vineyard. He'd probably hang out in Salvation Army homeless
shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus would not visit a Promise Keepers rally unless they let
Mary and Martha in, too.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus would be a Cubs fan.
</P>
<P>
   Source: ``The Door'', Trinity Foundation, Dallas
</P>
<P>
   WHEN SERMON TITLES GO TERRIBLY, TERRIBLY WRONG
</P>
<P>
   Satirical sermon titles from ``The Door'':
</P>
<P>
   If God had wanted me poor, he wouldn't have made you gullible
</P>
<P>
   Sex and the Rapture: Reading between the lines of Revelation
</P>
<P>
   Alcohol, Bribery and Cheating: the ABC's of seminary
</P>
<P>
   The Father, the Son and Me
</P>
<P>
   Heresies are better than Pharisees
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic groups that will burn in Hell
</P>
<P>
   I'm not saying that old people are stupid . . .
</P>
<P>
   If Rush Limbaugh were an apostle . . .
</P>
<P>
   God, your pastor and other benign dictators
</P>
<P>
   I don't think this is in the Bible, but . . .
</P>
<P>
   Source: ``The Door'', Trinity Foundation, ,Dallas
</P>
<P>
   TOP 10 WAYS TO KNOW YOU HAVE JOINED THE WRONG CHURCH
</P>
<P>
   10. The church bus has gun racks.
</P>
<P>
   9. The church staff consists of senior pastor, associate pastor
and sociopastor.
</P>
<P>
   8. The Bible they use is the Dr. Seuss Version.
</P>
<P>
   7. There is an ATM in the lobby.
</P>
<P>
   6. The choir wears leather robes.
</P>
<P>
   5. The worship services are B.Y.O.S. (Bring your own snake).
</P>
<P>
   4. There's no cover charge, but communion is a two-drink
minimum.
</P>
<P>
   3. The pastor regularly attends meetings in Las Vegas and
Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   2. The ushers ask, ``Smoking or nonsmoking?''
</P>
<P>
   1. The Woman's Quartet are all married to the pastor.
</P>
<P>
   Source: ``The Door'', Trinity Foundation, Dallas
</P>
<P>
   Steve Gushee writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
