<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-TAXFREE-WEEK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hurry, hurry! Step right up and take advantage of no taxes
 &HT;    By Lynda Edwards
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Beginning Saturday morning, you can buy
a new wardrobe and not pay a cent in sales tax _ if each item is
$50 or less.
</P>
<P>
   Tax-free week starts at 12:01 a.m. Saturday and ends midnight
August 21. The bargains are the state legislature's way of passing
along a windfall _ an $11 billion settlement from tobacco companies
_ to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Tax-exempt items include most clothing: baby clothes, lingerie,
sweaters, sports and professional uniforms, safety wear, shoes
without cleats, jeans, hosiery, vintage clothes. Not included are
helmets, jewelry, hair accessories, watches, handbags, sunglasses
and track shoes. Store coupons, but not manufacturer's coupons, can
be used to reduce a price to the exempt range.
</P>
<P>
   It might be wise to take a copy of a newspaper article about the
tax break with you when you shop. An unscientific, random sampling
of calls to popular area stores found many sales clerks who had no
idea a tax-free week was imminent.
</P>
<P>
   New York's similiar tax-free week, first held in January 1997,
was a bonanza for merchants; weekly retail sales doubled. But items
up to $500 were tax-free and the boon was heavily advertised by the
state. Florida's Department of Revenue had orientation meetings
this summer but John Merchant, who heads the local office, said not
many store managers attended.
</P>
<P>
   The Gardens mall in Palm Beach Gardens is heavily promoting the
week, even encouraging its merchants to add a 15-percent cut to
non-exempt items, said Stacey Boutet, who manages a Victoria's
Secret store in the mall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are expecting a bigger crowd than usual, particularly
college girls who want gowns...before they head back to school,''
she said. ``And guys doing early Christmas shopping.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynda Edwards writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
