<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3128 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUGAR-EVERGLADES-COX     08-13 0328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUGAR-EVERGLADES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Growers still improving on harmful water drainage
 &HT;    By Robert P. King
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the third year in a row, sugar growers have done far better
than state law demands in reducing the amount of phosphorus-tainted
water they drain into the Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   The water still contains phosphorus concentrations 10 times
higher than many scientists consider safe for the Everglades'
plants and wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   But growers prevented 85 tons of phosphorus from reaching the
Everglades in the past year by improving their handling of water
and fertilizer, water managers said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   They said 159 tons of phosphorus reached the Everglades from the
sugar farming region in the year that ended April 30. That was 35
percent less than what would have flowed without the growers'
reforms, scientists estimated.
</P>
<P>
   ``This doesn't mean the problem's solved,'' said Paul Whalen,
Everglades regulation manager for the South Florida Water
Management District. ``But it certainly means we're making
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It continues to look good,'' said Pete Rosendahl of the sugar
company Flo-Sun.
</P>
<P>
   Under a 1994 state law, the growers get a discount in a special
Everglades-restoration tax if they cut their phosphorus flows by at
least 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Since that requirement took effect in 1996, growers have reduced
their flows an average of 55 percent below what scientists would
have expected based on rainfall. Rainy years are expected to dump
more phosphorus.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers don't mean that phosphorus loads have dropped
dramatically from year to year. In fact, the sugar region drained
37 more tons of phosphorus this year than in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the district said growers had cut their phosphorus
tonnage by 49 percent below what would have flowed without their
efforts. In 1996, the estimated reduction was 68 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
