<P>
   &UR; NEVER MIND ...  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   An elderly widowed Italian gentleman, steeped in the old-world
tradition of secrecy as it related to money matters, was getting on
in age and was in the hospital for treatment of emphysema.
Believing his days were nearing an end, he called his eldest
daughter to his side and told her that after he was gone she should
look under his bed, where she would find a box containing stock
certificates and a substantial amount of cash. In a few days, he
was sent home, with his doctors assuring him of many more years of
active life. He called his daughter on the phone: ``Remember the
box I told you about under the bed? Its not there anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BILL'S WORLD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By Bill Tammeus, The Kansas City Star &LR;
</P>
<P>
   I'm the oldest man my age in America now,'' Mr. Clinton says.
Sounds like the kind of testimony the grand jury is likely to hear.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury hearing in the Lewinsky case is made up for 23
men and women. Mr. Clinton is home free. Who can get 23 men and
women to agree on anything?,
</P>
<P>
   Some 14 Secret Service employees have given grand jury testimony
in the Lewinsky case so far, reports say. Or about one for each
Clinton girlfriend?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, to be 50 again,'' says Mr. Clinton, who turns 52 soon.
Right. When he was 50 nobody knew yet about Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Safe water for our children,'' Mr. Clinton says, is something
all Americans agree on.'' Unlike whether sentences should end with
prepositions.
</P>
<P>
   The world is changing more rapidly and more profoundly,'' says
the president, than almost any of us can understand.'' Well, any
but Rush Limbaugh.
</P>
<P>
   This election year,'' says Mr. Clinton, should not be about
negative, 30-second ads.'' It won't be. Without campaign finance
reform it'll be about negative 60-second ads.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists in India are trying to rescue the Taj Mahal, the
white marble of which is yellowing because of pollution. Isn't this
a good place to test claims of whitening'' toothpastes?
</P>
<P>
   Britain's royal family says a new book on Princess Diana's death
is deeply hurtful'' and full of lies. That should guarantee a large
audience.
</P>
<P>
   The pope is getting wired for the Internet, answering the
question, Is the pope cathodic?''
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Carter has been in Plains, Ga., this summer helping to
build a recreation center. Not a bad description of the Clinton
White House.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton says prejudice against our state'' is
behind investigations of her husband. Maybe she's right. We've
always thought of Arkansas as below Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Clinton says he had no sexual relationship with Monica
Lewinsky
</P>
<P>
   though she apparently says she had one with him. Maybe they're
both right.
</P>
<P>
   Federal money is available now so there's new interest in
high-speed trains that operate by magnetic levitation. Sounds like
the way Mr. Clinton has avoided being taken down by scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are pondering five cities for their 2000 national
convention, Indianapolis, New Orleans, Philadelphia, New York and
San Antonio. If they had a sense of irony they'd pick Little Rock.
</P>
<P>
   Health care,'' says Mr. Clinton, is being revolutionized in
America.'' So is the language, as more and more nouns get turned
into verbs.
</P>
<P>
   Trading on the Russian stock market was halted temporarily the
other day because of a steep selloff. Which at least was better
than a steppe selloff.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican says it soon will begin live video broadcasts of
Pope John
</P>
<P>
   Paul II on the Internet. What software will be used? Mitersoft?,
</P>
<P>
   The British Petroleum-Amoco combination would be the largest
industrial merger in history. Yes, but that title is starting to
sound like the highest paid baseball player in history.''
</P>
<P>
   Things have been so topsy-turvy in Congo recently we half expect
to see the name changed to Procome.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
