<HEADER>
A3135 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-PGALEDE-COX     08-13 0380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGALEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woods on fire while 5 are two shots back
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Peering through the low-hanging branches at
Sahalee Country Club Thursday _ which isn't easy without a forestry
degree, by the way _ here's how things look in the 80th PGA
Championship:
</P>
<P>
   _ Tiger Woods, with his driver collecting cobwebs, is the leader
at 4-under-par 66 and in possession of the new Sahalee course
record, which took all of four hours to vanish.
</P>
<P>
   _ Two shots back at 68 are Bill Glasson, who has a bum elbow and
a surgery count that would impress Evel Knievel; Bob Estes, Glen
Day (who fell from 5-under), Frank Lickliter and 1993 champion Paul
Azinger.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mark O'Meara, with Masters and British Open titles on his
record, is lurking at 69, precisely where you would expect to see a
man trying to match a 45-year-old record.
</P>
<P>
   _ Defending champion Davis Love III of Sea Island, whose swing
frequently was of less than textbook quality, termed himself
fortunate to be at even-par 70.
</P>
<P>
   _Billy Andrade, having entered the tournament as the eighth
alternate, provided a new approach to major championship
preparation. After arriving Wednesday and barely able to get in a
hurried practice, Andrade birdied his first four holes to
temporarily share the lead with Woods, then awoke from the dream
with a double-bogey at the 6th hole.
</P>
<P>
   The 22-year-old Woods, teeing off with 3-woods or long irons and
displaying some newly-planted patience, shot a round that included
seven birdies, three bogeys and 27 putts.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just try to position myself every day,'' Woods said. ''I
just try to give myself a chance going into Sunday. And If I'm
there, hopefully I'll win. But I'm not going to put any more
pressure on myself because I'm near the lead right now. With three
days to go, it's an eternity.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara, 41, who is attempting to become the first player to win
three major championships since Ben Hogan in 1953, stablized his
round after two bogeys in his first three holes.
</P>
<P>
   ''I kept myself in the ballgame,'' O'Meara said. ''I tried to
remain patient and hit some better shots. I'm very pleased with my
postition.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
