<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3136 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CUBS-SOSA-HNS &LR;      08-13 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CUBS-SOSA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Cubs' Sosa enjoys career year
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By NEIL HOHLFELD &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
When Sammy Sosa takes batting practice, it's merely batting
practice and not some hyped-up event he dreads. When Sosa talks to
the media before a game, it's a give-and-take conversation
sprinkled with laughter, not an accusatory lecture.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from their chase of Roger Maris' home-run record, there
isn't much in common between Sosa, the Chicago Cubs right fielder,
and St. Louis first baseman Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   For that, baseball fans should rejoice. At least someone
involved in the home-run chase of 1998 is having some fun.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa is indeed having a joyful season, hitting home runs that
are keeping the Chicago Cubs alive in the National League Central
Division race and atop the wild-card standings. Whatever pressure
there might be, Sosa refuses to acknowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, McGwire grouses about pitchers who won't throw him
strikes, the throngs who watch him take batting practice and
continual media questions about his home runs or lack thereof.
Seattle's Ken Griffey Jr. refuses to even talk about his home-run
pace.
</P>
<P>
   And Sosa is having the time of his life during the season of his
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pressure is what you make it,'' said Sosa. ``I'm enjoying
this. You can talk yourself into pressure. I'm coming to the
clubhouse with a smile. This is what I want to be doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a professional, and this is my job. When you're doing
great, people want to know about it. I'm having a good time because
I'm having the best season of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa comes to the Astrodome to start a three-game showdown
series tonight with reason to smile. He is second to McGwire for
the major-league lead with 46 home runs, has a .311 batting average
and leads the NL with 116 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Without him, the Cubs likely would be where they usually are _
deep in the second division.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to hit a home run for us to win,'' said Sosa.
``If it's a double, single, walk, I'm going to take it. It's not
all about home runs. We're chasing Houston and trying to go to the
playoffs. I'm a player with more on his mind than home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I go to the plate, I'm thinking about ways that
will help us win games, not just hitting home runs. When you play
on a winning team, everything is different. You play better.''
</P>
<P>
   For Sosa and the Cubs, this weekend and next may represent a
fork in the road for the '98 season. They have been in a slump,
losing seven of their last 10 games and falling 8{ games behind the
Astros. The Cubs have a half-game lead over New York in the
wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not playing for the wild card; we're playing for the
division,'' said Sosa, 29. ``If we shoot for the division and just
fall short, we'll be the wild card anyway. Why not catch Houston?
That's our goal right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see the difference in the team this year. Everybody's
together. We're smiling, and we just go out and play. This is the
way I want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   This has been a special year for Sosa, whose previous career
high was 40 homers. He took off in June, when he hit a
major-league-record 20 home runs, with 40 RBIs, to jump into the
Maris chase. In his last 68 games, Sosa has 37 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Before this season, Sosa was regarded as a dangerous hitter but
one who often chased pitches out of the strike zone. The strikeouts
are not down much _ he has struck out 108 times this year and has
averaged 147 the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a huge difference. Before, he says, there were
times when he tried to ``hit two home runs every time I came up.''
This year, he better understands the role he must play.
</P>
<P>
   An example came last weekend in St. Louis, where the Cubs were
swept by the Cardinals. In a 9-8 loss in 13 innings, Sosa did
everything he could to win the game for Chicago. He used his power
to tie the game with a two-run homer in the ninth inning and his
newfound hitting savvy to produce an RBI single to the opposite
field in the 11th.
</P>
<P>
   It was the single to right that Sosa wanted to talk about after
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa's background in the Dominican Republic might be a reason he
is able to thrive in the kind of spotlight that seems to annoy
McGwire and Griffey. Sosa's father died when he was 7. He helped
his family survive by shining shoes and selling oranges.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, at age 16, Sosa signed with the Texas Rangers for
$3,500. At that point, playing in the major leagues was a faraway
dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never was a fan,'' said Sosa. ``I didn't know who this guy
was or that guy was. I was busy working, trying to make money for
my mother because she was struggling when my father died.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa had barely tasted the majors when he was traded to the
Chicago White Sox in 1989 in a deal that sent veteran Harold Baines
to the Rangers. He played without distinction for the White Sox for
parts of three seasons and was labeled as an undisciplined player
who swung wildly at anything close to the plate and made mistakes
in the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros tried to trade for Sosa in December 1991, offering
outfielder Eric Anthony, and actually came close to making the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a young player who just had great raw talent, and it
was matter of him putting it all together,'' said McGwire, who was
with Oakland until July 1997 and saw Sosa's developing years with
the White Sox. ``The last couple of years, he's really come into
his own. He's really good. And the thing he really loves is to play
the game of baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa hit 36, 40 and 36 home runs from 1995-97. He is in the
second year of a four-year, $42.5 million contract and has become
one of the most popular athletes in sports-crazy Chicago. He gives
back, too, donating a reported $500,000 annually to charities in
the U.S. and Dominican.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sammy's done a lot of great things the last few years,'' said
Cubs manager Jim Riggleman. ``He's hit 40 homers, had 100 RBIs.
This season, he's just put it all together, and all the work he's
done is paying off. He's matured into one of the elite stars in the
game with Griffey and (Barry) Bonds and a few others.''
</P>
<P>
   After Sosa hit two home runs in a game for the eighth time this
season in Monday's 8-5 win at San Francisco, Cubs first baseman
Mark Grace struggled to put into words Sosa's impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's beyond description,'' Grace said. ``I don't know the
right words to describe how great a season he's had. You say
MVP-type season, but I don't know if that's enough to describe
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The best might be yet to come. Sosa needs 16 home runs in the
Cubs' final 41 games to reach 62 and beat Maris' record. Sosa
repeatedly has said he thinks McGwire is the one to watch, but that
could be a subtle way to deflect pressure away from himself.
</P>
<P>
   If Sosa surpasses McGwire and becomes the leader during the
countdown to 62, he says he will not change his approach in dealing
with the demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever Mark wants to do, I think everybody has to respect
that,'' said Sosa. ``It's probably been a little aggravating to
him, all the reporters bothering him. Every day, every day, every
day. I know how he feels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I never have to go through the same situation as Mark.
I like to talk to people; don't get me wrong. To me, I'm friendly
with the media and I talk if I have the time. If I have to do
something, I'll let them know.''
</P>
<P>
   What Sosa is letting everyone know is that playing baseball for
a winning team and hitting home runs can be fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm enjoying it, believe me,'' said Sosa. ``There are people
out there with bigger problems than mine. Believe me, I know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
