<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUNK-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKUNK TRAIN SEEKING INVESTORS VIA ITS WEB SITE  
 BY KENNETH HOWE 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - SKUNK   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
Strapped for cash and in need of repairs, Fort Bragg's venerable
Skunk Train hopes to get back on track by selling stock to the
public over the Internet.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two years ago, local investors raised $1.6 million to save the
113-year old short-line railroad, which runs through 40 miles of
redwood forests between Fort Bragg on Highway 1 and Willits on
Highway 101.
</P>
<P>
   But today, Mendocino County's biggest tourist attraction is
nearly sidelined by debt and the need to rehabilitate its tracks,
locomotives and rolling stock.
</P>
<P>
   The 21 owners of the Skunk Train hope to raise $4.6 million by
selling stock directly to investors through its Web site
( &LR; www.skunktrain.com &LR; ), thus avoiding the expense &UR;  &LR; and regulatory
scrutiny of a traditional public offering.
</P>
<P>
   Starting this week, the train's parent company, California
Western Railroad Inc., intends to sell 614,000 shares, or 49.5
percent of the firm, for $7.50 a share, with a 100-share minimum.
</P>
<P>
   ``The original investors saved an historic artifact; now we need
more investors to ensure its survival,'' said railroad President
Gary Milliman, as he walked through the Skunk Train's roundhouse
where mechanics greased the 2,000-pound wheels of a diesel
locomotive.
</P>
<P>
   The Skunk Train is a key draw for Fort Bragg and Willits alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly wish the railroad well,'' said Fort Bragg City
Administrator Jim Murphy. ``The depot is located in the heart of
town and the train is important to the tourist economy here.''
</P>
<P>
   But for investors, the stock could be more memento than
moneymaker.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, companies that want to sell stock to the public
have hired investment banking firms to handle the sale.
</P>
<P>
   But investment bankers typically want 7 percent of the money
raised as a fee. Moreover, investment houses prefer larger deals _
$25 million minimum _ so they can sell the stock in big blocks to
institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, small companies that needed money to expand or
rebuild had to plead for bank loans or rustle up a few well-heeled
investors. But the Internet, with its ability to connect with large
numbers of people, has spurred the growth of so-called direct
public offerings, in which companies sell shares to investors
without a middleman.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 542 firms registered for direct public offerings,
according to Tom Stewart-Gordon, publisher of the SCOR Report, a
newsletter about financing alternatives. That's a 22 percent
increase from 1996 and a jump of more than 1,300 percent from 1990,
when a paltry 37 were filed.
</P>
<P>
   Although such companies are still regulated by the Securities
and Exchange Commission and the state, they have fewer reporting
requirements and undergo less scrutiny than companies that go
public the traditional way.
</P>
<P>
   Direct public offerings may also be a poor short-term investment
because their stocks often aren't listed on any stock exchange and
may be traded by only one or a handful of brokers. That can make it
difficult to get an accurate value and to sell shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the only direction (direct offering) stocks can go
is down,'' said Stewart-Gordon. ``All the people who are interested
in the company have already bought shares and may not be looking to
buy more.''
</P>
<P>
   Milliman acknowledged that if the Skunk Train can't raise the
money over the Internet, the company will have to ``restructure.''
</P>
<P>
   Since buying the train in August 1996, the owners have lost more
than $1.2 million, leaving them with only $84,200 in equity,
according to the company's latest financial statements.
</P>
<P>
   The current owners say the red ink has come from having to
borrow almost $1 million to buy the line. With total debt now at
$1.6 million, interest payments alone keep the line from making
much profit.
</P>
<P>
   Winter storms also hammered the line. In January 1997, a mud
slide buried the west entrance of a long tunnel along the route.
Digging it out and replacing the portal cost hundreds of thousands
of dollars, and the line was closed for six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   This past winter, the line was out of commission for 60 days due
to mudslides, fallen trees and washed out track.
</P>
<P>
   The line is particularly difficult to maintain, says Chief
Operating Officer Lynn Hakin, whose grandfather was a boilermaker
for the railroad. The train crosses 31 bridges, passes around 381
curves, chugs through two tunnels and travels from near sea level
to an elevation of 1,740 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The railroad plans to spend about $2.1 million from the offering
to replace two miles of track, install 30,000 new rail ties and
rehabilitate 13 bridges.
</P>
<P>
   Replacing track isn't entirely a safety issue. The Skunk Train
earns roughly 12 percent of its revenue from hauling lumber for the
nearby Georgia Pacific mill. To carry bigger loads, which means
more revenue, the Skunk Train must strengthen its track.
</P>
<P>
   Milliman said he plans to spend another $630,000 to buy
additional steam and diesel locomotives as well as refurbish
existing passenger cars.
</P>
<P>
   If they can make repairs, pay off debt and add more trains to
the Willits side of the line, the Skunk Train's owners think they
can make money. The railroad, which has a payroll of 24 in the
winter and more than twice that in the summer, attracts 65,000
riders a year, with adults paying $25 to $35 a ticket.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Right now, the rail line owns five diesel locomotives, two
steam locomotives, nine passenger cars and two gasoline-powered
motorcars. The latter have been around since 1925 and quickly
dubbed ``skunk trains'' because of their noxious odors.
</P>
<P>
   Milliman, who was Fort Bragg's city manager for 18 years, hopes
the Skunk Train's name and history will draw investors.
</P>
<P>
   He's also counting on the services of Drew Field, a San
Francisco securities lawyer and specialist in direct public
offerings.
</P>
<P>
   During the past 20 years, Field has helped a host of small
companies with direct public offerings: ZAP Power Systems, a
Sebastopol maker of electric bikes; Thanksgiving Coffee Co. based
in Fort Bragg; Blue Fish Clothing Inc., a Frenchtown N.J., maker of
handmade clothes; Ukiah's Real Goods Trading Co., which sells
renewable energy and other ``green'' products; and Mendocino
Brewing, a beer company in Mendocino County.
</P>
<P>
   Field argues that direct public offerings can be an excellent
financial alternative for companies that can't access traditional
markets. But he also acknowledged that a direct offering isn't
always a great short-term investment.
</P>
<P>
   Companies often choose the direct route because they are losing
money or can't finance operations through earnings or bank loans.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, ZAP, Real Goods, Blue Fish and Mendocino Brewing have
all shown losses in recent quarters and their stocks are trading
well below their offering prices.
</P>
<P>
   But Stewart-Gordon of the SCOR Report noted that a typical
shareholder of a direct public offering isn't strictly interested
in stock escalation.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many people it's investing in something they believe in
and want to support, like a local winery or the Skunk Train,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, many investors look at direct public offerings like
venture capital _ a high risk investment that needs a long time to
pay off.
</P>
<P>
   Milliman admits it could take five years to turn around the
Skunk Train.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you whether you're going to make any money or
not,'' he said. ``What you've got is a chance to own a piece of
railroad history.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
