<SLUG> BC-CONDOM-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONDOM MAKER SPONSORS RAIDERS BROADCAST  
 BY CAROL EMERT 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - CONDOM   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Oakland Raiders fans will be getting some latex with their pigskin
this season.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In what is believed to be a first in broadcasting, a condom
brand is an official sponsor of this season's Raiders coverage by
KTCT ``The Ticket'' radio.
</P>
<P>
   The sponsorship, by LifeStyles condoms, may indicate a turning
point in the mainstreaming of condoms _ a product that is used by
tens of millions of Americans each year and is crucial in
preventing the spread of sexually transmitted diseases. But if KTCT
has misread the public's readiness for sex-oriented advertising,
the promotion could backfire by offending listeners.
</P>
<P>
   While condom ads have appeared sporadically on KTCT and other
radio stations in the past, this appears to be the first time a
broadcast has aligned itself so closely with condoms _ or any other
sex-related product.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  Radio spots that ran during an exhibition game last weekend
said, ``Lifestyles is the official condom of Oakland Raiders
broadcasts on The Ticket, 1050-AM. Lifestyles: Because life is a
contact sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Those 10-second ads will run before and after 20 Raiders games
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from its relatively taboo subject matter, the LifeStyles
promotion is similar to the type of marketing that is done for any
other consumer product.
</P>
<P>
   Samples will play an important role. Free condoms will be passed
out from a KTCT van at four tailgate parties at the Oakland
Coliseum and the annual Raiders FanFest in Jack London Square in
September. The LifeStyles logo will appear on posters for the
FanFest. Condom-related goodies, such as key chains with
prophylactics embedded in the fob, will be handed out on a
first-come, first-serve basis at all of the events.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  And the marketing director for Ansell &LR;   &LR; Personal Products,
which makes Lifestyles condoms, will plug the company during on-air
interviews with KTCT talk show hosts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; But don't expect any condom-shaped blimps, or other blatantly
tacky promotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (Ansell) had said, `We want to fly planes with big condoms
behind, or do stunts with people putting condoms on cucumbers,'
that's not what we're about,'' said Rich Zirkel, local sales
manager for KTCT. ``We're not racy, we're not doing anything to
offend anybody. It's really an awareness campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I really think this will be successful because it's
being done tastefully.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of Zirkel's confidence stems from the fact that KTCT has
already tested the waters with a couple of recent LifeStyles
giveaways that were not linked to the Raiders. Condoms distributed
from the KTCT van at various events were the most popular freebies
in the station's history, and KTCT has not received a single
complaint about the giveaway or about condom radio ads, Zirkel
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody needs them and we're all embarrassed (buying) them
in the drug store,'' Zirkel said. ``I think it's refreshing to
people'' that condoms are being marketed in a straightforward
fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Geoff Clarkson, a marketing consultant with Greenfield Online,
said Ansell's direct approach is the right way to go. ``One thing I
learned when I used to do advertising for Tampax was that it is
better to be brutally honest. If you try to get cute or indirect,
customers read right through it and they say, ``Why are you
treating me this way?'''
</P>
<P>
   While the LifeStyles promotion may offend some listeners,
Clarkson predicted that it will be well received by its target
audience. If any group is likely to embrace a condom promotion, it
is Raiders followers, said marketing experts.
</P>
<P>
   Raiders fans tend to be 18- to 34-year-old men with some college
education, a core group for condom sales, said Carol Carrozza,
marketing director for Ansell.
</P>
<P>
   The fan base also includes a large number of African Americans
and Hispanics, two demographic groups in which condom sales are
growing fastest, said Carrozza.
</P>
<P>
   Staging the promotion in the Bay Area, known for its social
progressiveness, also minimizes the risk. ``If this were happening
in Cleveland, there probably would be protesters when I come in in
the morning,'' said Zirkel.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Becker, president of Becker Media in San Francisco, said
he doesn't expect the Raiders to suffer from the promotion. In
fact, breaching the condom taboo may even enhance the National
Football League team's ``skull-and-crossbones, bad boy image,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Condoms and the Raiders ``really go hand-in-glove, so to
speak,'' said Becker, whose company brokers radio air time.
</P>
<P>
   A Raiders spokesman declined to discuss the matter, apart from
pointing out that the LifeStyle's promotion is KTCT's project and
does not directly involve the team.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, KTCT doesn't have a lot to lose. The station ranks
an anemic 20th in the Bay Area among its target audience of men 18
to 34, according to Arbitron. KNBR, a sister sports station, is
ranked sixth. Most of the higher-ranked stations are FM music
stations.
</P>
<P>
   Becker estimated that Ansell is paying KTCT about $50,000 for
the promotion, an amount that offers a lot of bang for the buck, he
said. Consumer product makers ``are increasingly looking for
opportunities to get one-on-one contact with the public, and these
kinds of events give them an unparalleled opportunity to do that,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ansell, meanwhile, is pushing the envelope in other realms of
advertising. On August 22, the Eatontown, N.J.-based company will
run the first condom ads ever shown on national network television.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been on network affiliates and cable, but this is a
breakthrough,'' said Carrozza. The 30-second spots, which feature
``romping'' couples, according to Ansell, will run on Howard
Stern's Saturday night talk show on CBS. Carrozza has also appeared
on Stern's radio program.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, Ansell will distribute 435,000 posters on college
campuses with product information and illustrations. It also has a
Web site ( &LR; www.lifestyles.com &LR; ) with links to condom-selling sites.
</P>
<P>
   LifeStyles' share of the retail condom market has grown to 17
percent from 4 percent in 1985, but it still lags far behind the
Trojan brand, which has 58 percent of retail sales. LifeStyles
condoms comprise about 70 percent of the condoms that are
distributed through public health service organizations, Carrozza
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
