<HEADLINE>
BIG APPLE AD BLITZ FOR IMAC  
 BY JON SWARTZ  
 C.1998 SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE  

</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - APPLE  Apple Computer yesterday said it will launch its biggest
advertising campaign ever _ $100 million _ for its new iMac
computer.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The media blitz, which kicked off Tuesday on radio stations
across the country, will extend to TV spots on Sunday as well as
magazines and outdoor billboards this week, and will run through
the end of 1998. The $1,299 computer, sporting a gently curved
aquamarine plastic case, is scheduled to ship Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to reach people who are buying their first
computer,'' said Phil Schiller, Apple vice president of product
marketing. ``It is easily our most far-reaching, coordinated use of
the media.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Schiller declined to disclose the content of the TV
ads, he said they will stress the Internet terminal's ease of use,
simplicity and speed. The ads ``will be fun and factual,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company's billboards in 10 major U.S. cities _ including San
Francisco, New York and Seattle _ may offer a clue, however. The
placards feature a large photo of an iMac and one of the following
headlines: ``I think, therefore iMac.''; ``Chic. Not geek.'';
``Sorry, no beige.''; and ``Mental floss.''
</P>
<P>
   The TV spots were produced by TBWA Chiat Day, creator of the
widely acclaimed television commercial ``1984'' that launched the
original Macintosh and aired only once _ during the 1984 Super
Bowl. The commercials will premiere on the ``Wonderful World of
Disney'' and will run on episodes of ``Seinfeld,'' ``News Radio,''
``South Park'' and other shows next week.
</P>
<P>
   More than 15 million 12-page magazine inserts will be
distributed in Time, Newsweek, Sports Illustrated, Rolling Stone
and People this quarter. The sheer volume of inserts is more than
twice what Apple has distributed in its entire 21-year history.
</P>
<P>
   The Cupertino company will launch iMac campaigns in Europe and
Japan next month, according to Allen Olivo, Apple senior director
of worldwide marketing communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``This clearly is the biggest, most concentrated ad campaign for
any consumer PC in history,'' said Bradley Johnson, an editor at
Advertising Age in Los Angeles. ``To put this in perspective,
Compaq Computer recently doubled annual spending on its Presario
consumer computer, and that was $50 million.''
</P>
<P>
   The iMac blitz eclipses Apple's successful ``Think Different ''
marketing campaign. Those print and billboard ads, which debuted in
November, will continue to appear on the back covers of national
magazines, according to Apple.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising experts said the scope of Apple's campaign is akin
to America Online's carpet bombing of floppy disks in consumers'
mailboxes. And, like AOL, such aggressive tactics come with risks.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said PC makers usually shy away from extravagant
consumer-PC ads because of slim margins and cutthroat competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apple needs to sell a bunch of PCs to make this work,''
Johnson said. ``This is a huge bet.''
</P>
<P>
   The computer maker already has shattered its record for
first-week orders, with 150,000. An estimated 400,000 units are
expected to ship by the end of September.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
