<HEADLINE>
7 DIE IN CALIFORNIA DESERT, PROBABLY LEFT BY SMUGGLER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By DON TERRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In an oven-hot patch of California desert just
north of the Mexico border, the bodies of seven people were found
Thursday, apparently the victims of the heat and their dreams for a
better life.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities said it appeared that the group had illegally
crossed into the United States from Mexico and had been abandoned
by smugglers in one of the worse cases of death along the border in
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically, what we find is one or two people dead from the
heat at one time,'' said Bill Strassberger, a spokesman for the
Immigration and Naturalization Service. ``But I can't recall a
group this large dying from the heat.''
</P>
<P>
   Strassberger said the group, which included five men, a woman
and a teen-age boy, had been dead for at least three days when
their bodies were discovered about 90 miles east of San Diego and
about 35 miles north of the Mexico border in a stretch of
California desert where temperatures on a cool day hover above 100
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough area for the agents to work in,'' he said, ``so
you can imagine what it's like for someone trying to sneak in.''
</P>
<P>
   Strassberger said the group might have been part of an even
larger group making the increasingly dangerous journey across the
border and through the desert and the night, walking miles and
miles out of their way to avoid border checkpoints and being pushed
and prodded to keep moving, faster, faster by smugglers known as
``coyotes.''
</P>
<P>
   There were no signs of foul play when the seven were found
Thursday about seven miles west of Highway 86, but the authorities
are searching for their smugglers, who could be sent to prison for
life if captured and convicted of bringing the undocumented
immigrants across the border and then leaving them to die.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the lowest level of exploitation of another human
being,'' Strassberger said.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies were found Thursday after a farm worker stopped at a
border checkpoint at the intersection of Highways 78 and 86 at 8
a.m. and reported seeing several people possibly in distress a few
miles away. The worker did not know whether they were alive or dead
and drew a map for the border patrol agents, who then called for a
search plane.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the bodies were under a salt cedar tree about 250 yards
from Pole Line Road, a bumpy dirt track, and the seventh was about
20 feet away. There were no water bottles there, leading
immigration officials to speculate that a smuggler had dropped off
the victims nearby to wait for a connecting ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very unusual case,'' said Luis Herrera-Lass, counsel
general for the Mexican consulate in San Diego. ``We haven't in
recent times had seven people die at one time.''
</P>
<P>
   Herrera-Lass said that usually the only other scenario where
there had been multiple deaths of immigrants was car accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Still, 10 or 12 years ago 15 bodies were found in Texas in a
boxcar that had been locked by a smuggler, said Robert Gilbert,
deputy assistant director for the Western region for the Border
Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   Before Thursday, California authorities said seven people had
died from the heat since last January and 29, including a man found
Thursday, had drowned. Along the nation's border with Mexico, 80
illegal immigrants have died from heat this year, 23 in California
and Arizona and 57 in Texas and New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   They have died despite an extensive media campaign on both sides
of the border warning of the dangers from crooked ``coyotes,''
rivers and the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, another man was found dead in the desert, about seven
miles west of where the seven were discovered Thursday.
Strassberger said the authorities did not believe he was connected
to the larger party beyond their common fate.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, ``coyotes'' were charging a couple of hundred
dollars. These days, Strassberger said, the price can be exceed
$1,200 a person.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can get the word out about how dangerous it is,'' he said,
``but everyone seems to believe ending up dead or hurt is something
that is going to happen to the other guy. They all say the same
thing, `I'll get through.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
