<HEADER>
A3149 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-MERGERS-ART-$     08-13 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-MERGERS-ART-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POOF! FOR MORE AND MORE MUTUAL FUNDS, A QUICK DISAPPEARING ACT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 16) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., R.I.)  (ART ADV: Graphic of fund mergers is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's a merger boom that investors may not like: Responding to
a confluence of industry currents, mutual fund companies are
combining funds at a record pace this year. Such mergers, however,
can burn the shareholders they are purported to help.
</P>
<P>
   According to Morningstar Inc., the financial publisher in
Chicago, 232 funds had been merged out of existence this year,
through Aug. 11, compared with 150 in the corresponding period last
year and 154 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   If the furious pace continues, the total for 1998 will easily
surpass that of the record year of 1995, when 322 funds were merged
into other funds in the wake of the 1994 turmoil in the stock and
bond markets.
</P>
<P>
   Among stock funds alone, 102 have disappeared by way of mergers
this year, versus 64 in the like period last year and 77 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the trend may be oversupply. ``Fund companies
spun funds out like crazy over the past couple of years thinking
that investors would have an insatiable appetite,'' said Susan
Dziubinski, editor of the Morningstar Investor newsletter. ``But
they haven't attracted the assets they had hoped for.''
</P>
<P>
   Other factors may be driving the phenomenon, too. The financial
services industry has been consolidating, prompting firms to
combine fund families and reduce the number of offerings with
similar objectives.
</P>
<P>
   Geoff Bobroff, an industry consultant in East Greenwich, R.I.,
attributes the trend to the popularity of fee-based financial
planning. Advisers can use fund supermarkets and brokerage-firm
wrap accounts to assemble fund portfolios from many companies
without incurring transaction fees. As a result, a company may not
need to offer as broad a range of funds, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, as consumers become more sophisticated, there is a
growing impetus to get rid of lackluster funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of mistakes out there that are being merged out
of existence,'' Ms. Dziubinski said.
</P>
<P>
   She said the recent spate of fund combinations by BancAmerica
Robertson Stephens were examples of ``mercy mergers.'' In early
July, shareholders agreed to merge Robertson Stephens Global
Low-Priced Stock into the group's Partners fund.
</P>
<P>
   Global Low-Priced Stock returned an annualized average of just
1.7 percent from its inception in late 1995 through July 11, when
Morningstar stopped tracking it, compared with 17.3 percent for the
average world stock fund. Partners, by contrast, has returned an
annualized average of 14.6 percent from its inception in 1995
through Aug. 7, just less than the 15.9 percent of its peer group
of small capitalization value funds.
</P>
<P>
   Also in early July, Robertson Stephens filed a plan with the
Securities and Exchange Commission to merge its Developing
Countries fund into Partners. Developing Countries, an
emerging-markets fund, lost 10.5 percent a year, on average, from
its inception in April 1994 through Aug. 7, far more than the 7.1
percent annual average loss by its peers.
</P>
<P>
   In another high-profile merger, Strong Funds plans to fold its
lagging Small Cap fund into its Growth fund. Small Cap returned 5.6
percent, annualized, from the end of 1995 through Aug. 7, compared
with 9.4 percent for its average peer in the small-cap growth
category.
</P>
<P>
   So shareholders should pay close attention. ``Mergers usually
benefit fund families more than fund shareholders,'' Ms. Dziubinski
said.
</P>
<P>
   While mergers can sweep poor track records under the rug, they
can pose a danger: Companies don't necessarily merge funds with
similar objectives, so shareholders may end up with a different
investment than they started with.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson Stephens investors who bought Global Low-Priced Stock
and Developing Countries, perhaps with foreign diversification in
mind, ended up with a primarily domestic small-cap portfolio in
Partners. If the Strong funds merge, Small Cap investors will be
trading small stocks for larger ones in Strong Growth.
</P>
<P>
   An SEC ruling provides only ``loose guidance'' for mergers, said
Douglas J. Scheidt, associate director and chief counsel of the
agency's division of investment management.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC requires that fund companies compare investment
objectives, policies, asset totals and other attributes of two
merging funds to see which one will most closely resemble the
merged offering. The fund company then gets to use that fund's
record in its marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, fund companies engineer a merger so the better
track record survives. ``No one wants to continue a bad
performance, so they'll choose a fund that they know will be a
survivor under this test,'' Scheidt said.
</P>
<P>
   Some shareholders may balk, however, after seeing the
consequences of a merger. A big tax bill can await investors who
sit tight _ even those in the acquiring fund. David J. Mangefrida,
national director of investment management tax services for Ernst &AMP;
Young in Washington, said there could be capital gains when the
manager of the surviving fund liquidates the absorbed fund's
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders can vote against a merger, of course, but such
efforts seldom succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Fund mergers are not all bad, Ms. Dziubinski said. They can
create economies of scale, cutting costs for investors. And
perhaps, she added, it is better for companies to wipe out losing
funds than to continue to pocket the fees they generate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
