<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS TO RETURN TO WICHITA FALLS FOR 1999 TRAINING CAMP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ The Cowboys yesterday announced an
agreement with Wichita Falls to return for training camp in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement is for one year. The option to extend the deal
lies with Cowboys owner Jerry Jones and Midwestern State University
President Louis J. Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   This was the Cowboys' first training camp in Wichita Falls after
spending the previous eight summers in Austin. Before yesterday's
practices, some fans held up posters and banners that thanked the
Cowboys for coming here, and appealed to Jones to keep his club in
Wichita Falls for the upcoming summers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Training camp has gone incredibly well,'' Rodriguez said. ``If
you'd have asked me before camp started, I wouldn't think it would
have gone this smooth. But this has been a great experience. The
Cowboys are a great organization. They are always welcome back
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Through Wednesday, more than 80,000 spectators had turned out
for Cowboys workouts in Wichita Falls. More than two-thirds were
from out of town, and some from as far away as Turkey and Alaska,
university spokeswoman Janus Buss said.
</P>
</TEXT>
