s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-SCHWAB-ART-$A     08-13 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-SCHWAB-ART-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHWAB'S NEW PITCH: SEE, IT'S TIME TO SWITCH  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BRENDA BUTTNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Drawing a bead on full-service brokerage firms, Charles Schwab &AMP;
Co., the discount broker, has begun offering its customers analyses
of the performance of their mutual funds _ including load funds
they hold in full-service firms' brokerage accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The move is an effort to persuade customers to switch from funds
sold by the full-service firms to those offered by Schwab's no-load
network.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of them will dip their toes at Schwab and then decide to
transfer their assets to us,'' said Susanne Lyons, a Schwab
president in charge of customer segment marketing, referring to
dual-account holders, who make up nearly half of the company's
client base. ``And for us to grow, we really need to be appealing
to those types of customers who have traditionally gone to the
full-service brokers.''
</P>
<P>
   The service was started in late July and has been offered to a
few hundred thousand of Schwab's 5.2 million customers. All
customers are to receive mailings in late September.
</P>
<P>
   After filling out a form itemizing their mutual fund holdings,
investors receive a detailed performance analysis of each fund in
their portfolio, comparing 1-, 5- and 10-year returns to benchmarks
like the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index and the Russell 2000
index of small companies.
</P>
<P>
   For each fund, the profile includes a list of better-performing
alternatives that are available through Schwab.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a holder of Merrill Lynch Growth would see the
fund's return compared with the higher average annual return of the
Oakmark fund for the last one and five years.
</P>
<P>
   A $10,000 investment in the Merrill Lynch fund's class A shares,
which have a maximum front-end load, or sales charge, of 5.25
percent, would have grown to $20,931 over the last five years,
through June 30, compared with $26,939 for Oakmark, which does not
have a load.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to prompt investors to weigh alternatives to
lackluster funds. ``If you decide that one's a dog and you don't
want it anymore, we give you similar types of funds that have
performed much better,'' Ms. Lyons said.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab is betting that simply by pointing out the relative
underperformance of many full-service brokerage funds, it can
persuade clients to send significant portions of their outside
holdings in Schwab's direction. Indeed, to help shareholders do so,
Schwab already publishes a ranking of recommended funds called the
Mutual Fund Select List.
</P>
<P>
   The profiles are based on data from Morningstar Inc., the
financial publisher in Chicago. Morningstar research shows that
over all, funds managed by the major Wall Street brokerage firms
have not performed well relative to their peers over the last three
years, even before adjusting for the loads they charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The picture is of pretty consistent mediocrity,'' said John
Rekenthaler, research director at Morningstar. ``It's clear the
funds in Schwab's Select List will have higher average rankings and
category ratings than this pool.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwab hopes its profiles will persuade customers to follow the
example of David Monigal of East St. Louis, Ill. After he saw that
many of his Smith Barney funds were underperforming Schwab
alternatives, he switched nearly $300,000 to Schwab from the Smith
Barney broker he and his wife had relied on for nearly 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The profile really brought it home to us,'' said Monigal, a
vice president of Transunion, a credit bureau. Monigal said he
would now deal with Schwab exclusively. ``The value of the
full-service broker is really challenged with all of the tools that
Schwab provides in terms of analysis,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, officials at full-service brokerage firms
disagree with Schwab's take. Joe Lohrer, director of sales for
Smith Barney Mutual Funds, said his firm furnishes customers with
valuable asset-allocation services that Schwab's analysis ignores.
``With us, clients don't simply buy an individual fund; they build
an entire fund portfolio,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Thomson, a spokeswoman for Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., said the
Schwab program did clients a disservice by not viewing fund returns
in a broader context. ``It's a mistake to review performance of one
asset class in the absence of any consideration of a client's total
portfolio, risk tolerance and time horizon,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Merrill Lynch, the nation's largest brokerage firm, and
several other firms are looking at providing small investors with
research and perhaps even ratings for funds sold by their brokers.
</P>
<P>
   The battle for mutual fund money is intensifying as it becomes a
bigger percentage of assets under management at both discount and
full-service brokers. Schwab holds nearly $200 billion in mutual
fund assets, a 20-fold increase since the start of the decade. And
funds are a rapidly growing revenue source for the traditional
securities firms, too.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab representatives say response to the new service has been
strong, with 40,000 requests for performance profiles so far. The
company plans an ad campaign to reach full-service brokerage
customers who do not have Schwab accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the attempt to siphon mutual fund assets from
full-service brokerage firms would be important to Schwab's future.
``Right now, a lot of people with dual accounts use the
full-service brokers for the main part of their assets and just use
Schwab to play,'' said Steve Eisman, a financial services analyst
with CIBC Oppenheimer. ``If Schwab can convert a significant
percentage of them, this will be a big enhancement to growth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
