<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-GM-YUKON-2TAKES-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW, A PREVIEW OF CADILLAC'S COMING ATTRACTION  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JAMES G. COBB   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Detroit's long-running struggle for one-upmanship, the Big
Three take their victories wherever they can get them. When General
Motors bought the Renaissance Center complex downtown, the new
landlord got a certain pleasure in sending a group of tenants
packing _ those whose office doors were emblazoned with the oval
blue emblem of Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen miles west, at Ford's ``Glass House'' in Dearborn,
executives have had a year to gloat over their own coup: The
Lincoln Navigator had tapped into an unexpectedly large vein of
demand for oversized, overstuffed, overwrought sport utility
vehicles. Each Navigator returns some $15,000 in profit, and Ford
had the market pretty much to itself.
</P>
<P>
   GM, playing catch-up, found itself in a bind. Its existing
full-size sport-utilities _ the Chevrolet Tahoe and GMC Yukon, and
the monstrous Suburbans from both Chevy and GMC _ were near the end
of the line, since they are built on a truck platform that is being
replaced this year.
</P>
<P>
   And the company's brand managers _ a tribe of marketers who used
to purvey products like disposable diapers and laundry detergents _
decreed that GMC must establish itself as a luxury line distinct
from Chevrolet.
</P>
<P>
   So GM cobbled together a stopgap solution: It took the Yukon,
dressed it up in monochromatic paint and plastic lower-body
cladding, installed Bilstein shock absorbers to smooth the ride,
bolted on special Firestone Firehawk tires and six-spoke chromed
aluminum wheels. Inside, the truck cabin was upgraded with leather
captain's chairs, Zebrano wood like that in the Cadillac Seville
and a powerful Bose sound system.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting package is the Yukon Denali, borrowing the Native
American name for Mount McKinley, the highest point in North
America.
</P>
<P>
   This concept has a few problems. First, ``Yukon Denali'' is an
oxymoron on an international scale, since Denali is the pride of
Alaska, and Canada still claims the Yukon as its own. Would they
name a mini-van the Baja California Grand Canyon or call a sports
coupe the Tuscany Matterhorn?
</P>
<P>
   And with the Denali's development well under way, GM did a
U-turn, undercutting the rationale for a project intended to
establish GMC as the company's upscale truck division. After
insisting that there was no place at Cadillac for a truck,
particularly a truck shared with lesser divisions, Cadillac
succumbed to its dealers' pleas and announced that it would sell
yet another fancy variation of the Tahoe/Yukon, to be called the
Escalade.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving this fall, it will differ from a Denali chiefly with
softer leather, extra insulation, a bit more wood, a year-longer
warranty and the Onstar security-navigation system as standard
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 GMC Yukon Denali has been on sale since winter, but
supplies were tight even before the eight-week GM strike. Now that
the trucks are being produced again, here is a checklist to
determine if the Denali is right for you: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ You don't mind spending $44,000 for what is, at its core, a
$32,000 Tahoe.
</P>
<P>
   _ You're willing to lug around a 16.5-foot-long vehicle that
seats only five people.
</P>
<P>
   _ You can't wait a year or so for the GM sport utilities that
will be built on the company's all-new, much-improved,
full-size-truck platform, with new engines and a host of innovative
features.
</P>
<P>
   _ You don't feel the need to spend $3,000 more for a Cadillac
crest on the grille.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
