<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0456 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3159 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABOUT-CARS-GM-YUKON-2     08-13 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-GM-YUKON-2NDTAKE-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: the grille.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But if you like the Denali's considerable size, don't mind the
price and don't care about GM's tendency to disregard its own
edicts (not long ago, the company insisted it would stop slapping
different names on the same basic vehicles), the Yukon Denali is a
pretty good example of what a big luxury sport utility ought to be.
</P>
<P>
   Even with its dated body, frame and engine, the truck feels
solid, stable and responsive _ responsiveness being a relative
term, given its heft.
</P>
<P>
   The 5.7-liter V8 has enough grunt to move the 5,867-pound truck
around pretty well, though that engine feels more eager in a
4,865-pound Tahoe. The suspension strikes a nice balance between
responsive handling and a supple, well-balanced ride.
</P>
<P>
   In a dig at the oversprung Navigator, GMC brags that the Denali
``gives the driver the feeling of mastery of the road, not a
squishy ride that rolls in the corners.'' The speed-variable
steering returns excellent feedback to the driver.
</P>
<P>
   A new push-button four-wheel-drive system has four settings:
rear-wheel-drive for ordinary use, 4WD high, 4WD low and an ``Auto
4WD'' mode that engages the front axle but sends power there only
if it senses that the rear wheels are slipping.
</P>
<P>
   The interior has many nice touches, including separate climate
settings, stereo controls and seat heaters for rear occupants; an
inside mirror with built-in compass and exterior temperature
readout; a nifty two-piece console box with a deep lower bin
alongside the CD changer and a shallow upper compartment with a
clipboard that flips forward.
</P>
<P>
   There are two power outlets up front, plus a lighter, in
addition to outlets in the back seat and cargo area. There are
eight cup holders. You can't have a third row of seats, however, in
contrast to the Navigator, Ford Expedition and Dodge Durango.
</P>
<P>
   There are dual air bags and headrests front and rear. The front
captain's chairs are superb: cushy yet supportive, and easy to
adjust. But after picking up the Denali and fiddling with the seat
controls, I headed off on one of the steamiest days of summer with
the uncomfortable feeling that although the air-conditioner was
blasting, my backside was being fried.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the seat heater was on, but where was the switch? I
scanned the dashboard, looked over the console and finally pulled
off the road. Ultimately, I found the control hidden at the front
of the bottom seat cushion, where it can easily be tripped by
anyone trying to adjust the seat. (Two passengers gave themselves
hot seats, too.)
</P>
<P>
   Roomy, comfortable and easy-riding, the Denali seemed the
perfect vehicle to take out-of-state guests on a sightseeing tour
of the Hudson Valley. It has panoramic windows and a commanding
view of the road. Yet my backseat tourists found that the rear side
windows, which are nearly 21 inches deep, retract a scant 6 inches.
So close-ups of waterfalls and wildlife had to be seen through
dark-tinted glass.
</P>
<P>
   There were a few other irritations, perhaps born of the
vehicle's rapid development. You cannot buckle or unbuckle the
front belts with the armrests down. You can't have a sunroof, a
strange omission in a luxury vehicle. The express-down control on
the driver's window was cantankerous.
</P>
<P>
   But in all the important measures of a truck _ ride, handling,
comfort, brute force and towing capacity _ the Denali genuinely
impressed, turning this skeptic into an admirer. The GMC is more
rewarding to drive than the Navigator, and it looks more serious
than frivolous. It is elegant in a low-key way, without the
Lincoln's nouveau-riche pretensions.
</P>
<P>
   At $43,500, the Denali is pricey _ $8,000 more than the top-line
Yukon SLT _ but consider that Jeeps now brush $40,000 and the
Cadillac version is expected to be nearly $47,000. It's expensive
to keep up with the Joneses, especially if they're going off-road. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: The strong, silent type.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
