<HEADLINE>
MONEY ENDS COLLEGE LIST, BUT KIPLINGER'S PICKS UP THE SLACK  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FRED BROCK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The intense competition among personal-finance magazines has
been thrown into sharp focus with the September issues of Money and
Kiplinger's.
</P>
<P>
   Money magazine's annual college review, a seven-year-old feature
that has usually appeared in its September issue, is history _ at
least for this year. So Kiplinger's has jumped into the fray with a
college survey of its own, perfectly timed to fill the void.
</P>
<P>
   At Money, the leading personal-finance magazine with a
circulation of 1.9 million, the demise of the college feature is
part of continuing changes that will culminate in a new design
starting in the October issue. For several months now, Money
editors have added, dropped and changed editorial elements. For
example, the magazine sharply cut its annual survey this summer of
the best places to live in America.
</P>
<P>
   Money's editors have said in interviews and in notes to readers
that they want to make the magazine more relevant and easier to
read and use, all in an effort to retain its commanding lead in an
increasingly crowded field. But such a makeover runs the risk of
thinning the content. Time will tell if they are on the right
track.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the previous surveys in Money, which included public and
private schools, Kiplinger's review is limited to state colleges
and universities. Kiplinger's ranks the top 100 of these schools
based on value, educational quality and student satisfaction, among
other criteria. It tallies costs for tuition _ both for in-state
and out-of-state students _ and room and board.
</P>
<P>
   It also lists the average size of financial aid packages and the
average debt of graduates, plus academic statistics like SAT scores
of incoming freshmen, admission rates and graduation rates.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine concludes that students can get a high-quality
education at many public schools for a fraction of the cost at many
private colleges.
</P>
<P>
   Kiplinger's top 10 choices, in order, are the University of
North Carolina at Chapel Hill, the University of Virginia, the
College of William and Mary, the University of Illinois at
Urbana-Champaign, the University of Florida, the University of
Wisconsin at Madison, the University of California at Berkeley, the
University of California at Los Angeles, the Georgia Institute of
Technology and the State University of New York at Binghamton.
</P>
<P>
   Annual costs for in-state students at these schools range from
$7,184 at North Carolina to $12,142 at Berkeley. For out-of-state
students, they run from $14,184 at Georgia Tech to $20,811 at
William and Mary.
</P>
<P>
   Kiplinger's takes special note of No. 14 on its list, the
College of New Jersey in Ewing, which the magazine considers a
``gem'' in terms of cost and quality. The liberal arts college has
5,400 students; its classes are small and none are taught by
graduate assistants. Costs for nonresidents are $13,688, only
$2,830 more than what in-state residents pay. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GETTING THERE As the 1998 model year comes to an end, the
September issues of Kiplinger's, Money and Smart Money all examine
new-car bargains.
</P>
<P>
   The best deals, the magazines say, can be had on 1998 models
that are being discontinued or redesigned for 1999. For example,
Kiplinger's cites Nissan's discontinued 240SX and 200SX, with
sticker prices of slightly less than $19,000 and $15,000,
respectively. They are being sold with rebates or dealer incentives
of up to $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   The magazines say big discounts are also found on vehicles
facing redesigns _ including the Ford Windstar and Honda Odyssey
mini-vans, as well as Chrysler's Jeep Grand Cherokee sport utility
vehicles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BATTER UP Smart Money gives grades, or ``batting averages,'' to
11 leading market pundits for their predictions for the first half
of 1998. Based on a complicated formula of projections and results,
the winner was Abby Joseph Cohen of Goldman, Sachs, with an average
of .720. Rounding out the top three were Edward Yardeni of Deutsche
Bank Securities (.634) and Edward Kerschner of Paine Webber (.632).
</P>
<P>
   Of course, these scores are based on the market's performance
through June 30. Given the sharp falloff in equities since then, a
more telling score may be the one for predictions for the second
half. Stand by.
</P>
<P>
   OUT OF THE CLASSROOM The September issue of Mutual Funds
magazine examines the move by the Teachers Insurance and Annuity
Association _ College Retirement Equities Fund, or TIAA-CREF, into
public mutual funds. The group's first six offerings each require a
minimum investment of $250 and are aimed at limited-budget
investors who want to diversify.
</P>
<P>
   One advantage of the new funds, according to the magazine, is
that their portfolio managers have all been involved in operating
TIAA-CREF's top-rated private pension fund assets. Another is low
expenses: The annual expense ratio of each of the six new funds is
less than 0.5 percent, below the industry average.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
