<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 8/13/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) SOUTH BEND, Ind. -- Aug. 13, 1998 -- NOTRE-DAME-2, 8-13
-- Notre Dame's once-pristine reputation has been battered by a
lawsuit filed by Joe Moore, a former assistant coach, that featured
sordid testimony about its football program. Mike Rosenthal, an
offensive lineman, claims the summer's controversies have not
distracted the players. ``The trial has never been a factor,'' says
Rosenthal, a captain who testified on behalf of his former
offensive line coach, Moore, at the trial. (Joe Raymond/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) SOUTH BEND, Ind. -- Aug. 13, 1998 -- NOTRE-DAME-1, 8-13
-- Bob Davie prepares his players as expectations hover over his
program. Notre Dame's once-pristine reputation has been battered by
a lawsuit filed by Joe Moore, a former assistant coach, that
featured sordid testimony about the program, and an NCAA review of
violations involving gifts to players. (Joe Raymond/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) SAN FRANCISCO -- Aug. 13, 1998 -- CALIF-FONG, 8-13 --
Matt Font, the Republican Senate candidate and former California
state treasurer, has pulled virtually even with the incumbent, Sen.
Barbara Boxer, in the polls. In late July, a San Francisco Examiner
poll found Ms. Boxer leading by just 43 percent to 40 percent.
(Darcy Padilla/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) LOS ANGELES -- Aug. 13, 1998 -- WEST-POINT-NOVEL, 8-13
-- Lucian Truscott IV's new novel, ``Full Dress Gray,'' like his
1978 mystery, ``Dress Gray,'' is a steamy potboiler set at the
United States Military Academy in West Point. Surprisingly, the
academy has eagerly embraced the book. ``I thought I would never be
welcome up there again,'' says Truscott, who graduated from the
academy in 1969. ``Now they're in the process of milling a whole
new red carpet to run out for me.'' (Kim Kulish/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) CLARK, Colo. -- Aug. 13, 1998 -- WESTERN-LAND-TRUSTS-2,
8-13 -- Jay Fetcher, who formed the Cattlemen's Agricultural Land
Trust, donated his development rights to a trust to preserve his
family's ranch. Here and across the Rocky Mountain West, tourism
and the second-home industry have spurred a land rush that is
carving up the ranch land that composes heart-stopping Western
vistas, threatening the very landscape that draws so many people to
the Rockies. (Ellen Jaskol/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) STEAMBOAT SPRINGS, Colo. -- Aug. 13, 1998 --
WESTERN-LAND-TRUSTS-1, 8-13 -- As condominiums encroach on a
mountain in Steamboat Springs, ranchers and farmers are using land
trusts to preserve the West's wide open spaces, one of the reasons
so many people go there in the first place. As subdivisions and
``ranchettes'' replace cattle, the new rallying cries are ``Cows,
not Condos'' and ``Herefords, not Highways.'' (Kevin Moloney/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW BERN, N.C. -- Aug. 13, 1998 -- PEPSI-BOTTLERS-2,
8-13 -- The Minges Bottling Group has enjoyed a near monopoly as
Pepsi's bottler in this region, but its hold on the area is not as
solid as it once was. Employee David Bright makes a delivery in New
Bern. ``It's like David and Goliath,'' says Jeff Minges, president
of of Kinston Pepsi-Cola Bottling Co., of the fight for market
share against the infiltration of Coke and a changing market. (M.J.
Sharp/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW BERN, N.C. -- Aug. 13, 1998 -- PEPSI-BOTTLERS-1,
8-13 -- Even for the Minges family, bottlers on sacred Pepsi turf
in North Carolina, Coke and a changing market create pressures. In
New Bern, Hoyt Minges, stands in front of a truck shaped like a
Pepsi can as, from left, Tyrus, John, Tom and Jeff Minges pose
inside. (M.J. Sharp/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) BETHEL, N.Y. -- Aug. 13, 1998 -- WOODSTOCK-CONCERT, 8-13
-- A children's painting area, with cutout figures, will be part of
a music festival this weekend at the site of the 1969 Woodstock
concert. Alan Gerry has bought and tamed Max Yasgur's hayfield to
leverage the legend of Woodstock, luring buttoned-down yuppies, not
rainbow-clad hippies, to this long-depressed southern flank of the
Catskills. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) DALIAN, China -- Aug. 13, 1998 -- CHINA-CROQUET, 8-13 --
Croquet, or ``gate ball,'' is the game of the moment among elderly
Chinese. But in Dalian, as elsewhere in northern China, croquet is
war and there is no time for niceties. Harsh language is common.
(Seth Faison/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEWTON, Mass. -- Aug. 13, 1998 -- STUDENTS-TOGETHER-BOS,
8-13 -- Jake Geller, who has muscular dystrophy, will be rooming
with Jack Buchholz at Arizona State University. Buchholz, 19, will
also serve as his personal care attendant. The two, who have been
friends and classmates since first grade, have also been have been
roommates at the Computer-Ed High Tech Camp at Lasell College in
Newton for the past three summers. (Mark Wilson/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) BOSTON -- Aug. 13, 1998 -- ATHLETES-CHARITY-BOS, 8-13 --
Marc Pollick in his Boston office. Pollick started the Giving Back
Fund one year ago. It offers athletes a one-stop service for
establishing and administering foundations, and the opportunity to
turn their lucrative salaries into philanthropic endeavors. (Wendy
Maeda/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) ANDREWS AIR FORCE BASE, Md. -- Aug. 13, 1998 --
AFRICA-MEMORIAL-3, 8-13 -- During a memorial service at Andrews Air
Force Base on Thursday, Lori Dalize, oldest daughter of Hean Rose
Dalizu, who was killed in the bombing of the U.S. Embassy in Kenya,
holds a photograph of her mother. ``Nothing can bring them back,
but nothing can erase the lives they led,'' says President Clinton.
(Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) ANDREWS AIR FORCE BASE, Md. -- Aug. 13, 1998 --
AFRICA-MEMORIAL-2, 8-13 -- During a memorial service at Andrews Air
Force Base on Thursday, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and
Secretary of Defense William Cohen follow President Clinton past
some of the flag-draped coffins of Americans killed in the bombings
of two U.S. embassies in Africa last week. ``No matter what it
takes, we must find those responsible for these evil acts and see
that justice is done,'' says Clinton. (Stephen Crowley/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) ANDREWS AIR FORCE BASE, Md.-- Aug. 13, 1998 --
AFRICA-MEMORIAL-1, 8-13 -- During a memorial service at Andrews Air
Force Base on Thursday, Families watch as coffins containing the
remains of the 12 Americans killed in the bombings of two U.S.
embassies in Africa last week are carried to hearses. At least 247
people were killed in Nairobi, Kenya where the explosion razed a
building next to the embassy; 10 people were also killed in Dar es
Salaam, Tanzania. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. -- Aug. 12, 1998 --
NY-SARATOGA-HORSES, 8-12 -- A polo match at Whitney Field in
Saratoga Springs. Although the mallets and the hard ball of polo
suggest elements of croquet, as well as of golf, the sport itself
is fast and furious; when the ball flies in action it can be
lethally hard. (David Jennings/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Aug. 13, 1998 -- NY-ETHNIC-ENTERTAINMENT,
8-13 -- Belly dancer Ranya performing at Cedars of Lebanon in
Manhattan. If all New Yorkers share one experience, it's the
sensation of suddenly feeling like a tourist without leaving the
city. Take an alternate route, turn an unfamiliar corner, peek into
an open doorway, and suddenly you could be in Tokyo or Timbuktu,
with strangers chatting in an unknown language while intriguing
scents waft from a kitchen. (Linda Rosier/New York Times Photo)
*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Aug. 13, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 16 --
YIDDISH-MUSIC, 8-12 -- Itzhak Perlman, left, and Pinchas Zuckerman
performing at the Mostly Mozart concert at Avery Fisher Hall.
Perlman, like avant-garde and experimental musicians, are getting
caught up in the Yiddish music renaissance. Musicians have found it
as a means for exploring their Jewish roots via unlikely,
cutting-edge reinterpretations. (Michelle V. Agins/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Aug. 13, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 16 --
FRIENDS-AND-NEIGHBORS-FILM, 8-12 -- It comes as no surprise that
the writer and director Neil LaBute's new movie, ``Your Friends and
Neighbors,'' is as provocative and unsettling as his ``In the
Company of Men'' was last year. ``I think my films come from a
desperation not to be boring,'' says LaBute, 35, during a recent
visit to New York. (Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Aug. 13, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 16 --
MUSICALS-REVIVALS-2, 8-12 -- Rob Fisher, the dynamic, 46-year-old
musical theater conductor, serves as musical director of City
Center's Encores series. The Encores series is a nonprofit
operation that presents only six performances of each show. Fisher,
with his efforts to reconstruct old shows from original, often
incomplete, sources has become a hero to devotees of the American
musical. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Aug. 13, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 16 --
MUSICALS-REVIVALS-1, 8-12 -- Rebecca Luker, as Maria, with some of
the children in ``The Sound of Music'' at The Martin Beck Theater.
With its famous score, this 1959 show, the last Rodgers and
Hammerstein collaboration, is just one of Broadway's commercially
safe revivals. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Aug. 13, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 16 --
SERBAN-CYMBELINE-THEATER, 8-12 -- Andrei Serban in front of Lincoln
Center. Serban, 55, the director of ``Cymbeline'', ran the National
Theater in Romania from 1900 to 1993. A recent documentary entitled
``Crossroads,'' captures the graduate acting program at Columbia
University which Serban runs and his reaction to his recent work
and productions. (Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
