<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: FERRARO, BANKING ON POLLS, PLAYS IT SAFE AS
FRONT-RUNNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROY, N.Y. _ With politicians, it is usually wiser to watch what
they are doing rather than listen to what they are saying. From
that perspective, there is not much mystery these days about
Geraldine Ferraro's strategy as she runs for the Senate Democratic
nomination. Her public assertions notwithstanding, she is following
the unadventurous approach of a self-presumed front-runner, doing
as little as she can to spill the soup.
</P>
<P>
   That was apparent Wednesday night at the candidate's second
debate in Albany. Ferraro all but vanished in her chair, offering
familiar positions and endorsements of Democratic doctrine, as her
opponents, Rep. Charles Schumer and New York City Public Advocate
Mark Green, traded attention-grabbing proposals and quotes. And it
has been obvious in her relatively light public schedule, which
attests to the low-altitude campaign she is flying.
</P>
<P>
   This approach _ take few chances, hit the right Democratic
buttons, float above any fighting among her opponents _ is, on one
level, unsurprising. Assuming that the public and private polls
Ferraro is relying on are correct (not a small assumption in the
notoriously unpredictable world of New York primary voters), there
is little reason for her to do anything unconventional or daring
before the Sept. 15 primary.
</P>
<P>
   But there are potential risks in Ferraro's relatively complacent
approach. Notwithstanding her obvious popularity and political
fame, she finds herself in a contest that promises to be
distinguished by the sophisticated political skills and sheer
hunger of all her major opponents, from Green and Schumer now to
D'Amato in November.
</P>
<P>
   All three men are dogged, wily and unceasingly energetic, with
their dusk-to-dawn attentions focused on winning the Senate race.
Their level of excitement only serves to highlight what strikes
some Democrats, by comparison, as Ferraro's lethargy.
</P>
<P>
   To further complicate matters for Ferraro, she is facing in
Schumer and D'Amato opponents with enormous financial resources.
Ferraro's aides believe she only has enough money to afford two
weeks of advertising at the end of the primary; Schumer and D'Amato
have been advertising on television almost since the start of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, when Ferraro replaced her campaign manager amid
signs of difficulty with her candidacy, she said the change in
staff signaled a new phase in her race, in which she would
aggressively seek to counter concerns among some Democrats that she
was taking the nomination for granted. And Thursday, during a quick
campaign hop to this city across the Hudson River from Albany, she
said she was aggressively discussing education and health care and
``talking to voters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still ahead by double digits, so I'm just going to sit and
do what I have to do, which is to speak to the issues and come and
meet with people,'' Ferraro said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, her campaign activities, which have in recent days
consisted mostly of shaking hands at subway stations, have been
dwarfed by those of her rivals. Green, for example, gave a
different speech almost every day this week, while Schumer
continues to flood television with advertisements. In one revealing
afternoon earlier this week, Schumer, Green and D'Amato all showed
up at the steps of City Hall in New York for news conferences.
Ferraro went to a subway station that day.
</P>
<P>
   In following this route, Ferraro and her advisers are embracing
polls that have led them to conclude that, whatever bumps she might
hit in the weeks ahead, she is the overwhelming favorite to win the
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   On its face, that is not an unreasonable conclusion. Ferraro is
clearly popular, and starts with the instant advantage of having
been the first woman nominated by a major party to run for vice
president and having worked as a commentator on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   But annointing oneself the front-runner is a tricky business.
For one thing, taking an accurate measure of Democratic primary
voters in New York _ where it is hard to determine who is going to
vote _ is so difficult that some pollsters do not even bother
trying.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Ferraro in fact lost a U.S. Senate bid in 1992,
however narrowly, in a field that many Democrats believe was not so
strong as this one. And in any event, New York voters have tended
to look more kindly on underdogs than favorites, as New York City
Mayor Edward Koch learned when he ran for governor in 1982, losing
the Democratic nomination to Mario Cuomo.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, there is arguably a difference between avoiding the
crossfire, as the former television debater did Wednesday night,
and saying something that might stir the interests of voters. There
is something to be said for playing it safe, but Ferraro's
opponents are running the kind of campaigns that tend to interest
voters, which can matter in a primary where turnout is low. Voters
seem to notice and reward evidence that a politician is truly
interested in their vote _ no one, for example, campaigns more
energetically and relentlessly than Bill Clinton or Rudolph
Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   In discussing her debate performance Thursday, Ferraro said that
she accomplished precisely what she intended. Her ``sole goal,''
she said, was making her case to the New York State Public
Employees Federation, which sponsored the event, and thus winning
its support. ``I felt comfortable when I walked out that I had done
my part _ that I gave them, I think, sufficient grounds to vote an
endorsement for me,'' Ferraro said.
</P>
<P>
   But two hours later, the federation announced that it would be
supporting Schumer in the Democratic primary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
