r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-FREE-SAFE     08-13 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-FREE-SAFETY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOUTMIRE OUT FRONT IN RACE TO START AT FREE SAFETY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Omar Stoutmire might never start in a Pro
Bowl, as have some of his predecessors who have played free safety
for the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   And the second-year player might never be compared to the likes
of Mel Renfro and Cliff Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he would be the starting free safety in the Cowboys' defense
if the season were to begin today, defensive coordinator Dave Campo
said.
</P>
<P>
   Stoutmire's two years of experience, Campo said, and his
run-support ability give him an advantage over former cornerback
Kenny Wheaton and veteran George Teague, his main competitors.
</P>
<P>
   But Campo warns that the opener is still 23 days away. Stoutmire
must improve his ballhawking abilities to earn a start against the
Arizona Cardinals on Sept. 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no guarantees one way or the other,'' Campo said.
</P>
<P>
   That is because the competition at the position, left open by
the off-season departure of free agent Brock Marion, is one of the
fiercest in training camp. Stoutmire, in his second season, has
more snaps with the first team, but Wheaton and Teague bring their
own credentials to the Cowboys' defense.
</P>
<P>
   Wheaton has shown the best coverage skills in camp. Teague, who
appears to be running third-string based on the number of
repetitions he has taken, is a proven playmaker. In his last stint
with the Cowboys in 1996, Teague forced two fumbles and returned an
interception for a touchdown in the Cowboys' last playoff victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like I'm gnashing my teeth, lying awake at night
wondering what are we going to do,'' Campo said. ``We've got three
good football players. Whichever one starts, we'll be in good
shape. And then we'll have a good second guy, and a good third
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong safety Darren Woodson has an obvious interest in who will
be his running mate this year. He was Marion's teammate from
1993-97, and he depended on Marion to improve his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still blow \Rassignments\S and have bad reads, so I need
somebody that can help me get better as a player,'' Woodson, a
three-time All Pro, said. ``Brock and I competed in everything _
one-on-one drills, interceptions, passes defensed, big hits. It
didn't matter. Brock made me better because we pushed each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoutmire showed flashes of his potential to fit in the Cowboys'
defense during his rookie season. He played in all 16 games and
started twice, registering 13 tackles against the Eagles in his
first start and 17 tackles against the Oilers in his second start.
Stoutmire showed good timing on the blitz with two sacks in the
season. He had two interceptions, forced two fumbles and had 76
tackles _ which was seventh among NFL rookies.
</P>
<P>
   But much of Stoutmire's production in 1997 came as a nickel back
and at strong safety. Thus, there are no questions about his
hitting ability. But he said he has not quite mastered the mental
challenge that comes with being a free safety, which is charged
with directing the defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a big mental game,'' said Stoutmire, who holds his
fingers about 11/2 inches apart to describe how thick the defensive
playbook is. ``I'm just trying to get more comfortable with what we
are doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Stoutmire, Wheaton is also in his second year. But Wheaton
has the least experience at free safety. He was an All Pac-10
cornerback at the University of Oregon, coached by former Cowboys
safety Charlie Waters. He was the fifth cornerback with the Cowboys
in 1997, behind Deion Sanders, Kevin Smith, Kevin Mathis and
Wendell Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Wheaton's skills as a cornerback have helped him in coverage,
Campo said. But Wheaton's 5-foot-10, 190-pound stature has been a
challenge in run support.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing for me is getting better at coming up, taking on the
big running back and being able to hit him and let him know that
I'm really there,'' Wheaton said. ``That will come from me getting
stronger in the weight room and working on my tackling
techniques.''
</P>
<P>
   In Teague, the Cowboys have a veteran of six years who spent
last year struggling in Miami. He started the final 10 games of the
1996 season with the Cowboys when Marion was injured.
</P>
<P>
   Like Wheaton, ``tackling is the area that George needs to work
hardest on,'' Campo said.
</P>
<P>
   Teague said his problem stems from technique, and from being
overly aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been trying to make something happen to often instead of
just making the tackle,'' Teague said. ``I want to get the kill
shot, with the oohs and aahs. But I've come to realize that I don't
have to tear a guy's head off. I just need to get the guy down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
