</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LIVENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADIAN REGULATORS INVESTIGATE LIVENT  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Canadian securities regulators said Thursday that they are
investigating the accounting problems at Livent Inc., the
Toronto-based company that brought the hit musicals ``Ragtime'' and
``Showboat'' to Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are investigating the allegations the company has made,''
said Larry Waite, director of enforcement at the Ontario Securities
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   At the Securities and Exchange Commission in Washington,
regulators said that as a matter of policy, they could not confirm
or deny whether they might be proceeding with a similar
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Livent said that the company _ whose shares
trade on the Toronto Stock Exchange and on the Nasdaq market in the
United States _ was cooperating with regulatory officials.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Livent's new management announced that an internal
investigation had found serious accounting problems involving
millions of dollars. The new managers, led by Michael Ovitz, the
former Hollywood power broker, said that they were suspending Garth
Drabinsky, Livent's chief creative director, and Myron Gottlieb, a
vice president, as a result of their investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Drabinsky and Gottlieb have denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials have said that they are ``virtually certain''
that the company's financial results dating back to 1996 will have
to be restated.
</P>
<P>
   Livent's shares have not traded since the company disclosed the
problems.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
