<SLUG> BC-NY-WATER-TUNNEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH CEREMONY, NEW YORK STARTS USING PART OF A WATER TUNNEL BEGUN
IN 1970 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DOUGLAS MARTIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Third Water Tunnel seems timeless. In 1954, city
officials determined that it was needed, and in 1970 construction
began on what has long been billed as the biggest public works
project in America.
</P>
<P>
   There are men who have retired after spending every one of their
working days on the tunnel. City officials now expect that the
tunnel will be finished around 2020 and cost $5.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, it was expected that New Yorkers would not taste
water from the tunnel until it was completed. The Giuliani
administration decided about 15 months ago, though, that the
finished 13.5-mile segment, which was actually completed in 1993,
could be used as soon as some tests were completed.
</P>
<P>
   So in the summer heat Thursday, they paused to celebrate _ and
taste _ what they have accomplished so far.
</P>
<P>
   At a ceremony at the Central Park Reservoir, they also honored
those who have died during the construction. Altogether, the
legendary tunnel has claimed 24 lives, counting actual tunnel
diggers (called sandhogs), engineers, inspectors and one child who
fell into a shaft.
</P>
<P>
   As Mayor Rudolph Giuliani read each of the names in alphabetical
order, a sandhog stepped forward and rang a gold-colored bell.
There were 24 single rings. The mayor also recited two sayings that
are commonly used to describe the danger of the work: the death
rate works out to about one a mile, and one a year.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Miele Sr., commissioner of the Department of Environmental
Protection, said the accident rate was no worse than at other
construction sites, but he did mention some of the details of the
underground workplace. He said that heavy dust swirled incessantly,
that the noise was terrible and that workers could be trapped by
fires.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are always going to be industrial accidents,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Miele said the first section of the 14-foot-diameter tunnel cost
$1 billion. It runs from Hillview Reservoir north of New York City,
through the Bronx and into Manhattan, across Central Park, under
the East River and Roosevelt Island, and into Queens.
</P>
<P>
   He said it was his decision to reverse the original plan and
open this portion before the other three stages are finished. There
was no reason not to add to available water supplies in the Bronx
and northern Manhattan, he said. The new tunnel also makes it
possible to close one of the other two tunnels for repairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever portion of it we can use we should be using,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
