<HEADER>
A3176 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-USC-LADN     08-13 0473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALMER AHEAD IN BACKUP BATTLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's been no official word, but freshman quarterback Carson
Palmer appears to be making major strides toward becoming USC's
No.2 quarterback as coach Paul Hackett nears a decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been very impressed with No.15,'' Hackett said,
identifying Palmer by uniform number. ``He's got poise beyond his
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said he would like to decide on a No.2 quarterback after
the weekend, and Palmer has been impressive in practices this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to make what will not be an easy decision,'' Hackett
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said he will use freshmen only to play extensively and
not in a mop-up capacity.
</P>
<P>
   With both Palmer and freshman Jason Thomas vying for playing
time, Hackett said redshirting both ``would be a real reach.''
</P>
<P>
   Barring a surprise, sophomore Mike Van Raaphorst will be the
Trojans' starter in the season opener against Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes debuts: Wide receiver Windrell Hayes attended his first
practice, one day after receiving three years' probation and being
ordered to pay an $8,490.13 fine for writing bad checks.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes participated in some light drills and worked out
individually with wide receivers coach Mike Wilson because he must
practice his first three days without pads.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as the court case, that's over with and I'm glad to be
here,'' Hayes said. ``I'm glad USC gave me a chance. I'm looking
forward to starting over. I figured everybody makes a mistake. I
was just hoping to get a second chance.''
</P>
<P>
   USC insisted that Hayes pay the fine by obtaining a formal loan
through a Stockton bank to avoid the appearance of breaking NCAA
rules.
</P>
<P>
   Before he practiced, Hayes met with Hackett.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just kind of reviewed things. He needs to put all that
behind him. He'll get a clean slate,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes, who played two years at San Jose State before attending
San Joaquin Delta Community College, said he originally considered
attending USC out of high school. But poor grades and a fear of
leaving home helped keep him near his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I left (San Jose State) because I thought I could do a lot
more,'' Hayes said. ``I didn't think I could reach my potential at
that school.''
</P>
<P>
   First day in contact: USC practiced in pads for the first time
on Thursday, and Hackett was pleased with the results. ``I thought
it was a solid first day. There was great enthusiasm (in the
morning practice) and we settled into learning and teaching in the
afternoon. From what we wanted, I feel OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Larry Parker left the field in the afternoon, but
was suffering only cramps.
</P>
<P>
   Surprise appearance: Among the visitors on Thursday was former
USC quarterback Todd Marinovich.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 2221EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
