<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3178 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN     08-13 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
 
No. 7 FINE FOR NOW 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Football coaches usually treat preseason rankings
with either disdain or indifference. But not Bruins coach Bob
Toledo, not this year. After learning last season that the higher
you start, the higher you can finish, Toledo welcomed UCLA's No.7
ranking in the preseason coaches poll.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told our people that it's hard to come from 35th (to the
top),'' Toledo said. ``It's a lot easier if you start in the top
10.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins began the 1997 season unranked, lost to Washington
State and Tennessee, then rode a 10-game winning streak all the way
to No.5. But because of the low (and slow) start, they ran out of
time. They could climb only so high.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other thing is, (the No.7 ranking) shows respect for our
program,'' Toledo said. ``Now we have to go out and earn that
respect.''
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press preseason poll will be released Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Going fast: Combine the winning streak with a top-rated
recruiting class and a Heisman Trophy candidate, and the result is
a record jump in season ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have sold 29,000 season tickets, or 3,500 more than
last year at this time. The 14 percent jump is the largest ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had 400-500 calls a day to the ticket office since Aug.
1,'' ticket manager Scott Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins are shipping one million schedule cards to area Taco
Bells. They have hundreds of billboards around L.A. sporting a
``Heismania'' theme, with a picture of quarterback Cade McNown's
head and arm.
</P>
<P>
   In other ticket-related news, associate athletic director Rick
Purdy has received complaints from ``less than 1 percent'' of
season-ticket holders since they were informed of the new seating
chart.
</P>
<P>
   The installation of individual seats, with flip-up bottoms, has
reduced Rose Bowl attendance from 100,000 to 93,000 and forced the
Bruins to reconfigure their seating.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead: The Bruins have replaced Pittsburgh with Fresno
State on their 1999 schedule, and not by choice. In April, the
Panthers reneged on a nine-year-old written agreement for a
home-and-home series in '99 and 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Fresno State will visit the Rose Bowl next Sept. 18. There is no
return game scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd rather have a home-and-home with someone,'' said
media-relations director Marc Dellins, who handles the scheduling.
``But it was on such short notice.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA also needs an opponent for Sept. 9, 2000 _ a delicate slot
because it falls between dates with Alabama and Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Early accolades: At least four Bruins figure to contend for
postseason awards. McNown is a Heisman Trophy and Davey O'Brien
candidate. Safety Larry Atkins (Jim Thorpe Award), kicker Chris
Sailer (Lou Groza) and offensive tackle Kris Farris (Outland
Trophy) are on preliminary lists, as well.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule: UCLA's heralded freshman class makes its first
official appearance Tuesday morning with a workout at Spaulding
Field. The veterans report Aug. 20, and training camp opens Aug. 21
with non-contact practices at 10 a.m. and 4 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 2223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980813.0470 </DOCNO>
