<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCIVER STATEMENT DELAYED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS AND CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ The statement that was to be issued by
Cowboys guard Everett McIver will be postponed until later this
week, team owner Jerry Jones said. McIver was expected to issue the
statement yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   McIver is expected to speak on several subjects, including his
relationship with teammate Michael Irvin and his future with the
Cowboys. He is also expected to address a news report that Jones
negotiated a deal with Irvin to pay McIver for his silence about a
July 29 incident that left McIver with a cut on his neck. Sources
have said Irvin inflicted the wound to McIver with a pair of
scissors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect him \RMcIver\S to say something before the end of
training camp,'' Jones said.
Davis to get start
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said yesterday that Billy Davis will
get the start at No. 2 receiver in Monday's American Bowl game
against the New England Patriots in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Eight-year veteran Ernie Mills, whom the Cowboys signed as a
free-agent in the off-season, had been listed as the starter since
the beginning of training camp because of his experience and
knowledge of Gailey's offense. Mills played under Gailey when both
were in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Mills, however, has not caught a pass in the Cowboys' two
preseason games, while Davis has notched four receptions.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said he is not unhappy with Mills' performance, but he
thinks Davis deserves a chance to show what he can do with the
first team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy deserves a chance to start,'' Gailey said. ``We haven't
been unhappy with Ernie. But they are close enough where Billy
deserves a chance. We want to see how he'll react.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who has been mainly a special-teams player since making
the Cowboys team four years ago as a undrafted free agent, plans to
make the most of the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I've been waiting for a long time,'' Davis
said. ``I'm going to do the best I can.''
Mexico City field a concern
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said the league is already checking into the quality of
the playing field for Monday's game against the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   When the Cowboys played the Oilers in a 1994 game in Mexico
City, the field looked like a swamp.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said a poor playing surface could increase the risk of
injury and reduce the playing time of his star players, but he said
right now he is just going to wait and see until he gets there.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's dangerous, you got to be smart about it,'' Gailey
said. ``There is supposed to be some better precautions this year,
keep it covered and stuff like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said he will likely limit his starters to just a quarter
of playing time before increasing their workload in preseason
matchup against the Rams Aug. 22.
Helmsley earning spot
</P>
<P>
   Gailey all but guaranteed reserve linebacker Nate Helmsley a
spot on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said Helmsley, who played on the Cowboys practice squad
for much of last year before being called up late in the season,
has separated himself from the other linebacker hopefuls behind
starters Randall Godfrey, Dexter Coakley and Fred Strickland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nate has really played well,'' Gailey said. ``He has had a
good training camp. He has played well on defense and on special
teams. The guys after him are vying for positions.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said the team could keep as many as seven linebackers.
</P>
<P>
   Another linebacker catching the coach's eye is rookie free agent
Robert Thomas. At 6-foot-1, 255-pounds, Thomas is not the
prototypical middle linebacker, but he makes plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``He makes a lot of plays,'' Gailey said. ``You got to give him
credit for the things he's doing on the field.''
Waiting for Prime Time
</P>
<P>
   Even though Deion Sanders' long-awaited move to wide receiver
has been postponed by another injury, Gailey refuses to give up on
the possibility of using the speedy cornerback on offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like every time I talk about it, he gets hurt so I'm
going to quit talking about it and maybe he'll stay healthy,''
Gailey said. ``But I don't think we'll ever give up on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey, who couldn't play Sanders on offense during June
minicamp because he'd had ankle surgery, had hoped to finally
indoctrinate Sanders to the new offense over the next couple of
weeks. But the cornerback suffered a rib injury against the Saints
and is not expected to be available until the Sept. 6
regular-season opener against Arizona.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
