<SLUG> BC-NY-COLLAPSE-HOMELESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISRUPTIONS DRAG ON FOR TIMES SQUARE'S MOST FRAGILE LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LYNETTE HOLLOWAY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three weeks after a construction scaffold collapsed,
raining debris on 43rd Street, killing a woman and forcing hundreds
of people from their homes and businesses, some semblance of
normality has been restored to Times Square. The glitter has
returned to most Broadway theaters, street-corner peddlers are
back, and the crush of traffic can once again be felt for miles.
</P>
<P>
   But 274 residents of the Woodstock Hotel _ many of them elderly,
frail, mentally ill and formerly homeless _ still cannot go home
because their building, badly damaged in the accident, has not been
deemed safe.
</P>
<P>
   Though the city allowed hotel workers to search apartments
Tuesday for important belongings like eyeglasses and identification
cards, some residents say they still lack essential things.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Little needs the dentures he left sitting in a cup in the
bathroom of his tiny apartment. Gladys Lejuez needs the comfort of
home, period. Alvin Romans wants to gaze on the photograph of his
mother that is framed in a grandfather clock that chimes every
hour. And Margaret Lawson, 60, needs her Medicaid card so she can
go to the doctor to have a heart problem monitored.
</P>
<P>
   The accident has thrust many Woodstock residents back into a
life they thought they had long abandoned, forcing them to live out
of plastic bags in sterile hotel rooms. The residents are spread
out along Manhattan's West Side, and their temporary homes include
the Washington Jefferson Hotel in midtown, the McBurney YMCA in
Chelsea and The Times Square. The displacement has disrupted the
routines of people who can little afford such disruptions.
</P>
<P>
   It could be as long as three months before they can go home,
said Cynthia Dial, executive director of Project Find, a private
nonprofit social service agency that runs the 12-story Woodstock
Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The stretch of 43rd Street between Times Square and Avenue of
the Americas, home to the Woodstock and the Kit Kat Klub, location
of the hit Broadway musical ``Cabaret,'' might reopen Aug. 20, said
Sunny Mindel, a spokeswoman for the Mayor's Office of Emergency
Management. But even that is not certain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The demolition process necessary for the reopening of the
street is a delicate process that could be slowed by inclement
weather,'' Ms. Mindel said. ``But we are hopeful.''
</P>
<P>
   The accident at the Conde Nast building has financially drained
Project Find, even though the Red Cross is paying to house the
residents at seven buildings around the city. Project Find is
trying to raise $350,000 to help pay for clothing, meals and
transportation costs for the tenants and for overtime pay for staff
members during the displacement, Ms. Dial said.
</P>
<P>
   But residents not only are in shock over being forced out of
their homes; they also are mourning the death of a friend. Thereza
Feliconio, 85, who lived at the Woodstock, was killed when chunks
of steel from the Conde Nast construction site crashed into her
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew her,'' said James Mills, 69. ``I'm thinking about going
back to my hometown, Albany. This is getting to be too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Some residents complain angrily that they have been ignored by
the city, saying that more noise was made about pets trapped in
apartments. They say that Liberty Mutual Group _ the insurance
company for the Durst Organization, the developer of the Conde Nast
building _ and Tishman Construction Corp., the construction manager
for the building, quibble over every little detail, making their
lives difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``This city has its priorities all screwed up,'' said Little, a
barrel-chested 69-year-old. ``They forgot about us. I turn on the
news and all I hear about is how some people are worried about
their pets. Now, I like pets, but what about me? I don't have any
teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   Little, tired of living on food he does not have to chew, is
among 90 Woodstock residents staying at the Washington Jefferson
Hotel. Wednesday evening, many of them milled about the worn
wood-paneled corridors of the hotel, asking one another whether
they had heard any news about when they could go home.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the tenants are hard-bitten New York City characters,
shaped by harsh lives in the city. Some of them once were singers
or actors. Others describe themselves as former ``Bowery bums.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I owned, I left behind,'' said Ms. Lejuez, who
declined to reveal her age, saying only that she was over 30. ``I
walked out in a flowered nightgown that I threw a blouse over and
my pocketbook.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lejuez, a white-haired former cabaret and radio singer, had
trouble admitting that she had ever been homeless, and she glided
over the question like a skater over ice.
</P>
<P>
   She keeps her donated shoes and clothes in bags on top of two
chairs because she does not use hotel bureaus, she said, noting
that she had not had time to clean the drawers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been hard for me,'' she said. ``I need my things. I
even left my lipstick, which I had to replace.''
</P>
<P>
   Clyde Burton, 86, whose easygoing Southern manner made him seem
out of place amid the hustle of the lobby of the Washington
Jefferson Hotel, sat clutching a plastic bag of asthma medication
and blood pressure pills. Burton has lived at the Woodstock for
nine years. A Lower East Side residential center for the elderly is
named after him because of his work as a volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   Burton is a recovering alcoholic who has been sober for 20
years, and said he used to panhandle on the streets of the Lower
East Side. He believes the scaffolding accident is payback for the
life he threw away when he was a Bowery bum.
</P>
<P>
   His voice cracked and trailed off when he said he was afraid of
losing his apartment. He was concerned about the delicate china
that had been given to him as a gift.
</P>
<P>
   ``With my past, you feel terrible,'' he said. ``I'm reaping what
I sowed. It's just hard luck, but God doesn't put no more on you
than you can bear. What can you do when you've lost everything you
have? This reminds me of the days when I didn't have nothing, when
I was wrecking myself. It's a terrible feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Romans, 69, also believes that the scaffolding accident was a
sign of his past catching up with him. He said he did time in
prison and slept on the streets of the Bowery, begging for change
to buy a pint of white port before finding religion in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I get down, I think about the life I used to lead,'' he
said. ``I don't have the comfort of my little apartment at the
Woodstock, but I'm not a drinking man. What I'm hoping and praying
is that I can go back and that it's not gone. It's all I have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
