u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-ROBERTSON-COL-HNS     08-13 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ROBERTSON-COL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   New-growth forest &QL; 
thrives in Redmond
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
REDMOND, Wash. _ Good news for the PGA Tour. Tiger Woods is
learning how to play golf.
</P>
<P>
   But oh, boy, bad news for the other PGA Tourists.
</P>
<P>
   If you must compete with him, watching Tiger sort out the
nuances of his chosen vocation is frightening to contemplate. But
if you need the Woods magic to sell your product, his growing up
before our eyes has cosmic implications.
</P>
<P>
   Clueless, Tiger won the Masters by 12 strokes last year. He
gripped, he ripped, and it was good. At 21, the kid was swooshing
to legendary status.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, there have been complications since. Augusta National's
inviting, broad-shouldered fairways don't punish a young man's
macho instincts. In contrast, on tight courses such Sahalee, where
they're contesting the PGA Championship, swinging a golf club like
Ken Griffey Jr. swings a baseball bat is a foolhardly tactic.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger, Junior's house guest for the week, had no chance to win
this tournament, we assumed. Some of these holes, fenced in by
dark, brooding thickets of cedar and Douglas fir, can only be
described as claustrophobic. They resemble bowling lanes.
</P>
<P>
   The golfer formerly known as Eldrick was going to spend so much
time wandering lost among the trees, they would have to rename the
local forest the Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger's maturity showing
</P>
<P>
   He crossed us up big-time, though. His driver never left his
bag, and his golf balls stayed playable. Although he officially hit
just nine fairways, he rarely strayed into fatal terrain. By the
time he returned in triumph to the clubhouse, Woods had posted a
course-record 66, a feat roughly akin to Pete Sampras winning the
French Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a more mature Tiger than you saw last year at this time,''
he said, comparing himself to the frustrated also-ran who futilely
winged it at Winged Foot. ``I've got more shots. I understand my
game. I understand how to hit shots when I'm not feeling well over
the ball, how to get the ball out there and just keep it in play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tried to be myself and hit good golf shots. Just let it
come; don't force it.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods commands a superb putting touch on his best days, such as
this one, when he holed six of 15 feet or longer, including a
35-footer on No. 17. It's reason enough for him to temper his
testosterone off the tee, letting his myriad subtle gifts come to
the fore. He needn't outdrive the world in order to outplay the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said. ``Putting's the name of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``new'' Tiger revealed himself last month at the British
Open, where diabolical weather dictated he think his way around
Royal Birkdale or perish early. Three-quarter shots were mandatory
to avoid the howling gales blowing in off the Irish Sea, and Woods,
without being nagged, instinctively throttled down. He relied on
his head more than his club head and didn't bag his game plan even
after a discouraging, wind-whipped 77 on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The net result would be a final-round 66 _ so he's in a real rut
now, isn't he? _ that left him only one shot removed from the
playoff between Mark O'Meara and Brian Watts. It's the closest he
has come to winning a second major and the best indication, at
least until Thursday, that he will win a bunch of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a great change in the way he plays,'' his coach, Butch
Harmon, said after the British. ``Tiger is working hard to lower
his trajectory. He switched to a graphite-shafted driver because it
makes his balls fly a little lower. We've done things not just for
here but so he can control his distance all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Still learning at 22
</P>
<P>
   It's a growth process, or ``evolution,'' as Tiger calls it, with
which every callow golfer copes to some degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about learning how to play golf,'' Woods said. ``Ask
players in their teens or early 20s. They hit the ball pretty hard.
As they get older, they figure out how to manage their games.''
</P>
<P>
   And the better the game, the more it needs managing. What hurts
Tiger is his own perceived lack of limitations. He believes he can
do anything, with good reason.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, despite our perception that he has been mired in some
terrible slump, he has six top-four finishes in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   And he's No. 1 in the world rankings _ at 22 years of age.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not bad,'' Woods said. ``I've been right there in all
the majors. I'm pretty close to putting it all together and being
in the hunt where I could legitimately win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've accepted the fact that I've played well and just come up
a little short. But I've given it everything I've got.''
</P>
<P>
   By, strangely enough, not giving it everything he's got. Less
can be more. In the process of growing up, it's a lesson we're all
forced to learn sooner or later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 2234EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
