<HEADLINE>
SETTLEMENT IN DISPUTE OVER PAINTING LOOTED BY NAZIS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (js) 
 By JUDITH H. DOBRZYNSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the first Nazi looting case to be settled in the United
States, the relatives of two Holocaust victims said Thursday that
they had reached an agreement with a pharmaceutical company heir
over ownership of a Degas landscape.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement essentially calls for a ``split-the-baby''
solution. In it, the Art Institute of Chicago will acquire the
work, ``Landscape With Smokestacks,'' jointly from Lili Gutmann and
her nephews Nick and Simon Goodman, the daughter and grandsons of
two Holocaust victims, and from Daniel Searle, the current owner,
who is a trustee of the art institute and a former chairman of G.D.
Searle &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   The art institute will pay the Goodmans half of the work's
fair-market value, which was not disclosed, and Searle will donate
the painting. The agreement also stipulates that the names
Friedrich and Louise Gutmann, who died in Theresienstadt and
Auschwitz respectively, as well as that of Searle, be on the
institute's wall labels when the work is on display.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an agreement made in heaven _ nobody wins and nobody
loses,'' Nick Goodman said. ``And it was an opportunity. We wanted
to show the world that we could settle our case and maybe show the
way for all these other cases.''
</P>
<P>
   At least a half dozen claims for art stolen during World War II
have recently been made in the United States, and experts believe
there will probably be more. Claims have started surfacing only in
the past few years, as wartime archives have been opened, the Iron
Curtain has fallen and books and the news media have brought
attention to the issue.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Goodman-Searle case began simmering in 1995, when Simon
Goodman found ``Landscape with Smokestacks'' listed in an
exhibition catalog as the property of Searle. In 1939, his
grandparents had sent the country landscape, along with other
paintings, from their home in the Netherlands to Paris, where the
family contends it was confiscated during the war. The painting
changed hands a few times after the war, moving through Switzerland
to New York, where Searle, unaware of its history, bought it in
1987 for $850,000.
</P>
<P>
   All along, Ms. Gutmann, a 79-year-old resident of Florence,
Italy; her brother, Bernard Goodman, who died in 1994; and his
sons, Nick, 52, and Simon, 49, both residents of Los Angeles, had
been looking for the painting.
</P>
<P>
   After a year of unfruitful discussions with Searle, the Goodman
family sued him in 1996. The trial was set to begin on Sept. 9.
</P>
<P>
   But last Friday, Nick Goodman called Searle, suggesting one last
effort to settle the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman also suggested that the art institute might be part of a
deal, based on consultations he had had with Hector Feliciano, the
author of ``The Lost Museum: The Nazi Conspiracy to Steal the
World's Greatest Works of Art'' (Basic Books, 1997). Feliciano,
acting on the Goodmans' behalf, had approached James Wood, the
institute's director, to see whether he could participate in a
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Art Institute could help realize an equitable solution
to a very difficult legal problem, we were happy to do it,'' Wood
said. ``It's a work of art we've always wanted. And now it goes
into the public domain where its history is recognized.''
</P>
<P>
   Feliciano said of the pact: ``We are rectifying history at our
modest level and showing that this is the way to resolve these
cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Searle is traveling, but his lawyer, Howard Trienens, said:
``I'm sure he would say, `I'm glad it's over.' The problem here is
that it would have cost much more to try this case than the
painting is worth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Landscape with Smokestacks'' will go on view at the art
institute on Oct. 9, and the Goodmans will probably be there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen the painting,'' Nick Goodman said. ``I'm
looking forward to holding it for the first and probably last
time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
