u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICA-BOMBING-ART-1S     08-13 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-BOMBING-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-575(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POTENTIALLY SIGNIFICANT CLUES UNCOVERED IN NAIROBI BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Subs to change ``car'' references to ``truck'' and to clarify
Benson Okuku Bwaku's description of the suspect in graf 5.)   (See also: AFRICA-MEMORIAL, AFRICA-BOMBING, AFRICA-U.S.,
AFRICA-TANZANIA)  
(ART ADV: Graphic with details on the bombing is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(lh) 
 By TIM WEINER and RAYMOND BONNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ The FBI agent in charge of solving the bombing
of the U.S. Embassy here said Thursday that the bureau had found
fragments of the truck that carried the explosives, and was piecing
together a picture of what happened in the seconds before the bomb
went off.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators are trying to put together a puzzle of
countless parts, plucking shards of glass and metal from the
shattered embassy, and sorting through sometimes contradictory
accounts by witnesses. They are trying to reassemble the scene at
the moment when an explosion set off by three unknown suspects, at
least one of whom may still be at large, killed at least 247
people, including 12 Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The picture is developing slowly, and the initial stage of the
investigation may take a month, the bureau said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But the embassy's private security guards have given the FBI a
detailed account of what happened just after 10:30 a.m. last
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   One of the guards, Benson Okuku Bwaku, met with the FBI Thursday
to help them draw a sketch of one of the suspects. He described a
man with a light beard, gray slacks and a plaid shirt. The head of
the private company employing the security guards said the embassy
had told him not to characterize the man's ethnic background, but
said he was not white and not black.
</P>
<P>
   ``Painstaking detective work,'' including ``literally sifting
through piles of rubble,'' has yielded potentially significant
clues, said the FBI special agent in charge of the investigation,
Sheila Horan, a counterterrorism specialist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been successful, we think, in identifying certain
parts of the delivery vehicle,'' she said. Shattered parts of the
truck were carried possibly hundreds of feet from the blast, over
terrain that FBI forensics teams have combed for the last three
days. She did not explain how the investigators knew the fragments
were from the delivery truck.
</P>
<P>
   That twisted metal could help trace the truck's origins and the
type of explosive used, and take the investigation a step or two
down the long road ahead, U.S. officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get the car,'' a senior law-enforcement official said,
describing the future course of the investigation. ``Get the VIN,''
the vehicle identification number unique to every automobile and
soldered to its body.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll take you somewhere,'' the official said. ``Interview
everybody. Somebody saw something. Somebody knows something.
Somebody saw someone get on an airliner. You're far, far away from
a dead end.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI said that the first pieces of evidence from the scene of
the two bombings in East Africa would arrive in Washington this
weekend for forensic testing.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Thursday at FBI headquarters, senior bureau
officials said that the investigation would come down in large part
to the analysis of tiny, even microscopic bits of evidence from the
blasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're into the tedious task of looking for parts of cars,
trucks and other parts of the bombs and trying to determine what
happened,'' said Thomas Pickard, the director of the FBI's criminal
division. ``This is what the FBI does best, the painstaking
gathering of information that all comes together to make an
investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   FBI laboratory director Donald Kerr said that ``the evidence you
want most is part or closest to whatever explosive was used, and so
it's the small pieces that matter; it's the residues that matter.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bureau officials said that the FBI was making extraordinary
efforts to prevent evidence from the two bomb sites from
contaminating each other; evidence gathered from the sites will be
sent to Washington on separate planes and then stored at FBI
headquarters on different floors of the building. ``We're treating
them as separate incidents so as not to inadvertently come to the
wrong conclusions,'' Kerr said.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to speculate on the type of explosives used in the
two bombings. ``There clearly was substantial energy release'' from
the blasts, he said. ``But it could be a relatively small amount of
a high explosive or a larger amount of a mining explosive or the
like, and we don't want to speculate on that based on the effects
we observe on the ground until we can put it into a proper
context.''
</P>
<P>
   The bureau said that there are 215 bureau employees in Nairobi
and Dar es Salaam, Tanzania, and that the scene investigation _ the
gathering of rubble at the site and hundreds of interviews _ would
continue for four more weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law-enforcement officials said they were confident that
the terrorists would be captured. Pickard said he had been at the
White House on Wednesday to discuss the investigation, and ``the
president asked me if the FBI would be as successful as we were in
Oklahoma City, and I said, `Yes, sir.'''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI is working in teams with the Kenyan police, who have
detained five people for questioning, said Peter Mbuvi, the deputy
commissioner of Kenya's criminal investigations department. But
U.S. officials said the five were not considered prime suspects.
</P>
<P>
   One of the men detained was Anjum Javed, his family said
Thursday night. Javed is a Kenyan citizen of Pakistani descent. The
family said he had been arrested as he tried to rescue the wounded
at the site of the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Javed's neighbors in Pangani, a predominately Muslim
neighborhood, said the police had been harassing residents whom the
police think look like Arabs. Nearly 40 percent of Kenya's people
are Muslims of African, Arabian or Asian descent.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether one or more of the three bombers got away.
The security guards have given differing accounts as to whether the
driver and a passenger were still in the pickup truck when it
exploded, said their employer, William John Guidice, chief
executive officer of United International Investigative Services,
which provides the private security at U.S. embassies in Kenya and
12 other countries.
</P>
<P>
   The guards' accounts suggest that in carrying out the bombing in
Nairobi, the terrorists may not have been as sophisticated as the
overall plot, in which they managed to set off a second powerful
bomb, nearly simultaneously, at the U.S. Embassy in Tanzania more
than 300 miles away, killing 10.
</P>
<P>
   It has been assumed that the attackers in Nairobi wanted to
drive the explosives into the underground garage of the embassy.
Their initial stop at the front of the building suggests a lack of
meticulous planning, and allowed them to be seen by the guards in a
calm setting.
</P>
<P>
   Guidice said the guards had reported that the truck carrying the
explosives was a Mitsubishi Canter, a mini-pickup commonly used
around Nairobi for deliveries, and that it was first driven to the
gate into the parking lot at the front of the embassy on Moi
Avenue. The driver told the guard that he had a delivery for the
embassy. The parking lot is reserved for diplomatic cars, and
contrary to some earlier reports, the vehicle did not have
diplomatic plates, so the guards told the driver of the vehicle to
go around to the back.
</P>
<P>
   After being turned back, the pickup was driven down Moi Avenue,
made a U-turn, went around a traffic circle at the intersection
with Haile Selassie Avenue, made another U-turn and approached the
back of the embassy, Guidice said.
</P>
<P>
   A car coming out of the parking lot behind the embassy
inadvertently blocked the terrorists' path.
</P>
<P>
   The security guards, who were unarmed, saw a man jump out of the
back of the pickup, quickly pull three hand grenades out of one
pocket, and take a fourth out of another, Guidice said. The man
threw one grenade past Bwaku, who fled, calling for help on a
walkie-talkie.
</P>
<P>
   Just 20 seconds later, the vehicle exploded, realizing the worst
fears of diplomats who have served at the U.S. Embassy here in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Several of those diplomats said Thursday that fears of a
terrorist attack and other security concerns date back a decade at
the mission, but remained unresolved by Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problems were known,'' one of the diplomats said. ``Anyone
can drive to that spot at the back door,'' he added, referring to
where the bomb went off.
</P>
<P>
   Other State Department officials said concerns mounted in the
last three years, after the attacks on U.S. military bases in Saudi
Arabia in 1995 and 1996, which showed that even U.S. outposts in
friendly nations with stricter security procedures than Kenya's
were vulnerable to an attack.
</P>
<P>
   A diplomat who served here said that ``it takes a great deal of
will to get an embassy moved,'' as well as many millions of dollars
for the land, building, and security measures. He recalled
discussions about moving the embassy out of downtown Nairobi to a
leafy suburb where other foreign missions are situated.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not atypical of the way things work in the American
bureaucracy, unfortunately,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
