<HEADER>
A3332 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-FONG-1STLD-WRIT     08-13 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-FONG-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATT FONG: ONCE A CALIFORNIA LONG SHOT, NOW A REPUBLICAN STAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Sub 1st sentence of lede to present-tense Fong's position. No
other changes.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(js) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Less than three months ago, Matt Fong was little
known outside California, where he is state treasurer. Now,
Republican heavyweights like Newt Gingrich and Trent Lott regard
him as a new best friend.
</P>
<P>
   Since he narrowly won the Republican nomination in June to
oppose Sen. Barbara Boxer in the fall, Fong has pulled virtually
even with her in the polls, giving Republican leaders new reason to
believe they can gain five Senate seats for a filibuster-proof
majority of 60.
</P>
<P>
   It is an alarming predicament for a Democratic incumbent at a
time when the economy is strong and voter dissatisfaction is not
the overwhelming issue it was four years ago. Yet the most recent
statewide polls show that Boxer is in for a fight. In May, the
latest poll by the Field Institute, a nonpartisan organization,
showed that she held only a slim advantage over Fong, 47 percent to
43 percent, a statistical tie. In late July, a San Francisco
Examiner poll found Boxer leading by just 43 percent to 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barbara Boxer has the most partisan image of any elected
official in California,'' said Mark DiCamillo director of the Field
poll. ``At this stage, it's a yes-or-no vote on her.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the so-called ``year of the woman'' in Washington,
Boxer won a close race over Bruce Herschensohn, with 48 percent of
the vote. She has been consistently regarded as one of the most
liberal senators and, as such, has been a champion of abortion
rights and gun control. She is also a strong and steady supporter
of President Clinton, and her daughter, Nicole, is married to
Hillary Rodham Clinton's brother, Tony Rodham.
</P>
<P>
   Credentials like that and the possibility Clinton could be
damaged by the Monica Lewinsky matter have persuaded Republicans to
view Sen. Boxer as one of several Democratic incumbents who might
be especially vulnerable this year. They are also why Gingrich, the
House speaker, has traveled to California to appear with Fong, and
other ranking Republicans are scheduled to follow, including Lott,
the majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   But Fong, 44, a lawyer and former Air Force officer, is
predicting that after Labor Day, when Californians start focusing
on the fall elections, he will attract support for reasons beyond
Boxer's approval ratings.
</P>
<P>
   He, too, carries a well-known name in California politics, not
only as state treasurer since 1995, but as the son of March Fong
Eu, a Democrat who was elected five times over 24 years as
California's secretary of state. Her popularity could help Fong win
critical swing voters like Reagan Democrats who live outside the
traditional liberal strongholds of Los Angeles County and San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   She could also help him with Asian-Americans, who are about 5
percent of the electorate in California and tend to vote Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Fong would be the first Chinese-American in the Senate since
Hiram Fong, who is not related, represented Hawaii from 1959
through 1976, and the first Asian-American to represent California
since S.I. Hayakawa served one term through 1982.
</P>
<P>
   `'I'm not starting from scratch,'' Fong said in an interview,
alluding to his mother.. ``The Fong name has been on the state
ballot since 1974, so it's not a new brand name. It's no different
than if someone passes down a family drugstore that had a
reputation for integrity. My mother had the same reputation for her
integrity in public service.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The election in which Fong won the Republican nomination was
California's first open primary, and Asian-American voters played
an important role in his slim victory, 22 percent to 20 percent,
over Darrell Issa, a wealthy businessman. A poll of voters in San
Francisco found that 90 percent of Asian-Americans voted for a
Democrat in the gubernatorial primary and almost as many also voted
for Fong.
</P>
<P>
   Claudine Cheng, a former vice chairman of the San Francisco
Democratic Committee, referred to a ``hostile, anti-Asian political
environment,'' arising from the indictments of several
Asian-Americans on charges of campaign finance violations. She said
of the city's Asian-Americans: ``Most people are inclined to help
Matt Fong. It's important to see one of our own do well.''
</P>
<P>
   Fong is counting on his expertise as a fiscal manager, his
strong support for the military and his conservative social views
to convince voters that the values he holds are closer to the
mainstream than those held by Boxer, whom he describes as a
political extremist.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer points to Fong's opposition to gun control, campaign
finance reform and laws that protect the environment to
characterize him as the out-of-touch extremist.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest threat I face is not Matt Fong; it is but voter
apathy,'' she said Thursday, predicting that a higher turnout would
help her. ``I said even before I knew who my opponent would be that
this was going to be a race decided by two to five points. That's
the way it always is in California; the state is pretty much evenly
divided along party lines. But I think the more I'm compared to him
on the issues, the better I'll do.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Fong's strategy is to plow ahead with what he calls
a common-sense approach to issues, particularly those involving
budgets and economics. He said that his fiscal skills, honed by
managing the state investment portfolio of $32 billion, would serve
the nation well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every morning, I move anywhere from $200 million to $2
billion,'' he said of his job as treasurer. ``You take a look at
the challenges facing the country in the short and medium term,
like Medicaid and tax reform. As the chief financial officer of the
seventh-largest economy in the world, I have a far different
perspective than my opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   Among his highest priorities, Fong includes increased spending
on the military, a flat income tax and a closer balance between
environmental and economic policy.
</P>
<P>
   Conceding that voters are not yet focusing on key issues, he
said he could encounter problems when they do. Unlike Boxer, 57, a
native of Brooklyn who moved to California in 1965, he is not
particularly animated on the stump. On a recent night, walking the
grounds of the Stanislaus County Fair in Turlock, Calif., he seldom
stopped to greet voters or engage them in conversation. Delivering
speeches or talking casually, he sounds more rehearsed than
spontaneous.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign aides say he will loosen up soon and flash the
personable side that they say they see all the time. But for now,
Fong does not seem bothered by any stylistic concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as my wife thinks I have charisma, I'm OK,'' he said.
``I just want voters to think I'm competent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
