<HEADLINE>
IT'S ALL GOOD FOR SERENA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE STEVENS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANHATTAN BEACH _ Though it appears that two Williams sisters
are on the women's pro tennis tour, there actually are three:
Venus, Good Serena and Bad Serena.
</P>
<P>
   Good Serena Williams showed up on Thursday in the Acura Classic
at Manhattan Country Club and beat seventh-seeded Sandrine Testud
6-4, 3-6, 6-1. The match could have been a sign that Serena
Williams' split personality, or inconsistency, is gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bad Serena has been eradicated,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Signs of Bad Serena showed up in the second set, when Williams
trailed 4-1. But she fought back and did not go lightly. Testud had
13 set points before she finally won the second set.
</P>
<P>
   Serena Williams takes on top-ranked and top-seeded Martina
Hingis in the quarterfinals. Williams, ranked 21st, is in her first
tournament in six weeks and appears stronger and steadier than when
she played last. So does she have a shot at winning?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think so,'' Williams said. ``It depends on which Serena
shows up.''
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen-ranked Testud thinks so, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``She thinks she can beat anyone, so it makes it even harder to
beat her,'' Testud said.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis' take: Even before Williams beat Testud, Martina Hingis
pondered the possibility of playing her. In a simple way, Hingis
pointed out that the 16-year-old appears to have a stronger upper
body than a month ago. She said, ``I saw Serena play Tuesday night,
and she's a big girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucky loser wins again: Elena Tatarkova, who earned a spot in
the tournament when Mary Pierce withdrew, advanced to the
quarterfinals with a win over sixth-seeded Irina Spirlea 6-2, 6-2.
Tatarkova, ranked 63rd, will face third-seeded Arantxa Sanchez
Vicario in the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   Doubles update: Two doubles teams, Hingis with Natasha Zvereva
and Chanda Rubin with Spirlea, have advanced to the semifinals. Two
quarterfinal matches will be played today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
