u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTHCARE-SUIT-1STLD     08-13 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTHCARE-SUIT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT BACKS PROTECTIONS FOR MEDICARE PATIENTS DENIED BY HMOS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for general rewrite starting in 4th graf; in final graf,
corrects first judge mentioned from Marquez to Wiggins)  (mk) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal appeals court has ruled that Medicare
patients are entitled to immediate hearings and other protections
when they are denied care by health maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
   In ruling on a nationwide class action suit, the court said many
HMOs had failed to provide adequate explanations for the denial of
benefits and had failed to inform patients of their appeal rights.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, issued on Wednesday by the 9th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals, in San Francisco, was a major victory for consumers.
The lawsuit was filed in Arizona on behalf of nearly 6 million
Medicare patients in HMOs around the country. The opinion, for a
unanimous three-judge panel, was written by Judge Charles Wiggins,
a former Republican congressman from California.
</P>
<P>
   For the last seven months, Congress has debated whether to
guarantee similar rights for more than 150 million Americans with
private health insurance. The White House has denounced Republicans
and HMOs for resisting President Clinton's demand for a ``patient's
bill of rights'' with such guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton used executive orders to provide appeal rights to people
covered by Medicare, Medicaid and veterans' health programs.
</P>
<P>
   But the court's ruling sets more stringent standards, requiring
more information for Medicare beneficiaries and setting tighter
deadlines for decisions on appeals.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court said that in running the Medicare HMO program,
federal officials had not lived up to their duty to guarantee ``due
process of law,'' as required by the Fifth Amendment to the
Constitution. Indeed, it said, Medicare officials have failed to
enforce their own rules and have improperly renewed contracts with
HMOs that violated the rules.
</P>
<P>
   Wiggins said Medicare beneficiaries were entitled to due process
because the HMO decisions amount to ``government action.'' HMOs are
private corporations, but when they deny services to Medicare
beneficiaries they act ``as a governmental proxy'' and they are
``federal actors,'' the court said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government cannot avoid the due process requirements of
the Constitution merely by delegating its duty to determine
Medicare coverage to private entities,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   Other courts have reached similar conclusions in cases involving
Medicaid, the federal-state health care program for poor people.
</P>
<P>
   The decision on Medicare is significant because it holds that
beneficiaries have rights that are rooted in the Constitution, not
merely in statutes or regulations subject to change by Congress and
the president. The number of beneficiaries in HMOs is rising
rapidly and is expected to reach 10 million, or 25 percent of the
Medicare population, by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   While the administration has supported appeal rights for
patients, it argued in court that HMOs were private entities and
that the government should not be held responsible for their
decisions involving Medicare. It also objected to having a court
dictate the program's details.
</P>
<P>
   ``We absolutely believe in a strong, independent appeals
process, and we have taken steps to strengthen the appeal rights of
Medicare beneficiaries,'' Melissa Skolfield, a spokeswoman for the
Department of Health and Human Services, said Thursday. ``But we
have concern about the judge's finding that private HMOs should be
treated as if they were the government.''
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs filed suit in 1993 and won a ruling from the U.S.
District Court in Tucson, Ariz., in October 1996. The secretary of
Health and Human Services, Donna Shalala, then appealed, saying the
judge, Alfredo Marquez, had usurped her authority and gone further
than necessary in protecting patients' rights.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``The decisions of the HMOs are not government action,'' Shalala
said in court papers.
</P>
<P>
   Sally Hart, a lawyer at the Center for Medicare Advocacy who
represented patients in the Arizona case, said: ``The government is
speaking publicly as if it had an obligation to protect the rights
of Medicare beneficiaries in HMOs. But in court, it took the
position that it had no legal obligation to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   The government issued rules to define Medicare appeal rights in
April 1997, and Congress adopted similar requirements last August.
But Ms. Hart said, ``Many beneficiaries are still not receiving
written notice when services are denied.''
</P>
<P>
   The appellate court said that ``the appeal rights and other
procedural protections available to Medicare beneficiaries are
meaningless'' if patients do not receive such notices.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Ignagni, president of the American Association of Health
Plans, a trade group for HMOs, said: ``We were comfortable with the
Medicare rules issued in 1997. They made important changes that
responded to beneficiaries' concerns. We want to study the court's
decision to compare it with those rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Gottlich, a lawyer at the National Senior Citizens Law
Center, said: ``This ruling will provide new protection to Medicare
beneficiaries. It goes much further than current federal rules in
requiring HMOs to explain what additional evidence you need to
support your claim, and how to get that evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The court set tighter deadlines, too. Federal rules say that an
HMO must ordinarily rule in 14 days on a request for services from
a Medicare patient. The court allows just five days.
</P>
<P>
   Marquez had issued a detailed order specifying how Medicare
officials should protect patients' rights, and the appeals court
upheld that order, over objections by the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   When an HMO denies or terminates a service it must issue a
notice of appeal rights, written ``in at least 12-point type'' that
will be readable by older people, Marquez said. He found that HMO
notices ``were often illegible'' and ``failed to specify the reason
for the denial.''
</P>
<P>
   In urging the appeals court not to expand patients' rights, the
Clinton administration said, ``A beneficiary denied service by an
HMO can obtain such services outside the plan and then seek
reimbursement for their cost.'' The court rejected that argument,
saying it was ``of little comfort to an elderly poor patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Marquez also told Shalala to ``monitor and investigate the
compliance of HMOs'' with the requirement for hearings. If she
finds that a plan did not comply, he said, she ``is prohibited from
renewing or entering into a subsequent Medicare contract with the
HMO.''
</P>
<P>
   The secretary objected to this part of the judge's order, saying
she should not have to impose such drastic penalties. But the
appeals court said the penalties were required by the Medicare law.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Judge Wiggins, the other members of the three-judge
panel were Judges Herbert Choy and Mary Schroeder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
