<HEADER>
A3348 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-LADN     08-13 1354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES BELIEVE THEIR WAY IS RIGHT WAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC NOLAND  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ In the current baseball climate, championship
rewards often fall to the short-sighted _ clubs which flame
brightly in one wild, reckless stab at a World Series title.
</P>
<P>
   If this causes the farm system to go deeply into hock and the
cash reserves to tap out. Well, it was fun while it lasted. If the
team's fortunes crash soon after, there is always the prospect of
building up from the rubble.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Braves have taken a longer view _ and it could be
argued their title achievements have suffered for it.
</P>
<P>
   This team, built patiently and soundly around an incomparable
staff of starting pitchers, has become the most formidable. . . uh,
regular-season team in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta has reached the playoffs the past six years (in which
they've been held) and has but one World Series championship _
accomplished in 1995 _ to show for all that impressive staying
power. Minnesota. Toronto. Philadelphia. Florida. They all won
titles or pennants in the '90s at the Braves' expense then fell on
hard times soon after.
</P>
<P>
   Are the Braves meticulously trained for the marathon. . . but
vulnerable in the best-of-seven sprint?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the environment in which we live and operate,'' general
manager John Schuerholz said this week as the Braves, on a 107-win
pace, prepared for a weekend series with the Dodgers, their only
visit of the season to Los Angeles. ``With the format that is in
place _ a short-series playoff _ at any given time, one team, no
matter whether they are judged to have better talent or more talent
or be the better team, might be playing better than the team that
is more talented.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to prepare ourselves as best we can, and also keep our
fingers crossed that we're healthy. If not, that (falling short of
the pinnacle) is always a possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're hot, you're going to win,'' said manager Bobby Cox,
putting it a bit more simply. ``And if you're not, you're going to
go home. We've played great (in the regular season). It's a
crapshoot once you get into it.''
</P>
<P>
   And now, as they close in on yet another division title, a
bitter irony confronts these Braves.
</P>
<P>
   This past offseason, they made all the correct moves to address
the elements that can make a difference in a playoff season.
Right-left offensive balance? Andres Galarraga, a power-hitting
right-handed first baseman, was brought in to replace lefty Fred
McGriff. Defense? Walt Weiss was signed to replace Jeff Blauser at
shortstop, while the dazzling Andruw Jones supplanted Kenny Lofton
in center.
</P>
<P>
   But at the instant all of this began to settle into place, the
Braves were dealt a cruel dose of fate: Mark Wohlers, one of the
most overpowering closers in the game, suddenly went wiggo on the
mound, endangering subterranean creatures and low-flying fowl with
his errant fastballs.
</P>
<P>
   He currently is trying to work out his troubles in Triple-A, but
even Cox admits, ``Time's running out. We've got to set a (playoff)
roster (by the end of August).''
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of Wohlers, the Braves' bullpen is a menagerie.
Its characters have performed admirably during the season but could
fray nerves _ and create an even greater burden for starters Greg
Maddux, Tom Glavine and John Smoltz _ in the intense heat of the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Closer Kerry Ligtenberg, who has 18 saves in 20 chances, is a
former strike-replacement player for Seattle whom the Braves found
pitching in Minnesota's independent Prairie League.
</P>
<P>
   Right-handed setup man Rudy Seanez might be familiar to Dodgers
fans _ L.A. was one of four teams to release him in the past five
years. But he has flourished in Atlanta, compiling a 4-0 record,
1.96 ERA and 29 strikeouts in 23 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Also down there? Lefty John Rocker, a converted starter; Dennis
Martinez, all 43 years of him; Norm Charlton, whose nastiness these
days is confined strictly to his ERA (6.94 with Baltimore until his
release last month); and Adam Butler, a chubby lefty with an obese
ERA (19.29), who is filling in for injured ex-Angel Russ Springer.
</P>
<P>
   At mid-summer, as Houston traded for Randy Johnson and San Diego
picked up Randy Myers, and even the thin-hope Dodgers grabbed Jeff
Shaw, Atlanta stood pat. No panic moves that forfeited future
talent or upended the operating budget. No mad grasping for that
one missing cog.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe there is a farther-reaching wisdom to the strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Braves broadcaster Don Sutton, the former Dodgers pitcher who
was inducted into the Hall of Fame this summer, said he believes a
team's merit should be measured over the long term, over a period
of years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you beat the Braves in a World Series, that doesn't make
you the best ballclub, it makes you the best ballclub for that
week,'' he said. ``Sure, everybody wants to be a world champion.
That's why you want to go there. But the other (teams) that have
come and gone? A lot of it is philosophy. You take one shot. You
say, `I need to do this. I need to rent a player.' But then where
do you go?
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Braves are doing is what I saw when I was in L.A. in
the '70s. Your minor leagues exist to build winners in the major
leagues. The Braves build their nucleus from within and fill (with
free agents) from without.''
</P>
<P>
   The filler in this year's bullpen, however, has raised a few
eyebrows, and these pitchers aren't oblivious to the skepticism.
Absent a miraculous recovery by Wohlers, will this bullpen will be
Atlanta's Achilles' heel as the playoffs approach?
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah, we've heard that for 8{ years,'' said pitching coach Leo
Mazzone. ``If you put our bullpen behind ordinary starting staffs,
you'd say, `They're pretty good.' But they have to follow such a
high standard of excellence, any little slip-up and all of a
sudden, `Whoom!' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone takes it personally,'' said Seanez.
``Everyone just takes it upon themselves to do their part.''
</P>
<P>
   Seanez then contemplated his three-year stay in the Dodgers
organization and picked his words carefully: ``It's good to be
somewhere where everybody just concentrates on doing their one job
and doesn't worry what the other guy does or says. Everyone gets
along here. Chemistry, I guess you could call it.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere on the roster, the Braves exult in what is perceived
to be better balance and overall strength.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, they were beaten twice by Kevin Brown in the National
League Championship Series against Florida. Now Brown is with
another strong contender, San Diego. Meanwhile, Houston's deadline
trade two weeks ago raised the very real specter of Johnson working
twice in a seven-game series.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta vows to be ready. Galarraga has obliterated the notion
that his past numbers in Colorado were inflated by so much thin
air. He is batting .300, with 36 home runs and 94 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   It has provided a nice complement to Chipper Jones (a switch
hitter who wields much more power from the left side) and Ryan
Klesko.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be,'' said Maddux, ``you pretty much just threw any
lefty (pitcher) out there and they had a chance. Now, it'd better
be a good one.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel really positive,'' added Galarraga. ``The unit we've
been playing has been pulling everything together _ defense,
offense, pitching. . . We've got a good chance. We're looking to
the playoffs. I hope to win everything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another good team, that's what it is,'' said Cox, who is
much more familiar with this terrain. ``Whether or not we're any
better, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers could well determine that. Or that Ligtenberg guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``A source of great pride for us,'' said Schuerholz, ``is the
consistency of our success in this day and age and this
environment, where teams win and then fall, teams win and are
disbanded, teams win and, because of their rosters, off-load guys.
We've been able to make a lot of changes and still be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   They'd like to think all of this sensible diligence will be
worthy of a further reward.
</P>
<P>
   Come October.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-98 2334EDT &QL; 
