u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-GENOVESI-POLITICS-     08-13 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GENOVESI-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GATHERING OF OLD-SCHOOL POLITICIANS MOURNS A MASTER OF THE CRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Their stories recalled long-forgotten eras of this
city's political history, peppered with reminiscences of
neighborhood campaigns in Brooklyn that even years ago had become
the stuff of footnotes. Their common thread was the man who had
either engineered the campaigns or produced strategies to derail
them.
</P>
<P>
   For the two dozen or so former politicians and city officials
who gathered at the Park Plaza restaurant in downtown Brooklyn on
Thursday. It was the regular Thursday morning breakfast that had
been convened for nearly 20 years by Assemblyman Anthony Genovesi.
But this breakfast came three days after Genovesi was killed in an
auto accident on a rainy highway in Dutchess County, at age 61.
</P>
<P>
   It was part wake, part celebration and partly a look into how a
political technician handled the nitty-gritty of politics on the
streets of Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   There was Frank Macchiarola, the president of St. Francis
College in Brooklyn and a former city schools chancellor,
reminiscing about Genovesi as a gruff-talking architect of politics
who used the breakfasts to argue about the issues of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Seated nearby was Anthony Gliedman, a former official with the
Trump Organization whose prior career in government stretched back
to the Lindsay administration. On the other side of the table was
Peter Piscitelli, a lobbyist who was a senior aide in the
administration of Mayor Ed Koch.
</P>
<P>
   The weekly breakfasts where Genovesi held court had moved over
the years, from the old Woerner's restaurant to Junior's to
Thursday's location, a bright, airy coffee shop at Cadman Plaza,
where the late assemblyman, many recalled, typically ate a hearty
breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what we're going to argue about,'' said
Macchiarola, a close friend of Genovesi's. ``But he would want us
to continue, and to continue arguing.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there were none of the friendly arguments that were a
staple of the breakfasts. Instead, they took turns discussing the
role played by Genovesi, the heir to the leadership of the
Canarsie-based political club once ruled by the Brooklyn Democratic
boss Meade Esposito. They recalled his role in support of school
integration in Canarsie in the late 1960s. And they recalled his
role in making _ or breaking _ the candidacies of people whose
names are in the lore of New York City politics: Sebastian Leone,
Ed Koch, Stanley Steingut and Leonard Yoswein.
</P>
<P>
   They discussed his legendary antipathy toward being interviewed,
how he would do everything at the Thomas Jefferson Democratic Club
in Canarsie, from mopping floors to editing campaign literature and
micro-managing campaign expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly, they each attributed to Genovesi a single quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a man of absolute integrity,'' Piscitelli said. Another
participant spoke of the time when Genovesi, struggling with his
law practice, was offered the college tuition costs for his five
children if he managed a politician's campaign. They recalled that
he had already given his word to support a rival candidate and
refused the offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was gruff, but he was Brooklyn,'' said George Arzt, a
public relations consultant and former spokesman for Koch who had
worked with Genovesi. ``He was as scrappy as the old Brooklyn
Dodgers. He knew the politics of the neighborhoods like the back of
his hands. We won't see another like him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
