<HEADER>
A3360 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WELFARE-FRAUD-SCAM-LA     08-13 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELFARE-FRAUD-SCAM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSIVE WELFARE FRAUD SCAM   USED NONEXISTENT KIDS TO COLLECT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BETH BARRETT and PETER HARTLAUB  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- A welfare caseworker orchestrated the biggest
benefits scam in Los Angeles County history by arranging about
$700,000 in payments for ineligible or nonexistent children,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said Thursday that they expect the case eventually
to include as many as 15 people in Los Angeles and San Bernardino
counties, with search warrants issued at nine locations.
</P>
<P>
   At least 25 fraudulent welfare cases are believed to be
involved, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The caseworker, Jennifer Castillo, 41, of suburban Van Nuys, has
pleaded not guilty to five felony counts, including embezzlement,
aid by misrepresentation, public officer crime and two counts of
forgery, according to court records. She is in custody and bail has
been set at $565,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's huge,'' said George Mueller, supervising investigator in
the District Attorney's Office. ``I think internally, it's the
largest case ever involving one employee. But we're looking at all
the angles.''
</P>
<P>
   Castillo's attorney said she does not have a criminal record.
</P>
<P>
   ``She appears to be a decent person with no prior criminal
history,'' said Sherman Oaks criminal attorney Michael Goldstein.
</P>
<P>
   Castillo worked in the Aid to Families With Dependent Children
division of the county Department of Public Social Services' West
Valley District office in suburban Canoga Park. She had worked for
the department for seven years.
</P>
<P>
   The case broke after investigators with the department got an
anonymous tip in March, according to a case history detailed in a
search warrant filed by a District Attorney's Office investigator.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators found that Castillo's sister, Corrine Young, had
received welfare benefits on and off since 1987, according to the
search warrant. Investigators found 10 children listed in the Young
file, only one of whom could be verified with a birth certificate
or Social Security number.
</P>
<P>
   There were biological impossibilities, too: Department of Public
Social Services records showed that two of Young's ``children''
were born only five days apart. Another pair were born six months
apart.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators found Castillo had at least 15 more welfare cases
like Young's -- all involving large families with no verification
that some or all of the children even existed.
</P>
<P>
   Mueller said it is not known for sure whether Castillo worked
alone or with other county employees. She is accused in court
records of submitting false claims, forging her supervisor's
signature and failing to disclose that she was handling her
sister's case.
</P>
<P>
   Castillo used her access to case files to create phony cases so
that a ring of people could collect benefits fraudulently under the
AFDC and food-stamp programs, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   The catch: The children named in the cases either were not
eligible for benefits or were fictional characters made up using
fake birth dates, Social Security numbers and other identifying
information, Mueller said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For example, only the adult existed, but he would get money
for eight -- and the seven others didn't exist,'' he said. ``Or
maybe you would have one or two kids, but you'd be getting aid for
eight kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators believe the scam involved many layers of
fabrication, crossing state and international jurisdictions.
</P>
<P>
   The ``parents'' of the nonexistent children in some cases are
believed to have used phony identification, taking the identities
of relatives living out of state or out of the country, Mueller
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be like a person impersonating their brother to get a
driver's license in their brother's name, and then using that
identification to cash the (welfare) check,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Those who cashed the checks lived in Los Angeles and San
Bernardino counties, he said. They included people from the L.A.
suburbs of North Hollywood, Van Nuys, Reseda and Highland Park.
</P>
<P>
   Court records show Castillo had files for several clients with
her own last name.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein said Castillo emigrated from Belize in Central America
about 24 years ago, is a U.S. citizen and has a large family.
</P>
<P>
   On June 23, investigators searched Castillo's and Young's
apartments, located within a few blocks of each other in Van Nuys.
Court records show investigators turned up identification and
welfare records with names that matched the illegal accounts
Castillo is accused of setting up in department files.
</P>
<P>
   While no additional arrests have been made so far, interviews
with some people have resulted in confessions of receiving money
illegally, Mueller said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were made free and voluntarily,'' he said. ``Some people
feel real bad about this. They have a conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   The county is working to recover some of the money, Mueller
added.
</P>
<P>
   Department of Public Social Services Director Lynn Bayer said a
variety of methods were used to conceal the fraud, but
investigators were able to reconstruct records.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was clever, but not clever enough, and the district
attorney has considerable hard evidence against her,'' Bayer said.
</P>
<P>
   State and county investigators also are examining how the
alleged fraud could have gone unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   Bayer said a new, more sophisticated fraud-detection system will
be implemented next year.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators allege in court records that Castillo quit the
department June 17, shortly after learning that she was the subject
of an internal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   A preliminary hearing for Castillo is scheduled Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
