<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ILL-BOYS-KILLING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE RULES BOYS HELD IN GIRL'S DEATH MAY GO HOME TO AWAIT TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 BY ANDREW BLUTH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ A judge on Thursday ruled that two boys, ages 7 and 8,
who are charged with brutally killing an 11-year-old girl for her
bicycle can return home to await trial, but must wear electronic
monitoring devices and stay inside 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, Gerald Winiecki of juvenile court, said he had no
alternative since Illinois law prohibits defendants younger than 10
from being housed in a locked building. Since their arrest on
Sunday, the boys have been kept in a psychiatric hospital, which
the court ruled was a locked unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the seriousness of these charges,'' Winiecki said in
his ruling, ``it is my belief the boys cannot be locked up.''
</P>
<P>
   The boys' lawyers had agreed to keep the boys at the hospital
until psychological tests could be completed.
</P>
<P>
   In a hearing Thursday, Winiecki heard testimony from two
court-appointed psychologists who evaluated the boys on Wednesday
to determine whether they would be a threat to themselves or
society if released. Both psychologists recommended that the boys
be reunited with their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``All things being equal, I think he would be best off with his
mother and father,'' said Dr. James Kraus, who evaluated the
younger boy.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors objected to the boys' release, saying that the
psychologists did not have adequate time or information to make an
informed assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is just too important to rush to a judgment like
this,'' argued Patty Sudendorf, an assistant state attorney,
fighting back tears. ``It is a mockery to say that these two
children are not a danger to others.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts in juvenile justice say they know of no case in which
younger children have been prosecuted for murder in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The girl, 11-year-old Ryan Harris, was killed on July 27. The
boys are accused of knocking her unconscious with a rock, molesting
her and then suffocating her by stuffing her underwear in her mouth
and shoving leaves and debris up her nose.
</P>
<P>
   R. Eugene Pimcham, a former judge and mayoral candidate who is
representing the older boy, disputed the charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way these little boys have the physical strength
to have committed this murder,'' Pimcham said.
</P>
<P>
   During the hearing, Pimcham walked the boy to the center of the
courtroom and placed him on a scale, hoping to illustrate he was
not a threat to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't take a rocket scientist to figure a 4-foot 2-inch
boy couldn't have hurt anyone,'' Pimcham said outside the
courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   As they did at a hearing on Monday, the boys sat, legs dangling,
at the defense table occupied by coloring books and toys.
</P>
<P>
   During breaks, they hugged family members and showed off
pictures they had drawn. Immediately following the hearing they
were fitted with specially made ankle bracelets which they will
wear at all times.
</P>
<P>
   The older boy went home Thursday night, but the younger was
taken to an undisclosed location.
</P>
<P>
   Any youth convicted in juvenile court can only be held until age
21.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
