<SLUG> BC-EDIT-YANKEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL NOTEBOOK: JUST ANOTHER NIGHT AT THE STADIUM 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By VERLYN KLINKENBORG  
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beyond the right-field bleachers at Yankee Stadium, there is a
gap high in the outer wall. From most seats, through that gap you
can see the No. 4 train passing on elevated tracks. No one needs to
be reminded where he is when he's sitting in Yankee Stadium, but
when the No. 4 train passes, the sense of place is suddenly made
keener.
</P>
<P>
   It works the other way round, too. For several years I rode the
No. 4 train into Manhattan from a neighborhood near the Mosholu
Parkway, across the broken rooflines and ailanthus woodlots of the
Bronx. At 161st Street, just before the train went underground, I
always found myself, like other passengers, looking for that gap in
the stadium wall. Through it we could see a flicker of green grass
and the unmistakable blue of the stadium seats, a blue that would
be called ``cerulean'' if the sky were made of plastic.
</P>
<P>
   But now it's a night game against Minnesota _ Wells is pitching
and will win a four-hitter, 7-0 _ and the sky is blotted out by
thunderheads that refuse to take shape. The warmth of a steamy day
is trapped under the low ceiling above the main boxes and will not
dissipate. Now and then a weak breeze stirs with about as much
overall effect as a bunt rolling foul down the third-base line.
Somehow it seems remarkable when a Minnesota batter steps up to the
plate just as the scoreboard clock says 7:35, the scheduled
starting time. During all the apparent randomness near the dugouts
_ the interviews and the stretching of first basemen's legs and the
presenting of charitable donations in the form of beach-towel-size
checks _ someone has been keeping an eye on the time.
</P>
<P>
   But not in the stands. Fans seem to run in rivulets all around
the stadium, making their way to their seats or to the cavernous
outer passageways. For the young girl behind me, time is measured
by Derek Jeter's appearances at the plate. She carries a homemade
sign that says ``Nothing is sweeter than Derek Jeter,'' and she has
just told her mom that what the stadium really needs is a
heinie-cam. Like clockwork, her father bellows ``Go Boomer'' _
Wells' nickname _ in a voice that ruffles the hair of men and women
three rows away. The seal-bark of the vendors echoes through the
humid air.
</P>
<P>
   On the field the umpire gestures mutely after the catcher's
silent reception of each pitch. Planes from La Guardia pass quietly
overhead. The No. 4 train steals past. Sometimes the crowd roars _
O'Neill hits a two-run homer _ but when it doesn't roar it murmurs,
suppressing any audible evidence of a world other than the one
defined by the stadium lights. Wells forecloses on the Twins, and
the unbelievable season everyone hopes will never end is one game
shorter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
