<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-SIDEBAR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASE FAR FROM CLOSED ON BRAVES' BULLPEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC NOLAND  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Closer Mark Wohlers was still capable of knocking
down a wall with his fastball _ just not the one he was aiming at.
So, as baseball's summer swap meet opened for business, it appeared
the Atlanta Braves were one piece short of championship caliber.
</P>
<P>
   They did nothing, however.
</P>
<P>
   According to general manager John Schuerholz, only one
top-flight closer was available, Cincinnati's Jeff Shaw. The
Dodgers got to him first _ at a price widely considered
confiscatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite candidly, based on the players they (the Reds) were
asking for _ and got _ as much as we may have wanted somebody of
that caliber, obviously we determined that was too high an asking
price for us,'' Schuerholz said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, in the July 4 deal, parted with the two brightest
prospects in their system, Paul Konerko and Dennis Reyes.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later, San Diego acquired closer Randy Myers from
Toronto in a waiver deal, ostensibly because the Padres feared the
Braves would claim him. Atlanta reportedly put in no such waiver
claim, although Schuerholz wouldn't comment on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The decisions not to leap could haunt the Braves this
postseason, particularly if Wohlers can't right himself or if
unlikely stand-in Kerry Ligtenberg falters. But Atlanta figures to
be the winner in the long term.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, in deals Cincinnati and Montreal, picked clean
their farm system and potentially their future while San Diego is
in danger of throwing its operating budget crazily out of whack.
</P>
<P>
   Myers, who will earn just over $1 million with the Padres the
rest of 1998, is down for a guaranteed $12 million over the next
two seasons. Unless San Diego is able to move him, that could put a
crimp in efforts to re-sign such key figures as Kevin Brown, Ken
Caminiti, Steve Finley and Wally Joyner. All of their contracts are
up this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
