u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-PGA-LEDE-HNS &LR;      08-13 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-LEDE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Woods sets pace with course-record 66
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JAYNE CUSTRED &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
REDMOND, Wash. _ At first glance, it wouldn't appear that Sahalee
Country Club is Tiger Woods' kind of golf course.
</P>
<P>
   The layout is too short for Woods to pull his legendary driver
out of the bag very often, and there are only two par-5s on the
entire course.
</P>
<P>
   But look a little closer, and it becomes easy to see why Woods
set the course record at Sahalee on Thursday with a 4-under-par 66,
and why he has a two-stroke lead in the 1998 PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``My length is definitely a huge advantage on this golf course
because I'm able to hit 2-irons and 3-woods where guys are
sometimes having to hit driver,'' Woods said. ``And I've always
been a pretty good long-iron player. I feel very comfortable
hitting 2-irons and 3-irons off the tees. I had a game plan today,
and I did stick to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sahalee was there for the taking Thursday, but the course
managed to hold its own against the best players in the world
despite near-perfect conditions. Trailing Woods at the end of the
day was a group of eight players at 2-under 68, including Paul
Azinger, Bill Glasson and Glen Day. Houston's Steve Elkington and
Mark O'Meara headed a group of 11 at 69.
</P>
<P>
   Others struggled with the tree-lined fairways. David Duval, one
of the pre-tournament favorites, started the back side with a
triple bogey and finished at 76, while a disappointed Fred Couples
quickly left his hometown course after a 74.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara's solid opening round kept him in position to win his
third major championship of the year, a feat that hasn't been
accomplished since Ben Hogan won three in 1953. Despite being
pleased with his efforts, O'Meara said the man at the top of the
leader board had the round everyone wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw on the leader board that Tiger shot 4-under and had a
super round,'' O'Meara said. ``But I expected him to play well. He
was swinging well in the practice rounds.''
</P>
<P>
   And putting well, too, thanks to O'Meara. Woods finished his
round with 27 putts, including four of 15 feet or longer for
birdie. He is using the Ping Anser 2 putter that he ``borrowed''
from O'Meara's garage before the British Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one I stole,'' Woods corrected. ``It's something that I
just like the look of.''
</P>
<P>
   It also was one of the keys to his round Thursday, which Wood
found especially satisfying since it was one of the things missing
in his game earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's the reason why I've been finishing in the top
fours and not really getting the victory,'' Woods said. ``I can say
as a whole I feel so much more comfortable over the ball. I can't
really explain why. Putting comes in cycles. You have to ride it
when you have the highs and try to get out of the slumps as quickly
as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've worked on my putting pretty hard and just tried to get
the flow back in my stroke, just feel comfortable setting up over
the ball. I haven't really felt comfortable setting up over the
ball in a while. And if you don't feel comfortable, you're not
going to make a very good stroke.''
</P>
<P>
   His comfort zone was quite evident Thursday. After opening the
day with a bogey, Woods came back with a great birdie on the second
hole after narrowly missing the water on his second shot. He then
sank an 18-foot putt to save par on No. 3 and was off and running.
</P>
<P>
   Woods sank a 15-footer for birdie on No. 5, added an 18-foot
birdie putt at No. 7 and made the turn at 1-under. On the back
side, he sank birdie putts of six feet, four feet, 18 feet and
finally 30 feet on the 17th hole to break the course record at
Sahalee. The old mark of 67 was set by Jack Nicklaus in an
exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger had a wonderful round,'' said playing partner Jeff
Sluman, who shot 71. ``He made some key putts when he needed, and
that is the difference between his round and Nick (Price)'s and
mine. He made five or six putts of 15 feet or better. That is what
you're supposed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Others tried to keep pace. Billy Andrade made birdies on the
first four holes to get to 4-under early in the day, but he never
really recovered from a double bogey at No. 6 and finished with a
68. Day, who has had a fine season so far, was the only player in
the field to get to 5-under. Day had a front-nine 31 and then
birdied the 11th hole to move five strokes under par. But Day made
double bogey on No. 15 and bogey on No. 18 and closed at 2-under.
</P>
<P>
   That left Woods alone in the lead and hoping this final major of
the year will have his name on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been right there in the majors,'' he said. ``I had a
chance at the Masters going into Sunday and didn't quite fire a low
enough round. Had a really good shot at the British Open and came
up one shot short of a playoff. So I've been pretty close to
putting it all together and being in the hunt where I could
legitimately win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about getting the right breaks at the right time. So
overall, I'm very pleased with the way I've played.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, no one in the field was ready to concede this
championship, and Woods knows that beginning today, he is the man
everyone will be chasing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, I tried to go out and play a good, solid round,'' he
said. ``And tomorrow, the same thing. I just try to give myself a
chance going into Sunday. And if I'm there, hopefully I'll win. But
I'm not going to put any more pressure on myself, because I am in
the lead right now. With three days to go, it's an eternity. Three
rounds is a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I need to go out there and hold my own for three more
days.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
