r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEANIE-BABIES-BOOSTED     08-13 0434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEANIE-BABIES-BOOSTED-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZEN BEANIE BABY BANDIT BAGS BEST OF BUNCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSE HIESTAND  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- A gunman wearing a ski mask burst into a gift and
novelty shop, ordered seven people to the floor and demanded . . .
Beanie Babies.
</P>
<P>
   He passed up the cash register, ignored the least-collectible
Beanies and fled with 42 of the rarest, worth a total of about
$5,000, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Even seasoned detectives were amazed by the robber's unusual
booty during the 9 a.m. robbery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard of some weird things over the years, but the Beanie
Babies was a good one,'' said Los Angeles police Sgt. Roy VanDuyne
of the suburban Van Nuys Division. ``I had no idea how expensive
they were.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it was the first such heist in the division, and
perhaps the entire city, a wave of Beanie Baby robbers has hit this
year from Maryland to Santa Ana.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, crooks encouraged by Beanie Baby-mania have
targeted the most valued Beanies, some of which sell for hundreds
of dollars apiece. Newer models of the toys, made by Ty Inc., sell
in stores for about $5.
</P>
<P>
   At Aahs in suburban Sherman Oaks, the robber took the coveted
``Ty'' model, now worth $65 or more because it has been
discontinued, the store manager said.
</P>
<P>
   The toys likely will find their way to a burgeoning Beanie Baby
black market, which has outlets at swap meets and through
classified ads or on the Internet, VanDuyne said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even know what a Beanie Baby was until today,'' he
said. ``Hopefully we'll catch this guy. He'll probably be around
the area doing this again.''
</P>
<P>
   The manager said she believes the robber had cased the store
because he knew exactly where to find the most valuable Beanie
Babies. ``He just went right to them,'' said the manager, who
declined to give her name.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's stupid; it's crazy,'' she added. ``There (are) crazy
people out in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The store was open just five minutes before the robber arrived,
VanDuyne said. As the gunman ordered seven employees and customers
to lie on the floor, a 10-year-old boy hid behind a display case.
No one was injured.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses described the robber as an African-American man about
6 feet tall, wearing a black ski mask over his face, VanDuyne said.
</P>
<P>
   When a witness said the robber may have taken refuge in a nearby
store, police launched a door-to-door search but could not find
him. Investigators believe the robber got away in a car that had
been waiting in the alley behind the store.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
